<HEADLINE>
SITE BOOSTS HOUSTON'S NEW NFL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their favorite NFL team doesn't even start playing until 2002,
but it's not stopping these guys from starting an online tailgate
party.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Sweeney of Addison and a few of his buddies are such avid
Houston football fans that they've launched HoustonProFootball.com.
They've put together a quality resource of information on Houston's
new NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to ride the city's wave of enthusiasm and hopefully,
secure exclusive access to the team that no other site can offer,''
Sweeney said. ``That was a big factor in our starting this so
early. We wanted to be an established and known name when the games
start. And by 2002, we should be.''
</P>
<P>
   HoustonProFootball.com doesn't have a fancy virtual tour of the
franchise's new stadium like the team's official site
(www.NFL2002.com). But HoustonProFootball.com _ launched two weeks
ago and the only known fan site dedicated to the new team _
adequately does the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll help to reawaken any dormant fans that lost
interest in the NFL when Bud Adams and company left town,'' Sweeney
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been done before. Cleveland Browns fans used the Internet
for the same purpose when they learned the city would regain a
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   HoustonProFootball.com's most popular feature is Post Patterns,
a message board that has attracted nearly 200 posts since the
site's launch. The team's official site, which made its debut in
October, also has a message board.
</P>
<P>
   HoustonProFootball.com also includes news updates and
commentaries by Sweeney's associates, Byron Cox, Stefan Godbold,
Bob Hulsey, Kendall Kirsch, Pat O'Neill and Mike Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   HoustonProFootball.com also takes a shot at Dallas with its
anti-Cowboys section, complete with links to critical commentaries
on the Cowboys. Sweeney said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones' efforts to
market his team in Houston after the Oilers left prompted the
anti-Cowboys sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate a rivalry developing, so we thought we'd stoke
the fires now,'' Sweeney said. ``We have 2 to 21/2 years until we
can cheer on our team. Why not get in some much-needed practice by
cheering for whatever team the Cowboys are playing?''
</P>
<P>
   HoustonProFootball.com will evolve as more details about the
franchise are known, Sweeney said. Plans are to change the site's
domain name and its colors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney also said he is aware that some fan sites have had
trouble with trademark infringements with professional leagues and
their teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a concern,'' he said. ``We hope _ and our efforts should
bear this out _ that both the franchise and the league realize
we're helping to build the fan base and spread the word, and that
supporting such a venture is definitely more beneficial than
squashing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, however, we will do whatever we have to do
to appease the powers that be. It isn't our intention to rattle
cages.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he was influenced by fan sites for the Houston
Astros (www.astrosconnection.com) and the Houston Rockets
(www.clutchcity.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``Fan sites provide a unique perspective and a terrific outlet
for people to rant and rave _ they're like having a sports talk
radio program in cyberspace,'' he said. ``And if we're half as
successful as those Houston fan sites before us, we'll consider
this a huge success.''
</P>
<P>
   ENHANCED COWBOYS: Cowboys fans who believe they can outsmart New
England Patriots offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese have their
shot Sunday night. The Cowboys-Patriots game on ESPN's Sunday Night
Football will be available on ESPN.com's Enhanced TV.
</P>
<P>
   Enhanced TV lets viewers play a browser-based interactive game
against other viewers during Monday Night Football, ESPN's Sunday
games or postseason games telecast on ABC-TV or ESPN. Viewers gets
points for correctly predicting the ball carrier before every play
from scrimmage and bonus points for correctly answering trivia
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ROSE TAKES A CUT: Pete Rose was in New York on Monday for the
launch of Sportcut.com., which through Jan. 15 will contain a fan
petition calling for Rose's admission to the Hall of Fame. As long
as Rose is banned from baseball for life, he is ineligible for the
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep a guy from making a living,'' he said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ``It's not the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose's site is also online shot at John Dowd, who was hired by
the baseball commissioner's office to compile a report on Rose's
gambling. Dowd posted the report on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much is (Dowd) making on the Dowd report?'' Rose asked.
``If I died tomorrow, we wouldn't hear about John Dowd again until
the day he died.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG-MEDIA UPDATES: Bill Walton has joined MSNBCSports.com as an
online analyst where he'll also field e-mail questions. ... former
San Francisco 49ers running back Roger Craig has signed on with
Sacramento-based TodaySports.com as a health and fitness columnist.
... CNNSI.com plans live coverage from Sports Illustrated's 20th
Century Sports Awards preshow party scheduled from 8 to 10 p.m.
Thursday at Madison Square Garden in New York. SI senior
contributing writer Frank Deford opens the online version of the
event with a 1 p.m. chat session.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
