<SLUG> BC-TIMES-LIBEL-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES LIBEL SUIT BY FORMER MEDICAL EXAMINER AGAINST THE
TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.J., Ind., Ohio)  (Subs lede graf to clarify; subs 11th graf for clarification) 
(Eds: Elliot - with one `t' - is cq for Gross, and Elliott is cq
for Wilk. ) 
(ms) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A State Supreme Court judge has dismissed a
longstanding libel suit against The New York Times by Dr. Elliot M.
Gross, a former New York City chief medical examiner, who said he
was defamed in a series of articles in 1985 and 1986 that quoted
pathologists and others who accused him of misconduct and producing
inaccurate or misleading autopsy reports.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Elliott Wilk, in a pretrial ruling, did not address
Gross' conduct or competence but held that he had failed to show
that the Times and the reporter who wrote many of the articles,
Philip Shenon, had acted with ``actual malice'' or ``a reckless
disregard for the truth,'' a high standard of proof required of
public officials in defamation cases.
</P>
<P>
   The justice noted that Shenon had interviewed more than 250
people and had ``sought out sources who were friendly with or
neutral toward plaintiff.'' And in four interviews with Shenon
before publication of the articles, the justice said, Gross
``declined to speak about most of the allegations'' and did not
challenge sources he later accused of bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record does not support plaintiff's thesis that Shenon or
any other Times defendant published any of the statements at issue
with knowledge of their falsity or serious doubts as to their
truth,'' Wilk declared in a ruling dated Nov. 18 and made public
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tortuous, 14-year history of motions, dismissals, a
reinstatement and numerous appeals, the case has never gone to
trial, moving from the state's lowest court to its highest and back
again. And the latest ruling by Wilk, who originally dismissed the
case in 1991 on different ground, did not appear likely to end the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we will appeal _ there is no question,'' Leon Segan,
Gross' lawyer, said Monday. ``We have a good case. We felt we had a
good case from its inception. My client went through all kinds of
torment because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted, as Gross has all along, that the Times articles
were factually biased and based on interviews with sources who were
biased.
</P>
<P>
   Gross, 65, who was dismissed as the city's medical examiner by
Mayor Ed Koch in 1987, later became a pathologist in Indiana and
Ohio, and is now the coroner for Cape May and Cumberland Counties
in New Jersey. He said in a telephone interview that he was
``obviously disappointed'' by Wilk's ruling but declined further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   George Freeman, assistant general counsel for The New York Times
Co., hailed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did Justice Wilk find, as was clear, that there was
no actual malice, but just as importantly he recognized Phil
Shenon's diligent and fair journalism in the reporting of the
articles,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The articles quoted pathologists, colleagues of Gross and others
who accused him of producing inaccurate or misleading forensic
reports that supported the police in several high-profile cases of
people who died in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Gross denied the allegations, and four investigations _ by the
state Board of Regents, the state Board of Professional Medical
Conduct, a mayoral panel and the U.S. attorney in Manhattan _ found
no professional misconduct or criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1986 lawsuit, Gross contended that a series of Times
articles defamed him and were based on false information from
one-sided sources and published with reckless disregard for the
truth. That is the higher standard of proof prominent people in
libel cases must meet, a test which gives the media greater leeway
in reporting on governmental activities; ordinary citizens need
only prove that defamatory statements are false and were
negligently published.
</P>
<P>
   The Times argued that the articles reported expressions of
opinion about the conduct of a public official in the performance
of his duty and that as such they were constitutionally protected.
</P>
<P>
   A series of pretrial rulings ensued. In 1991, Wilk agreed with
the Times and dismissed the complaint. Gross appealed and in 1992
the state Appellate Division in Manhattan upheld Wilk. The Court of
Appeals, the state's highest tribunal, reinstated the suit, saying
the articles contained enough statements presented as facts to
warrant further proceedings. The case was then sent back to Wilk,
who after depositions of Times reporters and editors, granted the
most recent Times motion and dismissed it again.
</P>
</TEXT>
