<SLUG> BC-ELEPHANT-BIRTH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI ZOO TRUMPETS BIRTH OF BABY ELEPHANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA AND LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ Moola, an 18-year-old Asian elephant, began
her hard labor Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Her birth ``dance'' lasted 36 hours. Her ears would flap as her
tail swished. Her massive body eased itself to her left side, then
her right. Then, after all this moving, she froze in place.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over she repeated these moves, with cameras mounted
around her pen recording every flap, swish, sway and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Glazier, the senior keeper at Dickerson Park Zoo, kept
telling himself that even if the baby elephant was stillborn, its
birth would be significant. No elephant artificially inseminated
had successfully carried her baby to term.
</P>
<P>
   But with each passing hour, Glazier worried. Thirty-six hours of
hard labor probably meant the baby elephant was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept reminding myself about the birth's importance so I
wouldn't be too disappointed if the baby was dead,'' Glazier
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Moola bent her knees and elbows and bore down. Haji,
weighing 378 pounds with a waist of 61 inches, arrived at 10:45
a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But he was very still.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the first elephant baby conceived by artificial
insemination...snorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a live calf,'' Glazier gleefully announced to the
entire zoo staff over a hand radio.
</P>
<P>
   Within three hours Haji was nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the proud keepers at the zoo have been trumpeting
news of their big event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been, well, a real zoo around here,'' Glazier said with a
laugh. ``But we are very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The birth highlighted the zoo's world-known elephant breeding
program.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the zoo's size makes its research even more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dickerson Park is a good example of a small zoo that has
committed itself to big ideas,'' said Mike Keele, who runs the
American Zoo and Aquarium Association's species survival plan for
elephants. ``I think they're an example, even to big zoos, of what
can be done if you really want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson Park Zoo picked a tough species with which to make its
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants are notoriously difficult for zoos to handle. Their
reinforced exhibit areas cost money. Their bulk and aggressiveness
are dangerous for keepers. And they're tough to move.
</P>
<P>
   But the work of zoos to breed African and Asian elephants is
vital to preserving the species in North America. Only about 150
Asian elephants remain in accredited zoos, and some researchers
fear that the species could disappear if zoos don't accelerate
their breeding programs.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, it would have been hard to imagine that Dickerson
Park Zoo could pursue anything groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo was founded in 1922. By 1975 the city considered closing
it because buildings were falling apart and attendance was
dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Crocker, the zoo's director, recalls one embarrassing
example of the zoo's inability to find good animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, there was a beagle on display,'' recalled
Crocker, a Springfield native. ``A beagle! That was sad.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, the zoo started its Asian elephant program.
A master plan in 1985 suggested using geographic themes to better
present the animals. The zoo gained its national accreditation in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo pursued more ambitious attempts to breed Asian
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants from circuses and from zoos, including those in St.
Louis and Chicago, were brought to Springfield to breed with the
zoo's bulls. The zoo also successfully bred its own elephants
throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers nationwide worried that breeding wasn't enough.
Because America's zoos house five times more female elephants than
male, elephants often must be transported so breeding can occur.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson Park's researchers began looking for ways to
artificially inseminate elephants. The thinking was that it would
be a lot easier, and cheaper, to transport semen than to transport
the animals themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges were obvious.
</P>
<P>
   First, a female elephant only becomes fertile during three
cycles a year. Each cycle contains only about three days in which
the elephant can conceive. Researchers helped develop blood tests
that could predict the cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dickerson Park tests blood for circuses and other zoos.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the delicate matter of collecting the semen.
</P>
<P>
   A male elephant, up to 10 feet tall and weighing more than six
tons, can easily kill a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   To protect keepers, a former zoo staffer developed a chute that
would restrain the animal and rotate it 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, zoo staffers needed a way to inseminate the female
elephant. The female's reproductive canal is up to 3 feet long, and
surgery often was needed to place the sperm. Springfield
researchers, including Dennis Schmitt, developed a series of tubes
to make insemination safer and easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City and Indianapolis zoos are hoping to make history
as well next spring with the birth of the first African elephant
from artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
   Semen from a bull elephant named Dale in Kansas City was
successfully implanted in 1998 in a cow elephant named Kubwa in
Indianapolis. A Kansas City Zoo official said Monday the pregnancy
was proceeding successfully. The calf is due in March.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haji is the talk in elephant circles, the zoo's
elephants also strike a chord in Springfield. The seven Asian
elephants have become the zoo's unofficial mascots, appearing on
letterhead and other merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   But translating community support into money isn't always easy.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson Park Zoo makes do with a budget of about $1.5 million.
The city's share, about $1 million, hasn't changed much in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, progress is being made. Ground was broken Monday for a
new entry building to house the ticket office, gift shop and public
restrooms. Two new buildings were constructed in 1997, and a new
administration and education building went up in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker, the zoo's director, realizes that the breeding research
saps money from other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has never been in a position to put a lot of money
into the zoo like the community would like,'' he said. ``And when
you work with elephants, you have to give up resources that might
have gone to something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we know that elephants are an important
effort. It's important to the elephants, but it's important for us,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Matt Campbell contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
