A4771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT &LR;      11-30 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERNERS SHRUG AT RUSSIAN OIL COMPANY'S POWER PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A court-ordered sale of an oil company last week that
effectively made most of BP Amoco's half-billion-dollar investment
in Russia worthless has ignited new cries of outrage among foreign
investors. But it is not expected to have grave consequences for
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the fate of the Chernogorneft oil company has
been widely watched as a barometer of Russia's commitment to
protecting the interests of foreigners in Russian businesses.
Chernogorneft was the most valuable asset of Sidanko, a bankrupt
petroleum conglomerate into which BP Amoco has plowed much of its
Russian investment.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen Oil Co., a BP Amoco rival in Russia, successfully
persuaded a bankruptcy court last week to auction Chernogorneft,
which Tyumen then promptly bought for a fraction of its real value.
</P>
<P>
   Despite accusations of unfairness, Tyumen Oil will probably
continue to receive foreign loans and, more important, strengthen
its position within the Russian economic firmament, investment
analysts who follow Russia said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia itself attracts tiny sums of foreign investment already _
largely because of its history of wronging investors. The
Chernogorneft sale could hardly make the country's already dubious
reputation any worse, and it certainly will not cause an exodus of
the few companies already in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People investing in Russia are already pretty cynical,'' said
Erik Wigertz, oil analyst with Brunswick Warburg, a Moscow
brokerage firm. ``There have been so many blatant violations
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Chernogorneft was the latest in a series of setbacks
for BP Amoco's 10 percent investment in Sidanko, which once was
considered a sign of landmark cooperation between Russian and
Western business. Sidanko's owner, the influential banker Vladimir
Potanin, had the close ties to the Kremlin crucial to working here,
and the deal in late 1997 allowed what was then British Petroleum
to get involved in the development of a huge gas field in eastern
Siberia to which Sidanko owns the rights.
</P>
<P>
   But by late 1998 Potanin's influence had waned, and debtors
filed to push Sidanko's production companies into bankruptcy,
including the prize Chernogorneft, which was actually solvent.
Sidanko itself was declared bankrupt by the spring. BP Amoco and
others have alleged that Tyumen Oil used Russian law to drive the
companies into bankruptcy in order to buy them cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen has denied any wrongdoing, but has acknowledged its
interests in Sidanko properties.
</P>
<P>
   It acquired two Sidanko units this fall, including
Chernogorneft, purchased this past Friday for $175 million. That
business has been valued at about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now, left with no promising assets in Sidanko, BP Amoco must
choose the least painful of several options. In the short term, BP
Amoco must decide if it will fight the Chernogorneft sale in court
or pull out of the battle entirely and leave it to Sidanko
shareholders backed by Potanin. BP Amoco is even considering
selling its stake in Sidanko, although at a great loss.
</P>
<P>
   Tyumen Oil, by contrast, is no worse off. Russia's fuel and
energy minister said last week, before the sale, that he approved
of Tyumen Oil's purchase of Chernogorneft.
</P>
<P>
   Although oil analysts have predicted a dire future for Tyumen
Oil, the United States' Export-Import Bank has given preliminary
approval to about $500 million in loan guarantees to the company.
And while some banks close to BP Amoco might not lend to Tyumen
Oil, others will pick up the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had $100 million to give to Russian oil, I'd give it to
Tyumen,'' said one Western banker. ``It's a good credit risk, it's
performed well and never defaulted. It has been aggressive in
taking over Sidanko's assets but there's nothing wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's inability and unwillingness to intervene in the
bankruptcies belies its public statements about Russia's desire for
foreign investment. But many veteran foreign investors in Russia
caught on long ago to the nation's deep ambivalence about having
foreigners play a role in the nation's industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone finds a niche, he can do business here, independent
of any reforms,'' said one veteran Moscow businessman. ``But that
does nothing for the overall well-being of Russia. The Russians are
destroying themselves with this kind of behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
