<SLUG> BC-DRUG-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER-LAMBERT SUES PFIZER OVER DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Warner-Lambert Co. sued Pfizer Inc. as expected Monday in an
attempt to end the marketing agreement between the two companies to
sell Lipitor, an enormously successful cholesterol-reducing drug.
</P>
<P>
   Lipitor has become the prize in the merger battle involving
Pfizer, Warner-Lambert and the American Home Products Co. Three
weeks ago, Warner-Lambert announced a $70 billion merger with
American Home Products, only to have Pfizer make an $82.4 billion
hostile bid for Warner-Lambert that day.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, executives from Pfizer and Warner-Lambert have
battled. Pfizer immediately filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chancery
Court to eliminate several roadblocks _ including a $2 billion
breakup fee _ that Warner-Lambert created in its merger agreement
with American Home.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer unexpectedly filed a second suit in Delaware last week
that accused Warner-Lambert of breeching the Lipitor agreement.
Warner-Lambert's counterclaim, filed Monday, accused Pfizer of
breaking the Lipitor agreement and deliberately misstating parts of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert said in a statement that the company wanted to
end its marketing relationship with Pfizer and ``reclaim all rights
to Lipitor for Warner-Lambert and its shareholders.'' Analysts have
projected Lipitor to have $5 billion in worldwide sales next year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Warner-Lambert's counterclaim, Pfizer said in a
statement Monday that Warner-Lambert had engaged in ``a series of
desperate measures'' designed to prevent the company's shareholders
from considering Pfizer's higher bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
