<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRUCK-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRUCK SAFETY IN TRANSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 30:
</P>
<P>
   Just before adjourning, Congress approved a measure creating a
separate new agency within the transportation department to address
the pressing issue of truck safety. Last year 5,374 people died in
truck accidents, an average of more than 100 per week. The new
agency is needed because the organization long responsible for
policing truck safety, the Federal Highway Administration's Office
of Motor Carriers, is too complacent and too cozy with the trucking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic safety advocates have been calling for change for some
time. But Congress was goaded into passing the Motor Carrier Safety
Improvement Act of 1999 by two Republicans, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona and Rep. Frank Wolf of Virginia, and by sharp criticism of
the Office of Motor Carriers from the transportation department's
inspector general. Hearings further documented that the agency had
ignored serious safety violations, imposed inadequate fines and
relied on questionable research by the trucking industry and its
allies to justify weak safety regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure requires the transportation department to
institute all the truck safety recommendations set forth in the
inspector general's April 1999 report. In addition it tightens the
rules for obtaining a commercial driver's license, and improves
data collection on safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   Much now depends on how the reorganization gets carried out by
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater. If Slater is truly serious
about safety, he will let the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, which sets the safety standards for new trucks, say
how those standards should apply to vehicles already on the road.
He will also name an administrator for the new agency who is
devoted to public safety and independent of the trucking industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 0006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
