r a BC-CRASH-REPORT-KAN &LR;      11-30 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-REPORT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE OF METAL FATIGUE, MISSING PARTS CITED IN REPORT ON FATAL
CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The engine of a plane that caught fire and
crashed last year, killing five Kansas City area skydivers and a
pilot, showed evidence of metal fatigue as well as missing or loose
screws, according to a preliminary report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board report does not draw
conclusions as to what caused the crash. A final report is expected
to point to a probable cause or causes.
</P>
<P>
   But the safety board said an examination of the engine revealed
that connecting rods on two of the six cylinders were unattached to
the crankshaft and that one rod had fractures ``typical of an
overstress separation...''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City lawyer Gary C. Robb, who represents the families of
four of the dead skydivers, said the evidence points to a
metallurgical fault on the part of the engine manufacturer,
Teledyne Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the NTSB confirmed that there was a
progressive failure of the numbers 2 and 6 connecting rods in the
engine,'' Robb said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cotter, a local attorney for Teledyne, disputed that
conclusion, although he had not yet seen the safety board's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that the problems with this plane and the
engine were maintenance problems, and I think that's probably
pretty well documented factually by the NTSB,'' Cotter said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on air-traffic controller contacts, radar readings and
witness accounts, the aircraft dropped from a top altitude of 5,200
feet above sea level to the ground in about four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during that time a controller at Kansas City
International Airport, who had been in intermittent contact with
the plane, reported hearing, ``What the hell was that?'' One minute
later the pilot, David G. Snyder, reported he was aborting the
skydiving jump.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts from witnesses on the ground indicate the plane, which
took off March 21, 1998, from Independence Memorial Airport,
attempted to land at Grain Valley Airport. The plane was trailing
white and black smoke, spitting flames from the engine cowling and
making a banging sound as it lost altitude and struck the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, 55, of Independence, Mo., was killed along with five
skydiving passengers. They were Marion C. Rudder, 47, of Oskaloosa,
Kan.; John H. Schuman, 47, of Lawrence, Kan.; Kenneth L. Buckley,
50, of Independence; Paul Eric Rueff, 32, of Kansas City, Kan.; and
Julie L. Douglass, 24, of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Douglass was a newcomer to the sport. The others were
experienced skydivers. Autopsy reports indicated three of the
victims died of smoke inhalation, corroborating reports that the
plane was on fire before impact.
</P>
<P>
   Examination of the wreckage found evidence of oil on the left
wing's main strut, the left horizontal stabilizer and on fragments
of the Plexiglas windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings:
</P>
<P>
   - The oil-filler tube was missing from the engine.
</P>
<P>
   - Five of six screws were missing from the cylinder-six valve
cover and the remaining screw was loose.
</P>
<P>
   - The oil sump, or pan, contained debris from connecting rods
and pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions suggest the engine threw one or two rods, but
Robb contends that was due to defects in the manufacture of the IO
520-D series engine, as well as neglect by service mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Robb cited a statement in the safety board's report that
fractures found on a connecting rod piece had ``features typical of
fatigue cracking.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits on behalf of all six defendants have been consolidated
in Jackson County Circuit Court for purposes of pretrial discovery.
All name Teledyne, parent company of Teledyne Continental Motors,
as a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawsuits also name various mechanical-service
providers and officials of the Greater Kansas City Skydiving Club
as defendants. A message left on the club's answering machine
Monday was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration records cited by the safety
board indicate Snyder had been a certified pilot since 1971 and had
a successful flight review in August 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Cessna U206G was a 1979 model that had been inspected on
Nov. 5, 1997, with 7,280 hours of airtime logged. The craft and
engine were declared airworthy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the safety board, the engine had been overhauled in
March 1991. In May 1994 it was declared not to be airworthy because
of a cracked crankcase.
</P>
<P>
   But less than two weeks later another aircraft company, Jewell
Aircraft Inc. of Holly Springs, Miss., installed a certified
crankcase on the engine and it was returned to service.
</P>
<P>
   Robb contends Jewell should have detected metal fatigue in the
engine using spectrographic analysis. A co-owner of Jewell could
not be reached Monday. Robert Kroenert, a local attorney for
Jewell, also could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The engine was installed in the Cessna in July 1995, with 774
hours of service logged since its overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance logs from the FAA, but not included in the safety
board's report, show work was done on the engine's cylinders and
rings in February 1998 and that another certified mechanic worked
on the engine's oil pump and declared the craft airworthy one week
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sharp, skydiving club president, said days after the
accident that the Cessna had flown without incident many times the
Saturday of the crash. The plane had been allowed to sit after the
engine flooded.
</P>
<P>
   But just before it took off for the last time, Sharp said: ``It
sounded good. It sounded perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
