<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-UNIONS-STRIKES-NYT     11-30 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UNIONS-STRIKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS FIND THE HOLIDAYS A TIME TO ASK AND RECEIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many are the signs of the holidays: the lines at
Macy's, the traffic in midtown, the Christmas tree vendors taking
up stations on the street. And now comes another: the threat of
labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility of a walkout looming, the local stagehands'
union settled a contract dispute on Monday with a trade group
representing 18 Manhattan theaters, preventing a disruption of the
holiday season on Broadway, one of the city's main tourism engines.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, which the union had described in a statement
as ``an effort to avoid a strike that would cripple Broadway during
the holiday,'' showed once again that Christmas is a prime season
for labor brinkmanship in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The strike threat came as musicians and transit workers were
also seizing on the holiday season to press their causes. Labor
experts say the tactic suggests that unions in the city have come
to see the Christmas season, with its influx of tourists and its
emphasis on commerce, as an important time to make their demands
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kind of awareness, in a tactical kind of sense,
that all days are not equal, and you want to pick a day when the
cessation of your industry will have the greatest effect,'' said
Joshua B. Freeman, a labor historian at Queens College.
</P>
<P>
   The stagehands were not alone. Over the last few months, the
city's 33,000 transit workers have warned of a holiday walkout if
the city does not meet its wage demands. The strike deadline is
Dec. 15, forcing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration to make
contingency plans for the possible idling of the city's bus and
subway lines in the run-up to Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   And a second union, Local 802 of the American Federation of
Musicians, which represents the 70-member orchestra at the New York
City Ballet, voted to strike last week when negotiations with the
ballet stalled. The opening night benefit performance of ``The
Nutcracker'' at Lincoln Center had to be canceled, and subsequent
shows have been performed to taped music.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Local 802 also threatened to walk out on the
Christmas Spectacular at Radio City Music Hall, but the two sides
reached a contract agreement two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Richard W. Hurd, a professor of labor studies at Cornell
University, said the events fit a familiar pattern. Over the last
20 years, as strikes have become less effective labor weapons,
unions have had to become more imaginative in using them.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, striking in New York City during the holiday
season is akin to a cannery union striking during the harvest, or
an auto workers' union striking just as a plant changes to a new
model line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the pattern,'' Hurd said. ``It isn't the holiday season
that is a pattern as much as timing your strike when it has the
most impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said the labor demands this month bear some resemblance
to the holiday tactics that Michael Quill, the founder of the city
Transport Workers Union, used after World War II. Quill often
threatened that subway strikes would begin after the stroke of
midnight on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, all through the 50s and 60s, the way the TWU
contract was set up, it expired literally at the end of the year,''
Freeman said. ``So Dec. 31 traditionally was a cliffhanger. People
would be out all over the city, not knowing if they would get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Freeman said, not every strike is created equal: for
most New Yorkers, a theater strike would be disappointing, while a
transit strike would be truly disruptive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
