u l BC-FRONT-ROW-FASHION-NYT     11-30 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-ROW-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPIN AT HARPER'S BAZAAR  
 DIOR GETS IN ON THE GROUND FLOOR AT LVMH   
 WHAT TO WEAR WHEN MARRYING A WEDDING-DRESS DESIGNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first issue of Harper's Bazaar bearing the name
of its new editor in chief, Katherine Betts, has arrived on
newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the talk in media circles about the magazine re-evolving
along the lines of the Hollywood-centric ``In Style'' (whose
December issue exceeds Bazaar's by 244 pages), Ms. Betts put a
model on the cover _ well, a model-slash-actress, Carolyn Murphy,
who recently made her film debut in ``Liberty Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strongly that I wanted to make a statement that this is
a fashion magazine,'' Ms. Betts said, adding that she planned to
feature celebrities on approximately half of her covers.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the magazine's full makeover under Ms. Betts will
not be apparent until February, but in the December issue, which a
spokeswoman for the magazine said was two-thirds the work of Ms.
Betts, her hand is clearly visible.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding Ms. Murphy on the cover are many headlines, some
service-oriented and alliterative (``Party Politics: How to Get on
the A-List''), which make for a busy look that Bazaar's former
editor in chief, Elizabeth Tilberis, who died in April, avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a writer and I love to write cover lines,'' Ms. Betts
explained. ``I believe in titles and blurbs and display copy as the
skeleton of the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Bazaar's fashion photography, now under the stewardship
of a new creative director, Michel Botbol, has a lot more energy
than it had in the recent past, thanks to the use of more
avant-garde young photographers like Alexei Hay, who shot 12 pages
of fashion pictures at a party at the newly hip Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting fashion in the context of a real party, rather than a
staged one, is part of what Ms. Betts described as a more
journalistic approach to fashion that Bazaar will be taking.
</P>
<P>
   Will the magazine go all the way in the name of journalism and
include fashion criticism that advertisers might find unpleasant?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to come out and say we don't like something,''
Ms. Betts said.
</P>
<P>
   A New Dior Boutique
</P>
<P>
   The new Christian Dior boutique in Midtown will make its debut
next week, which will coincide with the official opening of the
building it sits in, the LVMH Tower at 19 E. 57th St. LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton is the parent company of Dior, Givenchy and
Bliss, among other luxury brands, and a Bliss spa is to open on the
third floor of the building on Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-story LVMH building, which will serve as the company's
corporate headquarters in America, was designed by the
Pritzker-prize winning architect Christian de Portzamparc.
</P>
<P>
   The ground-floor Dior shop, though, was designed by an architect
who sometimes seems the only one that upper-class merchants have
ever heard of: Peter Marino.
</P>
<P>
   The boutique's opening will be celebrated with a dinner for 250
in the tower's 30-foot glass penthouse Saturday night. John
Galliano will play host, and Foxy Brown will perform.
</P>
<P>
   The evening kicks off a marathon week of fashion-related
party-going that should tax even those with the highest levels of
tolerance for being around people just like themselves, many
carrying small shoulder bags that cost more than laptops.
</P>
<P>
   The VH-1 Fashion Awards will take place on Sunday night, and the
Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume Institute gala is just 24
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday night, LVMH will again celebrate itself with a
benefit for the Municipal Art Society for 600.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is too big for the LVMH Tower, and so the event will
be held across the street, in the lobby of the IBM Building.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bride Wore ...
</P>
<P>
   Another resident of 57th Street, William Calvert, an evening
wear designer, is about to embark on an equally frenzied holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   He will be married in Barbados on Jan. 2. Calvert has known his
fiancee, Halla Elias, who has a children's clothing line, for 10
years. They've been engaged for a temperate five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being two egomaniacal designers, the hardest thing was
deciding to spend our lives together,'' Calvert confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Because Calvert has a thriving wedding-dress business, one thing
was clear when the couple did finally set a date: The bride was not
going to go shopping anywhere else. Still, Calvert wanted to be
surprised by what his bride would wear on their wedding day, and
they found a novel way to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Calvert sketched five wedding-dress designs, and Ms. Elias
picked one without Calvert's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant to Calvert is making the dress. The bridegroom will
see it for the first time on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it lives up to her,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
