<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HOPE TO REVERSE DECEMBER FORTUNES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The mood around the Dallas Cowboys' Valley Ranch
training complex these days is not unlike that in most homes across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   With just 25 shopping days left until Christmas, moms and dads
are starting to feel the squeeze of having so much to do and so
little time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is the same for the Cowboys (6-5), who are facing
their own December blitz, which includes four of their final five
games.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys are to unwrap an NFC East title, they say they
must find immediate answers for their inconsistent play and end the
season on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The final rush begins Sunday at New England, which is 6-5 after
a 4-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   December ``is the month teams try to make a push, especially
when you are in the position we are in right now,'' Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``This is a critical month.
Historically, teams that have done well and went deep in the
playoffs have had good months in December. And that's what we are
striving for this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman cites last season's December swoon _ two dreadful losses
to the New Orleans Saints and Kansas City Chiefs and two
unimpressive victories against the Philadelphia Eagles and New York
Giants that gave way to a first-round playoff loss to the Arizona
Cardinals in January _ as how not to play out the final month. That
came a year after the Cowboys went O-for-December and ended a 6-10
season with a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   But Aikman also mentioned 1995, when Cowboys won the Super Bowl
despite a mediocre 2-2 December.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of those years seem relevant now because of the team's
up-and-down play in 1999. Aikman said the Cowboys are likely to
make the postseason only by overtaking the NFC East-leading
Washington Redskins (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cowboys would need help from outside themselves for
that to happen, Aikman said a strong finish is vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we didn't take care of some other games, we've given
ourselves little margin for error going into the five games ,'' he
said. ``Every game is extremely important to try to win the
division. That's one good thing about us. If we make the playoffs,
we are going to be hitting our stride. If not, we won't be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey: ``We understand exactly where we
are. The team understands what has to be done from here on out. We
have five games left and everybody knows what's at stake in each
one of those games. We have to learn from the past. We get our
chance this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' optimism is based primarily on the increasingly
dominant play of their 10th-ranked defense, which is coming off a
20-0 shutout of the Miami Dolphins. But nobody is making bold
predictions because nobody has answers for the problems that have
marked the Cowboys' season _ namely poor play on the road,
especially in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Cowboys' losses have come on the road. All have come
after the Cowboys have held halftime leads. The Cowboys have been
outscored 81-16 in the second half of those games and have been
shut out in eight of the 10 quarters after intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey refuses to look at the Cowboys' problems as simply a
matter of problems playing on the road. He said another issue is
the team's inability to finish off opponents with strong play in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys have been searching feverishly for
little things that might make a difference, but have yet come up
with answers.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has no answers either, but he said the bottom line is
that the Cowboys must somehow find a way to correct their road
woes, considering that two of their final five games are on the
road _ New England on Sunday and New Orleans on Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Add the fact that the Cowboys have not had consecutive victories
since their 3-0 start as reason players are dismissing the euphoric
Thanksgiving Day victory against the Dolphins and are pointing to
the New England game for an indication of what they can expect
during the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be the confidence builder,'' linebacker
Randall Godfrey said. ``If we win on the road (Sunday) that's going
to help us out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys know it won't be easy because the reeling Patriots
will be looking to end a four-game losing streak and keep their
sinking playoff hopes afloat. However, the Cowboys are counting on
their own bunker mentality to help them overcome the Patriots and
start their final Christmas rush to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our back is against the wall,'' Godfrey said. ``We aren't
guaranteed a playoff spot. It makes a difference that we are in a
dog fight for the playoffs. We just got to continue to play well
and stay focused. Everything is still up in the air.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
