r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     11-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAT-AND-HAPPY STARS ARE STEALING FROM FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Personally, I've got nothing against fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   In most circumstances, fat and happy signifies a positive state
of mind, as opposed to a waist measurement. It's just another way
of saying life's dice are rolling your way.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, there is a monumental exception to this concept
and it involves our friends in the jock kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   For any coach or any manager there is no more dreaded disease
than fat and happy. It's the same as saying advanced gangrene is
eating away at your team. Fat heads, fat wallets and warm fuzzies
are guaranteed to bring doom to even the best of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   When applied to the local Big Four, certainly heads and wallets
have reached the obese stage for the Dallas Cowboys. But let it
also be said that despite a 6-5 record, it's a team that can't be
condemned for lack of effort. The Cowboys give that.
</P>
<P>
   So certainly do the Dallas Mavericks, even with their limited
positive results in the NBA. And while the Texas Rangers were
playoff-spooked again by the ``Yankee Thing,'' there was nothing
over the long season to suggest they wanted to quit.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's the Dallas Stars, currently our local civic
disgrace and the most glaring example of fat and happy maybe ever
witnessed around here in any sport, any time.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this team stinks. But that's not the point. Worse
yet, the Stars simply don't care.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation from last spring and summer to what's
happening now goes beyond shocking. It's beyond belief.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars team that won the Stanley Cup was all about work
ethic, grit and determination. And that wasn't just in the
championship season. It also applied the season before.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to the Stars who play the New York Islanders on
Tuesday night. Does heartless, gutless thieves come to mind? Yes,
thieves. They steal the money of those sellout crowds at Reunion
Arena by going through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse-makers say it's early yet. The National Hockey League
season is only two months old. And what about the injuries? And
what about adjusting to a roster shakedown in such a short
off-season?
</P>
<P>
   But while all of those could have been valid factors, none are.
Not when there's a lack of effort, and a lack of caring.
</P>
<P>
   Newsprint dispatches from Atlanta yesterday morning told of an
``angry'' Derian Hatcher personally addressing his teammates after
the embarrassment of a lazy second period.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, Hatcher still cares enough to become angry. You
can put coach Ken Hitchcock in the same category, but there's also
a feeling Hitch can't believe what he's seeing. A majority of his
players are listening to Hitchcock, but they aren't hearing. Hitch
can't break through the fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   And what makes all excuses invalid is that going younger on the
roster has not been responsible for the rotten attitudes. Neither
was the departure of such soldiers as Pat Verbeek, Craig Ludwig and
Dave Reid. It's the stars on the Stars who are losing credibility
and games.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano? Has anyone seen him lately? Since that horrific
crash into the boards in the second game of the season, Modano has
been a ghost. His performance is totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull? He looks like a guy trying to buck the system, as in
Hitchcock's defensive system. Those who said Hull would never adapt
to the Stars' style of play may be right after all, one year later.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, give me six or seven Joe Nieuwendyks. You can
have all the Hulls and Modanos you want.
</P>
<P>
   In the category of having awful seasons thus far falls a Sergei
Zubov and a Darryl Sydor, among others. Where their game is at the
moment, it's many miles from where it once was. And that shows both
defensively and on the lack of a power play.
</P>
<P>
   Besides work ethic, the trademark of the Stars had been in
physical play. These people took a toll by constantly hitting the
other people. But it has become a soft team that goes shy when it
comes to contact or anything beyond contact. In the NHL, if you
have no fight, you will be pushed around. The Stars have none.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Anaheim, returning to the Reunion scene last week, was
made to pay for what happened in that second game of the season.
Modano issued a public statement after his neck injury, asking for
peace and goodwill in the NHL. Only his own team was listening.
Peace and goodwill are a proper fit with fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Western Conference is playing tougher than even
expected, particularly the Pacific Division. The Stars are in last
place in the Pacific for a good reason _ they deserve to be.
</P>
<P>
   The unthinkable is now a possibility. From the Stanley Cup to
not making the playoffs shouldn't be considered unreal. It's
actually the next step after heartless and gutless. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
