<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-WINNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPE TO START WINNING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The one big corner-turning, streak-starting
victory has been easy to get for the Dallas Stars this season.
</P>
<P>
   The second victory, on which single games become streaks and
corners are actually turned, hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Stars won two consecutive games was Oct. 20
against Edmonton and Oct. 22 against New Jersey. Only twice this
season have the Stars strung together multiple victories _ a
three-game winning streak to open this season and that
aforementioned ``streak'' in late October.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, many Stars evoked the ``bigness'' of Sunday's victory
against the Atlanta Thrashers, the first of a four-game road trip.
Exactly how big won't be determined until Tuesday night's game
against the New York Islanders and Wednesday's game against the
Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as big as we make it,'' Stars defenseman Jamie Pushor
said. ``It's going to be how we respond the rest of the trip. We've
had a couple of games before where we thought we'd build on. We
have to come out and build on this victory. This is critical. We're
getting close to Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   A season ago, with 24 games gone and Christmas fast approaching,
the Stars were 15-5-4.
</P>
<P>
   A season later, confined by similar parameters, the Stars
(10-11-3) are looking at a chance to get to .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just shows you how the mark has shrunk,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``We have a chance to go to .500, and that's a big
step for us. ... Sometimes that's a hard slap at your ego, a
reminder of where you used to be and where you want to get back
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Where they are is still where a lot of teams wouldn't mind
being.
</P>
<P>
   They're almost .500 and about to get arguably their best player,
Selke Trophy-winner Jere Lehtinen, back after being out six weeks
with a fractured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The time seems right to make a move, and the players realize
that a single victory, a sloppily played one at that, against a
first-year expansion team doesn't mean anything if they don't build
on it. The table is set: The Islanders and Canadiens are both in
last place in their respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, so are the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not meeting with success and you used to be
meeting with it, it's frustrating,'' Hitchcock said. ``Some teams
would be happy to be playing .500 hockey. Our group isn't happy.''
</P>
<P>
   They've talked about solutions, everything from team building to
line changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're digging down and trying to dig ourselves
out of it ... ,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``Guys care.
Everybody wants to win. Everybody really cares about our team and
the way we are heading. I think that's the most important thing. If
no one cared, then we'd have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, their problems are a power play that isn't powerful, a
1-2 punch that has lacked No. 1 in Modano, who's in a goal-scoring
slump, and, ugh, the elusive team chemistry that Hitchcock has been
searching for all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's there yet at all,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's
an ongoing process that takes time. It doesn't get built
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems have been magnified by injuries (Lehtinen is just
the tip of the iceberg) and losing (it's not easy to go from
Stanley Cup champions to battling for .500).
</P>
<P>
   The solution could be as easy as winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like anything else. It comes with confidence,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We're making strides. Confidence doesn't come in big
swoops. It comes in little steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Or little victories coming one right after the other. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
