<HEADLINE>
STARS' CALL-UPS COULD STAY WHEN INJURED RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Lost amid the poor second period and the
come-from-behind victory Sunday was Roman Lyashenko's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' rookie center scored the first goal of his NHL career
at 7:54 of the third period. And excited doesn't even begin to
describe his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kissed the puck when he came to the bench,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Lyashenko and winger Brenden Morrow have made quite an
impact since being called up because of injuries to key players.
The problem the Stars find themselves facing is what to do when the
injured players start returning to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said it's going to be hard to send the two players
down, which means somebody else would have to go. A situation that
has a couple of guys looking over their shoulders instead of just
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a big factor right now,'' Hitchcock said.
``There are a number of things that come into play, stuff like
you're not sure what the team is going to be? Veterans aren't sure
who is going to be here and who's not. There is trust factor and
that's what makes a team is trust.'' LEHTINEN STATUS UNKNOWN
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said he hasn't ruled out injured winger Jere
Lehtinen (ankle) from playing in Tuesday night's game against the
New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't skate Monday because of tendinitis in his ankle but is
listed as day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the tendinitis goes away, he'll be ready to roll,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Stars injured winger Grant Marshall (groin) also skated Monday,
but Hitchcock said he's at least a week to 10 days away from being
able to play. CARBONNEAU A STEP AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Guy Carbonneau didn't accompany the team on the
trip from Atlanta to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he had planned on giving Carbonneau Tuesday off
anyway. So Carbonneau flew to Montreal, where the team plays
Wednesday. Carbonneau has family there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than drag him around and not play on the Island, we
figured we'd send him up there so he'd be fresh and rested,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   With Carbonneau out of the lineup, Hitchcock said he'd have
Brian Skrudland center the fourth line with Blake Sloan and either
Juha Lind or Jamie Wright. The third line will be Roman Lyashenko,
Mike Keane and Chris Murray.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
