<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS CATCH NAP IN LOSS TO KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the city that never sleeps, somebody apparently
forgot to wake up the Mavericks and tell them they had a game
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep at the wheel, the Mavericks were in Monday night's game
for only a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks led by 11 points after the first period, by
25 at the half and by 32 entering the fourth quarter before
embarrassing the restless Mavericks, 107-82, in front of a sellout
crowd of 19,763 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a good old-fashioned whipping,'' said center Shawn
Bradley, who finished with 15 points. ``It was like your dad took
you behind the barn and taught you a thing or two, and New York did
that tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no explaining it. They just beat us up, played better
than us and scored a heckuva lot more points than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Mavericks' offense and defense was malfunctioning, they
added another player to their ever-growing list of the walking
wounded. Guard Erick Strickland left the game in the first half
after a collision with Knicks guard Charlie Ward, and X-rays
revealed that he has a second degree sprain of his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland will fly back to Dallas today to have his shoulder
examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it happened,'' Strickland said. ``I just know
it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, point guard Steve Nash started the game and was
scoreless with four turnovers in 17 minutes. Nash said he could
have returned in the second half _ his tender right ankle was
bothering him _ but he said Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson wanted to rest him for Tuesday's 6:30 game in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel good, and it's pretty infected,'' Nash said.
``But I could have kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game was the first of a five-game road trip for
the Mavericks, who are 5-10 after dropping their sixth game in
their past seven outings.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Mavericks' worst loss of the season, as they caved
in early and often and never put up much of a fight against a
Knicks team that received a career-high 25 points from Ward, who
hit seven 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavericks forward Kurt Thomas helped do in his
ex-teammates. Thomas did not play in the fourth quarter, but
finished with a season-high 20 points ( 10 of 14 field goals) and
six rebounds in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a Dallas native and former TCU star, entered the game
averaging only 8.5 points. However, he was rejuvenated by seeing
the NBA jersey he used to wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates really made it easy for me tonight,'' Thomas
said. ``I was just fortunate enough to get some shots to go down
for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to play well in front of my friends and family
back home in Dallas who don't really get to see me that much. It's
nothing personal between Kurt Thomas and the Dallas Mavericks. Kurt
just wanted to go out and show the fans in Dallas-Fort Worth that
he can still play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Three consecutive baskets by Latrell Sprewell (15 points, eight
assists) increased the Knicks' lead to 97-62 early in the fourth
period. Not even another 20-point night from Michael Finley could
keep the Mavericks from the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what can I tell you but we were awful,'' Nelson said.
``I think their defense had a lot to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the worst game that we have played. As some of you
know we are devastated with injuries, and we have a lot more now to
deal with. It's not a pretty picture at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Cedric Ceballos, who was only 3-of-20 from the floor and
scored 10 points, said now it's gut-check time for the lowly
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could wake us up for the rest of the road trip, or it
could put us down under,'' Ceballos said. ``Hopefully this is the
opportunity for us to wake up and see what's going on.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
