<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-SOCIAL-SECURITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SOCIAL SECURITY RULES TO PENALIZE EARLY RERIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN AND CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- For everyone born in 1938 or later, the new
millennium is about to get longer.
</P>
<P>
   That's because new rules taking effect on Jan. 1 will force
workers to labor longer to get full Social Security benefits or
accept smaller payouts for retiring early.
</P>
<P>
   And while the new regulations have been publicized in the 16
years since then-President Reagan signed them into law, few
Americans realize that the rules are about to change, and even
fewer know how they will be affected, according to public surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem, definitely a problem,'' Dennis DeYoung, a
certified financial planner with Brookstreet Securities Corp. in
Tarzana, said Monday. ``I don't think people understand the
difference between today's dollar and future values.''
</P>
<P>
   The new bottom line: For those born in 1938 or later, the age at
which people become eligible for full Social Security retirement
benefits increases as the years pass by. And those who opt to start
collecting benefits at age 62 will get less than those who did so
before them.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Verderano, for one, isn't taking anything for granted when
it comes to his retirement, least of all Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to work as long as I can because it's different
nowadays. The environment is different,'' said Verderano, chief
executive officer of Matadors Federal Credit Union in Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   The changes initially affect people born in 1938 because they
will turn 62 in 2000 and become eligible for Social Security's
early retirement option plan.
</P>
<P>
   If a worker chooses to retire on his 62nd birthday in the next
calendar year, his early retirement benefit will be approximately 1
percent less each month than someone who retired on his 62nd
birthday in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And that same worker will have to toil until two months after
his 65th birthday to be eligible for full benefits. Those born
before 1938 become eligible for full benefits on their 65th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of additional months that people must work to receive
full benefits will increase geometrically. Those born in 1960 or
later will have to work until they are 67 for full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, there will be an increasing penalty for taking the
early retirement option at age 62. For example, those born in 1938
will receive 79.16 percent of what their monthly benefits would
have been had they waited until they were a couple of months past
65. Those born in 1960 or later will receive only 70 percent of
full benefits if they start collecting at 62.
</P>
<P>
   Mariana Gitomer, public affairs specialist for the Social
Security Administration in Los Angeles, said the eligibility age
for Medicare is still 65 and will not be affected by the change.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security payouts were changed to help balance the
agency's books and in reaction to the fact that Americans are
retired longer. ``Americans are living longer and healthier lives,
which is very good news,'' Social Security Commissioner Kenneth S.
Apfel said. ``But the system needed to create greater incentives to
work longer in order to continue to function.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of publicity, a recent poll of Americans 26 and
older found that nearly 60 percent think they will be eligible for
Social Security benefits before they actually will be. The poll was
conducted by the Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the changes, financial planners and government
officials alike advise that Social Security shouldn't be a person's
only retirement income. They say workers need to take advantage of
Individual Retirement Accounts and the 401(k) plans their employers
offer to save and invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are depending on Social Security as your retirement,
you're going to be in for a shocker,'' said Tex Matthews, Van Nuys
district manager for the Social Security Administration. ``Social
Security is designed to be a supplement to your retirement plan.''
</P>
<P>
   DeYoung advises his clients to figure that Social Security will
pay one week's worth of expenses every month and to prepare for a
long retirement. ``It's very possible that they're going to be
retired for more years than they were working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews said those worried about their benefits should look for
new Social Security statements that his agency recently started
mailing to workers across the country. The forms will show a
person's complete earnings history along with estimates of benefits
for early retirement, full retirement and for retirement at age 70,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new forms are the best tool for them to know what their
retirement situation is,'' Gitomer said.
</P>
<P>
   --30-- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
