<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4795 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TWIN-JAILED-LADN     11-30 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWIN-JAILED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY TO VOTE ON PROPOSED SETTLEMENT FOR TWIN'S ARREST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Friends of fraternal twins Ray and Jay Nugent say
their lives are a story of good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Arkansas, Ray and Jay Nugent looked so much alike
that they liked to switch identities as practical jokes on friends
and others.
</P>
<P>
   But as adults, Ray wasn't laughing when Los Angeles County
deputies mistook the former Eagle Rock resident for his brother Jay
_ a federal fugitive wanted on bank robbery charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ray ended up spending 13 days in jail for a crime he didn't
commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unfortunate mistake,'' said principal Deputy County
Counsel Roger Granbo.
</P>
<P>
   County supervisors are expected to vote today on an offer to pay
Ray $150,000 for his time behind bars in exchange for dropping Los
Angeles from a $13 million federal lawsuit _ a million for every
day he was kept in jail with violent criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very unusual case in which the FBI was looking for
this guy, and we had his twin brother in custody,'' Granbo said.
``Once the Sheriff's Department confirmed he was not the person
wanted in the warrant, it took them four days to release him, and
that's why we settled the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray has agreed to take the county's proposed offer, although he
originally sought $385,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to use the money to publish a book I wrote and buy
my mother a house,'' said 43-year-old Ray, who now lives in his
hometown of Alexander, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really got upset with my brother,'' Ray said.
``Anybody can see that we don't look alike. What really got me
upset was that they made me a criminal because of what my twin
brother did. They said, if I have a twin brother who did that, I
must be like him too. It's that mentality that disturbs me.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted he doesn't know the whereabouts of Jay, although
authorities said the trail led them in 1991 to the wilderness of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found his belongings below an avalanche,'' Ray said. ``I
don't think he's dead, but it's information my family would like to
know. The FBI said they have no reason to believe he's dead because
he's a survivalist.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past is any measure, Ray will have more run-ins with the
law, at least until Jay is found.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, South Pasadena police checked Ray's driver's license
after a minor traffic accident and discovered his brother's
warrant. They held him five hours before releasing him with an
apology and a card with an FBI contact number so any law
enforcement officer who pulled him over could verify Ray was not
wanted on the warrants. Ray laminated the card and put it in his
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's troubles can be traced to June 17, 1985, when police said
a bank robber stole $7,000 from the St. Landry Bank and Trust Co.
in Opelousas, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real gunbattle,'' Opelousas Police Chief Larry
Caillier said. ``It was one of the biggest bank robbery operations
in this city in a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   After a car chase, the robber disappeared into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Police issued a warrant for the arrest of Jay Nugent for armed
robbery and two counts of attempted murder of police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Ray, a general contractor, was working in
Malibu on June 9, 1993, when he pulled his van off the road to walk
on the beach. When he returned, Malibu sheriff's deputies noticed
he was illegally parked.
</P>
<P>
   When deputies ran Ray's identification on the computer in their
patrol car, they found the warrants for Jay, Granbo said. The birth
date and birthplace were the same, and the physical description
matched.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies asked Ray if he had ever been to Louisiana, and he said
yes. The deputies believed Ray was the person named in the warrants
and arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   Ray showed them his card and told them the warrants were for his
twin brother.
</P>
<P>
   Opelousas police sent a teletype the next morning requesting a
hold be placed on Ray pending an investigation into his identity,
Granbo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten calls on him from all over the United States,''
Caillier said. ``You're dealing with twins. When you stop him, you
have no way of knowing if you have him or the bank robber.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Department asked Opelousas police to send a photo
of Jay and a certified copy of his fingerprints. Meanwhile, family
and friends of Ray attested to his identity, and an Arkansas
congressman and another of Ray's brothers, a Little Rock police
officer, called to seek his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``His brother is his twin brother, so naturally it sounded
crazy, like the good twin, evil twin,'' said Roberta Ikema, an
attorney for Los Angeles-based Public Interest Investigations, who
helped free Ray.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18 _ nine days after Ray was picked up _ the Opelousas
police acknowledged the wrong person was in custody, but it took
four more days before Ray was released, Granbo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think the process was real slow, and it should have
been faster,'' Granbo said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's attorney, Meir Westreich, contends that the Opelousas
police and sheriffs purposely delayed sending the information as
part of a conspiracy to force Ray to give up the whereabouts of
Jay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is he doesn't know where his brother is, and it's
possible his brother is dead,'' said Westreich, of Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the case of mistaken identity, the Sheriff's
Department has instituted changes to prevent similar situations in
the future, including enhanced policies relating to warrant arrests
and close monitoring of court ordered releases of inmates to ensure
they are released in a timely manner. When an inmate is
``over-detained,'' a sheriff's supervisor must conduct an inquiry
to identify the reason and corrective action taken.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is continuing to pursue his federal lawsuit against the
Opelousas police because the department has refused to implement
changes that would prevent future cases of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court trial is scheduled in Los Angeles for Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Caillier called Westreich's allegations outlandish and ``a
crock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawyer is trying to milk the cow dry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was a decision not to release him,''
Granbo said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ray, his false arrest has made him more philosophical
about freedom. A general contractor and long-haul trucker whom
friends describe as an eccentric science enthusiast and bookworm,
Ray moved into the woods after his incarceration and wrote a book
on the uses of light for new energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this happened, it changed my whole outlook on life. I
went to the national forest and became a mountain man, living off
the land,'' he said. ``It sort of woke me up. My brother may be up
in the mountains living a mountain man life too.''
</P>
<P>
   --30-- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
