r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-SECESSION-L     11-30 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-SECESSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD TO HITCH A RIDE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD -- A fast-track effort for cityhood for the nation's
entertainment capital could piggy-back on the San Fernando
Valley-Harbor area secession study, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of a movement to split Hollywood from Los Angeles plan
to launch a drive to get 15,000 signatures by June to trigger a
formal study by the Local Agency Formation Commission, the county
agency that will start similar studies for the Valley and San
Pedro-Wilmington area in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood VOTE's timing is critical if it wants to keep pace and
possibly get all three cityhood measures on the ballot in 2002 _ a
move that would enhance chances for the secession movements to win
the necessary local majority as well as citywide majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they start the petition process in January and they in fact
do it within six months, I think they could probably still make
it,'' said Larry Calemine, LAFCO executive officer. ``If they're
looking to piggyback on this thing, I would suggest they move at an
accelerated pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Voters Organized Toward Empowerment leaders this week
are beginning to meet with homeowners groups and neighborhood
activists in both Hollywood and neighboring communities to gauge
support and determine boundaries for the proposed city.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to capitalize on the civic pride and desire for better
schools and streets that led the community to incorporate as a city
a century ago. Hollywood was annexed by Los Angeles in 1911 because
the larger city controlled the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan and City Council members representing
Hollywood strongly oppose the new cityhood effort but supporters
remain confident of obtaining the estimated 15,000 signatures from
registered voters needed to qualify for the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right window of opportunity. We didn't want to miss
the boat,'' said Fares Wehbe, a Hollywood VOTE board member.
``People think we're our own city. So why not do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood VOTE expects to begin circulating petitions in
mid-January and will rely on both volunteers and paid signature
gatherers, leaders said. Under state law, the group has six months
to gather signatures from 25percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Both opponents and supporters of cityhood cite Hollywood's
revival, led by commercial development and dropping crime rates, as
reasons why cityhood will either resonate or fall flat with
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg has championed many of the projects
that have helped Hollywood rebound, including the city-subsidized
Trizec-Hahn shopping and entertainment center going up at Hollywood
Boulevard and Highland Avenue and featuring a theater to house the
Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's (cityhood) going anywhere,'' said Sharon
Delugach, Goldberg's press deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is on the upswing in particular because of what the
city has done. It's no accident. One could say, If it ain't broke,
don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some cityhood supporters contend many gains have come
despite City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is improving steadily and without the yoke of the
city it would take the lid off to really allow Hollywood to come
into full bloom,'' said Jerry Schneiderman, a developer
specializing in office redevelopment. ``We really want to see
Hollywood have the opportunity for some self-determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehbe, financial director for the Little Red School House, said
successful Neighborhood Watch groups are an example of community
involvement that could bolster the cityhood movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the many groups,'' he said. ``The galvanizing
issue is to see if we can make it better for the children, for
people to run their businesses. It is our obligation to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Hollywood cityhood proposal is generating a lot of
discussion because it is such a bold bid to take from Los Angeles
the city's very identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a lot of interest in it and that's probably
because of Hollywood's enormous role in L.A.'s image. Hollywood is
the top selling point for L.A.,'' said Leron Gubler, president and
chief executive officer for the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark Hollywood sign, for instance, will be the focal
point for the city's millennium celebration. The sign will be
lighted on New Year's Eve _ for the first time since the 1984
Summer Olympics _ with accompanying laser animation, graphics and
aerial displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you can rest assured that the city won't let Hollywood go
without a fight,'' Gubler said.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber has not taken a position on the issue, but is one of
many expected to eventually decide whether cityhood should be
supported.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, merchants and civic leaders in the Los Angeles
communities next to Hollywood also are watching, including Hancock
Park to the south and Silver Lake to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it starts to develop we may develop some opinion about
it,'' said Jim Wolf, president of the Hancock Park Homeowners
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock Park residents have shown some interest in a proposal to
form a separate city out of communities on the city's Westside,
though that effort hasn't moved ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Hancock Park residents want city government to more
closely represents the needs of the city's many communities. ``The
city of Los Angeles is so large a mechanism to identify that there
are varying interests between neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said community leaders support the effort to reform the
city's government charter through neighborhood councils and
regional planning commissions rather than breaking Los Angeles
apart. Wolf said the community just south of Hollywood likely would
want to remain outside the boundaries of the new city if it was
formed.
</P>
<P>
   If both Hollywood and the Valley became cities, the two might
solve several longstanding traffic problems on city streets in the
Cahuenga Pass, said Tony Lucente, president of the Studio City
Residents Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is, Could these cities cooperate to solve
regional traffic issues? There's always an alternative that might
work better, and maybe this is something to consider,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of greater local control is strong with the
burgeoning third cityhood movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly brings credibility to the concept of reorganizing
the city of Los Angeles,'' said Jeff Brain, president of Valley
Voters Organized Toward Empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
