r s BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN     11-30 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY EYES HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The tribute, spontaneous and genuine, is repeated
every time a pack of thoroughbreds and jockeys thunders down the
Hollywood Park homestretch with Laffit Pincay in contention.
</P>
<P>
   While his opponents on the track do their honorable best to try
to beat Pincay _ to slow his final surge toward Bill Shoemaker's
record _ idle riders in the jockeys' room gather around
closed-circuit TV pictures and urge him on.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding track programs, hairbrushes or empty palms, they slap
their hips like horseflesh, all those imaginary whips exhorting one
mount, Pincay's mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a cheering section,'' Kent Desormeaux said last
week, describing the scene. ``If there are 10 jockeys in the race
and 30 jockeys in the room, then Laffit's carrying the weight of 30
guys with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is rooting for him,'' said Alex Solis, a fellow
Panamanian who has won 12 local riding titles _ putting him 22
behind his boyhood idol.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime soon _ perhaps before his 53rd birthday, Dec. 29 _
Laffit Pincay (pronounced la-feet pink-eye) will ride the 8,834th
winning race of his career and capture the world record Shoemaker
has held since 1970. As a new racing week begins Wednesday, he
needs nine victories to tie the mark.
</P>
<P>
   In racing circles the achievement will be compared to Pete Rose
passing Ty Cobb, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar passing Wilt Chamberlain,
Wayne Gretzky passing Gordie Howe, Walter Payton passing Jim Brown.
But it will be different.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any other time a sport's ultimate record falls, there is
debate over the new holder's credentials, some small attempt to
discredit his accomplishment, to suggest he had it easier than the
old hero, that he's undeserving of history's crown.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. In Pincay's case it seems to be unanimous: He's
the right man for the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to be broken, there's nobody better to do it
than Laffit Pincay,'' said Shoemaker, who rode his last race in
1990 and now, at 68, is confined to a wheelchair after a 1991 auto
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just deserves it,'' said trainer Mike Mitchell, who calls
Pincay ``the greatest rider I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget his feats in the saddle,'' said East Coast-based jockey
Jerry Bailey, who has been competing since 1974 and has been the
nation's top big-race rider in the '90s _ and is some 4,000 winners
short of Pincay's career total. ``His dedication is just
unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   Dedication is the quality most often connected to Pincay and is
the reason he is so admired. He's an old-school gamer who has been
known to accept a mount on a 70-1 shot in the last race on a Friday
night, long after the other Hall of Famers have gone home.
</P>
<P>
   If dedication has a vaguely dull connotation, in fact the 35
years since Pincay rode his first winner in Panama have been
anything but that, whether he liked it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay fans inside and outside the local jockeys' rooms can
recite the obstacles he has ridden through, notably the suicide of
his first wife and a career-long battle with weight.
</P>
<P>
   They can also recite his accomplishments: five national Eclipse
Awards, more than any other jockey, trainer or owner; seven
national earnings titles; career-wins records at Hollywood Park,
Santa Anita and Del Mar; a record seven-win day at Santa Anita in
1987; seven Breeders' Cup victories; and the Kentucky Derby and
Belmont Stakes victories aboard Swale in 1984, that Belmont win
being the last of Pincay's three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   When Pincay was inducted into racing's Hall of Fame in Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., at age 28, he had come a long way fast since
beginning his racetrack life at 15 mucking stalls in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two years after his first winner, May 19, 1964 in Panama,
he was hired by horse breeder and owner Fred Hooper to ride in
Chicago. Pincay won with his first mount, July 1, 1966, and four of
his first six at Arlington Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a made rider, a very good rider,'' Cotton Tinsley, who
trained Pincay's first U.S. winner, said at his Santa Anita barn
last week. ``He didn't speak too much English, but he was a quick
learner.''
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians Pincay, Braulio Baeza, Manny Ycaza, Jacinto Vasquez
and Jorge Velasquez opened the door for younger Latin American
riding stars like Solis.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they broke in, people didn't judge you by your accent
(but) by how you rode,'' Solis said.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay first encountered Shoemaker when the latter rode in an
Arlington stakes race in 1966. Pincay was struck by how small
Shoemaker was. Shoemaker was immediately struck by Pincay's
physique and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not difficult to tell somebody who has class. It's like
looking at a horse. A lot of it (riding ability) you're born
with,'' said Shoemaker, who took the career-wins record from Johnny
Longden with No.6,033 in 1970. ``Of course, he still had to perfect
his timing and learn what individual horses need.''
</P>
<P>
   After leading the jockey standings at Arlington, Pincay moved up
to the Southern California tracks that have been his office for
three decades, and beat out Shoemaker and others to win the 1968
Hollywood Park title. Shoemaker had won 15 in a row. Pincay would
win nine of the next 12.
</P>
<P>
   Fans came to recognize the difference in their styles _
Shoemaker's quiet finesse, Pincay's sheer power. Even now, Pincay,
the oldest rider at any major U.S. track, dazzles his rivals with
the seeming ability to ``carry'' an exhausted horse to a desperate
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're going by, and his horse keeps going,''
Desormeaux said. ``That's profound.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own reckoning, Pincay had his greatest season in 1979,
when his victories included a historic Jockey Club Gold Cup aboard
Affirmed _ holding off repeated challenges by Shoemaker and
Spectacular Bid.
</P>
<P>
   That he's still competing at the sport's highest level 20 years
later is a testament to a body that, local trainer Bill Spawr said,
``doesn't know his age,'' and a heart that doesn't know the meaning
of quit.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker, 4-foot-11 and 95 pounds in his riding days, never
faced the weight problems his pursuer has. Pincay's struggle to
keep his muscular, 5-foot-1 frame at 113 pounds is so celebrated
that he said he plans to capitalize by writing a diet book when he
retires (whenever that will be).
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the struggle led Pincay to pills, induced vomiting and
other dangerous shortcuts that left him physically and emotionally
frazzled. A constant wooziness on horseback and frequent fistfights
with other jockeys were hints he was hypoglycemic.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, Pincay has tinkered with diets, and only two years
ago he hit upon a high-fiber, 850-calories-a-day menu that works.
Six mornings a week in the gym maintains what sports surgeon Robert
Kerlan used to call ``the best physique I've ever seen on an
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can ride eight horses (in an afternoon) and feel good after
the races,'' Pincay said at Hollywood Park recently. ``Of course, I
wouldn't want to do that every day ...''
</P>
<P>
   There was a point when some wondered if Pincay would ever do it
with his old intensity again. That was the period in 1985 after his
first wife, Linda, mother of two of his three children, shot
herself to death in their Los Feliz home. Linda had battled pain
and depression for about a year after suffering a ruptured
appendix.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter of a horse owner, Linda had been described by racing
writer Gordon Jones as ``like a celebrity politician's wife,
fiercely loyal, totally involved.'' After her death, Pincay was
quoted saying at the time, ``I felt like a hole opened up and
swallowed me. I didn't care whether I rode or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks later he rode and won again, and later in 1985 he
took over the career-earnings lead from Shoemaker with more than
$100 million in purses.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys bank something less than 10 percent of their horses'
purses, so Pincay should have been a millionaire many times over.
When he discovered he wasn't _ after the IRS blindsided him with a
bill for more than $300,000 in back taxes in 1987 _ he sued his
longtime business manager. He eventually won a $2.9 million
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the financial mess, Pincay thought he'd have to
keep riding just for the money.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as he has fought the inevitable injuries (he
has broken his collarbones 12 times in his career) and horsemen's
inclination to patronize younger riders, his motivation has been
been somewhat grander. Pincay wants the record.
</P>
<P>
   He has been riding with his old vigor, winning about once a day
since the Hollywood Park season began Nov. 10, and now the question
is whether No.8,834 will come at Hollywood, which closes Dec. 20,
or at Santa Anita, which opens Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it happens, the cheering section in the jockeys' room
will be thrilled for him.
</P>
<P>
   So will Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do deserve it,'' Pincay said when somebody posed the
question that nobody seems to be asking. ``There have been so many
times I thought about quitting, I thought about giving up, but
because of my love for the game, I kept hoping things would get
better. And they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I didn't give up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
