<SLUG> BC-BKC-BONSIGNORE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SHOPPING SHOULD BE UCLA PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One forward comes from the West Indies, the other
grew up in Kansas City. The center is from Massachusetts, by way of
Holland. The point guard lives in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't the Lakers starting lineup. It's this year's UCLA
men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Jerome Moiso, JaRon Rush, Dan Gadzuric and Earl
Watson, all talented young players with bright futures. But since
when does UCLA need to look any further than Southern California
for most of its players?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it certainly seems as if Bruins coach Steve
Lavin would rather look elsewhere, based on the makeup of the
current roster. Aside from freshman Jason Kapono, who's from
Lakewood, the impact players come from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be so blatant, but with sensational freshmen like
Grant High's Gilbert Arenas and Glendora's Casey Jacobsen bursting
onto the national scene at Arizona and Stanford, respectively, UCLA
fans must be wondering why the Bruins didn't land at least one of
those gems.
</P>
<P>
   They might even think Lavin isn't tending to his own backyard,
that he foolishly thinks the talent is better in New York or
Chicago than Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   They're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, we'd like to have 80 percent of our roster from
(Southern California),'' Lavin said. ``It makes sense for a lot of
different reasons. But sometimes, maybe because a talent base was
thin one particular year or some kids weren't good fits
academically, we have to look elsewhere for players. Fortunately,
we have enough of a national name, even international, that we can
go into a Kansas City or a Michigan and get players.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, recruiting is such a wacky process, it behooves the Bruins
to mine every imaginable area for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't put all your eggs in one basket like that,''
Lavin said. ``Let's say it's a down year for talent, or maybe
somebody decides to go someplace else, if you don't have a backup
plan, that could set you back a few years. Now you're looking at
the NIT.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono is a great example of how things work out sometimes.
Basically, he was a gift that fell into Lavin's lap.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono desperately wanted to be a Bruin, and UCLA considered him
its No.1 recruit. But it also targeted forwards Carlos Boozer from
Alaska and Kareem Rush from Kansas City, plus Baron Davis was still
on the team, taking up a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono looked at the situation and decided he'd be better off
somewhere else. The Bruins felt he wasn't interested in them, and
they were right.
</P>
<P>
   Utah was in the picture, as was Rhode Island, Missouri, even
Nevada Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a case of the player thinking the school didn't want him,
and the school thinking the player didn't want it.
</P>
<P>
   Then fate took over. Boozer and Rush settled on Duke and
Missouri, respectively. Davis left UCLA for the NBA, freeing up a
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Then it looked as if UNLV would go on probation, which took the
Running Rebels out of the picture. Missouri coach Norm Stewart
stepped down, eliminating the Tigers. Rhode Island fell out when
Jim Harrick moved to the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you know, Kapono needs UCLA and the Bruins need
Kapono.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is probably one of the best freshmen to come (to
UCLA) in 20 years or so,'' Lavin said. ``Sometimes you just never
know how it's going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono is exactly what UCLA needs, a mature, team-oriented
player not concerned about his own scoring or numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, if he gets homesick, it's just a 35-minute ride down the
San Diego freeway to Artesia _ OK, maybe an hour with traffic.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot different from the plane trips Watson and Rush have
to make to return home to the Midwest, which they've both done
during the season since arriving in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA doesn't need that. The best players in the country reside
within a car-ride's trip from its campus. At the very least, there
are enough Southern California players to field a nationally
competitive team every single year.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. The core base for the Bruins' NCAA titles came
from California. Sure, every once in awhile John Wooden would reach
beyond the state line to pluck out an impact player, but only for
extreme talents like a Lew Alcindor or Lucius Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The rest came from California.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walton, Keith Wilkes, Gail Goodrich, Keith Erickson, Lynn
Shackelford _ all kids from Southern California. All members of
Wooden's UCLA championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jim Harrick's 1995 NCAA champions had a distinct California
flavor. Ed and Charles O'Bannon came from Artesia, Toby Bailey from
Los Angeles and J.R. Henderson grew up in Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   It just shows that the Bruins are better served concentrating on
the elite players from the area, rather than trying to pull in kids
from all across the country. That's not a knock on kids from New
York, Michigan or North Carolina, only that history has shown that
California players stack up against anyone from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The key is keeping them home.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has a responsibility in that regard. The Bruins are the
standard bearer for West Coast basketball. Their objective each
year should be to build a team of home-grown players, then send
them off to represent this part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   They might not win every year. But we'll take our chances with
the kids from the neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
