<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ANYONE CAN LIFT LAKERS, IT'S ZEN MASTER JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Horace Grant isn't quite sure what to expect from Phil
Jackson and the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics center might walk into the locker room before the
game Tuesday night and find the place smoking like a Buddhist
temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lights incense. We'd walk into a room and it would be full
of smoke, to kill the evil spirits,'' Grant said, thinking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Phil being the Zen Master he is, he can sell swampland in
Alaska,'' Grant said, smiling, but with great respect.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Grant won three NBA championships with Jackson
in Chicago before heading to Orlando to team up with Shaquille
O'Neal, Grant has a little extra insight into the inner workings of
the new Phil Jackson Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team in which Woodstock collides with Showtime _ an
NBA, post-Jordan experiment that invites all sorts of skepticism
... unless you are Horace Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The wise veteran is sold on the idea that the Lakers will
prosper under Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Phil's into the Zen stuff,'' Grant said. ``I have one
of those Zen books at home that I bought a couple of years ago. I
have to get that out of the closet and dust that off.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant wasn't exactly joking.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Jackson recommended a certain book to Grant _ a common
practice of Jackson's, whose mission is to draw respect and power
from players so that they form the sacred bond of a team. The last
time he tried this experiment, the Bulls won six NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book was called `Joshua,' '' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about a carpenter who went into this little town, and
this carpenter turned out to be an angel, so to speak. Phil sort of
called me the diamond in the rough. The message of the book was to
be kind. Good things will happen to you. I think it's the workman's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much respect for him, whenever he did something like
that, it was for a reason. Being a veteran ballclub, we were very
intrigued by the books he gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Sonics have sprinted off to an eye-opening 11-3 record
and sit ahead of the Lakers in the feisty Pacific Division of the
loaded Western Conference, Grant thinks these cowabunga Lakers will
indeed catch hold of the psychic wave Jackson emits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Phil's first year. If anyone can convince a Michael
Jordan to run the triangle offense, then he can take care of the
situation in L.A. If he could contain a personality like Dennis
Rodman, he can take care of L.A.'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the world has been waiting for the Lakers to bust out
of their terrible toddler stage and seize control of the
postseason. The NBA Finals were supposed to be the Lakers' new
address.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the Magic Johnson stint as head coach _ one
that left the NBA great pulling his hair in anguish over the
selfishness of the Lakers players.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the Del Harris phase _ one that child-star Kobe Bryant
dismissed with the comment: ``Guys tuned out Del from Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, last season there was the short-lived reign of Kurt
Rambis, who had no better luck with his juvenile charges than his
predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, Rambis had so little control of his
players that he once screamed at Bryant during a timeout: ``Fine,
do whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's method is much less chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize, Phil is from the '70s. He's a straight-up
peace guy. He knows how to deal with different personalities,''
Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, despite the monstrous task of coalescing the bickering
Bryant and O'-Neal, a misplaced Glen Rice and a disgruntled Robert
Horry into a team, Jackson has had one major obstacle cleared.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, O'Neal has been especially eager to put his trust,
faith and career in Jackson's hands. And even if O'Neal is the
quintessential L.A., hip-hop, movie-star rapper, he is not a tough
sell on Jackson's psycho-spiritual methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (what Jackson preaches) is baloney,'' Grant
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to buy into it for it to be very successful. Shaq's
got to buy into it, and I think he's already done that. When I was
in Chicago, Michael had to buy into it first and everyone else fell
into order.''
</P>
<P>
   With the youthful Bryant out with a broken hand since training
camp, the Lakers have been able to establish O'Neal as the kingpin
of Jackson's vaunted triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jackson has lamented that O'Neal will be a flawed
leader until he overcomes his free-throw problems, O'-Neal is among
the league leaders in scoring, rebounding, blocked shots and
field-goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Batman is at work for L.A. Now the trick for Jackson will be to
establish Bryant as O'Neal's Robin _ much the same way Jordan had
Scottie Pippen as his running mate all those years in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is convinced Jackson can get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Phil is he never lets it get old. Even during
film session. We'll be watching film ... and he would stick a clip
of `Slapshot' right in middle of it. Phil would just go to
`Slapshot' for like four or five minutes and we would just sit
there, watching,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was always a meaning behind something he does. Like
the time he put a clip of `Full Metal Jacket.' The scene of the
drill instructor just chewing this guy out. I guess Phil was just
sending a message to the guys who messed up the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers coming in to play the Sonics, it was always
interesting. Now, with the Zen Master in charge, it could be out of
this world.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
