<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERSON LOOKS FORWARD TO FACING TEAM THAT CUT HIM LOOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonics forward Ruben Patterson insisted he may not be
able to sleep, not with the Los Angeles Lakers in town.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. He has dreamed about Tuesday night's Pacific Division
showdown in KeyArena since the schedule was announced, eager to
show his old team what he has become in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd pleaser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a grudge against them,'' Patterson said. ``I can't
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The first 14 games this season have been like a dream for the
second-year small forward. The Sonics are 11-3 in part because of
Patterson's youthfulness, athleticism and energy.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him play is often like waiting for the home run
distance to show on a major league scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   You can't wait to see how far he will go.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when he takes off like a jet, such as the night
in Philadelphia. What began with a leap just inside the foul line
ended with Patterson soaring past the 76ers' Larry Hughes for a
monster dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there are those occasions when he pounces like a tiger.
Allen Iverson knows. The prolific scorer was chased down from
midcourt only to have a would-be dunk pinned against the backboard
by Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Those are examples of how Patterson has permeated the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that he had a future in the
NBA,'' said Kurt Rambis, who coached Patterson last season with the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some nice defensive potential. He does a great job
running the floor. He rebounds. He plays hard. But like most young
ballplayers, he has some things to work on. ... He's just a
hustle/effort kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics want Patterson to dive for loose balls rather than
attempt his so-so jump shot. However, it is Patterson's tenacity on
the boards and defensive skills that won him the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly made fans forget Detlef Schrempf, who was a staple at
the position for six seasons. Fact is, Patterson's 14.6 points and
7.1 rebounds a game are near what Schrempf produced (15.0 and 7.4)
last season.
</P>
<P>
   And Patterson is younger and more apt to defend the quicker,
brash small forwards in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to play against Ruben. That's one of the best
compliments you can give a player,'' teammate Brent Barry said.
``You'd hate to face him if he was on the opposing side. But I'm
glad he's on my team and I can throw alley-oops just about anywhere
because he can go get them. The bottom line is he comes out every
night for us a steady force. You know you're going to get
aggressive, 110 percent effort from him. That goes a long way in
making up for some of the deficiencies in your game.''
</P>
<P>
   His weakness is an inconsistent outside shot, but the Sonics saw
all they needed in the Boston summer league. There, he lived up to
the 1998 scouting reports after he left the University of
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously was dying to prove himself, and did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a chance to show the world what I can do. A lot
of people are noticing what I'm doing for the Sonics,'' Patterson
said. ``So I'm just going to keep rebounding and giving it my all.
A lot of guys knew I was talented, and I'm a great player. I just
didn't have a chance to play (in Los Angeles). It feels good to
click on the TV and see myself sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson almost never saw Showtime in Los Angeles last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a grudge against them. I can't wait,'' Patterson said
of Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   His poor outside shot is one reason he did not fit in as a
rookie with the Lakers. It was a no-brainer that Rambis chose to
divide minutes between Kobe Bryant, Glen Rice and Rick Fox over
Patterson, whom the Lakers took 31st in the 1998 NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson averaged 2.7 points in six minutes a game. Rambis
concedes Patterson ``did a very good job of guarding Kobe in
practice. But practice and games are two different stories. There
are no fouls called in practice. ... Is he going to be a superstar
and all-star? I don't think so. But he's going to have a long,
constructive career.''
</P>
<P>
   So Patterson's productivity and popularity really has come out
of nowhere for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were only sure of a couple of things,'' Sonics president
Wally Walker said. ``One, he is going to play hard. Two, he's going
to be very confident. He's not intimidated by anyone or any
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton hasn't been as impressed as most fans by Patterson's
impact. Payton has periodically taken Patterson aside to check his
attitude. Earlier this week, Payton even held a private film
session with Patterson to point out defensive weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I want him to succeed but I don't want him to get a
big head until he does something,'' Payton said. ``Ruben hasn't led
us to a championship. We haven't won anything. ... This is his
second year in the league. Let him keep building and don't look at
those papers and `SportsCenter' and say, `Whoa, I'm good.' I did
that my first three years and I struggled a lot. Then, I realized I
have to stop watching the papers and the news and just play
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came out and said the `Kobe Stopper' stuff, I didn't
like that. ... That's just running your mouth. As you see, a lot of
the (small forwards) have been killing us. They've been having 30
and 35 points. He hasn't been stopping them. So he's just a `Kobe
Stopper?' Naw. We don't want that. Prove it to people on the court
instead of with your mouth. Then, when you do that, it's a
different story. Right now, he's not playing defense to me. I'll
tell him and I'll tell whoever. He knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sonics coach Paul Westphal enjoys Patterson's passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play in this league _ especially as a defensive
player _ and think any other way,'' Westphal said. ``You ask any
defensive player if he's afraid of who he's playing against. He'd
say `no' and you have to have that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Patterson has epitomized attitude _ as well as altitude
and fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident I can play in this league,'' Patterson said.
``I'm just glad I'm in the right place at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
