<HEADLINE>
TEAMS RELYING ON RECEIVERS, NOT RUNNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this weird, wacky NFL season, one thing has become clear:
Teams are relying much more on their wide receivers than their
running backs to produce game-turning plays.
</P>
<P>
   In contests played Thursday and Sunday, there were 11 100-yard
receivers and only five 100-yard rushers. Over the season, there
have been 110 100-yard receiving days and only 72 100-yard rushing
days.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the running games have been compromised by the
retirement of Barry Sanders, and the injuries to Jamal Anderson,
Terrell Davis, and Garrison Hearst. But offenses are also using
their wide receivers more because defenses are using more eight-
and nine-man fronts to stop the run and pressure the quarterback.
This alignment puts cornerbacks one-on-one with wide receivers, who
have capitalized by getting open with more frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Randy Moss, Jacksonville's Jimmy Smith, and
Indianapolis' Marvin Harrison are tied for the league lead with
five 100-yard receiving days. Smith, Moss, and New England's Terry
Glenn have all had one game with at least 200 yards receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Cris Carter, Chicago's Marcus Robinson, Carolina's
Mushin Muhammad, Detroit's Germane Crowell, Denver's Ed McCaffrey,
Oakland's Tim Brown, and Kansas City's Derrick Alexander each have
four games with at least 100 yards receiving..
</P>
<P>
   Although Moss has a club-record 331 yards receiving in his past
two games, he isn't even the hottest receiver on his team.
</P>
<P>
   With 136 yards and two touchdowns against the Chargers, Carter
surpassed 100 yards for the fourth consecutive game. He has 10
touchdowns in the 22 quarters since Jeff George replaced Randall
Cunningham as the starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is a leading candidate for MVP honors. If he doesn't get
it, perhaps another wide receiver will. TRASH TALKING
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Giants linebacker Jesse Armstead openly ripped his
offense in the club's loss at Washington. Armstead, presumably with
foot in his mouth, was unavailable for comment after the Giants
defense allowed 34 points to the Arizona Cardinals, ranked 29th in
total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Said Giants defensive end Michael Strahan: ``I'm still trying to
figure it out. I don't know how in the world they scored 34
points.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who were 5-3 at the season's halfway mark, are now
5-6, and their playoff hopes are fading faster than team unity.
YOUNG BUC
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers rookie quarterback Shaun King is set to take over the
starting role with the season-ending injury to Trent Dilfer (broken
collarbone). But if King is to master the quarterback position, he
at least has to get the basics down.
</P>
<P>
   In the Buccaneers' 16-3 victory over the Seahawks, King tipped
off the Seahawks defense. While in the huddle, King would hold up
one finger if the snap count was, ``on one,'' and he'd hold up two
fingers if the snap count was, ``on two.''
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneerss guard Frank Middleton finally realized the Seahawks
were on to King.
</P>
<P>
   ``For goodness sake!'' Middleton roared at King. ``Don't tell
'em the snap count.'' OBSERVATIONS
</P>
<P>
   It's about time that Steelers coach Bill Cowher benched
quarterback Kordell Stewart. Stewart has had more than enough time
to learn the position. And while no one expected him to be perfect,
the Steelers did expect him to get better. Instead, he got worse
and is the sole reason the club as dropped home games to dreadful
Cleveland and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   In their past two games, the Vikings defense has yielded
400-yard passing games to Jim Miller and Jim Harbaugh. Think Brett
Favre isn't betting he can get 500 when the Packers play at
Minnesota on Dec. 20?
</P>
<P>
   If the playoffs started today, the Cowboys would have the final
postseason spot. But that's not an entirely bad thing. Their first
playoff game would be at Washington, whom they've already swept
this year. It wouldn't get hairy until the next week, when they'd
have to play at St. Louis. Grading the NFL Vikings Air Game: A
Against the Chargers, Randy Moss, Jake Reed, and Cris Carter all
had touchdowns in the same game for the first time since Moss
joined the club last season. Denver Broncos: D Don't give me the
John Elway-Terrell Davis-Shannon Sharpe excuse. On offense they
average more total yards per game than Buffalo, Dallas, Detroit,
Tennessee, Seattle, Miami, and Tampa Bay. On defense they allow
fewer yards per game than St. Louis, Dallas, New England,
Tennessee, Detroit, Seattle, Green Bay, Washington and Minnesota.
So why is Denver 4-7? Dick Vermeil: A With his club already leading
the Saints, 36-12, the Rams coach could have ordered his club to
kneel on the ball late in the game. Instead, he called a simple
running play that sent a backup running back into the line for a
short touchdown with 1:14 remaining. ``I thought about kneeling on
the ball down there, but Mike Ditka is not a kneel-down type guy,''
Vermeil quipped. ``I don't think he would accept that as a gesture
of sportsmanship. That's not his nature.'' Good thinking, Dick.
LYONS' Top 5 1. Indianapolis 9-2 2. Jacksonville 10-1 3. Tennessee
9-2 4. St. Louis 9-2 5. South Grand Prairie (Tx) High, 12-1 (This
spot was to be for either Miami or Seattle, but those teams
combined to score a whopping three points in their respective
games. The Warriors, meanwhile, are in the state quarterfinals.) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
