<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-ROOKIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED ROOKIE SAYS TEAM ABANDONED HIM, SOURCE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An NBA source said the Mavericks refused to give
rookie forward Leon Smith complimentary tickets to two home games,
forcing him to purchase tickets from a scalper.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based source also said Smith admitted he attempted
suicide Nov. 14, and left a note thanking Mavericks coach/general
manager Don Nelson and his son, assistant coach Donnie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the note didn't say thank you for providing the
opportunity to play in the league, or thank you for being gracious
in helping me,'' the source said. ``The note just said, `Thank you
Don and Donnie.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Leon what did he mean when he wrote the note, and he
said, `I was saying thank you Don and Donnie for messing me over,
because if it wasn't for them I wouldn't be in this predicament.'
''
</P>
<P>
   When Don Nelson was asked before last night's game against the
New York Knicks about Smith, he said the NBA had asked him not to
talk about Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, executive director of the National Basketball
Players Association, said Smith left his aftercare players
assistance program in Atlanta and has been back at his Oak
Lawn-area apartment since Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purvis Short (of the NBPA) and I were with him until (Nov.
24), then I left to come back here and Purvis went back to
Houston,'' Hunter said Monday. ``Purvis returned to Dallas
(Monday), and is there now with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Purvis went to Dallas to help Leon open up a checking and
savings account, and also help him to get some ID. He doesn't have
any picture ID, so he's trying to help him get a driver's
license.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's agent, Matt Muehlebach, said he couldn't comment on
Smith's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when the time is right everybody will be willing to
say everything they can,'' Muehlebach said. ``We're just trying to
do what we can to protect him and give him an opportunity to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people pulling for him. We all hope
it's going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The league source said Smith purchased tickets from a scalper
for the Mavericks' Nov. 9 home game against the Los Angeles Lakers,
and the Nov. 13 game against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 14, Smith was found passed out in his apartment after an
apparent overdose of aspirin, according to a police report.
</P>
<P>
   While Don Nelson has repeatedly said Smith got a lot of
attention from developmental coaches Bill Peterson and Kiki
Vandeweghe, and from player personnel director Amadou Gallo Fall,
the league source said Smith told him he felt like an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistreatment was so bad that basically Leon was informed
that he shouldn't come around, and that they didn't want him in
touch with anybody on the team, and they didn't even want him
around the arena because it would distract the team,'' the source
said. ``Leon is a young kid, and he thinks Dallas drafted him
because they were interested in him, and they were going to give
him a fair shake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Leon's vulnerability is due to the fact that this kid
has been rejected all of his life. This is the first time he's been
given an opportunity to step up, and when he didn't get that
opportunity he just didn't
</P>
<P>
   know which way to go; he didn't know how to digest it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter stopped short of saying Smith should ask the Mavericks to
trade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the other players in the league have had no
difficulties making the transition from high school and college to
the NBA,'' Hunter said. ``In each of those instances, they all had
support networks that were put in place for the kid, and apparently
there was nothing put in place to assist Leon.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
