<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-AHMED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM BEGINS WITH ELATION AND PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With IMMIG-DETAIN) 
(sw) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the first things that Nasser K. Ahmed did in
his first hour of freedom on Monday night was to pray for five
minutes at the Al-Bader mosque, about a half-block from his
apartment in the Bensonhurst section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a Muslim tradition,'' he explained. ``You praise God
when he delivers you from trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, 39, was allowed to leave the Metropolitan Correctional
Center in Manhattan at 8:15 p.m. after three and a half years in
federal detention while the Immigration and Naturalization Service
sought to deport him to Egypt using secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed was elated to be able to return home to his wife of 13
years, Salwa Al-Byadi, 38, formerly a physician in Egypt, and their
three children, but he was still bitter at the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, boy, the kids are driving me crazy now, taking Polaroids
of everybody,'' Ahmed said in a telephone interview. ``It's been
three and half years now, and I still have no idea who accused me
or why they accused me. But this I know. What the government did
was similar to what happened in Waco, Texas. They tried to destroy
that religion, the Branch Davidians. There is no doubt that this,
too, is a government conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the evidence against Ahmed was released and successfully
refuted by his lawyers. Perhaps the most damaging allegation was
that Ahmed visited Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman, the blind Egyptian
cleric convicted in 1995 of conspiring to plant bombs at the United
Nations and other New York landmarks, and that Ahmed carried one of
the cleric's letters out of prison. When published, the letter is
said to have led to an attack by Muslim fundamentalists against
tourists in Egypt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were at least two other people at the prison three
days before I visited,'' said Ahmed, who denies any involvement in
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed acted as a paralegal for the sheik during his trial. ``I
definitely admire and respect and love him,'' Ahmed said. ``And he
did not do what the government said he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, who worked as an electrical engineer before he was
detained, doubts that he could return to his job after so much
time. ``I may have to go back to school,'' he said. ``My future is
the most difficult question to answer now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 0130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
