<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     11-30 1996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ After two months of steady advances
into Chechnya's heartland, the Russian military said on Monday that
it is beginning to encounter serious resistance from Islamic
militants, and that the fighting is likely to intensify in the next
few weeks. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CHILD (Miami) _ A 5-year-old Cuban boy who survived a
Thanksgiving Day rafting tragedy by clinging to an inner tube for
two days has become the focus of an international tug-of-war. Cuba
blames the United States for the tragedy and says the child had
been kidnapped by his mother, who died during the voyage. The boy's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and Cuba's Foreign Ministry have
demanded his return. Gonzalez has filed a complaint with the United
Nations to draw international attention to the issue. By David
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOOK (New York) _ A small Manhattan publishing house has
agreed to publish 25,000 copies of James Hatfield's controversial
book on George W. Bush, ``Making of an American President.'' The
author stands by the drug charges in the book but admits to his own
prison past. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-CALLS (Undated) _ For Ruth Smith, the telephone call from
prison was a way for her cousin to speak with his dying mother. For
Tulen Rivera, the calls from prison are an opportunity for her
three boys to speak with their father. For Ruby Jackson, speaking
by phone with her imprisoned husband was a chance to talk without
having to spend eight hours on an overnight bus. But for New York
state, like most other states, telephone calls from prison are
something else. They are a way to make money. Under current state
policy, the families of inmates are charged the highest possible
rates for calls from prisons, and most of the money is kept by the
state. By John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-DEVICES (Undated) _ Thousands of heart specialists
watched on closed-circuit television monitors as a tiny
experimental device was implanted in a patient's coronary artery.
The doctors heard the voice of Dr. Martin Leon, who was describing
the operation taking place in a hospital many miles away. But Leon
was anything but a disinterested observer. What he did not tell the
assembled doctors was that he was an investor in the company that
manufactured the device. He is not the only one to wear many hats
in the world of medical devices. Inventors are researchers.
Researchers are promoters. Promoters are investors. And, finishing
the circle, investors are inventors. It is a phenomenon found in
every medical treatment using devices, from laser surgery to gene
therapy. A special report. By Kurt Eichenwald and Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ One of the constants in
financial markets is that they regularly defy expectations. This is
true of the newest leg of the Japanese yen rally against the dollar
and the euro's plunge against the dollar and the yen. If they
continue, these moves could produce a numerical symmetry never seen
in the currency markets: the world's three major currencies all at
one _ 100 yen to the dollar and one dollar to the euro. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ Small Chinese investors and would-be
investors have been converging at new stock brokerages all over
China ever since China and the United States signed a trade
agreement that is expected to lead to China's membership in the
World Trade Organization. They have come filled with hopes and
worries, theories and predictions about the economic impact of the
deal. ``As soon as I heard the thing was signed I put all my money
in,'' said Liang Yongbin, a 31-year-old chef. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOOR-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The battle among advertisers for
eyeballs is not limited to the Internet. There is still warfare
being waged street by street as more marketers _ including dozens
of dot-coms _ turn to outdoor advertising to increase awareness of
their products and services. By Stuart Elliott.
