<P>
   GLF-CLUB-DISCRIM (Undated) _ Just weeks after a jury in Boston
found that a suburban country club had systematically discriminated
against a group of women golfers and awarded the women $1.9 million
in damages, the Massachusetts attorney general has asked a judge to
appoint a monitor to take over the country club. The takeover, if
approved, would mark the first time that a court took such direct
control of a private country club. By Marcia Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-ARATON-COLUMN (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Sports of The Times on the
only football coach on the Hofstra campus with a playoff team. It's
not Bill Parcells, whose Jets team is headquartered at Hofstra and
now has no shot at the postseason. It's Joe Gardi, whose Hofstra
team is now in the quarterfinals of the Division I-AA playoffs. By
Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COSMOLOGY-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Continued evidence over the
last year that the expansion of the universe is accelerating has
provided fresh new evidence of the distressing finding that
something in the wastelands of space could be pushing against
gravity. So scientists are reluctantly accepting the notion that
something in the most fundamental theories of physics is terribly
wrong. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CAROLINA-FLOODS (Undated) _ Scientists fear that the
post-hurricane flood of eastern North Carolina has created an
ecological time bomb, and they fear for the biologically rich
waters that separate the famous Outer Banks from the Carolina
mainland. This complex of sounds, bays and inlets comprises the
second largest estuary in the country, after Chesapeake Bay, and is
one of the nation's most important incubators of marine life.
Rarely have ecologists confronted such a striking example of what
can happen when a first-order natural disturbance is combined with
a first-order disturbance of the natural world by humans. By
William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-POLIO (Undated) _ The Doctor's World: The provocative
theory that AIDS is a manufactured disaster arising from early
testing of the polio vaccine in Africa seemed farfetched when it
first came to public attention, in an article in Rolling Stone in
1992. Most scientists dismissed it after a scientific committee
reviewed the theory and deemed the probability very low. But that
panel based its conclusion in part on a published finding that was
later shown to be in error. And now a remarkable new book, ``The
River'' by Edward Hooper, offers tantalizing clues to revive and
expand the polio vaccine theory. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-POLE (Undated) _ Less than a century after explorers
made their first heroic assault on the poles of Earth, an American
spacecraft is racing toward Mars and the first landing in the polar
region of another planet. The robotic Mars Polar Lander is being
aimed for a landing on Friday on the vast terraces of ice and dust
a few hundred miles from the planet's south pole. Spring is turning
to summer there, the season of constant sunlight, which the
spacecraft will draw on for energy to power its computer and
transmitter and array of cameras, sensors, digging arm and ovens
for heating and analyzing soil samples. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLOTKIN-RAINFOREST (Undated) _ Scientist at Work: Dr. Mark
J. Plotkin, who staked his reputation on finding new medicines in
the rain forest. But he earliest efforts at finding great medicines
failed, forcing him and others to recognize that even in the rain
forests medical miracles are rare. By Jon Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YEAST-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ Essay: New discoveries with
individual yeast cells raise intriguing questions about future
evolutionary possibilities. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
pollution automobiles generate by stirring up dust, a snake with
unusual eating habits and the Eberly telescope. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEVERS (Undated) _ Fevers can be mysterious, which is when
the challenges multiply. The hospital is always filled with
patients with fevers no one understands. In some, it is a sign of
an underlying disease that is not yet known. In other people, like
AIDS or cancer patients with suppressed immune systems, the fever
may have any number of causes, including their underlying disease
or, most dangerously, an infection that could rapidly kill if left
untreated. Whatever the case may be, mysterious fevers are common,
and among the most vexing of medical problems. By Sandeep Jauhar.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHILDREN-SPEECH (Undated) _ Parents now are being told to
seek speech therapy earlier for children who are exhibiting
problems, a sharp change from previous years when adults were
assured that often, very bright children did not learn to speak
until they were much older. The new advice is based, in part, on
studies showing that children with speech impairments are more
likely to have reading and social problems later on. By Randi
Hutter Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Research showing much puberty for
girls arriving much earlier than previous studies had shown could
force textbooks and medical schools to revise the age at which
puberty is considered premature. Current medical textbooks state
that just 1 percent of girls younger than 8 show signs of puberty.
In a new review of existing data, in the Oct. 4 issue of the
journal Pediatrics, researchers concluded that ``the onset of
breast development between 7 and 8 years of age in white girls and
between 6 and 8 years in African-American girls may be part of the
normal broad variation in the timing of puberty and not, in most
cases, a pathological state.'' By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLDER-ATHLETES (Undated) _ A new generation of older
athletes are healthier than their predecessors, living longer and
pointedly aware of the importance of getting and staying in shape.
They are forming pickup teams, creating senior divisions in sports
leagues and competing in large-scale events in gyms and playing
fields across the country. By Linda Villarosa.
</P>
