<HEADLINE>
USC FALLS SHORT IN BID FOR UPSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC wants to consider itself on the path back to
the elite among women's basketball teams. Texas Tech showed Monday
night the Trojans have some work ahead.
</P>
<P>
   USC led the 16th-ranked Red Raiders for most of the game, but
Tech overcame a six-point deficit in the final two minutes of
regulation and won 66-63 in overtime at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Plenette Pierson's one-handed bank shot with one second
to play forced overtime. It was her first career buzzer-beater and
it gave her a game-high 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tech (4-0), specifically guard Katrissa O'Neal (17 points),
took advantage of its athleticism, using a back-door play
effectively to build a 64-60 lead. Despite committing 27 turnovers,
USC (2-1) had a chance to tie in the closing seconds, but Ayesha
Smith's 3-point attempt was long.
</P>
<P>
   This was USC's first overtime game since Dec. 29, 1996, a
double-overtime loss to Western Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a classic example of _ I don't want to be a
cliche-ist,'' USC coach Chris Gobrecht said, ``but we stopped doing
the things that got us there: pressure, denial. We just froze up
and let them take it from us, which I hope is a hard lesson for a
team that has never done this before.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, USC hasn't beaten a Top 25 team since March 2, 1996,
against then-No. 22 Oregon State. And on paper, it didn't appear
the game would be this close.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Trojans haven't played together for long. Their top
scorers Monday, Denise Woods (19 points, 8 rebounds) and Danielle
Golay (14 points, 6 rebounds) are transfers. Plus, Texas Tech came
in with five players averaging in double figures. Yet USC used its
advantage in the post to go on a 12-3 run in the last 4:59 of the
first half and lead 33-26 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans defense limited Tech to 32-percent first-half
shooting and 39 for the game. Guard Aleah Johnson, averaging 17.3
points, scored zero in the first half and finished with nine. USC
also outrebounded Tech 43-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to run plays and they weren't working,''
Pierson said.
</P>
<P>
   Golay, meanwhile, was effective down low, scoring 10 straight
points, including the first six of the second half, giving USC its
biggest lead _ 39-30 with 17:02 to play.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Raiders contained Golay, Woods came off the bench
and took over. She scored the go-ahead basket with 15 seconds to
play in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot to develop in terms of the eye of the tiger,''
Gobrecht said. ``This is a good basketball team that has a lot of
toughening up to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
