<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     11-30 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE teams he played on at Texas might be described as streaky. His
first year, the Longhorns won their last four, including a shutout
of Ole Miss in the Bluebonnet Bowl. His junior year, their six
victories came in the middle of the season, and when he was a
senior they finished by winning their last nine.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing uneven or inconsistent about the career of
Chris Gilbert, who pretty much gave you 100 yards per game on the
ground and knew how to break the long ones, the way little boys run
for touchdowns in their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Next week it will all come back to him _ if any of it ever left
_ the games and golden moments of more than 30 years ago. On Dec.
7, a day that will not live in infamy, Chris will become the 10th
Texas player to be inducted into the College Hall of Fame. Bobby
Layne, the blond bomber of the mid-1940s, was the first to be
honored, in 1968, Gilbert's senior year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the legendary Texas running backs, he joins Jimmy Saxton,
who came before, and Earl Campbell, who came after him. The
ceremonies will be in the grand ballroom of New York's Waldorf
Astoria, and Gilbert will be part of a class that includes Herschel
Walker of Georgia, Greg Pruitt of Oklahoma, John Hannah of Alabama
and Billy Kilmer of UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his selection was announced in April, Chris has been
hearing from old teammates and friends saying how happy they are
for him. It would hardly be possible to feel any other way, because
Chris Gilbert hasn't changed since he was a schoolboy out of Spring
Branch. He has the gifts of gratitude and modesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully flattering,'' he says, ``to do something 30 years
ago and have it remembered and honored all these years later.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been hard to remain humble when Texas finished
6-4 when he was a sophomore and junior, seasons Darrell Royal
described as ``disasters.'' By Texas standards, they were.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris went quietly about his business, getting an education
and slip-sliding away for lots of yardage. That first season, he
rushed for 245 yards against Baylor. As a junior, he had a 96-yard
run against TCU that is still the longest from scrimmage in Texas
history. He also carried the ball 38 times against Arkansas and
ended the game without any body parts missing.
</P>
<P>
   That season the Longhorns rallied to beat Oklahoma 9-7 after
trailing at the half and hearing Royal lecture them in the locker
room: ``There's a heck of a fight going on out there. Why don't you
guys get in on it?''
</P>
<P>
   In each of his three seasons, Gilbert rushed for more than 1,000
yards, a feat that had never been accomplished before in college
football in the days of the 10-game schedule. He did a couple of
things Campbell and Ricky Williams, the UT Heisman Trophy winners,
did not do. He averaged better than 100 yards per game each year
and was voted the Most Valuable Player by each of his teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris never gave anyone the impression he was about scooping
up records and honors. Loyalty and friendship were the rewards for
the 5-11, 175-pound tailback, who turned down a chance to play in
the pros with the New York Jets. He chose a career in business, and
he chose wisely. He and his roommate, Corby Robertson, are partners
today in a sports camp outside Austin, one of several enterprises
Gilbert has seen turn into successes.
</P>
<P>
   It may be old-fashioned, even out of date, but the National
Football Foundation counts such things when it chooses a former
player for membership in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   This was a week for remembering, given the Bonfire tragedy at
Aggieland and a game in which emotion flowed like lava. Chris
thought back to his last regular-season game for Texas, standing on
the sideline at Memorial Stadium, watching the clock tick down on a
one-sided Longhorns victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was over at halftime,'' he said, ``and we had our
third- and fourth-stringers on the field at the end. I didn't even
think about finishing my Texas career on the sideline. I just
thought about how great it felt, knowing we had accomplished
something, had gotten on a roll and had turned the program
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas had averaged almost 500 yards per game, over 330 on the
ground, with the wishbone-T that Royal and Emory Bellard had
developed in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most fun I had,'' said Chris, ``was in practice, watching
coach Royal and coach Bellard invent plays on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two years, we played power ball. I was the only
running back in the I-formation, and that was pretty much the
offense. The wishbone was a totally different animal. It was a
wonderful change for me to become part of a multifaceted offense.
We had James Street, Ted Koy, Steve Worster and myself in the
backfield, and it brought out the best in everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
