<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4832 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      11-30 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ The great thing about playing an archrival is that you
don't have to worry about getting up for the game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad thing about playing an archrival is that it is often
difficult to get up for the next game.
</P>
<P>
   That is not particularly good news for Texas, considering it is
coming off an emotional loss to Texas A&AMP;M and its next opponent is
the No. 3-ranked Nebraska Cornhuskers in Saturday's Big 12
Championship Game at the Alamodome in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the Longhorns say there's no need to worry about their being
able to bounce back. Something would be really amiss if they can't
get up for Nebraska, especially with the Big 12 title on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're playing Nebraska is probably good after
the loss to Texas A&AMP;M, because it's not our last game,'' Texas
coach Mack Brown said. ``Our guys have so much respect for the
Nebraska team that they'll get themselves back up and be ready to
play. If we were playing somebody we didn't respect this week, it
would be very difficult. We'll have to move through the A&AMP;M game
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he has found it less difficult to prepare his team
when it is an underdog, as it is against the Cornhuskers, rather
than a favorite, as it was against the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to coach in Austin when it's a big game
against an opponent that the fans and the media respect than
against a team with a losing record or a team that you're supposed
to beat,'' Brown said. ``That's hard around here. I've learned in
two years that it's hard when everybody says that a team is not
going to beat you to get your team to listen. But when everybody
says you're going to get beat, there's no question the team
listens, so they'll be focused for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Kwame Cavil said it may not be that easy to toss
aside the A&AMP;M loss, but the Longhorns know that with quarterback
Major Applewhite slowed by illness and receivers Ryan Nunez (toe)
and Jeremy Jones (ankle) out of the game with injuries, they were
far from being at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   With Applewhite not playing until the fourth quarter because of
a stomach virus, Texas had its worst passing game of the season
against the Aggies, mustering just 183 yards through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just write it off,'' Cavil said. ``That's a rivalry
game. It sticks with you all your life. But we'll be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The passing performance) was a concern, but I knew we didn't
have all of our bullets in the chamber. We know what we're capable
of doing. We've done it before. You have to play with the cards
you're dealt sometimes, and we were dealt a bad hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns may have helped deal themselves a poor hand by
adding an extra game this year. Texas opened the season Aug. 28
against North Carolina State. Fifteen weeks later, the Longhorns
will play their 13th game.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to a typical team like Texas Tech, which began its
11-game season a week after Texas and ended it two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Texas already has nine wins, typically a good season, but should
it lose to Nebraska and in a bowl, it will finish with five losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine wins is a whole lot of wins for any team,'' Brown said.
``Next year we play a 12th game with Hawaii. I'm not sure if you
should do that here. A&AMP;M did it last year. If you're going to have
to play 14 games with the championship game in the Big 12 and the
SEC, I'm not sure that you should put your kids in that position,
because it makes the season so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe we're playing a 13th game this weekend,
and we're not through. It's hard to imagine. But I'm not going to
let anything that happens diminish what this team has been able to
accomplish. This is a team that people were talking about winning
five (games). I don't want to talk about a loss Saturday or a
possible loss in a bowl game because that would be negative, and
that's not my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said it doesn't matter how many games his team has played.
This one is special, and he won't have to use any tricks to get his
squad ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team will be motivated for this game. I mean, it's the
championship game,'' Brown said. ``This is an easy week for both
teams to motivate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about our team is they respect the Nebraska
team and program, but they're not intimidated by 'em, so they'll
enjoy this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
