<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS &LR;      11-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Nebraska's players seem resigned to the fact that their chances of
playing for the national championship probably have ended, but
their coach continues to state his team's case.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nebraska coach Frank Solich believes a convincing victory over
Texas in the Big 12 Championship Game on Saturday should give the
third-ranked Cornhuskers a chance at passing Virginia Tech for a
spot against top-ranked Florida State in the Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it a couple of different ways,'' Solich said.
``It's a difficult issue. Without question, Virginia Tech should be
congratulated on going undefeated because it's not a small feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you look at it on strength of schedule and look at the
teams they have played, the only one that is in the Top 25 at the
end of the season is Boston College, and they just got in a week
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech ended the regular season 11-0 after defeating
Boston College 38-14 on Friday. BC fell from No. 22 to No. 25 in
the Associated Press poll after losing to the Hokies.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech played three other teams that were ranked when
they faced them _ Virginia, Syracuse and Miami _ but the Hokies
have not played a Top 10 team this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (10-1) has played four teams that are ranked among the
top 18 in the latest AP poll, including eighth-ranked Kansas State,
which the Cornhuskers defeated 41-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on how you look at it,'' Solich said.
``Strength of schedule is mixed into the equation, but I don't know
how much. I know Virginia Tech has an excellent football team, and
I know how hard it is to go undefeated. We lost one game, which
came down to the end (24-20), to an excellent Texas team.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bowl Championship Series rankings that came out Monday,
Virginia Tech increased its lead over Nebraska from .63 to 1.54.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia Tech has handled its business all season and came out
on top,'' said Nebraska defensive back Mike Brown. ``Going
undefeated speaks highly of their team. They deserve a shot (at the
national championship) as much as anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also would be proud if we ended up with a spot in the
big game. It's every player's dream to play for a national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The final BCS standings, which determine the teams that will
play in the title game in New Orleans, will be released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies' advantage, according to one BCS computer expert, is
all but impossible to overcome _ even if Nebraska routs Texas in
the Alamodome at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no suspense,'' said Chicago-based BCS computer wizard
Jerry Palm. ``If Nebraska wins 50-0, I'm not sure that could
overtake Virginia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS standings are based on a formula that considers the AP
media poll and the USA Today/ESPN coaches poll, eight computer
rankings, strength of schedule and losses.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska probably blew its chance by barely beating unranked
Colorado 33-30 in overtime Friday after the Buffaloes missed a
field-goal attempt that would have won the game at the end of the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways we were fortunate to come out ahead,'' Solich
said. ``But in other ways our team came back at the end and got it
done. I'm proud of what our team has done down the stretch against
Texas A&AMP;M, Kansas State and Colorado. In two of those three games,
the score would indicate it was not close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska players don't seem to have Solich's zeal for making
an argument in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel Virginia Tech deserves it,'' said Nebraska running back
Dan Alexander. ``They haven't lost, and they've proven they are a
quality team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not concentrating on the BCS right now,'' said kicker
Josh Brown. ``Our goal always has been to win the Big 12
championship, and now we have to beat Texas to do it. Whatever else
happens is not in our control.''
</P>
<P>
   Solich was pleased to hear his players aren't worrying about the
BCS rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell our players are concentrating on winning this
game,'' Solich said. ``We're not trying to battle for position
here. We're trying to win a game against Texas, and that's no easy
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to overcome a major hurdle in the Longhorns before we
can be considered for anything else. If we don't win the Big 12
championship, it's all a moot point. If we do, it will come down to
the people who do the voting and enter the numbers into the
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The people crunching the numbers say the Cornhuskers probably
can't do enough to finish No. 2 in the complicated BCS formula that
has many fans screaming for a playoff format.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the system we have in place, and until a better system
comes on board, we have to get behind it,'' Solich said. ``But
certainly there will be some disappointment for the team that gets
left out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
