<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES     11-30 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GRIZZLIES </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ If there was any chance they might
actually do it, Rockets officials might be tempted to have Compaq
Center crowds boo Steve Francis lustily. He could pretend his name
was Lou or assume some similar-sounding nickname and respond as he
did Monday night, as if lifted to some new level.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grizzlies fans threw everything they had at Francis, from taunts
to insults to fresh fruit. Months of waiting to rebut the wrongs
they believed he did them built up until a crowd normally
anesthetized by losing was venomous and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Francis won the argument with his play, refusing to be rattled
by the treatment. More impressively, he won the game by refusing to
let the Rockets lose.
</P>
<P>
   Francis nailed a last-chance jumper to send the game to
overtime, then carried the Rockets to a secure lead. And after he
jogged off toward safety with 35.8 seconds remaining, he headed
happily out of town with a 118-100 win over Vancouver and his best
game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy, but I didn't want anybody to get hurt,'' said
Francis, whose only response to the crowd was a salute when he
fouled out with 2:45 left in overtime. ``I never knew people took
it that seriously to try to injure somebody. I didn't know they
were that serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just played Steve Francis basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he might have learned to thrive in such an
environment, his teammates might have learned something about him.
Francis finished with 24 points on 10-of-18 shooting and had 10
assists, nine rebounds, two blocked shots, two steals and zero
turnovers. And he was at his best with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was first and foremost,'' Rockets forward Carlos Rogers
said. ``Everybody had a part, but the way Steve played tonight, you
can't say enough about him. We used to get on him about turnovers,
and he had none. And 10 assists. He did everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything, however, was not enough until he added a little more
with the Rockets at the brink of what has become a typical night.
Charles Barkley had 22 points. Kelvin Cato had 10 rebounds and five
blocked shots. The Rockets' bench came up with an irreplaceable 50
points.
</P>
<P>
   But with Grizzlies fans still howling and the Rockets down to
their last breaths, Francis took an inbounds pass from Matt Bullard
and with 2.6 seconds left in regulation nailed a jumper from just
inside the 3-point line to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   He even began overtime with a 3-pointer, and the Rockets never
slowed down. Cuttino Mobley hit a technical free throw after an
illegal-defense call. Francis passed to Barkley for a jumper, then
passed to Bullard for a 3, then nailed a jumper to put the Rockets
ahead 111-106. Even after Francis fouled out, Bullard nailed
another 3 to put the Rockets ahead 114-106.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great that everybody hit big shots,'' Francis said.
``They missed free throws at the end, and we hit the shots we had
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mobley, ``Those were the shots we were missing. We made
them tonight, and hopefully it will carry over.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a difference in the shots made Monday and the many
late shots missed in previous games. On Monday, they were knocked
down with the Rockets back in the role of enemy, rather than
struggling former power. Halfway through the fourth quarter, the
15,086 in GM Place grew particularly ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the direction the night was turning, Barkley took the
attention and pressure, at first drawing the wrath of the
Grizzlies' fans and then inspiring them to begin tossing produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' Barkley said of his attention-grabbing response
to the fans. ``I've done that many times in my career. I felt like
it worked to my advantage to get them on my case, and Steve played
really well after that.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Barkley was trying to take the pressure off his protege,
he also took over the game. After twice missing free throws, he
passed to a cutting Kenny Thomas for a layup, posted up and drove
to a layup, then drew a foul, sandwiching two made free throws
around the cleanup of a lemon smashed across the court.
</P>
<P>
   After Barkley put the Rockets up 89-85 with a steal and a dunk,
that was enough to make the Grizzlies to do whatever they needed to
take the ball out of his hands. In the final 3{ minutes of the
fourth quarter, Kelvin Cato missed a layup and a 12-footer, Mobley
missed a 10-footer on the baseline, and the Rockets seemed to be
themselves setting up another close defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The miss that seemed to hurt the most came with 29 seconds left
and the Rockets down by two. Francis drove to the lane, drew the
defense on him, then sent a pass outside to an uncovered Barkley.
After first thinking better of it, Barkley launched a 3 that
missed. Sharif Abdur-Rahim made two free throws for a four-point
lead. And when Francis missed a free throw with 20 seconds left,
the Rockets were a few Mike Bibby free throws away from being 3-12.
</P>
<P>
   But Bibby missed a free throw, and Mobley nailed a 3. And with
10.4 seconds left, Bibby missed another free throw to give Francis
an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did an unbelievable job not making it too big a deal,''
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``I know his emotions were
high. If he would have reacted differently, it would have been
common. He's young, and he's never been through a situation like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up winning the battle with Bibby, the point guard
Francis believed already had his job when the Grizzlies selected
him.
</P>
<P>
   And he even proved himself a pretty fair evaluator of talent. He
said he didn't want to play in Vancouver because Bibby was already
there and was himself a gifted point guard. Bibby proved him right,
leading the Grizzlies with 25 points on 9-of-18 shooting. But he
had just five assists with six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a free throw that I should have hit to seal the
game, but I missed it,'' Bibby said. ``I put a lot of blame on me.
We've got to finish games off. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have been saying the same thing. But Monday, they
didn't have to, instead singing the praises of the center of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a great player one day,'' Barkley said. ``The
best way to shut them up is to play like he did tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
