A4837 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     11-30 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING AN EYE ON HIS INVESTMENT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ A short, round 80-year-old man comes every day
to the construction site of the new USF law library. He pulls up a
chair and watches the work, for hours, as if the pounding and
pouring and puttering were a great sunset or a wonderful movie.
<P>
   But it's better than that for Art Zief. The library is his baby
and he's watching the birth.
</P>
<P>
   Art is a graduate of the USF law school. As an undergrad in the
early '40s, he was an athlete. Sort of. The Dons' freshman
basketball team had 13 jerseys, and Art got the 13th. He scored one
basket in his career, and judging from his stature, I'm guessing it
wasn't a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Art loves the school and decided last March to give $3.2 million
to the library, which will carry his wife's name, Dorraine Zief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not  &UR; my  &LR; library,'' Art says, but he's the only guy I
ever knew who bought a season ticket to a construction site.
</P>
<P>
   The best part, he says, was watching the steel go up. When the
steel boys finished their amazing work, the general contractor
threw them a big lunchtime pizza party right there on site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Art,'' the steel workers called to the old guy in the
chair, ``get over here and join the party.''
</P>
<P>
   For $3.2 million, Zief got a slice of pizza and a can of soda,
and he can't believe what a sweet deal it is.
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY LITE: Karen Warner was heading for Thanksgiving dinner
at relatives' house, and her sister-in-law asked her to bring a
sharp knife for the turkey. So Warner wrapped a large carving knife
in a paper towel, put it in her purse and forgot about it.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to dinner, Karen and her boyfriend stopped at SFO to
pick up an arriving relative. Karen sent her purse through the
X-ray machine and ... nothing happened. So she carried her purse,
with carving knife, to the meet-the-plane area, then to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think paper towels deflect X-rays?'' Karen asks.
</P>
<P>
   HOBO.COM: The National Hobo Society has a Web site (hobo.org)
which, I would guess, gives tips on the best ways to do nothing.
There's also a goodwife.com, offering mail-order brides online,
possibly to hobos.
</P>
<P>
   Which has my pal Lonesome Lefty wondering when someone will
write a country song about how ``I lost my online bride to my best
pal, Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   BEAT A PARKING ticket? It might be possible to successfully
appeal a citation in San Francisco, but the bar is set fairly high.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Oklopdzic's car was slapped with a $30 citation for being
parked on a street during street-cleaning hours. Oklopdzic's excuse
was that he had a heart attack and was rushed to Seton Hospital for
quadruple-bypass surgery, making it difficult to move his car in
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``After investigating this protest,'' reads the letter Mike
received from the Department of Parking &AMP; Traffic, ``we have found
the following: there is no parking allowed during the posted street
cleaning hours. The citation is valid and your protest is denied.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to see some of the protests that are upheld by DPT.
</P>
<P>
   PIGGING OUT on Thanksgiving leftovers was not part of the
holiday festivities for many of the city's homeless. All the local
shelters served up wonderful Thanksgiving Day meals, then most of
them, especially the big ones, shut down for the long three-day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   St. Anthony's bucked the trend and stayed open, scuffling to
handle the extra load of hungry folks, showing once again that when
it comes to doing what St. Anthony's does, nobody does it with more
heart.
</P>
<P>
   FUSION FOLLIES: Walt Giachini figures he discovered the ultimate
expression of fusion dining. The Hyatt at Incline Village, Nev.,
has a restaurant called the Ciao Mein Trattoria.
</P>
<P>
   Says Walt, ``It reminds me of the `Odd Couple' episode where
slob Oscar heats up two TV dinners, one Italian and one Chinese,
and slaps the two trays together.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Sacramento orthodontist Dr. Gloria Nollie,
father African American, mother Japanese. Dad's favorite dish is
chitlins teriyaki.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIRAGE: On a recent afternoon, a 26 Valencia bus stalls at
Chenery and Roanoke.
</P>
<P>
   The driver picks up her radio microphone to call the Muni yard
for help. Just then, an SUV pulls up next to the bus, the SUV
driver rolls down his window and screams at the Muni driver, ``Get
off the cell phone!''
</P>
<P>
   And on Fifth St. near Market, a bicyclist, perhaps annoyed by
the heavy holiday traffic of fossil-fuelers, swings his chain-lock
like a bolo and shatters the side-view mirror of a car. A pedal-by
chaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good thing that driver doesn't have a gun,'' my cabbie says.
``A whole lot of people in this town are carrying guns, you know, I
mean a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's your holiday tip if you're looking for an
inexpensive, easy-to-find gift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
