<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-WTO-FOES-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-FOES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO, FOES FIND LITTLE COMMON GROUND IN SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SEATTLE _ With protest swirling in the air blowing in off Puget
Sound, the World Trade Organization reached out hesitantly to its
many critics gathered here Monday _ and got a chilly response.
<P>
   The WTO held a carefully scripted conference with
nongovernmental organizations _ the think tanks and activist groups
that have lambasted the trade body as a corporate-dominated
oppressor of the world's poor. It was billed as a historic event,
the first time the WTO had opened itself to the grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the event was staged showed the global group's
extreme ambivalence toward the idea. Most of the panelists were
government officials and speakers apparently chosen because they
oppose shedding further light on the WTO's secretive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few critics were allowed to the podium. The rest sat
steaming in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   WTO Director General Mike Moore set the tone by warning that
proposals to include labor rights and environmental protections in
the WTO's rules only hurt the interests of the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a contradiction among those who give generously at
church on Sunday when there is a flood or earthquake in the Third
World, then on Monday sign a petition to lock out the products
their workers create,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told there could be up to 50,000 demonstrators against us
(today),'' Moore added. ``But remember: In over 30 countries, 1.5
billion want to join the WTO,'' he said, referring to the 30
nations, including China, that have WTO membership applications
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers took a tougher line. Britain's international
trade minister, Clare Short, said, ``A lot of the criticism is
seriously misplaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University economist Jagdish Bagwati _ a prominent
pro-free-trade theoretician _ attacked the critics for what he
called ``a fear complex'' about the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization is a force for good, prosperity and equality,''
he said, adding that any suggestions otherwise are ``just
rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the seats in the vast hall of the Washington State
Convention and Trade Center, Lori Wallach packed her briefcase and
headed out in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either through hubris or ignorance, these guys think that by
lecturing to us and telling us, `You just don't understand,' over
and over again, that will shut us up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard-educated lawyer who is director of Public Citizen's
Global Trade Watch, a Washington-based think tank founded by
consumer advocate Ralph Nader, Wallach is one of the WTO's most
articulate and relentless critics.
</P>
<P>
   The few WTO critics who made it to the podium were more
deferential than Wallach, but their comments were pointed.
</P>
<P>
   Vwelinzima Vavi, a leader of the Congress of African Trade
Unions in South Africa, countered Moore by insisting that the trade
body adopt rules against labor and environmental abuse. Julian
Edwards, director of Consumers International, said the WTO's
current regulations discriminate against a wide variety of
consumer, health and safety laws in many nations.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's forum was held the day before the start of the WTO's
summit meeting, which is expected to open the way for a new series
of trade agreements on a great variety of economic subjects.
</P>
<P>
   But the WTO's rigid rules of secrecy _ for example, the closure
to the public of the proceedings of its powerful dispute panels _
have prompted widespread calls for increased openness.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has backed those calls belatedly and
was the prime mover in persuading Moore to hold Monday's meeting.
But many other governments oppose any participation by
nongovernmental groups, saying they are meddlesome and bring up
issues _ such as labor and the environment _ that are irrelevant to
poor nations' needs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than two-thirds of the approximately 750
``nongovernmental'' groups accredited to the WTO summit are
business lobby groups.
</P>
<P>
   The start of Monday's forum was delayed for more than four hours
because of an apparent attempted break-in overnight at the
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Police SWAT teams worried about a possible bomb got help from
sniffing dogs as they searched the downtown building while hundreds
of delegates, journalists and activists waited outside.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came a day before tens of thousands of anti-trade
protesters plan to take to the streets to denounce the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club staged a noisy but peaceful march in downtown
Monday under the watchful eye of police in riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Six arrests were reported after environmental protesters scaled
a giant construction crane in the downtown area to drape an
anti-WTO banner. The Rainforest Action Network claimed
responsibility for the action, saying in a statement that its
demonstrators had come to Seattle ``because the stakes are too high
for us to stay at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders said Monday's activities were only a warm-up for
what is to come. The biggest event of the week will be mounted
separately Tuesday by the AFL-CIO, a march by workers and their
families that will coincide with the summit's opening sessions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
