<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX     11-30 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Great-Aunt Octavia was rarely mentioned around
my grandmother Parker's home in Jacksonville, and when she was it
was in hushed tones. Auntie lived in Savannah, you know.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of such secretive carryings on, I spent an
inordinate amount of my childhood Lurking in shadowy halls or
crouched behind the furniture in a desperate attempt to overhear
something, anything, that would clear up the mystery that was
Savannah. But the grownups were too clever for me. Any time Aunt
'Tave's name was mentioned, voices dropped and dainty hands
fluttered up to hide the latest scurrilous news from the low
country.
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't much different across town in my Grandmother
Nichols' parlor. Early on, I learned there were but two basic
themes of conversation in my family, with a few variations thrown
in from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Theme one always sounded at dinner when someone felt obliged to
point out how beautiful the table would have been if the Yankees
hadn't stolen Great-great-grandmother Coolidge's silver. Theme two:
What a shame it was that (SET ITAL) certain (END ITAL) branches of
the family had opted to move to Savannah where, according to my
childish comprehension, the streets were lined with fallen women.
Once I even heard mention of a great-grandmother (married) who had
a gentleman friend (also married) in the tobacco business up in
North Carolina. He sent her postcards.
</P>
<P>
   As a curious kid, I was forever asking questions that appeared
to embarrass my elders like: When can we go visit Aunt 'Tave?
(Never!) or tell me about Great-grandmother Holmes-Owen (Who?). One
grandmother or another would remind me that (SET ITAL) our (END
ITAL) branch of the family did (SET ITAL) not (END ITAL) visit
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, as soon as I was old enough to travel on my own
(about 44), I lit out for Savannah as fast as my old brown station
wagon would carry me, determined to dig up an ancestor or two, and
maybe learn for myself the cause of all the eyebrow raising and
hand wringing I'd witnessed in those formative years.
</P>
<P>
   I was prepared for the worst, fully expecting to find a memorial
plaque nailed to a Dilapidated and long defunct house of ill repute
dedicated to my Aunt 'Tave, or maybe some archival mention of that
scarlet woman who was my great-grandmother. But it didn't happen. I
found no evidence that any of my forbearers might have been the
inspiration for that 1924 hit, ``Hard-Hearted Hannah (The Vamp of
Savannah)''.
</P>
<P>
   What I did find there was enchantment _ in the buildings, the
people, and Even in the Spanish moss so carelessly draped over the
trees in Bonaventure Cemetery where my search for roots had led me.
Odd place to look for a life _ in a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I was back in town, visiting with a friend whose
family history (on his mother's side) is literally laid in the
cornerstones of Savannah's historic district. We walked the brick
streets, pausing now and then to absorb the mysterious beauty that
is this city. The only thing that distinguished us from the other
out-of-towners was our conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent summers in that house with my mother,'' my companion
explained, pointing to a vine-covered brick place behind a fancy
iron fence on East Jones Street. I took his picture sitting on the
steps. He pointed to the house next door and told me his aunt had
lived there. The two sisters, unlike my Jacksonville family, were
very close.
</P>
<P>
   That made me wonder even more about the Savannah ladies hanging
from my family tree. What had caused them to move away?
</P>
<P>
   So far my only clue is something I saw on the front of a T-shirt
down on Bull Street. ``In Atlanta,'' it read, ``the first question
people ask you is, 'What's your business?' In Macon they ask,
'Where do you go to church?' In Augusta, 'What's your grandmother's
maiden name?' But in Savannah we ask, 'What would you like to
drink?' ``
</P>
<P>
   So maybe that's it _ maybe the ladies had to move to Savannah to
get a drink.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett
(AT)nwonline.net)u
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
