<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-AIDS-TEEN01-COX     11-30 2167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-TEEN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIDS in the family: Even the healthy hurt
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This fall, Dylan Edwards discovered something he was
really good at, something he loved, something he could be proud of,
something that suddenly made school worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   This talent gave him a distinct identity, entirely separate from
that of his little brother, in whose shadow he had lived for most
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Dylan, 15, debuted on the eighth-grade football
team at McNair Middle School in Decatur, Ga. He eventually helped
his team win the area championship.
</P>
<P>
   But he learned not to scan the bleachers for the faces he most
wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Tisa, came to the first game to cheer him on, and
was even elected an officer of the team's booster club. She never
made it to another game.
</P>
<P>
   For the next month she sat by her younger son's hospital bedside
in intensive care. She came home only to drive Dylan to school in
the mornings. He went to the hospital in the afternoons, after
football practice.
</P>
<P>
   Together they watched Dylan's brother, Chris, lose his last
battle with AIDS. And they tried not to think whether Tisa would
someday be in the hospital bed, comatose and alive only through
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan is the only member of his immediate family not infected
with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. But he is no less a victim of
the disease. The virus has consumed his life, and infected him with
a profound anger that sometimes shows.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Bruce, died of AIDS in 1992. Tisa, 35, is
HIV-positive but has remained healthy, aside from a serious bout
with shingles several years ago. Until Chris died six weeks ago,
three days before his 13th birthday, the family revolved around his
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's always been about Chris,'' Tisa said
matter-of-factly, but with deep regret. ``Dylan's life has always
been put on the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I have lost so much time, it's unreal. Every time we
would plan something, Chris would get sick, or he'd have to go to
the doctor, or he'd do something stupid and get hurt and we'd end
up in the emergency room anyway,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She relied upon Dylan to understand why things were the way they
were. He never complained. ``I'm sure he's been jealous of Chris in
the past,'' Tisa said. ``But he's always been very understanding.
He's never been a selfish kid.''
</P>
<P>
   But a child can be understanding and unselfish and still suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For children with AIDS, there are some resources,'' said Neil
Willenson, the founder and president of Camp Heartland, a Minnesota
charity organization for HIV-positive children and their siblings.
Both Dylan and Chris attended the camp for years. ``There are
social workers, medical professionals, organizations that look
after their needs. But often the siblings are left to fend for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Children still dying
</P>
<P>
   When Chris tested positive for HIV, there was only one AIDS
drug, AZT, and his doctors predicted he would survive a year,
perhaps two at most.
</P>
<P>
   In celebrating birthdays in the double digits, he outlived many
children with AIDS. The median survival time for children infected
with HIV from birth is about 8 or 9 years.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs have greatly improved the length and quality of life
for all people with HIV, but the drugs are no cure. In Chris' case,
his early treatment with AZT may have narrowed his later treatment
options. Doctors now know that a combination of three or more drugs
is the most effective treatment for HIV. Using a single drug can
lead quickly to drug resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Because Chris had generally enjoyed good health, his death was a
shock to many, including Willenson, who flew to Atlanta during
Chris' last few days. Chris was the fifth Camp Heartland child to
die in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost more children this year than any other,'' Willenson
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, designated World AIDS Day, the United Nations, the
World Health Organization and UNICEF will issue a joint report on
children orphaned by AIDS throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more and more families where one child may be
negative and everyone else may have HIV,'' Willenson said. ``We
have thousands of survivors who are not infected by HIV but are
horribly affected by it. We have to give them support.''
</P>
<P>
   Family time lost
</P>
<P>
   In November 1987, shortly after Chris was diagnosed, Tisa took
him to the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Md., where he
became one of the first children in pediatric AIDS clinical
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Tisa and Chris were gone for three weeks. Dylan was 3 years old.
It was the first of many, many absences. Tisa and Chris had to
travel to NIH every month, and the family couldn't afford for Dylan
to go, so he stayed home with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Tisa was careful not to make a big deal out of Chris' infected
status, and treated his medical care as a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   Then Chris had an accident. The boys, 4 and 6 years old at the
time, were at a Burger King playground when Chris fell and tore
open stitches in his chin from a previous mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look out, and Dylan is holding Chris' chin,'' Tisa
remembered. ``And Dylan's got blood in the palm of his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Dylan had come in contact with his
brother's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Tisa panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled, `Go wash your hands! And don't come out until you've
washed them for 10 minutes!' And Dylan freaked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Dylan swallowed his resentment when birthdays or
holidays or special occasions were overlooked because of Chris.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very common feeling of siblings of children with
AIDS,'' said Willenson. About 70 percent of the 400 kids who attend
Camp Heartland every year are the HIV-negative brothers and sisters
of children with HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel guilty for being healthy. But they also feel
jealous, because their parents have to spend any free moments with
the child with the virus,'' Willenson said. ``And then they feel
guilty for feeling jealous.''
</P>
<P>
   But the story of Chris and Dylan is not the story of Jacob and
Esau, the Old Testament brothers who competed bitterly for their
father's favor. Dylan and Chris fought like brothers, but they
loved each other. One summer, Chris wasn't allowed to go to Camp
Heartland because he had been fighting with other kids. Dylan
refused to go without his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kopple, an Academy Award-winning filmmaker, met Dylan
and Chris last year while she was directing and co-producing a
documentary on children with HIV and AIDS. She was so struck by the
intense bond between Dylan and Chris that she prominently featured
them in the film. (It will air again Wednesday, at 7 p.m. and 9:05
p.m. on the Disney Channel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt there was such a link and sensibility between them,''
Kopple said. ``Dylan really gave Chris so many allowances, because
he didn't know how long his brother might be with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling taunts at school
</P>
<P>
   When Dylan smiles, which is rarely, he is a handsome boy.
Relatives say he resembles his father.
</P>
<P>
   He is bright, and speaks with clear diction and a sophisticated
vocabulary unusual for a 15-year-old. But he does poorly in school.
He had to repeat seventh grade, and this school year his low grades
kept him from going out for the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've missed homework and tests for about two months, I was at
the hospital so much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His penchant for smarting off to teachers and his tendency to
fight with classmates have earned him school suspensions and a
spotty disciplinary record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate school,'' he said frankly. ``I don't like the classes,
I don't like the teachers, I don't like the people. I don't like
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst trouble Dylan ever got into was over his family. A
couple of years ago at another middle school, a boy began taunting
Dylan for having a mother and brother with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   One day at lunch, the boy slammed a bottle on the cafeteria
table in front of Dylan and said, ``Give that to your mother and
brother, it's a cure for AIDS.'' The bottle was filled with water.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan eventually was kicked out of that school for fighting with
his tormentor, who wasn't disciplined. Tisa's voice shakes with
fury when she tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   But Dylan's essentially a good kid, the sort who does nice
things for his mom but doesn't necessarily want the neighborhood to
hear about it. He's close to his uncle, Tisa's brother, and spends
much of his free time with him.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't get into trouble outside school. He says ``please''
and ``thank you'' and does his chores without being asked. He'd
like to go to college someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get my grades up,'' he said decidedly. ``I'm going
to go around and ask all of my teachers for all of the work I
missed, and I'm going to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Ireland, one of Dylan's football coaches at McNair, says
he has the ``utmost respect'' for Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was really courageous,'' Ireland said. ``He kept
a whole lot inside of him. But he seemed to love football, and he
did what the coaches asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When his brother died, we asked him if he wanted time off. We
had a game coming up. He said, no, he wanted to play,'' Ireland
said. ``And he did an outstanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisa attributes some of Dylan's anger to Bruce, who infected her
with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very angry at his father,'' Tisa said. ``He knows Bruce
did this to us. He knows that it's Bruce's fault that Chris died,
it's Bruce's fault that I could die, and it's Bruce's fault that he
will be the only one to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1987, as Tisa was doing the laundry, she found a
receipt from a clinic that treats sexually transmitted diseases in
a pocket of Bruce's jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `When were you going to tell me about this?''' Tisa
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She tested positive for HIV. Neither Dylan, who was 2 at the
time, nor Chris, 6 months old, was tested. ``Back then, they didn't
think to check children,'' Tisa said.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Chris developed a severe infection on the
skin lining the inside of his cheek. It looked as though someone
had cut a golf ball in half and stuck it inside the infant's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Tests showed Chris was infected. Dylan was pronounced HIV-free.
</P>
<P>
   Tisa doesn't know how Bruce was infected. But she is sure that
he infected her, and that she gave the virus to Chris while she was
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the circumstances, there is little bitterness in
Tisa's voice when she speaks of Bruce. But Dylan won't even talk
about his dad. It's hard enough for him to talk about Chris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best not to,'' he muttered.
</P>
<P>
   The day they had feared
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Chris started to cough. Terrible, heaving
coughs that sometimes made him vomit.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had been officially diagnosed with full-blown AIDS
since age 3, Chris had spent many years in good health, with only
occasional ear or sinus infections.
</P>
<P>
   This cough wouldn't go away, and Chris developed a fever and
body aches.
</P>
<P>
   At last, his doctors produced a diagnosis: whooping cough, an
illness that usually strikes babies.
</P>
<P>
   The whooping cough further undermined Chris' HIV-weakened immune
system. Other infections, including (BEGIN ITALIC) Pneumocystis
carinii pneumonia, (END ITALIC) seized the opportunity to attack
his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Because his lungs couldn't draw enough oxygen, Chris was placed
on a ventilator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dylan saw him on the ventilator, I think he understood
for the first time that Chris could die,'' Willenson said. ``And
Dylan clearly was not ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 12, Chris died.
</P>
<P>
   ``His body just couldn't handle it,'' Tisa said. ``He was tired,
and he wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Tisa and Dylan used Chris' ashes to plant a
tree in his memory at Camp Heartland. At the service, for the first
time, Dylan wept.
</P>
<P>
   A lot to get over
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to spend a lot more time with Dylan now, but he's
15, and spending time with Mom is not a cool thing,'' Tisa says
with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was it you were going to do this weekend?'' she asks
Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roller-skating,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Wait, I'll go with you.' And he said, `Mom, people
don't take their parents skating.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan rolls his eyes in that teenage way that translates as,
Duh! Tisa laughs and musses his carefully groomed hair.
</P>
<P>
   She knows she can't make up for the years spent dealing with his
brother's disease, and she can't promise him she'll live forever.
But she hopes she can at least help him heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smile, Dylan,'' she coaxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like smiling,'' he retorts through a tightly set
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smile anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   His face twitches, and he struggles with it for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like smiling,'' he repeats, but this time he is
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
