<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PETS-WORK01-COX     11-30 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-WORK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is the workplace going to the dogs?
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If she's not sacked out on a desk somewhere or
sprinting up the stairs after an office mate, look for Scarlett
begging a bit of barbecue from a co-worker who's just come back
from the restaurant down the street.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be what you'd consider proper office etiquette, but
as long as she's not piddling on the carpet or barging uninvited
into staff meetings, Scarlett and others like her are welcome at a
growing number of Austin companies that allow employees to bring
dogs to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs are part of our creative team,'' said Gay Gaddis, founder
and president of T3 (The Think Tank), an ad agency whose clients
include Dell Computer Corp. and Central Market.
</P>
<P>
   The trend apparently got its start in California's Silicon
Valley, where some high-tech companies started permitting pets in
the late 1980s. Today, dogs are finding their way into the
corporate world in laid-back Austin, sharing swivel chairs with
their owners, cruising the hallways or taking a quick romp
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Doggie gates have gone up at Garden.com, Shetland sheepdogs keep
employees happy and stress levels low at MQ and C Advertising, and
computer company 3dfx recently pitched its dog-friendly environment
in a radio recruitment campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just lightens the mood,'' said Laura Nell Soules,
Scarlett's owner and public relations director for T3 (The Think
Tank), which is housed in a 1912-era building on Rio Grande Street.
``It fits in with the culture of who we are, and I think it's
visual evidence that we love what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett, dubbed Scarlett O'Hairy by the T3 staff, likes to
while away her days lounging on Soules' desk or making the office
rounds, greeting co-workers who obviously adore her. They rumple
her fluffy fur or scoop her into their arms for a quick snuggle.
</P>
<P>
   Gaddis began permitting dogs about the time she instituted the
company's T3 and Under program, which allows new mothers to bring
their babies to work. On any given day, all or part of her personal
canine crew _ Bonnie, Bill, Joe David and Nolan Ryan _ can be found
scrambling over the marble table or settling in on the couch in her
office.
</P>
<P>
   Gaddis believes that having pets and babies around helps her
employees de-stress and promotes creative thinking. It also has
helped her retain good employees over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a business of creative ideas,'' Gaddis said. ``A
break with an animal or human touch with children relaxes people
and opens minds. When you feel good about where you are, the ideas
come.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a theory backed by the American Pet Products Manufacturers
Association, a Conn-
</P>
<P>
   ecticut-based national trade group that surveyed 50 companies,
small and large, across the country, that allow pets in the
workplace. The association's study of law firms, Internet sales
companies and retail shops showed that those with pets had lower
absenteeism rates and employees who were more willing to work
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``People work long hours today and are stressed out _ it's the
perfect way to be more productive at work,'' said Funda Alp,
spokeswoman for the association. ``You're more relaxed because your
loved one is there with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The only requirements at T3? Pets must be healthy, flea-free and
able to demonstrate a reasonable amount of decorum, and they can't
interrupt meetings. That's not to say you won't hear the occasional
intercom page for a pet that's wandered out of the room, or a yap
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   But even the clients don't seem to mind. ``They tend to think
it's kind of charming,'' said T3 employee Jennifer Ramsey, whose
chocolate Lab Reba joins her at work several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the offices that do allow pets are small, upstart
companies with young employes and a creative bent like advertising,
or high-tech firms competing for job applicants and using
dog-at-work privileges to lure in new hires.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Employees strolling the hallways with their dogs,
heading to the water cooler to fill up water bowl-- , or
congregating on the patch of grass outside while their dogs do
their business.
</P>
<P>
   But pets just don't work at every office. Although BMC Software
never officially allowed pets, a few of the company's 600 Austin
employees occasionally brought in their dogs, said facilities
manager Ruth Ann Cansler. That changed after a few pups didn't make
it outside for their bathroom break-- and office management was
left holding the pooper scooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to bring them in and didn't clean up after them,''
Cansler said. ``I've cleaned it up before and the vice president of
the company has had to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But at MQ and C Advertising, a small Austin advertising company,
owner Ben Morris believes that if it makes employees happy to have
their pets with them, it's worth it. ``I think this is very much in
touch with getting your work done and letting employees be adults
and manage their time and workload so they can have a positive work
environment,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at Garden.com, which has almost 200 employees, 15 to
20 dogs show up on a typical day. The crew includes Mr. Cracker the
greyhound, Bruno the boxer, Maggie the Labrador, Yobo the cocker
spaniel, and April, the 8-pound Italian greyhound, who sometimes
wears a sweater and always wears a heart-shaped chain that says
``Spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Sabrina Wallace, who paused to offer a
Saltine cracker to Tango, her 95-pound yellow Lab. ``Dogs give you
that smile you need sometimes. If I'm all stressed out, I'll come
back to my cubicle ... It feels like working at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has allowed dogs since it opened in December 1995.
Even its Web site, www.garden.com, features a photo gallery of dogs
that frequent the office. Boxes of dog biscuits, Four Paws cologne
and cushioned pet beds share space with computer equipment and
reference manuals in employee cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   The pet-friendly policy got started because founders of the
company, a leading online source for gardening products and
services, all had animals that they didn't want to leave at home
when they came to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it takes an edge off the work environment,'' said
co-founder Jamie O'Neill, whose golden retriever Jackson whiled
away a recent morning gnawing on a yogurt container beneath
O'Neill's desk. ``They have a soothing effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's ``three barks and you're out'' policy prohibits
incessant barking and stipulates that the pets be well behaved
while on the job. For most, that's not a problem. As for the
workers, they've just got to worry about rolling over the stray dog
ear with their rolling chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few rules gathered from companies that allow dogs in
the workplace:
</P>
<P>
   _ No excessive barking, sometimes referred to as the ``three
barks and you're out'' rule. At Garden.com, for example, a dog is
out after three mishaps, be it noise or potty violations. The pup
must prove it can behave before it's allowed back at the office.
</P>
<P>
   _ No doggy interruptions of staff or client meetings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dogs should be confined to a cubicle or an office.
</P>
<P>
   _ No messing on the floor, and if a mistake should occur, the
owner should clean it up immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dogs shouldn't disrupt business with clients, and if clients
are bothered by dogs, the owners should keep them out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela LeBlanc writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: pleblanc(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
