<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENS-SEA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Handbook aids gardening by the salty sea
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On its surface, Gardens By The Sea,
written and published by the Garden Club of Palm Beach, would seem
to have a fairly limited audience.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction, written by local horticulturist Gene Joyner,
calls it ``an in-depth how-to book on the trials and successes of
gardening on oceanfront and near oceanfront property.''
</P>
<P>
   A chapter in the book titled ``Designing a Seaside Garden''
notes that ``assuming there will be a section of beach along your
shoreline, consideration must be given to plant material that can
hold the sand in place.''
</P>
<P>
   We should all have such problems.
</P>
<P>
   But before dismissing the book in favor of one titled Gardens By
The Retention Pond, take a closer look. Most of the book provides
good information for almost anyone gardening in balmy, breezy
locales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're gearing the book toward anyone who lives
within 10 miles of the sea in a tropical climate, and not just in
South Florida,'' says Meredith Newton, spokeswoman for the Garden
Club, one of tony Palm Beach's oldest organizations. ``There are
unique challenges faced by anyone who gardens within 10 miles of
the coast, because of the salt air, the humidity and the soil being
based on sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The book largely is the brainchild and labor of two past
presidents of the Garden Club, Bess Summers and Joan Willmott, who
felt there had never been a good book written about coastal,
tropical gardening, Newton says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the money factor. Proceeds from sales of the book
will go to the club to help pay for beautification projects around
Palm Beach and programs at the Pine Jog Environmental Center, a
learning facility for elementary school students in western Palm
Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   A history of the mansions
</P>
<P>
   Gardens By The Sea opens with a history of Palm Beach's mansions
and their well-landscaped grounds that includes some of the town's
quirky details _ such as the story of how Paris Singer,
illegitimate son of the sewing machine magnate, teamed up with
``rogue and con man'' Addison Mizner to build some of the island's
most beautiful estates. This section features historic photographs
found in the Garden Club's archives just last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's followed by the ``Designing a Seaside Garden'' section, the
only poorly executed part of the book. A small sketch is used to
show the floor plan and surrounding garden of a fictitious
oceanfront home. Then, two full pages of text try to describe for
the reader what kinds of plants to use in the garden and where to
put them. There are no pictures, and the sketch is not a detailed
landscape plan, offering only a few plant names and locations to
help the reader. The text itself is complicated, especially for
anyone with limited plant knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the book is divided up into easy-to-follow
sections covering many of tropical gardening's most important
plants: palms, shrubs, flowering trees, fruit _ plus some of the
popular exotics such as orchids and gingers. There are other
sections, too, including those on herb and rose growing.
</P>
<P>
   Lush photographs, mostly taken in and around Palm Beach, accent
each section and make plant identification easier.
</P>
<P>
   Two editions available
</P>
<P>
   There are two editions of Gardens By The Sea; a ``deluxe''
version available through the Garden Club sells for $45 and is
printed on higher quality paper with a linen cover and includes an
additional chapter on Garden Club history. The less fancy ``trade''
edition is in bookstores for $34.95, but the Garden Club hopes to
sell more of the deluxe editions, of which they keep a bigger chunk
of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   And while anyone enjoying a coastal garden can benefit from the
book, those lucky enough to afford oceanfront property will find it
helpful, too, Newton says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people who live in Palm Beach,'' she explains,
``need to know what to tell their gardeners to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: heathergraulich(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
