A4929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-CD01-COX     11-30 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-CD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Tis the season for holiday music
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving is over. You know what that means (besides
leftovers). Time to start hauling out the holiday CDs. Every person
on Earth with access to a recording studio has made a holiday
album. And every year, we get inundated with a fresh batch.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they have ranged from folkie Jewel to popsters 98
Degrees to South Park's Mr. Hankey (really). Instead of wading
through all the new stuff, we asked some Palm Beach Post staff
writers to pick the discs _ those special evergreens _ they listen
to every year. Some you've heard, some you probably haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Happy start-of-the-holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Making Spirits Bright, Dean Martin (Capitol). When I was a kid,
my grandmother and her sisters owned a hotel and lounge in St.
Petersburg Beach. My grandmother was Italian, so one of the staples
on the jukebox during the holidays was Dean Martin. My favorite was
Rudolph, The Red Nosed Reindeer. This song always cracked me up
because Dean-o's obviously been hitting the eggnog hard in the
studio. In his best throaty cocktail voice, he trims his words and
improvises wildly. Christmas becomes Crizzmizz. Rudolph becomes
Rudy the Red Beaked Reindeer. At one point, he breaks into a German
accent and sings, ``Rudoph mit your nose so bright, won't you guide
mein sleigh tonight?'' It always reminds me of my grandmother at
the holiday party, a short glass of Baccardi and Coke in one hand,
cigarette in the other, singing along in a raspy voice, doing a
cha-cha around the bar with a huge smile. _ Jeff Houck
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson 5 Christmas Album (Motown). The Christmas season
doesn't really start for me until I start playing The Jackson 5
Christmas Album. This 1970 treasure takes me back to the days when
Michael was actually cute. Like Michael, I was a young kid who
could hit all those high notes on ``I Saw Mommy Kissing Santa
Claus'' and, my personal favorite, ``Santa Claus Is Comin' To
Town''. Jermaine Jackson did Nat King Cole proud with his soulful
rendition of ``The Christmas Song''.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the velvet-voiced Cole, his album, ``The Christmas
Song,'' is another classic around our house. When Cole croons O
Tannenbaum in German, you don't have to understand the language to
feel the soothing comfort of his lyrics. For jazz lovers, it's hard
to top Vince Guaraldi's wonderfully moving Christmas Time Is Here
on A Charlie Brown Christmas. Of the more recent holiday CDs, BeBe
&AMP; CeCe Winans' First Christmas is a gem _ their stirring,
gospel-filled version of The First Noel can make even hard-core
atheists convert _ and Luther Vandross' This is Christmas is one of
the best ways to get your partner in a cozy, late-night holiday
mood. _ Kevin D. Thompson
</P>
<P>
   Chanukah Songs, Cantor Larry Eschler. While there are no
shortage of Hanukkah albums, this cassette has always jumped to the
top of the playlist in our house. Part of the reason is personal:
We're members of Eschler's synagogue, Temple Beth David in Palm
Beach Gardens, Fla. But another part is simply the infectious folk
spirit Eschler brings to these holiday classics, including ``Maoz
Tzur'' and ``I Have a Little Dreidle.'' Eschler also sings one of
his own Hanukkah compositions, as well as a couple by contemporary
folk songwriter Debbie Friedman (you'll love ``I'm a Latke''). And
his renditions of the Hanukkah candle blessings are simple yet
inspiring. Available through Temple Beth David, Palm Beach Gardens.
_ Charles Passy
</P>
<P>
   A Broadway Christmas (Varese Sarabande). Perhaps in hopes of
getting independent holiday season airplay, lots of Broadway
musicals sneak Christmas-related songs into their plots. Fifteen
mostly merry examples have been compiled in ``A Broadway
Christmas,'' which I dig out and play annually. Some selections are
obvious, like Mame's ``We Need A Little Christmas'' sung buoyantly
by Lynnette Perry and ``Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas,''
from ``Meet Me in St. Louis,'' delivered with velvety sincerity by
Liz Callaway. Dipping a little deeper into the holiday bag yields a
little known song called ``Christmas Eve,'' meant for ``She Loves
Me,'' and a rare downbeat Irving Berlin number, ``The Happy New
Year Blues'' from ``The Music Box Revue.'' Even the disc's cover
art of the Chorus Line logo figures in Santa suits is enough to get
theater fans in a holiday mood. _ Hap Erstein
</P>
<P>
   In the Spirit, Jessye Norman, with the American Boychoir, St.
Thomas Choir of Men and Boys, Riverside Choir, St. Barnabas Choir
and the Orchestra of St. Luke's, conducted by David Robertson.
(Philips Classics). Christmas is my favorite season for music, and
it's always a treat to hear the unexpected. Norman scales her
magnificent soprano down for a searingly beautiful collection of
Christmas tunes that ranges from the hymn ``Angels from the Realms
of Glory'' to the spiritual ``Mary had a Baby,'' and classical
pieces such as Schubert's ``Ave Maria.'' Much of the CD is a
cappella, with magical interplay between Norman and the choirs.
John McCutcheon's ``Winter Solstice'' (Rounder) is another
favorite. McCutcheon, master of the hammer dulcimer, plays and
sings classic and contemporary Christmas and Hanukkah tunes in this
1985 recording. International fare is what makes Christmas with
``Nana Mouskouri ``(Philips) special. The Greek songstress' albums
range from the schlocky to the sublime, but she finds perfect form
in this 1972 collection of English, French and Greek holiday fare.
``Her Minuit Cretiens'' (Holy Night) is ethereal. Noel, Joan Baez's
1966 album for Vanguard, teams the queen of folk with Peter
Schickele (P.D.Q. Bach himself) for a heavenly collection of
English, American, French and German Christmas songs. Be sure to
check out ``Down in Yon Forest.'' _ Scott Simmons
</P>
<P>
   A Christmas Gift for You, Phil Spector and various artists.
(Uni/Abkco) There are many holiday CDs I like and happily recommend
_ Harry Belafonte, Barbra Streisand, The Beach Boys, Nat King Cole,
George Winston, Frank Sinatra, Elvis Presley _ but this is the only
one I play when it's not Christmas. Phil Spector's grandiose
productions, from ``Da Doo Ron Ron'' to ``Be My Baby'' to ``You've
Lost That Lovin' Feelin''', are justifiably famous, but he should
also get credit for being the godfather of rock holiday recordings.
Listen to Bruce Springsteen singing ``Santa Claus is Comin' to
Town'' and it's practically a straight-up ripoff of Spector's
version by The Crystals. No holiday is complete without The
Ronettes singing ``I Saw Mommy Kissing Santa Claus.'' Or Darlene
Love, one of the most underrated female vocalists of the '60s,
belting out a soul-stirring ``Christmas (Baby Please Come Home)''
while enveloped in Spector's cavernous ``Wall of Sound''
production. A great album for any season, but especially this one.
_ Larry Aydlette
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
