<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GUINNESS03-COX     11-30 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GUINNESS03-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   1bill rimmed, mburke slot
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Eyman
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Books Editor
</P>
<P>
   Sir Alec, smart aleck
</P>
<P>
   SMART ALEC
</P>
<P>
   Going, going, Guinness
</P>
<P>
   He's going, going, Guinness, according to his second, even more
entertaining memoir, and Sir Alec swears this lament at having
attained old age will be the last.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Eyman
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Books Editor
</P>
<P>
   A POSITIVELY FINAL APPEARANCE, by Alec Guinness. Viking; 246
pages; $24.95
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty four today,'' glumly notes Alec Guinness at the
beginning of this enchanting diary of a year and a half that
surpasses its predecessor My Name Escapes Me. This late life
success as a memoirist must be a surprise to the author, who is
more comfortable describing himself as an elderly English character
actor.
</P>
<P>
   Longevity itself holds no charms for Guinness. ``That is 30,660
days, mostly wasted,'' he continues. ``If I had been told when I
was eleven, say, that I would live to such an age I think I would
have fainted with nausea. Schoolmasters in their 30s already had
knobby knees, revealed by their long, floppy football shorts ... as
for tufts of hair in ears and nostrils, they were not to be
mentioned except with horror and youthful contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinness walked away from acting 10 years ago, distressed by the
way he looked and by his increasing problems in memorizing
dialogue. ``My compulsion for the limelight is not all that strong;
besides, pride played a part in my decision to retire _ I don't
wish to be seen as I am now when I know there was something better
on offer thirty years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He is still happily ensconced with Merula, his wife of more than
50 years, and loves to potter around his garden, taking care of his
plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   On a deeper level, Guinness seems to have hit his second _ or,
given his age, fourth _ wind; he's more active than he was in My
Name Escapes Me; he's always taking the train into London for an
art show, a play, or just to savor the glories of the Connaught. He
is, as always, gentle and urbane, a true Englishman, but one with
surprises on nearly every page.
</P>
<P>
   He reads everything, including Carl Hiaasen, whose Skin Tight he
calls ``a good gruesome thriller.'' Balancing that is an addiction
to the classics. Henry James, however, is not to his liking. The
Wings of the Dove forces him to throw up his hands in dismay:
``Over and over I had to return to interminable sentences to try to
fathom _ not so much what he might be getting at under the surface,
which was rarefied to a degree _ but just to grasp the plain story
line.''
</P>
<P>
   The English Patient leaves him cold (``too often suggested bits
and pieces of David Lean classics...'') and Obi-Wan Kenobi at last
lets his feelings about Star Wars out of the bag: ``Twenty years
ago, when it was first shown, it had a freshness, also a sense of
moral good and fun,'' but now he says he fears it has led to a
worldwide taste for a ``fantasy world of secondhand, childish
banalities.''
</P>
<P>
   The fame that it has brought him he finds appalling, and he
tells a young Star Wars fan who approaches him as a living god that
he wants only one favor from him: Never see Star Wars again.
</P>
<P>
   He contemplates Shakespeare and dismisses any possibility that,
say, Marlowe had a hand in the plays: ``Marlowe's stagecraft is
crude or non-existent when compared to Shakespeare's know-how. And
is there a character in Marlowe which makes one smile, let alone
laugh outright?''
</P>
<P>
   He expresses his lifelong affection for Samuel Butler and
approvingly quotes his remark ``The three most important things a
man has are, briefly, his private parts, his money, and his
religious opinions.'' He then proceeds to top Butler by saying,
``The first two diminish with age and only the last is rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   And like all true talents, he flagellates himself for not being
as good as he had once hoped he might be (only mediocrities think
they're really good). When he sees a play with Eileen Atkins and
Michael Gambon, he notes despairingly that he could never have
achieved acting of their caliber. At another time, he says that
``Personally I have only one great regret _ that I never dared
enough. If at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinness is always pillorying himself for not dragging down fire
from heaven like Olivier, or some of the old actor-laddies that he
documents with enormous affection in these pages, but he's
persistently misreading his own gifts.
</P>
<P>
   There are different kinds of actors, and Guinness was a
thoughtful, sly minimalist _ a contemporary cross-reference would
be Ben Kingsley. He was eminently suited for movies, where an
arched eyebrow or a slight hesitation can be as eloquent as a
soliloquy. Much as Truffaut always had an intellectual affinity for
Hitchcock, even though he didn't have the vaguest notion of how to
make those kinds of movies, Guinness is always pining for romantic
bravura.
</P>
<P>
   But his readers and fans will have to content themselves with
The Bridge on the River Kwai, and Great Expectations and Oliver
Twist and The Horse's Mouth and Kind Hearts and Coronets and _ to
his horror _ Star Wars.
</P>
<P>
   It's reward enough, for a singular kind of great actor, and, on
the basis of his books, a wonderful man.
</P>
<P>
   Distinquished actor and English gentleman Sir Alec Guinness, is
a gifted memoirist, it turns out, with a deft humor and personal
style. He starts his book by noting that had he known at age 11 he
would live to be 84, he would have `fainted with nausea.' He did
reach 84, however, and, to our good fortune, he's making the most
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
