<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Family-values and religious right groups are up
in alarms over a pamphlet about gay and lesbian youths recently
sent to school administrators around the country. Their distress is
understandable. The booklet's appeal to reason has little place in
the narrow cosmography of the sexually repressive. (Teepen, Cox
Newspapers). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Of all the feverish religious fervor that has
set people against each other, the present one between Israelis,
Muslims and Catholics is among the most aberrant. Even with a
scorecard, you can't tell the lineups.(Kleinberg, Cox News
Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ As a curious kid, I was forever
asking questions that appeared to embarrass my elders like: When
can we go visit Aunt 'Tave? (Never!) or tell me about
Great-grandmother Holmes-Owen (Who?). One grandmother or another
would remind me that OUR branch of the family did NOT visit
Savannah. Naturally, as soon as I was old enough to travel on my
own (about 44), I lit out for Savannah as fast as my old brown
station wagon would carry me. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
