<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN01-CO     11-30 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't get angry, get smart this tax season
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's no point in getting angry about taxes. Maybe
it's emotionally satisfying, but it won't do any good.
</P>
<P>
   What will help is focusing on things we can control. When it
comes to taxes, that means finding ways to make the tax laws work
for us.
</P>
<P>
   Economist John Maynard Keynes got it right when he said, ``The
avoidance of taxes is the only intellectual pursuit that carries
any reward.''
</P>
<P>
   I grant there are reasons to be mad about taxes. One big reason
is the law itself is difficult to understand. In a survey last
year, only one in four Americans said they prepare their own tax
returns. The majority hire a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The tax code runs 2.8 million words. The Taxpayer Relief Act of
1997 was 2 inches thick and dropped another 3,000 pages of
scripture on us.
</P>
<P>
   I like Roth IRAs, which were introduced in that new law. But I
can't say that I feel 3,000 pages worth of relief.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, much of your tax law and mine was written solely
for the benefit of special interests. One of the amendments tossed
around this year was a tax credit, worth $84 million or more, to
encourage poultry producers to burn chicken manure and generate
electricity. I am not making this up.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the complexity is the result of a never-ending struggle
between tax collectors and high-dollar tax avoiders. If enough
money is at stake, it's worth hiring an accountant or lawyer to pry
open a loophole. Then it's up to the Internal Revenue Service,
assisted by our elected professionals in Congress, to plug the
loophole with some more law.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to the second reason to be mad about taxes: We,
the people, can't get in on the really sweet tax breaks. They are
reserved for the people who make electricity _ or perhaps I should
say chicken salad.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us feel a wholly appropriate urge to be responsible
citizens. But we also suspect that a lot of other people and
corporations are cutting better deals.
</P>
<P>
   We want some sweetness ourselves. It is a case of loophole envy.
But face it: These are problems that none of us can change before
April 15.
</P>
<P>
   What we can do is recognize that Uncle Sam has chopped open some
loopholes for everybody. They reflect social goals, activities that
our government has decided to reward with tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   There are tax breaks for owning a home and for giving to
charity. There are deductions for saving money, either for our
children's college expenses or for our own retirements. There are
breaks for self-employed people, which we could interpret as an
encouragement of self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to make sure we take full advantage of those
breaks. A related trick is to make sure we don't make any expensive
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
