<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-MURPHY-BOS     11-30 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MURPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY, NOW A BRUIN, HAS BEEN AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He first appeared on the sports landscape back in the
spring of 1990, when he was an enthusiastic 22-year-old kid. Joe
Murphy's linemates then were 22-year-old Adam Graves and
19-year-old Martin Gelinas, and they were known as the Edmonton
Oilers' ``Kid Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, now a Bruin who is recovering from a knee injury,
remembers skating the Stanley Cup around Boston Garden, and he even
has a photo on his wall back in Chicago of him and his linemates
with the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how life turns out sometimes. Gelinas is now with the
Carolina Hurricanes and Graves plays for the New York Rangers.
Murphy, who started his career in Detroit, went from Edmonton to
Chicago to St. Louis to San Jose before landing here, with the team
he rooted for as a kid. Murphy has played one game for Boston _
against New Jersey Nov. 17 _ but he could return to the lineup
Thursday against the Capitals in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie Patrick Roy was a rookie with Montreal when he
won the Stanley Cup, and he said it wasn't until much later in his
career that he realized just how difficult it was to reach that
goal. When you win it so young, Roy said, you expect to win it
every year. Ray Bourque, by contrast, is in his 21st season and
hasn't won it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy appreciates his time with the Oilers for a lot of
reasons, and he understands what Roy is talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to be on such a great team,'' he said. ``We
thought every year we'd be back in there. It was really something
to go to the finals and win the Stanley Cup. It's been a while
since I've been there. I've been to the semifinals three or four
times after that, so I've knocked on the door but just haven't
gotten in again. It would be something for this team to have a
shot. It would be incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy knew on the first the day of practice that his time with
the Oilers was going to be a remarkable experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the hotel and Mark Messier said he'd pick us up for
our first practice,'' said Murphy, referring to himself and Graves.
``He arrives in this big Bentley. We both jumped in the back. We
felt like we were part of government going to practice. It was just
hilarious. Mark Messier to me, still to this day, he's such a great
leader. He's my favorite player.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's life changed when he went to Edmonton. When he began
his pro career, as the No. 1 overall pick by the Red Wings in 1986,
the expectations were overwhelming. Detroit had been on a downward
spiral for quite some time. At the tender age of 18, Murphy was
expected to come in and turn around the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy never thought of himself as a savior. He was a kid
trying to carve out a niche for himself. It turned out be a very
lonely time. Veteran players were worried about their own jobs.
There was no one there to throw Murphy a rope. That has made him
want to be a role model or sounding board for younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything to help younger guys,'' he said. ``They need
some help, they need some guidance. It's nice. I did have questions
and I didn't have anyone to turn to. Players were battling for
jobs. Looking back on it, I understand it. I don't mind battling
for the job but sometimes you need a little help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell, who was
Murphy's roommate when the youngster broke in, said it was a tough
spot to be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult time because the team was a last-place team
for a few years,'' said O'Connell. ``We had a new coach in Jacques
Demers and Joe was coming in as a highly touted kid. Joe really
didn't know what to expect, nor should he, as most kids don't. Back
then, it was a little different. People expected he was going to
save the franchise; it doesn't happen too often. Expectations were
high and he wasn't ready to do it. Not that he was a bad player,
but you're asking a hell of a lot for a young kid to come in and do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Pat Falloon, who was supposed to carry the weight of
the San Jose Sharks franchise at 18. Just ask Alexandre Daigle, who
was supposed to do the same with Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player goes through adversity and tough times,'' said
Murphy. ``I was drafted at 18 and I wasn't ready to play in the
NHL. I was the first pick and I took a ton of heat. I was sent to
the minors and that's too young now (with the existing rules). I
was 18 playing in the minors against pro guys who weren't very
happy that I was down there. I was up and down my first few years.
It was frustrating but I think that's why I'm still here and still
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was traded to Edmonton, he didn't realize how much his
life was about to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of my favorite times ever playing the game,'' he
said. ``We were really eager and young and we all looked up to Mark
Messier and Jari Kurri and Glenn Anderson and Grant Fuhr and all
those guys. They were my heroes when I was 14, 15, or 16. Those
were the guys I looked up to, and to be on that team, it was just
incredible. It was so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   With Graves and Gelinas, Murphy was comfortable. Not only was he
part of his own peer group, but given the talent of the Oilers'
veterans, he wasn't being asked to carry the entire load.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really looked out for each other,'' he said. ``We really
went to battle on the ice for each other, every game, every shift.
We really had something that will last forever. Whenever I see
those guys, I realize it was a great moment in time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most memorable games of that Stanley Cup run was Game
1 of the finals when Edmonton beat Boston in triple overtime.
Murphy will never forget the winning goal, by Petr Klima, and what
led up to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember (then Boston defenseman) Glen Wesley had that
wide-open net,'' said Murphy, referring to the second overtime. ``I
was backchecking and we wiped out Billy (Ranford) into the net and
that's why he had an open net. Wesley shot and it went over the
net. After that game, luckily we had two days in between games. I
remember nine of us got sick, we got dehydrated. We were just sick,
it was ridiculous. I was so done. I was tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he has been fortunate to play with some top forwards
over the years. His favorites are Bernie Nicholls, Vincent
Damphousse, and Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie and I really worked well together,'' said Murphy. ``He
came to play hard, he was a true competitor and a professional.
Jeremy was one of the best competitors I've ever played with. He
was cocky, he was perfect for Chicago. I think (his departure)
started all of Chicago's problems. He was what the city was all
about. Working hard, and brash and going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy thought his life would be even more idyllic in St. Louis,
where he signed a three-year contract that was criticized around
the league for its excessive value. Murphy was paid $2.8 million,
$3.4 million, and $3.8 million. The last season and change of the
contract he spent with the Sharks after the Blues traded him.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash and inflated expectations were like Detroit all
over again and it hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, it was tough on me,'' he said. ``The first year,
I scored 20 goals and felt I played good, but more was expected of
me because of the type of money I was making. I got offered a great
contract. It's pretty tough to turn it down. I'm more happy playing
for the amount of money I'm playing for now than I was at that
amount. Then my second year there I got hurt. I thought I was
playing the best hockey I'd ever played but the puck wasn't going
in the net. I was playing well all over the ice but I was having a
hard time scoring. I was playing with Geoff Courtnall and Pavol
Demitra. But I went in on a breakaway, got tripped, and snapped my
wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Murphy scored 25 goals for the Sharks, but it took
him until Nov. 12 of this year to find an offer. Part of it was
that Murphy was affected by the changing climate in the league;
owners are no longer free-spending on free agents. The Rangers, who
overpay for nearly everyone, stick out like a sore thumb as more
and more clubs are cutting expenses rather than increasing them.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy understood all that but it was frustrating to have no
team to go to at 32 years old and coming off the year he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a changing of the guard a little bit and a changing of
the thinking,'' said Murphy. ``They have to bean-count, they have a
business to run. New York was the only really active team in the
market and they were bidding against themselves. The climate has
definitely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   And Murphy, too, has changed. Gone is the naive kid who first
broke into the league in 1986. His black hair is flecked with gray,
and despite some of the disappointment, he wakes up every day and
considers himself so fortunate to be where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all lucky to play this game,'' he said. ``We make a
great living. You're at the rink and your job is to stay in top
condition and who doesn't want to do that? You get to perform in
front of crowds and try to win the Stanley Cup together and then
you get summers off. It's hard to look at the (long view) after
you've had a bad game or you're benched but you keep things in
perspective. I think I've picked that up over time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
