<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DISSIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What degree of loyalty does a policy adviser owe the team on
which he serves? Nearly 30 years ago, Paul McCracken quit as
Richard Nixon's chief economic adviser rather than implement a
policy of price controls _ but he held his tongue even out of
office.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Feldstein, on the other hand, feuded publicly with other
members of the Reagan administration over the economic significance
of the exploding deficit in 1983 and 1984, while serving as
chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers. There are those who
believe that he thereby seriously diminished the council's place in
the firmament of power.
</P>
<P>
   Feldstein eventually left office under his own steam. But
subsequent appointees in the Reagan and Bush administrations were
selected for their docility. And when Bill Clinton took over the
White House in 1993, he immediately created a more explicitly
political advisory layer in the form of the National Economic
Council. Its first chief was Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Joseph Stiglitz became the most recent figure in the
parade of dissidents when he announced on the eve of Thanksgiving
his departure from the office of chief economist at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the bank's economist is anywhere near as important as
the president's corps of economic advisers. His biggest job is to
prepare the annual World Development Report and discover other ways
to use his office as a bully pulpit, mostly to the developing
world. In the past decade, the position has served as a launching
pad for advisers aspiring to more responsibility: Lawrence Summers
and Stanley Fischer preceded Stiglitz in the job.
</P>
<P>
   But the widespread suspicion in Washington that Summers, now
secretary of the Treasury, insisted on Stigliz's departure as a
precondition for the reappointment of bank president James
Wolfensohn to a second five-year term suggests just how nettlesome
the 57-year-old economist had become during the several years he
served in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Stiglitz was an unmistakable free spirit even before he joined
the administration. Distinguished enough as a theorist to be
considered a likely candidate someday for a Nobel Prize, he
nevertheless left Princeton University for Stanford after the
former declined to offer tenure to his wife. A ``new Keynesian''
economist, he has been drawn to problems of market failure _ to the
point of having it said that he never met a scheme for government
intervention he did not like.
</P>
<P>
   During a stint at the Council of Economic Advisers, Stiglitz
shunned controversy for the most part. But once at the World Bank,
the Asian financial crisis and its aftermath led him to question
the International Monetary Fund's response to the dilemma. And in
recent months Stiglitz repeatedly has raised questions about the
conduct of policy by Washington and its European allies before and
after the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on global integration before all else may have been
misplaced, Stiglitz has argued. Short-term capital flows to
developing countries may have been a boon to Wall Street _ but a
curse to fragile political authority in newly industrializing
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the choice of ``conditionality'' as a way of changing
policy _ requiring privatization, budgetary austerity, and
macroeconomic stability as preconditions for further assistance _
may have been downright wrong. More than a few minds have been
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Stiglitz afforded a clear view of the candor that made
him among the administration's least wanted men. He fired off two
new bursts of genteel criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the Economic Journal, Stiglitz called for a
significant reorientation of the World Bank's mission. Henceforth
it should focus its lending on projects promising significant
poverty reduction, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And in a separate speech at the Harvard University Center for
Business and Government at the John F. Kennedy School, Stigliz
called on the World Trade Organization to address developing
country priorities as never before. Trade ministers meeting in
Seattle are seeking to begin a lengthy new round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Stiglitz's criticism of the handling of the Asian crisis
has the taint of hindsight and second-guessing. Where was he on the
issues in the years before the hard decisions were being made? Yet
it is hard not to admire the conviction of an economist who has
begun to speak for his clients. The world's poorest citizens can
use all the sophisticated advocacy they can get.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
