<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER TOWNS FEAR HIGHER MEXICAN FEE WILL PUT BRAKES ON TOURISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico _ As mayor of this industrial city across
the Rio Grande from El Paso, Texas, Gustavo Elizondo Aguilar has
tried hard to attract more American tourists, shoppers, and
businesses to his side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   But a new federal law, drawn up by bureaucrats 1,500 miles away
in Mexico City, will make it harder _ if not impossible, he said _
to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to crack down on illegally imported cars from the
United States and to recoup millions of dollars in lost tax
revenues, the Treasury Ministry will dramatically increase the
deposit required from American and Canadian motorists who travel
into Mexico's interior. Beginning this week, the deposit will
increase from the current $11 a car to as much as $800 for each
vehicle that travels beyond the 15-mile border zone.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy that has followed the new rule has sparked a
cross-border squabble between the US and Mexican governments _ only
days before global trade representatives gather for this year's
World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle _ as well as with many
Mexican-American residents, who fear the higher fees will prevent
many of them from visiting relatives in Mexico during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this decision was made to hurt relations between
the United States and Mexico,'' Elizondo said last week from his
office, which has a view of downtown El Paso, less than a mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's hard to see the logic in this decision,'' he added.
``The people in Mexico City who decide these things don't
understand the environment that we're trying to develop up here on
the border.''
</P>
<P>
   And in light of the five-year-old North American Free Trade
Agreement, which among other things is supposed to foster more
cross-border commerce and tourism along the US-Mexico boundary, the
Treasury Ministry's decision is even more puzzling, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economies of the border are already under stress because
of a lack of infrastructure and high unemployment,'' said Mike
Allen, president of the Economic Development Corporation in
McAllen, Texas, a border city of 500,000 residents that relies
heavily on NAFTA manufacturers. ``We should be working for more
openness, not for more restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics of the measure insist the higher prices will have
a chilling effect on the roughly 2 million Mexican immigrants who
live in the United States and drive back every year for visits at
Christmas and Easter, Mexico's most family-centered holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tradition for us to visit our relatives every
Christmas,'' said Rogelio Rivas, 52, an El Paso resident who
planned to drive his wife, three children, and four grandchildren
to the northern Mexican city of Torreon, about 700 miles away.
``But with this fee, we won't all be able to go. Or maybe instead
of visiting every year, we only do it every two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some border region leaders, like Allen, say the agency's
decision is one of a series of steps taken by the US and Mexican
governments lately that have hurt local trade. Earlier this year,
the Mexican officials announced a steep increase in the price of
tourist visas.
</P>
<P>
   Other local leaders, meanwhile, complain of hours-long backups
at the international bridges for people and cargo entering the
United States because there are not enough immigration and customs
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Ministry officials postponed the start of the car
deposit program because of the backlash created on both sides of
the border, but the agency says the new deposit is required by law,
and that it has done all it can to make the payment as easy as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The deposits, for example, are less for older cars _ about $400
for cars built before 1994. They are refundable, returned once the
car crosses back to the US side. And the deposits can be charged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stemming the flow of the illegally imported cars,
the measure was needed to curb the traffic in stolen vehicles.
Mexican citizens often turn to this black market to buy cars _
knows as ``chocolates'' _ to avoid paying expensive excise taxes
that are charged on cars purchased domestically. Of the 14 million
cars in Mexico, an estimated 1.5 million were brought in illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal cars mean lost revenue for the government. The 14
million cars that are legally registered in the country, for
instance, produce $800 million in tax funds every year. Officials
also said that allowing more chocolates into the country threatens
Mexico's automotive sector.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than increase the fees and threaten the flow of
tourists and businesses along the border, Elizondo said, officials
in Mexico City should let local governments create their own
programs to stop the illegal vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Under a project begun in Ciudad Juarez in January, local police
and officials have identified and recovered 1,916 illegal cars.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Woods, general manager of Sanborn's Mexico Auto Insurance,
one of the largest underwriters of auto insurance policies for
motorists traveling in Mexico, said many tourists have taken their
vacations earlier than planned to avoid the higher deposits, which
go into effect on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also predicts the biggest loser in the car-deposit rule
will be Mexico, where tourism by car fell 27 percent from 1997 to
1998. Woods attributed that decline to negative publicity about
safety in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now with this on top of everything else, it doesn't look good
for Mexican tourism,'' Woods said of the new deposit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
