<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-SCHAMA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     11-30 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SCHAMA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History had always interested Schama _ he wrote a 12-page
illustrated ``History of the Royal Navy'' when he was 9 _ and at
Cambridge he made it his profession. ``He was the most exciting
pupil one is ever likely to have,'' says Plumb _ no small praise
from a man who has been an academic for six decades. Schama became
a lecturer at Oxford in 1976 and a year later published his first
book, ``Patriots and Liberators: Revolution in the Netherlands
1780-1813.''
</P>
<P>
   Even writing on something so seemingly arcane, Schama managed to
grace his narrative with a beguiling array of offbeat characters
and odd bits of social history. His next book, ``Two Rothschilds
and the Land of Israel'' (1978), is his least typical _ in
stylistic restraint as well as subject matter _ but with ``The
Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the
Golden Age'' (1987), Schama came into his own. It was a great
critical success and actually managed to sneak onto the bestseller
list, as did Schama's next book, ``Citizens: A Chronicle of the
French Revolution'' (1989). He described that book as ``an exercise
in animated description,'' words that apply equally to its
predecessor. Both books drew criticism from specialists, but their
author's popular reputation was made. Emboldened by success and
ever eager to test the limits of the discipline, Schama even tried
his hand at fictionalizing history, in ``Dead Certainties'' (1991).
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence, perhaps, that Schama wrote all three books
after coming to the United States. The tight little world of
English academe never knew quite what to make of such ``a disturber
of lazily repeated formulae'' (a phrase Schama applies to Rembrandt
that might double as autobiography). ``He aroused enmity as well as
good will, of course,'' Plumb sighs. Schama found Harvard, where he
arrived in 1980, and then Columbia, where he has taught since 1993,
more hospitable than Oxbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Schama usually lives in Westchester County, north of New York,
with his wife, Virginia E. Papaioannou, a professor of genetics at
Columbia, and their two children: Chloe, 16, and Gabriel, 14. At
present, though, he and his family are in England, where he's
immersed in a 16-part BBC series, to be broadcast next fall, called
``Britain: A Television History.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a series on British history _ of any kind.
I soon found out why: The weather, it's called! . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Has (the filming) been fantastic fun? Absolutely, not a minute
of boredom. You know, the odd thing is, I've always said I could
only work on a foreign culture _ Holland, France, and so on. Of
course, Britain isn't a foreign culture, but its idiosyncrasies
past and present I no longer take for granted. I do have the eye of
a visitor now.''
</P>
<P>
   The series is Schama's biggest opportunity yet to reach an
audience beyond academe (``There is a slight proselytizing aspect
to it,'' he says with a barely suppressed smile), and that audience
can expect a goodly helping of exotica. ``It's all location stuff,
really, and artifacts as well, lovely things,'' he explains.
``Someone phoned me up and said, `Simon, did you know' _ which I
certainly didn't! _ `that the Westminster Abbey Museum has the
underthings they took off of Queen Elizabeth I when she died in
1603?'. . . I knew, instantly, the film has to start with very,
very tight shots of the stitching.''
</P>
<P>
   A book will accompany the series (it's a tribute to Schama's
transatlantic buzz-straddling that the publisher will be Tina
Brown's imprint, Talk Miramax Books). Then he returns to his
students at Columbia, where he holds a university professorship,
which means he can teach in any department he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shameless eclecticism has been my only methodological guide,''
he writes in ``The Embarrassment of Riches,'' a sentence applicable
to most of his books. But if he ever did find himself struck with
shame, what's the one field he would limit himself to?
</P>
<P>
   Schama does not hesitate. ``Cooking. I love cooking.'' Told he
must choose an academic discipline, he grimaces and then makes sure
his selection leaves him ample wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art history, because . . . such a lot of human experience I
care about is embedded in it. Not just pictures. It would have to
be an art history, very much as in the 19th century, in Vienna,
about tapestry weaving and furniture making and crude prints and
ancient forms of pornography: the history of images. If that's all
I could do, yes, that would be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
