<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIED TRAVELERS CATCH THE WAIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were listening to the radio Wednesday _ either from your
traffic-jammed car or your onion-scented kitchen _ you may have
heard an announcer say that tolls had been waived on the turnpike
and traffic was being waved through. If you'd been asked to spell
the words, would you have wavered?
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, after a Fast Lane-related slowdown, a reader wrote
to say waived through must be the proper term, since tolls were
being waived. Wave and waive aren't high on the list of troublesome
homonyms, perhaps because they're used in such different contexts,
but our traffic problems may be reviving a dormant confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Such a mix-up would have been highly forgivable in earlier
centuries, when there were two versions of waive in English: The
one still in use today, with Old French origins, and another one,
now obsolete, derived from Old Norse. To add to the muddle, the
now-obsolete waive overlapped in meaning with wave, an Old English
word; both could mean flutter. The absence of standardized spelling
made matters worse: Samuel Johnson, in his famous 1755 dictionary,
chose to spell our waive as wave.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, this is now, and our spelling task is
simpler.
</P>
<P>
   True, we have new ways of using waive since Johnson's time: The
20th century gave us the sporting version (a player is ``waived
through every team in baseball''). But this, like our older uses _
he waived the law through to enactment, the suspect waived his
right to counsel _ describes an abstract process. You can't draw a
picture of someone waiving your parking fines. Waving, however, is
a concrete action, something done by a flag in the breeze or a baby
saying bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   So if you can see it, it's a wave; if it involves an
institutional process, waive's your word. As in: If our leaders
would waive work and school attendance Thanksgiving week, we could
wave goodbye to traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The end of the affair?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One friend recently told another that a woman she knew was
having an affair. ``Is the guy married?'' asked the listener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' said the tale-teller. ``That's what an affair
means.''
</P>
<P>
   The listener was dubious. Did affair imply adultery, he asked,
or had the meaning only recently shifted in that direction as sex
outside marriage became more acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   If the definition is changing, my 1997 dictionary hasn't caught
up: It defines affair as ``an amorous relationship between two
people not married to each other,'' no adultery required.
</P>
<P>
   Just how ``amorous'' an affair must be it does not say, and that
has surely varied with time and place. As recently as 1910,
novelist E. M. Forster could make a plot turn on the fact that a
kiss, for a respectable young English couple, implied an
engagement; yet Norman Rockwell and his first wife had, as The New
York Times put it, ``a very 1920s marriage in that both had affairs
with others.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fine distinctions in the movie ``Indiscreet'' are worthy
of our recent presidential parsings on the subject of sex: The
(discreet) affair between Cary Grant and Ingrid Bergman is
acceptable while he's pretending to have a wife who won't divorce
him. But once his bachelorhood is revealed, he himself is
scandalized by Bergman's teasing suggestion that they carry on as
unmarried lovers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a case that cries out for readers' testimony. Does
anyone speak of affairs today when the principals are unmarried? Or
are the couple an item, having a thing? I've just been instructed
by a college-age daughter in the nomenclature of pairings at her
school _ you progress from seeing each other to dating to being
together to going out _ and college kids can't be the only ones
struggling to define such relationships.
</P>
<P>
   So please tell me, in language appropriate for a family
newspaper, whether you think an affair must include a betrayed
spouse (or even a complicit one), or whether it takes only two to
tango. Include your age, too (not necessarily for publication, but
to clue me in to generational differences).
</P>
<P>
   And if affair is over, in your set, what words have replaced it?
Do you just say they're seeing each other, and guess at (or ask
about) the level of intimacy? If we've decided to change the
definition of affair, our lexicographers shouldn't be the last to
know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
