<HEADLINE>
CARROLL VOWS CHANGES TO RIGHT PATRIOTS SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ ``Coaches live on the edge,'' Patriots coach
Pete Carroll said Monday, but seldom if ever have he and his team
been dangling over such a sharp edge as this. Even if for the third
straight year Carroll has his team at 6-5 over 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Things have unraveled so quickly _ with three straight (and
one-sided) losses to division foes _ that the usual midseason swoon
seems more threatening than in the 1997 and 1998 seasons. In those
years, there was no sense that opposing defenses knew the Patriots'
playbook better than the New England players.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sick time for coaches,'' said Carroll, not to
mention a sick time for Patriot players and a sick time for Patriot
fans. ``It's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   And those legions of fans calling for his head? No concern, said
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for that,'' he said. ``I've already been through
enough stuff in my coaching career. I've been around guys who've
been . . . uh, scrutinized . . . that it's not going to affect what
I do or how I do things. Like I've told you, that has never been a
factor in how I do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   New England cornerback Steve Israel said, ``We're in a slump
now, a Bad News Bears slump,'' but the Patriots have no time for
slumps to take their natural course. Immediate action is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever losing three games in a row in my
life,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy, who forgot the three straight
losses in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have indeed lost those three straight games, and
they also lost their offense in the bye-week vacation four weeks
ago. They clearly have lost their confidence, too. A lost season
looms.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, for his part, was little different from his usual
upbeat personality Monday even as he promised changes. The coach
said he was confident in both himself and his team that the many
wrongs of the last three weeks can be righted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that we can get this fixed,'' said
Carroll. ``I'm very confident in what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, he said, ``live and die with what goes on. But where
your confidence comes from is knowing what you've been able to do,
what you can do, and trusting you can do that. So, from where I
sit, I feel we can turn it around right now. It's going to be
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, said the coach, his players have not given up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still with it,'' he said. ``I'm not disappointed at
all in their effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll would not be specific about changes, whether they will
be in personnel or game plans, other than to say ``a little of
both.''
</P>
<P>
   As for changes in schemes, Carroll conceded that he should have
acted earlier, as it became clearer to some observers weeks ago
that the New England offense was becoming more and more mired in
quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished we would have made those changes a little bit
earlier,'' he said. ``But we figured we would have been able to
execute (the offense), and that's why we did what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was practice the offensive plays harder after the dismal
effort against Miami. But after scoring only 7 points Sunday in
Buffalo, Carroll has concluded that the offense needs more than
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team that can't make its third-down conversions, nothing
looks right,'' said Carroll. ``That's the way it looks like. You
don't get to feel the rhythm of the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the offense has to be revamped.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he and team owner Robert Kraft talk regularly and,
``since I've been here, I've always received strong support.'' That
support might not be so strong if the Patriots collapse in their
final five games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing it in the way I know best how to do it,'' said
Carroll. ``That's the way I've felt about it any other time in my
career and that's the way I feel about it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
