<HEADLINE>
SINKING CAUSED BY SMALL LEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ You watch the Patriots' slow demise the
past three weeks and the past three years and you wonder how this
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Little things, not big ones. That's how it happened.
</P>
<P>
   A few of them stared owner Bob Kraft in the face Sunday as he
was packing up his gear in the visiting owner's box at Ralph Wilson
Stadium and walking out on his team before they were finished
staggering to a 17-7 defeat. Walking out while thinking thoughts
that were not happy thoughts even on this Thanksgiving weekend.
</P>
<P>
   One of those things was Chris Carter getting called for
interference when he put his hand in the face of a receiver despite
appearing to be in perfect position to make the play without doing
that. It was another close play not made by someone the team's
brain trust had assured Kraft would fill in ably for Willie Clay
after they exiled Clay two days before training camp rather than
renegotiate his contract down from a salary-cap figure that had
grown too high.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lousy thing to do to a guy who hadn't missed a
practice, let alone a game, since he came to New England. A lousy
way to treat a good soldier and a lousy message to send to a team
that already had too many guys coming in late or not working hard
enough on the days when games are won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we're a championship team or not has nothing to do
with me being late (to practice),'' said Terry Glenn, who was
benched in the first quarter for that transgression. He didn't
learn that from Willie Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Clay would never be mistaken for Ronnie Lott, but three weeks
ago he quietly moved into the starting lineup in New Orleans,
beating out a man far younger, far faster, far more physically
gifted than he is because Mike Ditka concluded that Clay was a
smarter player who could help his struggling team. Could he not
have helped the struggling team he was already on more? Would he
have missed any more tackles than Carter has or made any fewer
plays? Would he, maybe just once, have put his defense in the right
spot at the right time or maybe put himself in such a spot?
</P>
<P>
   Little things.
</P>
<P>
   Tebucky Jones, whom the Patriots drafted instead of Green Bay's
talented pass-rushing defensive end Vonnie Holliday, was beaten
again in nickel coverage on third down. Beaten twice the week
before in the same circumstances. Beaten after being put where the
men who wanted him insisted he needed to be. Beaten when put in
position to make plays because he is not a cornerback. Wasn't the
day they used a first-round draft pick on him and isn't today _
regardless of what Pete Carroll keeps trying to feed the media _
because his hips don't turn the way they need to turn and that's
not his fault. That's nature's fault, but there's not much Jones
can do about it but be one step short too often at one of the
game's loneliest positions.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he wasn't even the best safety on the Syracuse team
he was drafted from. His former teammate, Donovan Darius, was taken
well after Jones but has been starting for two years on what is now
statistically the best defense in football, Jacksonville's. They
came out of the same draft. Two safeties. The difference? One is
still playing safety.
</P>
<P>
   Little things.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Gash caught a pass out of the Buffalo backfield Sunday. Tedy
Bruschi was faced with both a gap (inside run) responsibility and
coverage in the flat. That's a difficult spot under the best of
circumstances, and this was not the best of circumstances because
Bills offensive coordinator Joe Pendry had a perfect call on.
</P>
<P>
   With a tight end crossing in front of him and a wide receiver
picking him off while crossing from the other direction, Bruschi
simply had too much traffic to fight through and he couldn't get
where he needed to be to cover a guy who should still be playing
fullback in New England but isn't because Kraft was led to believe
the ultimate team player had turned into a sour clubhouse lawyer
two years ago during a contract dispute that was more about
personalities than money.
</P>
<P>
   He was told Gash was damaged goods, not recovering from a knee
injury that everyone with any experience in such things knew takes
at least a year to come back from. Told he was killing the new
coach in the locker room. Told that despite all Gash had done to
prove otherwise, he was selfish.
</P>
<P>
   After Gash took that pass and slipped out of the hands of Andy
Katzenmoyer for a 31-yard touchdown that finished the Patriots,
here's what a teammate said about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the great leaders on this team,'' Doug Flutie
gushed. ``He keeps his mouth shut, works hard, and motivates guys.
He's got an intensity level about him and does all the dirty
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The malingering, loud-mouthed clubhouse lawyer who couldn't get
along with the new coach in New England goes to Buffalo and gets a
personality transplant? No, he goes to Buffalo and continues to be
what he has always been. What he'd still be in New England if
they'd let him: a Pro Bowl blocking back despite having not carried
the football a single time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gash does his job so well the Bills coaches give out a weekly
award called the ``Sam Gash.'' It goes to the player who works the
hardest and goes 100 percent on every play. Gash had won it twice
before Sunday. After being handed a game ball, he won it again, in
a place where nobody has a bad thing to say about him.
</P>
<P>
   Little things.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road a piece, Curtis Martin was going over the
1,000-yard mark, rushing for 83 yards in 19 carries for the Jets
against Indianapolis. He has 1,042 yards, which is only about 40
percent more than the Patriots' leading rusher has. He is third in
the NFL in rushing and this is the second straight year he has
rushed for more than 1,000 yards since he left New England after
being branded as too expensive and too injury-prone and on the
downside of his career. Someone in the New England organization
actually produced a computer analysis that said you could find a
back to do what Martin does in the draft with relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the Patriots are still looking for that guy
when they should be looking for the one with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Little things.
</P>
<P>
   It is early in the fourth quarter of a game you are trailing,
17-0, because your defense has gotten a couple of bad breaks, but
you have the ball at your opponent's 48-yard line and you're
driving. There is still plenty of time if you can get something
here. It is fourth and 1 and you elect to go for it, but despite
having a quarterback who has sneaked his way to such first downs
five times this year without being stopped, you decide not to let
him try the one run he seems capable of making. Worse, you don't
run at all.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, you put this less-than-mobile quarterback in the
shotgun, virtually screaming out that you're going to throw. The
ball is snapped and seconds later the quarterback is on his back,
sacked for a 13-yard loss. Your defense holds, but when you get the
ball back, you've lost two precious minutes and now every play is a
pass and you go nowhere, and by the time you get the ball back
again and score, there are less than three minutes to play and it's
over. The game and probably the season.
</P>
<P>
   In football, as in most of life, little things add up. You do
enough of them well and the big things take care of themselves. If
you don't, you spend your life at 6-5, fighting to survive from
week to week.
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to know what has happened in Foxborough since the
Patriots made their last trip to the Super Bowl, add up the little
things. Add up all those draft choices you got from the Jets for
Martin and Bill Parcells and remember names such as Sedrick Shaw,
Damon Denson, Chris Floyd, Robert Edwards, and Tony Simmons, and
ask yourself if you got real value for your losses.
</P>
<P>
   Add up someone coming to the conclusion that Chris Canty was a
better cornerback prospect than Sam Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Add up all those offensive linemen you've drafted the past three
years, six of them all together, and ask where they are when your
quarterback is being sacked 13 times in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the little things, and you'll have your answer to the
big question of what's gone wrong in Foxborough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
