<HEADLINE>
IN THE MILD, MILD EAST, IT ALL SEEMS TO EVEN OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Celtics coach Rick Pitino had the NBA standings in his
hand Monday and was going over the Eastern Conference. After
rattling off all the teams at or around .500, he said, simply,
``We're right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's true. But it's also true of a lot of other teams.
After four weeks of NBA competition, here's what we have in the
East: the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   We have Miami ahead of the pack. We have Chicago chasing the
1972-73 Sixers. We have New Jersey and Washington, two teams
playing horribly. And then we have Everybody Else.
</P>
<P>
   We have 11 teams bunched together, all within four games of each
other. Throw out 5-9 Atlanta and the remaining 10 are all within
three games. Six teams as of Monday were at .500, although 7-7
Indiana and 7-7 New York had games Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets win at home. The Raptors win on the road. The Magic
_ the Magic? _ play the same no matter what the venue. The Knicks
have already played 10 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's topsy-turvy. All of those teams had better fasten their
seat belts because I think it's going to be a bumpy ride all
year,'' said Chris Wallace, paraphrasing the immortal line from
Bette Davis in ``All About Eve.'' He added, ``I think there's very
little difference between the teams. It's an `on any given night'
type of thing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Orlando. The Magic have won seven games, or seven
more than many figured they'd have won by now. On Sunday night,
they played the Pistons at the Palace of Auburn Hills. They were
coming off a close loss the day before against the Knicks while
Detroit had won seven of nine and was off on Saturday. The Magic
won, easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unsung team in all of this has to be Orlando,'' Wallace
said. ``They tore their house down over the summer and they're
hanging tough. They're there, every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino was asked if he thought one of the Jumbled Ten might
break away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Detroit, and then (Sunday) night, Orlando is up 20
for the entire game. And you think Milwaukee is going to break out
of it and Philly goes in and beats them without (Theo) Ratliff and
(Allen) Iverson. I don't know what to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very close in talent. Very close. I think there
are dominating basketball players and dominating basketball teams.
The San Antonios, the Portlands, the Sacramentos, they're
dominating teams. And Miami. Then, you have everybody else equal in
talent. Some are younger. Some are older. There's great parity.''
</P>
<P>
   And where do the Celtics fit in?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who we are right now,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a team that, like the others, has been up and down. The
Celtics have played the fewest road games, and most home games, of
any team in the East. They've had only one game against a team from
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Those two areas work against them. But, like New York (Patrick
Ewing), Philly (Iverson, Ratliff, Matt Geiger), Cleveland (Zydrunas
Ilgauskas), and New Jersey (Jayson Williams, Kerry Kittles), they
have a player deemed to be important (Danny Fortson) who has missed
a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said Monday that while Fortson might return in early
January, he did not expect him to be at full strength for another
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to need a month,'' Pitino said. ``I don't think you
expect a guy eight weeks off to become a great player (right away).
I have not seen that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Marty Conlon, said to be Fortson Insurance, Pitino was
asked Monday how close he was to coming off the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics finished the month with a 7-7 record, not as
successful as Pitino had hoped, and 6-3 at the FleetCenter, which,
given the level of competition, probably was about where it should
have been. They gave one away on the road (Chicago) and one away at
home (Detroit). They blew one at home (Milwaukee) and on the road
(Atlanta). They won unexpectedly on the road (Toronto) and at home
(Charlotte, New York, Indiana).
</P>
<P>
   They've done this with a rookie starter and with their top-paid
player and captain playing, well, ``nowhere near playing his best
basketball,'' according to the coach. He added, however, that
Antoine Walker wasn't the only one not playing as well as he should
or could.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well as a team,'' Pitino said. ``But our parts
are not playing well. That's true mostly of this team. I think
it'll come on at the end of the year. Paul (Pierce) is not playing
his (best) basketball . . . Kenny (Anderson) started off good, but
. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones playing great basketball, by himself, are two
people: Adrian (Griffin) and Eric (Williams). I think (the rest)
are going to come on and play better basketball, especially at the
defensive end. Defense is our Achilles' heel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule, their November ally, is about to turn against
them. The Celtics have to play the Sixers, Knicks, Cavs, Spurs,
Rockets, Clippers, Kings, and Nuggets on the road in December. But
they also get the Sixers without Iverson and the Knicks without
Ewing (and maybe Larry Johnson, too). And among their home visitors
in the month are Miami (next up, this Friday), the Jazz, and the
Lakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
