<HEADLINE>
TIME TO TUNE IN AND AIR SOME GRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, Korn thinks it has ``Issues''? Here are some issues for you:
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of intellectual foreplay and incessant
teasing, Mulder and Scully on Fox's ``The X-Files'' finally
smooched. Well, was it good for you? Was it everything you've
waited for? I dunno _ somehow, I felt a little unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's hokey, inexplicably popular game show for dummies, ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' recently claimed seven of the top 10
slots for the week's most-watched television shows. An average of
24 million viewers tuned in to watch contestants who would be left
for dead on any installment of ``Jeopardy.'' Yes indeedy, we get
the TV shows we deserve. And speaking of ``Millionaire,'' isn't
Regis Philbin just the luckiest white man in show biz? (For
luckiest black man in show biz, see Will Smith.)
</P>
<P>
   And staying on the tube tip, back in the 1950s, ``I Love Lucy''
packed it in after six seasons. In the 1970s, the cast of ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show'' sang ``It's a Long Way to Tipperary'' and
walked away after seven sparkling years. Neither classic comedy
stayed on to the point where the seams began to show; hence we have
memories of both programs ending at the top of their game. To wit,
I'm proposing a five-year statute of limitations for TV shows,
especially sitcoms _ sort of an expiration date before they go
stale and sour. No comedy, regardless of how fresh and clever it
may be at the beginning, can sustain itself for much longer than a
half-decade. Think of shows like ``All in the Family'' (1971-79),
``Cheers'' (1982-93), ``The Cosby Show'' (1984-92), and
``Seinfeld'' (1990-98), all of which limped to their respective
finish lines. The latest casualty seems to be NBC's ``Frasier''
(1993-??), which had been the best comedy on television for a good
chunk of the '90s. Now the show seems tired and redundant. How much
more innuendo can we take between Niles and Daphne? How many more
jokes are there to be made about Roz's promiscuity or Frasier's
inability to sustain a relationship? And is Martin's hip better by
now? Time to hang it up, gang. The show is so over, it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What with all the gats and gangstas still clogging up hip-hop,
it's easy to forget that rap used to have a sense of humor. After
all, the genre's first hit, 1979's ``Rapper's Delight'' by
Sugarhill Gang, concerned itself with nothing more lethal than a
lousy meal of soggy macaroni, mushed peas, and woodlike chicken
served by your best friend's mama. To remind all of us of the humor
within hip-hop, its fans, and practitioners, there's ``ego trip's
Book of Rap Lists,'' a spanking-new compilation by the editors of
the irreverent (and all-too-irregular) rap 'zine ego trip. It's
arguably the funniest book of the year, and certainly one of the
best ever about hip-hop. There are lots of factual lists _ the
first recorded rap song was ``King Tim III (Personality Jock)'' by
Fatback _ but many of the lists are just plain hilarious, the
twisted flotsam of true hip-hop heads. A wee sampling:
</P>
<P>
   10 Things Rappers Do to Ruin Their Careers:
</P>
<P>
   --Pull guns on A &AMP; R men (No. 1)
</P>
<P>
   --Say, ``My cousin is my manager'' (No. 4)
</P>
<P>
   --Get incarcerated (No. 6)
</P>
<P>
   --Have too much money, not enough brains (No. 7)
</P>
<P>
   Things Rappers Spend Their Money on:
</P>
<P>
   --Acting lessons (No. 7)
</P>
<P>
   --Johnnie Cochran (No. 8)
</P>
<P>
   --Millions of thugs on salary (No. 9)
</P>
<P>
   Women Russell Simmons (hip-hop impresario and cofounder of Def
Jam Records) wishes he dated before he got married:
</P>
<P>
   --Bond girl supreme Pussy Galore of ``Goldfinger'' (No. 1)
</P>
<P>
   --Pam Grier (No. 8)
</P>
<P>
   --Penny Marshall (No. 13)
</P>
<P>
   --Priscilla Presley (No. 17)
</P>
<P>
   Penny Marshall?!
</P>
<P>
   10 Reasons Why Rap Will Never Die:
</P>
<P>
   --Some blacks can't jump, shoot, or go to their left (No. 8)
</P>
<P>
   --You can't kill something that's already dead (No. 1)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And another thing: Beck is the Elvis of the 1990s. Do with that
what you will.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Third Eye Blind, which just released its sophomore
album, ``Blue,'' realizes it will never again make a song as good
as the breakthrough hit ``Semi-Charmed Life''?
</P>
<P>
   On her latest CD, Celine Dion does the necrophiliac singing
thing (a la Natalie Cole and her beyond-the-grave duet with her
father, Nat King Cole on ``Unforgettable'') with Frank Sinatra on
his classic ``All the Way.'' That's wrong on so many levels, I'd
need a whole 'nother column to list them all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't gotten your Prada survival kits and Ikea bomb
shelters, what are you waiting for? Only 32 more shopping days till
the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
