<HEADER>
A5081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-GERRARD-BOS &LR;      11-30 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GERRARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING MUSIC TO THE MOVIES: A CHANGE OF ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 16 years as half of the enchanting and ethereal
world-music-and-beyond group Dead Can Dance, Lisa Gerrard finds
herself in a new role: soundtrack artist. She has been working with
Michael Mann and Ridley Scott, two of the top directors when it
comes to incorporating music in film. Gerrard and collaborator
Pieter Bourke composed and/or played much of the score for Mann's
``The Insider,'' the tobacco-whistleblower drama out now; and
Gerrard is at work with Hans Zimmer in Los Angeles on an upcoming
Scott film, ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose me,'' Gerrard says, barely suppressing a pinch-me
feeling of astonishment. ``I feel like I am at school at the
moment, I am learning so much. Just working with Michael was really
a huge education.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourke and Gerrard ``wrote nearly 100 pieces, and now working
with this project there is a different education being picked up.
So I feel very much at the moment I am a part of an apprenticeship,
and I am very fortunate because I am working. I forget the
magnitude of these projects. It is not possible for me to think
about the external sort of things; the things that I must think
about are what the characters are going through.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gerrard speaks about magnitude, she's talking about these
films' potential for worldwide reach. As acclaimed as Dead Can
Dance was, and as fervent is its fan base, its music is unlikely to
reach as many people as films do.
</P>
<P>
   The haunting, exotic score for ``The Insider'' is particularly
effective. It's not an action movie, so the Bourke and Gerrard are
not providing a soundtrack for car chases and gunplay. A lot of
``The Insider'' deals with the action and reaction of the
characters, as well as their interior landscapes. The music _
atmospheric and polyrhythmic, with Gerrard sometimes contributing
chantlike vocals _ adds an otherworldliness, often amplifying
Russell Crowe's character's confusion and frustration as
executive-turned-secret-spiller Jeffrey Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   Gerrard is fascinated by the depth and detail in Mann's film.
``There is one shot of Jeffrey and his wife,'' Gerrard says, ``and
she is sitting on the couch.'' Al Pacino's character, CBS producer
Lowell Bergman, calls. ``She answers the phone and says, `He does
not care to talk to you,' and she puts the phone down. There are
these curtains in the back of that shot that look like concrete;
they are cold, and unmoving, fabric that looks like it could be
hosed down. It is this sort of chiseling and sculpting that
surrounds this incredibly fragile fabric that is the human
consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mann ``allows you, with the music, to take you further and
further and further into a greater understanding of what the human
being is. I think that is the important thing about his films: You
are touched by this man's work, and he can take it to the most
brutal situations, and he will find a human factor in each, and
unlock that for you. And he unlocks that with music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlock'' is a word Gerrard uses frequently in discussing the
work. That is the key, she suggests, in making what she does mesh
with, or enhance, what is happening on screen.
</P>
<P>
   As such, she says, she strives to unlock ``the multidimensional
possibilities to arrive at the stories or psychology the director
wants to conjure up.'' On ``The Insider,'' her task was to unlock
``the internal things that he is experiencing, his memory. I sort
of went through his struggle with his conscience, his humiliation
of losing his work, and the losing of his family, deciding to tell
the truth, taking risks, being put under the most incredible
pressure a human being can be put under, having a nervous
breakdown, losing everything, his wife and his children.''
</P>
<P>
   Soundtracks these days, of course, can mean big business in the
record stores, as many a movie is chockablock with the
flavor-of-the-week act. (Say hello to 'N Sync and Christina
Aguilera.) If people choose to buy ``The Insider'' soundtrack,
they'll be getting something entirely different, something not at
all related to the notion of a pop hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do film music, we do music for film,'' Gerrard says.
``We write pieces of music and then break them down so that they
work with the images, painting in bits and pieces until the piece
is written. Then we start editing, and holding things back, so the
pieces of music work in their own right. I can't just paint on
shadow; I have to have the atmosphere and something that is
abstract that points toward something else in the piece of music
first. And then you show that to the director and they might say,
`It doesn't affect me emotionally' or `Yes, it does affect me
emotionally.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gerrard occasionally gets lost in a thicket of words _ she'll
pause and ask, ``Was that too convoluted?'' _ but clearly she is
excited about her new life. Dead Can Dance dissolved amicably, by
mutual agreement _ she thinks. It just kind of happened. Her former
partner, Brendan Perry, has released his first solo album, ``Eye of
the Hunter,'' and recently played a compelling concert in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important part of being in Dead Can Dance for me were
the concerts,'' says Gerrard, ``and they were my liberation period,
where I was liberated by the sense that can be arrived at through
the most simple music.'' The breakup?
</P>
<P>
   ``What reasons do we have to have? Things got to a point where .
. . it's as simple as this: When you want to go down a road, the
two of you, and you want to go together, and you get to a point
where one thinks that the way you're going down the road isn't
right, and the other thinks it's right, and you can't go down the
road anymore, you have to part for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The telepathic communication they once shared was dissipating,
she says, and, ``we could not step forward confidently, either of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a liberating feeling,'' she says, of her split. ``I
mean of course it is sad, too, but we worked together for 16 years
and we learned so many things. I learned so much from Brendan. Even
in the work I am doing now, I am constantly sort of pillaging
things, his approaches and the way he would go about doing things.
His dedication and his capacity to work _ that influenced me,
because I am extremely dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   She's happy being a free agent, working with different people on
various projects. ``I will never connect myself with someone
permanently again,'' she says. ``I think it would be difficult now,
it would stunt the growth _ to just remain with one other person.''
</P>
<P>
   Athough Gerrard is confident in her work, she remains humble.
``I was surprised when I got this call about `Gladiator.' I did not
expect any work to come, and I know that Michael (Mann) has this
completely different opinion, and says, `You are going to get all
of these offers.' But you never really believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   What is ``Gladiator'' about? ``It goes from the most fragile
poetry to the deepest wound,'' Gerrard says. ``It is an
extraordinary piece of work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
