<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ARCHER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFREY ARCHER'S CHARMED CHAPTER COMES TO A CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jeffrey Archer's novels have made him a millionaire,
but many people believe his autobiography would be far more
interesting than any of the political potboilers he's dreamed up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many also believe that the 59-year-old Archer could never
write what would be his best book because he is incapable of
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's propensity for lying caught up to him last weekend when
he was forced to withdraw as the Conservative Party's candidate for
mayor of London. Archer had unwittingly admitted asking a friend to
lie for him in a libel case he brought in 1987 against a newspaper
that claimed he had had sex with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   His career and the reputation he had guarded so fiercely with a
sharp tongue and a battery of lawsuits now lies in ruins, destroyed
by a tale of debauchery, betrayal, high living, and low morals that
would fit readily in the plot line of one of his novels.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his undeniable charisma and a stable of
influential friends, Archer has survived countless scrapes, and in
1992 he was appointed to the House of Lords, an honor usually
reserved for those with less controversial backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   But now Archer faces the prospect of jail if a police
investigation substantiates the accusation of witness tampering,
even though the potential witness never did lie under oath, because
his testimony wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Ted Francis, is an old friend of Archer's. A
socialist who said he didn't want to see Archer become mayor,
Francis secretly recorded Archer recalling how he had asked Francis
to provide him with an alibi in the 1987 libel case.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Archer's political career, which stretches
back 30 years to his election to Parliament, appears to be over.
William Hague, the Tory leader who last month extolled Archer as a
man of ``probity and integrity,'' turned around this week and
banished him, saying ``this is the end of politics for Jeffrey
Archer.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer's sudden, scandalous withdrawal from politics will
deprive Britain of one of its most flamboyant characters, and the
Tories of a candidate whom many believed capable of becoming mayor
of one of the world's biggest cities. Had he been elected next May,
he would instantly have become a major international figure. It was
a pedestal he openly coveted, spending more than $1 million of his
own money in that pursuit over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has been the rare breed of Conservative who straddled the
world of politics and pop celebrity. Parties at his 10th-floor
apartment on the Embankment overlooking the River Thames serve up
Krug champagne, shepherd's pie, and an eclectic mix of the famous,
the near-famous, and the notorious.
</P>
<P>
   Born poor, Archer is a self-made social climber who spent
lavishly on the finer things in life. He has what the late Boston
Globe columnist George Frazier called ``duende.'' When first-time
guests at his parties ask for directions to the bathroom, he
invariably says, ``Go straight past the Picasso, take a left at the
Matisse.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also been an inveterate fund-raiser. He first came to
public prominence in Britain in 1963 by persuading the Beatles to
back a campaign against world hunger, and has raised millions for
Oxfam and Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his ability to survive extraordinary, repeated
attacks on his character and reputation that set him apart. Like
Bill Clinton, Archer has risen from the dead so many times that
there remains this week a small cadre of friends and even enemies
who refuse to write his political obituary. Also like Clinton,
Archer got into trouble over a woman named Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Crick, a journalist for the BBC who four years ago wrote
an unauthorized biography of Archer called ``Stranger Than
Fiction,'' called him a compulsive, pathological liar. He found
that Archer had falsified his academic records to get into Oxford
University.
</P>
<P>
   Archer was an accomplished sprinter, and the BBC recently aired
some archive film in which Archer was shown jumping the starter's
pistol three successive times in one race. Under the rules, two
false starts mean automatic disqualification. But in an episode
that was a portent of the charmed life that would follow, Archer
was allowed to run the race.
</P>
<P>
   Crick said Archer lied about things little and big, even when
there was no real need to lie. He listed himself on his 1966
marriage certificate as a research assistant _ needlessly, Crick
said. Archer described his father as a senior British Army officer
who was decorated for valor. Crick found that that was also made
up, that Archer's father was a con man and bigamist who was sought
by police in Britain, Canada, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, a brush with bankruptcy showed both Archer's poor
judgment and an uncanny ability to reinvent himself. After
investing $700,000 in a fraudulent Canadian industrial cleaning
company, Archer was forced to resign his seat in Parliament. Then,
while in Toronto trying to sort out the mess, he was arrested for
shoplifting suits from a department store. The charges were later
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, Archer reinvented himself, publishing his
first novel, ``Not a Penny More, Not a Penny Less.'' Borrowing a
line from the book's villain, Archer had managed to ``turn disaster
into triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   While many critics panned his books, the public bought them in
huge numbers.
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining raconteur, he began making a name for himself in
London social circles. His parties began attracting the likes of
Frank Bruno, the heavyweight boxer, as well as media and political
heavyweights from David Frost to Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, Archer's political rehabilitation, necessitated by his
imprudent investments, was complete, and he was appointed vice
chairman of the Conservative Party. But in September of the very
next year, he got caught up in the scandal that would eventually
destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's carefully cultivated image portrayed him as a family
man devoted to his wife, Mary, and their two sons, but two
scandal-mongering tabloids learned that Archer was involved with a
prostitute named Monica Coghlan. The News of the World reported
that Archer gave her $3,200 to leave the country. The Daily Star
didn't resort to innuendo, saying flat out that Archer had sex with
Coghlan in a seedy London hotel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ARCHER-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     11-30 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ARCHER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LONDON: ... London hotel.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The libel case Archer brought against The Daily Star was the
most sensational of the decade. Archer maintained that he had never
met Coghlan but had sent a friend to give her money after she
called him and said she was in trouble. He also maintained that at
the time Coghlan said she was having sex with him, he was having
dinner at Le Caprice, one of London's finest restaurants, with his
literary editor and two other friends.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Archer, an academic at Cambridge University, testified on
her husband's behalf. The judge was impressed. In his instructions
to the jury, the judge spoke of her ``elegance.'' The judge
practically implored the jury to find in Archer's favor, asking
jurors in his instructions to them, ``Is he in need of cold,
unloving, rubber-insulated sex in a seedy hotel round about quarter
to one on a Tuesday morning after an evening at Le Caprice?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not, the jury decided, awarding Archer a then-record
$800,000. The News of the World settled out of court for a fraction
of that. But his admission that he had given Coghlan money forced
him to resign as the Tories' deputy chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, he remained a political player without portfolio, and
in 1992 then-prime minister John Major rewarded him with a life
peerage. Archer courted political writers, inviting them to his
soirees and flattering them. But he was infamous for waking those
same scribes at dawn to berate them if they had written anything
unflattering about him.
</P>
<P>
   And there was always something unflattering being written about
Archer, particularly in the left-wing press. He was, to liberals,
the bete noire of politics. His rags-to-riches story and ability to
appeal to working-class people, the kind who used to vote for
Thatcher, struck fear in the heart of liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Archer was conscious of his unlikely popularity with ordinary
people. Earlier this month, he complained to The Daily Telegraph
about its practice of referring to him as Lord Archer instead of as
Jeffrey Archer. He said he wanted his first name used in future
reports so as not to alienate ``the common man.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some Tories who loathed Archer, seeing him as a rogue
who would only bring the party into disrepute. But many others saw
him as a rare Conservative, someone who socialized with the rich
but appealed to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   As Norman Tebbit, a former Tory Cabinet minister, put it, ``He
gave the party dash and style.''
</P>
<P>
   While Archer's brushes with notoriety would have spelled exile
for just about anyone else, his defenders included the last three
Tory party leaders, Thatcher, John Major, and Hague.
</P>
<P>
   He was seen as something that most Tories have not been of late:
electable. Last year, when it became apparent that Archer would
emerge as a candidate for mayor of London, Crick, the biographer,
offered to brief Hague, an Oxford classmate, on at least a
half-dozen cases of Archer's unethical behavior that, if brought to
light, could embarrass the Conservatives. The offer was spurned,
and last month party activists voted 15,716 to 6,350 to make Archer
their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that he was caught in a sting that could easily fill
a chapter of one of his novels. Francis, an old friend, went to the
News of the World, saying he was willing to betray Archer rather
than see him become mayor. Francis, a self-described socialist, has
said Archer had once humiliated him in front of a woman, but
insists his real motive was to deny Archer the mayoralty.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid got Francis to call Archer, claiming that someone
had learned about their concocted alibi in 1987. As a tape recorder
whirred, Archer recounted the whole affair. The newspaper showed
him the transcripts, and Archer pulled out of the mayor's race on
Saturday, just hours before the presses started to roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Star also wants back the money, now more than $5
million with interest and legal costs, that Archer won in the libel
trial.
</P>
<P>
   According to Francis, Archer asked him to say he was having
dinner with Archer at the time the author was actually dining with
Adrina Colquhoun, his former personal assistant. Archer's wife, not
to mention Thatcher, had told him to stop seeing Colquhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was paid more than $30,000 by the tabloid for his help.
But his publicist, Max Clifford, said Francis could have commanded
five to ten times that amount if money were his motive.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, Archer has been holed up in his country
estate, the Old Vicarage in Grantchester. His friends say he is
writing letters of apology.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, he is not without influential supporters. Fay Weldon,
the writer, said that what Archer did in 1987 is irrelevant to
running for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All politicians lie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Shakespeare, Archer's friend, said the novelist is a
victim of snobbery.
</P>
<P>
   But it was another Shakespeare, in ``Richard II,'' quoted by
Archer's lawyer at the opening of the 1987 libel trial, who paid
homage to something Archer can never regain:
</P>
<P>
   ``The purest treasure mortal times afford is spotless
reputation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
