<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-II-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICES OF 6 WHO AWAIT THEIR FATE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Black-and-white photos being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Executions are big events here.
</P>
<P>
   The prison museum in town proudly displays the electric chair
affectionately known as Old Sparky, which was used until 1964.
Bonnie and Clyde's bullet-riddled morgue photos hang on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's execution of Karla Faye Tucker, the first woman put
to death in Texas in 135 years, attracted more people outside the
prison than attended a Harlem Globetrotters basketball game at
nearby Sam Houston State University the same night, according to
prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   But in death, fame is fleeting. If an inmate is executed and
laid to rest by the state it is his number, preceded by an ``x''
for execution _ not his name _ that appears on the small white
cross in Captain Joe Bryd Cemetery in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Texas Department of Criminal Justice Ellis Unit One
Prison, 12 miles outside Huntsville, the sun gleams off the
half-million-dollar razor wire added after a death row inmate
successfully scaled the fence last November. He was shot in the
escape then found drowned in a creek a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Death row, like the rest of the prison, is cleaner than most
office buildings. ``We've got a lot of labor,'' said one official.
The warden's office is one of the few prison areas with air
conditioning. On his walls are pictures of John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners are allowed fans in their 6-by-10-foot cells and they
can vote on what to watch on the cellblock television. They are
taken to showers daily in handcuffs. All their mail is screened.
Two hours are allowed for recreation, but there is no shade from
the relentless sun. The basketballs in the courtyard all need air.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the triple-tiered cellblocks have both bars and wire
screens around them. These are for the inmates in segregation for
violating prison rules. When correction officers pass the
segregation cells with other prisoners, they use a shield of
plexiglass to protect themselves and the inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are gang rivalries here and they can fire handmade darts
crafted from paper and bits of metal,'' said Larry Fitzgerald, a
spokesman for the Texas criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Photojournalists have not been allowed on Texas' death row in a
year. What follows are the thoughts and images of six juveniles
offenders there. All were 17 years old when the murders were
committed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Derek Guillen, 18
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was convicted and sentenced to death for the March 26,
1998, robbery, rape, and murder of Margaret Shores, 51, the
director of a Texas child care agency. Police said Guillen broke
into Shores' home, fractured her skull, and stabbed her to death.
Guillen never testified at his trial. He told his mother that he
was at the robbery scene, then left with a friend. When he
returned, Shores was on the floor, dead, with a towel over her
head. His friends were on the couch, giggling and high on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was captured along with four other teenagers trying to
use Shores' credit cards at a local mall. Witnesses at his trial
testified Guillen bragged that he killed Shores and then had sex
with her. DNA experts said Shores' blood was on one of Guillen's
sneakers and inside her 1996 Toyota Corolla, and his pubic hairs
were found on her corpse. At his trial, Guillen pleaded not guilty
to the charge of murder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guillen: It wasn't the way I thought it would turn out. I wasn't
there when the killing happened, and I came back and the person was
already dead. I didn't say anything. I didn't want to give a
statement to the Texas Rangers or the DA (district attorney). I
told my lawyer what happened and who to look for, and right now the
guy who did the killing is living right next door to my mom. He was
my best friend. I always thought snitching was wrong and I knew I
didn't do the actual crime.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There was a conference in Atlanta recently where they talked
about speeding up the appeals process and executions. How does that
make you feel?
</P>
<P>
   Guillen: Sometimes I think a lot of guys should get the death
penalty. (But) it's not right to hurry up and take my life just
because it will make somebody feel better. In the long run, I think
it will make matters worse. Taking a life is different than a
murder. . . . Personally, I'd rather kill myself before I let
someone kill me. It's something that bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was your family life like?
</P>
<P>
   Guillen: In the beginning my dad was a pimp. He used to pimp my
mom. . . . My biological father did a lot of things. He hit her,
went out on her. I finally got a letter from him. He's locked up on
drugs. He's trying to get things right with me. He thinks I don't
remember some of the things he did to my mom.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I got high I was seven years old at my
grandfather's. I was living in Detroit. I'm half Mexican, half
black. I broke into my first house when I was nine years old, just
for something to do. My mom stands by me to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you ever think about the execution?
</P>
<P>
   Guillen: I try not to think about it. I would like to spend time
with my mom. I saw her in court crying, and I haven't been able to
touch my mom in I don't know how long.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Arroyo, 20 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo, a.k.a. Abdullah Arroyo, was convicted and sentenced to
death in the March 1997 murder of US Air Force Captain Jose Cobo
during a carjacking in San Antonio. Arroyo and an accomplice,
Vincent Gutierrez, were looking for spare parts for Arroyo's Mazda.
According to witness testimony at the trial, Cobo tried to escape
but got caught in the automatic seat belt. Arroyo told Gutierrez to
shoot Cobo. The captain was shot twice in the back and his body
dumped on the shoulder of a crowded Houston highway during morning
rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo pleaded not guilty of murder and turned down a plea
bargain to testify for the state. He never testified at his trial,
but Arroyo's lawyers argued that their client was guilty only of
aggravated robbery. Gutierrez was also convicted of murder and
sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: It's just hard, man. I don't believe they think I'm here
because I'm guilty. I'm here because I'm ignorant of the law. I
ain't got no money to pay for no lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's it like to be so young and be on death row?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: It's nasty. It's harder than people think. The hardest
part is coming in at 17. I'm just like every other kid. I lived in
the ghetto. I worked for every cent I had. I went to school. I
tried to get out of school. All of a sudden they pick someone at
random because it's a captain of the Air Force. Prosecutors wanted
to look good so they grabbed the first people they could come up
with.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How could you be like every other kid if you are on death row
for murder?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: That's if you did it. It's a terrible crime. As much as
they put out I was guilty, I want to see if they give me the same
publicity when I show how the cops corrupted the statements. No, I
didn't pull the trigger. I was not at the scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But you were quoted at the trial as shouting, ``I tried to
help him,'' after the verdict was announced?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: Uh, I tried to. . .call the police when I found out what
happened. I didn't know the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you grow up in a dysfunctional family?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: I don't know what dysfunctional means. I didn't grow up
in any messed up family. We grew up hard, but we weren't messed up.
I didn't grow up with a father.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At what minimum age should a juvenile be eligible for the
death penalty?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: I couldn't put no age figure on it. I think that the age
that I was, I shoulda been tried as a juvenile because I'm still
ignorant to a lot of things. I don't believe no one should get the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you're young, you think you'll live forever. Do you
still feel that way?
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo: Well, since I believe in eternal life, I do. I believe
that something good will come out of this. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Dewberry, 22
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dewberry was sentenced to death for the 1994 shotgun slaying of
Lamar University registrar Elmer Rode. Police said Rode's body was
found on Christmas afternoon. He had been tied up and shot several
times in the head during a robbery of his Beaumont, Texas, home.
Witnesses testified that Dewberry, then 17, gave items taken in the
robbery to friends as Christmas presents. Awaiting trial in 1996,
he escaped briefly while chained to another inmate, jumping from a
transport van that was taking them to a dental appointment.
Dewberry pleaded not guilty to murder and never testified at his
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Dewberry: I've been here since Nov. 25, 1996. It's
indescribable. It's an emotional roller coaster. It's a mental and
physical stroke, dealing with this place and the people that are
running it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think about the needles?
</P>
<P>
   Dewberry: Everybody on death row thinks about being executed.
It's not a matter of if you will or you won't. . . . I don't see
how you can learn a lesson from something you didn't even do.
That's one thing I never did understand about people saying, `He
showed no remorse' for this or for that. How is a person supposed
to show remorse for something they didn't have anything to do with?
I can understand it being a tragic loss for that family but they
ain't considering the tragic loss in my family.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you grow up any faster on death row?
</P>
<P>
   Dewberry You grow up quick, real fast, on death row. Hear no
evil, see no evil, speak no evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's that picture of a race car on your wall?
</P>
<P>
   Dewberry: It's a fantasy car. I sit here and pretend I'm
driving. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
