<HEADLINE>
A SPECIAL HOLIDAY SEASON FOR BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a city that once banned Christmas (in Colonial days), Boston
boasts a holiday season that is one of the most festive in the
country. Add to this a spectacular exhibit of Egyptian treasures,
and what promises to be an unbelievable welcome to the new century,
and you have more reasons than ever to stay in the city _ or, if
you're from out of town, more reasons to head this way.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 holiday events in Boston and Cambridge are
highlighted, along with information on First Night, a festive way
to enter the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   To plan a trip to Boston, obtain the Greater Boston Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau's new 87-page free winter Travel Planner. Included
in the planner are events, performances, holiday happenings, hotel
packages for various events, and a Family Value Pass with 41
discounts good for shopping, restaurants, and museums.
</P>
<P>
   For a copy, call 888-SEE BOSTON (888-733-2678) or visit
www.bostonusa.com.
</P>
<P>
   This season there is added excitement in the city with an
eight-month Egypt Cultural Celebration going on. ``Pharaohs of the
Sun: Akhenaten, Nefertiti, Tuttankamen Exhibition'' runs through
Feb. 6 at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts, which already has one of
the best Egyptian collections in the world. The ``Mysteries of
Egypt'' Omnifilm is playing on the huge screen at the Museum of
Science. The Boston Lyric Opera, which just performed ``Aida,''
will feature ``Akhenaten'' in January and February; and
``Cleopatra'' is coming to the Wang Theatre in May.
</P>
<P>
   For the holidays, the traditional ``Nutcracker'' by the Boston
Ballet continues through Jan. 2 at the Wang, and across the street
at the Majestic, the Ballet Theatre of Boston offers its version of
the Tchaikovsky classic Dec. 8-28. Other musical treats in December
include The 146th annual performance of Handel &AMP; Haydn Society's
``Messiah,'' the 29th annual ``Black Nativity,'' the Vienna Boys
Choir, and the Holiday Boston Pops. And the Boston Symphony
Orchestra will be performing throughout the season. On stage are
``Stomp,'' ``Footloose,'' ``Ivanov,'' ``Buddy Holly Story,'' ``The
Idiots Karamazov,'' and the ``Sisters Matsumoto.''
</P>
<P>
   Festivities in Boston get underway with the lighting of the
Prudential Center tree Dec. 4, a gift of the people of Nova Scotia,
while the next night on Boston Common, another tree, this the gift
of New Brunswick, will be lighted.
</P>
<P>
   There will be lights throughout Boston. Faneuil Hall is always
colorful at this season. Newbury Street will be festive during its
annual Holiday Stroll Dec. 5, and Harvard Square will hold its
annual Holly Fair Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   More ideas for the season include Planet of the Penguins, a
celebration of these waddlers at the New England Aquarium Dec. 4-5;
the Aquarium's Bird Watching and Nature Cruise Dec. 5; the 226th
Boston Tea Party reenactment Dec. 12; the 29th Christmas Revels at
Harvard University's Sanders Theatre Dec. 10-26; the Holiday
Chocolate Bar Brunch with Santa at the Meridien Hotel Dec. 12; and
the Boston Crafts at the Castle show Dec. 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the place to be Dec. 31 is Boston for First Night
2000. The city's celebration of the eve of the millennium is a
Boston original (First Night is now celebrated in more than 100
cities). And this First Night is going to be like none before, with
countdowns and finales across the city, including multimedia
presentations and spectacular fireworks displays, with additional
fireworks the evenings of Jan. 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to catch the fun of the season is to stay in the
city. Most hotels have special packages for the Egypt exhibit,
First Night, and shopping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
