<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-I-     11-30 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-I-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US STANDS ALONE ON EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Black-and-white photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ The needles, those lethal injections that
deliver $86.06 worth of chemicals designed to stop the heart, are
years away from his veins. But they are already on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate number 999210 is a scared teenager on death row in the
only country known to kill its juvenile offenders. Texas leads the
nation in such executions.
</P>
<P>
   Head down, shirt off, and sweating in a 100-degree cell, Derek
Guillen, 18, wants to hug his mother, a mother who loves him so
much she once sold her body to get him milk on Christmas Day. But
if his appeal fails, he will be sent to the death chamber for the
1998 rape and murder of Margaret Shores, the director of a Texas
child care agency. As is the case with most death row juvenile
offenders interviewed, Guillen maintains he did not commit the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   On execution day, the inmate gets a last-meal request, a hot
shower, and a choice of prison-made clothes. When it is time, he
will be strapped in seven different places to a gurney and asked to
make a final statement. When the warden gives the signal _ removing
his eyeglasses _ the medical team begins a series of three lethal
injections.
</P>
<P>
   How long does it take to lapse into unconsciousness? ``One
inmate sang `Silent Night,' '' said Larry Fitzgerald, a spokesman
for the Texas criminal justice system. ``When he got to `mother and
child,' he was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th century comes to a close, the United States finds
itself in a position that critics argue should be as uncomfortable
as a prisoner strapped to the gurney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internationally, every other country has abandoned killing
juvenile offenders,'' said Victor L. Streib, a professor of law at
Ohio Northern University who has been tracking the number of
juveniles sentenced to death over the past 25 years. ``We're the
only ones left.''
</P>
<P>
   A report issued in October by the Death Penalty Information
Center, a Washington-based group that opposes capital punishment,
called the United States ``the most flagrant transgressor of the
international ban on executing juvenile offenders in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said that by condemning juveniles to die, the United
States is in violation of three treaties: the United Nations
Convention on the Rights of the Child, the International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights, and the American Convention on Human
Rights. ``Nowhere is the US in such clear and direct conflict with
the consensus of international law,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States says it is not bound by the treaties because
it has not ratified two of them, and is exempted from a key
provision of the third. Washington has signed all three documents,
but it only ratified the international covenant after placing a
``reservation'' against the article that outlaws the juvenile death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 international covenant was adopted by 144 nations.
Eleven US allies, angered by Washington's reservation, formally
protested. Sweden said the American action ``undermined the basis
of international treaty law.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, the UN's Human Rights Committee voted to call the US
reservation invalid. The committee also passed a resolution urging
that the death penalty not be imposed for crimes committed by
anyone under the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   There are five other countries known to have executed juvenile
offenders in the '90s: Iran, Nigeria, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, and
Yemen, but none since 1997, according to Amnesty International.
China, believed to have one of the highest rates of capital
punishment in the world, has also officially ceased the practice of
executing juvenile offenders, in accordance with laws implemented
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald, the Texas criminal justice spokesman, says the
emotional juvenile death penalty debate is often clouded by the
distinction between sentencing offenders to death when they are
juveniles, and actually carying out executions of juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't execute kids,'' he said. ``They are certified as
adults in the eyes of the law. Plus, they go through a lengthy
appeals process.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has executed 10 juvenile offenders this
decade, half of them in Texas. Because of lengthy automatic
appeals, none were teenagers at the time of their deaths. The
average time on death row in Texas is eight years and 10 months;
180 juvenile offenders have been sentenced to death in the United
States since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   A 1988 US Supreme Court ruling prohibits the death penalty for
juvenile offenders whose crimes were committed before they were 16.
Today, of the 38 states that have the death penalty, 25 allow for
the execution of juveniles whose crimes were committed when they
were 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 70 juvenile offenders currently sentenced to die
account for only two percent of the 3,600 US prisoners on death
row, the United States is under increasing pressure to stop
executing juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, Oklahoma executed Sean Sellers, 29, the first person
in 40 years put to death for crimes committed when he was 16. The
execution of Sellers triggered an international protest.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Robinson, the UN high commissioner for human rights,
unsuccessfully appealed to US officials to stop the execution, and
urged Washington to honor the UN Convention on the Rights of the
Child, even though it hadn't ratified the accord. ``The
overwhelming and growing international consensus that the death
penalty should not apply to juvenile offenders stems from the
recognition that young persons lack maturity and judgment and,
therefore, cannot be fully responsible for their actions,''
Robinson, the former president of Ireland, said at a press
conference in October. ``More importantly,'' young people ``have a
greater potential for rehabilitation than adults.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Stop Killing Kids Campaign'' sponsored by the National
Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty has gathered nearly 50,0000
student signatures urging a moratorium on the sentencing of
juveniles to death. The group plans to present the signatures to
the United Nations later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The US Supreme Court recently asked for additional arguments in
the Nevada death-penalty case of 16-year-old Michael Domingues
after his lawyers contended that by pressing for the death penalty,
the United States is in violation of the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights. Last month, the US Solicitor General
argued that the request should be denied, and the high court
announced later it would not hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   But to Samuel Jordan, director of Amnesty International's
program to abolish the death penalty, it is a moral issue, not a
legal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only barbaric it's a brutal disregard of children's
human rights,'' Jordan said. ``Most have either mental illness or
violent abuse in their backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims' rights groups say that argument is a copout. ``That's
no excuse for murder,'' said Dianne Clements, president of Justice
For All, a Houston-based advocacy organization. ``Who doesn't live
in a dysfunctional family? I think it's very barbaric for criminals
to murder. I think it's very appropriate for the death sentence to
be the ultimate sentence for the ultimate crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Clinard, the daughter of Margaret Shores, vowed that she
will be there to witness Guillen being put to death. ``My son had
to learn that there are disgusting, perverted people like you in
the world,'' Clinard said at the trial in her victim's impact
statement. ``On the day you die, I will be there watching you as
you twitch.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, families of both the victim and the convicted killer
are invited to watch the executions in separate rooms behind glass
and bars. From the gurney, Guillen will be able to see his mother
watching him. There will be no hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow any physical contact,'' said Fitzgerald. ``Not
even before the lethal injections.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
