<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-I-     11-30 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 HUNTSVILLE, Texas: ... lethal injections.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juvenile executions in the United States began in Massachusetts'
Plymouth Colony, in 1642 when Thomas Graunger, 17, was executed for
having sex with animals. Of the 19,200 executions held in the
United States since 1608, 356 have been juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   A Cherokee Indian boy was the youngest to be executed for
murder. He was hanged in 1885 at the age of 10. The youngest person
executed since World War II was George Stinney, 14, who at 5-feet
1-inch tall and 95 pounds was so small his mask fell off during his
electrocution in South Carolina in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in the aftermath of the horrific school shootings
that shook the country this year and last, there was a flurry of
efforts in various states to lower the eligible age for the death
penalty. One proposal in Texas would have set the age at 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected more Draconian laws'' to be approved, said Richard
Dieter, executive director of the Death Penalty Information Center.
``But none of them passed. No state has lowered its minimum age
that allows for the death penalty for juveniles in the last 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several states have raised the age. Florida went from
16 to 17 and Montana from 16 to 18 on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed, according to antideath penalty advocates,
is that minorities are being disproportionately targeted.
Two-thirds of the juveniles on death row are either black or
Hispanic, while two-thirds of the victims are white. Both figures
are higher than the adult death row population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real driving factor is the race of the victim,'' said
Streib, the law professor who produces a biannual report on
juvenile offenders on death row. ``White is the so-called valuable
victim syndrome. The end result is the people being executed are
four times to 10 times more likely to be people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors cite opportunism as the more relevant factor.
``It isn't racism,'' said Chuck Rosenthal, an assistant district
attorney in Houston's Harris County. ``It's poor people targeting
and murdering wealthy people.''
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the 581 executions in the United States since 1976
have been in Texas. In the nearly five years that Governor George
W. Bush has been in office, 105 people have been executed here. The
list includes juvenile offenders, the mentally retarded, and
foreign nationals. Texas is the leader in executions of juvenile
offenders, accounting for seven of the 13 juvenile offender
executions that have taken place in the United States since the
death penalty was reinstated in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current status of the state of Texas: 17-year-old
executions is appropriate,'' Bush said last year. The Bush
administration also was responsible for lowering the age that
juveniles can be tried as adults to 14, and increasing the maximum
sentence for juveniles between 14 and 16 to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many opponents of the death penalty feel that no one under 18
should be sentenced to death. ``That is the bright line in our
society. We don't draft or vote or serve on juries under 18,'' said
Dieter.
</P>
<P>
   But victims' families and proponents of the death penalty
disagree. ``Most bleeding hearts haven't had something like this
happen to them,'' said Bill Green, the father of Micheal Eakin, a
25-year-old Texas deputy constable who was shot to death by a
17-year-old last year. ``It's the kind of thing you only read about
in the papers. Where is the line? Did you ever go to your high
school reunion? The kids that were turds when they were 17 are now
older turds. By the time you are 16 or 17, you are pretty well set
for life. If I could volunteer to put that needle in his arm, I
would do it. Absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
