<HEADLINE>
PLAYING TRICKS WITH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where will you be when Year 2000 arrives? Whether it's near or
far, chances are your location won't be as unusual as that of
passengers on the steamer Warrimoo when the year 1900 was about to
be ushered in. Here, from the long-gone publication Ships and the
Sea, is their story.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 30, 1899, the Warrimoo was in the mid-Pacific on its way
from Vancouver to Australia when the first mate told Captain John
D. S. Phillips, ``We're only a few miles from the intersection of
the equator and the international date line!''
</P>
<P>
   Now Phillips had a somewhat prankish personality, so he set out
to achieve the navigation trick of a lifetime. He changed course
and adjusted the ship's speed so that at midnight local time the
Warrimoo was right on the equator at the exact point where it
crosses the date line. That brought these results:
</P>
<P>
   --The front part of the ship was in the Southern Hemisphere and
in the middle of summer. The stern was in the Northern Hemisphere
and the middle of winter.
</P>
<P>
   --The date in the after part of the ship was Dec. 30, 1899.
Forward, it was Jan. 1, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   --The ship was thus in two different days, two different months,
two different seasons, and (as the popular conception has it,
anyway) two different centuries _ all at once.
</P>
<P>
   --Not only were passengers cheated out of a New Year's Eve
celebration, they lost an entire day _ Dec. 31, 1899 _ forever. But
then again, they were undoubtedly the first to greet the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Phillips said, ``I never heard of it happening
before, and I guess it won't happen again until the year 2000!''
But as Robert Norling of Concord, N.H., who forwarded the article
to us, notes, ``What if . . . ships, large and small, have the same
idea, all jousting for position at (latitude/longitude) 0/180?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which is the world's highest city? (Answer at end of
column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Disney Magazine reports that some theme-park employees
are beginning to use ``Disney'' as a verb. ``To `Disney' someone is
to make them happy against their will.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Never let a stranger guard your laptop (at the airport)
while you go for a newspaper or a cup of coffee _ even if the
person looks exactly like your Peoria grandmother'' _ one of 19
tips on protecting your laptop while traveling, offered by veteran
Boston publicist C. Paul Luongo in Travel Smart newsletter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
How's that again? A Norwood resident named Casey found this sign at
a Holiday Inn a tad amazing: ``Our indoor heated pool . . . is open
year round . . . weather permitting.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Punchy: Visitors to Tokyo's fashionable Ginza district may see an
unusual attraction: a human punching bag. A man named Jun Sato has
allowed anyone to punch him up for 1,000 yen ($10) for three
minutes, according to the Mainichi Daily News. (He does wear
protective face and stomach equipment.) Says Sato: ``I enjoy being
used as a punching bag. It's good business and also another way to
experience life.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Oxford, Ohio, forbids a woman to take her
clothes off while standing in front of a man's picture. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lots of company: Some 33.8 million people will be traveling during
the holiday season, the AAA estimates. Nearly 58 percent will stay
at the home of a friend or relative; 32 percent will stay in a
hotel or motel; and the rest will camp, be on a ship, or stay at a
bed-and-breakfast. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: As the standard ``contract of carriage'' printed on
plane tickets notes, airlines are not required to provide lodging
or meals for weather-related delays or cancellations. But it never
hurts to ask. Some airlines will do something sometimes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Lhasa, Tibet, which stands at 12,087 feet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
