<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-VOYAGER-BOS &LR;      11-30 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VOYAGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG RESORT AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Is this a ship or a land-based resort that just happens
to be floating on water?
</P>
<P>
   This is the question cruise passengers will be asking as they
wander about the Voyager of the Seas, the world's largest cruise
ship. It even dwarfs the USS Nimitz, the Navy's largest aircraft
carrier!
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, cruise lines have been racing to build new and
bigger ships. Carnival and Princess cruise lines have each held the
title of world's largest with liners in the 100,000-ton class. But
the Voyager is 30 percent bigger than those ships, so Royal
Caribbean now has the title and should hold it for some time. No
other company, as yet, has announced plans to top this 142,000-ton
liner.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Voyager a resort at sea, and Royal Caribbean officials
will nod in agreement. ``The Voyager was not built to top our
competition,'' Richard Fain, chief executive officer of the line,
said. Instead, it was built to take aim at Las Vegas and other
resorts by luring more land-based vacationers out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Voyager of the Seas, now into its second week of sailings in
the Caribbean, has to be seen to be believed. ``Incredible'' is the
most heard comment of passengers. ``Like no ship before'' is
another comment. And to make sure no one misses the point, Royal
Caribbean has emblazoned ``Like no vacation on Earth'' on the side
of the ship. Sail on it, and you'll more than likely agree _ it is
like no other vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you'll find features other ships offer, but the Voyager
goes beyond other liners in both amenities and technology. What
other ship has a full-sized ice skating rink? Or a four-deck-high
Royal Promenade that meanders down the center of the vessel, with
staterooms overlooking the scene rather than the water? Or a
rock-climbing wall 200 feet above the sea, or an in-line skating
course, or a Johnny Rockets hamburger haven?
</P>
<P>
   Despite its 15-deck size and capacity to carry almost 4,000
passengers, the Voyager of the Seas is an easy vessel to get
around.
</P>
<P>
   Being the biggest ship at sea, it has, well, the largest of
everything, from theater to casino. About the only things
standard-sized are the staterooms. They are comfortable and nicely
furnished but no bigger than staterooms on other Royal Caribbean
ships _ unless one goes for one of the fancier suites. Of the
ship's 1,557 staterooms, 765 have private balconies on the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Voyager has the latest in technical systems. With its
Dynamic Positioning satellite guidance system, the ship can stop
and hold its position without dropping anchor, making the vessel
environmentally friendly around fragile Caribbean reefs. Royal
Caribbean, which has paid a heavy price for its former
environmentally unfriendly deeds, now has one of the strongest
environmental programs at sea
</P>
<P>
   For those who go on a cruise to be on the ocean, the most
negative feature of the ship is that Royal Caribbean is trying too
hard to have the Voyager be a resort with an emphasis on inside
activities, not on the ocean. However, the ship does have lots of
deck space topside and boasts three swimming pools, six whirlpools,
a sports court, a jogging track, an in-line skating track, a
nine-hole miniature golf course, and a sunbathing area. The
rock-climbing wall is aft on the ship's smokestack.
</P>
<P>
   Inside is where the ship truly impresses. The Royal Promenade is
probably the most innovative mall experience you could ask for. Set
between two 11-deck atriums, with the width of three car lanes, are
shops, dining areas, a coffee bar, a sports bar, an old-English
bar, a gaming arcade that not only revolves but has the world's
largest interactive roulette wheel, activated by a four-deck-high
roulette ball tower The promenade is also a mecca for jugglers,
musicians, mimes, and even a parade or two featuring lavish
costumes and a marching band. Another innovation is overhead, where
three decks of staterooms overlook not the ocean but this lively
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Below the Royal Promenade is Casino Royale, not surprisingly the
largest at sea. One entrance has buried treasure underneath the
Plexiglas floor. Down one more deck is the ice-skating rink,
complete with a Zamboni-like machine. Not only will there be
performances by ice skating professionals, but passengers can rent
skates. This afternoon, a TV special filmed last week on the rink
will be seen on NBC television at 4 p.m. The show stars champion
figure skater Katarina Witt, who is also the ship's godmother,
having dedicated the Voyager Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The rink also doubles as Studio B, a fully equipped television
studio that also will be used for game shows.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is very lively at night. La Scala, a 1,350-seat
five-story theater, complete with an orchestra pit and
state-of-the-art technology, offers spectacular, original, and
colorful entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Vault is a two-level disco that requires a handprint to
enter its dark but lively scene. The Schooner Bar has a talented
piano player ready to play your favorites or provide the sounds for
a sing-along. There's also Cleopatra's Needle where you'll find
music for dancing or easy listening. Or head to Deck 14 for the
Viking Crown lounge and some cool jazz sounds. Or try the Royale
Promenade where you can sip champagne or just watch the
entertainers strolling about. Or head to the Connoisseur's Club for
a fine cigar.
</P>
<P>
   As on any cruise ship, no one will go hungry. But on the Voyager
there is dining in fine style. The dining room features three
separately themed areas _ Carmen, La Boheme, and the Magic Flute,
all named for operas _ and covers three decks, with all rooms
connected by a grand staircase. It's not only beautifully designed
but also very quiet; you can talk without shouting at your
neighbor. There is also an alternative Italian restaurnat, and for
casual dining, the Windjammer with indoor and outdoor seating on
Deck 11 is open for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. Even Johnny
Rockets, with its '50s diner appearance, works very nicely on this
ship.
</P>
<P>
   On this ship, no passengers can say they are bored. It has
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Even the children will be amazed at what is offered them. The
3-to-17 set will discover a world all their own, with separate
areas for ages 3-5, 6-8, 9-12, and 13-17. A pool, science program,
slides, teen lounge, and are available. Some party or other
activities do have a charge, but most activities are free.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has a large Internet cafe on Deck 8 along with a
library. Cruisers can send and receive e-mails, check on stocks,
even send picture postcards.
</P>
<P>
   The Voyager is also after business travelers and has not only a
convention center but also a business center with all the services
found in a fine hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And, like a fine land resort, it has a spa that offers all the
relaxing treatments one could ask for, along with a huge gym that
overlooks the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean is so confident of this vessel that it has two
similar ships setting sail in late 2000 and a third in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
