<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-II     11-30 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-EXECUTION-II-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 HUNTSVILLE, Texas: ... I'm driving.  Leo Little, 19
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated only 35 minutes before convicting Little of
capital murder for the kidnapping, robbery, and slaying of Antonio
Christopher Chavez, an accountant and devout Jehovah's Witness, on
Jan. 22, 1998. Little told police he was looking for drug money. In
his confession, he detailed how he hid in the back seat of Chavez's
unlocked car outside a San Antonio restaurant. He forced Chavez at
gunpoint to drive to his apartment and then down a rural road.
Little forced Chavez out of the car and ordered him to kneel before
firing three shots into the back of his head and robbing him of
several hundred dollars in church offerings. Chavez was found 12
hours later in critical condition. He died two days after that.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement Little's attorney, Jeff Scott, told
jurors, ``It would be an insult for us to tell you to do anything
but find Leo Little guilty of this crime.'' Little, testifying in
his own behalf, begged the jury to sentence him to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You are in here for capital murder. Are you guilty?
</P>
<P>
   Little: Yeah, I did it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What led up to the murder?
</P>
<P>
   Little: I was drunk. I was a real druggie out there. I told them
I killed him. I confessed all the way. I asked for pity and
everything and they just acted the other way. I killed a Jehovah's
Witness. He was real religious and that's about it. I was drunk and
I didn't use good judgment. I didn't need to kill the guy. I just
pulled the trigger and it happened in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you get executed are you going to make a final statement?
</P>
<P>
   Little: I've been thinking about that a lot lately. Debating
what to say. It may sound stupid but I may sing a song. I don't
know the name of it. It's a country song about choices. Choices I
made. It's between that and apologizing again to the family
members.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you pass the time?
</P>
<P>
   Little: I sleep all the time and put on weight. That metal roof
gets real hot. I went two months without a fan. It's tough.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you worried about being executed soon?
</P>
<P>
   Little: They're rushing executions. Some older guys have been
here 15, 20 years. I hear they're speeding things up for them to
get executed five years after you get here. I just told my defense
lawyers, `Just get me the death sentence.' I was on a little
suicide mission. I felt like the state killed me already, I was so
depressed. I'm still a kid when I get here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think about in here?
</P>
<P>
   Little: Always thinking about my past. Constantly. The break in
the road, where I went off the path. I should've stayed in school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe in an eye for an eye?
</P>
<P>
   Little: I don't think it's fair to execute anybody. But then
again, if it happened to my family, I would have real hatred
towards the person and would kind of want the state to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible to get rehabilitated on death row?
</P>
<P>
   Little: I was rehabilitated the moment I went into county jail.
I'm not supposed to take a life. I got depressed straight. Help me,
I'm not much of a speaker. I'd cry in front of you if I could.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lopez, 18
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was convicted of the Sept. 29, 1998, killing of Micheal
Eakin, 25, a Harris County deputy constable.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez and five others were in a car stopped by Eakin for
speeding. The 5-foot-3-inch, 120-pound Lopez, who was high on paint
thinner and afraid of going to jail for parole violations, ran.
Eakin caught him and was about to handcuff him when Lopez pulled a
gun and fired over his shoulder, wounding Eakin in the head. Before
fleeing, he fired again, hitting Eakin in the throat. Lopez was
captured the next day. He gave police a videotaped confession at
the scene then changed his story several times. At his trial, Lopez
pleaded not guilty to murder. On the advice of his attorneys, he
didn't testify, but in a rambling courtroom outburst he lashed out
against his lawyers. He also said the shooting was accidental.
``Only me and only God and only Jesus know what happened,'' Lopez
said. ``I didn't mean to kill him. I didn't shoot to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I didn't do it. I mean, I don't want to talk about it.
I'll talk about anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think it's fair for a 17-year-old to be given the
death sentence?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: All that stuff ain't fair. You get people that kill lots
of people and they get out of death row, like Charles Manson. He
killed a lot of people. I had a bad attorney. He didn't want to
help me. I think 17 is too immature. They charge you as an adult
but you can't do all the adult things. You can't buy beer, you
can't even buy cigarettes. You can't do a lot of things. You're not
even mature enough to buy condoms and all that stuff, but you're
mature enough to get the death sentence and go through all of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think you can be rehabilitated?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: Yeah, I believe in God. I just believe in the Lord, know
what I'm saying? You learn a lesson. I'm already rehabilitated. I
got the Lord on my side.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have dreams?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: Bad dreams. I'm running through the fields and the cops
are chasing me. . .then I wake up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are you going to be thinking when they strap you down on
that table?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I'll be thinking about my girl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have anything against cops?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I don't like the ones that are racial, the other ones I
don't have nothing against. They're good people too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the family of the cop you killed? What would you
say if they were right here?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I felt real bad. Whatever anything I say, I don't think
it's gonna matter. I mean, I feel real bad for them, everything
that happened, but there ain't nothing I can do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you scared?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I'm afraid, do you know what I'm saying?
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been convicted of killing a cop. You're not going to
get a lot of sympathy from people about being with your girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I don't really care what people say or what they think. I
just know what I know and what I want. I know I'm no threat to the
future. I know I'm safe to be out on the streets. I've completely
changed. A situation like this will change a man completely.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think a 17-year-old is too young to die?
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: I am a kid. I never shaved before I got in here and they
gave me a razor. You from Massachusetts? Where's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: New England.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez: New England? That's another country. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gary Graham, 38 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a.k.a. Shaka Sankofa, was convicted and sentenced to
death in the May 1981 robbery and fatal shooting of Bobby Grant
Lambert outside a Houston supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   A witness testified that Lambert was leaving the supermarket
when Graham reached into his pockets and then shot Lambert as they
scuffled. Lambert, robbed of the change he had from a $100 bill,
staggered back into the store and died.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a grandfather who has spent more time in jail than he
has been free, is the oldest juvenile defender on death row. Graham
pleaded guilty to 10 other aggravated robberies _ including two
shootings _ during a weeklong crime spree following Lambert's
murder. But he pleaded not guilty to the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham case sparked international attention with celebrity
support from Danny Glover, Spike Lee, Harry Belafonte, and Kenny
Rogers. Graham was convicted on the testimony of one eyewitness.
Later eyewitnesses surfaced who claimed the killer was shorter than
Graham. The prosecution contended the witnesses were not credible,
but no murder weapon or matching fingerprints were found linking
Graham to the killing. He has steadfastly denied he killed Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been quoted as saying you're going to fight like hell
on the way to the execution chamber. Is that still true?
</P>
<P>
   Graham: Absolutely. In the final process, the only way to
maintain dignity is to fight. It's a normal human process.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's it like spending more time in jail than as a free man?
</P>
<P>
   Graham: It's a very horrendous ordeal. It's been a long time.
But the only thing I can do is what I have done _ try to make the
most of a bad situation, and to speak out about the death penalty
process.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were you like at 17? Did you consider yourself a
juvenile or a man?
</P>
<P>
   Graham: I was a young kid. I think it's a development process.
You have to become a man and stand up and fight for what you
believe in. You have to fight or else you die.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What message do you have for the 17-year-olds on death row?
</P>
<P>
   Graham: It depends on the kid, his circumstances. The most
powerful message is to speak out against what's happening here.
This killing process in Texas. I think the
</P>
<P>
   hardest part is seeing the senseless process of men being
executed. Seeing that continue to rise. Resist. Change the system
for those that come behind us. Death row is not just for the dead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
