<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, November 30, 1999   Editors  
    The Hearst News Service will file the following for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-TRACING (Washington) _ Federal law officials unveil a new
gun-tracing software program aimed at letting state and local
police find the source of guns used in crimes more quickly so that
traffickers can be identified and arrested. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-PREVENTION (Washington) _ Although the federal government
scores high for bankrolling AIDS research, it rates poorly in
funding prevention programs and helping poor nations battle the
deadly disease, the advocacy group AIDS Action reports. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-VIEQUES (Washington) _ With a White House go-ahead
expected, a Navy-Marine Corps battle group sets sail beginning
Friday for final combat training, including limited practice on the
Puerto Rican island of Vieques. The armada will return to various
ports for the Christmas holidays before leaving Feb. 18 for a
six-month deployment in the Persian Gulf. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOW-CORNING-BANKRUPCTY (Bay City, Mich.,) _ A federal judge
approves Dow Corning Corp's $4.5 billion plan to emerge from
bankruptcy. The plan allocates $3.2 billion to settle claims made
by women with breast implants. Dow Corning, once the world's
largest manufacturer of silicone breast implants, filed for
bankruptcy in May 1995. By CHERYL WADE and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ If you think the undefined role of
first lady is awkward, consider Tipper Gore's pickle as second
lady. She's got prestige but no power, and she is not supposed to
upstage the president, the first lady or her husband, the vice
president. That doesn't leave much room to be useful, but she is
trying with crusades for the homeless and the mentally ill. And
she's out campaigning to become first lady herself. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
