<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-NEW-THING-BOS &LR;      11-30 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NEW-THING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING SAIL ON THE WATERS OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE NEW NEW THING 
A Silicon Valley Story 
By Michael Lewis. Norton. 268 pp. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all its prodigious research, a vital fact is missing from
Michael Lewis's remarkable new book, ``The New New Thing: A Silicon
Valley Story.'' He nowhere reveals the name of the wealthy fellow
who hired a Dutch boat builder named Wolter Huisman to build a
remarkable yacht called Juliet, and thereby changed the course of
economic history.
</P>
<P>
   This Juliet, completed in 1993, was easily among the most lavish
sailing vessels ever built. Its anonymous owner was a friend of a
brilliant, erratic, passionate computer scientist named Jim Clark,
who took one look at the boat and decided he had to have something
even grander _ a giant sailboat entirely run by computer. It would
be a boat so advanced that Clark would be able to sit at his office
desk and sail it by pressing buttons on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Only trouble was how to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Clark raised the money by persuading the backers of his new
business venture to sell a large piece of their firm on the stock
exchange. Netscape Communications Corp. made software for the
Internet, a communications medium then used by a mere handful of
people. Netscape gave away its products and had never earned a
dime. But against the better judgment of his colleagues, Clark had
his way. And so in 1995, Netscape went public _ and had the biggest
new stock offering the world had seen up to that time.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet boom that has transformed the US economy began that
day, as stunned venture capitalists and entrepreneurs spent
billions in hopes of repeating Netscape's astounding coup. That day
also began the establishment of the Internet as a mass
communications medium, today used by 70 million Americans. And that
day may also have begun the downward slide of giant Microsoft
Corp., which now faces the threat of a government-sponsored
dismantling _ payback for the company's allegedly illegal efforts
to crush the Netscape challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But what of that? What really matters is that Jim Clark could
now afford to build a boat bigger than the Juliet.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of Lewis's irreverence that he places the greed
and arrogance of one man at the center of the most significant
business story since the days of Henry Ford. Yet Lewis also
captures Clark's childlike curiosity, his heroic daring, the
ferocious diligence of a dirt-poor high school dropout turned
microchip designer and entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape was the second great company Clark had founded. In the
1980s, he created Silicon Graphics, once the world leader in
three-dimensional computer graphics. Enraged that the lion's share
of the wealth went to the guys in suits instead of the engineers,
he founded Netscape as payback. And once he became convinced that
Microsoft would inevitably overwhelm Netscape, he headed off to
found yet another stock market sensation, the medical software
company Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis leaves no doubt that avarice drives Clark like a cattle
prod; now a billionaire with the yacht of his dreams, he cannot
bear the thought that database software magnate Larry Ellison is
still richer than he is and vows to retire once he has pulled even.
But Clark's also the guy who works himself to exhaustion designing
software to control his boat, just because it has never been done.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's former life as a Wall Street investment banker taught
him the ways of the wealthy; somewhere along the way he has picked
up a great deal of knowledge about computers and the Internet as
well. Perhaps the most impressive aspect of this book is that the
casual reader, with little knowledge of the industry, will scarcely
notice how well informed this book is. There are no chapter-long
ramblings through the underbrush of bytes and bandwidth; on most
pages, the only digits you will see are a page number, or perhaps
an important date. The whole thing is well under 300 pages and will
take you an evening or two to read.
</P>
<P>
   And yet all the vital information is here _ a capsule history of
an economic drama like few others. Those of us who write about this
stuff for a living know how difficult it is to sound even vaguely
coherent; Lewis's prose achieves a novelistic elegance. He has
written a book to go on the shelf alongside Tracy Kidder's 1980
classic about the computer business, ``The Soul of a New Machine.''
And as with Kidder's book, it succeeds because it ultimately is not
about technology at all, but about a flawed, fascinating man who
designs yachts and entire industries to suit himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray, a Globe business columnist, writes about the world
of computers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
