<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CANNON-BALL30-COX     11-30 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNON-BALL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tree near Civil War battle site drops a heavy reminder of
conflict
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAFFIN'S BLUFF, Va. _ More than 130 years after Appomattox,
Karen Storer came within a second or two of becoming another
casualty of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this noise _ `chachoo, chachoo' _ looked up and a big
old branch was coming down, and then a cannon ball,'' says Storer,
47. ``It might've hit me on the head, but I was washing my car, and
had just moved.''
</P>
<P>
   When it went kaplunk, she instantly knew what it was, ``because
there's a trench right behind my house,'' 10 miles south of
Richmond, where a major Civil War battle took place in the fall of
1864.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many unsung battles near Richmond before Lee's
surrender at Appomattox a few months later, so the Battle of
Chaffin's Bluff doesn't take up much space in history books.
</P>
<P>
   To historians, though, it's famous because 14 of 18 Medals of
Honor awarded to African-American soldiers in the War Between the
States were for acts of heroism while fighting well-entrenched
Rebels right around here, overlooking the mighty James River.
</P>
<P>
   The 25th Battalion Virginia Infantry, also known as the Richmond
City Battalion, was stationed at Chaffin's Bluff for most of the
war, and a hospital was located nearby. It's likely many artifacts
found by current residents Jimmy Dean and his wife Donna belonged
to men in that unit.
</P>
<P>
   Storer doesn't know why the 6-pound cannonball fell, but many of
the trees near her cottage are ancient.
</P>
<P>
   A full-time gardener for Dean, known in Virginia as the
``sausage baron,'' Storer told her employer about the incident. He
called police to make sure the ball, probably fired by attacking
Yankees, wouldn't blow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a story 'round here of a guy trying to beat the rust
off of one and it exploded and killed him,'' says Dean, most famous
as the singer of the superhit ``Big Bad John'' in 1961. ``It had
powder in it.''
</P>
<P>
   This one didn't, and it's now on the mantle in Dean's mansion
nearby, near dozens of other Civil War relics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Lord, we've found knives, forks, horseshoes, belt buckles,
bullets by the blue jillion,'' Dean says. ``But the idea that the
cannon ball could've been tucked in that big tree for 130 some
years, it's wonderful. It makes it all come alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Storer's just grateful she's not dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close call,'' she laughs. ``And I'm a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
