<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR-TRADE COFFEE BREWS RICHER CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Maybe you haven't heard about fair-trade coffee yet. I know
most of you sit around sipping your latte and never think about
where the stuff comes from, or what goes on behind the scenes to
bring it to you. You never think of the sweat and the danger we
face getting the beans from the mountainsides of Nicaragua to your
smiley-face coffee cup in Wherever.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let me tell you, right now there is a movement afoot in
the United States to disrupt the time-honored traditions of the
great coffee-growing regions of the world. The fair-trade coffee
campaign recently has washed onto America's shores from Europe,
where for the past 11 years it has whipped up consumer hysteria in
favor of a ludicrous set of ethical standards for the business of
farming and selling coffee beans. This movement is just like those
other wild-eyed campaigns that have forced unreasonable principles
on tuna fishermen and sweatshop operators.
</P>
<P>
   The fair-trade movement allows poor coffee farmers to sell their
beans directly to roasters and retailers. In America, it has taken
off in the San Francisco area. The group behind it, TransFair USA,
plans to expand soon to Seattle and then to Boston and Washington,
D.C. next year. The organization sweet-talks US roasters, shops and
grocery chains into promising to buy only coffee that carries the
fair-trade stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   It all smells like the rich aroma of early morning, doesn't it?
Well, guess who loses? I do _ big, bad Coyote. That's what they
call me in the mountains of Nicaragua. All this fair-trade stuff
cuts me right out of the picture. I'm the middleman. I'm the guy
who buys the coffee from the farmers and sells it to the next
person down the line.
</P>
<P>
   I pay a fine figure of 40 cents a pound. Now that I'm out of the
picture, the farmer is selling direct to his buyers at $1.26 a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous! What does a poor farmer need that kind of money for?
Sure, I know all about the fellow who buys a new mule and some farm
equipment, and eats a little better than he used to, maybe even
sends his kids to school. Is all of this really necessary? Coffee
farmers are used to suffering. Why upset things?
</P>
<P>
   Listen up: Coyote needs his cut. And he'll do whatever it takes
to get it. There was that mishap in Chiapas, Mexico, where a guy
was shot to death for trying to organize local farmers into a
fair-trade group. The simple fact is we middlemen are essential.
Coffee farmers need me just as much as stock market investors need
brokers. For a teeny price, we provide a gigantic service. Mark my
words _ neither of us will ever vanish. I reserve the right to beat
and kick and kill to preserve an honored way of life.
</P>
<P>
   So now you've heard the truth. It's up to you, the consumer. Go
ahead and look for the fair-trade label on your coffee. Have a
nice, peaceful cup. But ask yourself, do you really want to lift up
the poor, miserable coffee farmer at my expense? Think about it.
His life, after all, doesn't amount to a hill of beans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1412EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-SCHAMA-2TAKES-     11-30 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SCHAMA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY IN BRILLIANT BRUSHSTROKES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the decade Simon Schama spent working on ``Rembrandt's
Eyes,'' his massive new book about the Dutch painter, he hit upon a
novel form of research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deliberately did not want to use the professional lingo,''
Schama (pronounced SHAH-muh) says over lunch at the Boston Museum
of Fine Arts. ``I did want to use verbs that came from walking
around or cooking or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``So going around with my little notebooks and sitting in front
of every Rembrandt, I would actually make word lists in this crazy
way. I wanted to try and develop a way of describing paint which
was actually about the physical properties as they appear if you
were to do the thing which you must never do, rub your hands over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rembrandt's Eyes,'' as in his six other books, Schama, 54,
has striven to make the past a hands-on presence in the lives of
his readers. ``Making it immediate,'' he says of history, ``that's
the attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he has become one of the most celebrated
historians of his generation. He's also drawn the occasional
disdain of specialists and been accused of sloppiness and
superficiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's somebody I have a huge admiration for,'' says Oxford
University historian Niall Ferguson, who sees Schama's career as
``an encouragement not to be too abstruse in one's work and (to)
try to reach that general readership.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Israel, professor of Dutch history at University
College London, agrees with Ferguson about Schama's ability to
reach a popular audience _ but little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my opinion that he is particularly good as a
historian,'' Israel says. Although Schama ``is very important as a
writer and popularizer of both historical and art-historical
knowledge, I don't consider him an important scholar in either
field.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an age-old story, the battle between popularizing
generalists and academic specialists, but Schama adds a twist. His
academic credentials are impeccable (educated at Cambridge,
teaching posts there and at Oxford, Harvard, and now Columbia). His
field of expertise, early-modern Dutch history, is far from the
Anglo-American mainstream. Yet this hasn't kept Schama from
offending what he terms ``the appropriateness cops.'' He has
actively reached out to a broader audience and essayed such
anomalous roles for an academic historian as BBC documentary
presenter and art critic for The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very sui generis. There's no one like Simon,'' says Sir
J. H. Plumb, who taught him at Cambridge. ``He was born to be a
star.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schama looks like Gene Hackman and writes a pyrotechnic
prose worthy of a Fourth of July sky. ``Obviously, I'm drawn to
it,'' Schama says when asked about intellectual showmanship, and
his writing is as much performance as communication. No one puts
quite the torque on a fact that he does _ let alone comes up with
such astonishing oddities of historical data. The overall effect
can be breathtaking in its bravura.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this description of a 1629 Rembrandt self-portrait:
``The light reveals a full, mobile mouth, the lips highlit as if
nervously licked; large, liquid eyes; a great acreage of cheek and
chin; and, planted in the center of his face, the least aquiline
nose in seventeenth-century painting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' says Israel, ``what is truly
exceptional about his work is its rhetorical skill. . . . In that
respect, he's unrivaled. Of course, there's always a temptation
then to move away from what is intellectually cogent to what is
(merely) evocative.''
</P>
<P>
   Even its detractors concede that the new book is a tour de
force. But even some of its admirers wonder where the tour
ultimately leads. ``Rembrandt's Eyes'' is classic Schama. It opens
with a cannon salvo and ends with the birth of a baby in Indonesia.
What comes in between isn't quite a biography, nor is it a social
history, nor is it a work of art criticism _ though it comprises
elements of all three and much else besides.
</P>
<P>
   What the book has in abundance is an appreciation for ``the
eloquence of peculiarity.'' That phrase comes from the Rembrandt
book's immediate predecessor, ``Landscape and Memory'' (1995), and
describes the ruling intellectual passion of the art historian Aby
Warburg. Schama's own fondness for the concept is hard to miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's certainly true,'' he says. ``I'm drawn to the
uproarious, the teeming canvas: a sense of history as theatrum
mundi, the sort of aliveness you find in a Hogarth print.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for a further example, Schama turns to literature. ``I
love that incredible detail right at the very end of (Giuseppe
Lampedusa's novel) `The Leopard,' where Concetta and her sister are
throwing out all the old rubbish and they throw out the prince's
dog, which has become a rug, literally at the master's feet, and
they chuck it as an old, mangy, moth-eaten, piece of crap. And
Lampedusa describes it in flight, in midair, as for a moment
resembling the dog alive, jumping up, actually, or in space. And I
thought, oh God, you know, that's it. History is the illusion of
something very dead being brought instantaneously alive: the dead
dog in flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Schama in flight is, if anything, even more playful and
irreverent than on the page. ``He's always been almost excessively
ebullient,'' Plumb says with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   A man of headlong enthusiasms and effervescent talk, Schama
speaks in jitterbugging italics. Emphases and escalating
superlatives punctuate his speech the way ums and throat-clearings
do most people's. ``This is brilliant,'' he announces in a
characteristic progression. ``This is so good, so funny. It's just
absolutely divine.'' He's talking about a menu.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly everything is grist for Schama's conversational mill:
Viking graffiti in Scotland, the Venerable Bede's world view,
admission rates at Columbia, the perils equine flatulence pose to
equestrians. He's the senior-common-room equivalent of a great jazz
soloist, his riffs pure Oxbridge bebop.
</P>
<P>
   What's so impressive about Schama's talk is his ability to
improvise on his own improvisations. He'll start out talking about
one thing, immediately shift to another, and then (after a lengthy
aside about something altogether different) manage somehow to get
back to where he started, hardly missing a beat, and with room to
spare for the inevitable ``colossal,'' ``stupendous,'' and/or
``catastrophic.'' It comes as no surprise when he mentions that one
of his favorite books is ``Tristram Shandy,'' that 18th-century
monument to the delectability of digression.
</P>
<P>
   A descendant of Eastern European Jews, Schama grew up in
northern London and remembers seeing his first Rembrandt, a
self-portrait, at Kenwood House on Hampstead Heath. ``There was
something staggeringly, intimidatingly mysterious about it,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
