   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Dec. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MASSGRAVES (Ciudad Juarez) _ Developments in search for
bodies on two ranches. The Mexican attorney general says there
might be 100 bodies, including 22 Americans. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SPY (Moscow) _ Russia arrests a U.S. Embassy employee on
spy charges. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Washington) _ More on the health of President
Boris Yeltsin. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-TALKS (Seattle) _ Developments: A big labor protest is
scheduled for today at the World Trade Organization meeting. By
Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Former Chancellor Helmut
Kohl admitted Tuesday that he had used a system of secret accounts
to receive donations to his Christian Democrats but rejected
charges he had been bribed during his 16 years in office. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-ELECT (Kuala Lumpur) _ An election folo: ``We have
achieved whatever we have achieved according to the Sinatra
principle,'' Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said shortly before
winning a new five-year term on Monday. ``We have done it our own
way.'' By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PLAYBOY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears arguments
in a First Amendment case involving obscenity, scrambling, and
cable television. The Playboy Entertainment Group wants to be able
to show its material without fully scrambling it all day long; the
government wants to restore a law that restricts such programs to
the hours between 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-GENES-FOOD (Washington) _ The FDA has a second meeting to
hear views on how it should regulate genetically modified foods.
The first was in Chicago. This Washington meeting is expected to
attract many of the most vocal advocacy groups. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BRADY (San Francisco) _ President Clinton, at a Stop the
Violence benefit, touts the successes of the Brady bill gun sales
restrictions, on the sixth anniversary of their implementation. By
Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-DEATHS (Undated) _ A news analysis: Why, after so many
years of public attention to medical malpractice, the National
Academy of Sciences wants to crack down now by creating a federal
agency to protect patients. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-EXPELL-EDUC (Chicago) _ Beyond an intolerance for
weapons and drugs, a new ethos on conduct in American education has
profoundly changed views on what is normal, if annoying, behavior
by adolescents. No longer is the playground scrap or the kickball
tussle deemed a rite of passage, best to be settled by a stern
teacher who orders the pugilists to their corners, hears out the
warring sides, and then demands apologies and a handshake. Known
most often as the ``zero tolerance'' code, aggression is viewed as
violence, and teachers are instructed to file a report with the
school authorities, so that a uniform policy can run its course,
and no offending student escapes punishment. While proponents of
the stringent policies say uniform rules are necessary to insure
safe schools, some educators and psychologists have raised concerns
that common sense has sometimes been a casualty in a crusade for
safety and non-violent behavior. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-HOMELESS (New York) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton talked
like a Senate candidate on Tuesday, blasting the city's policy of
arresting the homeless. Without mentioning her opponent's name at a
breakfast with ministers in New York, she called the policy
inhumane. By Jonathan P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-AIRBUS (Undated) _ Ever since Frontier Airlines started
in 1993, it has flown airplanes made by Boeing. But last month,
Frontier decided to swap its entire fleet of20 737's for jets made
by Airbus Industrie, the European consortium that is Boeing's sole
rival. After training its pilots and mechanics to fly and maintain
its new Airbus planes, it is unlikely that Frontier will buy
another Boeing jet for at least a generation. Boeing is losing many
orders like Frontier's. So far this year, Airbus has outsold Boeing
by more than 2 to 1. The lopsided orders have prompted many in the
aviation industry and on Wall Street to consider what would have
been unthinkable a decade ago: Boeing is in danger of slipping
behind Airbus. And such a decline would echo far beyond Boeing's
Seattle headquarters. The company is the nation's single-largest
exporter, and a weakened Boeing could revive trade tensions between
the European Union and Washington. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission is
expected to approve Exxon's acquisition of Mobil. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are down in mid-afternoon. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 57 points, the S&AMP;P down 4 and the
Nasdaq composite down 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MEDIATE (Chicago) _ Developments at an introductory
one-day session between Microsoft and Justice Department
negotiators takes place under the mediation of Judge Posner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MALONE-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ For five years, Thomas W. Malone,
a professor of information systems at the Sloan School of
Management at MIT and an alumnus of Xerox's Palo Alto Research
Center, has helped lead an effort to think about what shape the
company and the workplace will take in the new century. In his
view, the century will bring a new golden age for small enterprise
and a new springtime for individual creativity in business. By Fred
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
