Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-SUIT _ John and Patsy Ramsey today sued the supermarket
tabloid The Star on behalf of their 12-year-old son, Burke,
charging that he was libeled by stories accusing him of killing his
sister, JonBenet. The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in
Atlanta, seeks $25 million in actual and punitive damages. It said
the stories, published May 25 and June 1, were false and
defamatory, subjecting Burke Ramsey to ``public hatred, contempt
and ridicule.'' (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CANNON-BALL _ CHAFFIN'S BLUFF, Va. _ More than 130 years after
Appomattox, Karen Storer came within a second or two of becoming
another casualty of the Civil War. ``I heard this noise _
`chachoo,chachoo' _ looked up and a big old branch was coming down,
and then a cannon ball,'', says Storer, 47. There's a trench right
behind her house, 10 miles south of Richmond, where a major Civil
War battle took place in the fall of 1864. It was one of many
insung battles near Richmond before Lee's surrender at Apomattox a
few months later, so the Battle of Chaffin's Bluff doesn't take up
much space in history books. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MATH-TEACHING _ WASHINGTON _ Witnesses testify before a national
commission chaired by ex-astronaut John Glenn on how to increase
the quality of math and science teaching. Two days of hearings end
at 4:30 p.m. Tuesday. (Mollison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
