<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HURRICANE01-COX     11-30 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANOTHER HEAVY HURRICANE YEAR EXPECTED TO FOLLOW THIS ONE
 &HT;    CHART BELOW
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This year's hurricane season, which officially
ended Tuesday, was busier than usual, said James Baker,
administrator for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, and similar activity is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the hurricane season began June 1, there were 12 tropical
storms, eight of which became hurricanes, including and five major
hurricanes _ Category 3 and higher. A Category 3 storm has winds of
at least 111 miles per hour. This year's hurricanes claimed 76
lives, and cost about $4.3 billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, also an active hurricane season, there were 14
tropical storms, 10 of which became hurricanes, including three
major hurricanes costing $7.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd, which posed a serious threat to Florida and the
Carolinas in September with winds up to 155 mph, killed 57 people
and was the deadliest storm since Hurricane Agnes killed 122 people
in 1972. Floyd ranked as the 20th deadliest U.S. hurricane in the
century.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Hurricane Irene battered Cuba and the Florida Keys
with winds of 110 mph and caused the indirect deaths of eight
people. Irene dumped torrential rains of up to 20 inches on Dade
and Broward counties, causing urban flooding and $800 million in
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricanes Floyd and Irene are cruel reminders that hurricanes
can produce tragic loss of life and devastating economic
disruption,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The best predictor of hurricanes is the impact of El Nino and La
Nina. El Nino is a disruption of ocean atmosphere systems in the
Pacific Ocean resulting in warmer waters in the Pacific Ocean,
while La Nina produces colder waters in the Pacific Ocean. As the
colder waters of the Pacific Ocean shift, a change in the
atmospheric winds occurs that generates the formation of hurricanes
in the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The annual average of hurricanes has increased over the past
five years, said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane
Center. While officials have been largely successful in predicting
hurricane tracks, they still lack the tools to forecast rapid
changes in a hurricane's intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Inland flooding remains the leading cause of hurricane deaths
and damages. Jarrell said better education about hurricane flooding
and reviews of evacuation routes is needed to reduce future
hurricane devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes of 1999 (provided by NOAA)
</P>
<P>
   Name Date Wind Speed Damage Deaths in millions
</P>
<P>
   Bret Aug. 18-25 140 mph (Category 4) $60 none
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Aug. 19-31 140 mph (Category 4) none none
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Aug 25-Sept.5 105 mph (Category 2) $157 4
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Sept. 7-17 155 mph (Category 4) $3,000-$6,000 57
</P>
<P>
   Gert Sept. 11-23 150 mph (Category 4) none none
</P>
<P>
   Irene Oct. 13-19 110 mph (Category 2) $800 8 indirect
</P>
<P>
   Jose Oct. 17-25 100 mph (Category 2) none 2
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Nov. 13-22 150 mph (Category 4) $330 13
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
