<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-1201-C     11-30 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-1201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM KOSOVO: LISTENING TO THE SWEET SOUND OF FREEDOM
 &HT;    With photo mug of Roughton.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ One recent night, a friend and I popped
into a new basement nightclub here called Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
   It is the rage. This is obvious because it is filled with smoke,
loud music and young fashionable people dressed predictably in
black. Each night at around 11 Zanzibar fills with pretty men and
women equipped with an apparently endless supply of German marks.
In a subtle form of rebellion, people in Pristina don't use dinars
_ the official Yugoslavian currency _ even though Kosovo province
remains part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Each night is a celebration, a victory party. It has been nearly
five months since NATO's bombers drove Serb forces out of Kosovo.
Pristina is Kosovo's biggest city and nominal capital. It is filled
with ecstasy _ a hint of what it must have been like in Paris after
the liberation near the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It was jazz night at the Zanzibar, which is owned by a ranking
member of the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA _ a
terrorist gang in the view of Yugoslav government leaders in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   We sit at a small table surrounded by Albanian kids in their
20s. As the trio _ bass guitar, drums and saxophone _ crank up, I
notice something familiar about the sax player. He's a tall, thin
man in his late 20s or early 30s. At the moment he is transported
from this bar on soaring notes of music both sweet and agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I remember him. Last March, a few days after NATO war
planes began bombing, I travelled to the remote mountain border
crossing between Kosovo and neighboring Albania. It was near a town
called Kukes on the Albanian side. We had heard that thousands of
refugees were moving toward the Albanian border. It was the
beginning of the huge exodus that played each night on televisions
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Early one morning after I arrived, the flood began to choke the
border crossing. I had stationed myself on the bridge between
Albania and Kosovo to speak to refugees as they came over. In the
crowd, was this guy wearing a black leather jacket and sunglasses.
He was hip. His English was stunning. He said he was from Pristina,
and said he had been forced to leave his home by armed Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The memory is clear as I watch the same guy playing at Zanzibar.
Small world. The sound of the sax is rich and flowing. The notes
hang in the smoky air. He is in a league far above the bass player
and drummer. They are playing at the music _ he feels. Few art
forms allow you to express the sensation of freedom better than
jazz. The music isn't held back by written notes. The player goes
by instinct, and he takes us with him.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds are American, even though the sax player had never
been to the United States. He is a Muslim from Eastern Europe, a
tremendous cultural distance from the basements of Chicago, New
Orleans and Memphis where jazz was born. Yet, he is playing music
from my country as I could only dream of playing it.
</P>
<P>
   That day last spring on the bridge, I was touched by what was
happening to these people. The sax player had two brothers in the
KLA. He has confronted death, forced eviction from his homeland and
a million things I can only imagine. Yet, he could be someone on
any street in America.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in the music, I see Visar, the KLA guy who owns
Zanzibar, working the sound system in the back of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds great,'' I tell him.
</P>
<P>
   Visar smiles at me. During the NATO campaign, we used to have a
beer in the Rogner Hotel in Tirana, Albania. We would watch CNN and
talk about the Albanians' war on the Serbs. I never admitted this
to Visar, but I was never convinced that the United States and its
allies were right to pick a side in this ancient feud. The vicious
assaults on Serbs by Albanians since the
</P>
<P>
   refugees came home only make me more dubious. It's a little sad
that there aren't any Serbs at Zanzibar to hear the music.
</P>
<P>
   But the night is full of jazz, and for the moment it seems like
something worth fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Visar says. ``It sounds like freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
