<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      11-30 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK TRIP TO TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shish Kebab is a quintessential Turkish dish, but this twist on
the classic combination of lamb and peppers takes a great idea and
makes it easier. First of all, this dish can be made indoors,
although in good weather the initial browning could certainly be
done on a grill. Second, it makes its own sauce, a combination of
yogurt and the juices exuded by the meat and roasted vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The process could not be more straightforward: You first quickly
sear large chunks of lamb. Then, you roast peppers _ a combination
of sweet and hot is ideal but not essential _ along with an onion.
Those few ingredients are all combined with yogurt, then browned
under the broiler. It's a one-dish meal with only three steps.
</P>
<P>
   For the lamb, you can use either leg or shoulder. Meat from the
leg is leaner and best kept on the rare side; shoulder meat, which
has more fat, can be cooked a little longer without drying out,
which means it can be left under the broiler for a few extra
minutes to give it an extra-crisp crust.
</P>
<P>
   As for the peppers, any assortment of sweet bell peppers is
fine, red or yellow. One or two mildly hot peppers, like Anaheim
chilies, make the dish more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The technique is not difficult, although searing the lamb
produces prodigious amounts of smoke. It takes only a couple of
minutes, though, so just turn on an exhaust fan and temporarily
disconnect the smoke detector. The smoke produced by the peppers as
they are seared is pleasantly fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   I have kept this dish as simple as possible, but there are a few
other ingredients that can improve it, if marginally. You can add a
couple of skinned tomatoes; just sear them with or after the
peppers. This takes only a minute or two and adds another level of
flavor to the final sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Another addition might be a teaspoon or so of thyme leaves along
with the yogurt. A sprinkling of fresh lemon juice or chopped mint
after cooking will also heighten the flavors. And finally, this
dish is best served with either rice or good pita bread, but lots
of either.
</P>
<P>
   LAMB WITH PEPPERS AND YOGURT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boneless lamb, cut into 2-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   3 bell peppers, red, yellow or a combination
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 chilies, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, peeled and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups plain yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   1. Turn heat to high under a cast-iron or other heavy, large
skillet. A couple of minutes later, add lamb and quickly sear on
all sides. Don't worry about cooking it through, but brown the
exterior well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove lamb and put peppers and chilies in skillet, still
over high heat. Add onion halves, cut sides down. Cook until
peppers blacken on all sides, turning as necessary (the onion will
blacken quickly; remove it and set aside). When the peppers are
beginning to collapse, after 10 to 15 minutes, remove skillet from
heat and cover with foil or a lid. Preheat broiler, and adjust rack
so it is as close to the heat source as possible.
</P>
<P>
   3. When peppers cool slightly, peel and seed them, then cut or
tear them into strips. Separate the onion into rings. Combine with
lamb, salt, pepper and yogurt in a roasting pan just large enough
to hold meat in one layer. Broil until charred on top, just a few
minutes, then serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
