<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      11-30 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISPY SEARED STRIPED BASS 
</HEADLINE>
   This is the fourth of eight columns by Patrick O'Connell, the chef
and an owner of the Inn at Little Washington in Washington, Va.
They are written with Marian Burros.  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans are sometimes reluctant to eat fish with the skin on.
But cooking a fish fillet with the skin attached has some distinct
advantages. The skin helps keep the flesh moist, reduces shrinkage
and provides a tantalizing textural contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Weighting the fish fillet while cooking it skin side down
results in a skin as crispy as Peking duck. It takes a little
practice adjusting the heat of the pan and using just the right
amount of oil to achieve the perfect results, but mastering this
technique is well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   This dish has definite Asian overtones but uses a classic French
sauce-making method. Sugar is melted and caramelized over heat,
then vinegar is added and reduced, followed by chicken stock. This
reduced caramel-vinegar syrup is called a gastrique and was often
used in dishes pairing fruit and game, like duck a l'orange or
rabbit with prunes, to create a depth of flavor and sweet-and-sour
notes.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is simple yet dazzling. The fillet is leaned up
against the braised bok choy bulb, and the honey-colored sauce is
dribbled over the fish and around it in a ring. Tatsoi shoots
(miniature Asian sprouts with a peppery flavor) or snipped chives
are scattered around the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The tender braised baby bok choy placed under the fillet
provides a good contrast to the crispy skin and balances out the
sweetness in the dish. If baby bok choy is not available, regular
bok choy, sliced on the bias, may be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian aspect of the dish is reinforced by briefly marinating
the flesh side of the fish with a simple mixture of soy sauce,
ginger and garlic before cooking. The fish is only marinated on the
flesh side because the skin absorbs very little of the marinade and
must be dry in order to crisp properly. If you're in a hurry, you
can forget the marinade and bok choy _ just place the crispy fish
on some delicate raw salad greens and drizzle the sauce on the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the skin crackling crisp is the challenge; the joke in
our kitchen is that it should be so crisp that the guest had better
have dental insurance. It's important to get the oil very hot
before adding the fish. We use grape-seed oil because it has a
higher smoking point than other oils, but peanut or safflower oil
also work. Olive oil is not recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The fish used here is referred to in our area as rockfish, a
regional name for striped bass. We used to be limited to serving it
only at certain times of year, when we could get it from the
Chesapeake Bay. Now, we are lucky to have someone raising rockfish
in a pond near the inn, who brings them to us still alive.
</P>
<P>
   CRISPY SEARED STRIPED BASS ON BRAISED BABY BOK CHOY WITH
SWEET-AND-SOUR SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the sweet-and-sour sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup seasoned rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   [ cup V8 juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fish sauce (Vietnamese nuoc mam or Thai nam pla)
</P>
<P>
   For the braised bok choy:
</P>
<P>
   3 bulbs baby bok choy
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grape-seed oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   \ cup vegetable stock or water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the striped bass:
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely grated ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   { cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 generous pinch cayenne
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds striped bass fillets, scaled, skin on and pin bones
removed, cut into rectangles about 1{ by 2{ inches
</P>
<P>
   Sliced chives or tatsoi shoots (available at Asian produce
markets), for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare the sweet-and-sour sauce: in a medium saucepan,
combine sugar and vinegar. Place over medium heat, and simmer,
stirring constantly, until mixture turns a rich amber color, 10 to
15 minutes. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add V8 juice a little at a time. Return pan to heat, and
reduce sauce to a syrupy consistency. Remove from heat, and add
lemon juice and fish sauce. If a thinner consistency is desired,
add water a drop or two at a time. (Sauce may be made a day ahead
of time and reheated.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare bok choy: preheat oven to 400 degrees. Remove and
discard outer leaves, and split bulbs in half lengthwise. In a
large saute pan over medium-high heat, bring grape-seed oil to
smoking point. Add bok choy, cut side down, and sear until golden,
1 or 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add wine and stock to pan. Stir gently with a wooden spoon,
scraping bottom of pan. Transfer pan to oven, and cook until bulbs
are tender, 4 to 5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
(Bok choy may be prepared the night before and reheated in a
microwave oven.)
</P>
<P>
   5. Prepare marinade for bass: in a large mixing bowl, combine
garlic, ginger, scallions, sesame oil, olive oil, lemon juice,
vinegar, soy sauce and cayenne. Stir well. (Marinade may be
prepared a day in advance.)
</P>
<P>
   6. To assemble: place fish fillets in marinade for 2 to 4
minutes. Remove, and drain well on paper towels. Season to taste
with salt and pepper. Place a large nonstick saute pan over high
heat, and bring to smoking point. Add fish to pan, skin side down.
After about 30 seconds, lower heat to medium. Place another heavy
pan on top of fish so that it stays flat in pan and the skin will
crisp. Cook 3 or 4 minutes, then remove top pan and turn fish
pieces over. Cook 20 to 45 seconds on flesh side.
</P>
<P>
   7. On each of six warm plates, place one halved bulb of bok
choy. Place equal amounts of fish fillet, skin side up, on each
plate. Drizzle each plate with sweet-and-sour sauce, and garnish
with a sprinkling of chives or tatsoi shoots. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings as a first course, 3 servings as a main
course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
