<SLUG> BC-GREENS-EATING-WELL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENS WITH UNWILTING FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One striking characteristic of the American palate at the end of
the century is its preference for more assertive flavors over bland
ones. People now favor red wine over white, fiery salsas over
ketchup, espresso over the standard morning blend and very dark
chocolate over milk chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes for the greens we eat. In a gradual shift during
the last 15 years, we have moved well past iceberg lettuce and
spinach. I remember that when I first moved to New York in 1981, I
ordered broccoli di rape in an Italian restaurant and found myself
deep in conversation with the owner, who was excited that this
green was becoming the darling of cooked greens. From a few
portions a week, he said, he was now serving 10 to 15 a day.
</P>
<P>
   If you go to a New York City Greenmarket or a specialty food
store today, you will find not only the greens beloved by
Southerners, like collards and mustard, but also those that have
always been sold in Asian markets, like mizuna and tat soi, as well
as the latest Italian green to reach our shores, Tuscan kale (which
is also known as cavolo nero or black kale, and is actually a deep,
deep green).
</P>
<P>
   What all these dark, leafy greens have in common is a piquancy
that appeals to jaded palates in search of something new, something
challenging. They may have a slightly bitter edge, an earthy
intensity or a surprisingly mellow sweet flavor. They can be
divided according to taste; here, by category, are some of the best
known:
</P>
<P>
   Bitter: chicory, dandelions, escarole, broccoli di rape,
radicchio.
</P>
<P>
   Earthy: collards, kale, fully grown mustard and turnip greens.
</P>
<P>
   Peppery: arugula, watercress, young mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet: Swiss chard, lamb's-quarters, beet greens, spinach.
</P>
<P>
   All these greens are cruciferous vegetables belonging to the
genus brassica. Some people may recall that, in first learning
about cruciferous vegetables, they were praised for their
anti-oxidant properties, which may help prevent cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While there will always be some who eat cruciferous vegetables
because of their nutritional value, even if they have to hold their
noses, most people reach for leafy greens today because they like
the taste. That these greens come with important doses of nutrients
is serendipitous.
</P>
<P>
   They are high in vitamins C and E as well as beta carotene. In
addition, the darker ones are important sources of folic acid,
which may help prevent certain birth defects. They are also good
sources of iron and calcium, and some have potassium.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that many of us hated the greens we were served as
children is that they were boiled indiscriminately for 20 minutes,
until they were a gray-green mush with a characteristic cabbage
odor that clung to the walls.
</P>
<P>
   While greens don't need a lot of fussing, they deserve a bit
more care than that. Their age dictates the appropriate
preparation. Young ones can simply be sauteed in olive oil with
garlic and a bit of hot red pepper. Older greens need to be boiled
or parboiled to tenderize them and mellow their metallic, bitter or
assertive taste.
</P>
<P>
   Other versions found in various cultures include greens served
with potatoes in a side dish or a soup. And many greens can be used
interchangeably, though most Asian greens are served raw, while
European are usually cooked.
</P>
<P>
   When buying greens, the younger the better. But no matter the
age, avoid those that are limp, wilted, bruised or discolored.
Generally you'll find the freshest and youngest at a Greenmarket.
</P>
<P>
   TART OF GREENS AND CHEESE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Cooking in Piedmont'' by Roberto Donna (Food
Concepts Marketing Corporation, 1996) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds Swiss chard, kale or any combination of bitter greens
(washed, trimmed of tough stems and sliced into bite-size strips)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely grated Parmigiano Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   \ cup flour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons red-wine vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Place a large saute pan over
high heat. Reduce heat to medium and add oil. Add greens and saute,
stirring often until they wilt. Season with salt and pepper and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir egg with cheese and flour to blend well. Stir in vinegar
and mix with greens.
</P>
<P>
   3. Oil an 8- or 9-inch springform pan and spoon greens into pan,
spreading evenly. Bake about 10 minutes, until egg and cheese
mixture is firm. Remove from oven; cool 2 minutes and remove
springform ring. Serve, cutting into wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings as side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Dish can be made ahead of time through Step 2 and
refrigerated. Remove from refrigerator an hour before baking. You
may need to add a couple of minutes to baking time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      11-30 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING A CELLAR: A CLOSET WILL BE FINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night back in college, a friend of mine discovered classical
music on the radio: something from ``Swan Lake,'' I think, or some
kind of waltz. Chronically afflicted with more money than sense, he
promptly rushed out and bought himself a record library, a
shelf-full of Beethoven, Brahms and Chopin. I doubt if he listened
to any of those records more than once, and some he probably never
played at all.
</P>
<P>
   Fledgling wine lovers have a tendency to act that way when it
comes to storing their wine. The idea of owning a ``cellar,'' of
talking about one's ``cellar,'' is well nigh irresistible, even for
newcomers who cannot yet distinguish a barbera from a beaujolais.
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to discourage the gathering in of a goodly
supply of decent wine. Aside from bragging rights and the
fundamental thrill of acquisition, there are entirely sound reasons
for having something more around the house than a bottle or two
stashed under the sink.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there is convenience. Buying wine a bottle at a
time is a nuisance. If you know what you want, and are not
seriously bereft of funds, it takes no longer to buy a case than it
does a bottle. And there is usually a 10 percent discount on a
12-bottle case. If there isn't, ask why.
</P>
<P>
   A case guarantees a measure of consistency. Wine distribution is
haphazard at best, and if your choice is not a popular, commercial
wine, there may be no more of it the next time you shop. Buying a
case also locks in a price, if only for a while. Wine prices these
days climb like ivy on a backyard fence; with a case you know the
last bottle costs the same as the first. Then there is the
ineffable pleasure to be derived from knowing that the end of a
memorable bottle no longer portends the end of the meal or the
mood. There are all those others, awaiting your pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, in states like New York where primitive laws still
bar the sale of wine in supermarkets, you can avoid all those extra
trips to the liquor store for a single bottle.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you've been listening to me, you've concluded that having
a little wine cellar _ or even a big one _ is a nifty idea. You
have also concluded, I'm willing to bet, that it's an expensive
one. It can be: a year or two ago, a newly affluent banker was
dismayed _ slightly _ to learn that recreating the stone floor of a
Burgundy winery in his East Side apartment required shoring up the
entire floor of the building. He did it anyway. The benefits to his
ego: incalculable. To his wine: none.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, it doesn't have to be this way. Many a good, working
wine ``cellar'' is a spare room or an ample closet high above the
street.
</P>
<P>
   But, you ask, what about temperature control? What about those
formidable wine refrigerators, some with glass doors, no less, that
claim to keep those precious bottles properly cooled? OK, if you've
got precious bottles, buy one. If your wine tastes and, more
important, your wine purse, are more modest, forget the high-ticket
gadgets. They're mostly for show anyway. It's accepted wisdom in
the wine trade that almost all wine is consumed within a year of
its being produced, and 80 percent of the wine purchased in this
country is consumed within two days after leaving the retail shop.
Which means that only a small fraction of the wine made needs
special cellaring.
</P>
<P>
   Well-heeled connoisseurs and would-be connoisseurs, the people
who haunt the auction rooms and who buy wine futures, often install
elaborate cellars to protect their investments. Older wines need
special care because they are fragile and easily affected by
excessive heat, light and vibration. New wines that need extensive
aging will also benefit from special care. But even fine Bordeaux
and Burgundies, if they are to be consumed within three or four
years of their purchase, need no special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A consistent temperature, even if it's 70 degrees, is more
important than a temperature that jumps up and down _ a cellar
that's warm in summer and freezing in winter, for example. A
constant 55 degrees in the cellar of a Bordeaux chateau may be
desirable for wines that will be kept for half a century, but it
serves little purpose in any setting where wine will be consumed in
a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Is wine susceptible to heat damage? Yes, especially during
transportation. Almost everyone in the wine trade has horror
stories about containers of wine left sitting on piers or in
un-air-conditioned warehouses for weeks in temperatures well over
100 degrees. Once, lawsuits over spoiled wine were not uncommon.
Now conscientious importers demand that their best wines be shipped
in refrigerated containers, and very little imported wine arrives
in this country in poor condition. In fact, wine is sturdier stuff
that it might seem to be. And it is made better than it was in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Kept away from bright light, in a space with a constant
temperature not too different from what you require for yourself,
it will last a surprisingly long time. It may age a bit faster in
warmer temperatures, but most wine is drunk too soon, anyway. An
extra year in your hall closet might do wonders for your prized
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   So much for storage space. Next week, we will talk about filling
it. Hint: don't splurge on what you think you should own, like my
college friend and his records. Buy cautiously and buy only what
you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
