<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-HANUKKAH-ART-2TAKES-N     11-30 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANUKKAH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW-FAT HANUKKAH, WITH LATKES AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kansas City Star)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By STEVEN RAICHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some years ago, before carbohydrates became the dietary bugbear,
I was urged by my doctor to go on a low-fat diet. I did fine until
December rolled around, for Hanukkah is unique among Jewish
holidays in that its liturgy involves the consumption of fat.
</P>
<P>
   And it is consumed with a vengeance during the eight-day
Festival of Lights, which this year begins on Friday at sundown.
Israelis delight in soofganiyot, puffy balls of jelly-filled fried
dough similar to American doughnut holes.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Jews eat fried pancakes called tiganites and syrup-soaked
puffs of fried dough known as loukoumades, also called zvingous.
American Jews, following the example of their eastern European
ancestors, revel in potato latkes.
</P>
<P>
   Hanukkah celebrates the victory of a tiny band of Jewish
patriots over a mighty Syrian army in 165 B.C. A tiny cruet of oil,
enough for one night, burned for eight straight days and nights.
Today, Jews light candles in nine-branch menorahs and eat foods
fried in oil. Especially latkes.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't bear the thought of Hanukkah without latkes, made
with grated potatoes, flavored with onion, golden brown and
dripping with oil. The only thing better may be licking your greasy
fingers afterward.
</P>
<P>
   I had already figured out how to make low-fat kreplach
(dumplings, using wonton wrappers instead of egg dough) and even
low-fat chopped liver (by substituting roasted mushrooms for most
of the organ meat). I was not about to be daunted by a latke.
</P>
<P>
   The solution lay in a technique I call ``bake frying.'' I cook
the latkes in a little olive oil, just enough to crisp and brown
them, on a nonstick baking sheet in a 450-degree oven. (Olive oil
is traditional, but more cooks use vegetable oil. Someone somewhere
may fry them in chicken fat, but they could not be served with sour
cream because of the proscription against mixing meat with dairy
products.)
</P>
<P>
   To give my enlightened latkes a richer taste, I use Yukon gold
potatoes, which have a buttery flavor, more so than Idaho potatoes.
Bake-frying works better with smaller pieces of food _ they crisp
better _ so I form my latkes in 2{-inch discs that you can dispatch
in a bite or two.
</P>
<P>
   Bake-fried latkes are lighter and cleaner-tasting than than the
oily potato pancakes. They also make less mess in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The same technique works for sweet potato latkes, which I like
to spice up with cinnamon and nutmeg. Either version can be served
with homemade applesauce and, if you're obsessive, no-fat ``sour
cream.''
</P>
<P>
   A minor but great debate rages over what is the better
accompaniment, applesauce or sour cream. Adherents of the former
emphasize the Eastern European Jewish love of mixing sweet (fruity)
and salty flavors. Sour cream makes for a more savory dish. Ever
ecumenical, my family serves both.
</P>
<P>
   Potato latkes are so enmeshed in American Jewish food culture
that they seem to have existed forever. But the potato latke is a
relatively recent invention, dating to the 16th century, when
potatoes first arrived in central Europe from the New World. Before
that, latkes were made with different vegetables; in parts of
Europe, they still are.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Levy, the author of ``The Low-Fat Jewish Cookbook''
(Clarkson Potter, 1997), takes a slightly different approach, using
corn instead of potatoes, fat-free egg whites and a minimum of oil
in nonstick skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by my success with latkes, I tackled another family
Hanukkah favorite, loukoumades. My Aunt Rosa Miller learned to make
these puffs of deep-fried dough as a child in Greece. The dough
resembles French choux pastry, but with olive oil instead of
butter.
</P>
<P>
   I replaced the eggs in the recipe with egg substitute, which is
almost all egg whites, reduced the oil and baked the loukoumades
instead of frying them. The dough balls puffed and crisped, though
perhaps not as dramatically as the deep-fried originals. But when
you douse them with cinnamon and honey syrup, you get the very
essence of a Greek Hanukkah dessert.
</P>
<P>
   As for soofganiyot, the jelly-filled cousins of the doughnut,
I'm still working.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LOW-FAT LATKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds Yukon gold potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup matzoh meal or unbleached white flour
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup egg substitute, or 2 eggs plus 4 whites
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   No-fat sour cream (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Applesauce (optional). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place large nonstick baking sheet in oven, and preheat to 450
degrees. Peel potatoes and onion, and coarsely grate. Squeeze
handfuls of grated vegetables tightly to wring out as much liquid
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer vegetables to mixing bowl, and stir in matzoh meal,
baking powder, egg substitute, parsley and plenty of salt and
pepper. Latkes should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   3. Spray baking sheet with oil. Spoon small mounds of potato
mixture onto sheet to form pancakes 2{ inches in diameter. Leave 1
inch between each.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake-fry latkes until bottoms are golden brown, for 8 to 10
minutes. Spray tops of latkes with oil. Turn them, and cook until
tops are golden brown. Repeat with remaining dough. Serve at once
with sour cream or applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 50 to 60 small latkes; 8 to 10 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPLESAUCE WITH WINE AND VANILLA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds fragrant apples, like Galas or McIntoshes (6 to 8
apples)
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick or 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 2-inch piece vanilla bean, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2 strips lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons lemon juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry white wine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash apples, and cut in half. Remove stems and cores; leave
skins intact. Place apples in large heavy pot with other
ingredients and 2\ cups water. Bring to boil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reduce heat, and simmer apples, covered, until soft, for 20
to 30 minutes. Remove pan from heat, and let cool slightly. Discard
cinnamon stick and vanilla bean.
</P>
<P>
   3. Puree apples and pan juices in blender or food processor:
blender will yield a silky puree; processor, a chunkier applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 4 cups; 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOUKOUMADES (GREEK HANUKKAH FRITTERS WITH HONEYED SYRUP) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the syrup: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup honey, preferably Greek
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 strips lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   2 strips orange zest
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Cognac or brandy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the pastry: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unbleached white flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup egg substitute, or 2 eggs plus 4 whites lightly beaten
with fork
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon egg substitute or 1 egg white, beaten with a little
salt, for glaze
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon for sprinkling. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare syrup. In saucepan, combine 1\ cups water with sugar,
honey, cinnamon, cloves and lemon and orange zest, and boil until
thick and syrupy, for about 4 minutes. Strain syrup into bowl, and
cool to room temperature. Add Cognac, stir and refrigerate. Syrup
can be prepared up to a day ahead to this stage.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In heavy saucepan, combine 1 cup
water with oil, lemon zest, salt and sugar, and bring to boil over
high heat. Remove pan from heat, and sift in flour. Stir well with
wooden spoon to make thick paste. Return pan to high heat, and cook
until dough is thick enough to come away from sides of pan in a
smooth ball, for 2 to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add egg substitute in 4 batches, beating vigorously with
wooden spoon until mixture is smooth before adding next batch.
Mixture should resemble soft ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer dough to piping bag fitted with ]-inch round tip.
Pipe 1-inch balls of dough onto nonstick baking sheet lightly
sprayed with oil, leaving 1{ inches between each. (If you don't
have a piping bag, use 2 spoons to drop balls of dough onto sheet.)
Dip a fork in cold water, and with back of tines, smooth top of
each ball. Lightly brush balls with egg glaze. Sprinkle sheet with
few drops of water.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bake dough balls until puffed, firm and nicely browned, for
40 to 50 minutes. If puffs brown too much before they are cooked
through, reduce heat. Remove sheet from oven, and cool for 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Using spatula, transfer hot puffs to serving bowl. Pour cold
syrup on top, and let soak for 3 minutes. Serve puffs with syrup in
bowls. Sprinkle with cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 32 to 36 puffs; 8 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
