profoundly changed views on what is normal, if annoying, behavior
by adolescents. No longer is the playground scrap or the kickball
tussle deemed a rite of passage. Known most often as the ``zero
tolerance'' code, aggression is viewed as violence, and teachers
are typically forbidden from simply resolving any physical dispute
with a lecture. Instead, they are instructed to file a report with
the school authorities, so that a uniform policy can run its
course, and no offending student escapes punishment. By Dirk
