<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WASHINGTON-EXHIBIT-2T     11-30 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY DEAR SIR: LETTERS BY A RELUCTANT COMMANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: excerpt at beginning of article should be italicized)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In confidence I can assure you _ with the world, it would
obtain little credit _ that my movements to the chair of government
will be accompanied by feelings not unlike those of a culprit who
is going to the place of his execution.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a handwritten letter to a friend, dated April
1, 1789, less than 30 days before the writer would be inaugurated
as the first president of the new United States of America. And
from the first ``My Dear Sir'' to the final scribble of a farewell
_ ``your affectionate, G. Washington'' _ it provides, in its
penmanship and its candor, a telling portrait of a reluctant leader
being pushed into service at a time of great uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's letter to Henry Knox, the first secretary of war,
is one of about 160 documents, maps, artifacts and artworks on
display at the Pierpont Morgan Library, at 29 E. 36th St. in
Manhattan, through Jan. 9 to commemorate the 200th anniversary of
Washington's death (Dec. 14, 1799).
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``The Great Experiment: George Washington and
the American Republic,'' offers, usually through Washington's own
hand, a complex view of the conflicted new leader and the
challenges that were confronting the nation as it stumbled into
existence 210 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear sir,'' Washington writes James Madison on Aug. 5,
1789, enjoying an advantage that today's Supreme Court justices
might well envy in struggling with questions that Madison had not
contemplated in drafting the Constitution. The governing document
required the president to obtain the ``advise and consent of the
Senate'' in negotiating treaties, which Washington was then
attempting to do with the southern Creek Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would an Oral or written communication be best?'' Washington
inquires. ``If the first what mode is to be adopted to effect it?''
</P>
<P>
   In another letter two years later Washington, at this point
president, confesses to an aide what would today be considered an
early bit of executive bumbling: he had just discovered that his
Annual Message was due to Congress a week earlier than he had
presumed. ``I had no more idea of this than I had of its being
doomsday,'' Washington complained to his private secretary with
evident irritation.
</P>
<P>
   At times it is hard not to feel wistful while following the flow
of Washington's career through the letters presented at the Morgan.
How doubtful it is that another curator will be able to assemble a
similarly revealing exhibit about any contemporary president.
</P>
<P>
   The handwritten letter _ in all its self-edited glory, with
scribbled-out lines and inserted words and phrases _ has been lost
to the typewriter, the word processor and e-mail, to say nothing of
the the discouragement caused by special prosecutors and
congressional committees. And it is hard to imagine a modern-day
president (Jimmy Carter excepted) confessing self-doubt, or at
least putting such thoughts down in a letter. Here, in Washington's
hand, there is a stream of self-doubt, dark humility and candor
that, even if at times calculated, remains startling and
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective was to somehow correct this notion of Washington
as a mere figurehead or as a guy who looked good in a uniform,''
said John Rhodehamel, the curator of American history at the
Huntington Library in San Marino, Calif., which first presented the
exhibition. ``My sense of Washington is that he is vastly
underrated. He was without question the most successful statesman
in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting portrayal is of Washington as the ambitious yet
reluctant leader. He turns away from power at nearly every critical
moment in his career, starting from the end of his military
service. He did not want to be Virginia's delegate to the
Constitutional Convention, nor the nation's first president, and he
did not want to serve a second term. He was melancholy and, from
today's perspective, unduly pessimistic about how the experiment
that was the United States would turn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Affairs, generally, seem really, to be approaching to some
awful crisis,'' he wrote Knox from the Constitutional Convention in
1787. ``God only knows what the result will be. It shall be my part
to hope for the best; as to see this Country happy whilst I am
gliding down the stream of life in tranquil retirement is so much
the wish of my Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are letters in which Washington agonizes over his
ownership of slaves, including correspondence in which he considers
leasing Mount Vernon to, as he obliquely put it, ``liberate a
certain species of property which I possess, very repugnantly to my
own feelings.'' The slaves were not freed until the execution of
Washington's will, which can also be viewed as a published pamphlet
at the Morgan. At times Washington's sentiments seemed conflicted:
in another letter he advises a friend on ways to trick an escaped
slave back into service.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's correspondence here is unfailingly fascinating. A
letter from the battlefield finds Washington the general begging
for gunpowder to arm his troops. Later he turns to a neighbor for a
loan to pay for the trip to his inauguration. ``Never 'till within
these last two yrs I have experienced the want of money,'' he
wrote. ``Under this statement I am inclined to do what I have never
expected to be reduced to the necessity of doing _ that is, to
borrow money upon interest.'' Washington found himself in these
straits partly because he declined a salary while commanding the
Continental Army, though he did file an expense account. He claimed
$64,335.30 over eight and half years, including reimbursement for
his laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Often it is the medium itself _ the written letter _ that is the
most stirring aspect of this exhibition, starting with those
written by Washington, but also including some of his
contemporaries. Martha Washington wrote from her camp outside
Boston in the winter of 1775, ``Some days we have a number of
Cannon and shells from Boston and Bunkers Hill, but it does not
seem to surprise anyone but me; I confess I shudder every time I
hear the sound of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   And John Adams, an aging man writing in a cramped hand, offers a
rather prickly judgment of Washington after his death. In words
that resonate today, Adams describes the first president as one of
the ``great masters of the theatrical exhibitions of politics.'' He
added, ``Washington understood this art very well, and we may say
of him if he was not the greatest President, he was the best actor
of Presidency we have ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is chronological, and toward the end of
Washington's second term familiar patterns of American political
discourse emerge, from the scorn of his foes _ ``As to you, sir,''
Thomas Paine wrote in a pamphlet, ``the world will be puzzled to
decide, whether you have abandoned good principles, or whether you
ever had any'' _ to the gloom and bitterness of a leader
contemplating the twilight of his years in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days before he stepped down from power in 1797,
Washington wrote Knox complaining about enemies who sought ``to
misrepresent my motives; to reprobate my politics; and to weaken
the confidence that has been reposed in my administration.'' All
that was missing was a depiction of the departing president taking
a few mulligans as he played a round of golf alone at dusk one
lonely weekend afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
