<HEADER>
A5240 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-BAPTIST-POWER-NYTSF &LR;      11-30 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-POWER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY OR NOT, HERE COME 100,000 SOUTHERN BAPTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As I walked to work this morning, a man stood on a street corner
shouting, ``Do you know Jesus? Repent! Repent or suffer eternal
torments in Hell!''
 &HT;    Since I live in Memphis, I figured this brother to be a
Pentecostal or a Southern Baptist.
 &HT;    Whatever the case, I knew that I -- as an Episcopalian -- was
fresh evangelistic meat, so I crossed the street.
 &HT;    Never enter into a discussion with street-corner evangelists. I
have told them they give Christians a bad name and pleaded with
them to preach God's love. They don't listen. Even if you are a
Christian, they refuse to believe you unless you are their
particular kind of Christian. Talking is not an option.
 &HT;    On Nov. 28, the Council of Religious Leaders of Metropolitan
Chicago, representing the city's Roman Catholic Archdiocese and
thirty-nine other Christian and Jewish organizations, criticized a
Southern Baptist evangelistic plan to target their city with
100,000 missionaries next summer.
 &HT;    While the Council recognized the rights of Southern Baptists to
engage in evangelism, they questioned the wisdom of such an effort,
saying, ``a campaign of the nature and scope you envision could
contribute to a climate conducive to hate crimes.'' Citing concern
for Jews, Muslims and Hindus, they urged Baptist leaders to ``enter
into discussion with us and reconsider your plans.''
 &HT;    R. Albert Mohler, president of Southern Baptist Seminary in
Louisville, responded: ``To link New Testament evangelism with hate
crimes is cowardice posing as compassion. Fortunately, Southern
Baptists do not receive orders from Chicago's Council of Religious
Leaders, but from the New Testament and the words of our Lord Jesus
Christ.''
 &HT;    What those folks up north don't know is that their (implicit)
accusation -- Southern Baptists are narrow-minded bigots -- are
fightin' words. Chicago's council may desire consensus and
cooperation, but they only fuelled the Southern Baptist fire to
evangelize those spiritually blind northerners.
 &HT;    Talking to a bunch of liberal religious leaders is not part of
God's plan -- except, perhaps, to convert them.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, the Chicago debacle prefigures that which is to
come in cities across the nation. Earlier this year, Southern
Baptists launched the ``Strategic Focus Cities'' initiative to
evangelize major metropolitan areas. Ostensibly, they just want to
``share'' Jesus. In reality, however, the Southern Baptist
Convention (SBC) wants to extend its influence to other parts of
the country by starting 60,000 new churches -- mostly in the North
and West -- by 2020.
 &HT;    Until recently, the 15-million-member SBC has been a regional
denomination. Not widely known elsewhere, it is a social, cultural
and political powerhouse in the South, where it serves as a
quasi-official religious establishment.
 &HT;    Here in Memphis, non-Southern Baptists refer to Adrian Rogers,
pastor of the city's largest Southern Baptist church, as ``Pope
Adrian,'' a moniker befitting his influence.
 &HT;    In their home region, Southern Baptists need not listen to
anyone. They do as they please. Over the last two decades, they
purged their denomination, insisting on strict theological and
moral conformity.
 &HT;    The current leaders, self-proclaimed ``Fundamentalists,'' do not
negotiate. As dissenting Southern Baptists know, they only dictate
terms of surrender. They are not used to talking to -- or invited
to discussions with -- other Protestants, Roman Catholics, Jews,
northerners, apostates and nonbelievers.
 &HT;    With any luck, as Southern Baptists attempt to become a
``national'' church, they will become less rigid and willing to
cooperate with other people of faith to promote the spiritual
welfare of all. The Chicago confrontation will not be the last.
Other groups of religious leaders, who have toiled to make their
communities better places, will insist that Southern Baptists come
to a common faith table.
 &HT;    Those of us who have lived in the North and West understand the
delicate complexity of religious pluralism, and the potential that
fundamentalist religion possesses for creating (even unintended)
violence. The narrow bigotry of the current Southern Baptist
leadership won't (I hope and pray) play in Peoria or Chicago or
Boston.
 &HT;    They are free to shout from street corners or send 100,000
missionaries to an already spiritually vital city. The Council of
Religious Leaders in Chicago has graciously asked them to slow down
their evangelistic assault -- inviting them instead to discuss
religious diversity and pluralism.
 &HT;    I wonder as I listen to this regional religious cross talk: What
would Jesus do? But having observed the SBC over the last decade, I
suspect the campaign will go on as scheduled. If I were those
Chicago leaders, I'd have just crossed to the other side of the
street.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
