<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-WTO-1201-COX     11-30 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WTO-1201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO PUSH FOR MORE OPEN MARKETS AT WORLD TRADE CONFERENCE
 &HT;    (450&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With WTO-PROTESTS-1201.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Eying trillions of dollars in potential U.S. exports
over the coming decade, President Clinton is making a major push to
widen overseas markets for American companies in new global trade
talks opening here this week.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies marketing services _ from telecommunications and
finance to parcel delivery and computer systems design _ took in a
record $246 billion from overseas sales last year. That's a 42-fold
increase over 1960 levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration foresees even greater potential for
increases, though, as the global marketplace becomes more tightly
knitted together and the competitive and strategic advantages of
U.S. companies in the service fields continue to widen.
</P>
<P>
   Services now account for 70 percent of U.S. economic output,
which totalled $8.5 trillion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet, the market access globally is not nearly what it
should be,'' U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky told
White House reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
   As trade ministers from 135 countries gather here to kick-off a
new round of World Trade Organization (WTO) negotiations expected
to last three years, Barshefsky aims to widen U.S. access to
foreign markets, particularly in services areas.
</P>
<P>
   In telecommunications, for example, only 74 of the WTO member
countries have signed on to a 1998 global telecom agreement _ aimed
at ending monopoly control over the burgeoning telecommunications
business. Adopting new WTO rules that mirror that agreement could
open huge new market opportunities for U.S. telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, Barshefsky said, global
telecommunications capacity could increase a stunning 50-fold,
owing to market access agreements already reached and undersea
cable projects in the works.
</P>
<P>
   She's also pushing for U.S. financial services companies and for
the information technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few areas where the potential rewards for the United
States are as great as they are in services,'' Barshefsky told the
Senate Banking Committee in November. ``Our services industries,
ranging from finance to telecom, distribution, health care . . .
and so on, provide 86 million jobs in the United States and over
$5.5 trillion (a year) worth of production.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first round of global trade talks of the Internet
age, and Clinton is pressing to extend tax-free status for
so-called e-commerce, where U.S. companies ranging from Amazon.com
to Landsend.com have built a $20-billion-a-year industry from
on-line shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sales have grown faster than regulators' understanding
of the medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to e-commerce,'' said Barshefsky, ``is it a good,
is it a service? I can tell you now trade ministers don't have a
clue.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are high, also, for U.S. farmers and ranchers. U.S.
agricultural exports, which the administration claims support
750,000 American jobs, slid to $52 billion last year _ down from
$60.6 billion two years before _ owing largely to economic troubles
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes this WTO round will strike down massive subsidies
and other supports provided to farmers chiefly in Europe, Japan,
South Korea, Norway and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   European governments spend $7 billion a year _ 85 percent of the
world's agricultural subsidies _ to prop up farmers that can't
compete with their counterparts in the United States and elsewhere
around the world, according to White House figures.
</P>
<P>
   To fight those subsidies, the United States has lined up a
strong coalition of countries _ largely poorer nations in Asia,
Africa and Latin America _ that would like to boost exports to
Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barshefsky said, the United States is fighting an uphill
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture will be very, very difficult in general,'' she
told the Senate committee, ``as it has been for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
