<HEADLINE>
HEADLINES DON'T TELL WHOLE STORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today we take travelers beyond the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AIRLINES COMBAT CARRY-ON CRUNCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that most carriers have placed new limits on
carry-on luggage, and passengers aboard a recent flight from
Redding, Calif., to San Francisco likely applaud those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Stienstra reports in the San Francisco Examiner:
</P>
<P>
   ``The passengers were just settling in when suddenly, on
climb-out, this red, foul-smelling juice started flowing out of the
overhead baggage compartment and onto the passengers below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several passengers shouted, one screamed, and all tried to
shield themselves from the pervasive red juice. It was sticky, foul
and just kept coming, dripping on the passengers despite their best
efforts to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the plane angled for higher altitudes,'' Stienstra
continued, ``the juice seemed to move to the rear of the plane, as
if alive in the baggage compartment. Meanwhile, one passenger,
Larry Ivancitch, just smiled nervously.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the plane leveled off, the juice stopped, and a flight
attendant opened the overhead bin _ and a wet, slippery 30-pound
salmon fell out, right into the lap of one of the horrified
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that Ivancitch had caught the fish earlier that
day from the Sacramento River, then stowed the fish in an overhead
bin as carry-on baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   The real ``fish tale'' may have come when security guards
attempted to explain how this ``parcel'' got through the carry-on
inspection station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MILLENNIUM CELEBRATION A DUD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to the 16,000 employees at 35 Ritz-Carlton
hotels and resorts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Among items on order for the big event:
</P>
<P>
   _ 40,680 bottles of champagne
</P>
<P>
   _ 8,370 sets of Bulgari bath amenities
</P>
<P>
   _ 27 pounds of caviar at the Ritz-Carlton in Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   _ A cigar stash worth $40,000 at the Ritz-Carlton in Naples
</P>
<P>
   _ 45 chefs at the Ritz-Carlton on Amelia Island, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two tons of gingerbread to form replicas of London's Big Ben,
Paris' Eiffel Tower and New York's Times Square in the lobby of the
Ritz-Carlton Tysons Corner in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but what about the ``biggest-ever'' morning after?
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton in Hong Kong plans to open a Hangover Hospital
where guests can choose their remedy: Bloody Marys or Alka-Seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the chain's property in Seoul can partake of a
home-grown hangover antidote: haejanggook, a hot and spicy soup
available at all restaurants and from room service.
</P>
<P>
   The Portman Ritz-Carlton in Shanghai is taking no chances. It's
stocking up on familiar headache medications and on Barocca
``hangover helper'' vitamin drink. Guests may also avail themselves
of wu liang ye, a 3,000-year-old ``hair of the dog'' Chinese herbal
remedy. Brewed with Chinese sorghum, husked rice, glutinous rice,
wheat and maize, it is fermented for 70 days, producing a mellow,
fragrant concoction often called ``wine from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MEXICO CITY FIGHTS BACK AGAINST CRIME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's government merits praise for several measures
taken recently to address health and safety concerns expressed by
travelers. These include stricter controls of taxis, anti-pollution
regulations and the establishment of tourism-information kiosks
staffed with English-speaking personnel.
</P>
<P>
   In another new strategy, 950 female officers have been added to
the city's predominantly male police force. They've been stationed
at 30 of the city's busiest intersections. According to the Mexico
City Tourism Authority, they are the only officers now allowed to
write tickets for traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning: The government says it believes women are
stricter than men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VACATIONERS PREFER SHORTER GETAWAYS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not Elbert Pence of Kanmore, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Pence is among 250 people who have signed up for Odyssey 2000,
an around-the-world bicycle ride. Participants will begin their
adventure Jan. 1 as the lead unit in the Tournament of Roses Parade
in Pasadena, Calif., and won't finish until Dec. 31, 2000, after
pedaling for 20,000 miles in 45 countries.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Pence apart from his fellow tour members? He's 80
years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to be the oldest,'' says the semi-retired
research physicist. ``I suspect that when we get to some long
inclines, I'll be a little slow going up the hills. Other than that
I don't feel any trepidations.''
</P>
<P>
   Space is still available in Odyssey 2000. Cost is $36,000. Call
800-433-0528 or access www.odyssey2000.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ADVENTURE TRAVEL SPANS THE GLOBE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm inundated with tour brochures about biking, hiking, birding,
sea kayaking, mountain climbing, in-line skating and every other
kind of active pursuit. But former Houstonian Craig Nelson takes
adventure travel to new extremes in his new book, ``Let's Get
Lost'' (Warner Books, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Nelson writes: ``I've been threatened by an orangutan in Borneo
... taught dance steps to cannibals in New Guinea ... taken
psychoactive pharmaceuticals with a Jivaro shaman in the middle of
the Amazon ... sailed the South Pacific in an 18th-century
brigantine ... and stalked gorillas in Uganda.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll leave you with just a hint of the fun here: In the African
bush, Nelson writes, ``The tribe offered me a lunch of baboon and
(traveling companion) Brenda some fresh impala, but in an amazing
coincidence, we'd just eaten and had to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Area bookstores stock or can order ``Let's Get Lost.'' Or access
www.warnerbooks.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
