<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY CHANGES LIKELY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decade, the generation of children attending elementary
school now will begin entering the work force. Their taxed wages
will pay for the Social Security benefits you and I will collect
when we retire.
</P>
<P>
   That is until 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Government analysts have determined that in that year, if Social
Security continues to operate as it does, the system would only be
able to cover about 71 percent of all the funds needed to provide
full retirement, disability and survivor benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is abuzz with talk about reforming the system and
lessening the nation's dependency on it.
</P>
<P>
   Laissez-faire politicians want the system dismantled and
replaced with individually managed retirement accounts for every
American.
</P>
<P>
   The president, meanwhile, has suggested buying back old U.S.
Treasury bonds to reduce the nation's debt and use the money saved
to fund future Social Security payments.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear if either proposal will work, but two outcomes
seem certain: Social Security will be re-engineered in the near
future and the uncertainty surrounding it means retirees must
depend on other sources of sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the latter, the Social Security Administration
began mailing last month a benefits statement to every worker age
25 or older not already receiving benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The four-page document estimates the monthly amount you would
get when you retire or become disabled if you didn't work another
day past the statement date. It also shows what your spouse and
dependent children would get if you died on that day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CREDITS AND LIMITS AND CAPS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility for Social Security retirement benefits is
determined by a credit system based on income and years of
employment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this year you earn one credit for every $740 in
wages, up to four credits each year. Most people must have 40
credits to qualify for retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That means the typical worker has to be in the work force at
least 10 years and earning a minimum yearly salary of $3,000 to
collect a check.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of your benefit depends on how much money you earned
during a lifetime of work. However, since there is a limit on how
much of your income is subject to Social Security taxes &UR;  &LR; _ $72,600
this year _ there is also a cap on how much you can get in
benefits. This year the maximum monthly payment is &UR;  &LR; $1,373 for a
person who retires at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   This is the last year that full retirement benefits can be
collected as soon as a person turns age 65. Over the next 27 years,
the age requirement will gradually increase to 67.
</P>
<P>
   Since medical advances continue to lengthen lives and America's
largest generation is on the cusp of retirement, the Social
Security Administration asked Congress for some breathing room
before it had to help support our graying society.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit statements that are being mailed to about 125
million Americans have long been available to workers who requested
them. But a new law requires the government to send unsolicited
statements of potential benefits to the nation's workers each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GET A PLAN AND START SAVING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mass mailing costs about $70 million this year, but that may
prove to be a bargain if it gets more people to start seriously
thinking about planning and saving for their retirements.
</P>
<P>
   A person born in 1960 with an estimated future annual income of
$68,400 can expect a Social Security check of $1,580 per month when
she retires at age 67. The amount falls to $1,105 a month if she
retires early at age 62.
</P>
<P>
   A common retirement rule of thumb is 70 percent of current
income is needed to maintain the same lifestyle in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So, this 39-year-old person would need a monthly income of
$3,990. Social Security provides 40 percent of that, which is about
average for most U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   But with the future of the Social Security Trust uncertain,
financial planners advise workers to prepare for Social Security to
account for only about 20 percent of their retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   That means paying off credit cards, maxing out your 401(k) and
putting aside 15 percent of your net income each month for
investments, if you are age 39 or older and haven't begun to plan
for retirement, says Gary Ferguson, head of the Houston office of
AXA Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security will not be enough to take care of you in your
golden years. And the statements coming in the mail show it was
never designed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
