<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CLEARY-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      11-30 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEARY-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON KLICKITAT STREET, BEVERLY CLEARY IS FOREVER RAMONA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Ore.)   (bl)  
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 C.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ Beverly Cleary sometimes forgets that she is a
world-famous writer. Or she simply refuses to believe it. Even
after 50 years of fan mail and book signings and awards, attention
unsettles her, especially when it comes in concentrated doses as it
has since the release of her latest children's book, her 38th.
</P>
<P>
   For this interview, she is sitting on a well-stuffed sofa in her
living room with her back straight as a board and her hands folded
in her lap. She prefers phone interviews. Better still is when she
can satisfy the press with an eight-minute video about her book,
``Beverly Cleary Talks About `Ramona's World,''' produced by her
publisher, Morrow Junior Books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wonder why all the fuss?'' Ms. Cleary says, brushing
invisible lint off a maroon jumper. Her hair is a soft gray, her
cheeks, at the moment, the pink of her oxford shirt. ``Maybe,'' she
says, after a pause, ``it's because it's my first Ramona book in 15
years.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, her husband, Clarence Cleary, who has been sitting
quietly to her right in an armchair, leans his wiry frame forward,
as if to reveal a great secret. They have been married 59 years. He
does have stories. ``If I tell you,'' he says, ``some of the honors
Beverly has received in the last few years . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarence!'' the voice is an alarm. ``Don't you dare!''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, had she not written ``Ramona's World'' (released in
August and working its way up children's best-seller lists ) Ms.
Cleary would still generate lines at book signings. Her characters
_ from Henry Huggins and Ribsy to Beezus and Ramona to Ralph S.
Mouse and Socks the Cat _ would remain embedded in the memory of
millions of children speaking 14 languages in 20 countries. Her
name is one of the first recognized as a writer once they realize
that books are written and not produced out of thin air.
</P>
<P>
   So when at age 83 she becomes 9, with a 9-year-old's hopes
(``The fourth grade was going to be the best year of her life, so
far'') and a 9-year-old's concerns (``The fourth grade suddenly
began to stretch ahead, long and dreary and full of spelling''),
people want to know how and why she did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she says with a giggle. ``Ramona just wouldn't let me
alone. I would go about my daily business, and she kept intruding.
Finally she just insisted. She said, `Come on, sit down and write
the book.' So I did.''
</P>
<P>
   So every morning after breakfast, she sat down with a pen and
yellow legal pad, as if Ramona were giving dictation. When she was
done, she typed up the manuscript on an old electric typewriter in
the corner off her bedroom. She does not use a computer, but has
her manuscripts retyped by a professional before being sent to her
publisher. She has never had an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing earth shattering happens in ``Ramona's World.'' No
magical Harry Potter adventures. No taken-from-the-headlines social
problems. No great moral lessons. Ramona's world is Klickitat
Street in Portland, Ore., near the street where the author grew up.
She insists that the neighborhood is much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Once a week she speaks to an old friend who still lives there,
she says, and life there remains cozy. It is a world of ordinary
beauty, where children play rough and tumble outside and compare
battle wounds. (``Ramona's calluses were hard and yellow, because
she lived close to the park.'') They don't dodge drug dealers. They
don't have nannies.
</P>
<P>
   Such a world is exciting enough for a precocious 9-year-old with
a wild imagination. Ramona, who was 5 when she starred in her first
book, ``Ramona the Pest,'' now has a baby sister, Roberta, a best
friend, Daisy, and a boy she likes, Daniel, nicknamed Yard Ape for
his playground prowess. Beezus, her big sister, is entering high
school. And the ever-curious Ramona (``the sort of girl who was
always early because something might happen that she didn't want to
miss'') experiences the best moment in a 9-year-old's life: turning
10.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if Ms. Cleary, who sees much of herself in Ramona the
dreamer, has never forgotten what is important in life at 9. ``I'm
very fortunate in that I do have a very good memory of my
childhood,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote her first novel, ``Henry Huggins,'' in 1950. She was
33, a children's librarian in Yakima, Wash., and a boy complained
that he could not find any books he could relate to. This inspired
the story of a boy from Klickitat Street who finds a stray dog and
takes him home on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning her writing was crisp and clean. Her first
book begins: ``Henry Huggins was in the third grade. His hair
looked like a scrubbing brush and most of his grown-up front teeth
were in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way I know how to write,'' she says, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Atlee Bunn met Clarence Cleary when they were students
at the University of California at Berkeley. They eloped in 1940.
She was Protestant, he Catholic, and her parents disapproved. The
couple settled in California, following his career as an
accountant. She says she always knew she wanted to write _
children's books especially _ but didn't start until both she and
her husband were well established in their careers. After having
twins, a boy and a girl, in 1955, she became more prolific, using
her children's lives to write about experiences she had never had,
like going to kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes she has won include the American Library Association
Laura Ingalls Wilder Award, for lasting contribution to children's
literature, and a 1984 John Newbery Medal for ``Dear Mr. Henshaw,''
the story of a 10-year-old boy's correspondence with his favorite
author while his parents divorce. She has won two Newbery Honor
awards, for ``Ramona and her Father'' and ``Ramona Quimby, Age 8,''
and dozens of statewide awards based on readers' choices.
</P>
<P>
   One of her husband's favorite tributes to her is the Beverly
Cleary sculpture garden at Grant Park in northeast Portland, with
bronze statutes of Henry Huggins, Ribsy, Ramona and Beezus based on
the classic illustrations of the books by Louis Darling. There is
also the Beverly Cleary residence hall at the Berkeley campus.
</P>
<P>
   She will not talk about all the mail she gets, about 100 letters
a day, her publisher said. And the letter she has tacked up on the
wall behind her desk is hardly a fan letter. Written by a boy in
awkward cursive, it is a hello from an old friend of hers who is
dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S. This is all a lie,'' the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   She says she does not remember when she got the letter. ``It
should have a date on it,'' she says. ``They should teach that in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   But when she looks at the letter, she laughs and utters what
Beverly Cleary readers know is a high compliment. ``That kid,'' she
says, ``has some imagination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SPAETZLE-ART-2TAKES-N     11-30 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAETZLE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GERMANY BY WAY OF EVERYWHERE, SPAETZLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Italy, Ill., Calif., Vt.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Eds: Recipes appear at end of story.)  (DW) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a time when Mediterranean accents seem to dominate
many American menus, a little German is creeping in. Spaetzle, the
tiny dumplings of Eastern Europe, are turning up where couscous
once did, alongside duck, venison and fish.
</P>
<P>
   These close cousins to gnocchi and fresh pasta look like little
squiggles of dough, but taste like buttery air. (Think Mozart, not
Wagner.)
</P>
<P>
   Spaetzle are everywhere lately, from Quilty's in SoHo to Artie's
New York Delicatessen and Picholine on the Upper West Side, from
Italian restaurants like Felidia and Circo to Frenchified Japanese
places like Sono, all in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Part of their wide appeal is their chameleon quality. Spaetzle
can be plain or be made with chestnut or buckwheat flour; they can
be seasoned with only salt and pepper or turned almost green with
fresh herbs like chives or sage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a million and one ways to do spaetzle _ and that's
without getting too crazy with them,'' said Eberhard Mueller of
Lutece, who is from the cradle of spaetzle, Swabia, the Black
Forest region of southern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Spaetzle (usually pronounced SHPEH-tzl in English) take no
special skills to make, and in fact look best when they are rather
haphazard, almost misshapen. So they are that rare restaurant trend
that works for home kitchens. The basic ingredients for the thick
batter are flour and eggs. Although there are special German and
Austrian spaetzle gadgets, cutting board and knife, or just press
the dough through a colander can be used. The little dumplings are
dropped into boiling water until they firm up and float and are
often tossed in butter afterward. But they can be varied at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``As American cooks, we're exploring the last European
frontier,'' said Katy Sparks, the chef at Quilty's, who serves
black pepper and herb flecked spaetzle to complement squab in
Madeira sauce. ``First came the Mediterranean, but it's time we
recognized Eastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sparks said she knew spaetzle from visits to Vienna and
other parts of Eastern Europe with her father, M. Kimberley Sparks,
who is professor emeritus of German at Middlebury College in
Vermont. ``It was easy for me to make a gesture to the region with
something delicious I'd been exposed to in the past,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other chefs, like Mueller and Mario Lohninger of Danube, are
even more familiar with spaetzle from their childhoods. Lohninger,
the chef de cuisine at Danube, David Bouley's homage to Austria in
TriBeCa, is the son of restaurateurs in Salzburg who sometimes
served spaetzle tossed with cheese as a main course, or in soup. At
Danube he adds pureed garlic chives to the thick batter, giving the
spaetzle a sharp flavor and a verdant tint.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, who is now using spaetzle as an accompaniment to
venison and red cabbage, recalled how they were typically served at
Sunday lunch in Germany with braised beef, veal or pork as well as
German potato salad and lettuce dressed with lemon juice. ``And my
mother would put parsley and chives in her spaetzle long before it
was fashionable,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lidia Bastianich, the owner of Felidia, said she often ate
spaetzle back in Friuli, the region in northeastern Italy that
abuts Austria. ``We make spaetzle to go with braised dishes and we
season it with saffron, tomato or spinach, like gnocchi,'' she
said. (But she added, ``I just came back from Italy, and I was
served spaetzle in Piedmont. I have no idea where they got it
from.'')
</P>
<P>
   Even chefs with no spaetzle in their pasts are experimenting:
Terrance Brennan at Picholine makes them with chestnut flour; Chris
Metz at Artie's New York Delicatessen works kasha into the dough;
John Reese at Adrienne flavors spaetzle with saffron; and John
McGrath at C3 adds sage. Tadashi Ono at Sono makes his with
buckwheat flour, giving them the flavor of Japanese soba noodles.
Outside New York, spaetzle are being seasoned with Dijon mustard at
Spruce in Chicago and with curry at Charles Nob Hill in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Cuisines of Germany'' (Poseidon Press, 1980), Horst
Scharfenberg called spaetzle the ``quintessential Swabian
delicacy.'' Some trace the name to fat-bodied little sparrows, or
spatzen in South German dialect. But Scharfenberg favored the
derivation from the Italian spezzare, meaning to cut in pieces. He
wrote that spaetzle are thought to have been brought to Germany by
Italian workers or monks in the Middle Ages. But he also suggested
that they might have arrived earlier with Roman soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Because spaetzle require no rolling or cutting, they may be the
simplest, least technically demanding pasta to make. The process is
just tedious. There are special spaetzle-makers: wood boards with
sharp edges over which the batter is scraped with a knife (there is
even such a thing as a spaetzle knife), or perforated metal gadgets
that fit over the pots and have sliding hoppers to push the dough
through.
</P>
<P>
   But most chefs make spaetzle simply by forcing the thick batter
through the holes of a colander or a hotel pan (a kind of
perforated saucepan used for warming or steaming). A large
stainless-steel colander with holes one-eighth inch to one-quarter
inch wide can be used. Hold it over a pot that is half filled with
boiling water and use a large spoon, a wooden spatula or a dough
scraper to push the batter through the holes.
</P>
<P>
   That is the method of choice of the cashier at Schaller &AMP; Weber,
the German food store on the Upper East Side, where I bought
packaged spaetzle for comparison purposes. When I asked which of
four brands to choose, she responded: ``You don't have to buy it.
You make a simple batter with eggs and flour and press it through a
colander.'' (I now understand the universal disdain for the
packaged spaetzle, which are more like twisted bits of egg noodle
and not as feathery as the homemade kind.)
</P>
<P>
   Mueller scoffs: ``The colander is not the authentic way in
Germany. That's considered the fast food version.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he scrapes the bits of dough off a board and into
boiling water with a knife, in a rapid-fire motion he learned from
his mother. ``Where I grew up, there was a saying that if a woman
couldn't make spaetzle by hand she was not worth marrying,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I found a cutting board easier to use than a colander, and the
yield was slightly greater, since there was no waste. With a
colander, some batter will cling.
</P>
<P>
   Balance the small wooden cutting board, preferably one with a
handle, on the edge of the pot and use a table knife to scrape tiny
bits of batter off and flick them into the pot. Dip the knife blade
frequently into cold water to help the batter slip off.
</P>
<P>
   When the dough is pushed through a colander, a hotel pan or a
perforated metal spaetzle maker, the pieces tend to be plumper and
shorter. Scraped off a board, they are like little strips or
squiggles. The thicker the batter, the shorter the pieces tend to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs like spaetzle because they do not have to be served at
once _ a boon to the home cook as well. They can be reheated later
by lightly toasting them in a skillet with butter. A good,
traditional finishing touch is to let the butter turn hazelnut
color, stir in bread crumbs and let them brown before adding the
spaetzle and a dusting of minced herbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, liver puree is sometimes mixed into the batter. It's
a variation New Yorkers might like _ but with foie gras, of course.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   BUCKWHEAT SPAETZLE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Sono
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup light buckwheat flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   } cup vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter.
</P>
<P>
   1. Whisk flours, salt and pepper in large bowl. Add egg and
}-cup stock. Beat until well-blended to make thick batter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring 3 quarts salted water to a boil in a large pot. Add 1
teaspoon olive oil and reduce to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   3. Hold a colander a few inches above the pot. With a large
spoon or spatula, push about \ of the batter through holes into the
water. Or place \ of the batter on a small wooden board and rest it
on the edge of the pot; use a knife to scrape tiny bits into the
water. When spaetzle rise to top, remove with skimmer or slotted
spoon to a baking sheet lined with paper towel. Continue making
spaetzle in batches.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer well-drained spaetzle to bowl, cover and set aside.
You should have 3 to 3{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   5. When ready to serve, melt butter in large skillet. Add
spaetzle and saute a few minutes, until starting to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 side-dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK PEPPER AND CHIVE SPAETZLE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Quilty's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour plus 1 hour's resting  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3\ cup flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   1. In large bowl, mix eggs, lemon, pepper, chives, nutmeg and
salt with 1{ cups water. Slowly beat in flour. Cover. Set aside 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring 3 quarts salted water to a boil in a large pot. Reduce
to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   3. Hold a colander a few inches above the pot. With a large
spoon or spatula, push about \ of the batter through holes into the
water. Or place \ of the dough on a small wooden board and rest it
on the edge of the pot; use a knife to scrape tiny bits into water.
When spaetzle rise to top, remove with skimmer or slotted spoon to
a baking sheet lined with paper towels. Continue making spaetzle in
batches.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heat butter in large skillet. Add spaetzle and toss until
coated with butter and starting to become very lightly browned.
Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 5 to 6 cups spatzle. Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   SWABIAN SPAETZLE WITH HERBED BREAD CRUMBS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Eberhard Mueller
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes plus time for making spaetzle
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons dry white breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons each minced fresh parsley, chives, chervil
</P>
<P>
   3{ cups prepared, drained spaetzle
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat butter in 2-quart saucepan over medium heat until golden
brown. Add bread crumbs and continue cooking until crumbs are
lightly browned. Remove from heat and add herbs.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add spaetzle and stir gently to coat with butter and the
herbed bread crumbs. Reheat briefly. Season with salt and pepper.
Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 side dish servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
