<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOUD-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEYOND THE CLOUDS': THREE VIGNETTES AFLOAT IN ROMANTIC
OBSESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The precede may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Clouds'' was shown as part of the 1996 New York
Film Festival. Following are excerpts from Stephen Holden's review,
which appeared in The New York Times on Sept. 28, 1996. The film
opens Wednesday in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of such astounding visual power in
Michelangelo Antonioni's film ``Beyond the Clouds'' that you are
all but transported through the screen to a place where the
physical and emotional weather fuse into a palpable sadness.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene the brooding, peripatetic director who introduces
the movie's vignettes (played by John Malkovich), finds himself in
Portofino, where he becomes obsessed with a beautiful woman he sees
in a shop. As he lingers on the beach under an ominous sky, a stiff
wind churns the sand into a diaphanous river.
</P>
<P>
   With the ground literally moving under his feet, and the sea and
sky threatening, he becomes an eerily isolated figure, seemingly
floating just above the earth in a melancholy reverie.
</P>
<P>
   If this scene recalls similar moments in Antonioni's 1959
masterpiece, ``L'Avventura,'' in which a group of friends combs the
rocks of an abandoned island in search of a woman who has
mysteriously vanished, the allusion seems deliberate. For ``Beyond
the Clouds,'' this Italian filmmaker's first movie since 1982, has
the feel of an eloquent, quirky swan song that recycles for one
last time themes that have run through all of his films.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago Antonioni, who is now 83, had a stroke that
left him severely incapacitated. ``Beyond the Clouds'' was
completed with help from Wim Wenders, who wrote its prologue and
epilogue and worked on the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who will be impatient with this film, which was
adapted from short stories in Antonioni's book ``The Bowling Alley
on the Tiber.'' The dialogue is sparse, and what there is often
sounds stiff and pretentious. Malkovich, playing Antonioni's
stand-in, makes blunt, oracular pronouncements about desire, art
and the pursuit of reality that ring sophomoric or prophetic,
depending on your feelings about Antonioni.
</P>
<P>
   These vignettes portray characters caught up in romantic
obsessions presented as metaphors for the artist's pursuit of an
elusive truth. In the opening vignette two beautiful young lovers
(Kim Rossi-Stuart and Ines Sastre), filmed with a cool, soft-core
elegance, never consummate their passion because the young man
prefers to imagine a perfection that reality could never match.
</P>
<P>
   The second pas de deux finds Malkovich's character in Portofino
stalking the woman inside the shop. She enigmatically informs him
that she murdered her father.
</P>
<P>
   From Italy we move to Paris for the third and most conventional
story, a romantic triangle in which an ardent philanderer (Peter
Weller) tries to appease the demands of his wife (Fanny Ardant) and
mistress (Chiara Caselli).
</P>
<P>
   In the final story Vincent Perez plays a young man who trails a
woman (Irene Jacob) to church and falls more deeply in love with
her the more inaccessible she makes herself. By the time she tells
him that she will enter a convent the next day, he is besotted.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of these stories is not in the words but in the way
the mood, texture and the acting build each situation into a
visually intense parable about the similarity of spiritual, erotic
and aesthetic aspiration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5259 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-HANUKKAH-AUTHOR-RECIP     11-30 1937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANUKKAH-AUTHOR-RECIPES-LADN </SLUG>
 
How to light up your Hanukkah celebration 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Recipes) 
By Natalie Haughton 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICOTTA LATKES
</P>
<P>
   Both cheese and latkes are very traditional foods for Hanukkah.
The following latkes are much more delicate and refined than the
potato type and make a tasty breakfast or even a nice dessert,
especially when topped with a good jam or fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   BATTER: &QL; 
1 (15- to 16-ounce) container part-skim ricotta cheese &QL; 
4 large eggs OR 1 cup egg substitute &QL; 
2 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
1/2 to 1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter, melted and cooled &QL; 
1/2 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
FOR FRYING: &QL; 
Butter OR margarine OR canola oil &QL; 
FOR SERVING: &QL; 
Jam, applesauce, plain OR vanilla yogurt, AND/OR chopped fresh
fruit
</P>
<P>
   For Batter, in a food processor fitted with a steel blade (or in
a blender in batches if necessary), combine ricotta cheese, eggs,
sugar and vanilla. Process until well mixed. Add melted butter and
process briefly. Add flour, and process until batter is very
smooth, like thick cream. Scrape down sides of container a few
times during processing. Batter will be thinner than most pancake
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a griddle or shallow skillet, preferably nonstick, over
medium heat (not hotter). An electric skillet set at 325 degrees F
also works well. Lightly grease griddle with butter. (You can use a
stick of cold butter to make 3-inch circles on griddle.)
</P>
<P>
   For each latke, spoon a 1 1/2- to 2-tablespoon measure of batter
(no more) onto greased preheated griddle. Batter will spread to
form an approximately 3-inch-diameter latke. Keep latkes at least
1/2-inch apart.
</P>
<P>
   Cook about 3 minutes or until a few bubbles have risen to
surface of pancakes, tops are beginning to look dry and bottoms are
golden brown in a sort of splotchy pattern. Latkes will not rise at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully use a pancake turner to turn latkes once. (If bottoms
of latkes brown before tops are dry enough to turn, heat is too
high.) Cook latkes briefly on second side just until golden brown.
Repeat until all batter is used, greasing griddle between batches.
</P>
<P>
   Serve pancakes warm or at room temperature, with your choice of
accompaniments. Latkes can be reheated in a microwave oven or kept
warm for a short time in preheated 200- to 250-degree F
conventional oven. Makes about 24 to 30 (2 1/2- to 3-inch-diameter)
latkes.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: It's recommended that these latkes be prepared on a
nonstick griddle, which requires very little grease. Gloria Greene
prefers to cook latkes in butter because this adds to their flavor.
The small amount of butter in batter also improves taste of latkes.
</P>
<P>
   NO-FAT RICOTTA LATKES: Although the original recipe above is
preferred, the following changes will work for those on restricted
diets. Use nonfat ricotta cheese and egg substitute. Omit melted
butter in batter. Use 1 teaspoon vanilla. When cooking latkes, use
a nonstick griddle that has been coated with nonstick cooking spray
before preheating. Make sure that heat is not too high.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHILI CON QUESO
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shredded regular Cheddar, longhorn OR Monterey Jack
cheese (see Note) &QL; 
2 tablespoons all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive OR canola oil &QL; 
1 large onion, finely chopped &QL; 
2 garlic cloves, minced &QL; 
1 (14- to 16-ounce) can tomatoes, including juice, finely chopped &QL; 
1 (4-ounce) can diced green chiles &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped ripe olives (optional) &QL; 
Corn chips, nacho chips OR broken taco pieces for dipping
</P>
<P>
   Toss cheese with flour and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put oil into a large saucepan over medium-high heat; then saute
onion and garlic until very tender. Add tomatoes with their juice
and chiles. Heat, while stirring, until sauce gently boils.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually add shredded cheese, stirring constantly. Continue to
stir over medium to medium-high heat 5 to 10 minutes or until
cheese is completely melted and smooth and mixture just comes to a
boil. Stir in olives.
</P>
<P>
   Remove mixture from heat and cool, stirring occasionally, about
5 minutes, so it can thicken slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm chili con queso in a chafing dish, fondue pot or deep
bowl with your choice of accompaniments for dipping. Makes about 4
1/2 cups dip.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Reduced-fat cheese may not melt properly in this recipe.
Do not use nonfat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUICK-AND-EASY CHEESE BLINTZ CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   BATTER: &QL; 
4 large eggs (no substitutes) &QL; 
1 1/4 cups milk &QL; 
2 tablespoons dairy sour cream &QL; 
1/4 cup butter, melted (for best flavor, no substitutes) &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 1/3 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 to 2 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
1 1/4 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
FILLING: &QL; 
2 (7 1/2- to 8-ounce) packages curd-style farmer cheese &QL; 
1 (15- to 16-ouncee) container ricotta cheese, any type &QL; 
2 large eggs OR 1/2 cup egg substitute &QL; 
2 to 3 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons lemon juice &QL; 
FOR SERVING: &QL; 
Dairy sour cream &QL; 
Plain OR vanilla yogurt &QL; 
Applesauce &QL; 
Sliced fresh strawberries OR other fruit
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9x13-inch baking dish or coat with nonstick cooking
spray.
</P>
<P>
   For Batter, in a blender or food processor (fitted with a steel
blade), combine all Batter ingredients. Process until very smooth,
scraping down sides of container once or twice. Measure out 1 1/2
cups batter and pour into bottom of prepared baking dish. Bake in
preheated 350-degree oven about 10 minutes or until set.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine all filling ingredients in a large bowl and
mix well. When bottom layer has set, remove from oven and spread
filling over it, smoothing top. Give remaining batter a brief stir
to mix ingredients; then very slowly pour over cheese filling so
filling is completely covered.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully return casserole to 350-degree F oven. Bake an
additional 35 to 40 minutes or until top is puffed and set. Let
casserole stand about 10 minutes before cutting into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with your choice of accompaniments. Makes about 8 servings
as a main course, more as a side dish or buffet dish.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The types of cheeses in the filling were determined after
much experimentation with various mixtures. It is the best
combination to produce the desired results of separate layers.
</P>
<P>
   The top of this casserole is rather plain. If desired, sprinkle
lightly with ground cinnamon or cinnamon-sugar before casserole is
returned to oven for final baking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELI SALAD
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is meant only to be a guide; vary ingredient
proportions to taste. For the best flavor, prepare the salad just
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   3 large tomatoes, ripened, diced &QL; 
2 to 3 medium cucumbers, peeled (if desired) and diced &QL; 
4 green onions, including green tops, thinly sliced OR 1 small
onion, peeled and finely diced &QL; 
1 to 2 medium green OR red bell peppers, diced &QL; 
1/4 cup finely chopped fresh parsley &QL; 
3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice OR to taste &QL; 
3 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine tomatoes, cucumbers, green onions, peppers and parsley
into a large serving bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix together lemon juice and oil. Pour over
vegetables and toss well. Season salad to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately, as a side dish or in a pita loaf as an
accompaniment to falafel. Makes about 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRUIT-NUT CONFECTION BALLS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1/2 cup dried apricots &QL; 
1/2 cup pitted dates &QL; 
1/2 cup dried figs &QL; 
1/2 cup pitted prunes &QL; 
1/2 cup walnut pieces &QL; 
1/4 cup shredded coconut (optional) &QL; 
2 tablespoons honey OR as needed &QL; 
Granulated sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop apricots, dates, figs, prunes and walnuts in a food
processor fitted with a steel blade or put through coarse blade of
a food grinder (nuts will help push sticky fruit through). Or, if
desired, finely chop by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in coconut and honey; mix until well combined. If mixture
seems very crumbly, add honey as needed, but do not use too much or
it will become very sticky.
</P>
<P>
   Use your hands to mold walnut-size portions of mixture into
compact 1-inch-diameter balls and, if desired, roll each one in
sugar to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Store in refrigerator. Serve at room temperature for best
flavor. Makes about 36 balls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE-CHIP MANDELBROT
</P>
<P>
   The original recipe for these mandelbrot (almond bread, in
Yiddish), was given to me long ago by a cousin, and I have adapted
it. Although the original recipe didn't, I double-bake them. They
are quite good either way. The extra baking makes them a little
crunchier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3/4 cup canola oil &QL; 
1 1/4 cups sugar &QL; 
3 large eggs OR 3/4 cup pareve egg substitute &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1 teaspoon almond extract &QL; 
1 tablespoon baking powder &QL; 
3 3/4 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 to 1 cup slivered OR sliced almonds &QL; 
1 to 1 1/2 cups regular OR miniature chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Put oil, sugar and eggs in a large bowl and beat with an
electric mixer until very light and fluffy. Beat in vanilla, almond
extract and baking powder. Add flour and mix in slowly by hand or
heavy-duty electric mixer until completely combined. Finally, stir
in (or use a heavy-duty mixer at lowest speed), almonds and
chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer sticky dough from bowl to a large sheet of plastic
wrap; then wrap dough and press into a large disk. Chill dough at
least 1 hour or until somewhat firm.
</P>
<P>
   Line 2 large baking sheets with cooking parchment or coat with
nonstick cooking spray or grease. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Unwrap dough and divide into 4 equal parts. Transfer 1 part to a
floured surface and coat entire surface of dough lightly with
flour. (Return remainder of dough to refrigerator.) Form chilled
dough into a log that is 2 inches in diameter and about 10 to 11
inches long, using additional flour as needed. Brush off any excess
flour on dough log. Immediately transfer log to one long side of
prepared baking sheet. Repeat to make another log. Keep 2 logs
parallel and at least 2 inches apart, as they expand a lot during
baking. Press in sides of each log with both your hands to even
width of logs along entire length.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 25 to 30 minutes or
until lightly browned. (Do not be concerned about cracks that form
on logs.) Loosen from baking sheets with a metal spatula, but leave
in place to cool to at least lukewarm. When first 2 logs are almost
done baking, form remaining 2 logs on another baking sheet and bake
and cool as directed.
</P>
<P>
   When baked logs are cool, carefully slide, one at a time, off
baking sheets onto a cutting board. Use a sawing motion with a
serrated bread knife to crosswise cut each log on diagonal into
5/8-inch-thick to 3/4-inch-thick slices (thinner slices may fall
apart). (Save odd-shaped ends for a nosh; they will quickly
disappear.)
</P>
<P>
   For softer mandelbrot, cool slices completely and serve as is.
If desired, sprinkle slices with sieved powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   For crunchier mandelbrot, stand cut slices back on baking sheet
so there is about 1/2-inch between each. Do not lay slices on cut
sides or chocolate will ooze out. Carefully, so slices don't fall
over, put baking sheets back into 350-degree F oven. Toast
mandelbrot 8 to 10 minutes. (They will crisp even more as they
cool.) Remove baking sheet from oven.
</P>
<P>
   If a coating is desired, put some superfine sugar into a small
bowl. Sprinkle both sides of each warm mandelbrot slice with
superfine sugar, shaking excess back into bowl. Cool slices
completely by standing up on a wire rack. Store mandelbrot in
airtight food containers at room temperature up to 1 week or freeze
for longer storage. Makes about 50 mandelbrot slices.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: One end of mandelbrot can also be dipped in melted
semisweet chocolate, if desired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
