How to light up your Hanukkah celebration 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
( With art , 2 takes) 
By Natalie Haughton 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; At sundown Friday, Jews will begin the eight-day celebration of
Hanukkah, also known as the festival of lights. They will light
candles in the menorah each night until all eight are lit in
remembrance of the miracle that occurred when the Maccabees
defeated their oppressors, who were trying to make the Jews give up
their religion.
</P>
<P>
   Oil, symbolically associated with the miracle oil in the
rededicated temple in Jerusalem, is traditional in Hanukkah
cooking. Latkes _ made with grated potatoes and onions or ricotta
or other cheeses and fried in oil _ long have been a holiday
favorite. Other popular menu items include jelly-filled doughnuts
(known as sufganiyot) and holiday pastries (such as Zelebi,
Bimuelos and Koeksisters), which are also fried in oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lesser-known Hanukkah culinary custom is the partaking of
cheese and all sorts of dairy dishes in honor of the brave Jewish
heroine Judith,'' writes Gloria Kaufer Greene in ``The New Jewish
Holiday Cookbook'' (Times Books; $27.50), a collection of recipes
and customs from different countries around the world. The book is
a revision of an earlier edition which came out in 1985 _ and has
100 new recipes with variations.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is appealing to novices who have never cooked Jewish food
as well as accomplished cooks looking for variety. ``A lot of
people have never learned from their parents how to celebrate the
holidays and have fun with family and friends _ and eat good food
at the same time.'' Her book is designed to teach the basics and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Greene has concentrated on offering updated, quicker,
streamlined recipes along with healthier ingredient options (such
as oil instead of margarine; egg substitute for eggs, etc.) where
possible.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the recipes appear uncomplicated, others have
lengthy ingredient lists and directions (she wanted to make the
recipes fail-proof, she said) that are somewhat off-putting and go
on for several pages. But judge for yourself and pick and choose
the dishes that fit your skills and schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Greene combines the two culinary traditions of
Hanukkah _ dairy dishes and oil-fried foods _ and with her husband
and four children _ hosts a Sunday open house celebration for
family and friends featuring a dairy buffet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very casual, joyful, fun-filled time and usually includes
dishes like Ricotta Latkes, Potato Latkes, Chili Con Queso,
Quick-and-Easy Cheese Blintz Casserole, Rich-and-Fruity Lokshen
Kugel, a fruit or vegetable salad, an assortment of cookies such as
Chocolate Chip Mandelbrot, Fruit-Nut Confection Balls or Hanukkah
Butter Cookies, and Soft Pretzels or Cinnamon Buns.
</P>
<P>
   If time and energy are at a premium but you still want to
entertain, Greene suggests making one dish you feel really good
about that will impress your guests, then purchasing the rest of
items to complete the menu or have friends contribute a specialty
such as a kugel, salad or dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is a firm believer in preparing as much in advance as
possible _ then freezing or refrigerating the dishes and thawing
and reheating prior to serving. You can make the Ricotta Latkes the
day before and refrigerate them. On the day of the party, arrange
on a serving dish and reheat in the microwave oven just prior to
serving. Be sure to watch them carefully so the pancakes are just
warm and don't end up rubbery, advises Greene. She likes to serve
them with fresh raspberries or strawberries, a little jam and
vanilla yogurt or sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   For best taste and texture, potato latkes should be eaten as
soon as possible after cooking, notes Greene, but they taste almost
as good if made the morning of the party. Reheat them uncovered,
slightly overlapping, in a shallow roasting pan in a 400-degree
oven about six to eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are as many variations of these pancakes as there are
Jewish cooks who make them. Some prefer to saute the onions before
adding the potato shreds; most use raw onions. Some insist on matzo
meal as a thickener; others use flour.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of experimenting, Greene has developed a food
processor technique that requires minimal time. She also uses an
electric peeler to peel the potatoes and an electric skillet to fry
them with little fuss. She believes they taste better and require
less salt if the salt is sprinkled on after cooking _ and not added
to the raw potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The Tex-Mex Chili Con Queso dip is a great party buffet dish and
can be whipped up in minutes with shredded cheese (don't substitute
reduced- or no-fat cheeses), garlic, onions, tomatoes, diced green
chiles and ripe olives. Serve warm from a chafing dish or fondue
pot with corn chips for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   A blintz casserole is Greene's easy answer to serving cheese
blintzes. It has a flavor similar to blintzes but is less work.
Unlike some of the popular casseroles that use store-bought frozen
blintzes, Green's version bakes a layer of cheese filling between
two layers of a special blintz-type batter. To gussy up the baked
casserole, sprinkle the top lightly with cinnamon or
cinnamon-sugar. Offer guests sour cream, applesauce and sliced
fresh fruits to accompany the cut-up squares. This casserole is
another good candidate to bake a day or two ahead and reheat in the
microwave oven before arranging on the buffet table. You can also
freeze it up to twomonths ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that blintzes, latkes and chili con queso don't
have to be served piping hot _ so don't drive yourself crazy.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sweets _ such as mandelbrot, fruit balls and
butter cookies _ Greene opts for baking everything several days to
several weeks ahead and using the freezer to keep the goodies fresh
up to two to three months. ``If you do a good job of wrapping food
for the freezer, it can be a great time saver. Also, the sweets
will stay fresher than at room temperature or in the refrigerator
for any length of time.'' With a variety of sweets stashed in the
freezer, you can offer a greater assortment on different occasions,
says Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to thaw frozen items, notes Greene, is to leave the
food wrapped and thaw non-perishables on the countertop and
perishables in the refrigerator. Greene believes cooking for the
Jewish holidays should be fun and satisfying _ and manageable for
the cook. ``Most important is that the food tastes and looks
delicious.'' She favors simple garnishes to embellish the food.
``If it doesn't look good, people won't be attracted to it. It's
often been said that what people remember most is the last thing
they ate _ and that's dessert.'' So make it wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, a cooking teacher for 20 years, has created a Web site _
!bold!www.jewishcuisine.com!off! _ to share her excitement about
Jewish cooking and Jewish cuisine. ``It's time for Jewish food to
come into its own as a legitimate cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, celebrate Hanukkah with these creations from Greene's
book.
</P>
<P>
   caption
</P>
<P>
   John Lazar/Staff Photographer
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Kaufer Greene shares recipes from around the world in her
latest book, ``The New Jewish Holiday Cookbook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
