r l BC-BOOK-BLONDE-HNS &LR;      11-30 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLONDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BLONDE' WAS A NATURAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Absinthe.'' ``Martinis.'' ``The Cigar.'' And now ``The
Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer and bon vivant Barnaby Conrad III, 47, probably was born
50 years too late. He is much more at home with the expatriate
spirit of his idols, Ernest Hemingway, F. Scott Fitzgerald and
their favorite Lost Generation couple, Gerald and Sara Murphy
(Fitzgerald's models for Nicole and Dick Diver in ``Tender Is the
Night'').
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's books for Chronicle Publishing are about cultural
icons. The latest two - ``The Blonde'' and, due out in a few weeks,
an illustrated compendium on ``Pan Am,'' the airline that flew the
Clipper out of San Francisco - are a natural progression from his
first book, ``Absinthe,'' which he wrote and then revised
successfully after spending his own ex-pat days in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He can't help being a peripatetic uber-dilettante with
workaholic habits. It's in his blood. Following in his boulevardier
father's Seven League boots, Conrad's life has been one filled with
adventure, travel lust, pretty women, well-connected friends, good
cigars and, above all, very, very dry gin martinis. Barnaby the
Second owned the famous North Beach club, the Matador (named for
his best-selling book), during the hip `50s. It's as if Conrad the
younger is re-creating Conrad the elder's high life.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's ``The Blonde: A Celebration of the Golden Era
From Harlow to Monroe,'' with a photograph of Veronica Lake's
famous cascade of wheat-blond hair on the cover. ``I decided not to
use Marilyn Monroe because then the book would be about her,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, he's covered everything from the Clairol slogans
(``Does she, or doesn't she? Only her hairdresser knows for sure''
and ``If I have but one life to live, let me live it as a blonde'')
and the famous `50s blondes - Kim Novak, Grace Kelly, Jayne
Mansfield, England's Diana Dors, Eva Marie Saint (his favorite),
Eva Peron, Brigitte Bardot and Marilyn Monroe - to director Alfred
Hitchcock's blonde fixation, Lady Godiva's ride, and the continuing
myth of the blonde.
</P>
<P>
   As Conrad writes in his introduction: ``Blonde women have
stirred, inspired and bedeviled the imaginations of men and women
for centuries.'' If he was to pick his quintessential blonde, he
says, it would be Marilyn. ``Monroe, as far as I'm concerned, was
The Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These books are not my life's work,'' says Conrad, relaxing in
a living room cluttered with the effluvia of his travels and
interests - a massive bison head over his fireplace shot by a
Native American rancher from Montana, numerous artifacts in the
shape of martini glasses, including a cocktail table (complete with
olive under glass), Conrad's paintings of Lucky Strike packs (his
favorite design icon) and a fascinating photograph of William
Burroughs making nice to a Colt .45 (not the beer, the pistol).
</P>
<P>
   ``Graham Greene called his work `novels and entertainments,'
which is how I feel about these books,'' says Conrad. ``They were
done largely for fun and came out of my bachelor habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't,'' he interjects very quickly (maybe too quickly?),
``intend being a bachelor forever.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boy can't help it. There's always a new picture to paint
in the rabbit-warren, roof-top studio he rents eight floors above
Pacific Avenue. Or there is a trip to take, like the one he did in
1994 when he went searching for his roots in the wilds of Montana,
where his ancestors, fugitives from Yale, founded a town called
Conrad before coming to California. And there's always another city
like Paris to explore; he lived in the City of Light for five years
in the `80s.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, a Yalie with the cultured but slightly dangerous mein of
a big-game hunter on sabbatical, says that with ``The Martini,''
``The Cigar'' and now ``The Blonde,'' he is ``tweaking the PC
aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   His subject matter would have been right at home circa 1955 at
the Stork Club in New York. ``Nobody would have thought twice about
it,'' he says. ``My father lived that life and did all that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blonde'' seems to be a natural progression in retro-ship,
given the subjects of his other books. ``The book company asked me
what was next and said, `How `bout Champagne?' Nope, it's been
done. Beer. No. Sex. No. What could I do that wasn't a clichd jump.
The Blonde! Nobody had ever done it.'' (Although now, there are two
books on the market about blondes.)
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's next subject is rum, probably because he can't wait to
get himself down to the Caribbean for ``research.''
</P>
<P>
   The rum thing goes back to when he was living in Paris and was
racked up with a broken jaw for a few months. It was winter, raw
and snowy, but he'd been in all day and felt the need to get some
air. He went out for a jog, took a wrong turn and slipped, falling
into one of Paris' many statues.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, his broken jaw was wired shut. ``I got very
tired of soup,'' he says with a laugh, remembering that he was
fixated on liver and onions and even went so far as to cook them
and puree them so he could drink his dinner.
</P>
<P>
   He began to fantasize about rum, and he started painting after a
long hiatus. One of his pictures: a very green, leafy,
tropical-themed canvas with the word ``RUM'' printed in vivid red.
It'll probably be the next book cover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
