<SLUG> BC-MILLENIAL-GUINNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIAL `GUINNESS' MAKES A BIG DEAL OF TRIVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some believe humankind's infatuation with ersatz knowledge
kicked in around 1970, when pseudo-intellectuals everywhere
embraced the line, ``Love means never having to say you're sorry,''
from Erich Segal's drippy novel ``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Others target the '50s/'60s/'70s explosion of TV quiz shows,
when contestants could win lots of money by proclaiming things like
``Mr. Greenjeans'' in response to the question, ``Who was Captain
Kangaroo's farmer friend?''
</P>
<P>
   But the infatuation with trivial knowledge became a legitimate
pastime on Aug. 27, 1955, when the first volume of the Guinness
Book of Records was published. Leisure-afflicted readers could
suddenly learn who was supposed to have thrown a tennis ball the
farthest and discover the identity of the heaviest 8-year-old in
recorded history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for those who like to know a little about a lot, comes
Guinness World Records 2000: Millennium Edition (Guinness, $25.95).
From the owner of the biggest collection of ``Star Wars'' effluvia
(Jason Joiner of London, over 20,000 movie-related toys) to where
you're most likely to be killed (Bogota, Colombia, with an average
of nearly one homicide an hour), Millennium Edition celebrates
facts and figures that are to knowledge what Twinkies are to
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to remember that the ``records'' presented in any
Guinness publication include only those certified by the
organization. It's entirely possible that somebody has walked a
longer distance than the 33,151 miles strolled by Arthur Blessitt
that is noted in Millennium Edition. But Blessitt's is the longest
walk among those presented to Guinness for record certification.
</P>
<P>
   For those who enjoy posing as masters of the mundane, here's a
trivia test based on items mentioned between Millennium Edition's
silvery, faux-tinfoil covers. Six right is a passing grade; eight
right answers get you an `A.' If you get all 10 correct, our advice
is to get a life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. The most expensive liquor currently available for general
sale is:
</P>
<P>
   A) Wild Turkey 101 distilled in 1960 _ $1,700 a bottle
</P>
<P>
   B) Springbank 1919 Malt Whisky _ $10,800 a bottle
</P>
<P>
   C) Toru Tanaka Celebration Sake _ $21,050 a bottle
</P>
<P>
   D) Glenfiddich Scotch Whisky 1949 _ $79,550 a bottle
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. The highest auction price paid for a letter written by a
currently ``living'' person is:
</P>
<P>
   A) $20,000 for a letter written by Madonna
</P>
<P>
   B) $16,415 for a letter written by Monica Lewinsky
</P>
<P>
   C) $14,850 for a letter written by Frank Sinatra
</P>
<P>
   D) $12,500 for a letter written by Ronald Reagan
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. The world's longest recorded skateboard jump was:
</P>
<P>
   A) 41 feet
</P>
<P>
   B) 30 feet, 9 inches
</P>
<P>
   C) 29 feet, 4 inches
</P>
<P>
   D) 17 feet
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4. Most drinking glasses balanced on one chin at one time:
</P>
<P>
   A) 80
</P>
<P>
   B) 41
</P>
<P>
   C) 22
</P>
<P>
   D) 20
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. The most prolific murderer killed this many people:
</P>
<P>
   A) 931
</P>
<P>
   B) 819
</P>
<P>
   C) 86
</P>
<P>
   D) 44
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   6. The costliest theme park to build (including design and
development) was:
</P>
<P>
   A) Tokyo Disneyland, $1.35 billion
</P>
<P>
   B) Disney's Animal Kingdom, $1 billion
</P>
<P>
   C) Six Flags Over Denver, $795 million
</P>
<P>
   D) Astroworld, $550 million
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The world's most sophisticated toilet'' is identified as
such because:
</P>
<P>
   A) It automatically flushes when the user is done
</P>
<P>
   B) It plays prerecorded cassettes of the user's favorite songs
</P>
<P>
   C) It plays sound effects to drown out embarrassing noises and
expels air freshener after use
</P>
<P>
   D) Its seat automatically is warmed or cooled to 72 degrees
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   8. The longest recorded hiccuping fit lasted from:
</P>
<P>
   A) 1866 to 1941
</P>
<P>
   B) 1930 to 1980
</P>
<P>
   C) 1922 to 1990
</P>
<P>
   D) Four months, 19 days
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   9. The most frequently played country music song in radio
history is:
</P>
<P>
   A) ``I Will Always Love You,'' written by Dolly Parton
</P>
<P>
   B) ``Crazy,'' written by Willie Nelson, performed by Patsy Cline
</P>
<P>
   C) ``By the Time I Get to Phoenix,'' written by Jim Webb,
recorded by Glen Campbell;
</P>
<P>
   D) ``Gentle on My Mind,'' written by John Hartford, recorded by
Glen Campbell
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   10. The fictional character most often portrayed in film is:
</P>
<P>
   A) Sherlock Holmes, 211 films
</P>
<P>
   B) Davy Crockett, 209 films
</P>
<P>
   C) Santa Claus, 188 films
</P>
<P>
   D) Tarzan, 91 films
</P>
<P>
   _ Answers: 1-B; 2-D (The subject of the Reagan letter is Frank
Sinatra, who, yes, is dead); 3-D; 4-A (and there's a photo in the
book to prove it); 5-A (Behram, a member of the Thuggee cult,
between 1790 and 1840); 6-B; 7-C; 8-C; 9-A, C and D are tied at 4
million times each; 10-A (elementary, my dear Watson, and, by the
way, Davy Crockett was ``real.'')
</P>
