<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-FATHER01-COX     11-30 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FATHER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S LATE FATHER AN UNSEEN FORCE IN THE CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his travels across the country in pursuit of the
presidency, Al Gore's constant companion is his father.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since Al Gore Sr. died, the obedient son has rarely
given a speech in which the sometimes stern, always exacting father
is not praised, both as a parent and a politician.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeatedly praises his father's ``great courage'' for
politically unpopular stands against racial segregation in the
South and the U.S. war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But longtime observers suggest that Gore is still trying to win
the approval of a father who was absent during much of his
childhood _ one of the reasons, some believe, that his rhetoric
occasionally strays into overstatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all likelihood, his exaggerations reflect a yearning for a
kind of approval and admiration that he never quite got from his
dad,'' Bob Zelnick, author of ``Gore: A Political Life,'' a highly
critical biography, said in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick cited Gore's overblown claims of his involvement in the
creation of the Internet, of being the sole inspiration for Oliver
Barrett in Eric Segal's novel ``Love Story,'' and of his ``combat''
experience in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't serious character flaws so much as a notion that
he has not accomplished as much as he should have,'' added Zelnick,
a former ABC News correspondent who now lectures at Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's grandiosity about the guy that's always been there,''
Bill Turque, a Newsweek correspondent and author of ``Inventing Al
Gore,'' a biography to be published next March, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the campaign gaffes are ``a reflection of the great
expectations that his parents, and particularly his father, had for
him,'' added Turque. ``The script that his parents wrote for his
life called for him to be heroic and to save the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not the only presidential candidate with a famous
father. Texas Gov. George W. Bush's father was president of the
United States. Sen. John McCain's father was a four-star admiral.
And Steve Forbes's father was a flamboyant magazine publisher and
jet-setter.
</P>
<P>
   Father-son dynamics have long been a part of presidential
politics, but rarely as much as in this campaign. Cambridge, Mass.,
writer and psychotherapist Michael Vincent Miller has called 2000
``the year of the Oedipal presidency,'' with the principal
candidates either ``running to please Dad or to spite Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   But while some in the current presidential field often rebelled
against their fathers in their youth, Gore was the dutiful son _
responsible, conscientious, eager to please.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a student at Harvard during the rebellious 1960s, Gore
``listened to his father,'' said John Tyson, one of Gore's college
friends. ``He emulated him.''
</P>
<P>
   To suggest, though, that Gore's quest for the White House is an
attempt to fulfill his father's own unrealized dreams or to best
his father is a stretch, said Turque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is to reduce him to a stereotype,'' Turque said.
``He's already achieved higher office than his father. He's also
past 50 now, and my sense is that he's worked a lot of these things
out about his father. But there's no question that it's still a
force within him, and that he sometimes still lives within that
view of him that his father had.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gore Sr., a wily larger-than-life Tennessee populist who
entertained voters with speeches and a fiddle, preceded his son in
the House and the Senate. He was elected to the Senate in 1952
after 14 years in the House and nearly won the nod to be Adlai
Stevenson's running mate on the 1956 Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He is still remembered fondly in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   C.D. Owens, an African American clergy leader in Memphis, noted
in a recent introduction of Gore that the vice president ``came
from good stock,'' that his ``great father fought for justice and
human dignity when it was not popular to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gore began grooming his son for a career in politics
almost from birth. And in 1992, when Bill Clinton picked the
younger Gore as his vice presidential running mate, his father
remarked, ``He was raised for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Gore lost his Senate seat in 1970, having taken
unpopular stands against school prayer and the Vietnam War and in
favor of gun control and welfare programs at a time when
conservatism was sweeping New Deal liberalism from the South.
</P>
<P>
   He played a large behind-the-scenes role in his son's first
congressional race, in 1974, and in his son's 1988 campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination. His advice that his son run in
every primary rather than only in targeted states is widely viewed
as hastening the end of the 1988 Gore presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore died last December at the age of 91, just as his son was
getting ready for another White House race, as the frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was the greatest man I ever knew in my life,'' Gore
told the 1,000 mourners who attended the senior Gore's memorial
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the choices you made,'' he added. ``Dad, your
whole life has been an inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
