u l BC-BRITAIN-MARBLES-1201-     11-30 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MARBLES-1201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH DENY RESPONSIBILITY FOR DAMAGE TO GREEK MARBLE
STRUCTURES
 &HT;    (350&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The battle over the Elgin Marbles continued Tuesday as
archaeology experts opened a symposium focusing on damage to the
precious carvings during a cleaning by British technicians in the
late 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was held against the backdrop of a larger dispute
between Britain and Greece over the sculptures, which were removed
from the Parthenon in Athens nearly 200 years ago and brought to
Britain. The 17 figures and section of a 160-yard frieze from the
temple on the summit of the Acropolis are on public display at the
British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium, which continues Wednesday, is an attempt by the
museum to clear the air on the handling of the precious carvings.
It is likely to spur a new round of Greek demands to return the
sculptures taken when Lord Elgin was the British ambassador to the
Ottoman Empire in the early 19th century. The British government
argues that the museum has the marbles legally.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has been accused of defacing the marbles and then
trying to hide the severity of the damage. The museum denies it has
tried to hide anything, and some experts argue that much of the
damage is the result of the sculptures' being 2,500 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen conservation and archaeology specialists met at the
museum in London to examine documents and visual evidence. After an
earlier examination, Greek archaeologists determined that they were
damaged during a cleaning carried out 60 years ago. The sculptures
were scraped and cleaned using wire brushes and copper chisels, the
Greek scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the meeting was intended to be a scholarly exercise,
passions were nevertheless evident. One angry Greek delegate
reportedly yelled: ``You're grabbers. We'll take them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Jenkins, a senior British Museum academic, argued that most
of the damage was the result of weathering atop the Acropolis for
two millennia. Jenkins said that only between 10 and 20 percent of
the damage was caused by the cleaning, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   However, Theodore Skoulikidis, the head of the Greek delegation,
argued that most of missing surface was removed by the British
cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Anderson, the director of the British Museum, said the
museum wants to clear the air on the marbles. ``The purpose of our
conference is to revisit the cleaning of 60 years ago and to
attempt to reach a broad consensus on what happened to the
sculptures,'' Anderson said. ``At the same time we shall look at
wider issues surrounding the cleaning of art works.''
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing the conclusions of a team of experts, Greece's
culture minister on Monday said the precious marbles were severely
damaged. Many of the marble surfaces were smoothed out and stripped
of original details such as chiselled grooves that characterize the
architectural work of the Parthenon. ``There truly was a barbarous
cleaning,'' Elisavet Papazoi told The
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press after reading a Greek report. ``The marbles
were tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain maintains that Elgin acquired the sculptures legally
when Greece was ruled by the Ottomans.
</P>
<P>
   Papazoi stressed that the symposium is ``clearly a scientific
meeting'' and not a deliberation on the marbles' repatriation.
``But we believe and hope that the presentation from the Greek side
of the reality that exists after the 1937-38 cleaning of the
marbles will have some positives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to the Acropolis earlier this month, President
Clinton gave his personal support to Greece's campaign to reclaim
the statues. Britain's Prince Charles also reportedly has voiced
his support.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
