</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TILTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charlene Tilton used to hate tabloid gossips...Now she is one
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Big paychecks are in the past. Limos are long
gone. No one's asking for autographs. But Charlene Tilton still
gets those double takes _ Isn't that? Wasn't she?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she was. But teenage tart Lucy Ewing on the CBS prime-time
soap ``Dallas'' is 40 now. She's a single, working mom who recently
broke show-biz ranks when she signed on as the Boca Raton,
Fla.-based Globe's gossip columnist.
</P>
<P>
   The actress who was savaged weekly by the grocery-store tabloids
during her early '80s slugfest divorce from country singer Johnny
Lee (Looking For Love In All the Wrong Places) is now making her
living as a professional gossip, whose column items include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Natalie Portman freaks out over dog poop''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Maguire beauty wants to bed Beatle Paul''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod Stewart rejects gal, 33 _ she's `too old'''
</P>
<P>
   But she will eat lunch again in Tinsel Town and, in fact, she's
doing it now. She has just finished a Where-are-they-now? interview
with a British TV crew and is having lunch at the private Le
Montrose Hotel dining room. Just off Sunset Strip, it's discreet,
hidden and a favorite of pop and rap groups. Rapper E40 is in the
house, his entourage doing figure-eights in the lobby, jewelry
jingling, as they wheel and deal on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Tilton picks at a Caesar salad, talking about the days when she
made, not reported, tabloid news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was on the cover every week,'' she says. ``It got to
the point it was really difficult. Now I can laugh about it, but
then it wasn't funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilton made her name playing the oft-married, illegitimate
daughter of black sheep Gary Ewing. She stuck with the show from
1978 to '90 with a two-year break in the middle. She left the show
a year before it ended to retreat to the middle-class suburbs and
raise the daughter she had with Johnny Lee. Cherish is now 17,
attends a performing arts high school, and wants to be an actress.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe job, Tilton begins, ``is an interesting way to
reintroduce and reinvent myself. It's never been done to have an
actor, celebrity, do a column for a tabloid.'' She has no idea if
it will cost her possible acting jobs. ``It remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   She told her editors not to expect sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I want to do anything that's slanderous or
malicious or mean-spirited or sarcastic. It's not my nature, I
don't believe in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The British TV crew that paid Tilton union scale (that's counted
in hundreds, not thousands) for an interview finds her in the
hotel's dining room. They had interviewed Tilton, Linda Gray and
Patrick Duffy separately and now they want to stir up bad blood
``Dallas''-style. They want `Lucy' to pop into the lobby _ cameras
rolling _ and reunite with former ``Dallas'' stablemate ``Sue
Ellen,'' whom she hasn't talked to in several years.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tilton leaves the table, she swears there's no animosity
between her and Gray. She blasts into the lobby, scattering E40's
people. They stop talking on their phones long enough to figure out
why a buxom blonde is rushing, calling to an older woman who's
leaving the hotel with an entire wardrobe slung over her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The shocked look and quick recovery on Gray's face could have
been a scene from ``Dallas'' _ Sue Ellen seeing middle-aged Lucy
coming at her. The Brits are ecstatic with the impromptu ambush.
</P>
<P>
   But any ``Dallas'' bad blood that once boiled in Tilton has
simmered to steam. Producers didn't invite her back for the
``Dallas'' reunion movies in 1996 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pissed, really mad,'' she says, returning to her salad.
``It was odd, but what can you do? But actually, it was probably
better. My God, can you imagine Lucy, 80 years old in a hayloft
with the foreman? Not a pretty picture.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tilton left the show, she worked occasionally, mostly bad
movies. Silence of the Hams, Deadly Bet, Ragin' Cajun, Border
Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   She did land a few good jobs, such as London stagework in Who's
Afraid of Virginia Woolf? (1990).
</P>
<P>
   When Tilton recently decided to get back into acting and hire an
agent, she hit the harsh reality of limited roles for women who are
closer in age to 50 than 30. ``My agent submitted me for a part to
play a mother and they said, `We don't see her as a mother.' I am a
mother. That's all I am,'' she says, delighting in the irony.
</P>
<P>
   She did land a job in the John Travolta-produced feature Bar
Hopping, not yet out. ``It's a comedy based on L.A. bar life. I
play an aging, bitter actress,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Tilton, who never met her father, is a second-generation mom
devoted to her daughter. Her mother, Katherine, 78, worked as a
single mom, a secretary at an insurance agency. She did the best
she could, but Tilton is never far from the memories of shabby
Hollywood apartments.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Dallas,'' the money went fast _ ``Bad investments. I
trusted the wrong people. I took care of my mom and she had a lot
of health problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilton says it was a no-brainer trading career for family. ``I'm
a great daughter to my mother. And, I am a great mother who has
raised an unbelievably productive, kind-hearted, compassionate
member of society.''
</P>
<P>
   She's convincing when she says she has no regrets, doesn't miss
the always-new Mercedes or the jewelry she was fond of flaunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lifestyle changed, but it's actually better,'' she says.
``I need one car (she drives a Prelude), I don't need three cars.
To me, my career was what I did, it's not who I am. I am my
daughter's mother. I think that there's a big difference. People
might look at my house and say, 'Oh, she's not successful.' Maybe I
don't have as much money as the next person, but I am
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   And she's convinced that Cherish will hit big in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so talented, so dedicated. She'll make it. She'll be
starring on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom and daughter take dance lessons together. Mom advises
daughter on auditions, helps with scripts. Mom won't let daughter
get a driver license yet. ``It depends on grades,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   One perk that goes with the Globe job is that Tilton is back on
the party circuit. ``I was out of that so long.'' But only if there
are no mom duties to be done. ``We get up at 6. She goes to a
performing arts school. I pick her up, we get home at 7. She has
two hours of homework a night, at least. I make dinner. That's our
life. Cherish is my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, too. It's college day at Cherish's high school. Mom has
to return where there are no spotlights or applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go to the bank,'' she says. ``Stop at my mom's. Go
home and do laundry and help Cherish with her homework. She has an
essay due. I'll get her to bed early.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 17 and I still make her lunch every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: paullomartire(at)pbpost.com. Dorothy Shea contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
