<HEADER>
A5274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WASHEDUP-ACTORS-COX     11-30 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHEDUP-ACTORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few TV stars have enough versatility to create back-to-back hits
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One of the fastest ways to fail in the
prime-time TV game is to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Actors who come off a big hit rarely follow up the success with
another hit. Think of prime-time actors in recent hits.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you saw Rob Morrow (''Northern
Exposure''), Gary Burghoff (''MASH'') or Delta Burke (''Designing
Women'')?
</P>
<P>
   You need an old TV pro to explain the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why,'' says Eddie Foy III, a casting director
since 1962. For prime-time series TV, ``writers, producers and
directors write the material for the limitations or expansions of
that character and that person. You write to their ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike TV, where a role is contoured to the actor, stage and
film work requires that actors fit the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your job once you have gotten the (movie or stage) role is to
bring the role to life,'' Foy says. ``The role has breadth, the
role has passion. But it happens to be sitting on an inanimate
object called paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Foy, 64, is the son of an actor and grandson of a legendary
vaudevillian. He's been casting top TV shows going back to ``The
Monkees'', ``The Donna Reed Show'' and ``Barney Miller.'' He was
the casting boss at both ABC and NBC and his film credits include
``MASH'' and ``The Posiden Adventure.'' He is currently the casting
director for Dick Clark Productions and has been casting the Jerry
Lewis Labor Day Telethon since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Actors coming off a TV hit, Foy suggests, must get back to
studying acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that they don't have talent, it's just that they've
gotten pigeon-holed into doing something, and from there you've got
problems. They can't handle the other stuff. And you know what's so
sad? It happens mostly with children.''
</P>
<P>
   Foy concludes, ``when you take a cast from Show A that has good
looking and pretty people who are minimal in their talent but
within the scope of what they're doing, they're wonderful, that's
great. But then all of a sudden, they're canceled, where do they
go?''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
