<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SUSHITREND-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSHITREND-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 The Latest American Food Craze _ Sushi   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  California rolls have nudged aside chicken nuggets
on lunch trays in Palo Alto schools. At Wolfe's Lunch in San
Francisco, truckers order sushi instead of cheeseburgers. And on
bar mitzvah buffets throughout the Bay Area, sushi trays threaten
to crowd out traditional challah.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like pizza and tacos before it, the Japanese delicacy that
combines seasoned rice with bites of fish and vegetables is the
latest food import to go mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   First created some 1,300 years ago, sushi has shown up in such a
variety of places over the past year that it has become the great
American equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers take it to school. Young dot-com workers wait in line
for hours to get into San Francisco's hippest sushi bars.
Homemakers eat it on the run. Construction workers pack it in their
lunch pails. A cosmetic company even named a nail polish ``sushi.''
</P>
<P>
   Sushi's popularity reflects the nation's obsession with eating
healthier, people in the business say. But it also reflects
America's constantly evolving ethnic makeup and palate.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Americans make up about 12 percent of the United
State's 10 million people of Asian ancestry. In the early 1990s,
when the first of two recessions hit Japan, the number of Japanese
immigrants increased sharply to about 10,000 a year, said Karl
Matsushita of the Japanese-American National Library in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   That gave American sushi bars a bump in business, but he and
others say it's not why sushi has become so popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because of the Caucasians as much as Japanese,''
said Matsushita. ``I don't think they're interested in Japanese
culture. They think it's a health food and it doesn't taste bad.
All my friends who I went to college with are popping sushi like
doughnuts. It seems like it happened overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sushi crosses all sorts of other ethnic boundaries. San Mateo
mother Lisa Murphy says her 10-year-old daughter, who is Caucasian,
gingerly considers trading her peanut butter and jelly sandwiches
with Japanese-American school chums who bring sushi for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lunches are absolutely beautiful, traditional sushi,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Korean family runs Wolfe's Lunch, a classic diner in San
Francisco's Potrero Hill district. They added sushi to their
regular menu of bacon, eggs and burgers a few years ago. They also
sell Korean dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area, especially with the ethnic influence, is
changing, so you have all kinds of people in the area that
influence the taste,'' said Allen Kim, whose parents bought the
diner in 1979. ``It's a natural for us to serve sushi along with
the typical diner food. It's the American way, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 90 percent of all the new Japanese restaurants that open
in the Bay Area will feature sushi, said Takehiko Yasuda, president
of the California Japanese Restaurant Association, which represents
120 restuarants. That's up from 70 percent a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico's supermarkets began selling sushi in its Stanford
store about three years ago. It caught on quickly in San Francisco,
Berkeley and Los Altos Andronico's, and now the Danville store
sells more sushi than any other, President and CEO Bill Andronico
said.
</P>
<P>
   At International Marine Products, a San Mateo-based fish
wholesaler that provides top-grade fish to restaurants and
food-service companies, business is so good that the number of
employees has almost doubled in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got sushi bars all along the way from here to the
Sierras and Reno,'' said assistant branch manager Glenn Sakata.
``Even Fairfield and Truckee _ places you'd never really imagine
there'd be a sushi bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a matter of taste or a concern about bacteria and
parasites in raw fish, new sushi eaters aren't necessarily shoving
down pieces of nigiri or other uncooked styles of sushi. Rather,
they're eating California rolls with avocado and cooked crab or
other versions that feature vegetables or cooked shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Because more than 90 percent of raw fish eaten in the United
States is first frozen to kill parasites and bacteria, it's
relatively safe, according to the Food and Drug Administration. But
raw fish is not recommended for elderly, young children, people
with cancer, liver disease or compromised immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Alva Spence, food service manager for the Palo Alto Unified
School District, said that's why raw fish isn't part of the school
menu.
</P>
<P>
   But students, who made it clear in a Girl Scout food survey that
they wanted sushi at school, eat plenty of California or vegetarian
rolls. Five pieces sell for $1.90 _ milk, salad and fruit included.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very popular, which I think surprised a lot of
people,'' Spence said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, sushi enjoyed its first wave of popularity
among Yuppies in the 1980s. That trend gave birth to upscale,
Americanized sushi bars like SoMa's Blowfish and Tokyo Go Go in the
Mission District, both of which opened in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   But sushi's appeal has spread beyond the young and trendy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you believe now older people are eating sushi?'' said
sushi chef Steve Fuji of Ebisu in San Francisco. ``An 83-year-old
came in and said she tried it the first time three months ago and
now has to have it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even teenagers like Oakland's Sam Eckhouse are running to the
sushi bar instead of to Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother got me into it when I was 10 or so,'' says
Eckhouse, a 16-year-old high school student who eats sushi about
once a month _ or whenever he can afford it. ``It's not like most
food. There's a lot of flavor and variety to choose from. It's like
an art.''
</P>
<P>
   California, the birthplace some 20 years ago of the top-selling
California roll, is leading the nation's broad new fascination with
sushi. The rest of the country is catching up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 18 months it's been a quickly growing trend. Now
it's everywhere _ Costco even,'' said Lisa McCue, spokesperson for
the Grocery Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in sushi is turning up in the most unexpected parts of
the country. Last summer, Lawrence Pong, principal environmental
health inspector for the San Francisco Department of Public,
presented a seminar on how to safely prepare sushi and other Asian
food at health conferences in Tennessee and Denver. The seminars
were the first of their kind, Pong said.
</P>
<P>
   Want more proof that sushi is on the rise among America's
lunch-bucket set?
</P>
<P>
   _ The October issue of ``Restaurants and Institutions,'' a
magazine read by foodservice workers in schools, military bases and
prisons, named sushi as a rising star, based on a survey of
food-service menus around the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Advanced Fresh Concepts, a California sushi franchise,
reported this year that it had opened sushi counters in more than
500 supermarkets in the United States and Canada. Two of their
Michigan stores pull in as much as $4,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the International Dairy Deli Bakery Association, a
1,200-member organization based in Wisconsin, the Japanese staple
has generated more inquiries and revenue from stores this year than
ever before, said spokesman lan Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We here in the Midwest have the perception it is more popular
where you are. But it holds a lot of interest with people here _
not the raw stuff, though,'' he said. ``In this country, I don't
think raw fish will ever be that popular.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A Historical Timeline of Sushi in America &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tracing exactly how and when Americans made sushi their own is
something of an inexact science. In many ways, food scholars and
cultural anthropologists say, it is the pizza of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and '30s, Italian immigrants had just begun opening
small pizzerias. The food they served was considered very exotic,
said Bertram Gordon, a food historian and acting provost at Mills
College in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   GIs who ate pizza in Italy during World War II helped popularize
the version being baked in America. Then, when more Americans began
traveling to Europe in the 1950s, Italian food became even more
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   After a few decades of Americanization, pizza with all sorts of
very un-Italian toppings like pineapple and ham, became de rigueur.
Today, pizza parlors are as ubiquitous as hamburger stands.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi is on the same trajectory, Gordon says. As part of a
research project, he searched through the Readers' Guide to
Periodical Literature, which reflects popular culture from 1890 to
present. Sushi was first mentioned in the popular press in the
United States in 1964. But it remained largely an exotic food until
the '80s, when eating it became a Yuppie badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   The trend was fueled by an increase in business and culture
exchanges between America and Japan in the 1980s, according to
Bertram and sushi experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese (culture) got popular after `Shogun,' the TV show,''
said sushi chef Steve Fuji of Ebisu in San Francisco. The series
ran in 1980. ``After that, there was a boom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
