 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Panelists Belly Up to Supermarket Sushi   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As the sushi craze continues, more markets are
carrying premade sushi in their refrigerator cases. Most markets
contract a company to make the sushi for them, but many of these
companies have employees in each market making the sushi throughout
the day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But how good is it? Today's panel tasted five California rolls _
cucumber, avocado and crab (either real or faux) wrapped in seaweed
and rice _ available at local markets. Most come six pieces to a
package and cost $3.19-$5.75 per package.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the tasters were not impressed. The biggest complaint
was the fishy flavor of many of the rolls, although the rolls were
bought at the stores the morning of the tasting.
</P>
<P>
   First place went overwhelmingly to  &UR; AFC &LR;  (seven ounces,
$3.95-$4.50 at many supermarkets), the brand found most frequently
at Bay Area grocers. Two panelists commented on the fresh look and
taste; one particularly liked the flavor of the sesame seeds. Two
would buy it, two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andronico's &LR;  (six pieces, $4.99 at Andronico's) came in second.
Andronico's hires its own sushi-makers rather than contracting with
an outside company. One panelist thought the flavor was decent,
while another liked the ratio of rice to crab. But others thought
the crab tasted overwhelmingly fishy and fake. One would buy it,
one might buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kikka &LR;  (seven ounces, $5.75 at Whole Foods), came in third,
just five points below Andronico's. Kikka is the only brand that
claims to use fresh crab, rather than the standard imitation
product. Two panelists noted an unpleasant fishy flavor, although
one conceded that the other elements of the roll were fine. One
might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Koho &LR;  (six pieces, $4.99 at Safeway) came in fourth, but
panelists were divided. One described it as ``tasting a lot better
than it looks.'' Others objected to the avocado, which was turning
brown, and the crab, which they described as dry and stringy. One
might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kami &LR;  (10 ounces, $3.19 at Trader Joe's) was fifth. Three
panelists thought the filling was more like crab salad than the
traditional center of a California roll. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe for All
Seasons, San Francisco; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
