 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This round-up column will make practical sense
of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering
offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your
plate. &HT;       
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: Chew Your Sushi Well... Tiny Travelers Enjoy 
 Sushi, Too  By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Seafood accounts for about 15 to 20 percent of all
food-poisoning outbreaks in the United States every year.
<P>
   Health experts don't know how many of those cases are related to
eating raw fish in sushi, but Lawrence Pong, principal inspector
for the San Francisco Department of Public Health, isn't too
worried about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risks? Not much,'' he says. That's because most of the raw
seafood used in sushi is blast frozen to minus 31 degrees for 15
hours, or minus 10 degrees for seven days, as per Food and Drug
Administration's 1990 recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger concern, he says, is hepatitis A. The Bay Area is six
years into a serious outbreak of the virus, which can be
transmitted when cold or uncooked foods are handled by people who
have not properly washed their hands after using the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Improperly handled raw fish can also carry a host of nasty but
rare bugs. Chief among them are bacteria and a thin round worm
called anisakid nematode. The worms live in marine mammals and are
picked up by fish that come in contact with the mammals or their
excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Freezing kills the worms. So does chewing. Seafood safety expert
Bob Price at the University of California at Davis says that
nationwide about a half dozen cases of people coughing up a
nematode are recorded each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't have chewed their sushi very thoroughly,'' he says.
``If you cough it up, it doesn't hurt you, but it turns you off to
sashimi.''
</P>
<P>
   If the worms aren't killed by freezing, chewing or cooking or if
they aren't removed through visual inspection, they can lodge in
the intestinal wall. Only about 10 such cases are recorded in the
United States each year. But many incidents might go undetected
because people get sick but cough up the worm before it burrows in,
says Janet McDonald, a Bay Area spokesperson for the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA recommends that the elderly or people with cancer, liver
disease or compromised immune systems avoid all raw seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not only because of the parasites but the fact that
freezing does not kill bacteria or viruses,'' McDonald says. ``Add
problems from the food handler and you'd have no barrier because
it's not going to be cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinating raw fish in citrus juice or vinegar _ as in ceviche _
does not kill all the bacteria and parasites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lime juice only makes them angry. That's why they thrash
around,'' says the health department's Pong, who advises people to
visually examine any raw seafood for worms before they eat it.
</P>
<P>
   Some raw seafood is safer than others. Shellfish are potentially
the most dangerous because they most readily absorb whatever toxins
or bacteria are in the water. Freshwater fish, which can harbor
lung flukes, tapeworms and pathogens from human waste, are next on
the list. Deep seawater fish such as tuna have the smallest chance
of infestation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is if you want to eat sushi and sashimi, stick with
open water fish like the tunas that don't come close to marine
mammal populations,'' says Price of UC Davis.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check the Food and Drug Administration's
Web site at  &LR; www.cfsan.fda.gov. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
