 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Le Colonial's Italian Ice Adorns Fresh 
 Oysters   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  It doesn't happen often, but once in a while a
dish comes along that is so clever and makes such good sense that
you wonder why everyone doesn't do it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm talking about the Chile, Lime and Mint Granita that is
spooned over fresh oysters at Le Colonial, the chic Vietnamese
restaurant that took over the spot that once housed Trader Vic's.
</P>
<P>
   A spoon of this intensely flavored ice not only keeps the
oysters chilled, but as it melts it creates a delicious sauce that
pools in the shells. The combination of chile, lime and just a hint
of mint is a miraculous pairing with the oysters.
</P>
<P>
   The dish is also perfect for the environment of Le Colonial _
with gently swirling fans, delicate palm trees and rattan
furniture, it looks like a French-inspired tropical plantation.
</P>
<P>
   As you eat the oysters you practically feel the balmy nights and
gentle breezes _ quite a feat in December in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Le Colonial, 20 Cosmo Place (off Taylor, between Post and &LR; 
 &LR; Sutter streets), San Francisco; (415) 931-3600. Lunch weekdays, &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _  &UR; The granita. &LR;  This spicy-icy mixture keeps the oysters chilled
and adds a burst of flavor so you don't need any other sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Stirring the mixture. &LR;  Stirring and breaking up the ice
crystals as the granita freezes helps to form lighter, ``shaved
ice'' flakes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OYSTERS WITH CHILE, LIME &AMP; MINT GRANITA
</P>
<P>
   The granita is best when made the day before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 mint sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Asian fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chile-garlic sauce (sambal olek)
</P>
<P>
   24 oysters, shucked and arranged on a bed of crushed ice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring the water to a boil in a small pot and add the mint.
Reduce heat and simmer until the liquid reduces by half.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and add the lime juice, sugar and fish sauce.
Stir the mixture until the sugar dissolves. Discard the mint
sprigs. Add the chile-garlic sauce and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the mixture to a stainless-steel or glass pan and place
in the freezer. Whisk the mixture every 10 to 20 minutes and
continue to freeze until mixture is consistency of shaved ice,
about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Break up crystals and whisk before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Top each oyster with a tablespoon of the granita and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 210 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 20 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 5 g fat (1 g saturated), 110 mg cholesterol, 937 mg
sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
