<SLUG> BC-LEARN-QUICHE-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;       
 LEARNING TO COOK: Old Favorite Slips Into Busy Holiday Lifestyle 
 &HT;     By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  This is the time of year when quiche Lorraine
shines. It is quick, simple to make and a soothing dish for lunch
or supper around the holidays.
<P>
   Quiche Lorraine is just one of a number of wonderful recipes
that have become forgotten classics. My friend Sharon Kramis
recently gave me her recipe for quiche, which consists of a savory
(nonsweet) custard, made of eggs and rich milk, and grated Gruyere
cheese baked in a tart shell.
</P>
<P>
   This basic recipe may be varied by adding one or two of the
following: bits of cooked bacon, sliced mushrooms, diced ham,
chopped cooked onion, or just about anything you like.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to make a version using grated Gruyere and cooked
chopped bacon _ and I skipped the tart shell. I sprinkled the
cheese and bacon into a buttered 8-inch pie plate, then I carefully
poured in the custard and popped it into the oven. It baked in just
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While it was baking I toasted some thin slices of rye bread to
serve with it. Since the quiche did not have a crust, the toast
provided a pleasant crispy contrast to the silken custard.
</P>
<P>
   I also made Sharon's relish/salad, which provided the perfect
crunchy/ tart balance to the quiche. To make it, chop 3 celery
stalks and 2 cored but unpeeled apples. Toss them with a dressing
made of 4 tablespoons olive oil, 11/2 tablespoons rice vinegar and
a little salt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUICHE LORRAINE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 slices of bacon (optional)
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce chunk Gruyere cheese (11/2 cups grated)
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Butter an 8-inch pie pan (one
that holds 2 cups liquid).
</P>
<P>
   Separate the slices of bacon and stack them evenly on top of
each other. Cut them into 1/2-inch slices crosswise.
</P>
<P>
   Put a skillet on the stove and turn the heat to medium. Separate
the little slices of bacon and spread them in one layer in the
skillet. Cook, turning them over after 2 or 3 minutes. Cook the way
you like bacon, soft or crisp. When the bacon looks brown around
the edges it is almost to the crisp stage. Using a fork, lift the
pieces of bacon from the skillet and place on paper towels to
drain. Pat the bacon with paper towels to sop up the fat. Set the
bacon pieces aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using a hand grater, grate 11/2 cups cheese onto a piece of wax
paper. Press the grated cheese into a measuring cup, it doesn't
need to be packed firmly, but press a little so you have a generous
amount of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mixing the custard:  &LR; Crack the eggs into 1-quart mixing bowl or
a quart liquid measuring cup. Add the half-and-half and, using a
fork or rotary beater, briskly beat the milk and eggs until they
are well blended and a homogeneous color. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Assembling the quiche:  &LR; Spread the bacon pieces over the bottom
of the buttered pie pan. Sprinkle the grated cheese evenly over the
bacon, then carefully pour in the egg mixture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Baking the quiche:  &LR; Put the quiche into the oven and bake for
20 minutes. Test for doneness by inserting the blade of a table
knife into the center of the custard. If it comes out clean _ no
uncooked egg clinging to it _ it is done. Remove the pan from the
oven and let sit for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut into four equal wedges and, using a spatula, gently lift
each wedge onto a serving plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 470 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 38 g fat (20 g saturated), 313 mg cholesterol, 420 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5286 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-TORTILLA-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 1995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORTILLA-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Reviving a Tortilla Tradition  
 By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NAPA, Calif. _ &LR;  For Americans accustomed to storebought,
preservative-laden corn tortillas, a fresh tortilla made with
just-ground corn is a taste revelation.
<P>
   That's why Rick Bayless, the noted restaurateur and Mexican food
authority, insisted on serving only fresh tortillas when 400 people
gathered for a Mexican food conference at the Culinary Institute of
America at Greystone last month. Bayless agreed to be conference
chair only when the CIA agreed to grind the corn and make the
tortillas on the St. Helena premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light goes on in people's eyes when they taste a fresh
corn tortilla,'' says Bayless, who operates Frontera Grill and
Topolobampo in Chicago. ``It is the very heart of Mexican life. If
I have one crusade in my life, it is the crusade for fresh masa.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh masa _ the soft, buff-colored dough used for tortillas _
took center stage at the conference, an educational gathering for
food professionals. But as attendees learned, the sweet-smelling
fresh masa from ground  &LR; mixtamal &LR;  (partially-cooked dried corn) is
losing ground at the Mexican table. Few modern Mexican women have
time to soak dried corn and take it to the mill as they used to.
Instead, tortilla production, both at home and in factories,
increasingly relies on an inferior dough made with the dehydrated,
flourlike masa known as masa harina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corn tortillas made with (masa harina) may look the same, but
they don't taste of anything and they're not as soft,'' says Diana
Kennedy, renowned Mexican food authority and conference keynote
speaker. Kennedy blamed Maseca, the country's largest producer of
dehydrated masa, for accelerating the disappearance of dried corn
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   With Maseca, a cook just adds water. In contrast, dried corn
must be treated with lye to soften the skin, partially cooked,
steeped for several hours, then well-rinsed before it is milled or
ground by hand on a basalt  &LR; metate &LR;  (grinding stone). As she has
done countless times for her large family and her customers at
Tlamanalli, her restaurant in rural Oaxaca, Abigail Mendoza Ruiz
got down on her knees at the conference, picked up a stone rolling
pin, and painstakingly crushed mixtamal into masa on her sloped
metate. To make tortillas this way for her family can take three
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that Mexican women eventually embraced the mills
that sprung up in the early 20th century. Distrustful at first that
a machine could do the work of their muscular shoulders and
forearms, most women finally relegated their metates to special
occasion use. While the industrialization of tortilla-making has
liberated Mexican women, it has also threatened to drive out the
real thing _ the seductively corn-scented, mixtamal-based,
preservative-free fresh tortilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cheating the Mexican public of their rightful diet,''
Kennedy says.
</P>
<P>
   To produce the nearly 7,000 fresh corn tortillas that attendees
ate over 21/2 days, conference organizers turned to San Leandro's
Mi Rancho Tortilla Factory, which set up a commercial stone grinder
on the school grounds. A dozen Napa Valley Latina women were
pressed into service to knead, shape, press and bake the mountains
of soft, fresh masa.
</P>
<P>
   Lined up behind gas-fired griddles, with square wooden presses
that many had brought from Mexico, the women worked as smoothly as
ballroom dancers who no longer have to think about the steps. As
they chatted and laughed, their hands scooped up balls of masa,
shaped them into rounds, pressed them into perfect circles, and
then, with a graceful sweep of the arm, laid them across the hot
griddle. With bare fingers, they flipped the tortillas once, then
again, then prodded them with fingertips to get them to puff like
pita bread. When you can get them to puff, the women say, you're
ready for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Yolanda Tierrafria of Napa Valley's Mi Fiesta Catering
showed a reporter how to make tortillas on a home gas stove, using
fresh masa, a hinged metal press and a metal  &LR; comal &LR;  (griddle).
Several clumsy attempts _ made more frustrating when the caterer
announced that youngsters master the technique right away _ evolved
into some modestly respectable specimens, including a few that
might qualify the maker for marriage. Tierrafria herself can make
80 to 100 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   A fresh tortilla, smelling powerfully of toasted corn, begs to
be eaten hot off the comal with an all-American swipe of butter and
salt. Mexicans are more restrained, however. The hot tortillas are
transferred to napkin-lined baskets _ not stacked inside, warns
Tierrafria, but loosely overlapping, like the petals of a flower.
At the table, they embrace taco fillings and soak up silky moles
and chile-based sauces. Day old, they're fried and topped with
shredded meat or beans, lettuce and salsa; or dipped in chile
sauce, softened in hot oil, then wrapped around cheese to make
authentic enchiladas.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh tortilla, like rice in Asia, is the unseasoned staple
that underlies Mexico's entire culinary tradition. ``It's a spoon,
it's a plate, it's a food,'' says Susana Trilling, a cooking school
owner in Oaxaca who taught at the conference. ``It really is
everything in the Mexican kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How to Make Fresh Tortillas &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You will need fresh masa, a heavy tortilla press, a comal or
griddle and plastic wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Knead the masa to test its consistency. It should be smooth,
soft and malleable, like a very soft bread dough; when you form a
clump of masa into a ball, the dough should clean your hands. Add a
little lukewarm water if the masa is too dry. (If your tortillas
crack around the edges as they cook, your masa is too dry.) Add
water cautiously; too much water will make a sticky, tacky masa
that can't be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the comal or griddle several minutes over moderate heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cut two squares of plastic wrap large enough to overhang the
tortilla press slightly. Put one square on the bottom plate of the
press.
</P>
<P>
   Take a clump of masa about the size of a golf ball. Shape it
into a ball between your hands. Place the ball in the center of the
plastic-lined plate of the press and flatten the ball slightly with
your palm. Top with the second square of plastic, then close the
press and use the lever to gently but firmly press the masa into a
thin round. If you press too hard, the tortilla will be too thin
and impossible to get off the plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Open the press and lift off the top square of plastic. Place
your left hand (if you are right-handed) palm down over the right
half of the tortilla. Lift up on the plastic to release the
tortilla from the press, then invert your palm so that half the
tortilla is hanging off the right side of your hand. Carefully
remove the second sheet of plastic. Put your right hand, palm up,
under the hanging tortilla half. Lift up to disengage the tortilla
from your left hand. Now the tortilla is in your right hand with
the left half of it hanging.
</P>
<P>
   Standing over the hot comal, lay the tortilla on it with a
sweeping gesture. Your hand should move away from your body as you
lay the tortilla down without inverting it.
</P>
<P>
   Let the tortilla cook until the edges begin to brown, less than
one minute. With your thumb, carefully lift an edge and flip the
tortilla. If you move swiftly, you will not burn your fingers. Cook
tortilla on the second side until it is marked with brown freckles
and no longer looks moist, about 45 seconds more, then flip again.
</P>
<P>
   Firmly press the tortilla with your fingertips to encourage it
to puff, the sign of a well-made tortilla. When it puffs _ usually
within a few seconds _ the tortilla is ready. It may refuse to
puff, but don't worry; it will still be delicious. Transfer to a
napkin-lined basket, placing it puffed side down. Repeat with
remaining masa.
</P>
<P>
   As you improve your technique, you will be able to cook several
tortillas at once.
</P>
<P>
   One pound of fresh masa will make about one dozen 6-inch
tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; YOLANDA'S ENCHILADAS, GUANAJUATO-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   From Yolanda Tierrafria of Napa Valley's Mi Fiesta Catering
Company.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Salsa
</P>
<P>
   1 pasilla chile, seeds and veins removed
</P>
<P>
   3 cascabel or New Mexico chiles, seeds and veins removed
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Mexican oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   1 heart of romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   7 small yellow-fleshed potatoes, peeled and coarsely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 pound Mexican-style longaniza sausage (similar to chorizo)
</P>
<P>
   12 day-old corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   3 cups grated queso fresco (Mexican-style fresh cheese) mixed
with 1/2 cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   Garnish
</P>
<P>
   12 trimmed radishes
</P>
<P>
   12 chiles en vinagre (pickled chiles)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the salsa:  &LR; Place the chiles in a blender; add the
garlic, oregano, cumin seed and salt. Puree with enough hot water
to make a thin, completely smooth salsa. Set aside in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The enchiladas:  &LR; Decorate a large platter with 6 unblemished
romaine leaves. Finely shred the remaining romaine with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the vegetable oil in a large skillet over moderately high
heat. Add the potatoes and carrot. Cover, reduce heat to moderate,
and cook until slightly softened, about 5 minutes. Remove the
sausage from its casing and add to the skillet, breaking it into
large chunks. Cover and cook until the vegetables are tender,
uncovering occasionally to break up the sausage further with a
wooden spoon. Using a slotted spoon, remove the contents of the
skillet to a plate, leaving any fat behind.
</P>
<P>
   Working with one tortilla at a time, dip tortilla in salsa until
lightly coated all over, then add to the skillet. Fry on both sides
until the tortilla softens, about 10 seconds per side.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a plate, fill with a generous 1/4 cup cheese/onion
mixture, roll and set on the romaine-garnished platter. Repeat with
remaining tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Top the tortillas with the sauteed vegetable/sausage mixture.
Garnish the platter with shredded romaine, radishes and pickled
chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 605 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 66 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 29 g fat (13 g saturated), 60 mg cholesterol, 892
mg sodium, 6 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; YOLANDA'S CHEESE ENCHILADAS
</P>
<P>
   From Yolanda Tierrafria of Napa Valley's Mi Fiesta Catering
Company. Serve with Mexican-style red rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Salsa
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato
</P>
<P>
   2 cascabel or New Mexico chiles, seeds and veins removed
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   The Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   6 day-old corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups finely grated queso fresco (Mexican-style fresh
cheese) or cheddar mixed with 1/4 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   Garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup finely grated queso fresco or cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 cups finely shredded romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the salsa:  &LR; Combine the tomato, chiles, garlic, cumin
and black pepper in a blender and puree until completely smooth.
Heat the oil in a small skillet over moderate heat. Add the tomato
puree and simmer for 5 minutes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The enchiladas:  &LR; Heat the oil in a large skillet over
moderately high heat. Working with one tortilla at a time, fry
tortillas quickly on both sides just until softened, about 5
seconds per side. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the salsa to a simmer. Working with one tortilla at a
time, dip tortillas in sauce briefly, then transfer to a plate,
fill with the cheese/onion mixture and roll. Transfer to a serving
platter.
</P>
<P>
   Top with some of the remaining salsa, then with the 1/3 cup
cheese. Garnish the platter with shredded romaine.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 585 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 34 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 42 g fat (15 g saturated), 63 mg cholesterol, 379
mg sodium, 6 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
