<HEADLINE>
'99 
 &HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Great Expectations for Last Harvest of Vintage  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Never a dull moment about sums up Vintage 1999 for
most of the wine world. Even with the impact of El Ni &LR; n &LR; o and La
Ni &LR; n &LR; a, the wine-grape harvest in the Northern Hemisphere was, in
the words of Sonoma winegrower Marimar Torres, ``Late, small and
great.''
<P>
   High expectations for a quality vintage were evident early in
the year, when Southern Hemisphere vintners brought in the 1999
harvest. Australian vintners are hailing 1999 as one of their best
in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great year to finish off the decade, century and
millennium,'' says Wayne Stehbens of Katnook Estate in Coonawarra,
South Australia. Chile reports low yields, as much as 50 percent
below normal by some estimates, but ``incredible quality,'' says
Don Baker, winemaker for Vinas de la Calina. Similar reports of
excellent quality come from Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   With a late harvest just ending, California growers and
winemakers are already excited about the high quality. At the 1999
Vintage Press Conference in San Francisco, California Wine
Institute president and CEO John De Luca said, ``The effects of La
Ni &LR; n &LR; a created a long, cool growing season and a late harvest that
produced normal to lighter yields per acre.''
</P>
<P>
   How light? Estimates are running to 20 percent below average, or
between 2.5 million to 2.9 million tons of wine grapes for the
state. In contrast, 1998, a cool, wet year hit hard by El Ni &LR; n &LR; o,
recorded 2.53 million tons of wine grapes. Both vintages lagged
behind the record 2.89 million tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A late vintage also encourages nail biting among growers and
winemakers, who worry about frost. In most parts of the state, the
vintage was late by as much as a month, with the harvest still
under way in some parts of the South Central Coast.
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean in terms of grape quality? De Luca says,
``The longer hang time for the grapes concentrated the fruit
flavors and deepened the colors _ quality marks for an exceptional
vintage.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres also leans to superlatives like ``great'' and
``outstanding'' to describe the quality she and her winemaker, Bill
Dyer, are seeing from the 1999 Sonoma County vintage. According to
Torres, quantities of 1999 Marimar Torres Estate Pinot Noir and
Chardonnay will be small, but the quality will be outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the second largest wine producing state in the
country, some winemakers are calling 1999 the best ever. According
to the Washington Association of Wine Grape Growers, this year
marked the state's second largest harvest _ 65,000 tons _ which was
the result of exceptionally warm, dry days during fall and is
expected to result in wines of high quality.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, usually bothered by rains at harvest, experienced warm,
dry days during harvest, turning what was expected to be a very
good vintage into one that's hoped to be exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Europe Vintage 1999
</P>
<P>
   Across Western Europe, raves for the quality of the 1999 vintage
are piling up. It's the sixth excellent vintage this decade,
especially for Italian red wines.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Gaja, one of the leading wine producers of Piedmont in
Northern Italy, rates 1999 as excellent and the quantity of the
harvest as very good. ``The climate conditions produced superb
grapes for all the red varieties and for Nebbiolo from Barbaresco
and Barolo in particular,'' he says. The same high rating applies
to Tuscany, where Castello Banfi rates 1999 as excellent.
</P>
<P>
   In France, Vintage 1999 brought more high praise. Exceptional
weather in Beaujolais should produce ripe, fruity red wines with
great charm. After a hot spring and a cool, dry winter, winemakers
in St. Emilion are encouraged that wines from the 1999 vintage will
be similar to the very good 1998. On the left bank, in the Medoc
and Graves, chateau owners are optimistic that 1999 will produce a
good vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Torres Wines, in the Penedes region of Northeastern Spain,
reports a 15 percent shortfall in grape yield, but representatives
expect the grapes to be high in quality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wine Q &AMP; A
</P>
<P>
   Chemist Arthur Dunlop of Berkeley enjoyed the Cellar Selection
description of the Australian Riesling from Jasper Hill, but was
puzzled by the label term ``natural sulfur dioxide.'' ``Is it
captured from a volcano?'' Dunlop wonders. In reality, Jasper Hill
owner and winemaker Ron Laughton was overstating the obvious, since
all sulfur dioxide is natural.
</P>
<P>
   The mail also brought a letter from Mrs. Marzolf Carmen, the
wife of a winegrower in Alsace, France. Mrs. Carmen liked our
coverage of Alsace wines in Potpourri and wants American lovers of
Alsace wines to know about her family winery in Gueberschwihr.
Consider it done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Happy Birthday, Opus One
</P>
<P>
   Opus One, the Napa Valley red wine collaboration between the
Baroness Philippine de Rothschild of Bordeaux's Chateau
Mouton-Rothschild and Robert Mondavi of Robert Mondavi Winery in
Oakville, is 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi first conceived the idea of a partnership with the
Baroness's father, Baron Philippe de Rothschild. Today, the name
Opus One denotes quality and prestige, more so than the wine's
rumored unofficial name, ``Bob &AMP; Phil's Big Red.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
