<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SUSHI-SFCHRON &LR;      11-30 2730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSHI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Sushi American Style: We've fallen in love with this
Japanese  delicacy, but what we're getting is a far cry from
Tokyo.   By Robin Davis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; ``I told you we'd have to wait,'' lamented a young
woman one night at Ebisu when she and a friend arrived just before
6 p.m. to an already packed house.
<P>
   It was typical. Customers crowd into the popular Inner Sunset
sushi restaurant night after night. The lucky ones snag seats in
the small entryway until their tables or seats at the sushi bar are
ready _ which can be an hour or more. But by 7 or 8 o'clock, twice
as many people are usually huddled outside in the fog or drizzle.
More daring patrons might grab a drink at Park Chow down the
street, but most are too fearful of losing their spot on the
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown's Metreon, customers flock to trendy Sanraku, opting
for sushi instead of burgers and Cokes before catching a movie
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   All around the Bay Area, sushi restaurants are filled to
capacity. And more are on the way _ every time a restaurant closes,
it seems a sushi bar rises in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi's popularity doesn't end with restaurants, though.
</P>
<P>
   Construction workers, office managers and Silicon Valley techies
pack sushi in their lunch boxes. Supermarkets sell premade sushi so
customers can pick up California rolls along with their cereal and
milk. Kids look forward to ``sushi day'' in school cafeterias,
their anticipation rivaling the excitement of pizza day. And there
may come a day when baseball fans can get spicy tuna rolls along
with hot dogs during the seventh inning stretch at the Giants'
Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi has become America's new fast food. We've taken an ancient
Japanese tradition and made it all-American. We eat it because it's
easy and because it's healthful. But above all, it's quick: We can
wolf down a few pieces of  &LR; maguro &LR;  and  &LR; hamachi &LR; , some jumbo rolls,
and wash it down with beer in the same time it takes to gorge on a
burger and fries. Plus, sushi fills our never-ending quest for
something new and exotic.
</P>
<P>
   But what we're eating in this country is a far cry from the
original Japanese finger food. We've turned the delicate vinegared
rice dish into something wholly American _ big and bold. We eat it
differently and make it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Some see this as an abomination, but most sushi experts embrace
American-style sushi as a food of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi was developed hundreds of years ago in Japan as a way of
preserving fish. To properly ferment the fish, it was packed in
rice, but then the rice itself was discarded. Over time, cooks
began experimenting with cooking the rice to eat with the fish.
Eventually people started eating the fish raw rather than
preserved, so cooks mixed the rice with sugar and vinegar to give
it the sharp fermented flavor they missed from the fish. The word
``sushi'' actually refers to the seasoned rice, not the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Japan, sushi chefs emphasize presentation and the
importance of using a variety of fish. They design sushi platters
with a certain amount of empty space, considered aesthetically
pleasing. And with sashimi (raw fish served without rice), elements
that represent heaven, earth and movement _ such as julienned
daikon, shiso leaves or shredded carrot _ should be present on the
platter.
</P>
<P>
   But this sort of finesse gets lost in the American
interpretation. ``How they decorate is supposed to have meaning,''
says Steve Fuji, owner of Ebisu. ``But maybe 80 percent of
(American diners) don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   American-style sushi represents what Americans like: large
servings and bold flavors. When Japanese-trained sushi chefs
started coming to this country in large numbers in the early 1970s,
they noticed the difference in the American palate, and began
creating spicy rolls, spider rolls made with fried soft-shell crab
and, of course, California rolls. Those evolved into today's
popular rainbow rolls and dragon rolls stuffed and layered with a
mixture of cooked and raw ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these rolls incorporate non-Japanese ingredients like
cream cheese, chile paste and smoked salmon _ favorite American
flavors and textures. These rolls helped sushi gain popularity with
an American audience. But their use in sushi started out of
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that we didn't have enough material available in
the United States so chefs got creative using avocado and
crabmeat,'' says Takehiko Yasuda, president of the Northern
California Japanese Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   But others think that American sushi remains what it is _ jumbo
rolls with nontraditional ingredients _ because of the inferior
quality of American fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here fish is tasteless compared to Japan so sushi chefs have
to modify,'' says Hiroshi Takama, sushi chef in the Lobby Lounge of
the Ritz-Carlton San Francisco where traditional Japanese-style
sushi is served. ``In Japan, halibut is very sweet. The halibut
here tastes just like dead fish. Some chefs try to reinforce with
spice.''
</P>
<P>
   Takama refrains from this practice because he wants to offer
something distinctive to his customers. He starts with what he
calls ``the very best fish in the whole city,'' and supplements it
with ingredients like top-of-the-line caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Lowe, owner of Ace Wasabi Rock 'n' Roll Sushi in the Marina
and Tokyo Go Go in the Mission, both of which cater primarily to
the twentysomething set, feels American-style sushi works as a
lead-in to true Japanese sushi. ``Customers start on the specialty
rolls, then they try the more traditional  &LR; nigiri &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, feel that the Yankee interpretation just adds
to sushi's overall appeal. To Glenn Sakata, assistant branch
manager at fish distributor International Marine Products in San
Mateo, the development of American-style sushi is part of sushi's
evolution. ``Sushi from a historical point of view has always been
changing,'' he says. ``I think this is just one of its steps. I
think it's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences between Japanese and American sushi extend to the
way the food itself is served and eaten. Part of the Japanese
experience is the interaction with the sushi chef. Customers pay
attention to seasonality and will leave much of the ordering to the
chef, who knows what fish is best on any given day.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, on the other hand, have become used to their
favorites.  &LR; Maguro &LR;  (tuna),  &LR; hamachi &LR;  (yellowtail) and  &LR; sake &LR; 
(salmon) have to be served all year long because they're what
Americans have come to expect.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Ebisu's Fuji, who believes the customer is
always right. In fact, if he has the ingredients he'll make
whatever the customer wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, someone ordered chicken teriyaki  &LR; maki &LR; ,'' he
recalls. ``I made it for him. I don't know how it tasted, but it's
what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a classically trained French chef who diverges from
tradition, Fuji feels comfortable in creating distinctly
non-Japanese sushi. But he worries about diners who eat sushi made
by untrained chefs _ which the crush of new sushi restaurants can
bring. Many chefs simply learn as they go _ not the best situation,
he says. If sushi is made by someone without experience, the fish
can be incorrectly cut, making it difficult to chew and unpleasant
to eat.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why the owners of Hama Sushi in Venice in
Southern California last year opened the first sushi school in
America to train professional sushi chefs (see related story, this
section). The school breaks the male-only tradition of Japanese
sushi chefs _ a third of the school's graduates are women, and
students come from many ethnic backgrounds. In addition, the two
three-month programs significantly shorten the old-school
apprenticeship in Japan that takes as long as eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Ebisu's Fuji also feels that sushi chefs have a certain
responsibility to educate their customers about different kinds of
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say they don't like sea urchin,'' he says. ``But I
teach them to like it.'' First he cooks the sea urchin, called
 &LR; uni &LR;  in Japanese, and serves it with a special sauce. A customer
who likes it will usually order it again. Eventually, he says, the
customer will try it raw.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he says, ``If customers have a bad taste the
first time they have sushi, they won't have it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuji and others see mass-produced sushi as providing that
negative first hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick with sushi is having quality fish that's nice and
cool and then the warm rice,'' says Ken Lowe. ``If you refrigerate
the fish and the rice (which necessity dictates with ready-made
sushi), the quality suffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was casually approached about doing sushi at Pac Bell Park,
but declined because he believes mass-produced sushi _ which is
what would have to be served to handle the volume _ is horrible.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Andronico, president and CEO of Andronico's Markets,
begs to differ. He reports a positive reception to the sushi sold
at his supermarkets. For three years, Andronico's has offered sushi
that's made fresh throughout the day and stored in the refrigerator
case. And its popularity shows no sign of waning _ most of the
buyers are repeat customers, Andronico says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it the best sushi? No, of course not,'' he admits. ``But
the basics that we do, we do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just supermarkets that have popularized premade sushi.
The Ritz-Carlton in Marina del Rey includes sushi along with luxury
items like raw oysters, caviar, shrimp and carpaccio at its lavish
Sunday brunch buffet. The sushi, which is prepared by a company in
Los Angeles and then delivered to the hotel, is consistently the
most popular item on the buffet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have 150 people at brunch, I'll go through 500 pieces of
sushi,'' says executive chef Jacques Sorci.
</P>
<P>
   As for the evolution of American sushi, Tommy Kousaka, one of
the chef/instructors at the California Sushi Academy, doesn't see
it as a problem. In fact, he thinks that one day things will go the
other way _ American-style sushi will become available in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's American sushi, and why not? You can't get spicy tuna
roll in Japan.'' He pauses and smiles, ``Yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; How to Eat Sushi &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How Americans actually eat sushi differs from the Japanese
technique in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Here, most sushi eaters mix a large amount of  &LR; wasabi &LR;  _ green
Japanese horseradish _ in a small dish of soy sauce, then dip the
sushi rice-side down into the mixture. But using extra wasabi and
dipping the rice side into the mixture actually obscures the flavor
of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fuji, owner of Ebisu in San Francisco, explains that sushi
should be dipped fish-side down into a bowl of soy sauce with no
additional wasabi. ``The wasabi is already in the sushi and you
only need about one drop of soy sauce for each piece,'' he
explains. If you want more wasabi, tell the sushi chef.
</P>
<P>
   Most  &LR; maki &LR;  (the rolls) usually have a sauce of some kind and do
not need to be dipped into anything. The only rule is to eat each
slice in one bite, except for the very large pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the Japanese technique for eating  &LR; nigiri &LR;  sushi:
</P>
<P>
   _ Grasp the sushi between your thumb and first finger. Remember
that sushi is finger food; true sushi buffs do not use chopsticks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dip the fish side of the sushi very briefly into a small bowl
of soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turn the sushi fish-side up, then flip the sushi into your
mouth, placing the fish side on your tongue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whenever possible, eat each piece of sushi in one bite. If the
sushi is too large, hold the remaining piece in your hand; do not
return it to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SPEAKING SUSHI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Here's a short list of some Japanese words commonly used in sushi
bars:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gari &LR; . Thinly sliced pickled ginger served as an
accompaniment to sushi and sashimi. A slice should be eaten between
consuming different kinds of fish to cleanse the palate.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Hamachi &LR; . Yellowtai
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Maguro &LR; . Tuna
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Maki &LR; . Rolled sushi, usually four to six slices per order.
The filling is rolled in rice, then in seaweed and then cut into
slices. Some maki, such as the California roll, are ``inside out,''
meaning they are rolled in seaweed first and then in rice so the
rice is on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nigiri &LR; . Fish or shellfish pressed into an oval of sushi
rice. Most nigiri is served two pieces to an order.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nori &LR; . Dried seaweed
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sake &LR; . Salmon, though it also refers to the alcoholic rice
drink. The words are pronounced slightly differently, but to avoid
confusion, order your sushi from the sushi chef and beverages from
the waitress.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sashimi &LR; . Sliced raw fish (served without rice)
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sushi &LR; . A dish based on rice seasoned with vinegar and water.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Temaki &LR; . Hand rolls, ususally served one to an order. The
filling is rolled in a seaweed cone.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Unagi &LR; . Barbecued eel
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Uni &LR; . Sea urchin
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Wasabi &LR; . Spicy green horseradish paste used in most nigiri
sushi and served as a condiment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; American Sushi School Breaks Old Barriers &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If someone wants to become a chef, he can choose from many paths
to reach his goal: American culinary schools and colleges, European
schools, Old-World apprenticeships.
</P>
<P>
   But what about sushi chefs?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the owners of Hama Sushi in the Southern California
beach town of Venice, opened the California Sushi Academy to fill
continued requests from restaurants for skilled sushi chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with the intent of opening up the art of sushi to
anyone who wanted to learn,'' says Phillip Yi, vice president of
marketing at the Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to its opening, the only way to receive training was
through the rigorous Japanese apprenticeship program, which could
take as long as eight years. Apprentices would work and frequently
live with sushi chefs, often from a very young age. The first year
was spent mopping the floor; the second year, apprentices might get
to wash the sushi rice. It was years before they actually touched
fish.
</P>
<P>
   And the apprenticeships were almost always offered exclusively
to Japanese men.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy is breaking that barrier by training women and men
from various ethnic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The curriculum consists of two three-month programs, both
part-time. One covers basic knife skills and Japanese cooking
techniques; the other concentrates on making sushi and sashimi.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy also offers non-professional one-day sushi and
sashimi classes for those who want to learn how to make sushi at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the professional classes, each student is pursuing a
dream. Brian Delaney wants to return to Atlanta to open his own
sushi bar, or at least a restaurant that incorporates sushi into
the menu. But he admits he was intimidated by Japanese food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to cook Cajun, French, lots of other foods, and I
thought, `Why not Japanese?' But I was scared of the Japanese
tradition,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Tomlinson, who graduated from the Academy last spring,
spent the summer in Michigan coaxing people to eat sushi at her
restaurant. Now she's back in Los Angeles going to massage school
and helping out with the one-day classes for the public. Her dream
is to open a combination spa, gym and sushi bar.
</P>
<P>
   Yi is quick to point out that, like American and European
cooking schools, the Academy lays down a foundation. Students still
need to work in sushi bars to hone their skills before they can be
considered sushi chefs.
</P>
<P>
   While the Academy opens the doors to women and non-Japanese men,
the Japanese born and trained sushi chef/instructors teach
traditional Japanese sushi making _ not shortcuts _ and barely
touch on the large  &LR; maki &LR;  rolls so popular in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm teaching 400 years of Japanese history, not just
knife skills or cooking,'' says chef/instructor Andy Matsuda. He
wants his students to learn the traditional way before they branch
out and become creative.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  California Sushi Academy, 115 Main St. (near Venice &LR; 
 &LR; Boulevard), Venice, Calif.; (310) 581-0213. The academy is also &LR; 
 &LR; offering one-day classes at Sur La Table in Berkeley on March &LR;   &LR; 30
and May 24, 2000; call (510) 849-2252 for more information. &LR;   &LR; The
one-day classes will also be offered at Sur La Table in Los &LR;   &LR; Gatos
on March 29 and May 25; call (408) 395-6946. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
