<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain eager to show foreign policy know-how at Jewish forum
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Arizona Sen. John McCain will take his turn at the
foreign policy lectern today in an effort to set himself apart from
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will talk about foreign affairs at the Republican Jewish
Coalition's candidate forum in Washington. But unlike Bush in his
foreign policy speech last month, McCain will answer questions from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important for members of an audience to engage
directly with a candidate,'' said Dan Schnur, a McCain spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of McCain's remarks is not expected to be much
different from Bush's. Both hold an internationalist view of the
world that includes a clear-headed trading relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, a former POW in Vietnam, is eager to show his
expertise in this area and that he would come to the presidency
with no need for on-the-job training.
</P>
<P>
   He counts former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and former
U.N. Ambassador Jeanne Kirkpatrick among his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   All six GOP candidates are expected at today's forum. They will
meet Thursday night in New Hampshire in the first debate that will
include Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, today's speech marks the first of five policy talks
he plans to give in December to flesh out his campaign themes of
character and reform.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy has been a focus of McCain's 13 years in the
Senate, and his aides count the subject as one in which McCain has
an advantage over Bush. The governor has stumbled over the names of
countries and world leaders, but gave a generally well-received
speech at the Reagan Library on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   At campaign stops, McCain talks often about foreign policy,
describing a world that was dangerous and predictable when the
Soviet Union was the U.S.'s principal rival and that is now ``as
dangerous and much less predictable'' without another superpower.
</P>
<P>
   He has repeatedly criticized President Clinton for a foreign
policy that suffers from two flaws, ``strategic incoherence'' about
what the U.S. wants the world to look like and ``self-doubt'' about
how to act as the world's lone superpower.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was a critic of the American-led NATO bombing campaign in
Kosovo, complaining that the president aided Serbian leader
Slobodan Milosevic by announcing that he had ruled out the use of
ground troops in the Balkans. McCain charged that Clinton's
decision was driven by opinion polls that showed no support for
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also invoked his military experience when he said NATO
pilots were being ordered to fly high enough to avoid being shot
down, which had the effect of decreasing the accuracy of their
bombs and increasing civilian casualties on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a conscripted force. The pilots signed up for
this,'' McCain said at a recent event in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lack of resolve has characterized the administration's
dealings with Iraq, McCain has said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has squandered American credibility in Iraq, idly
threatening force on some occasions and engaging in desultory
bombing raids on others, McCain said in a March speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never make idle threats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Russia, McCain favors suspending international loans until
Russia ends the fighting in Chechnya, where Russian forces are
accused of having committed atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   He supports building a missile defense system and would put
Israel and Taiwan under its umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also would consider covert military assistance to
dissidents in so-called rogue nations, including Iraq and North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
