<HEADLINE>
IT'S EASY TO COAX AMARYLLIS BULBS TO BLOOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: Please tell me how to force amaryllis into bloom.
</P>
<P>
   A: Amaryllis bulbs are among the easiest to force into winter
blooms. The large, lilylike flowers are available in red, pink,
salmon, white, yellow and bicolors. The blooms may be single or
double, and there are miniature amaryllis, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is traditional to coax, or force, large Dutch hybrid
amaryllis into bloom for the holidays. Simply plant a bulb in a
pot, and in six to eight weeks you'll have blooms.
</P>
<P>
   African amaryllis bulbs will flower three to five weeks after
planting and have large blooms on shorter stalks that do not
require staking. Ask your nurseryman to identify the bulbs if they
are not labeled.
</P>
<P>
   To force amaryllis for winter color, select large, firm bulbs.
Bigger bulbs generate more flower stalks, therefore more blooms.
Stay away from bruised or discolored bulbs and/or those that lack
roots. Clean the bulbs by removing dried scales and any dried
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Amaryllis bulbs do not require pre-chilling but you can
refrigerate them (but do not place near vegetables or fruit) to
delay blooms or store them in a cool, dry place until potting time.
</P>
<P>
   Soak the roots and the bottom of the bulb in lukewarm water for
at least four hours before potting. Keep the upper half of the bulb
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom time varies a little among varieties. Pot African
amaryllis bulbs three to five weeks before desired bloom time. For
an extended flowering period, start a new pot every few weeks for
blooms all winter and into spring.
</P>
<P>
   Use a clean clay pot with a drainage hole. Use a pot large
enough to allow an inch of space between the bulb and the inside
wall of the pot. Amaryllis bloom best when the succulent roots are
pot-bound. For more drama, pot three bulbs in a 12-inch container.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the container with a rich, well-draining potting mix. The
ideal pH range is 6.0 to 6.8. Spread the roots over a small mound
of soil in the pot, then add more potting mix and gently press the
soil to eliminate air pockets and secure the bulb. Leave the upper
third of the bulb above the soil line, which should be about an
inch down from the top of the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Water well with tepid water, and do not water again for two
weeks. Then water sparingly until the flower stalk and the foliage
are growing well.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the pot in a place where the temperature is above 68
degrees. Avoid drafts and areas where there are great swings in
temperatures. Place the pot in indirect light for the first three
weeks, then move the amaryllis into bright light.
</P>
<P>
   Stake the flower stalk of Dutch bulbs to support the large and
heavy blooms that will come. The stalks can be 2 feet tall, the
blooms as much as 8 inches across. Tie the flower stalk loosely to
the stake. Do not allow the stake to touch the petals or bulb.
Rotate the container to avoid a permanently leaning flower stalk.
</P>
<P>
   Heat initiates the amaryllis bloom, while light affects the
quality of the bloom. Bright light is good, but direct rays can
lower the quality of the flowers. Under good conditions, amaryllis
flowers retain quality for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the flower stalk 2 inches above the neck of the bulb once
the blooms have withered, but leave the straplike foliage to grow.
</P>
<P>
   You can continue to grow the holiday amaryllis in its container
or transplant the bulb into the garden, with half of the bulb above
the soil in a fertile, well-draining bed, ideally with morning sun
and afternoon shade. Wait to leave amaryllis outdoors until April,
when there is no threat of frost.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners simply sink the bulb, pot and all, into a raised
bed. The roots will eventually grow into the bed. Should harsh
weather hit, the pot can be lifted and the bulb moved temporarily
to a protected area. While those roots in the garden bed will be
torn, those within the container will not be damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Amaryllis need a year to acclimate in the garden. Then the bulbs
will begin a natural spring-flowering period. Water amaryllis
regularly through spring and summer. Decrease watering when the
foliage yellows, as lower fall temperatures trigger dormancy.
</P>
<P>
   Amaryllis are known as heavy feeders, and the bulbs benefit from
organic and synthetic nutrient sources. Do not fertilize bulbs
during dormancy. Lay container plants on their sides in a cool
place during dormancy. Mulch garden bulbs. Amaryllis will come
around in spring as the soil warms.
</P>
<P>
   Amaryllis forced to flower can bring years of enjoyment as pot
plants or in the garden. But don't attempt to force the bulbs two
years in a row. They need rebuilding time. Buy new bulbs next fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents an individual reply to each letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
