<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE MOST OF BEING SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For seven years we have watched Hillary Clinton
cope awkwardly, in good times and bad, under intense public
scrutiny with the undefined role of first lady.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a painful process. But if you thought that was
tough, consider the plight of the second lady, Tipper Gore. Her
public responsibilities are in some ways as complicated as those of
Clinton, although she has been so discreet and well-mannered that
she has attracted less media attention and less controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the first lady is free to do virtually whatever she
wants, a sensible vice president's wife is not free to do much of
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her status, Gore is not just a homemaker whose
obligations end with her family, although she clearly puts her
husband and four children first. Now 51, she is so youthful, bubbly
and good-looking it is hard to believe that she is a grandmother.
Before a speech at the National Press Club Monday, with very little
urging she pulled pictures of her married eldest daughter Karenna's
baby out of her purse to show me.
</P>
<P>
   Out of that same purse also promptly came pictures of Tipper
skydiving this summer, demonstrating that grandmas these days can
be frisky folk.
</P>
<P>
   But because she has no power, she cannot assert herself in any
way that might upstage the Big Three _ the president and his wife
and her husband Al.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tricky business being a loyal vice president dependent
on the good will and confidence of the president. But for an
intelligent woman accustomed to participating in political life, it
can be just as dicey playing female second banana to the male
second banana.
</P>
<P>
   She isn't left much room to be useful.
</P>
<P>
   Since her husband's first race for Congress in 1976, she has
campaigned at his side and she is already involved in his
presidential bid. Political wives are expected to do that.
</P>
<P>
   She became briefly controversial in the 1980s when she led a
crusade against the then-popular porn rock to persuade the music
industry to put warning labels on records with raunchy lyrics.
Initially, she was ridiculed by those who smelled prudish
censorship, but eventually her efforts in advocating increased
parental awareness came to be seen positively as a stand for
``family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Her real public policy passion has been the defense of the
homeless and the mentally ill. These are not popular topics and
thus fit neatly into the narrow activities box traditionally
permitted vice presidential spouses.
</P>
<P>
   But she has been trying to help manic-depressives and
schizophrenics for two decades, long before Al Gore became vice
president. She also has a personal reason for her interest. She
recently disclosed that she took medication for depression after
her son narrowly survived a 1989 auto accident. Decades ago her
mother was institutionalized twice for severe depression.
</P>
<P>
   She is currently promoting a photo exhibit at the Corcoran
Gallery of Art here that encourages help for the homeless. It
includes some of her own photographs. In her speech Monday she
stressed the connection between homelessness and mental illness,
since a high proportion of those who live on the streets are unable
to cope with reality.
</P>
<P>
   National sympathy for the homeless has waxed and waned. It is
currently at a low ebb in New York City since a woman was
critically injured by a brick thrown by a homeless man. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani announced in a fury that hereafter homeless bums
will be kept from sleeping on the city streets, producing a rash of
arrests and disorderly conduct charges but no improvements in
outpatient services or subsidized housing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore tactfully disagreed with the Giuliani approach. ``I
represent a view that's very compassionate,'' she said. ``I don't
think it's a crime to be homeless on the streets of America. I
think it's a crisis that needs to be addressed with compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not mention that tough guy Giuliani is preparing to run
against Hillary Clinton for a New York Senate seat. But Gore made
no effort to put some distance between herself and the first lady,
as her husband is trying to do with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore defended Mrs. Clinton, saying that she is ``proud of
the way she's significantly used her role as first lady'' and
predicting she will help Al Gore's presidential prospects because
she's ``a terrific candidate'' who can strengthen the Democratic
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore's image as a nice person has thus far been
untarnished by the political attacks on her husband and the
Clintons. Perhaps it is that she has been underestimated, her job
as an unpaid volunteer in the Gore camp viewed as insignificant.
Perhaps it is that she is so genuinely decent and well-liked that
it is difficult to work up any complaints about her. Perhaps it is
that her husband's rivals fear generating a backlash if they pick
on a smart, family-oriented woman who is warm, kind, engaging and
not wooden at all.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps her turn is coming later, when everybody gets bored
picking on the others.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     11-30 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS LONG AGO SURRENDERED THE OTHER WINSTON CHURCHILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent and unexpected literary discussion off the court
after a lively tennis match, I was able to set things right for my
doubles partner. She had assumed that a series of novels by Winston
Churchill on a local library shelf were the handiwork of the late,
great British statesman.
</P>
<P>
   I thought, my, how the mighty have fallen!
</P>
<P>
   Not the lionized prime minister, but the American namesake only
four years his senior. Yes, there were two Winston Churchills. They
were distant relatives, and the American one was famous earlier,
and very famous indeed. Yet no one reads him today, and, truth to
tell, no one should. But if there's confusion among the readership
of these books pages, I can help some more.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Churchill _ the American one, born and raised in St.
Louis _ was the champion seller of fiction in the first decade of
the century about to end. It was exactly 100 years ago, in the
autumn of 1899, that he broke through with his first bestseller,
``Richard Carvel,'' a romance of the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   In the early months of 1900, ``Richard Carvel'' dislodged
another historical saga _ Mary Johnston's ``To Have and to Hold'' _
as No. 1 on the then-newly-devised bestseller chart. Before the
year was over, he was back with another novel that swamped all
competition commercially. This was ``The Crisis,'' set before,
during and immediately after the Civil War, and featuring
descendants of Richard Carvel.
</P>
<P>
   This Winston Churchill (1871-1947) was squarely in the narrative
tradition of Walter Scott and James Fenimore Cooper. He continued
to spreadeagle the field with ``The Crossing'' (1904), ``Conistan''
(1906) and ``Mr. Crewe's Career'' (1908). He was inordinately fond
of the alphabet's third letter, which appears somewhat less
prominently in ``The Inside of the Cup'' (1913) and ``A Far
Country'' (1915).
</P>
<P>
   By then he was in his 40s and sales were dropping. After his
early start, it wasn't a matter of his burning out young. Literary
fashions were changing and would be altered more drastically after
the first world war. Churchill seems to have sensed the times had
passed him by; he wrote no more fiction after 1917, and his last
three decades encompassed an ever-deeper immersion into
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   A brief report on ``The Crisis'' may explain its population and
give fair indication of what regaled readers of novels at the
century's long-ago turn. Anyone familiar with Herman Wouk's ``The
Winds of War'' and ``War and Remembrance'' can have a keen notion
of how Churchill's ``Crisis'' works.
</P>
<P>
   In the Wouk saga, protagonist Pug Henry keeps bumping into the
historical household names of World War II, including President
Franklin Roosevelt, who calls him by his first name. Stephen Brice
is Churchill's hero, and during the novel's design from 1857 to
1865, he rubs shoulders and chats with such luminaries as Ulysses
Grant (not yet 40 and a has-been), William Sherman and many others,
among them Abraham Lincoln, met first as a failed candidate for the
Illinois Senate and later as a president whose assassination closes
the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill scores best in ``The Crisis'' in his portrayal of St.
Louis as a hotbox of Northern and Southern sympathies before and
during the war. And the Romeo-Juliet device is recycled: Stephen
Brice is an abolitionist; the Virginia Carvel who is his unrequited
love is pro-slavery (that's why it's unrequited). There's a
romantic triangle of sorts, for Virginia is betrothed to her cousin
Clarence Colfax, her fellow Southerner who emerges a fairly decent
chap, but a stick-figure like Stephen.
</P>
<P>
   The author was lauded in his time for narrative sweep. You're
free to investigate. I'm told the novels stay on library shelves
and are seldom checked out.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emeritus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
