<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY-SUIT-COX     11-30 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramseys file suit against tabloid for publishing 'vicious,
outrageous lies'
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ JonBenet Ramsey's parents Tuesday sued the tabloid
Star, saying it libeled and defamed their son by alleging he was
the prime suspect in his sister's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   John and Patsy Ramsey filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court
in Atlanta. They seek $5 million in actual damages and $20 million
in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Star published false and defamatory stories about Burke on May
25 and June 1, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   In its May 25 issue, Star reported it had a ``World Exclusive''
and, in a front-page headline, said evidence showed that ``JonBenet
was killed by brother Burke.'' The June 1 article said prosecutors
were ``closing in'' on Burke and described him as having a ``sad,
twisted life.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, who was 9 at the time of his sister's slaying, had
nothing to do with the killing and has been cleared as a suspect by
the Boulder County, Colo., District Attorney's Office, the lawsuit
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements published by the Star were vicious, outrageous
lies,'' the Ramsey's lawyer, Lin Wood, said. ``Star magazine used,
and I would submit, abused a child for profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys, Wood added, are prepared to give pre-trial
testimony and ``answer any question on relevant issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old JonBenet was found beaten and strangled Dec. 26,
1996, in the basement of the Ramsey's home in Boulder, Colo. A
Colorado grand jury investigating JonBenet's death did not indict
anyone before adjourning in October.
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, Star retracted its stories about Burke, saying he
had been cleared and was not a suspect. ``We were wrong,'' the
retraction said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Star and its parent company, American Media Inc.,
said they will vigorously defend the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Star said it feels obligated ``to conduct a complete
investigation of the murder, pursuing avenues of inquiry that were
not available to state investigators. Almost three years after this
horrible tragedy, the fundamental question remains this: Who killed
JonBenet Ramsey? Star intends to answer that question through this
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid said it hoped ``the Ramsey family joins us now in
the search for the killer of their daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood strongly criticized Star's intentions. ``If they feel
they're going to use this litigation, through discovery, to write
more stories, they're mistaken,'' he said. ``I don't think any
federal judge in Atlanta will tolerate that misuse of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues in the Ramsey's libel suit are straightforward, the
Atlanta lawyer said. ``Where the statements false? Clearly they
were. Were they defamatory? Of course. They branded this child a
murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, now 12, lives in Atlanta in the Ramsey home across from
the private Lovett School, which he attends.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Ramseys said they do not allow Burke to enter
grocery or convenience stores that sell tabloids. Despite the
publicity, John Ramsey said, Burke is ``doing very well. He's
turning into a normal teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
