<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MIDEAST-BOOK-REVIEW-N     11-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EMPIRES OF THE SAND': ROMANTIC NOTIONS OF MIDEAST HISTORY
CHALLENGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What might be called the Lawrence of Arabia vision of Middle
Eastern politics has long dominated the Western view of a major
part of Arab history. In that vision, the dashing and eloquent
British army officer T.E. Lawrence persuaded the Hashemite princes
of Arabia to rise up in a great rebellion against their Ottoman
Turkish rulers and to create a new Arab nation. But after the
Ottoman Empire was destroyed in World War I, the nationalist
Pan-Arab dream was betrayed by British and French imperialism, and
it is in that betrayal that many of the persistent problems of the
Middle East have their origins.
</P>
<P>
   This is decidedly not the view of Efraim Karsh and Inari Karsh,
Middle East historians in Britain, whose new book, ``Empires of the
Sand,'' is a readable, scholarly re-examination of a long and
complicated Middle Eastern history. The Karshes' book tells the
saga of the dissolution of the Ottoman Empire, beginning with
Napoleon's expedition to Egypt in 1797 and ending with the creation
of new Middle Eastern states out of the former Ottoman Asian
possessions. In this sense the Karshes, a married couple, provide
useful historical backgrounds to the emergence of independent
countries in Egypt, Greece, the Balkans and former Danube
principalities like Serbia and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   But the main purpose of this very detailed and broad-shouldered
history is to revise many of the standard interpretations that have
been given to Middle Eastern history over the last two centuries.
Most generally, the Karshes dispute the idea that the main events
and developments in the region stemmed from the machinations of the
great powers, especially Britain and France. The ``main impetus
behind regional developments,'' they write, was ``the local
actors.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of history in this book, most of it diplomatic
history, with other factors like social conditions, trade relations
and military maneuverings introduced only in cursory fashion. This
makes for a dry account at times, one that covers the diplomatic
goings-on in more detail than many readers will want.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the authors write clearly and authoritatively and with
great geographical sweep. They provide crisp and informed accounts
of the main events involving the Ottomans and the rest of the
world. These include the almost accidental British acquisition of
Egypt, the virtually pointless Crimean War and the genocide
committed by the Turks against the Armenians during World War I (a
remorselessly efficient action that the Karshes believe, contrary
to persistent and continuing Turkish contentions, had no rationale
or justification).
</P>
<P>
   They also cover the early stirrings of Zionism in the Middle
East and, most important in this history, the complicated story of
the Arabs, the French and the British during World War I and
immediately after. Those who do not know very much of these events
will learn a great deal from this book, while specialists with
views differing from the Karshes' will face a robust challenge to
their interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent vision of the Middle East stresses the romantic
notion of Islamic or Arab solidarity against interfering,
imperialist outsiders. In the Karshes' nearly opposite vision,
local rulers constantly allied themselves with those very outsiders
to maneuver against their local Islamic or Arab rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The first few chapters of ``Empires of the Sand'' are a history
of the Ottoman manipulation of ``infidel Europe'' to suppress local
Muslim challengers to Turkish rule, a policy that enabled the
fabled ``sick man of Europe'' to remain intact as an empire long
after its strength had ebbed. In the Karshes' interpretation, for
example, the Ottomans were the major, if generally unacknowledged,
victors of the Crimean War, fought by Britain, France and Turkey
against Russia. ``It was the Ottomans who had triggered a war they
could not afford, only to harness the great powers to their
cause,'' they conclude.
</P>
<P>
   More important for contemporary politics is the Karshes' take on
the notion, central to Arab history, that a ``great Arab revolt''
was among the main events in the Middle East during World War I.
The Karshes contend that there was no great Arab revolt, no great
Arab movement for freedom or national liberation. In addition, the
authors contend that there was no great Arab cultural awakening
behind the nonexistent great revolt. This revisionist view sharply
differs from standard histories, which see the emergence of a group
of nationalist writers during the first third of the 20th century
as marking the beginnings of Arab nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   The central figures in the Karshes' account of World War I in
the Middle East are the sharif of Mecca, Hussein ibn Ali of the
Hashemite family, and his three sons, Ali, Abdullah and Faisal.
From a base in Mecca, the Hussein clan expanded its power to what
would eventually be Jordan, Iraq and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   In this retelling of the story, which continued more recently in
the career of King Hussein of Jordan, the great-grandson of Hussein
ibn Ali, the revolt against Ottoman rule was motivated by the
imperialist desire of Hussein ibn Ali to replace the Turks in a
new, multinational empire, not an Arab or a Muslim one. The
majority of Arabs, the Karshes write, remained loyal to the
Ottomans and did not support the Hashemite cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the `Arab Nation' did not look to Hussein as their
would-be savior, so the sharif was interested not in the
`liberation' of his `Arab brethren' from the Ottoman yoke but
rather in the establishment of his own kingdom,'' the Karshes
write. The imperialist powers, notably Britain, did not so much
manipulate the Hashemite rulers into serving European interests as
get drawn into Hussein's scheme by the wily sharif's skillful
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   This interesting view is less romantic than the one purveyed in
David Lean's classic film ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and in numerous
other books, the view in which a passionate Arab nationalism is
first stimulated and then betrayed by perfidious Britain. The
historical reality, the Karshes say, gives a less heroic role to
the Arabs themselves but a more central one, too, since it presents
them, rather than the outside powers, as mainly responsible for
their fate.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EMPIRES OF THE SAND
</P>
<P>
   The Struggle for Mastery in the Middle East, 1789-1923'
</P>
<P>
   By Efraim Karsh and Inari Karsh
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 409 pages. Harvard University Press. $29.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
