<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SHERRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT     11-30 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE TROUBLE WITH SHERRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Servic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When you sit down at Solera, the Midtown Spanish
restaurant, a little bowl of green olives appears on the table. I
find that this prompts a Pavlovian response. Olive and brine means
manzanilla, the featherlight, bone-dry sherry that may be the
finest aperitif wine known to humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, I asked for the manzanilla and then, slipping
into an old habit, simply continued drinking sherry throughout the
meal. With a plate of serrano ham, sliced chorizo and sweet and hot
salchichon, I moved to a slightly more substantial but still
light-bodied fino. With a main course of braised rabbit, I had a
medium-weight amontillado, with just enough heft and depth to match
the richness of the dish. With dessert, a warm chocolate hazelnut
cake with figs and apricots, I ordered a viscous, raisiny dessert
sherry. And at the end of the meal, I wondered, Why don't more
American diners do the same?
</P>
<P>
   Sherry is one of the greatest of all misunderstood wines.
Actually, the case is worse than that. Most diners pay so little
attention to it that misunderstanding would represent a rise in
status for this most unfortunate beverage. On paper, sherry has
everything going for it. The lighter, dry sherries make superior
aperitifs, bracing and invigorating. As complements to seafood they
cannot be equaled, especially when matched with the assertive
tidbits that adorn the tapas bar. Garlic, vinegar, spice and pepper
_ these are all friends to the finos and manzanillas. The weightier
amontillados and olorosos, at their best, achieve the complexity of
fine Bordeaux or Burgundies, and the best dessert sherries can
equal the best ports and Madeiras.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Image, to begin with. For generations, Americans have associated
sherry with a musty bottle in their grandmother's kitchen. I still
remember a visit that my then-fiancee paid to the house of elderly
neighbors to announce our wedding. We entered what can only be
called a parlor. The dear old souls, wanting to celebrate the
moment, went toward a walnut cabinet, pulled out a decanter and
began pouring a murky brownish liquid into delicate little crystal
glasses. That's the image. Anyone who can get past the image then
confronts the complexities of sherry itself. For some reason,
diners who can master the Bordeaux classification of 1855 or who
revel in the arcana of single-malt distilleries balk at sherry. The
subject seems complex. It isn't. Sherry is a peculiar product, for
a couple of reasons, but it is not terribly hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Sherries come in two broad types, fino and oloroso. Both are
made from the same grape, the utterly undistinguished palomino
fino, which makes a flaccid, forgettable wine that the French
sometimes call a three-man wine, because it takes two men to hold
down a third to make him drink it.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, when the wine is first put into barrels, no one
knows what form it will take. Some wines develop a thick, cheesy
yeast known as flor, which keeps oxygen out and ensures that the
developing sherry will remain light and crisp. These are the finos.
When flor fails to appear, the wine is destined to oxidize and turn
into a rich, full-bodied olo-roso.
</P>
<P>
   Manzanillas, the lightest of all, are fino-style sherries
produced in Sanlucar de Barrameda, at the Spanish seaside, where
they pick up a distinct whiff of salt and brine. Finos, when aged,
become amontillados.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Dawes, an American writer on sherry, says that a fino is
to an amontillado as a Chablis is to a Meursault. Same grape,
different weight and character.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in the sherry family is palo cortado, which starts
to develop flor, then changes its mind and backtracks, winding up
somewhere between an amontillado and an oloroso. The name, which
means ``broken stick,'' refers to the chalk mark that the cellar
master inscribes on the barrel to indicate its development.
</P>
<P>
   All sherries, in their natural state, are completely dry, and
all are fortified, which is to say that at a certain point, alcohol
is added to halt fermentation. All have a distinctive nutty taste.
One maker has compared fino to almond, amontillado to hazelnut and
oloroso to walnut. In Spain, sherries are appreciated dry, but for
the foreign market, a sweet wine called Pedro Ximenez, or P.X. for
short, is added to amontillados and most olorosos. Cream sherry,
developed by English merchants to compete with port, is an oloroso
with P.X. added.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry is traditionally served in a copita, a small aperitif
glass that looks a little like a champagne flute cut down to half
size. It has the benefit of concentrating the aroma of a delicate
manzanilla or fino and sending it straight toward the nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   Most people do not have copitas, but one way to approximate the
glass is to fill a champagne flute halfway. Richer amontillados and
all olorosos can be served, like port, in wider glasses. Finos and
manzanillas are served very cold. Olorosos are always served at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   There are two schools of thought on the proper temperature for a
palo cortado or an amontillado. One prefers cellar temperature or
cooler, while the other believes that serving the wines at room
temperature opens them up. My rule of thumb is to drop the
temperature according to the richness of the wine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Learning the sherry basics is one thing; finding the wines is
another.
</P>
<P>
   Because Americans, by and large, do not drink sherry, and tend
to regard it as a dessert wine, the pickings tend to be slim. Most
wine stores carry two or three sherries, and if they have a fino,
it tends to be from a bigger brand name like Tio Pepe or La Ina.
Some of the better stores like Crossroads and Sherry-Lehmann offer
more, but even they devote scant shelf space to sherry, whose
neglect seems all the more mysterious given its price. Most cost
$10 to $20, a third the price of wines of comparable quality.
</P>
<P>
   There are some restaurants, however, that make their sherry
lists a point of pride. Some go a step further, matching their
sherries to their menus.
</P>
<P>
   Solera, whose name means sherry cellar, does both. It serves 15
sherries, covering all the styles, including the ethereal, lemony
La Gitana (``The Gypsy Woman''); a manzanilla from Hidalgo; and a
strong lineup of sherries from Emilio Lustau, a company that has
become synonymous with high-quality, small-producer sherries.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice I strongly approve of, the restaurant's menu
suggests pairings like a palo cortado with seared foie gras and
Catalan spinach in an oyster-mushroom and port sauce. Piquillo
peppers stuffed with braised oxtail and cauliflower puree go
beautifully with the startlingly deep Los Arcos amontillado from
Lustau, and the restaurant proposes a pale cream sherry to go with
sauteed quail with white grapes and a moscatel wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Solera organized a series of menus to highlight the
sherry-food possibilities. One meal began with an Andalusian
consomme with meatballs, egg and mint. The sherry was La Ina, a
fino. Quail eggs over mushroom puree with shaved truffle took a
single-cask palo cortado from Lustau, whose very finest sherries
are labeled with the term almacenista, a reference to tiny
producers who, in the past, would either sell their product to
blenders or save them for family and friends. A dish of prawns and
Moroccan spices was paired with a manzanilla, and confit of duck
with white beans and raisins took an oloroso. For dessert, the
restaurant poured an intensely sweet glass of pure Pedro Ximenez
wine.
</P>
<P>
   The pan-Latin trend has been good to sherry. It would be hard to
find a better list than the one at Bolivar, nearly 25 sherries that
include the snappy fino from Valdespino, a single-cask palo cortado
and oloroso from Lustau, and Sandeman's lush, velvety Royal
Corregidor oloroso. Robert Guarino, the manager of Bolivar, also
keeps a few special bottles on hand that he will open for
interested customers, like Osborne's astounding Solera India
oloroso, a complex, rich wine with overtones of orange peel, fig,
brown sugar and gingerbread.
</P>
<P>
   Patria carries nearly 15 sherries, including an old amontillado
from Hidalgo and two almacenista olorosos from Lustau: 1918 Dona
Pilar Aranda y Latorre, and the dry oloroso of the purist,
Emperatriz Eugenia. Jorge Liloy, Patria's wine director, likes to
pair a manzanilla with crispy oysters and fufu, spinach and
huacatay sauce, made from an Ecuadorean mint. The Hidalgo
amontillado goes with a black lobster empanada with yellow tomato
and saffron aji, and Liloy proposes a fino to go with sweet pea
crepes filled with bacalao and yuca. Other restaurants with
respectable lists are N, Marichu, Meigas and Xunta.
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs outside the Latin culinary borders have also picked
up on sherry. Sherry is a natural with most Japanese foods, so it
is only slightly surprising that March, with its Japanese
affinities, should feature sherry. In part this is because Joseph
Scalice, an owner and the wine director of March, took a trip to
Jerez, Spain, the town whose name the English rendered as
``sherry,'' and underwent something like a religious conversion.
March has eight dry sherries and eight dessert sherries, including
a Solera BC200 oloroso from Osborne, which the restaurant pairs
with its confit of duck foie gras, done Indian style with garam
masala, a papadum and sweet chutney. Manzanilla goes perfectly with
sashimi slices of hamachi with olive oil and white soy sauce, and
the grand Solera India oloroso is the suggested pairing for panna
cotta with bittersweet almond cream.
</P>
<P>
   I like to see sherry used this way, pushed outside its normal
boundaries. But the drink has a natural drift that brings it back
to the tapas bar. It is too alcoholic to quaff like wine (although
Julian Jeffs, the English writer on sherry, claims that it is
difficult to drink less than a bottle of manzanilla on a hot day),
but perfect for sipping a little at a time, which makes it ideal
for small bites.
</P>
<P>
   I recently sat down at Marichu to taste my way through a phalanx
of sherries. The chef, Teresa Barrenechea, sized up the situation
and brought one sherry-friendly appetizer after another: fried eels
in garlic, marinated anchovies in a slick of olive oil, sizzling
shrimp in garlic and pepper, piquillo peppers stuffed with bacalao,
and squid in ink sauce. It was a selection that allowed me to work
from manzanilla to fino to amontillado. And at the end, she put a
plate of Spanish cheeses on the table to show off the olorosos.
</P>
<P>
   I could have ordered wine, of course. But at the time, I
couldn't think of one reason why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
