<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Dec. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Periods of rain and snow will develop Wednesday over eastern New
England as a broad area of low pressure strengthens to the east of
Cape Cod. Bands of snow will sweep inland, crossing much of Rhode
Island, eastern Connecticut and southeast Massachusetts. On Cape
Cod, the snow will mix with rain as warm air from the ocean moves
overhead. Farther north and west, snow showers will develop over
interior sections of New England on the fringes of the storm.
Strong, gusty winds will accompany the precipitation, bringing
frigid wind chills and blowing snow.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, following a very cold morning, the interior Middle
Atlantic states will once again be rather chilly Wednesday as
breezes from the north continue to usher cold air into the region.
It should be sunnier than it has been, however, as sinking air
currents under a region of high pressure crush any cumulus clouds
that form. The Southeast will also be much cooler as some of the
cold air moves across the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A weak front sweeping over the northern Plains will bring some
chillier air and cloudy skies to the region. Farther south, the
central Plains will have one more day of unseasonably mild weather
before noticeably colder air slides across the prairie Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, yet another low-pressure system will approach
coastal Washington and Oregon, bringing showers and periods of
rain. Farther inland, snow showers will develop from the Wasatch
through the Tetons and into the Bitterroots. Meanwhile, the
Southwest will begin to turn more seasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Private Snowstorm
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Cape Cod had a private snowstorm early Tuesday. While
partly sunny skies covered much of New England, windswept snow
accumulated a few inches in a short time near Chatham, Mass. Cold
winds from the north garnered moisture as they passed over the long
stretch of the relatively mild waters east of New England. The
narrow, roiling bands of clouds that formed were responsible for
heavy snow. A similar process leads to the renowned ``lake-effect''
snows near Buffalo, N.Y. Today, a large ocean storm will bring
widespread snow in extreme eastern New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
