<HEADLINE>
STATE, LOCAL POLICE GET HIGH-TECH GUN TRACING TOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new computer program unveiled Tuesday by the
federal government should help state and local law enforcement
authorities quickly trace guns used in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called Online LEAD, has been operating on a trial
basis since February and helped local law enforcement officials and
the Treasury Department's Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
(ATF) to trace guns used in crimes in New York, Washington, Boston
and Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville Police Chief Emmett Turner, who participated in the
pilot program, said the system allowed his department to trace a
gun used in the 1996 murder of Nashville police officer Francis
Scurry. The gun was tracked back to two people who illegally sold
the weapon along with 400 other firearms. They were arrested and
convicted for violations of federal firearms' laws.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the online program will
allow federal, state and local law enforcement agencies to
``quickly bring together data, disseminate it quickly and see
patterns where we haven't before.''
</P>
<P>
   The software taps into an existing ATF database that contains
information about hundreds of thousands of guns sold by federally
licensed gun dealers. The database includes the make, serial number
and manufacturer of the guns and information about where they were
sold and who bought them.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, that information was stored on computer discs in
Washington that had to be shipped out to local ATF field offices, a
process that sometimes took several days. ATF officials explained
that in many cases guns used in crimes are often purchased only a
few days ahead of time _ information that will now be captured and
readily made available by the new online program.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this week the software will be made available to state
and local police through the ATF's 331 local field offices. The
database is continuously updated and can be instantly downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more quickly we can follow up on leads the more likely we
are to solve the crime,'' said ATF director John W. Magaw.
</P>
<P>
   The system is also designed to track down gun traffickers as was
done in the Nashville case. ATF officials also cited a case in
Boston where police recovered six handguns from various crime
scenes around the city. They discovered that the guns were all
purchased from various gun shops in Mississippi. This discovery
eventually lead them to Jose Andrade _ a Jackson State University
originally from the Boston area _ who used other students to
purchase guns for him at area pawn shops. Andrade then illegally
sold the guns to Boston gang members when he was home on school
breaks. Andrade is currently in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help us prevent crime by allowing us to focus on
sources of gun crimes and shut them down,'' Magaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said he hoped the new program would help police more
quickly find and arrest illegal gun traffickers and result in fewer
guns on the streets and fewer violent deaths. He noted that the
murder rate has fallen by five percent each year for the past five
years while violent crime has dropped 35 percent in the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 42,000 Americans are still killed each year by firearms,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
