<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HARUF-PLAINSONG-2TAKE     11-30 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARUF-PLAINSONG-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES COVERED BUT SEEING, A NOVELIST LOOKS INWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (js) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURPHYSBORO, Ill. _ One thing to know about Kent Haruf, author
of the novel ``Plainsong,'' is that he wrote the first draft of the
book with a wool stocking cap pulled down over his eyes. He would
sit typing blindly in the unheated basement of his unpretentious
white frame house in this sleepy town trying to visualize the high,
dry Colorado plains of his childhood. He would try to imagine two
little boys whose mother leaves them because she is so depressed
and a half-Indian girl who is pregnant and has nowhere to go.
Written in sparse, clean language, ``Plainsong'' is a novel about
kindness and how it comes in unexpected ways.
</P>
<P>
   Haruf had never written a novel with a wool stocking cap over
his head before. But his rather eccentric method was, he said, an
effort to reach the emotional heart of his story unconstrained by
the feeling that someone _ an invisible critic _ was watching over
his shoulder and scrutinizing every word he chose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying not to be analytical, to get in touch with the
intuitive, the visual, the spontaneous, without any attention to
detail and syntax,'' said Haruf, whose last name rhymes with
``sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes away the terror when you're blind and you can't go
back and rewrite a sentence,'' he said. ``It calls for
storytelling, not polishing.'' His method seems to have worked.
``Plainsong,'' published by Knopf, has gone into six printings
since its publication in October. It was nominated for a National
Book Award and has received almost universally positive reviews.
``He has conjured up an entire community and ineluctably immersed
the reader in its dramas,'' Michiko Kakutani wrote in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Giles wrote in Newsweek, ``Watch for fireworks over the
plains.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has come on the late side to Haruf, who is 56. His work
has always been praised by critics. He won a Whiting Writers' Award
as well as a PEN/Hemingway Foundation special citation for his
first book, ``The Tie That Binds,'' published in 1984. But that
novel and his second, ``Where You Once Belonged,'' in 1991, did not
sell very well, and they came hard. He had three small daughters to
support, and he held jobs teaching high school and as a farm
laborer and construction worker. As a consequence Haruf, who has
the unremarkable looks and plain manner of a small-town insurance
salesman, is modest in his consideration of his new found praise
and cautious about the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nuts, crazy in this country about fame,'' he said in his
soft voice. ``We expect writers to be something between Hollywood
starlet and a village idiot. In both cases, they're supposed to
perform antics on demand. I think it would be most dangerous for a
writer to be famous. It's very distracting. Mailer wrote his best
stuff before he became famous.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that Haruf will move away from Murphysboro any
time soon. The town is so quiet that the only sound besides Haruf's
voice as he speaks in his living room is the gentle tinkle of a
wind chime. And the only thing that seems to move in the general
stillness are the leaves falling from the hardwood trees onto the
deserted backyards.
</P>
<P>
   Haruf teaches at the University of Southern Illinois in nearby
Carbondale, and he says he has always liked this small town
atmosphere. He knows that he gains something from it, a sense of an
enclosed, encompassable place. He tells his students that they are
lucky to come from the small towns of the Midwest. ``They feel
embarrassed, but I tell them it is a great advantage to grow up in
a distinct place with so many little towns,'' he said. ``You know
people, you know their histories, whose pickup is in front of the
bar. You may not know everything, but you get a sense of the stages
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Haruf was born in Pueblo, Colo., the son of a Methodist
minister. His father moved frequently from congregation to
congregation, and the landscape of northeastern Colorado became the
setting for Holt, the fictitious town that is Haruf's
Yoknapatawpha, where most of his work is set.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of four children and was particularly close to his
younger brother, Mark. ``We thought the ideal life would be to live
it out together, with horses,'' he said. ``That's what we had
planned to do. That situation was on my mind for 50 years.'' The
boyhood dream never materialized, but it formed the basis for the
relationship between the two little boys in ``Plainsong.'' Mark is
now a certified public accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Haruf attended Nebraska Wesleyan University in Lincoln, where he
discovered Faulkner and Hemingway. In 1965 he went to Turkey as a
Peace Corps volunteer. During the Vietnam War he was a
conscientious objector and did alternative service in a hospital
and an orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that he wanted to be a writer and applied to the Iowa
Writers Workshop, but he was rejected. The urge to go was so
powerful, however, that he moved his wife, Virginia, and their
infant daughter to Iowa City in hopes of being accepted. Eventually
he was accepted on a probationary status, he said. For his master's
thesis he wrote a novel, and hope beckoned when the first four
chapters were optioned by Harper &AMP; Row. But the final manuscript
was turned down. It seemed he might not be a writer after all.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years he taught high school English in Colorado and
Wisconsin. He began writing another novel, working during summers
off from his teaching job. He was ``desperate to have time'' to
write, Haruf said. But ``I wanted to be an attentive father,'' he
added, and he found it hard to work in the midst of the chaos of
child rearing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 he landed a job at Nebraska Wesleyan University as an
assistant professor, which gave him more time to write. At 41 he
finally sold a short story, to the literary magazine Puerto del
Sol. He also finished a novel. That, too, was turned down by Harper
&AMP; Row. Through a former teacher of his at Iowa, John Irving, he
contacted Peter Matson, the agent, who, Irving warned, had turned
down every writer he had sent to him.
</P>
<P>
   Matson broke his pattern, took on the book and sold it to Holt,
Rinehart &AMP; Winston. ``The Tie That Binds,'' published in 1984 and
set in Colorado, is about a woman who gives up her chance for love
to take care of her domineering father. The novel is narrated by
the son of the man she loved but had forsaken for her father. Chris
Wall in The Los Angeles Times Book Review called it ``an
impressive, expertly crafted work of sensitivity and detail, absent
the hokum that usually accompanies sad tales of simple women and
their domineering fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s Haruf's daughters were nearly grown, and his
relationship with his wife was ending. He decided to attend his
30th-high school reunion in Canon City, Colo., and there he caught
sight of Cathy Dempsey, who had been in the band with him, he
playing the snare drum and she the tenor sax.
</P>
<P>
   The two had lived on the same street in Canon City where her
father was the Episcopal minister. She had gone on to marry and
have three children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lightning flashed,'' said Haruf. They fell in love, and
married in 1995. Mrs. Haruf is a special-education teacher at a
high school in Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Haruf published his second novel, ``Where You Once
Belonged,'' about a former high school football hero who through
his greed and arrogance destroys the lives of many in his hometown.
But to this day the book makes Haruf uneasy. ``In some ways I sort
of lost that book,'' he said. He had written it too fast, he said,
under pressure to finish writing by the middle of August so he
could get back to teaching. Despite his doubts, the book received
excellent reviews; it was called ``a deeply affecting novel'' in
Publishers Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kent is interesting to view in terms of American
literature in the 20th century, the two different strains of
Hemingway and Faulkner,'' said the novelist Richard Russo, who
hired him at the University of Southern Illinois in 1990. ``He has
faith in the power of simple, honest language. He believes deep
down that simple language not only suffices, but he just doesn't
like artifice.'' At the same time, Russo said, ``he has learned
from Faulkner the wisdom of knowing something very well, of being
at home there, that the more something is specific, the more it is
universal.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Plainsong'' the half-Indian girl at the center is
``somebody at the edge of society,'' Haruf said. ``Why is she so
lonely and willing to be attracted and seduced by the boy from the
next town?'' Kindness comes in the form of a high school teacher,
Maggie Jones, who rescues her, and two old men, the McPheron
brothers, who have lived together in an isolated farmhouse for 50
years and who take her in. There is also a high school teacher,
Guthrie, who is left to raise his two young boys by himself. Just
at his hour of deepest loneliness, Maggie, who teaches with him,
makes her interest in him known, and they fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' was a difficult book to create, said Haruf. He
struggled hard to get the right ``sound of the novel.'' He wanted
the writing to be ``as direct and straightforward and as simple as
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result the book begins almost colloquially: ``Here was this
man. Tom Guthrie in Holt standing at the back window in the kitchen
of his house smoking cigarettes and looking out over the back lot
where the sun was just coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had a lyric gift; I don't,'' Haruf said of his
writing, perhaps disingenuously. But then he couldn't help
admitting, ``I don't like gorgeous writing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
