<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FOOD-PRESENTATION-ART     11-30 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PRESENTATION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING THE PLATE AS A BLANK CANVAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean-Georges Vongerichten was doodling. First he made
a triangle, then several loops attached to the triangle. Then he
dotted the triangle like mad, finishing with a loose, fluid
squiggly.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't just any doodle. Vongerichten, the chef at Jean
Georges, was figuring out just how he wanted to present his new sea
bass dish. It needed textures that varied, flavors that harmonized
and looks that would cause audible gasps upon arrival in the dining
room.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, all the effects cooks might want for their
efforts in the kitchen. But professionals know that their efforts
can't stop there: for food to be fully appreciated, attention must
be paid to the way it is arranged on the plate and set before the
diner.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, home cooks are happy just to get the food to
the table. That changes at this time of year, though, when the
entertaining season is in full swing and the everyday habit of
serving food family-style feels like quitting the race in the
homestretch. Taking time to present food thoughtfully, even
artfully, can add another dimension to the pleasure of eating it.
</P>
<P>
   If you present a dish and the diner says, ``Wow!'' ``you're
already ahead of the game before they put a fork in it,'' said
Charlie Palmer, the chef at Aureole.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs are increasingly conscious about how they present food,
and today's restaurants can serve as advanced courses in postmodern
plate design. As with any art form, schools vary. Marcus
Samuelsson, the chef at Aquavit, creates plates that appear to be
made of vivid, thickly layered brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten's spare style reflects the clean, pure flavors of
his cooking. That sea bass dish, for example. By placing the
triangle fish off-center on a plain white plate, it brought
attention to it _ just the point, when you serve a great piece of
fish and little else. The coarse salt crystals dotting the top of
the fish added texture, and the free-form curve of green sauce
surrounding the fish set it off: the plate didn't need another dash
of color, or another element to fill the open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the classic style of filling the plate symmetrically is
passe. So is the nightmarish fussiness of nouvelle cuisine. Even
the overwrought dishes with towering components and sauces that
resemble Jackson Pollack canvases are fading away.
</P>
<P>
   The fashions will continue to change, but the purpose will not:
the components of a dish need to harmonize and tempt the eye.
Underlying it all are some simple techniques that collectively have
a powerful impact on the finished dish.
</P>
<P>
   The first trick restaurants use is warming plates before placing
food on them. Food cools very quickly, and if it is placed atop a
cool plate, it can easily lose its luster before the diner even
touches it. By placing the food on warm plates, it won't
deteriorate on the way to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants have special heating units for warming them, but the
effect can be replicated at home by placing them in a 150-degree
oven (the low or warm setting) for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs also take great pains to make their food easier to eat. If
you go to a bistro, roasted chicken is likely to be served intact
or cut into small pieces and arranged in a tight pile with the leg
bone pointing upward.
</P>
<P>
   But at a finer restaurant, the bird is usually boned, and its
breast meat is sliced. Thin slices of meat are more elegant and
easier to cut. You can fan out slices on a plate and lean the legs
against another part of the dish, say a mound of celery root puree.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to think of how guests will eat the meat. You
don't want to have to destroy a tower to get at a piece. Generally,
unless you want a large piece of meat to be the feature of the
plate, meats and fish should be cut down to make them more
approachable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most basic principles is layering. This doesn't
necessarily mean that ingredients should be stacked on top of one
another like a napoleon. They can just overlap slightly, linking
them implicitly.
</P>
<P>
   This could be done with any dish. Typically rice, pasta or
grains are used as the base, and the primary component, usually the
meat, is laid on top. If there is a vegetable, it may lean on the
meat or be tucked between the base and the meat. Sauce is spooned
over specific parts of the dish and around the border.
</P>
<P>
   The dishes at Union Pacific are great studies in layering: Rocco
DiSpirito, the chef, has made a science of it. Components are
layered directly on top of one another, and each has a distinct
textural and flavor identity.
</P>
<P>
   In his mackerel salad, a thin circle of pear and celery puree is
spooned into the center. It is the mortar for the bricks laid above
it. A crunchy salad of celery root and pear fills the middle
portion, then slices of charred mackerel, and a julienne of pear.
It is crowned with a fluff of celery leaves and Asian greens. A
celery oil vinaigrette dresses the salad layer and circles the
tower.
</P>
<P>
   It is a complex piece of architecture, not unconnected building
blocks. DiSpirito constructs the dish this way so that with each
forkful the diner gets the perfect proportion of each layer and the
dish's flavors coalesce. It also looks impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Layering can be used to make an ordinary dish look beautiful or
to incorporate elements of surprise. The frisee aux lardons at Cafe
Boulud does just that. When the dish arrives, all you see is a
rough tangle of frisee, but each bite uncovers something new: a
poached duck egg, cubes of sauteed foie gras, bacon and chicken
livers and a dark sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The salad and meats could have been mixed together in a bowl and
laid out on the plate, but this layered arrangement made the salad
much more fun to eat.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement also solves a problem with salads. By leaving
the livers and sauce below, the salad stays fresh as long as
possible and does not wilt or turn slimy as you eat it. This is a
trick that may be applied to any salad involving multiple
components _ especially when some are warm. Rather than serving it
on the side and having guests toss it aside as a useless garnish,
you can place a tuft of it atop primary components like terrines or
sauteed fish.
</P>
<P>
   Saucing is one of the most important principles neglected by
home cooks. It is a good idea to spoon some sauce onto a dish, so
that flavors can blend. A sauce is a great decorative tool as well.
A thin stream drizzled around the border of the plate contains the
dish visually and allows the people eating it to incorporate the
sauce as they want, rubbing forkfuls through it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Texture is important, too. A variety of textures gives a dish
concealed complexity. It is rare that you will be served a dish
with a uniform texture. Consider the lamb with orzo at Park View at
the Boathouse.
</P>
<P>
   A bed of orzo is spread around the base of the plate. Kumquats
and pistachios are sprinkled over the orzo, and a braised lamb
shank is laid atop the orzo in the center of the plate. A lamb jus
is spooned over the lamb and around the orzo, providing the dish's
flavor thread.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than eating the different parts of the dish separately,
you get a little taste of each in nearly every bite. The sauce is
wet, the orzo soft, the pistachios crunchy.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients shouldn't be added carelessly. Usually you can add
texture without altering the content. Rather than steaming fish,
for instance, you can sear it to give the skin a crisp texture. Or
you can take a much more subtle approach, as Vongerichten did in
his sea bass dish, seasoning it just before serving with coarse sea
salt.
</P>
<P>
   Color has more straightforward appeal. An all-white or all-brown
dish is tough to get excited about. But it can be obvious when a
chef throws in an ingredient just to add color. It becomes a
distraction, not a complement. A monochromatic dish can be striking
in its absence of color.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Rodriguez, the chef at Bond Street, uses color
deliberately. Most of her dishes include a dark component, a light
component and a bright component. So in a sea bass dish, the fish
is seared on the skin side so that it is dark, and she pairs it
with bright bok choy and light daikon simmered in fish broth. The
flavors make sense together, and the ingredients happen to be
colorful.
</P>
<P>
   Color should be organic, not forced. Generally, if you cook with
seasonal ingredients, using a variety of meats, vegetables and
fruits, your dishes will naturally have a variety of colors. Even
if there is just one bright element, that is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Every sense should be considered in the dining experience. Many
dishes, like soups, give off a burst of aroma when they are ladled
into a hot bowl, and many restaurants have begun doing this kind of
dish-finishing at the table. At home, a simple flourish at the
table, like snipping herbs over a soup, can have the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   These are the techniques. What most diners notice are the styles
chefs use. It is important to have a point of view. A chef with one
of the most recognizable styles is Alfred Portale of Gotham Bar &AMP;
Grill. His food is almost always concentrated at the center of the
plate with ingredients tightly clustered and positioned in towers
that seem to explode upward from the plate. They are beautiful to
look at, difficult to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular style descends from classical cuisine.
Generally, the main components of a dish are placed neatly in the
center of the plate and surrounded by sauce that covers the base of
the plate. Garnishes are then arranged symmetrically around the
center component.
</P>
<P>
   Dishes presented this way can be beautiful and easy to
comprehend: you eat from the center and incorporate the surrounding
sauce as you go.
</P>
<P>
   But the central tower and symmetry are receding in favor of new
styles. Probably the most pervasive is one influenced by Japanese
cooking. Rather than symmetry, food is presented asymmetrically,
often marked by a great deal of open space.
</P>
<P>
   With Vongerichten's foie gras terrine and brioche toast, there
is more negative space than positive. A slice of truffle lies on a
half circles of terrine and toasted brioche. They are sprinkled
with fleur de sel and coarse pepper. There is nothing else on the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is modern and stark, but not merely stylish.
Its simplicity has a way of making the dish more welcoming than
cool, complex, architectural formations.
</P>
<P>
   It is a useful technique. If you have a dish with just a few
elements, there is no reason to fill up the plate. Arranging food
plainly naturally calls attention to it: there are no other
distractions. And if the food is good, no one will be disappointed
by the spareness.
</P>
<P>
   Another Asian influence has been the use of tableware to give a
sense of variety. A plate with an interesting shape or finish can
transform something ordinary. Ceviche presented in a martini glass,
for instance, somehow feels more special than ceviche on a flat
white plate. Lobster soup in an oversize bowl feels grander. Beets
on a narrow rectangular plate do not seem a humble root.
</P>
<P>
   Tadashi Ono, the chef at Sono, and Takako Yoneyama, the chef at
Taka, both potters, design and make their own dishes to suit their
needs. Every plate at Sono is slightly different _ and memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Even without homemade pottery, though, this approach can easily
be translated in a home kitchen. All you have to do is free
yourself from the strictures of the five-piece place setting. Why
not use large pasta bowls for a fine little salad or teacups for
soup?
</P>
<P>
   More and more, chefs design dishes that invite diners to get
involved. At Bond Street, Ms. Rodriguez wraps the ends of lamb
chops in raffia to encourage picking them up. Vongerichten places
caraway crisps between mounds of crab salad and has the waiter
instruct diners to spoon it onto the crisps.
</P>
<P>
   Plating food takes practice. Even great chefs make mistakes.
Cyril Renaud, the chef at La Caravelle, wanted to present a scallop
tartare as naturally as possible, so he spooned it into a scallop
shell and rested it on a bed of cornmeal, to suggest sand. It
doesn't seem the kind of dish that requires an instruction manual,
but Renaud said that some diners tried to eat the shell and others
sprinkled the cornmeal over it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough lesson: if it looks good enough, people will want
to eat it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
