<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `MILLIONAIRE' SUCCESS; `SOPRANOS' REDUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cashing In On `Millionaire'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the November sweep officially ending Wednesday night,
network program executives spent Tuesday taking stock, and talking
about game shows.
</P>
<P>
   The seismic effect of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' was
especially apparent at ABC, whose executives literally felt the
earth move when discussing the show in a conference call with
reporters. Two minor earthquakes rumbled through Los Angeles during
the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' was unquestionably the engine that drove ABC to
its first sweep-month victory in five years, lifting the network by
more than 30 percent from last November. In contrast, NBC and CBS
were down slightly and Fox down precipitously from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything said by every network executive Tuesday
concerned ``Millionaire'' in some way. ABC Entertainment
co-chairmen Stu Bloomberg and Lloyd Braun assertively put off all
inquiries about the network's plans for the show, saying they would
make an announcement later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is expected to make ``Millionaire'' a regular part of its
schedule, showing it up to three times a week. It ran for 18
consecutive nights in November. But Braun said, ``We're still
debating a lot of different scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   So are programmers at the other networks, who know a juggernaut
when they see one. NBC announced that it was rescheduling its most
ambitious mini-series of the season, a 10-hour fantasy epic called
``The 10th Kingdom,'' to try to get it out of the way of the
``Millionaire'' express. Instead of starting the first Sunday in
February, the show has been postponed until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at three networks said they were developing game
shows designed to compete with ``Millionaire,'' which was adapted
from a British show. (Fox already has one on the air, ``Greed,''
which has fared passably well.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC cited another game show being developed by ``Millionaire''
executive producer Michael Davies. Neither Braun nor Bloomberg
mentioned its name, but Davies had disclosed that he had bought the
format rights to another British game show, this one called
``Mastermind,'' and was working on getting it onto the air soon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing in show business right now is as valuable as a
British game show. CBS said Tuesday that it, too, had purchased
format rights to a British game called ``Winning Lines.'' This one
is even from the same producers as ``Millionaire.'' CBS Television
president Leslie Moonves said Tuesday that it would be on the air
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has produced several rehearsals of an updated version of the
1950s game show ``21.'' NBC Entertainment president Garth Ancier
said the show had promise but was not ready to become part of NBC's
schedule. He added, with obvious hope in his heart, that when
``Millionaire'' is shown more often ``it will become more
humdrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun called that wishful thinking, and Bloomberg dismissed it,
saying that ``Millionaire'' was a ``true cultural phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   But the coming glut of game shows is at least indirectly
intended to help exhaust the public fascination with
``Millionaire.'' One senior programmer said he planned to get as
many game shows out in front of the public as soon as possible to
wear out the phenomenal appeal of ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves, though he agreed he was ``playing the copycat game,''
lamented the move to game shows, saying it was ``not the best
trend'' for network television.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said that 13 of 17 ABC series had improved their
ratings during the sweep month, which he attributed to a halo
effect from ``Millionaire.'' There have been questions, however,
about whether the game show's success has truly carried over to
other ABC shows. David Poltrack, the executive vice president for
research at CBS, said there was ``minimal trickle-down effect''
from the show and that within a half-hour after it ended most of
its big audience was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But depending on how often ABC adds the show to its regular
schedule, it may not need quite as many new series as it once did.
Braun noted that ABC is adjusting its development philosophy
because of what it expects to get from the ``Millionaire''
franchise. ``It enables us both to fill holes and enhance
development,'' Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   Encore for `Sopranos' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of what is likely to be a surge of interest in
the start of the second season of ``The Sopranos'' in January, HBO
announced Tuesday that it would pre-empt a large portion of its
prime-time schedule for a week next month to run a marathon of the
first 13 episodes of the series.
</P>
<P>
   HBO executives said they had never before cleared out so much of
their schedule for an entire week, nor had they devoted so much
program time in one week to a single show. But HBO has never had a
show with a following like the one that ``The Sopranos'' built last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Dec. 26, HBO will rerun two episodes of ``The
Sopranos'' back to back every night at 10 and 11 Eastern time for
five consecutive nights, through Dec. 30. On Sunday night, Jan. 2,
the network will run the final three episodes back to back starting
at 9.
</P>
<P>
   All of this will begin what HBO executives called a huge
publicity push to lead up to the 13 episodes of the second season,
which is to begin Sunday, Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which is shot on location mainly in New York and New
Jersey, is wrapping up production in the next two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
