<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-N     11-30 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 5,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-CENTER (Washington) _ The Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts, once thought of as the imperial heart of culture
in an acultural town, has transformed itself into a palace of the
people. The chairman, James A. Johnson, a Minnesotan with pedigree
credentials in the Democratic Party, is unabashed about his
populist bent. He takes pride in describing the dramatic increase
in the number of performances at the center: more than 3,000
compared with half that number more than five years ago. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS-ADES-MUSIC (Undated) _ Thomas Ades, the English composing
phenom (still under 30) is really something, and the records keep
coming. The fourth and latest Ades disc from EMI Classics brings
``Asyla,'' the 23-minute orchestral tetrad that has just won its
young composer Louisville University's Grawemeyer Award, the
biggest plum the classical-music world now offers. Is all the
shouting merited? Yes indeed. If the attention being paid Ades, 28,
is another sign of the times in classical music, there is reason,
at this time of millennial stock-taking and auguries of doom, for
renewed hope. By Richard Taruskin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DELHOMME-CINEMATOGRAPHER (Paris) _ ``Being a cinematographer is,
in many ways, like being a psychoanalyst,'' said Benoit Delhomme
recently at his studio here on the outskirts of the city. ``We let
the director of a film talk, and then, from just a few key words,
we guess what's in his head and come up with the images that he
seeks.'' Delhomme, 38, who is one of France's leading
cinematographers and one of the few whose work is sought outside
his homeland, has fashioned the lighting, camerawork and imagery of
some of the most distinctive directors working today. By Laura
Winters.
</P>
<P>
   CRADLE-WILL-ROCKS-FILM (Undated) _ Tim Robbins, who has taken on
politically charged subjects in his previous films ``Dead Man
Walking'' and ``Bob Roberts,'' brings Marc Blitzstein's 1930s
musical play back to life in his new movie, ``Cradle Will Rock,''
opening on Friday. Not simply a cinematic rendering of Blitzstein's
play, or the story of its premiere, the film is a panoramic view of
New York in the Depression years, filled with such historical
characters as Nelson Rockefeller, Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo,
William Randolph Hearst, Margherita Sarfatti (Mussolini's former
mistress who wrote pro-Fascist stories for Hearst) and the young
Orson Welles, a fireball of theatrical energy. By David Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH-FILMS (New York) _ This month, the Film Society of
Lincoln Center, in collaboration with the Instituto Cervantes,
which supports Spanish culture abroad, the Spanish Society of
Authors and Publishers and the Spanish Ministry of Education and
Culture, will present 18 independent films, most of them American
premieres, from Friday through December 24 at the Walter Reade
Theater. By Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (New York) _ Vincent Canby reviews ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' at the Martin Beck Theater and ``Putting It Together at the
Ethel Barrymore Theater. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-THEATER-Q&AMP;A (New York) _ A Q&AMP;A with the playwright, Arthur
Kopit, about his thriller of an Internet hacker who ruins a
couple's life. By Katie Hafner. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROUSSEVE-DANCE (New York) _ By now David Rousseve is a familiar
face at the Brooklyn Academy of Music. But when he returns this
week, to present his third commissioned piece in seven years, he
will show a side he has never revealed before. Long accustomed to
working with black female vocalists, Rousseve has turned for the
first time to classical music _ and not just any classical music.
He punctuates the new piece, a collage of dance and theater called
``Love Songs,'' with the enigmatic strains of Wagner, whose
famously heroic scores and anti-Semitic sentiments made him an
emblem of German nationalism. By Christopher Reardon. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHANTICLEER-CHORUS (Undated) _ Organizations, like human beings,
go through periods of transition. Chanticleer, the San
Francisco-based male vocal ensemble, has weathered its share of
changes in recent years. ``Chanticleer is definitely at a
crossroads,'' said Lynn Luckow, its chairman of the board. ``The
question is, how do you build on past successes to ensure future
significance?'' The 12-voice chorus, named for the rooster in
Chaucer's ``Nun's Priest's Tale'' whose singing was ``swich a
joye,'' will perform three concerts of Christmas music in New York
this week. By Sarah Bryan Miller.
</P>
<P>
   MENOTTI-MUSIC (Undated) _ At 88, Gian Carlo Menotti claims to
tire more easily than of old and apologizes for memory lapses, but
his enjoyment of life remains as evident as his recall, and he
tells stories charmingly. This jesting reminiscence complements
better-known accounts of the genesis of ``Amahl and the Night
Visitors,'' the most popular not only of his operas but probably of
all operas. As the Italian-born composer-director-librettist told
the tale in an essay for the original-cast recording, he had
accepted a commission to write a Christmas opera for the National
Broadcasting Company. The opera's world premiere was on Dec. 24,
1951, the first written for television and based on the ``Adoration
of the Magi.'' By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-SONGWRITERS (Undated) _ What does it mean when artists
who are strongly identified as singer-songwriters record entire
albums of other people's songs? Two recent releases, ``In Spite of
Ourselves'' by John Prine (Oh Boy) and ``I'll Take Care of You'' by
Mark Lanegan (Subpop), raise that question from contrasting, but
equally intriguing vantages. By Anthony DeCurtis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MET-SCROLL-PAINTING (New York) _ The Metropolitan Museum has
heard it many times in the past two years, after one of its most
highly touted recent acquisitions, the Chinese scroll painting
titled ``Riverbank,'' attributed to the 10th-century artist Dong
Yuan, was accused of being a 20th-century forgery. The word is
likely to crackle in the air like static at the Met next Saturday,
when the painting _ a towering depiction of a mountainous landscape
being swept by a violent storm _ gets its day in court at an
international symposium titled ``Issues of Authenticity in Chinese
Painting.'' Leading the prosecution will be the art historian James
Cahill, who contends that ``Riverbank'' dates from the 1950s and is
the work of the Chinese artist, collector and forger extraordinaire
Zhang Daqian (1899-1983). By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   GOLD-RUSH-TREASURE (Undated) _ A Gold-Rush treasure, burnished
by 130 years in the icy depths of the Atlantic, has finally reached
its destination _ New York. Mined, sifted, assayed or minted in
California, the three tons of gold bars, ingots, coins and dust was
shipped on Aug. 20, 1857 from San Francisco bound for New York but
not even a small portion of it ever made it until a year ago. By
Rita Reif. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MORIYAMA-PHOTOGS (New York) _ Daido Moriyama is the photographer
of the season in New York. With three exhibitions this fall _ at
Japan Society, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and the Laurence
Miller Gallery _ and a handsome catalog on his life and work (from
the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and DAP), has garnered more
scholarly devotion than any Japanese photographer has ever enjoyed
in this country. At the age of sixty-one, he is finally a star,
albeit a dark one. Given Moriyama's acknowledged debts to American
artists, especially to the harsh, confrontational graphic style of
William Klein and the rancid, pop sensibility of Andy Warhol, this
belated recognition is as instructive as it is overdue. By Richard
B. Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Hot travel deals. By Janet Piorko.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
