<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX     11-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire in the mountains exhilarating, frightening
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 2.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ As forest fires raged through thousands of
acres in North Georgia recently, many of us carried on the
tradition of intentionally and carefully burning brush, trees and
stumps to improve our own private ridges, hollows and hills.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is inescapable. One day I am setting fire to piles of
briars, twigs, little tree sections. A few days later, while
fishing for bream with friend Charles Abernathy, I am watching a
shiny, red helicopter swoop down repeatedly over the placid lake,
dip out huge bucketsful of water and whirr off into the blue sky to
help douse flames.
</P>
<P>
   Fire had been on my mind for months, as I had begun a long-term
transformation of the long, steep slope down to Fightingtown Creek,
a slope featuring The Rock, which is some 20 feet across _ and, I
am discovering, many smaller rocks that crop out of the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, I want to expose as many of those rocks as
possible. To do that, I need to get rid of the myriad suckering
sourwood stumps, briar thickets, oak saplings, scraggly pines,
replacing them with plants such as beautyberry, hearts-a-bustin',
Christmas ferns, sweet shrub. These, along with the already present
holly, ferns, dogwood, wild rhododendron and laurel, ginger,
rattlesnake plantain, will make fine understory plants to the big
old trees left standing.
</P>
<P>
   In October, I took my first whack at this monumental task,
pruning, sawing, pulling and chopping enough unwanted growth to
make four manageable piles. As many of my mountain friends know, it
makes a lot more sense to burn this stuff in place than to try
hauling it off the aerobic slope.
</P>
<P>
   So, I lit up a pile, and after it was safely burned out, I lit
the next. Until all piles were gone. My first burn.
</P>
<P>
   Not since I was a child in Meridian, Miss., and East St. Louis,
Ill., had I done any outdoor burning. Then, it was leaves (which
now get composted), their roasting fragrance a melding dictated by
the trees providing the leaves _ in much the same way a combination
of grapes creates a wine altogether different from any of its
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this burn on the ridge was not my childhood leaf-roasting;
this was alternately scary, educational, mesmerizing and,
ultimately, satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Before the flames and smoke, I did not notice how many breezes
flitted around that ridge, how the prevailing ones seemed to come
off the creek, dashing ominously toward the cabin, freezing me in
place, rake and water hose at the ready, eyes following any errant
embers, lest they head for the roof or a nearby patch of dry
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   How dry this burning can make your insides, even though you seem
not to sweat. Afterward, I drank six glasses of water and still had
muscle cramps. I'll never burn again without drinking water nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It is all too easy to forget to drink amid the power and fury of
even a small controlled fire. Seeing and feeling the flames and
heat dance and snake around the ridge, I got a sense of what the
big fires must be like.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Evans knows firsthand; the U.S. Forest Service's Conasauga
River coordinator for the Cherokee and Chattahoochee National
Forests has fought and seen his share of conflagrations. I talked
with him after my burn _ the day before he joined the battle
against November fires in Fannin, Gilmer, Union and Lumpkin
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who is based in Blue Ridge and advises property owners on
how to burn safely, noted that my frisky fire was typical. ``Fire
runs uphill,'' he said, ``and it gathers speed faster than people
realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, especially noteworthy in the shrub-rich mountains, ``On a
warm, sunny day, laurel burns almost like gasoline'' because of its
oily leaves. Be wary of laurel too close to your house, Evans
advises, also urging burners to keep the hose handy and primed,
have a rake and shovel at the ready to control fire and, if
necessary, dig dirt to help extinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   Too, he warns against floppy, flammable clothing, noting that,
``Unfortunately, every year somebody trips and falls into a fire,
wearing fuzzy slippers and a fleece bathrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid precautions, including watching out for ground-dwelling
birds and other wildlife, Evans, like other foresters, hails fire
(during plants' dormant season) for renewing the land, as burning
can open space, admit light, release nitrogen and yield diversity
of small, tender plants like lady-slipper and orchid: ``You get a
floral response.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what I'm looking for as I slash and burn plant
trash on the slope of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May is a regular columnist on gardening lifestyles for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. E-mail him at
leemay(at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
