<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5326 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ROSES02-COX     11-30 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Georgian's rosy courtship can't be nipped in bud by freeze
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Dec. 2.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALTON, Ga. _ Sam Pullen puts on his jacket, turns up the
collar, grabs his snippers and braves the brisk wind of a
late-autumn morning to launch his daily ritual.
</P>
<P>
   True gardeners seem to find a way to grow plants under almost
any conditions, at any time of year.
</P>
<P>
   But roses? In late November? We're not talking a few confused
strays that pop during a warm fall. Sam and his wife, Allene,
produce dozens of long-stem beauties, which he shares with women
all over this carpet capital every day in nursing homes, banks,
real estate offices, his fitness center, even the Waffle House _
each in exchange for a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``When frost hits, I just turn the water on them to wash it off,
and they'll last until the first freeze,'' says the retired
insurance man.
</P>
<P>
   During peak season in June, Sam has picked as many as 30 dozen
in one day from up to 750 hybrid tea and floribunda bushes covering
two large beds in his yard. He averages 10 dozen a day in summer
and as late as last week managed to fill two buckets with several
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you pick them, the more they bloom,'' Sam says, ``It
takes a lot out of the rosebush if you don't cut them often.''
</P>
<P>
   His is a hobby that started nearly 20 years ago with a couple
dozen bushes, which he added to year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, after having two-thirds of his larynx removed
because of throat cancer, Sam reduced his plots to some 450 bushes,
and Allene took over much of the work. ``It wasn't too bad because
we don't grow them for the bushes,'' she says. ``We grow them for
their long stems'' _ and the joy that comes from watching the faces
of strangers glow when Sam hands them a rose.
</P>
<P>
   He's now fully recovered but, because of a tracheotomy, speaks
in a whisper, a factor that also catches rose recipients off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, some women will refuse to take them because they
think you're looking for a donation or a handout,'' he says. What
he asks is ``for a little sugar,'' and nine out of 10 oblige. ``I
don't always get it,'' Sam says, ``but at least I've never been
slapped.''
</P>
<P>
   His day starts with two hours of debudding (removing one bud for
every two to make room for bigger, tighter blooms) while cutting
the 12- to 15-inch stems of partially opened buds. He immediately
places the stems, cut diagonally just above the node of the last
cut, in a bucket of water in preparation for his run. Sam uses no
gloves, yet his hands show no battle scars from thorns.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the notorious maintenance, which includes watering
an inch per week and applying pesticides and fungicides every seven
to 10 days and a systemic fertilizer every six to eight weeks.
``They're definitely high maintenance, but if you plant them in
morning sun, in well-drained soil, they're not a big problem,''
Allene says.
</P>
<P>
   Sam loads several buckets of his multicolored roses _ the pink
variety ``perfume delight'' is his pick because his mother grew
them _ into the back of his Chrysler Town and Country van and heads
out on his route.
</P>
<P>
   First stop is the Waffle House off I-75 where Sam takes his
bounty booth to booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little old ladies here love him,'' says waitress Tracy
Griffin. ``He just likes to brighten their day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam's M.O. is to hand over a long-stem beauty and after the
woman accepts, point to his cheek, asking for his trademark
``sugar.'' When she agrees, Sam turns quickly so that his payment
gets planted right on the kisser.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're tricky,'' says Tiffany Ruble, getting her morning rose
at the Bradley Wellness Center. ``But you did bring my favorite
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of others get theirs, too, and with his bucket near
empty, Sam heads back into the cold to head home.
</P>
<P>
   As a chill blankets the North Georgia mountains, his thoughts
turn to preparing his rosebushes for their short winter's nap _
covering them with pine bark mulch until spring returns.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think the downtime will stop Sam from spreading his
little version of sunshine. In winter, he simply gives out tiny
stick-on roses.
</P>
<P>
   The message, if not the gift, is just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Tucking roses into bed before winter
</P>
<P>
   To discourage growth and encourage full dormancy once winter
arrives, All-American Rose Selections, an organization of
commercial garden rose growers and introducers, recommends you:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stop fertilizing six weeks before the first frost.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Allow seedpods to develop instead of clipping spent flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Water plants well throughout autumn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mound mulch around the base of the bush to help prevent
repeated freezing and thawing, which can damage roots and even
canes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place potted roses in open cardboard boxes or other containers
and move them into an unheated building, such as a garage or shed.
Insulate the container with straw, shredded newspaper or Styrofoam
packing material to protect against temperature changes.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
