<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPEN LETTER TO REGIS PHILBIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Regis:
</P>
<P>
   I am a big fan of your show, ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, it drove me crazy when a contestant wasted a lifeline
to answer a question a relatively intelligent beagle would know,
such as: In its solid form, water is called ... A) Silly Putty B)
Jabba the Hut C) the theme song from ``Love Story'' D) ice.
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with these people, Regis? Does that goofy
background music set up some sort of harmonic vibration in their
brain that causes them to forget the things they learned in first
grade? Or maybe they're just dazzled by your suits. Pretty snazzy,
Reeg, I must say. Much better than those loud sport coats you wear
on Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee, the ones that make you look like you just
stepped off a used-car lot.
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject, what is it with Kathie Lee, anyway?
Is she the loudest, most obnoxious woman in the world, or what? You
must have a lot of self-control, that's all I can say.
</P>
<P>
   Where was I? Oh, yeah. Your new show. We watch it every night,
even if Dilbert is on another station. It's about the only thing we
do together as a family, which is sort of pathetic, in one sense,
but I prefer to think of it as a reflection of the excellent
quality of your show.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what it is about ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' that I find so fascinating. One thing that intrigues
me is the qualification test, where the 10 contestant hopefuls try
to put four things in chronological order faster than their
competitors. Like, list the four Spice Girls in descending order of
their first appearance in People magazine. Regis, it would take me
10 minutes just to come up with the names of the Spice Girls (Baby
Spice always eludes me), yet one of the contestants always manages
to answer the question correctly in something like 3.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   What I want to know, Regis, is how someone can solve a problem
like this in 3.72 seconds _ a problem that most Americans would
need several weeks to work on and still get wrong _ and yet have to
burn two lifelines in order to be reasonably confident in saying
that broccoli is a vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, the lifelines are a great idea, Reeg, because
without them some contestants would have a tough time walking away
with $500, let alone $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   I have some questions about the call-a-friend lifeline, though.
For one thing, how do you define the word ``friend?'' Is it a
strict definition, like someone who stood beside you at your
wedding? Or is it a loose definition, like maybe someone you
``know'' through watching TV or reading a magazine? If it's the
less-strict definition, then why do the contestants so often wind
up calling a friend who, if anything, is stupider than the
contestant?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, if I were going to give you a list of ``friends,'' I'd
have names on it like Henry Kissinger, Marilyn vos Savant, Stephen
Hawking, that crowd. I wouldn't be giving you the names of the guys
I go bowling with every Thursday night, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Also, how do you ensure that these invisible ``friends'' don't
cheat, say, by leafing through the Almanac or maybe conferring with
a few hundred thousand of their nearest and dearest friends via a
computer chat room? My guess is you've got some burly AT&AMP;T thugs
working for you, guys who are paid to keep an eye on the so-called
``friends'' and make sure no funny business occurs.
</P>
<P>
   It all boils down to credibility, doesn't it, Reeg?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Reeg (it is OK if I call you Reeg, isn't it?), I just
wanted to tell you how much I enjoy your show. Who knows? I might
even apply to be a contestant if I can just learn to list Martha
Stewart's four favorite glue-gun projects in ascending order of
difficulty in under 3.7 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
