u a BC-DRUGS-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      11-30 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS RISE IN NUMBER OF WOMEN JAILED FOR DRUGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Minn.)   By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new national study shows a remarkable surge in the number of
women incarcerated for drug offenses: an 888 percent jump between
1986 and 1996, in comparison with a rise of 129 percent for nondrug
offenses, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, almost the entire increase in the number of
women sentenced to prison was a result of drug offenses, according
to the study, results of which were released early last month.
</P>
<P>
   The study, a 26-page booklet titled ``Gender and Justice: Women,
Drugs and Sentencing Policy,'' was researched and written by the
Sentencing Project, a national nonprofit organization that promotes
sentencing reform and conducts research on criminal justice issues.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the number of women in prison has increased at
nearly double the rate for men. Minority women, especially blacks
in New York State, are disproportionately affected by drug arrests
and imprisonment, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more men in prison for drug offenses than women,''
said Marc Mauer, assistant director of the Sentencing Project and
co-author of the report. ``But of the women in prison, they are
more likely to be incarcerated for drug offenses than the men in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the women in prison for drug offenses in three states singled
out by the study _ New York, California and Minnesota _ researchers
found substantial variation. Those states were chosen because of
geographical differences, varying sentencing structures, and good
data.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, nearly all _ 91 percent _ of the increase in women
sentenced to prison from 1986 to 1995 was in connection with drug
offenses. In California, drug offenses represented 55 percent of
the increase; in Minnesota, 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the women sentenced to prison for drug offenses in the three
states, many were members of minority groups _ 91 percent in New
York, 54 percent in California and 27 percent in Minnesota _
numbers substantially greater than the minority proportion of each
state's population.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the justice system on Hispanic women varied from
state to state. In New York, in 1995, Hispanic women constituted 44
percent of the women imprisoned for drug offenses, but only 14
percent of the state's population. In California Hispanic women
represented 25 percent of imprisoned drug offenders and 31 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   New York State officials said they could neither confirm nor
contradict the findings because they had not had time to study the
report. ``But what I can say,'' said Caroline Quartararo,
spokeswoman for the governor's criminal justice director, Katherine
N. Lapp, ``is that of the first-time felony drug offenders _ male
or female _ fewer than 10 percent received prison sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauer said there were numerous factors that snared women in the
criminal justice system: the impact of drug abuse on low-income
women; declining economic opportunities for many women; limited
treatment options and the harsh mandatory-sentence policies adopted
in conjunction with the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Mauer also theorized that a greater percentage of women than men
were incarcerated because men were often able to cut a deal with
prosecutors. ``I've heard this anecdotally,'' he said. ``The men
may not be the major drug dealer, so they can cooperate with
prosecutors by giving them the name of the major dealer. The women
may know only their boyfriend as a dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauer said the solution for the high rate of women's
incarceration for drug offenses was drug rehabilitation treatment.
``I think there are studies that show a dollar of treatment is more
effective than a dollar spent in incarceration,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-2TAKE     11-30 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RARELY TAKES MIDDLE-ROAD APPROACH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ There was a Bill Bradley moment a few weeks
ago when saying nothing said it all.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate was surrounded by hundreds
of civic activists in the capital of Iowa, a state crucial to his
quest. They were taking part in a downtown walk that raised money
to find a cure for breast cancer, a disease that once attacked
Bradley's wife, author-professor Ernestine Schlant &UR;  &LR; Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The chatter, echoing off office building walls, was about
politics, weather, cancer and family life. But for a sustained
string of minutes, Bradley talked to no one and met no one's
glance. He shuffled along, a head taller than almost anyone else,
lost temporarily in one of the things a campaigner usually hates:
silence.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is not the usual campaigner. He is not a natural
gladhander. He doesn't do much prancing down the middle of the
road. Most important to his campaign hopes, he is not Vice
President Al Gore. Bradley's canny maximizing of his position as
the ``not Gore'' option in the Democratic primary has made him the
surprise of the political season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore served together in the Senate and grew up, as
the only sons of prominent families, with the dream of becoming
president.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Gore, Bradley has not served at the right hand of the
current and controversial president, Bill Clinton. That
automatically makes Bradley the candidate of change within the
political party of the president, who himself made ``change'' the
buzzword of the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley was a loner in the Senate who split from the
Democratic ranks on a few sensitive issues, he is no moderate from
the mold of the Southerner vice president. Years after lashing
himself in print for being a timid legislator, Bradley calls for a
bigger, bolder use of the federal government to fight poverty,
health care inequities, racial injustice, the proliferation of
handguns and the influence of special interests on campaign
finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only national government can moderate or prevent the
insecurity that the transformation of the American economy has
brought to middle-class lives. Only government can balance the
clout of private power,'' he wrote in his weighty 1996 memoir,
``Time Present, Time Past.'' The former senator from New Jersey who
attended Princeton University and played professional basketball
for the New York Knicks would have a hard time avoiding the
``Northeastern liberal'' tag.
</P>
<P>
   And while Gore has gone through some recent image adjustments in
an attempt to match Bradley's surge, Bradley, 56, plods along with
an air of low-key self-assurance. Through 40 years in the public
spotlight, starting as a high school basketball star in a
Mississippi River town in his native Missouri, he has remained an
intellectual introvert. His calm and sometimes raspy speech, larded
with rhetoric about ideals and brotherhood, is refreshing to some
voters accustomed to candidates who strive for charm and flash.
Other voters just find the Bradley package boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he seems ministerial, that is because he is,'' author John
McPhee wrote in a 1965 book about Bradley's astounding college
basketball career. McPhee also stated that Bradley stood out from
players prone to flamboyance because ``he adorns nothing that he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Words from Bradley's own pen give some explanation to why he
didn't feel an obligation to make small talk in the Des Moines
fund-raising walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not depend on the outside for recognition,'' he once
wrote. ``Some friends say I am functioning in a world that bears
little resemblance to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Bradley campaign looks more conventional every
day, with slick advertising and a fund-raising effort that leans
heavily on contributions from Wall Street financiers, law firms and
colleagues in the world of former sports stars. He has become more
of a gab-and-greet machine. Following the rules of political
engagement, he has begun to respond to Gore's criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   He even gave the press corps _ which he has described in various
writings as largely misguided _ a guided tour of his boyhood haunts
in Crystal City, Mo. But his staff declined to make him available
for an interview for this article.
</P>
<P>
   The town is the best place from which to explain Bradley's
motivation for seeking the presidency. He was the exceptionally
cerebral, exceptionally tall, only child of a father who ran the
town bank and a mother who was a whirlwind of civic activity. The
Republican couple bred their boy for success and courtliness,
providing lessons in everything from French horn and piano to
boxing and golf.
</P>
<P>
   But the idyllic picture wasn't perfect. Bradley endured ``the
frequent silences and somewhat staid moralizing of my parents,''
according to one of four books he has written. Growing up in a
small factory town, Bradley wrote, ``I felt I had something to
prove: that I could win, that I was as good as other people.''
</P>
<P>
   In solitary practice sessions, Bradley developed a precision-mad
approach to basketball as he grew to his adult height of 6 feet, 5
inches. He scrubbed oil and dead skin from his fingertips to feel
the leather ball better. A scientific test showed that while the
average person can see 47 degrees upward when focused horizontally,
Bradley could see 70 degrees upward.
</P>
<P>
   During his high school years, when he served as president of the
Missouri Association of Student Councils, he also witnessed
prejudice against blacks _ a subject that became a focus of his
later life as a basketball pro, senator and White House contender.
According to Bradley, his Little League baseball team, which
represented the ethnic mix of Crystal City, walked out of a
Missouri restaurant that had refused to serve the black members.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, in a memoir about his life on the road in the
National Basketball Association, he would write about how his
personality and his politics changed because of interaction with
black teammates such as Walt Frazier and Earl ``The Pearl'' Monroe,
whose upbringings had been more challenging than his. The result,
Bradley said, was that ``I regard authority a little more
skeptically than I once did. I am more interested in experiencing
life than analyzing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a congressional intern in 1964, Bradley was present at the
Capitol when U.S. Sen. Barry Goldwater of Arizona, the Republican
Party's presidential nominee, voted against major civil rights
legislation. Bradley says that moment is what drove him away from
his family's political alignment and into the Democratic Party. It
came in the same year he won an Olympic gold medal as a member of
the U.S. basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley legend of perfectionism continued in the classrooms
and the basketball games at Princeton University. Coach Butch Van
Breda Kolff declared that Bradley was ``happiest when he can deny
himself pleasure.'' Bradley even balked at becoming a professional
athlete, saying that the money and the attention could be
corrupting.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the New York Knicks after a period of soul searching
and study at Oxford University in England as a Rhodes Scholar. He
refused commercial endorsement contracts, saying that he was
getting more offers than his black teammates.
</P>
<P>
   On a team that won two championships, Bradley became known as a
player who could outthink, if not out-hustle, the opposition; who
could ``move without the ball.'' It is one of the facets of his
sports career that has become a ready symbol for the race against
Gore, because Bradley has moved from long-shot to formidable
contender without the backing of party power brokers or a superior
campaign treasury. Instead he has presented himself as an unhurried
underdog who has reached out to gays, blacks, gun control advocates
and other key Democratic voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   As a basketball player, Bradley was teased by his teammates for
his upright, bookish approach to life. He challenged that image
occasionally, once revealing that he had a ``pregame fantasy
ritual'' of staring at the same three attractive New York women in
the stands. Nevertheless, some of his locker room nicknames were
``senator'' and ``president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when Bradley retired from the hoops game, no one was
surprised that he decided to run for office. Nor was anyone shocked
that a popular sports figure with academic credentials could pull
votes in New Jersey, where he lived among suburban fans of the New
York team.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Bradley the lawmaker was the same as Bradley the
jock: enigmatic and brainy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not a bold kind of person, but somebody who would do
his job very well and was completely trustworthy _ sort of the way
he played basketball,'' said Gerald Pomper, a Rutgers University
political science professor who supported Bradley for the Senate
seat. ``He was not the guy who took the spectacular shot, but he
would work very hard at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marveling at Bradley's presidential campaign, which is based on
sweeping proposals such as a plan to extend health insurance to the
uninsured, Pomper added: ``The idea of him as a crusader is
somewhat out of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's Senate voting record is hard to pigeonhole, a fact
illustrated by Gore's criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recently attacked Bradley from the left, saying that
Bradley should not have voted in the Senate to fund a
Republican-backed experiment in giving government funds to parents
who send their children to private schools. Gore has also attacked
from the right, saying Bradley's health care proposal would
constitute a risky government spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley voted with most Democrats against the use of military
force against Iraq as proposed by President Bush. Bradley instead
favored continued economic sanctions against Saddam Hussein's Iraqi
government. Bradley also opposed Clinton's welfare reform package,
saying its time limits for welfare recipients were unjust.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the spectrum, Bradley was, in his own
words, President Reagan's ``strongest ally in Congress'' on closing
federal income tax loopholes as part of the Republican package to
lower tax rates. Bradley was also one of 11 Democrats in the Senate
who voted in 1986 to give $100 million to the Nicaraguan Contra
forces, a favorite Reagan cause that ultimately led to a White
House scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show his Senate votes matched Gore's about 80 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But as a candidate, Bradley has steadfastly gone farther than
Gore in proposing new laws with a traditionally Democratic,
activist government bent. He wants all handguns to be licensed and
registered as cars are, for example. His broad proposals addressing
health insurance, child care and poverty will cost $78 billion a
year by his own tally, and he says the money for them can be found
in budget surpluses. The federal government should fund campaigns
for federal office to keep special interest money out, he proposes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says gays should be able to serve openly in the
military, not under the restriction of the Clinton administration's
``don't ask, don't tell'' rule. In pressing harder than Gore for
campaign finance reform, Bradley has even said that special
interest groups that run political advertisements should pay for
their opponents to respond.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, he voted against ethanol subsidies and other farm
support programs. He now supports the items as a presidential
candidate sensitive to the verdict of Iowans. It's not a flip-flop,
Bradley says, but rather a change of views, from considering the
needs of New Jersey to considering the needs of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in a campaign based on big ideas, Bradley has no specific
proposals to back up his idea that race relations are the deepest
problem facing the nation. He promises instead to promote unity
from the presidential bully pulpit and to appoint government chiefs
who will keep the principle at the top of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley recently told Democrats at a political supper in Iowa:
``One of the reasons I did this (run for president) in the first
place was to try and restore confidence in the public will.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Bradley's own will to be outspoken and to reveal himself
in the contest stems from a political crucible in 1990, when he ran
for a third Senate term.
</P>
<P>
   He had already countenanced some private, national surveys to
find out if he would be an attractive presidential candidate. His
re-election to the Senate seemed a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley barely pulled out a victory against Republican
Christine Todd Whitman, who later became New Jersey governor.
Analysts said Bradley, already in a trough as an aloof incumbent,
had wounded himself by not speaking out about state tax increases
proposed by the Democratic governor, Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   The close call led to a stunning self-flagellation by Bradley.
In ``Time Present, Time Past,'' he wrote that the election results
forced him to examine his personal and political shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not waded into turbulent water by defining my views
clearly, preferring instead the comfort of ambiguity or silence,''
he said. ``Ambition had fueled a desire to please and had choked
off my leadership impulses. For much of my career I had no
authentic political voice.''
</P>
<P>
   With his image bruised, Bradley passed up the chance to run for
the 1992 Democratic presidential nomination. He and his wife faced
a different kind of challenge that year when she underwent
treatment for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Short and sparkly, unaware of basketball when she met him,
Ernestine Bradley is her husband's opposite in several ways. He has
talked about the pain of being booed and spit upon when he was
making a rocky transition from college basketball to the pro
league, but he says that dealing with his wife's illness was the
biggest test he has faced. Ernestine Bradley, a naturalized U.S.
citizen born in Germany seven years before her husband, credits him
with handling many of the details of her illness _ treatment
schedules, the science of cancer _ while they both dealt with the
emotional strain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year after Republicans took control of both
chambers of Congress, Bradley announced he would not seek another
Senate term in 1996. ``Politics is broken,'' he declared, citing
partisan gridlock and public cynicism. He flirted with the idea of
running for president in 1996 as an independent candidate against
Clinton. This has led Gore to question Bradley's Democratic Party
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is trying to use what happened next to turn the tables
on Gore. In 1997 and 1998, Bradley lectured, wrote and consulted
his way across the country. Those experiences, combined with his
basketball career, gave him outsider insights that Gore lacks, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went off to do my work with the American people,'' he
explained at a recent Iowa campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the period also gave Bradley time to develop federal
policy ideas, court potential contributors for his presidential run
and hone his political pitch in relative obscurity _ while Gore was
scarred by a campaign fund-raising scandal and Clinton endured
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   So as he courted about 30 voters in the living room of a
lawyer-supporter's artsy home in a Des Moines suburb one recent
evening, Bradley was a complex, lanky package: the outsider
candidate who has been on the inside, the man with a plan to fix
what he had declared broken four years earlier, a high-brow Huck
Finn in his talk about his riverside boyhood and black-white
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Looking into the receptive faces of physicians, teachers and
other professionals, Bradley said he was running against Gore's
``entrenched power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we've got `the people,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Bradley got a look at how his rival's entrenched
interests are real people, too. In a conscious foray into Gore
territory, Bradley drove to a Democratic dinner at a union hall in
Newton, Iowa, where unions that represent workers at an appliance
manufacturing plant are backing the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Gore supporters stood outdoors near the entrance,
holding Gore campaign signs and planning to chant slogans as
Bradley passed by. But then they got a look at how Bradley's
disarming approach to the campaign has made him the viable
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   With a sheepish grin, Bradley unfolded himself from his campaign
van, walked directly to the Gore folks and started shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you? Nice to see you,'' Bradley said. ``Now everybody
can come in and get warm.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
