<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5336 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN-COX     11-30 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GSU gets a thrill from QB Hill
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ Throughout his career, Georgia Southern
quarterback Greg Hill has impressed opponents with his speed and
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victim, Northern Arizona, was awestruck after Hill
accounted for six touchdowns in the Eagles' 72-29 victory in the
first round of the Division I-AA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anybody who can run that option better, I'd like
to see it,'' Northern Arizona quarterback Travis Brown said. ``Talk
about a big-play guy, he could hurt you any time.''
</P>
<P>
   With Heisman Trophy candidate Joe Hamilton at Georgia Tech and
Quincy Carter at Georgia, Hill hasn't received enormous amounts of
publicity for his efforts at quarterback this season. But he is the
primary reason why Georgia Southern has returned to the I-AA
playoffs. The Eagles will host Massachusetts in the quarterfinals
Saturday at Paulson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is the leader of an option offense that has scored 42 or
more points 20 times in the past two seasons. The 72 points against
Northern Arizona was the most in postseason history for Georgia
Southern, but it wasn't even the highest total this season _ the
Eagles opened the season with a 76-0 victory over Fayetteville
State.
</P>
<P>
   Hill appears to be at the top of his game at the right time. To
end the regular season, he rushed for 219 yards and a touchdown
against Furman and 72 yards and three touchdowns against
Jacksonville State.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, he has gained 1,290 yards and scored 20 rushing
touchdowns and has hit on 60 percent of his passes for 1,362 yards
and 11 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, he brings a lot of big-play capability because of
his great quickness and speed,'' Georgia Southern coach Paul
Johnson said. ``I feel, the more Greg has played, the better he's
gotten, because he understands the offense so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill has benefited from the presence of one of the most prolific
ball carriers in the history of I-AA football _ sophomore fullback
Adrian Peterson. But Peterson, with his 3,547 rushing yards and 63
touchdown runs in two seasons, is aware of the main reason he and
the team have been so successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Greg. He's in control out there,'' Peterson said. ``If
teams move in close and try to key on me, Greg will make athe team
spread out. He'll find another way to hurt 'em. He takes the
pressure off me.''
</P>
<P>
   What Hill has brought to a Georgia Southern offense that has
been refined under third-year head coach Paul Johnson is a package
almost certain to produce big numbers. Hill is fast, running the
40-yard dash in 4.44 seconds, quick on his feet and and an
excellent decision-maker with the ball in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can talk all they want to about Peterson, who is a
great back, but Hill is the key in that offense,'' Furman coach
Bobby Johnson said. ``The things that guy does (are) almost
unbelievable. He can hurt you every way possible on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill recently became the first player in I-AA history to rush
and pass for more than 3,000 yards each in his career. At a slender
5 feet 11, 163-pounds, Hill still is considerably larger then he
was the year he led the Riverview High Rams of Sarasota, Fla., to
the District 8-AAAAAA and South Florida championships back in '94.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his size, and his distaste for flying, are a few
reasons he ended up in Statesboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I led my high school team to a 13-1 record, but I weighed only
140 pounds,'' Hill said. ``I guess that 140 kept a lot of
recruiters away.''
</P>
<P>
   But The Citadel, Western Kentucky and Ohio University were more
than willing to take a chance on a slender kid who was efficient in
directing Riverview High's triple-option offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first college visit was to Georgia Southern, and I flew _
for the first time _ to Atlanta,'' Hill said. ``I had three or four
more visits lined up after that, but I found out on that first one
that I didn't care too much about flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I decided right away that it was going to be Georgia
Southern for me,'' Hill said. ``They ran an offense similiar to the
one we ran at my high school, and there was the winning tradition.
Plus, it's closer to home than the other schools that were
recruiting me. I could drive instead of fly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Hill, a redshirt sophomore in '97, who replaced injured
starter Kenny Robinson and helped to lead the Eagles to the
Southern Conference title. With a 4-1 record as a starter that
year, Hill rushed for 896 yards and scored 14 touchdowns for the
Eagles, who finished 10-3 after a loss to Delaware in the second
round of the '97 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the most satisfying things to happen to me here
_ coming in after Kenny was injured and leading the team to that
conference title,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill since has guided the Eagles to another conference title
outright and a share of the '99 league crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an offensive lineman, you know that if you can go down
field and get a piece of a safety or move a linebacker just a
little bit, Greg is going to make a big play,'' Eagles All-American
senior guard Mark Williams said. ``He makes you want to give that
extra effort, because that's what you're going to get from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
