<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINGER-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN SUES JACK-IN-THE-BOX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Texas woman has sued Jack-in-the-Box because a
bathroom door allegedly slammed on her hand last year and tore off
flesh from her fingertip.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Barrs of Houston claims in the state district court
lawsuit she filed last week that a Jack-in-the-Box employee
``peeled the amputated fingertip off of (sic) the door jam and
returned it ... so that it could later be surgically reattached.''
</P>
<P>
   The alleged mishap occurred Nov. 5, 1998, at a Jack-in-the-Box
restaurant located at 4232 Highway 6 North.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Schellhorn, spokesman for San Diego, Calif.-based
Jack-in-the-Box, said the company regrets ``the extremely
unfortunate incident'' and it will try to quickly resolve the
dispute ``to the satisfaction of both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Jack-in-the-Box has attempted to contact Barrs'
attorneys, but the company's calls were not returned. He said he
did not have information on whether there was a problem with the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Barrs' attorney, Ross Sears II, said he has no record of being
contacted by Jack-in-the-Box. He said he sent a settlement demand
letter to the company, but it never responded.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said the flesh was surgically reattached to his client's
finger, but scarring is still visible. He said his client is an
elderly woman, and she could not control the bathroom door because
it was unreasonably heavy and it shut too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney declined to say how much he will seek in damages.
He said the restaurant chain has not paid for any of the medical
expenses incurred by his client.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said Barrs was exiting the bathroom when the door slammed
shut toward her and trapped her hand against the door jam. The
attorney said the restaurant may have installed a safer door after
the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Jack-in-the-Box is accused of failing to operate the door and
its hinge safely, failing to repair the problem and failing to warn
the public of possible danger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
