A5339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX     11-30 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' leading tackler Carter out for seasonBy Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second season in a row, Falcons strong safety
Marty Carter will finish one tackle short of averaging 10 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's season ended after 11 games Tuesday when he was placed
on injured reserve with a partially torn medial collateral ligament
in his right knee. He suffered the injury in Sunday night's 34-28
loss at Carolina. He will not need surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' leading tackler, Carter was replaced by cornerback
Derrick Gardner, who began the season on the practice squad and was
released on Oct. 20 after playing in two games. Carter had six pass
breakups, one interception and one fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Carter, 29, hurts the team because of his range of
coverage. His size _ 6-foot-1, 210 pounds _ also made him critical
in run defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of dazed,'' said Carter, who hyperextended his knee
and took a helmet-to-helmet blow on the same play. ``I was in pain
but had no idea from the pain how bad it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a LaGrange, Ga., native, is the fourth player on injured
reserve, joining rookie center Todd McClure and running backs Gary
Downs and Jamal Anderson. All four players have injuries to their
right knees.
</P>
<P>
   After adding two tackles against the Panthers, Carter ended up
with 109 for the season. He had 159 tackles in 16 games last
season, his fourth with the Bears. He has missed just three of 139
games in a nine-year career and started 129 times.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-year veteran Gerald McBurrows will start at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-9 Falcons have two safeties in addition to free safety
Eugene Robinson, second on the team with 85 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Brown, a fourth-round pick in 1998, on Sunday got his first
two tackles as a pro, and rookie Johndale Carty has been playing
special teams but no defense. Starting cornerback Ronnie Bradford
also has experience at safety.
</P>
<P>
   Note: About 10,000 tickets remain for Sunday's home game against
the Saints (2-9). Fans are encouraged to bring an unwrapped toy for
the annual ``Toys for Tots'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
