<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MATH-TEACHING01-COX     11-30 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATH-TEACHING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MATH &AMP; SCIENCE COMMISSION SPLITS ON IMPROVEMENTS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of a national commission wrangled
inconclusively Tuesday over how to improve math and science
teaching in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours of passionate debate were triggered by ex-astronaut
John Glenn, the former Ohio senator who chairs the National
Commission on Mathematics and Science Teaching for the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that as a starting point, we should have in
mind what the objective is, what we want the level of
accomplishment to be,'' Glenn said. ``It seems to me we're flying
blind in some way, if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig R. Barrett, president and chief executive officer of Intel
Corp. suggested that the goal should be raising the performance of
U.S. math and science students to ``number one or number two in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have standardized tests and we can compare ourselves to
other industrialized or semi-industrialized countries,'' Barrett
said. In one such comparison, American 12th graders were among the
lowest-scoring students from 41 countries in the Third
International Mathematics and Science Study (TIMSS).
</P>
<P>
   The TIMSS tests aren't precise enough to decide which nation
ranks first or second, argued school superintendent Paul Kimmelman
of Northbrook, Ill. He suggested that the goal be ``scoring in the
top tier of all the countries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this talk of becoming number one or two or whatever
strikes me as meaningless or worse,'' objected U.S. Rep. Rush Holt
(D-N.J.), an engineer. Improvements should be aimed at increasing
appreciation of math and science, preparing students for jobs,
encouraging innovation and equipping citizens to use scientific
methods to avoid being misled or cheated, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is not so much to see scores on TIMSS tests rise,
but to see readership of astrology pages of the newspapers fall,''
Holt declared.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Keenan, Montana superintendent of public instruction,
endorsed Barrett's formulation, but said the commission should go
further. It should make specific recommendations on educational
methods that could help governors, schools of education, school
boards, principals and teachers reach that goal, Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   But that could interfere in state and local decision-making,
objected Wyoming Gov. Jim Geringer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This commission should not engage itself in trying to mandate
what states or even local school districts should do,'' Geringer
said. He said the commission should seek a consensus on the need
for improvements, but leave it up to ``states to adopt their own
alternatives to improve results.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett countered that such deference to local decision-making
helps explain the failure of a decade of efforts to improve the
performance of U.S. youngsters in science and math.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this broad mush in which education is decentralized,
it's under nobody's control, so nobody's really accountable, and
the system just lurches on,'' Barrett said. ``I would think that is
the problem the commission is trying to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   After its debate, which followed two days of hearings, the
commission adjourned for several weeks with its disagreements
clarified, but still unresolved. Education Secretary Richard Riley
appointed the commission of eight federal officials and 25
prominent citizens in July. It has until next fall to agree on a
final report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
