<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Dec. 1 If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CELEBRATE (Phoenix) - It was envisioned as a huge public party to
ring in the new millennium, but it turns out Phoenix Celebration
2000 organizers purposely created a system to skirt the public open
meetings law, the Arizona Republic has learned. The city gave the
group $25,000 before it even incorporated as a non-profit
organization and a $500,000 loan even though it still doesn't have
its official 501(c)3 status. Now, it looks like the group will have
trouble repaying the loan before private donations have been slow
to trickle in, possibly leaving Phoenix taxpayers with the bulk of
the $1.3 million party bill. By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOBACCO (Phoenix) - Attorney General Janet Napolitano is warning
the maker of Winston cigarettes that it is violating the
multi-billion national tobacco settlement by distributing free
samples children could easily get their hands on. Under the
settlement, tobacco companies are supposed to verify that any
samples go only to adults. Napolitano wants to meet with R.J.
Reynolds to discuss the giveaway, but is prepared to go to court if
the cigarette maker does not abide by the agreement. By MIKE
MCCLOY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
POLLUTION (Phoenix) - For the first time in four years, pollution
levels for carbon monoxide in the Phoenix area have violated
federal health standards, bringing on a high-pollution alert
through Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County environmental officials said they could not
immediately determine what this means for the Valley's status on
carbon monoxide under EPA rules. By MARY JO PITZL. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODYKOONTZ (Undated) _ It would be easy to dismiss ``Ultimate
Trek: Star Trek's Greatest Moments'' as a show that appeals only to
hard-core fans of the series. But what's the point? That's true of
all ``Star Trek'' shows from the original to the ensuing knockoffs.
Trekkies love all things ``Trek''; the rest of us scratch our heads
and wonder whether a pocket protector is really a necessary fashion
accessory. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
