<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-REFS-SUSPENDED-CO     11-30 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REFS-SUSPENDED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC crew who missed call suspended by officials supervisor
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The SEC officiating crew that worked the
Georgia-Georgia Tech game has been suspended by the conference. The
crew will not be allowed to work Saturday's SEC Championship Game
at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, rated the SEC's best, ruled that Georgia's Jasper
Sanks fumbled at the 2-yard line in the final seconds of the game.
Television replays, however, showed that the ball popped out after
Sanks hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   After the ball went into the hands of Georgia Tech's Chris
Young, the officials blew the ball dead. Georgia later maintained
it should have been awarded a safety because Young picked up the
ball near the 1 and then ran back into his own end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at 48-48 when the ball was awarded to Georgia
Tech, which went on to win 51-48 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, referee Al Ford of Florence, Ala., defended the
call, saying that two of his officials had seen the ball come loose
before Sanks was down.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, Bobby Gaston, the SEC supervisor of football
officials, told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution that the officials
had been wrong, based on his viewing of the play on television.
Gaston also received a call on Sunday from Georgia coach Jim
Donnan.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, SEC commissioner Roy Kramer said he would not comment
on the status of the officials. But Kramer was livid over the
situation and on Tuesday the conference suspended the crew from
working Saturday's title game between Florida and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the officials involved in the play also will lose
their postseason assignments. It is not known if this incident will
affect the future employment of these officials by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Ford, Saturday's officiating crew included Bud
Williams of Tallahassee, Fla.; Ron Leatherwood of Waynesville,
N.C.; Al Matthews of Duluth; Blake Parks of Murfreesboro, Tenn.;
Ben Oldham of Lexington, Ky.; and Toby Silberman of Lookout
Mountain, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Suspending officials, particularly an entire crew, is unusual.
Earlier this season, the ACC gave a one-game suspension to the crew
that worked the Clemson-N.C. State game in Raleigh on Oct. 9. In
that game, the crew incorrectly marked off the yardage on a penalty
and allowed the 25-second clock to expire without calling a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
