<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING THE GOD QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN Francisco _ When I was 13, the neighborhood five-and-dime
store was my refuge from life. That's where the comic books were,
and the Hershey almond bars, and the magazine rack with
``forbidden'' publications like Playboy and National Enquirer. Far
more startling than Miss April or the ``Man Cut In Half to Save His
Life!'' though, was the cover of Time magazine for April 8, 1966,
which asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is God Dead?''
</P>
<P>
   A whole generation of baby boomers saw that magazine cover; some
of us recall exactly where we were when we first saw it. The Time
cover was pure black, save for those three chilling words and the
Time logo. God... dead?!
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I had long since abandoned belief in Santa Claus, and was
starting to disbelieve in UFOs, but God? The Creator of the
Universe, who saw every sparrow's fall, heard every prayer and
rewarded the good in heaven? The immaterial, infinite benevolence
without whom the cosmos made no sense?
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the five-and-dime with a Hershey bar in one hand and
a Superman comic in the other, I felt the earth shake beneath my
Keds.
</P>
<P>
   The Time story upset at least one fellow boomer, TV's Jay North
(of ``Dennis the Menace''). He wrote Time: ``In sending you my
views I realize I have two strikes against me: I am a teen-ager,
and I am in show business. ... This God-is-dead premise seems to me
merely a fad; religion will live through it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis'' was right.
</P>
<P>
   A third of a century later, religion is paradoxically more
powerful than ever, while the ``God is dead'' movement in theology
now seems like a dusty intellectual fad of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the 20th century, social scientists
predicted that belief in God would decrease by the end of the
century because of the secularization of society,'' Michael Shermer
explains in this important and highly stimulating book, ``How We
Believe - The Search for God in an Age of Science.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact... the opposite has occurred. Never in history have so
many, and such a high percentage of the population, believed in
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Gallup poll of American adults published in the Wall Street
Journal on Jan. 30, 1996, reported that 96 percent believe in God,
90 percent believe in heaven, 79 percent in miracles, 73 percent
believe there is a hell, 72 percent believe there are angels and 65
percent believe the devil is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Shermer, an agnostic, ask: Why? In the most
``scientific'' century ever, why do both faith and superstition
flourish amid the sleek modernist vistas of urban life, with its
sky-piercing citadels to Reason and Materialism? The answers, as
Shermer shows, are less certain and more complex than you might
have guessed. And for complex philosophical reasons, by the time
you finish reading this book you might conclude that the question
``Does God exist?'' is not only unanswerable, it is unaskable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If science is the art of the soluble, religion is the art of
the insoluble. God's existence is beyond our competence as a
problem to solve,'' suggests Shermer, who teaches science,
technology and evolutionary thought at Occidental College in Los
Angeles and wrote the acclaimed ``Why People Believe Weird Things''
(1997).
</P>
<P>
   In Shermer's senior year of high school, he became a born-again
Christian; in college, he planned to major in theology. Then (he
writes) his faith was challenged by philosophical quandaries,
including the ``Problem of Free Will'' and the ``Problem of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   To oversimplify, the former asks how humans can be ``free'' to
make choices if God is all-knowing and all-powerful; and the latter
asks why evil exists if God is all good (e.g. why didn't He stop
Hitler before the Holocaust?).
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day I have not heard an answer to the Problem of Evil
that seems satisfactory,'' Shermer says. ``As with the Problem of
Free Will, most answers involve complicated twists and turns of
logic and semantic wordplay. ... Either God allowed Nazis to kill
Jews, in which case He is not omnibenevolent, or God could not
prevent Nazis from killing Jews, in which case He is not
omnipotent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Christians would probably respond to such heretical talk by
shrugging and saying, ``God works in mysterious ways.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, many atheists (like myself) respond by saying the
solution is obvious: God doesn't exist - or if He does, then He is
for all effective purposes irrelevant to our lives, as irrelevant
as, say, the inhabitants of another galaxy. Even Shermer observes:
``If by fiat I had to bet on whether there is a God or not, I would
bet that there is not. Indeed, I live my life as if there is no
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet billions of people do believe in God. For almost 300 pages,
Shermer discusses the evolutionary, social and intellectual roots
of faith with a clarity and depth rarely found in popular accounts
of this murky topic. Believers can enjoy his book as much as
skeptics, for he writes respectfully and knowledgeably of religion
while doubting its core precepts.
</P>
<P>
   I have two favorite chapters, including Chapter Eight (an
enthralling anthropological discussion of ``messiah myths'' around
the world, which shows Jesus wasn't alone in claiming to represent
God). Then there's the absolutely brilliant Chapter 10, an analysis
of the theological implications of Stephen Jay Gould's concept of
historical ``contingency.'' The latter notion is best explained by
a question: If the history of planet Earth were a film, and we
rewound it and played it again from the beginning, would the movie
end in the same way, namely with Homo sapiens dominating Earth?
</P>
<P>
   Again, a typical Christian response is: ``God works in
mysterious ways.'' But the hard-headed won't settle for such
answers, especially after being provoked, educated and entertained
by Shermer's excellent book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1835EST &QL; 
