<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SWEEPS-BOS &LR;      11-30 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MILLIONAIRE' THE RIGHT ANSWER FOR ABC DURING SWEEPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the middle of a conference call Tuesday with TV writers, much
of which was spent trumpeting the success of ABC's ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,''(cq no question mark) the network's top two Los
Angeles-based entertainment executives, Stu Bloomberg and Lloyd
Braun, suddenly uttered exclamations of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having an earthquake, guys,'' Bloomberg explained.
</P>
<P>
   Now they know how the rest of the TV industry feels.
</P>
<P>
   For rival networks still reeling from the earthquake that was
``Millionaire,'' today is another day for giving thanks ... that
the November sweeps period is finally ending.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is on the verge of its first sweeps victory in five years
due almost entirely to the popularity of ``Millionaire,'' a sleeper
hit that put a glitzy face on an old format and drew an average of
24.2 million viewers while demolishing everything in its path,
including costly miniseries and specials. ``Millionaire,'' hosted
by Regis Philbin, drew twice as many viewers as the ABC sitcoms it
preempted; of 18 episodes of the quiz show, 11 of them ranked among
the top 20-rated shows for the month.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is how much the ratings punch of
``Millionaire'' carried over into late local newscasts. Though ABC
disputed it, analysts at other networks argued that many of the
viewers who tuned in to ``Millionaire'' did not stay with the ABC
programs that followed.
</P>
<P>
   But numbers only begin to suggest the impact of a show that
Bloomberg Tuesday called ``a cultural phenomenon'' that ``made the
water cooler a noisy and crowded place again.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it has spawned a quiz-show craze reminiscent of
the 1950s, the last time the genre had a decisive claim on prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, ABC is going to bring back ``Millionaire'' early next
year, though executives wouldn't say exactly when, but the network
is also turning to ``Millionaire'' producer Michael Davies to
develop a companion program. NBC is preparing to bring back the old
quiz show, ``21,'' Fox already has its own copycat, ``Greed,'' on
the air, and CBS is resurrecting ``The $64,000 Question'' and
developing a new quiz show called ``Winning Lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wouldn't be putting `Winning Lines' on my schedule
if it wasn't for `Millionaire,' '' admitted CBS Television
president Leslie Moonves. ``When you see a 15 rating ... it would
be silly not to enter the fray.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the copycatting, the success of ``Millionaire'' on a
shoestring budget upended a key assumption of network programming:
that the way to succeed during sweeps _ and deliver big ratings for
the local affiliates that use them to set future ad rates _ was to
produce hugely expensive miniseries, movies and specials. Now, the
question arises: Is it still worth it for networks to invest big
bucks in such extravaganzas when a low-cost, out-of-left-field hit
like ``Millionaire'' can obliterate the competition?
</P>
<P>
   The math certainly didn't add up for ABC's rivals in November.
</P>
<P>
   An average episode of ``Millionaire,'' excluding prizes, cost
about $400,000, a sum ABC reportedly could make back on a single
30-second commercial during the show. By contrast, ``Shake, Rattle
&AMP; Roll'' cost around $10 million and ``Leprechaun'' cost around $20
million, both of which were swamped in the ratings by
``Millionaire,'' as was a ``farewell'' special by Celine Dion on
CBS. Fearing similar damage from ``Millionaire'' during the
February sweeps, NBC West Coast president Scott Sassa said Tuesday
that part of ``The 10th Kingdom,'' a 10-hour miniseries, will be
rescheduled so part of it airs in early March, out of sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thompson, head of Syracuse University's Center for the
Study of Popular Television, said that ``with this `Millionaire'
mutation, a lot of people are going to be thinking, `Why do one of
these elaborate miniseries when you can just slap together a set'
'' for a game show. Noted Thompson: ``The biggest line item in
`Millionaire' is probably the electricity bill for all those goofy
lights.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rash, senior vice president of ad agency Campbell Mithun
Esty in Minneapolis, said the dominance of the quiz show
underscores ``the increasingly unnecessary folly of sweeps month.''
Rash predicted it will add momentum to the push for year-round
measurement of the precise demographic breakdowns of local
viewership that are now confined to sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   That would probably suit Moonves fine. He asserted Tuesday that
``Millionaire'' underscores ``why we think sweeps are a ridiculous
measurement.'' He has often argued that it's absurd for local ad
rates to be established on the basis of one-time programming
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, given the way the game is played and television's
need to generate excitement, both Moonves and NBC West Coast
president Scott Sassa and Moonves said they will continue to
develop potential blockbusters for sweeps. ``We're always going to
want big events, because we think that's what network television is
about,'' said Sassa.
</P>
<P>
   Network television is also about sitcoms and dramas, or it used
to be. But at a time when network schedules are already crowded
with newsmagazines, ``Millionaire'' and its clones will make it
even harder for dramas and sitcoms to make it onto the air. ``Every
game show that's on the air means another 100 people in Hollywood
out of work,'' remarked Moonves. ``We're going to do less pilots,
less scripts, less marginal programming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' has proven that even in an era of steady
audience erosion, network television can still draw a mass
audience, though it is arguable whether a prime-time schedule
filled with game shows and newsmagazines represents progress. But
even those networks that were pummeled by ``Millionaire'' find its
success reassuring in a way. CBS head of research David Poltrack
said his analysis showed that ``Millionaire'' pulled viewers away
from cable, which has been draining viewers from the broadcast
networks for years. Sassa tossed a verbal bouquet to what he called
ABC's ``phenomenal show,'' saying it ``really shows that broadcast
networks have the ability to create shows the public will find if
they capture the imagination of the entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the other networks will find it harder to muster kind
words if ``Millionaire'' stays on a roll next year. ``It's a
wonderful weapon to have,'' said ABC's Braun. ``It's not
necessarily like having one hit show. Depending on how you schedule
it, you can have a lot of hit shows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
