r s BC-FBN-RICE-HNS &LR;      11-30 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST SEASON LEAVES LITTLE TO DO BUT WATCH RICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _The pass tipped off his helmet, and Jerry Rice
looked back, watched the ball float up and grabbed it out of the
air, tumbling down for a 32-yard gain, his longest of the season by
13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Candlestick crowd went crazy, chanting his name, enjoying
this shred of what remains of the 49ers' dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Quibble if you want about Rice's performance, for there's plenty
of material. The 32-yarder was a freak catch, aided by the hard
dome on his head. He let the first play of the game, a deep pass
along the sideline, slip through his hands. His team lost
miserably, abysmally, hideously to the sinking Green Bay Packers,
20-3.
</P>
<P>
   But in these days of Niner decline, there's only one thing left
to do. Watch Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   Watch him stumble. Watch him soar. Watch him for happy memories
of the past. Watch him for sad reminders of the present. Just watch
him. Because there's nothing else to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ask ABC. The network turned Monday Night Football into the Jerry
Rice Retrospective. He was the story, shown in closeup, his Bambi
eyes and bandage-trimmed nose filling up the screen as if he were a
1950s screen idol. On the sideline, on the field, before plays,
after plays, the camera followed him.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had called for this sort of attention a week earlier, when
he said he wasn't seeing enough passes to get into a rhythm. Yes,
we've heard it before from him, but never like this. Never when he
had been marginalized on a team that had slipped off the margins
and off the page. Never when he had dropped two passes in a game
and still felt slighted by the offensive plan.
</P>
<P>
   That was the drama of this wan game. Would the 49ers coach bow
to the legend, give him the ball and let him see whether he would
snap out of a funk? The opening play answered that question.
</P>
<P>
   Stenstrom threw deep, and the ball flew just beyond Rice's
reach, grazing his fingertips. In years past, Rice probably would
have made the catch and gone for the touchdown. Or he would have
seethed over missing it. In 1999, though, on a 3-8 team, he could
only be pleased to see a long pass of any kind - caught, dropped,
underthrown, overthrown, anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had connected on the first one, that could have been the
momentum change right there,'' he said. ``I worked the (cornerback)
good, and I think he was surprised that the old guy could still
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would have scored on the same pass three years
ago, before injuries that wiped him out in 1997, Rice said: ``No, I
felt as fast as I did three years ago, but the ball was... no, I'm
not going to point any fingers, or anything like that. Anytime you
can get your fingertips on it, or get close, you've got to make the
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want to criticize Stenstrom, but he admitted that with
new quarterbacks, ``you're going to lose chemistry.'' Does he want
a change, a new man behind center? ``That's not for me to answer
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since there aren't many better options than Stenstrom, he'd be
wasting breath and good will. Would it make a difference, if there
were another quarterback, if Rice saw more passes, if his
37-year-old hands were the 49ers' first target on play after play?
</P>
<P>
   Some of that can't be answered. Some of it, we can guess,
especially after seeing Rice covered by lone corners and still not
making plays. But let's reach for excuses, remembering that he was
invisible in the preseason, that he and Steve Young had started to
hit something that looked vaguely like a stride when Aeneas
Williams smacked the lefty QB unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Young obviously got the worst of that collision, but Rice didn't
make out too well, either, losing his telepathic mate. Going into
Monday's game, he hadn't made a catch of 20 or more yards in 11
games. On Monday, he made two. He had four catches altogether for
63 yards. He didn't look like the Jerry Rice of old, but he didn't
look like the Jerry Rice of Nov. 14, either.
</P>
<P>
   Rice tried to backpedal from his pleas of a week ago, saying
that he hadn't demanded anything. ``For some reason,'' he lamented,
``when I say I want to do more, people take that the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   But if his, well, heavy hinting yielded compliance from the
coaches, so what? We may think we have the answers on Rice's status
at 37, but why not search out every nuance. We seem to have the
answers on the 1999 Niners, but they're not allowed to write
themselves off. So if there's a choice between exploring Rice's
potential, and exploring everybody else's, that's no choice at all.
Watch Jerry. See what he can do, what he can't do. On a 3-8 team, a
legend deserves to spend everything he has left, every week.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the Packers game, ABC went to the archives and
dug up video of a Monday Night game five years ago, when Rice broke
the record for career touchdowns. In the video, his uniform was
bright scarlet, his face was beaming, and his teammates were
lifting him onto their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The camera immediately panned to the current day, showing Rice
in a drenched, muddy jersey, face grimly set, his team lining up
for another futile play. It was a sad contrast, the video set
against the live footage, but every second of it was worth
watching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
