<SLUG> BC-WTO-FACES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET SOME FOLKS IN SEATTLE DURING WTO WEEK  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Some of the people on hand for the World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle:
</P>
<P>
   Wyconda Holcomb
</P>
<P>
   Seattle
</P>
<P>
   protester/student/fast-food worker
</P>
<P>
   Wyconda Holcomb carried no signs, banged no drums and wore a
simple sweat suit with no message. But she stood out in a sea of
thousands, commanding attention with a kinetic, vocal fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all about money! They are giving us genetically
engineered foods and using us like guinea pigs!'' she hollered to
the heavens, feet stomping, hair flying, fingers pointing east and
west.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice, which rumbled slow and fast, drowned out drums,
bullhorns and chants. Around her, people stopped chanting and
videotaped her.
</P>
<P>
   Holcomb, 20, grew up in Mobile, Ala., where she said few people
knew or cared about free trade. Because she missed the civil rights
movement in the '60s, she feels obligated to protest now. She says
she's a humanitarian, which meant she woke up at 5 a.m. and found a
sitter for her 3-year-old daughter, Nabi'hah, so she could march
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Holcomb moved to the Central Area about a year ago and studies
computer technology at Seattle Central Community College. Oh, and
she also works at Taco Time, which she was initially reluctant to
divulge. But don't ask her about any ``Franken-burritos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't have GM (genetically modified) food, because
it's really going to piss me off,'' she said, cranking up another
spitfire sermon. ``Who suffers from it? The water suffers, the air
suffers, the Earth suffers! Who benefits? The WTO!''
</P>
<P>
   Henri Benkoski
</P>
<P>
   Government official
</P>
<P>
   Brussels, Belgium
</P>
<P>
   While protesters jeered at delegates outside the Sheraton
Seattle Hotel &AMP; Towers, Henri Benkoski stood in the drizzle and
looked bemused. As deputy chief of staff for the French-speaking
government of Belgium, Benkoski was supposed to be at a European
Union meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first time in Seattle, but he felt as if he were back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like Europe. Each week or month, we have a big
demonstration,'' he yelled over the chants.
</P>
<P>
   Benkoski's agenda for the week was to promote international
diversity in movies, music, theater and books. He said Hollywood
dominates most Belgian movie screens, but he would like to promote
and subsidize his own country's cultural goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Hollywood movies, but I want to see my own Belgian and
French products,'' he said. ``We don't have a Hollywood. Ninety
percent of movie screens show American movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many Belgians watch American television, which is OK
in moderation, he said. ``But we don't want 100 percent `Starsky
and Hutch' and `Streets of San Francisco.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, the last two American movies Benkoski saw were
``The Runaway Bride'' and ``The General's Daughter.'' He said
Richard Gere's movie was ``nice,'' but he didn't sound very
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of movie that was nice to see if you have been
working non-stop for 10 days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like the 135 countries to confirm a cultural
diversity from each country. People have a right to their own
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Serna
</P>
<P>
   Store manager
</P>
<P>
   Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Outside, mayhem. Inside, frustration and the giant sucking sound
of lost dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's protests meant an empty store at Mario's, an upscale
European clothing boutique on Sixth Avenue, where manager Jennifer
Serna watched anxiously behind a locked door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to talk to the people who decided that this was a
good thing,'' said Serna, a career clothing manager. ``Anywhere in
the U.S., it's a huge part of the economy, the month of December.
It's a severe loss of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the store, owned by a Portland clothier, did less than
10 percent of its regular holiday business.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, someone put graffiti on Serna's storefront, glued the
locks of neighboring shops and broke the windows to Old Navy and
Starbucks. The scrawled message on many windows: ``We are
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   But against whom, Serna wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that people voice their opinion, but I don't
understand how vandalism helps,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a delegate from Norway bought a coat from her and asked
if the rioters were all from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   She was saddened to think that her city had turned ugly while
the world watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offends me, for this to be happening in our very peaceful
city,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   C.C. Chen
</P>
<P>
   Trade official
</P>
<P>
   Taipei, Taiwan
</P>
<P>
   ``A great civil society,'' joked C.C. Chen, as he watched young,
masked men stomp on overturned newspaper boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, Taiwan's section chief for the Board of Foreign Trade, had
been on his way to the WTO opening reception at the Paramount
Theater when demonstraters shut down the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can anyone break through that?'' he asked good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has made a bid to become a member of the WTO, and Chen
had planned to monitor the proceedings. As a member country, he
said, Taiwan would be able negotiate market access and develop
rules on trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be able to participate, and participation is most
important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first visit to Seattle, which he had heard was
pleasant and pretty. But since his arrival Saturday, he had been
too busy to sightsee.
</P>
<P>
   Would he see the Space Needle? ``Maybe, after work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had he eaten any good food? ``Yes, room service at the Westin.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen described his home city, Taipei, as ``crowded, noisy, never
sleeps.'' Also, he was very familiar with Starbucks, which he said
was on every five blocks. Personally, he likes the caramel
macchiatos: ``It's like a candy drink. ``It's nostalgia coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Botafogo
</P>
<P>
   Trade ambassador
</P>
<P>
   Brasilia, Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Jose Botafogo began his diplomatic career 40 years ago, after
earning a law degree in Rio de Janeiro when he was 24. Over the
decades, he has watched global trade expand while farmers in his
country grow poorer.
</P>
<P>
   As ambassador for foreign trade in Brasil, Botafogo arrived in
Seattle Monday to lobby for more exports of his country's sugar and
soya crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our farmers are poor because of the protectionist policies in
the United States and Europe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a high-ranking official, he keeps a demanding schedule. He
works 60 hours a week and spends about half his time on an
airplane, traveling around the globe. He speaks and reads five
languages: English, French, Spanish, Italian and Portuguese, his
native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know other countries, the better you can serve
your own country,'' is Botafogo's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   While not working, he jogs six kilometers a day, attends Mass on
Sunday in Brasilia and relaxes to classical music and bossa nova.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in Seattle Monday and has been true to his tireless
work schedule. As protesters ranted around him, he strolled Fifth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know only my hotel lobby and this part right here,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
