<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV07-     11-30 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY NOT TO WISH ON ANYONE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Dec. 7)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every holiday fanatic is out there, at the gate, or halfway down
the track, shopping like there's no tomorrow and so on. We know
that because we've been told that the day after Thanksgiving the
race begins.
</P>
<P>
   But ask yourself: What's the rush? There are weeks left to shop.
Today, folks, stores seldom close. They were even open on
Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to, you could actually give yourself a breather.
Get in shape for the weeks ahead by taking the day off. Not to take
anything away from the merchants, but you know they'll get theirs.
The economy is fat. People are working. There may be as many
millionaires running around as Pokemons.
</P>
<P>
   How much shopping do you really have to do? Have you gained that
many more relatives and friends since last year?
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to panic. Think of what human beings can
accomplish in a few weeks. People fall in love and get married.
Wars are started and ended. Babies learn to walk. Lives change. You
ought to be able to round up a dozen or so presents in that time.
</P>
<P>
   Are there any real mystery people on your list? You know all of
their tastes. They already expect you to hit it or bomb. And they
already know you love them. Go to the feed store and get something
for their animals. There are seldom crowds at feed stores and their
parking lots are quite civil.
</P>
<P>
   But relaxing is not part of the tradition. Is not the challenge
to ``get through the holidays,'' as if it's some big chore?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you rationalize that if you go for broke, now you can
sit back at the end, oh silly you. Let's have ourselves a
multitasking Christmas. Overload is the ritual. Stress tolerance is
what we really celebrate at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   I was talking to someone right before Thanksgiving and after I
told her what I was doing and she said what she was doing, I
automatically groaned, ``Isn't this crazy?'' and she said the most
amazing thing. She said, ``No, it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   So where do we find the wonder in all this? Can we put it on our
Visa, buy it over the Internet? Where's the big sale on wonder,
calm and peace?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a soothing ritual that a friend employs all year long,
not just in December. Diane spends every Sunday reading a book. The
whole day. She told a group of us about it one night and we gaped
at her with envy and admiration, as if she'd announced she spent
every Sunday locked in with Mel Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   But this is better.
</P>
<P>
   Diane decides during the week which book it will be and she
takes the entire day to read it, moving from her bed to her couch
to some sunny spot by a window. Sometimes she makes soup while
she's reading, but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   We could do that. We could take one day off during this madcap
season to read. Or sit on the deck in a wooly sweater and watch the
hawks. Imagine that. People would worry something was wrong, that
you were grieving a death or that you had the chicken pox. You
can't just drop out of the rat race when you've been such a good
little rat, can you?
</P>
<P>
   This is not the season of peace. This is Nutsville. This is the
season when if you don't already feel stressed out, you soon will
feel like you should. We must walk fast. Shop quickly. Buy on
impulse. Load up those aching arms. Overdraw. Overcharge. We are
like the little kid whose parents have let her stay up too late.
Her cheeks are flushed. She's laughing and crying at the same time.
She's stuffed with sweets and has been around too much chatter,
music and toys. She's sipped from the eggnog, been tickled and
squeezed and now spilled something on her red velvet.
</P>
<P>
   The kid needs to go to a quiet room and so do we.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who know how to do it. You'll be at a party,
babbling over what is still to be done and they serenely report how
they learned to back off. They pick a single event to make the
season bright _ one concert, play or ballet each December and focus
on just it. They get the best seats they can afford, dress
themselves and their kids to the max and make this event their big
Christmas present. A choral group filling the rafters with
``Gloria'' or the Sugar Plum Fairy spinning a dream, they say,
makes a longer lasting memory than the other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   No, I haven't managed to do it either, but doesn't it sound so
very smart?
</P>
<P>
   'Tis the season for demonstrating grace under pressure. Pressure
arrived with a full cart but grace seems to be lost in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
