<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BOUTIQUE-HOTEL     11-30 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOUTIQUE-HOTELS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOMS WITH ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Dec. 5) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It isn't in the dictionary, but the term boutique hotel has
become shorthand for a hotel with high-concept design and
personality, one that aspires to originality, attracting a young
crowd with hipness rather than grandeur, and (at least in the early
days of the trend) moderate prices. Trailblazing boutique hotels
include the Royalton, the Paramount and the Mercer in New York, the
Triton in San Francisco, and the Delano in Miami. But the trend can
be traced as far back as Blakes Hotel in London, a clubby luxury
retreat carved from a pair of Victorian townhouses that opened in
1981, where no two rooms are alike and the restaurant is as
adventurous as the decor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boutique hotels go beyond the functional purpose of providing
a clean bed and bathroom and feed the aspirations and desired
self-image of their guests,'' says Chekitan Dev, a professor of
marketing at Cornell University's Hotel School. ``A 55-year-old
business executive feels like a hip 25-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike grand hotels, which share certain qualities and
amenities, boutique hotels are harder to define as a group. The
name implies small size, but it's not unusual for a so-called
boutique to have 200 rooms or more. And though moderately priced
boutique hotels exist, style, it appears, isn't cheap, especially
at the most recent entries. The boutiques, by definition, are also
whimsical. Some offer a handsome menu of services but don't turn
down your bed at night. Many substitute a stall shower for a
bathtub. And rooms can be tiny, with narrow hallways, particularly
in old buildings that morph into boutiques. But even the smallest
room will probably have an imaginatively stocked minibar, handsome
window treatments and terrific electronic toys.
</P>
<P>
   Though the boutiques pride themselves on their individuality,
similarities exist. Look for candles in the lounges, leather and
velvet furniture in big bold shapes, dramatic lighting. Instead of
chintz or damask, expect canvas or plush and solid colors. And if
you're still not sure if a hotel is, or aspires to be, a boutique,
look at the doorman. If he's young, good-looking and in head to toe
black, you've got the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at four of the newest boutique hotels in New
York, Washington and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Feather beds, duvets and a grand view
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY TRUCCO
</P>
<P>
   I was told that my room, like many at the W Tuscany, would be
large, but no one mentioned the view. An enormous window looked
from this spot at Park Avenue and 39th Street onto a dazzling New
York cityscape _ brownstones, a church spire and the Empire State
Building. I plopped onto the pretty checked daybed near the window,
wrapped myself in the chenille throw and gazed happily at the city
lights. The floor show ended at midnight, when the Empire State's
yellow and orange topknot blinked off. I fell asleep humming
Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad all the surprises beamed my way by the W Tuscany weren't
so sweet. Though stylish and spacious, my room, 1602, lacked a
certain polish. The light in the cramped closet wouldn't turn on,
and the switch near the front door didn't work. The gray carpeting
was stained in several places. And the bathroom doorknobs were
dented, a reminder of the hotel's former incarnation as the
comfortable but staunchly unchic Doral Tuscany.
</P>
<P>
   The 122-room Tuscany officially became a member of Starwood's
hip W group on Nov. 1, following a dramatic refurbishment (the
lobby still wasn't finished when I stayed). It's on the same block
as its sister hotel, the 196-room W Court, another freshly
renovated addition to the chain. A third hotel, the 720-room W New
York, opened last year 10 blocks uptown.
</P>
<P>
   The two new Ws share a smoky palette of taupes, browns and reds
and an attractive, if increasingly familiar, clean but romantic
style, with pale walls, dark woods and flashy accents of velvet and
silver leaf. They also share their facilities. The Court's moody
Wet Bar lounge and atmospheric Icon restaurant, created by the
restaurateur Drew Nieporent, serve guests at both hotels, as will
the two-level fitness center planned for the Tuscany, according to
a front desk attendant, who, of course, wore black.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the Court's lobby, a spacious if self-conscious setting
with high-back sofas and huge round velvet ottomans that managed to
feel retro and futuristic at once. Comfortable by day, it is wildly
glamorous at night when it's lighted by a polished wood fireplace
and the requisite votive candles. The matching restaurant evokes a
1950s nightclub, albeit with bare dark wood tables. A friend joined
me for dinner, and our meals were outstanding, particularly the
goat cheese tart and the seared char. Not so our table. Though we
asked to be in the main dining room, we were told everything was
reserved and briskly escorted to a chilly, glass-walled room near
the kitchen. I observed, with annoyance, that some tables stood
empty in the main dining room all evening.
</P>
<P>
   I retreated to my room, surprisingly expensive at $470 on
weeknights, down to $269 on the weekend. It was so large that I was
astonished by the cramped bathroom. Clad in floor-to-ceiling
marble, it was pretty but small, with a tight-fitting stall shower
instead of a tub. But the room was soothing and restful. I loved
the buttery wool Roman shades on the windows and liked the
electronic accessories, which included a bedside CD player and a
portable keyboard with Internet access. My king-size bed, outfitted
with a feather bed and goose-down duvet, was splendid. And it was
all for sale _ the leather desk set ($175), the polar fleece
blanket ($90), even the mattress ($900). ``The experience doesn't
have to end when you check out,'' a catalog proclaimed. For me, the
memories were sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The W Tuscany, 120 East 39th St.; (212) 686-1600, (877)
946-8357, fax (212) 779-7822; www.whotels.com. Double rooms from
$299 to $475; weekend rates $219 to $269, plus 13.25 percent tax,
and $2 per room per night occupancy tax.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   A warm welcome (plus 2 phones lines)
</P>
<P>
   By FRANK BRUNI
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, the staff at the Hotel George should have
recoiled from me. I arrived late on a lazy Sunday when I had taken
a vacation from shaving, showering, wearing clean clothing or any
other semblance of civilized behavior. But what they did, even
before I pulled out my credit card, was give me a spectacularly
warm welcome. The woman at the front desk extended her hand to
shake mine. The bellhop appeared instantly and struck up a friendly
conversation. If the point of a boutique hotel is to establish a
more intimate environment than larger establishments can or do,
then the George was hewing beautifully _ and, in my case, bravely _
to that mission.
</P>
<P>
   The 139-room George, which opened in February '98, actually
starts off with one mark against it, and that is location. Situated
on one edge of Capitol Hill, just a stone's throw from Union
Station, it does not offer the neighborhood pleasures of Dupont
Circle or Georgetown: the streets surrounding it can be ghostly at
night. The George makes the most sense for people actually
conducting business at or around the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   And yet its spirit is more artistic than that. Near the
reception area, contemporary sofas and chairs upholstered in blue
and black sit on red carpets, forming an archipelago of bold color
in a sea of white fossilized coral stone. Up a narrow flight of
stairs, teasingly visible from the lobby, is a glass-walled
billiards parlor available only to guests.
</P>
<P>
   My fourth-floor room was modern, sleek, sensibly laid out, just
spacious enough and rife with conveniences: an ironing board, a
coffee maker, a minibar, a hair dryer, you name it. Best of all,
the bathroom, tiled with white marble, was enormous, including a
tub and a separate, glass-walled shower.
</P>
<P>
   But I ultimately judge a hotel by whether it has the prescience
to anticipate and accommodate whatever my desires may turn out to
be. Had I wanted a workout, the George provided a well-equipped
fitness room in the basement. But on this night, I needed to do an
hour of work on my laptop, during which I needed to gain access to
the Internet while also making and receiving calls. The George gave
me two phone lines and plenty of outlets at the desk with a
cushioned, extremely comfortable chair that was just the right
height. I also wanted to watch a football game on ESPN and ``Sex
and the City'' on HBO, and I turned on the set with trepidation,
knowing that many hotels do not offer these channels. The George
does, along with about four dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
