<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-CORRUPTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILED PALESTINIANS BACK AWAY FROM CORRUPTION ALLEGATIONS AIMED AT
ARAFAT ADMINISTRATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ A push by Palestinian intellectuals to
curb graft in their government seemed to fizzle Tuesday when four
jailed dissidents backed away from a manifesto denouncing ``tyranny
and corruption'' in Yasser Arafat's administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by prison officials of the Palestine
Authority, the four said they ``did not mean to attack any person
or the president or to show a lack of confidence in Palestinian
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The words ran counter to the manifesto that was circulated
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It said, ``Alarm bells should sound in every village, town and
refugee camp. ... Our homeland is being sold out, and our people
are being betrayed.'' The authors accused Arafat of ``opening the
door to opportunists who are spreading corruption throughout
Palestinian society.''
</P>
<P>
   In the statement issued Tuesday, the four jailed Palestinians
said they never meant the document to be released publicly, but
rather intended it to be discussed in closed sessions of the
Palestinian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' the statement said, ``was to find a solution which
the government and the intellectual community see as possible. We
are against any (adverse) political activity which may arise from
this memorandum.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Palestinian who signed the document, Parliament Member
Hosam Khader, sent a similar ``clarification'' to an Arabic
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the backpedaling by five of 20 academics and
lawmakers who had signed the document would likely spell a quick
end to their attempt to confront the sensitive subject of official
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   And the jailings of the four were seen as another worrying sign
that the Palestinian state-in-the-making may not be as democratic
as many had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   The manifesto accused the Palestinian Authority of ``adopting a
modus operandi of graft, corruption, humiliation and exploitation
of the Palestinian people,'' and went on to hold Arafat ultimately
responsible for opening the doors for corruption to spread.
</P>
<P>
   It also criticized the Palestinians' performance in peace talks
with Israel, charging that Arafat's negotiators had ``deceived''
their people by promising statehood and a thriving economy, while
they went about ``selling out the Palestinian homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the document's being reported by the media, nine
intellectuals who signed it were jailed by Palestinian police. Two
other signers were put under house arrest. Nine Parliament members,
shielded by immunity, were not taken into custody, but legislators
defending the government talked about lifting their immunity so
they could be prosecuted. The Parliament will hold a special
session Wednesday in Gaza City to debate that possible punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Most Palestinian analysts lauded the intellectuals' efforts but
predicted that they would fail to stem what many people here
describe as rampant government corruption or to strengthen the
Palestinians' negotiating positions.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the government said the manifesto's language, which
came across in Arabic as highly inflammatory, had crossed the
boundaries of protected free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the statement a major incitement,'' said Nabil
Amro, the Palestinian minister for parliamentary affairs. ``We see
clearly the line between incitement and freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's administration was particularly incensed that the
petition had lambasted its negotiating performance just as it is
entering sensitive talks with Israel aimed at reaching a
comprehensive peace deal that, among other things, would include
the fate of millions of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of corruption in Arafat's administration are not
new. Two years ago, Palestinian legislators, appalled by dishonesty
and mismanagement in government, forced Arafat to take some
measures to curb abuse, although legislators admit little has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that since its inception in 1994, the Palestinian
Authority has created the institutions of democracy _ a judiciary,
a legislature, a freely elected president _ but has actually
functioned more like a dictatorship. Parliament members engage in
lively debate and often pass ;thoughtful laws but their efforts
typically go unheeded, the critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat just ignores what he doesn't like, and he doesn't like
most of what they do,'' said Ghassan Khatib, director of the
Jerusalem Media and Communications Center.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators who signed the manifesto said they did it after
mounting frustrations at being ignored by government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've demanded to end corruption, we've asked for the people
responsible to be brought to court,'' said Ali Abu Rish, one of the
nine Parliament members who signed the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, all our efforts have failed,'' he said. ``So we
decided to say it in a loud voice. This was a scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian intellectuals agreed that the language of the
document was severe. But they were angered by arrests that they
said only spread fear and stifled free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language was crude,'' said Albert Aghazarian, head of
public relations at Birzeit University in the West Bank. ``But
detaining these people, it's a horrible mistake. The authority is
acting like a crude authoritarian state.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
