<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-BOUTIQUE-HOTEL     11-30 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOUTIQUE-HOTELS-$ADV05-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: dozen others.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the fluffy comforter on the bed to the dispatch with which
room service conjured a glass of chardonnay at 10:50 p.m., the
George did not hit a single false note. I could quibble over the
nonexistent view and poor light from two small windows, but I could
also praise the adjoining restaurant, Bis, which combines elegance
and deliciously rare tuna with, on many weeknights, a cast of
senators, cabinet members and television journalists.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very good thing I had eaten there before. On this
night, I was not exactly dressed for it.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel George, 15 E Street, NW, Washington, D.C. 20001; (202)
347-4200, (800) 576-8331, fax (202) 347-4213; www.hotelgeorge.com.
Doubles from $205, plus 14.5 percent tax, with special weekend
rates often available.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</P>
<P>
   Piles of pillows and high-tech gizmos
</P>
<P>
   By JAN BENZEL
</P>
<P>
   On the corner of Howard and Third Streets in San Francisco's
trendy SOMA (South of Market), men in black whisk cars into the
depths of the W's garage. Another man in black hands out key cards.
A third, wearing a wired headset, zipped me through the lobby of
this new entry in the W hotel chain, abuzz with a young, hip crowd,
up to the 23rd floor and careering around a few corners down a dim,
narrow hallway with black and tan horizontal-striped carpeting,
cool blue lights and glowing green exit signs.
</P>
<P>
   The effect would have been intimidating had not each of the men
in black (there were some women, too) been so ebulliently
welcoming. ``You're gonna love this hotel!'' promised Alex, in a
charming Eastern European accent, pointing out with glee that the
stripes of the carpeting matched the two-tone brickwork exterior of
the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art next door. The restaurant
downstairs, XYZ, was so good, he said, that I couldn't possibly get
a reservation, but I could have the same food by just calling room
service! ``Look,'' he said, ``You've got a T1-line.'' He brandished
the Category 5 high-speed Internet connection over the long black
desk. ``And a floating keyboard. You point it at the TV and check
your e-mail.'' He enumerated the other gizmos in the
just-big-enough, stylishly appointed room. The CD player! The
video-cassette player! Cordless phone! Nonallergenic pillow in the
closet, in case I was allergic to the four oversized fluffy feather
ones on the king-sized bed. The decent-sized bathroom, across the
tiny foyer from a full-length mirror and behind a sliding
ribbed-glass door, had a sleek sink, bathtub with in-tub shower,
waffle-weave robes, lots of thick white towels and strong plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me if you need anything at all,'' Alex said,
reassuringly, and disappeared, leaving me to perch on the inviting
window seat and marvel at the westward view out over Yerba Buena
Gardens, the new urban park built over the Moscone Convention
Center, and the mountains beyond, bordering the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned to the W after dinner (elsewhere), the
ground-floor coffee bar and lobby were overflowing with an eclectic
crowd drinking, chattering, playing chess and generally milling
about.
</P>
<P>
   In my room, where the honey brown carpet looked and felt like
wide-wale corduroy, turndown had occurred. It involved two fortune
cookies left on a small beveled silver tray and the house CD, a
collection called ``Rhythm and Muse,'' that to my relief included
mostly musicians I knew: Stan Getz, Etta James, Grace Jones. In my
nest high above the city, under the soft brown brushed cotton
duvet, all was cozy and quiet. If I listened hard, I could detect
faint traffic sounds below.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast came when requested. But a small box of raisin bran, a
tiny pitcher of low-fat milk, a smallish glass of O.J. and some
sliced fruit, delivered with panache, cost $18.88, tip included on
the bill. I made my own (free) coffee. If I'd ordered it, the tab
would have been eight bucks more. With its high-tech comforts, this
423-room W, opened in May, clearly caters to a young business crowd
whose IPO ship has come in.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee, tea and the modishly packaged Aveda bath products were
the only gratis offerings in the room. The honor bar was full of
'90s essentials, among them Altoids, a box of Oreos and a safe-sex
Intimacy Kit. I grabbed a $3.74 bottled water for the flight home,
stopping for a peek at the 24-hour pool and gym on the fourth
floor. The glass-roofed area was busy even at 7:30 Sunday morning.
My car (valet parking, $30 a night) was waiting, but before I
jumped in, I plucked a perfect green apple from the bowl in the
lobby. Never pass up a free piece of fruit when you're staying in a
pricey hotel, I always say.
</P>
<P>
   W San Francisco, 181 Third St., San Francisco, Calif. 94103;
(415) 777-5300, (877) 946-8357, fax (415) 817-7823;
www.whotels.com. Rooms are categorized as ``wonderful,''
``spectacular'' (which is what I had, for $271, with a 30 percent
AAA discount), ``cool corner,'' ``far-out corner'' and ``groovy
corner.'' The corner rooms are slightly larger, with seating areas.
Doubles from $229 to $399, plus 14 percent tax.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Millennial minimalism
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY TRUCCO
</P>
<P>
   I sat on my bed in Room 1111 and tried to feel red. Urging me on
was a pamphlet explaining that each of the hotel's 193 rooms
showcases a primary color _ red, yellow or blue. ``Think about how
color affects your moods, your psyche, your sense of place,'' the
pamphlet intoned. This marriage of interior decoration and ``color
theory provocation,'' a concept inspired by Alexander Theroux's
book, ``The Primary Colors,'' was designed, according to the
pamphlet, to arouse the senses. I can't say I entered a state of
true redness, even after I uncorked the tiny scent vial that was
supposed to help me smell red. But I enjoyed the handful of cherry
Jelly Bellies. They matched the bedspread perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   What would a boutique hotel be without a theme? Just to be safe,
The Time, which opened in April, has two. Taking a cue from its
name, a wink at the hotel's location on the far outskirts of Times
Square, clocks and numerals abound, like the big black I through
XII emblazoned across the hall carpeting. The themes are diverting
but hardly necessary, since the hotel's design by Adam Tihany is
confident and smartly detailed, provided you like millennial
minimalism.
</P>
<P>
   A cool, futuristic atmosphere derived from brushed stainless
steel and marble envelopes you as you pass through the big glass
doors (yes, the doormen wear black). A glass elevator deposits you
on the second floor near the creamy-white lounge with woven leather
chairs and high-backed velvet sofas with leather pillows. At night,
the lounge was crowded, noisy and dark, lighted by votive candles
and little else. By day it was a light, roomy place to read a
newspaper or, less enjoyably, overhear a cell phone conversation. I
liked the miniature TV screens embedded, like moving photographs,
in the brushed-steel wall panels.
</P>
<P>
   Once in my room, however, I would happily have sacrificed some
style for space. My not inexpensive $309 room was extremely snug,
with room for a king-size bed and not much else. Fortunately, not a
scrap of space was wasted. The bed, a vivid scarlet centerpiece,
was backed by a huge rectangle of matching fabric, framed by creamy
white molding. An identical molding encased the enormous mirror
opposite the bed. The TV, set atop a discreet minibar, wore a
removable white canvas hood stenciled with the word NEWS. And a
creamy wool curtain hid the wide but shallow closet.
</P>
<P>
   The room looked crisp and new, and there were toys galore _
coffee maker, Bose radio, fax machine and plug-ins for laptops by
the desk. (A hotel spokesperson said there will be a keyboard and
Internet access in rooms by the end of the year.) But no one turned
down the bed at night. And the compact bathroom had a large stall
shower but no tub.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't imagine where I would put a room service tray, so I
had dinner downstairs at Palladin, the hotel's glamorous restaurant
named for its French chef. Though it was quite full, I was offered
a choice of tables and as a lone diner felt welcome. The dinner _
pumpkin soup with duck prosciutto and seared tuna _ was delicious.
As I ate, my thoughts wandered upstairs to my vibrant red room. The
color might help you rev up for a meeting. But if I were to return
for a quiet weekend, I'd ask for something in blue.
</P>
<P>
   The Time, 224 West 49th St., New York, N.Y. 10019; (212)
246-5252, (877) 846-3692, fax (212) 245-2305; www.thetimeny.com.
Double room from $195 to $429 plus 13.25 percent tax, and $2 per
room per night occupancy tax, with weekend specials based on
availability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
