</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Dec. 1 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ECON (Washington) _ A look at what may be expected whe
George W. Bush offers his economic and tax proposals in a speech on
Wednesday. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER (Washington) _ The FTC on Tuesday approved the merger
of Exxon and Mobil after they agreed to give up 2,431 service
stations. The commission had been expected to back Exxon's $81
billion purchase of Mobil. The European Union gave conditional
approval of the merger in late September after they agreed to
divest from some natural gas activities. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-TALKS (Seattle, Wash.) _ Demonstrations delayed the start
of the World Trade Organization meeting Tuesday as police fired
tear gas into a crowd of protesters near the Convention Center.
(Developing. Summary from wires.) By Sam Howe Verhovek and Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-HOMELESS (New York) _ Offering the most pointed
attack to date on her likely opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton
Tuesday sharply criticized Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's policy of
arresting homeless people for sleeping on the streets. By Jonathan
P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-EXPELL-EDUC (Chicago) _ Beyond an intolerance for
weapons and drugs, the new ethos on conduct in schools has
profoundly changed views on what is normal, if annoying, behavior
by adolescents. No longer is the playground scrap or the kickball
tussle deemed a rite of passage. Known most often as the ``zero
tolerance'' code, aggression is viewed as violence, and teachers
are typically forbidden from simply resolving any physical dispute
with a lecture. Instead, they are instructed to file a report with
the school authorities, so that a uniform policy can run its
course, and no offending student escapes punishment. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CHURCH-DOOR (Jerusalem) _ The Church of the Holy
Sepulcher is a venerated house of worship that is elaborately
divided, arch by arch, candle by candle, among three major
Christian rites and several minor denominations. Not even a sewer
cover is simply a sewer cover. It is turf. What hope, then, can
there be for Israel to persuade the Christians to install an
emergency exit and corridor before an expected millennial rush of
pilgrims? By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Former Chancellor Helmut
Kohl admitted Tuesday that he had used a system of secret accounts
to receive donations to his Christian Democrats but rejected
charges he had been bribed during his 16 years in office. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
</TEXT>
