<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GOLD-RUSH-TREASURE-AR     11-30 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLD-RUSH-TREASURE-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLDEN BOUNTY RECLAIMED FROM THE OCEAN FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 5)  
 (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A gold-rush treasure, burnished by 130 years in the icy depths
of the Atlantic, has finally reached its destination _ New York.
Mined, sifted, assayed or minted in California, the three tons of
gold bars, ingots, coins and dust was shipped on Aug. 20, 1857 from
San Francisco bound for New York, but not even a small portion of
it ever made it until a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo that many people envisioned would stop a monthlong run
on New York banks was taken by the S.S. Sinora to Panama and
transferred by rail to the paddle steamer Central America. After a
stop in Havana, the boat steamed north, and into the path of a
hurricane. It went down in the storm 160 miles off the coast of
Cape Fear, N.C., in one of the greatest peacetime marine disasters
in American history.
</P>
<P>
   The shipwreck took the lives of 425 passengers, officers and
crew _ two-thirds of those on board. And the loss of the bullion _
valued at $1.2 million, or about one-fifth the gold then in Wall
Street banks _ compounded the financial crisis that had dangerously
lowered gold reserves in New York banks, spurring the Panic of
1857.
</P>
<P>
   Then, though insurers made swift payments to the gold's owners,
the recession deepened: 980 businesses failed in New York and 1,400
banks closed nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a decade after the treasure was salvaged and a year after
the battles over its ownership ended in the federal district court
in Norfolk, Va., there are once again powerful expectations for at
least a fraction of the gold.
</P>
<P>
   The American and British insurers or their successors were
awarded nearly 400 pounds, about eight percent of the total. The
rest of the gold went to the salvagers, the Columbus America
Discovery Group of Ohio, which was founded by the engineer-explorer
Tommy Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   From 1986 to 1989, Thompson and his crew, using a robot vehicle
to scour the wreckage and vacuum the ocean floor, wrested gold and
artifacts from the rotting timbers and rusted iron ribs of the
Central America. Thompson has not yet disclosed what he intends to
do with his much larger hoard.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers' gold, which arrived in New York at Sotheby's a
year ago, will be sold first in a live auction and then hours later
on the Internet. In the past, Internet sales have come a week or
more after the live ones. The total expected for the treasure, now
on view on the Internet (sothebys.amazon.com), could reach $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   The more valuable pieces will be auctioned live in 250 lots, to
sell for $1,000 to $350,000 each, on Wednesday and Thursday. On
Thursday evening the sale moves to the Web site, which is operated
jointly by Sotheby's and Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   There, 1,000 lots of gold _ nuggets, 40 pounds of dust and one
bar _ will be offered over two weeks. The estimates range from $100
to $1,000 for each of the nuggets and vials of dust; the hefty gold
bar, weighing 374 ounces, may sell for from $125,000 to $175,000.
All told, the sale may bring as much as $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few pieces of gold out there with a provable
provenance from the gold rush,'' said David E. Tripp, a Sotheby's
coin consultant in charge of the sale. ``The gold has an allure,
over and above its intrinsic value. This is fairy dust from the
bottom of the ocean _ far better than a snapshot of an important
moment in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold sold for roughly $20 an ounce when the Central America went
down; today it's worth is about 15 times that, or $300 an ounce.
But historical gold is so valued by coin collectors and history
buffs that it commands much higher figures depending on its
fineness, story and look.
</P>
<P>
   The gold bars, produced by five different assayers, bear stamped
markings ranging from crude to fine, and some pieces are gloriously
colored, from blood red to iron brown, patinas left by the ship's
rusting ribs.
</P>
<P>
   The tiniest ingot in the sale, a five-ounce piece stamped Blake
&AMP; Co., looks good enough to eat, like a foil-wrapped chocolate. It
is estimated to sell for $30,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   A brick-like bar, by Kellogg &AMP; Humbert at 663 ounces, the
largest in the sale, may bring as much as $275,000. But the bar, by
Justh &AMP; Hunter, with the highest valuation _ $350,000 _ weighs 652
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, the gold had remained intact after the Central
America sank, and much of it was together on the ocean floor. The
bars, once boxed, had toppled like dominos, and many coins were
found still stacked. But the gold dust, which looks like Grape Nuts
and was probably carried aboard in sacks or pouches that men wore
around their waists, was widely strewn about the site.
</P>
<P>
   To David Redden, an executive vice president at Sotheby's who
oversees books, collectibles and Internet sales, it is the gold
dust that inspires the mystique about gold and greed. ``The gold
dust, panned in the mountain streams of Northern California, was
brought to town in the pockets of the miners,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even the greed of those who knew that gold fetched a higher
price in New York dissolved when lives were at stake. ``The people
who went down on that ship would have discarded anything weighty _
the coins, nuggets and even the gold dust _ as they were swimming
for the doors and an escape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gold dust is an extraordinary human story,'' he said,
``that takes us from the top of the Sierra Madre to the bottom of
the Atlantic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
