<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATORS-KICKER-COX     11-30 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATORS-KICKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's Chandler hopes to have the last laugh against
AlabamaBy Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Florida's Jeff Chandler received dozens of
letters from all over of the country the week after Oct. 2. On that
date, Chandler missed the extra point in overtime that helped
Alabama win their matchup in The Swamp, 40-39.
</P>
<P>
   Some letters offered support; many others were downright nasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget this one,'' said Chandler, a junior from
Jacksonville. ``It said: `You'll always remember the time you made
the Gators lose. You look a little stressed out. Why don't you get
a girlfriend _ like Doug Johnson.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't very funny at the time. But Chandler was able to
chuckle about it Tuesday in a conference room beneath Ben Hill
Griffin Stadium. Two months after the fact, Chandler knows he still
can have the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama and Florida are scheduled for a rematch Saturday at the
Georgia Dome. For the fourth time this decade, the two teams are
meeting in the SEC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   When Chandler found out who the opponent would be, no Gator was
happier than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kicked in big games before,'' Chandler said. He made
three field goals, including a 50-yarder, in a 30-23 loss to No. 1
FSU two weeks ago. He also made field goals of 23, 33 and 41 yards
in a 23-21 win over Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this game is any bigger than the FSU game was,''
he said. ``So I feel like I can handle the pressure well. I'd like
for it to come down to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said revenge is not so much his motivation. His main
goal is silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing when you have such a good year and
everybody keeps talking to you about the Alabama kick,'' he said.
``That's why I want this game to get over with. I want to have a
good game. Then, everybody can talk about this Alabama game.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that missed extra point was about the only blemish on
the record of Chandler's season. Heading into Saturday's game,
Chandler leads the nation in field-goal percentage, with a success
rate of 87.5 percent (21 of 24). He is first in the SEC and second
in the nation in field goals made (1.9 per game) and is second in
the league in scoring with 9.1 points a game. Chandler also is a
semifinalist for the Lou Groza, which goes annually to the nation's
best place-kicker.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he has done it at a school where kickers usually
are looked down upon. In coach Steve Spurrier's world, field goals
are just the result of inept offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Spurrier doesn't like to kick field goals, I can tell
you that,'' Florida quarterback Doug Johnson said. ``We like to
score (touchdowns). That's not taking anything away from Jeff
Chandler, but when we come off the field, it feels like we're
punting instead of kicking a field goal.''
</P>
<P>
   After saving the Gators' hides on a few occasions, Chandler has
helped change Spurrier's tune about kicking specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leads the nation in field goals; why wouldn't I be
confident in him?'' Spurrier said. ``He's the No. 1 field-goal
kicker in the country. He can make them from the 50 on in. That's
good to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's path to becoming the starting place-kicker at Florida
is a strange one. Both his parents, Donald and Pamela, graduated
from the University of Georgia and were devout Bulldog fans.
</P>
<P>
   His mother grew up in Marietta, Ga. His father ran track at
Georgia, 1967-69; his 110-meter hurdle time of 14.37 seconds
remains the fourth-fastest in school history. Chandler has spent a
lot of time in and around Athens and Atlanta. And having grown up
in Jacksonville, he is quite versed in the tradition of the
Georgia-Florida rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through Georgia-Florida weekend, I was always a big
Georgia Bulldog fan,'' he said. ``But I got into school here, and I
was just lucky when I got the opportunity to walk on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler did not play football until his senior year at Mandarin
High, concentrating instead on soccer and tennis. He walked on for
Florida football at the urging of former Gator assistant and
Georgia letterman Barry Wilson. Chandler played in one game in
1997, then took over as the starting place-kicker after Collins
Cooper's fateful miss against Tennessee in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Chandler is 32 of 39 in field goals for his career.
Oddly enough, he has missed seven of 77 point-after attempts in
that time. None was bigger, of course, than the miss against
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   As for the infamous letter-writer, Chandler hasn't decided
whether to write back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Chandler would like to write a different ending
against Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ON TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Jeff Chandler missed an extra point and a 41-yard
field goal attempt in a 40-39 overtime loss to Alabama on Oct. 2.
Since then, however, he's been nearly perfect:
</P>
<P>
   OpponentField goals
</P>
<P>
   _ LSU1-for-1 (22-yard kick)
</P>
<P>
   _ Auburn4-for-4 (21, 35, 22, 19)
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia1-for-2 (missed from 44 yards, hit from 40)
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanderbilt2-for-2 (29, 33)
</P>
<P>
   _ S. Carolina2-for-3 (missed from 42 yards, hit from 46 and 29)
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State3-for-3 (50, 45, 22)
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
