<HEADLINE>
CORNYN URGES JUSTICES TO UPHOLD CONVICTION OF TEXAS MAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State Attorney General John Cornyn urged the
Supreme Court on Tuesday to uphold the child molestation conviction
of a north Texas man, even though he was convicted based largely on
testimony that would have been inadmissible at the time of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Scott Leslie Carmell, now serving a life sentence
for aggravated sexual assault and related offenses against his
stepdaughter, countered that the Constitution should have barred
Texas prosecutors from allowing the victim to testify at trial.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong argument, the justices questioned both
lawyers in weighing the vexing issue of whether the Constitution's
Ex Post Facto Clause prohibits prosecutors from using at trial
testimony that would have been prohibited when the attack occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision in the case,
Carmell vs. Texas, by July.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, making his first appearance before the justices as Texas
attorney general, said the state rightfully applied to Carmell's
repeated attacks a 1993 law that made it easier for sexual assault
victims to testify. The new law for the first time allowed victims
between ages 14 and 17 to testify against their alleged attacker
even if they waited more than six months to tell anyone of the
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell's victim, who had waited more than six months before
telling anyone of the attacks, was permitted to testify at his
trial because of the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell's court-appointed attorney, Richard Bernstein of
Washington, said the Ex Post Facto Clause should have barred
prosecutors from using the testimony of the victim, identified in
court papers only as KM. That argument, however, has lost in Texas
courts, which upheld the conviction, prompting Carmell, formerly of
Iowa Park, to appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell's high-court appeal addressed only four of the 15 counts
on which he was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The four counts concerned charges that Carmell attacked KM
before the new 1993 testimony rule took effect but when she was
over age 14. During that time, the old testimony rule would have
required KM to tell someone of the attacks within six months, which
she failed to do.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors, using the new rule, had KM testify to those
earlier attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Carmell, based in part on that testimony, was convicted in 1997
of sexually abusing his stepdaughter from age 12 to 17, a period
that stretched from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the court rules in Carmell's favor, Cornyn said the
convict would remain in prison for a long time based on his
conviction on the other 11 counts.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing Carmell's case, Bernstein argued that the
Constitution's authors inserted the Ex Post Facto Clause to prevent
legislatures, after a crime had been committed, from relaxing rules
prohibiting testimony in order to ensure a conviction. The Texas
Legislature, by easing restrictions on the testimony of alleged
child sexual assault victims, made it easier for prosecutors to win
Carmell's conviction, Bernstein argued.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Sandra Day O'Connor interjected that the
constitutional provision is designed to prevent legislators from
outlawing an act that was not a crime when it was committed. The
Texas statute does not change state criminal law but merely enables
a witness to testify, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a very sympathetic case,'' O'Connor said, noting
that Carmell sexually assaulted a young teen-ager. The justice
added that she doubts Carmell considered the Texas rule on the
admission of testimony before attacking his stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, however, responded that the new law governing child
testimony was significant to Carmell's criminal case in that it
meant the difference between his acquittal and life in prison. The
statutory change did not merely alter the rules governing testimony
but created the equivalent of a new criminal statute that was used
unconstitutionally to secure Carmell's conviction, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn countered that the new rule on testimony amounted to ``a
mere procedural change'' that did not affect state criminal law
regarding sexual assault. Prosecutors, therefore, did not violate
Carmell's constitutional rights when they had his stepdaughter
testify, the attorney general added.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Anthony M. Kennedy and Stephen G. Breyer said a
procedural rule could violate the Ex Post Facto Clause if it makes
it easier for the government to win a conviction it might have lost
under the rules in effect when the crime was allegedly committed.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Cornyn said courts have often upheld changes in
rules regarding testimony despite Ex Post Facto challenges.
</P>
<P>
   He cited ``rape shield laws'' that bar criminal defendants from
basing their defense on their alleged victim's sexual history. The
laws have been used to protect victims, even if they were attacked
before the statutes were enacted, Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Solicitor General Beth Brinkmann voiced the
Clinton administration's support for Texas' position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
