<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MALONE-MANAGEMENT-NYT     11-30 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALONE-MANAGEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER MANIA GOT YOU DOWN? THINK SMALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Texas, Mass.)   By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We might be forgiven for concluding that everything in corporate
America is getting bigger and bigger. The global couplings in
autos, oil and gas, financial services, telecommunications and now
pharmaceuticals sometimes give the impression that the business
world is driving toward an acquisition apocalypse. When the dust
settles, we will all draw a paycheck from the same employer.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Thomas W. Malone to file a minority report. Malone is
a professor of information systems at the Sloan School of
Management at Massachusetts Institute of Technology and an alumnus
of Xerox's creative Palo Alto Research Center. For five years, he
has been co-director of a major-league effort to think about what
shape the company and the workplace will take in the new century,
now only a month away.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the century will bring a new golden age for small
enterprise and a new springtime for individual creativity in
business. Communications in the Internet era will be so powerful,
so rich, so cheap that even the smallest enterprises, already
nimble, will be armed with the information they need to compete
with corporate giants. He expects an economy in which companies as
small as 1 to 10 talented people can thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Newborn Web businesses are already swirling like snowflakes. How
long before they carpet the ground? Malone summarized his views
last month at a valedictory gathering of M.I.T.'s initiative on
Inventing the Organizations of the 21st Century, an extensive
research effort he cofounded in 1994. The project (ccs.mit.edu/21c)
has drawn in two dozen scholars and numerous companies, with
financing from British Telecommunications, A.T. Kearney, National
Westminster Bank, Union Bank of Switzerland and a consortium of
Norsk Hydro and other Norwegian business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's talk in Wong Auditorium on the M.I.T. campus amounted
to instructing the elephants on the mouse. The assemblage was
mostly big companies trying to peer over the horizon, among them
Ford Motor, DaimlerChrysler, Fidelity Investments, State Farm,
Polaroid, Intel, Sun Microsystems, Compaq Computers,
PricewaterhouseCoopers, Andersen Consulting and the Naval Undersea
Warfare Center. (One mouse in the crowd, tiny Sohodojo of Raleigh,
N.C., billed itself as ``a nanocorp'' and lamented the tax
disadvantages of working out of the home.)
</P>
<P>
   Malone's term is ``the e-lance economy,'' a play on the word
``freelance.'' He expects a business landscape in which much work
that large corporations now do will be done by ``temporary
companies'' _ ad hoc combinations of small specialist firms that
come together to tackle a single project and disband upon its
completion.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of that economy will be a vast electronic
marketplace in business services, already taking shape. Small
companies will be able to rent the design, manufacturing and
marketing muscle now available only to big businesses. Small talent
pools will be free to focus on what they do best.
</P>
<P>
   Malone likes to talk about TopsyTail, a tiny Dallas-based
producer of hair and fashion accessories. Relying on a score of
vendors, from demand forecasting through manufacturing and order
fulfillment, it has produced more than $100 million in sales at
retail with three employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not good with employees, I am good with vendors,''
TopsyTail's energetic founder, Tomina Edmark, said in an interview
on Monday. Outsourcing to the limit not only fits her managerial
personality, she said. It also provides instant, inexpensive
expertise in a consumer business where the race is always to the
swift. Her next step is a Web store, herroom.com, to sell women's
underwear online, starting in February.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of an economy of microenterprises are everywhere.
Malone sees them in the surge in outsourcing; in the popularity of
telecommuting; in the proliferation of virtual companies; in the
erosion of the Fortune 500 as the premier employer; in the legions
of people who opt for freelance or part-time work. He sees the same
trajectory inside large companies, which increasingly work through
project teams, joint ventures, ad hoc alliances, internal markets
and independent business units.
</P>
<P>
   In some familiar industries, the e-lance economy has long been
the norm. ``It is the way that films get made,'' Malone said.
``It's also the way that we make buildings.'' Decades ago, the
major Hollywood studios had everything under one roof. Today, a
coalition of artistic and technical talents is assembled piece by
piece. The studio does the financing and manages marketing and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone believes the next century will see much greater
decentralization of business decision-making. There the debate
begins. Will the Internet foster an economy of small enterprises,
or will it make it possible to build a global empire far more
extensive than anything known today? Is the prototype Edward Jones,
the investment firm, with more than 5,000 local offices united by
cutting-edge communications and an engrained culture of serving the
careful long-term investor? Or is it the cottage industry of
thousands of independent financial advisers who rely on Charles
Schwab for their transaction needs and tap the Internet for endless
sources of financial analysis?
</P>
<P>
   Many experts, including some at the M.I.T. conference, say that
economies of scale and new efficiencies in harnessing corporate
learning favor the larger-and-larger structure. They say that only
the largest will be able to assemble and manage the costly
information engines needed to power a global empire. Huge companies
like BP Amoco are devising new systems to organize and index the
vast business savvy that exists within their ranks but today is
tacit and untapped.
</P>
<P>
   Malone contends that it is easier to think about flattening the
corporate hierarchy by chopping away at middle management and
empowering underlings _ all half-measures in his view _ than it is
to grasp the workings of a vast network of many, many small players
under no central direction or control. (Some people call that a
market.) But his model of creativity and efficiency is not merely a
leaner, flatter company.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, consider the celebrated Linux operating
system, which was developed and perfected by thousands of
volunteers after Linus Torvalds posted his early efforts on the
Internet and invited all and sundry to have a go at them. Or
consider the Internet itself. Malone invariably draws smiles when
he asks if the Internet could have been developed by AT&AMP;T, with the
normal panoply of corporate procedures and clearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's literally no one in charge of the Internet,'' he said
at the conference, ``no one who can shut it down, no one who can
keep you from connecting with it.'' Fundamentally, it is a
collection of interaction protocols, a set of rules for exchanging
information. ``Anyone who follows those rules can basically play
any role they want.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the idea: No one organization can match a thriving
marketplace of ambitious talents for creativity and innovation. So
why shouldn't a General Motors, instead of being wedded to its
in-house battalions of engineers, open its needs to innumerable
design enterprises from outside? That is the open architecture that
propels Silicon Valley. Why not tap it to build cars?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
