<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-PREVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP GIVES GOVERNMENT LOW MARKS IN AIDS PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although the federal government gets high marks for
bankrolling AIDS research and treatment programs, it scores an F in
funding U.S. prevention programs and only a C in helping other
countries battle the deadly disease, an advocacy coalition here
called AIDS Action said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time of increasing HIV infection rates and evidence of
laxity around safer sex, official Washington has tragically
short-changed domestic prevention efforts and has failed to launch
new initiatives around HIV prevention and education,'' the group
said in a new study released on the eve of World AIDS Day
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Action is one of the largest coalitions seeking greater
U.S. commitment to stamp out the disease, which attacks the body's
immune system. The group annually issues a report card on the
federal response to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   This year's F on AIDS prevention was down from the government's
D grade last year, and the group cited inadequate funding as the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   In the new fiscal year, the government has allotted $695 million
for AIDS prevention through the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDC), a $37.5 million increase over the previous year.
But AIDS Action, a coalition of 3,200 advocacy groups that had
sought $848 million, contended that the increase is not enough to
bolster public education programs that might slow the burgeoning
infection rate in young people.
</P>
<P>
   In what public health officials have described as an alarming
trend, people under 25 comprise nearly half of the estimated 40,000
new cases of HIV infections each year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Zingale, AIDS Action's executive director, said the trend
was linked to the federal government's failure to provide more
money for prevention programs. ``We've spent more on teaching our
kids about the make-believe world of Pokemon (a video game) than on
teaching them about the real dangers of HIV,'' which causes AIDS,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In giving the government a C (up from an F in 1998) for trying
to help stem the spread of the disease globally, AIDS Action noted
that the Clinton administration in the last year has focused on the
Third World, where the epidemic has struck the hardest. The
government has allotted $100 million to help other nations stem the
AIDS crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the coalition charged, ``the U.S. government has failed
to aggressively support emergency care initiatives and HIV
prevention worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The group gave the government an A-minus for AIDS research
funding and a B for its support of the care and treatment of AIDS
victims, the same grades it held last year. The ratings reflect the
robust annual federal allocations of more than $1.5 billion for the
care of U.S. citizens fighting the disease and about $1.8 billion
for the search for new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   While not addressing the coalition's report card directly, the
CDC in Atlanta agreed that more money is needed to increase AIDS
prevention. ``The nation must make a renewed and intensified
commitment to prevention,'' the agency said in its own report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC added that it has made significant strides in AIDS
prevention, which it said has ``helped slow the rate of new HIV
infections in the U.S. from over 150,000 in the late 1980s to
approximately 40,000 per year now.'' AIDS killed 17,171 Americans
last year, compared with 21,445 in 1997 and 37,221 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. death rate also has plummeted because government- and
industry-sponsored research has produced strong anti-viral drugs
and a new class of treatments known as protease inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   But because most developing nations can't afford the costly
drugs or many of the prevention programs, the death rate from the
disease is spiraling upward in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   According to a separate study released last week by the United
Nations, 2.6 million people worldwide will die of AIDS this year,
the highest annual number since the epidemic began. The majority of
those deaths are likely to occur in sub-Saharan Africa, where 70
percent of people with HIV reside.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations reported that about 5.6 million new HIV
infections will occur this year, raising the number of people
currently living with the infection globally to about 33.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
eric &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
