<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SPANISH-FILMS-2TAKES-     11-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPANISH-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH MOVIES MINE A RICH VEIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until Pedro Almodovar's first zany comedy ``Pepi,
Luci, Bom ...'' in 1980, Spanish films rarely caused a stir. Then
came his hit ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown'' in 1988.
His latest, ``All About My Mother,'' which opened here last month
and in Europe six months ago, is topping his previous box-office
records. But Almodovar is just one of many Spanish directors who
are making waves.
</P>
<P>
   At the Film Society of Lincoln Center, Richard Pena, the program
director, began tracking the Spanish film revival in 1992 when he
inaugurated the first Spanish film festival in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we began, it was at a low point,'' Pena said recently.
``Now it's become one of the strongest in Europe. Along with Iran,
Spain makes the most interesting films today.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday, 18 independent films, most of them American
premieres, will be presented through Dec. 24 at the Walter Reade
Theater by the Film Society, in collaboration with the Instituto
Cervantes, which supports Spanish culture abroad, the Spanish
Society of Authors and Publishers, and the Spanish Ministry of
Education and Culture.
</P>
<P>
   The featured director, Ventura Pons, 54, will be represented by
six films, among them the probing drama ``Beloved/Friend''
(``Amic/Amat''), a prize winner at the recent Berlin Film Festival,
and his first film, ``Ocana, Intermittent Portrait'' (1978), a
documentary about a famous Barcelona transvestite.
</P>
<P>
   Made in his native Catalan language, these films are among
several from three distinctive regions of Spain _ Catalonia,
Andalusia and the Basque country. Regional film production is
another growing trend in the industry. The festival also brings
back Ivan Zulueta's 1979 cult classic ``Rapture'' (``Arrebato''),
an off-beat vampire tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series should give a real snapshot of Spanish cinema,''
said Pena, adding that every year a few more films from the
festival are picked up for commercial distribution. Samuel Goldwyn
Films has already acquired Benito Zambrano's ``Alone'' (``Solas''),
to be shown in the United States next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-hitting, sophisticated and beautifully acted, the entries
cover the spectrum from Manuel Cusso-Ferrer's fantasy love story
``Babaouo,'' based on a 1932 scenario by Salvador Dali, to the
near-pornographic ``Between Your Legs'' (``Entre las Piernas'') by
Manuel Gomez Pereira, a director in the flashy, stylized manner of
Almodovar.
</P>
<P>
   The generational span is also broad. The eminent Carlos Saura,
67, renowned for his flamenco trilogy, ``Blood Wedding'' (1981),
``Carmen'' (1983) and ``A Love Bewitched'' (1986), and the recent
``Flamenco'' (1995), contributes ``Goya in Bordeaux,'' an eloquent
homage to his favorite painter, and the actress and director Iciar
Bollain, 32, offers ``Flowers From Another World'' (``Flores de
Otro Mundo''), a comedy concerning mail order brides in an isolated
Spanish village.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our filmmakers have moved away from the great transcendental
themes of Bunuel,'' said Maria Lozano, director of Instituto
Cervantes in New York, referring to Luis Bunuel, one of the
century's great directors, perhaps best known for ``The Andalusian
Dog'' (1928) and ``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie'' (1972).
``And they no longer treat love and death in grandiose terms. By
treating everyday realities, they connect better with young
audiences. Whether for good or bad, we've become more European.''
It has been a long journey.
</P>
<P>
   During Francisco Franco's dictatorship, from 1937 until his
death in 1975, many of the subjects Spanish directors deal with now
_ homosexuality, racism, marital abuse and drug addiction _ were
forbidden. Moviegoers had to be satisfied with corny folklore
musicals or films that glorified Spain, although by the 1950s a few
directors had begun to successfully challenge the
ultra-conservative status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Bunuel, who died in 1983, retained his artistic integrity by
working in France and Mexico, while Saura, among others, adopted an
allegorical and metaphorical style to mask his themes, notably in
``The Chase'' (1965). Once freed of constraints, Spanish directors
often dedicated themselves to reconstructing the past, trying to
depict their history more authentically.
</P>
<P>
   So great was the need to resurrect the ``true'' Spain that 300
historical films were released between 1976 and 1982, more than
half of all Spanish films made during that period. Saura challenged
the idea of whether we could ever even know what is historically
true in ``Blindfolded'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers born toward the end of the Franco era and afterward
did not share their elders' preoccupation with the past. Enamored
of Hollywood films, they adopted the American thriller, the film
noir and screwball comedy as models and made them their own.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing transformation of their cinema was also fueled by
economic exigencies. In 1994, the government changed its policy of
granting subsidies to projects it deemed of artistic merit to one
retroactively dependent on a film's success in the market place.
Now directors don't receive government money unless their films
attract an audience of about 70,000, a moderate number in Spain. As
a result, the industry reached its production nadir in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the savior: television. Today, 80 percent of Spanish film
production relies on co-financing arrangements with public and
private television stations, with the remaining 20 percent still
provided by government and private subsidies. But the stations,
too, expect the films they finance to have popular appeal, since a
television broadcast is part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In this new atmosphere, the industry is thriving. In 1998, Spain
produced 96 features, up from only 44 in 1994. What's more,
audiences have doubled, foreign distribution is up and,
increasingly, young Spaniards are choosing to become filmmakers. In
1995, the National Film School reopened after being closed for 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's film industry still lags behind its European
counterparts in production but not, crucially, in energy and
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Saura's passion for his trade has weathered the vicissitudes of
his country's film history. In fact, he first began thinking about
making his new film ``Goya in Bordeaux'' at the start of his career
in the '50s. ``Long ago, Goya inspired me with his statement, `I
don't see lines and colors, only shadows,''' Saura said. ``I wanted
to create his atmosphere in film. There's something strange and
mysterious that unites the greatest Spanish artists _ Goya,
Picasso, Bunuel. They all had enormous ego, strength, passion and
sensitivity. My next film will be about Bunuel.''
</P>
<P>
   Two themes run through most contemporary Spanish films _
personal responsibility and the difficulty of establishing honest
relationships. They are at the heart of Pons' ``Beloved/Friend,''
which documents the final days of a dying professor who wants to
leave his best friend a self-revealing essay. Frustrated in his
attempt, he finds that a young, sadistic, gay hustler may be his
only avenue to immortality. ``I show the struggle between
generations and how each grasps for its future,'' said Pons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bollain and Antonio Hernandez, director of the thriller
``Lisbon,'' approach the same themes very differently. In her
poignant ``Flowers From Another World,'' three lively women from
Cuba, the Dominican Republic and the Spanish city of Bilboa seek
mates among the bachelors of a provincial town.
</P>
<P>
   A love story, it also addresses Spain's persistent racism.
Hernandez, a filmmaker for 20 years, pairs an embittered woman and
a cowardly salesman in a search for her husband's killer. While a
major studio asked Hernandez to rewrite the story in English and
direct it for American distribution, he declined. ``Why repeat
myself?'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Would he have been able to keep the original's inconclusive
ending? ``Oh, no,'' he said. ``That's another reason why I can't do
it. They wanted everything to work out fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
