<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GUPTA-MANAGEMENT-BOSS     11-30 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUPTA-MANAGEMENT-BOSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SUCCEEDING WITHOUT LEMONADE-STAND EXPERIENCE  (ART ADV: Photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
(Eds: Umang Gupta is chairman and chief executive of Keynote
Systems Inc., a company in San Mateo, Calif., that measures Web
site performance for e-commerce companies. Keynote went public in
September. Gupta's stake in the company is now worth more than $125
million.) 
 By UMANG GUPTA with BRENT BOWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had no entrepreneurial ambitions until I came to America. I'd
love to say I was one of those kids who set up a lemonade stand or
had a paper route. But I didn't. I just wanted a job that paid more
than my dad earned as a civil servant in India. I came to America
in 1971 at age 22, got my MBA at Kent State University, worked for
a steel company in Ohio, then joined IBM as a salesman. After six
years, I said, OK, this is it, time to go back and resume my life
in India. But I was in love with a woman named Ruth, and it was
either Ruth or India. I was torn. I went back to India in order to
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   By then, I had got the entrepreneurial bug. For a while, I
considered starting a computer-related company in India. Then I
asked: Why India? Why not go back to the United States, marry Ruth,
move to Silicon Valley and start a company? So I did. Marrying
Ruthie was the best decision I ever made. We now have a daughter,
17, and a son, 11. Moving to Silicon Valley was my second-best
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I joined a Silicon Valley start-up that was an IBM
competitor. Then I tried to start my own company but couldn't get
any venture capitalists to fund me. So I joined a start-up called
Relational Software Inc., later to become Oracle Corp. I wrote
Oracle's first formal business plan in 1981 and ended up becoming a
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, I started Gupta Technologies, a provider of the world's
first client/server database software and tools for PCs. We went
public in 1993, and for a brief time the company was worth about
$400 million and a real hot IPO
</P>
<P>
   When the big boys like Microsoft and Oracle began competing
against us, I thought I could beat them at their game. I was wrong.
My dad once told me, ``No victory is final, and no defeat is
fatal.'' I hadn't paid attention. I thought my company's victory
when we went public was final.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, I've always been resilient. My mother always encouraged
me to question everything. When I was 11 or 12, I got into an
argument with a friend: ``Maybe there's no God,'' I said. He said
there must be a God because somebody had to create you, amoeba, the
world. I explained all this to my mother, and she told me to go ask
my friend who made God. After I became a father, the death of our
second child led me to reject my early skepticism and to believe
very firmly in God.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I stepped away from Gupta Corp. It was one of the
toughest things I ever did. It was like losing a child. I took
several months off and traveled all across America with my family.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, I made an early investment in Keynote, when it was
still very small. A few months later the board asked me take over
as CEO. The last two years have been a blast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
