<SLUG> BC-MA-AIDS-NEEDLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI URGED TO DECLARE NEEDLE EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a desperate attempt to slow what is now the leading
route of infection by the AIDS virus in Massachusetts _ intravenous
drug use _ nearly 800 doctors, nurses and others demanded Tuesday
that Gov. Paul Cellucci declare a public health emergency and
expand access to clean needles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts residents are dying,'' said Robert Greenwald,
director of public policy and legal affairs for the AIDS Action
Committee of Massachusetts, in a rally on the Statehouse steps
before the nearly 800 letters of protest were taken up to the
governor's office. ``This public health emergency demands an
immediate public health response.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is one of only 10 states that make it illegal to
possess a hypodermic needle without a prescription, and only four
communities have taken advantage of a state law that allows up to
10 communities to adopt pilot needle exchange programs, in which
drug users are given clean needles in exchange for used ones and
offered the opportunity to get into drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, between 53 to 58 percent of the people now living
with AIDS in New Bedford, Springfield and Worcester _ where efforts
to adopt needle exchange have been rejected _ contracted the virus
through IV drug use, according to the latest public health
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in Boston, which has had a needle exchange program
since 1994, only 29 percent of people living with AIDS were exposed
through IV drug use. The only other communities to adopt needle
exchange are Northampton, Provincetown and Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The transmission of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, through IV
drug use disproportionately affects women and minorities _ either
as a result of being drug users themselves, or of being a partner
of one _ according to state and federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ribeiro, 47, is one of those New Bedford residents living
with AIDS who contracted it through IV drug use. In an interview
after the rally, he said that after nearly a decade of his trying
to get a local needle exchange program adopted without success,
he's convinced it will take a declaration of a public health
emergency by Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to appeal to his humanity. The support is
out there, the medical community, the church community, the
families who have lost people,'' said Ribeiro, who has been
drug-free for 10 years, and founded Treatment on Demand Inc. in New
Bedford to advocate for expanded drug treatment resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tina T. Saxon of Disciples Baptist Church, who has
recently voiced concerns at black churches in the Boston area about
the AIDS epidemic, agreed. ``People are dying. People are dying
from this disease at every economic level, at every age level,''
said Saxon, who was not at the Statehouse rally, but attended
another rally Tuesday night on the eve of World AIDS Day in Roxbury
instead. ``It should be a national emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, during an unrelated news conference Tuesday, responded
to AIDS activists by citing several state programs that help combat
the epidemic _ including his administration's recent expansion of
Medicaid coverage to people who are infected with HIV, the virus
that causes AIDS, and not just those who have been diagnosed with
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's necessary to declare a public health
emergency. I think we have stepped up to the plate and will
continue to step up to the plate for those people who have AIDS and
those who are HIV-positive,'' said Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he pointed out that the state began the pilot
needle exchange programs with the stipulation that they have
community approval. ``We'll continue to be supportive as long as
it's something the local community wants.''
</P>
<P>
   David Amaral of the Christian Coalition of Massachusetts, who
helped lobby against a needle exchange program in New Bedford, said
it's clear the community there doesn't want the program, based on a
referendum defeating it. He said in an interview that he opposes
issuance of clean needles because it would ``enable'' IV drug
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they do with these clean needles? Inject themselves
with illegal, dangerous life-ruining drugs. It's like handing out
nips of Southern Comfort to alcoholics,'' in the hope that they
will not buy large amounts of the liquor and ``drink themselves
into an alcoholic coma or death,'' said Amaral, who is field
director for the coalition in Southeastern Massachusetts. ``It just
doesn't make sense. It flies in the face of common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents of needle exchange have cited concerns about
increases in crime and IV drug use. But supporters of clean needle
programs cite studies showing that they reduce the spread of HIV,
the virus that causes AIDS, and get more people into treatment,
without increasing crime and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needle exchange programs are not giving anybody drugs and
injection equipment they don't already have,'' said the Rev. Jon
Fuller, a Jesuit priest and an AIDS doctor, who spoke at the rally
Tuesday. ``It's not a small public health issue. It's about saving
hundreds of lives a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the state declared a public health emergency was
in the early 1990s, under then-Gov. William Weld, after a western
Massachusetts town's water supply was contaminated, according to
David Mulligan, who was state public health commisioner at the time
and is now an associate professor at Stonehill College. The
declaration allowed the state to use a privately owned quarry for a
temporary water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Boston needle exchange program began in 1994, more
than 3,000 people have been enrolled, and nearly a quarter of them
have been referred to drug treatment programs, according to
statistics from the city's public health commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
