<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE REST OF THE SEASON, 49ERS PLAY FOR PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It isn't like Jim Mora blows his cork on
national television all the time, and it isn't like he'll get many
chances to do it again soon.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after the January 3 game between the 49ers and Falcons
in Atlanta, Mora, the defensive coordinator of the San Francisco
Close Cover Before Striking, is going to have to change jobs to see
the business end of a ``Monday Night Football'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he was on the sideline as Green Bay's Tyrone Davis
lumbered into the end zone with the Packers' second touchdown,
unencumbered as he was by any visible 49er presence.
</P>
<P>
   And Mora bent a piston rod right then and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this!'' he yowled, an easy lip-read for even
the least attentive of football fans. ``What the ----?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mora knew very well what had happened. Linebacker
Winfred Tubbs hadn't made a fairly basic adjustment to the Packers'
formation on the second-down play from the San Francisco 10, and
Davis, an otherwise little-known tight end from Virginia, bustled
into the end zone with what proved to be a very extraneous score.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, though, it should be said that it was actually
Green Bay's first score, a 13-yard pass from Brett Favre to Corey
Bradford, that was the game-winner, because Mora knows, as we all
do, that the opponents' first touchdown is by definition the
game-winner with the offense the 49ers are churning out these days.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it was the aesthetics of Davis' touchdown that tore at
Mora's already raw sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't have happened,'' he said flatly. ``The thing is,
we know there's so little margin for error right now, and to make a
mistake like that on something so easy... well, it's just not
excusable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mora didn't say any of this in anger. He had expended his anger
with that Bulgarian folk song he emitted as Davis bundled himself
into the end zone. Besides, what was there to do about it? Oh sure,
he could flog the miscreant in the Tuesday film session, but the
deed had been done. The 49ers had lost convincingly yet again, and
even though Mora's defense had held its own against Favre's
improvisational gifts, the fact is that 20 is too many points.
</P>
<P>
   No, the fact is that seven is too many points against the 49ers
these days, and it isn't going to change between now and Draft Day.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 49ers lost two more cornerbacks Monday night, the
much maligned R.W. McQuarters to a fractured right collarbone and
the so-far unnoticed Monty Montgomery to a fractured right radius
(near the elbow). Thus, Mora's mood figured to be a little grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the plan is now,'' he said, although he did
say that Darnell Walker and Ramos McDonald would probably start
Sunday in Cincinnati. ``I'm sure Bill (Walsh) and Terry (Donahue)
will come up with something. I know we have to do something fast.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, there isn't much voodoo Walsh and
Donahue can do, other than activate Wasswa Serwanga and Craig
Newsome from the just-watching list. And let's face it, they're
just names replacing other names at this point. Among other things,
neither of them shows any interest in playing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Which is quite a coincidence when you consider those who
actually play on the offensive side of the ball. The 49ers played
about as well as they can defensively the last two weeks, and it
made no more difference than if they had allowed 650 yards. The
49ers got their three points early, and came dangerously close to
actually attaining double figures for the first time in over a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Like it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, a fourth 49er win this season is nearly
inconceivable, and it is surely a fact that the employees are
playing only to like what they see when they shave on Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   It seems equally odd to consider Mora's position. His side of
the ball is doing reasonably well now after the tortures of
October, and it's still two touchdowns short every week.
</P>
<P>
   As we remember from the acrid fumes of the chemical fire that
was October and the first half of November, the defense was a
thorough shambles, incapable of stopping anyone from doing anything
at any time for any reason. Mora heard things his father Jim, Sr.,
didn't hear even in his last strange days in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerbacks were perfectly dreadful. There was no pass rush.
The linebackers were being moved pretty much at will. They allowed
20 touchdowns in four games, a ridiculous figure even by Pac-10
standards.
</P>
<P>
   So now the defense has gotten at least nominally better, just as
the offense has completely imploded, leaving the same result, the
same margin of defeat, the same feeling of inescapable doom.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, Jim Mora, Sr., is so happy with his Colts that
he doesn't get flustered when a backdrop falls against the back of
his head. Two years ago, he fled the Big Easy after a series of
defeats that left him uttering phrases like ``diddley-poo'' in
public.
</P>
<P>
   His son, on the other hand, was safe and learning the business
with the most successful team of the last two decades. Now he is
secure only with the knowledge that the 49ers' ills have outgrown
his ability to affect meaningful change.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe that's what his Vesuvian outburst really was _ the
knowledge that the 49er defense put in a stomachable performance
Monday night, and the only thing people will remember is him
torquing himself into a snit after a meaningless touchdown in a
hopeless season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
