<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTED TO SUPPORT REVAMP OF INCOME TAX SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Governor George W. Bush plans to announce
Wednesday that he has rejected the idea of a ``flat tax'' and
instead will propose a revamped income tax system with a top rate
of 33 percent and lower marginal rates for most taxpayers, a
campaign aide sayu.
</P>
<P>
   After months of internal campaign debate, Bush will unveil the
plan in Des Moines and hopes to trumpet it Thursday during his
first GOP presidential debate in Manchester, N.H. Some of Bush's
opponents have criticized him for failing to provide details of his
tax policy until now.
</P>
<P>
   The key feature of Bush's plan is reducing the current top tax
rate of 39.6 percent to 33 percent. In addition, the middle-income
tax rate of 28 percent would drop to 25 percent. Surprisingly, the
Republican presidential contender does not address whether he wants
to reduce capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, by contrast, has proposed a flat tax of 17
percent, and Gary Bauer has suggested a 16 percent plan.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes, who also is seeking the GOP nomination, is likely
to criticize Bush's plan for not cutting taxes enough, Democrats
are expected to say it puts too much emphasis on helping the
wealthiest taxpayers. For example, only 1 percent of the taxpayers
would benefit from cutting the top tax rate, according to Robert
McIntyre, director of the labor union-backed Citizens for Tax
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said the Bush plan ``is a pretty big tax cut for rich
people.'' McIntyre's initial analysis shows that the ``top 5
percent of taxpayers would get three-quarters of the benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign is focusing on the benefit to lower- and
middle-income taxpayers by providing examples of how the plan would
affect average families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you earn $1 million, you get a big tax cut,'' another Bush
aide said. ``The governor plans to cut taxes for everybody from all
walks of life. The governor is not going to start carving people
out (of the tax cuts) just because they are successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said that when various deductions are counted,
a family of four earning $35,000 a year would get a tax cut of
$1,500, and a family earning $50,000 would save $1,900 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan sets out to make life better for average men women and
children,'' Bush says, according to the draft of Wednesday's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   To put the Bush plan in perspective, the proposal would cost
$483 billion over five years. While it is difficult to compare the
cost of tax plans without knowing all the details, that amount
falls between the estimated $1.5 trillion cost of the Forbes plan
and the $156 billion tax cut proposal unsuccessfully put forward
this year by congressional Republicans, McIntyre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan would also provide a number of increased tax
deductions. For example, Bush plans to double the child tax credit
to $1,000 and to increase the allowable annual contribution to
educational savings accounts to $5,000 from $500. Bush also
proposes expanding the use of the education accounts not just for
college but also to pay for private elementary and secondary
schooling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      11-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Patriots safety Lawyer Milloy shed more
light Tuesday on incidents between him and teammate Vincent Brisby
at suburban Boston restaurant last Wednesday and at practice the
following morning.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy said he regretted what happened at the Palace in Saugus,
but he also echoed the sentiments of team management that they have
received far too much scrutiny, given what actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret it because it got out in the public,'' said Milloy.
``Being one of the leaders of this team, I have to suffer the
consequences of it, but this is getting blown way out of
proportion. The way the media is talking about it, it's like
Lewis-Holyfield or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy said he arrived to teammate Willie McGinest's ``Big
Brother'' charity event at the Palace with a woman at about 11:30
p.m. in a limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't been there more than 15 minutes and I was sitting
there and all of a sudden Brisby had me in a headlock,'' said
Milloy. ``I pushed him and then all my teammates started to grab us
and break it up. I know Rod Rutledge pulled me away and held me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out later from Briz that he was just playing. I didn't
know it while it was happening, so I reacted. I don't know where
this stuff about the pool sticks came from. I played baseball, so
if I had a pool stick in my hand I could do some damage. That's
completely false.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Brisby approached Milloy before practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't had a chance to discuss it and resolve it, so that
morning he came over and started pushing me,'' said Milloy. ``It
was broken up right away by our teammates. Neither time did it ever
get out of hand. Neither one of us got hurt. We're fine. It's way
past us. It's not even an issue with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier said
coach Pete Carroll imposed fines but reports of a $5,000 figure for
each player were ``too high.''
</P>
<P>
   WBZ-TV in Boston reported Tuesday that a woman who was at the
club suffered a gash above an eye as a result of the scuffle. That
surprised Milloy. ``I don't recall seeing another woman in that
area other than the one I was with, and she brought me home,'' said
Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy also said he and Brisby often engage in horseplay on the
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   While Grier didn't appreciate the players acting as they did in
public, he said, ``What happens is when we're going bad, it's
newsworthy. We're not playing very well. Everything is magnified.
After the incident, both guys played hard and both guys handled it
well. There were no repercussions.''
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the story _ Terry Glenn being stopped by
police for speeding at 4 a.m. and subsequently being late for
practice _ also needs clarification.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a copy of Glenn's citation, and it says that
he was stopped at 8:30 a.m., not 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who reportedly was helped to a limousine after drinking
too much after the Palace event, was already an hour late for a
team meeting the next morning when he got stopped, so he wound up
being two hours late.
</P>
<P>
   As a disciplinary measure, Carroll benched Glenn for the first
quarter of Sunday's 17-7 loss in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, from owner Bob Kraft on down, view last week's
incident in Saugus as regrettable because it occured at a charity
event. But after an investigation, the team concluded that the
squabble at the Palace and the follow-up altercation between Milloy
and Brisby on Thanksgiving were minor in nature.
</P>
<P>
   They do not reflect a ``lack of control'' by Carroll in
management's eyes. Anyone who was around the team during the Bill
Parcells era recalls a vicious fight between McGinest and Ferric
Collons, and other lesser skirmishes among players.
</P>
<P>
   According to Grier, the incidents have not detracted from team
preparation. The Patriots, after three straight losses to
divisional opponents, need to spend the week getting in sync,
particularly on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is in no hurry to fire Carroll, despite the team's slump.
As he does in his other businesses, Kraft will evaluate things when
the year is over, but bringing in a new coach isn't high on his
priority list.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kraft is going to bat for Carroll, talking to him
almost every day to offer support. Grier said he, too, offers
support to Carroll on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots don't turn it around, Grier himself will be
under fire for drafting some unproductive players.
</P>
<P>
   But right now Kraft isn't panicking on his management team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1928EST &QL; 
