<HEADER>
A5416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MEXICO-BODIES-BOS &LR;      11-30 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BODIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES OF MISSING HOPE MASS GRAVE WILL HOLD ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico _ Among the dozens of spectators who
gathered Tuesday outside a dusty ranch and shooting range known as
the ``Hidden Treasure,'' Roman Alonso Aguilar stood humbly, holding
a faded, photocopied newspaper article about his younger brother,
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   In one frightful but unforgettable moment on May 22, 1997,
Alonso said, a pair of men in cowboy boots and hats burst into his
home in this northern Mexican city and took his 33-year-old brother
away. He hasn't seen or heard from him since.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mexican and American authorities dug through the earth
Tuesday at this ranch in search of a mass grave that is said to
hold the remains of 100 people, including nearly two dozen
Americans, Aguilar hopes to find an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know something, anything about where he is,''
Roman, 36, said as officials continued their work less than 300
yards away. ``Our whole family has been searching all over for him,
including his 11 kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Working on a tip from a Mexican police informant, scores of US
and Mexican investigators have descended on this patch near the
border in search of the bodies of victims believed to have been
murdered by one of Mexico's largest and fiercest drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary joint effort among the FBI, the DEA and the
Mexican federal Attorney General's Office, forensic experts were
searching for mass graves at two ranches outside this city, which
sits across the Rio Grande from El Paso, Texas. Authorities said
they would be searching two other nearby sites.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
estimated at least 100 bodies were buried in the graves, and that
22 of them could be US citizens. Some of the victims may include
former informants to authorities and maybe even US law enforcement
agents who have disappeared in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant FBI Director Thomas Pickard said in Washington that
investigators at the scene has recovered part of one body Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe these people were killed for their knowledge or for
being witnesses to drug trafficking endeavors,'' Pickard said.
``Most of the information we have shows these individuals were
buried there at least two to three years ago, so it's not a recent
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials were led to the ranches by a paid informant who
approached the FBI earlier this year. The informant reportedly took
and passed lie detector tests before agents decided to begin their
searches.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of armed soldiers dressed in black outfits and ski masks
surrounded one of the ranches on Monday night. Local media reported
that six people in the main house, five of them ranch workers and a
6-month-old baby, were taken into protective custody, before
investigators began their hunt for the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, workers returned to the site, which sits on a desolate
stretch of highway across from junkyards about 10 miles south of
Ciudad Juarez, to continue the exhumations. Officials said it could
be about 30 days before any identifications could be made.
</P>
<P>
   If the tips prove fruitful, the graves could be an important _
if gruesome _ break for US and Mexican anti-narcotics
investigators, who for years have tried to gain additional leads
against the Juarez drug cartel, one of the dominant cocaine
shipping organizations in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   As the power of Colombian druglords has waned over the last 10
years because increased police pressure, they have been steadily
supplanted by Mexican groups. The amount of cocaine that now
crosses the US-Mexican border has tripled over the last decade,
according to the US Customs Service, to more than 1 million tons in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton said he had not received
confirmation that 22 Americans were among the suspected victims but
condemned the killings as ``a horrible example'' of the excesses of
Mexico's drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it reinforces the imperative of our trying not only to
protect our border but to work with the Mexican authorities to try
to combat these (drug cartels),'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the border center of Ciudad Juarez has been the base
for the Juarez cartel, a drug gang formerly run by Amado Carrillo
Fuentes. Carrillo was the country's No. 1 cocaine trafficker before
he died in 1997 following complications from plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of his death, many residents and local officials
say, hundreds of people were kidnapped, tortured or killed in the
city in what police believe was at least in part a battle for
control of the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of many of the victims, like Aguilar, said their pleas
to local and state police officials go unanswered, perhaps because
many of the officers themselves work for the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know why our police never mobilized to help us look
for (our brother),'' Aguilar said as his eyes welled with tears.
``We can only think that they don't want to help us because they're
helping (the cartel).''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of kidnappings and unexplained murders has become so
frequent in Juarez that relatives of missing people have formed
their own association, which is based in El Paso and has been
prompting authorities on both sides of the border for years to take
action.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime F. Hervella, the association's director, said that since
the group formed in 1997, there have been 196 cases of missing
people, roughly 500 execution-style murders and 198 young women who
have been killed in Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the impotence of the (Mexican) authorities to
investigate these tragedies which has brought us to this kind of
situation,'' Hervella said Tuesday. ``How can we believe that
graves like this existed in our own backyard and no one knew
anything about it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-PLAYBOY-485&AMP;AD     11-30 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PLAYBOY-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT HEARS ARGUMENT ON LAW CURBING CABLE TV SEX CHANNELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (also see SCOTUS, about an abortion case)  
 (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration came before the Supreme
Court on Tuesday to defend a federal law aimed at shielding
households that do not subscribe to sexually explicit cable
television channels from receiving unwanted and incompletely
scrambled signals during hours when children might be watching.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which a special three-judge federal court struck down
last year on First Amendment grounds, requires any cable system
lacking the technology to scramble unwanted signals completely to
relegate sexually oriented programming to hours when children were
least likely to watch. The Federal Communications Commission
subsequently defined that ``safe harbor'' period as 10 p.m. to 6
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the justices appeared puzzled by the law, a provision
of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 that was adopted as a floor
amendment, without any debate or congressional finding. They
questioned the extent of the technological problem, known as
``signal bleed,'' and wondered why, as Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg
put it, the government was acting as ``kind of a super parent''
rather than leaving it to parents who are concerned about the
problem to order blocking devices for their home television sets. A
parallel provision of the 1996 law requires cable systems to make
these devices available without charge upon request.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a question of each individual parent being able
to decide'' whether to take measures to block the blurred pictures
and muffled sounds from entering the home, said Assistant Solicitor
General James Feldman in reply to Ginsburg. He added that ``there's
a social interest'' in shielding children from the material and in
not interpreting parental inaction as authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman said Congress had decided that such images were harmful
to children and that parents who nonetheless wanted their children
to see them should have to take the affirmative step of ordering
the sexually explicit programming. ``Consent should not be
inferred,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   The law was challenged by the Playboy Entertainment Group, a
cable television spinoff of the magazine that picked up support for
its challenge from a wide array of media groups. A brief filed by
organizations representing booksellers, the movie industry, the
recording industry and others said that because ``the once discrete
worlds of print and electronic media are discrete no longer,'' the
Supreme Court should stop trying to calibrate different First
Amendment standards for different media.
</P>
<P>
   The court has not managed to define a constitutional standard
for review of government regulation of cable television, according
cable somewhat more protection than radio and broadcast television,
where regulations governing indecency have been upheld, and less
than the print media, where sexually explicit expression is fully
protected as long as it falls short of obscenity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In striking down the law last December, the special three-judge
U.S. District Court in Wilmington, Del., applied a high standard of
review and required the government to prove that the law was the
``least restrictive means'' of shielding children from the sexually
oriented programming. Because the blocking device was available to
those who wanted it, the time-of-day restriction, which limits
viewing even in homes with no children, was not the least
burdensome approach and so was unconstitutional, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy's lawyer, Robert Corn-Revere, described the law as ``a
case of regulatory overkill'' that restricted adults' access to
constitutionally protected speech. He said the problem of signal
bleed was tremendously variable, absent from some cable systems,
only intermittently present on others, depending on equipment and
sometimes on the weather. ``A blanket, across-the-board approach is
strikingly inappropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As cable systems switch from analog to digital equipment, the
problem is expected to disappear, but that could take 10 years or
more, according to briefs in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' responses to the arguments in the case ranged from
the theoretical to the intensely practical. When Corn-Revere said a
cable subscriber could order a blocking device with ``a simple
phone call,'' several justices wanted to know whether the
subscriber would then have to put up with the inconvenience of
waiting at home for a service call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all had to stay home to wait for repairmen who didn't
come,'' said Justice Stephen G. Breyer, adding almost under his
breath: ``The repairmen still don't come.'' His point was that the
blocking device, while free, could still be so inconvenient to
obtain that parents would not bother to order it. So for purposes
of shielding children from sexually explicit material, he said,
``it makes an enormous difference'' whether the law requires
parents to take some action, or whether it operates regardless of
what the parents do.
</P>
<P>
   Corn-Revere said that with current technology, subscribers could
install the devices on their own. Most of the 20 million to 30
million televisions sold every year now come with built-in
channel-blocking devices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The case, United States vs. Playboy Entertainment Group, No.
98-1682, presented the court with a provision of the same
telecommunications law that it confronted three years ago in a
landmark ruling on free speech on the Internet. That unanimous
decision, Reno vs. American Civil Liberties Union, struck down the
Communications Decency Act, a separate provision of the 1996 law
that made it a crime to send or display indecent material on the
Internet in a way that made it available to minors. The court said
the law's goal was laudable but that it threatened to suppress
protected speech among adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
