   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following financial
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Dec. 1 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3704.
</P>
<P>
   FORECAST-SOCAL (Los Angeles) _ After outperforming expectations
during 1999,Southern California's economy will grow at more modest
pace during the first part of the next century, according to a
report that will be released today. The outlying areas of Ventura,
Riverside and San Bernardino counties will record the biggest gains
employment through 2001 while sprawling Los Angeles County will
record smaller, but still solid, gains. By Greg Wilcox (Will move
on the ``n'' California, ``a'' national and ``f'' financial news
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   GHOST-EMPLOYEES (Los Angeles) _ The LAUSD's top investigator
said his findings of widespread employee timecard abuse and ``ghost
employees'' were only a preliminary glance at a problem he would
like to explore fully if he had enough money. Chief investigator
Don Mullinax said the intent of his confidential memo, obtained by
the Daily News, was to convince the district to dedicate more money
to rooting out abuse. On Tuesday, board member Caprice Young, head
of the audit committee, said the findings are so startling that she
will ensure Mullinax has enough funds to complete his
investigation. By Greg Gittrich (Will move on the ``n'' California
and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS_MARCH (Los Angeles) _ U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein and others
announce plans to hold a Million Mom March against guns in
Washington, D.C., on Mothers Day, May 14. Joining Feinstein at the
Sportsman's Lodge in Studio City are several mothers from Southern
California, including Joy Turner, whose 10-year-old son was gunned
down and killed. The march will be a call for passage of gun laws.
Afterward, Feinstein joins more than 100 Valley residents and
business people at the latest in her ongoing series of community
lunches throughout the state. By Robert Monroe (Will move on the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   AMMO (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Police Commission votes 3-2
on Tuesday to recommend a citywide ban on the sale of ammunition.
If L.A. adopts the ban, it would be the largest city to do so, on
the heels of Chicago and West Hollywood. But such a ban depends
partly on an expected ruling by the state Attorney General's Office
on the legality of such a policy by cities. In the meantime, the
Police Commission will forward its recommendation to the City
Council's Public Safety Committee, which wants to expedite it to
the full council. By Beth Barrett (Will move on the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   TRULOVE-CARWASH (Los Angeles) _ Sonny should have caught on when
Sherry showed up two or three times a week at the Valencia car wash
he managed for a wash and wax, but it took the big lug a year to
realize she was smitten. Now the two, who run Sonny and Sherry's
Hillbilly Hot Dog Stand in Virginia, have returned home to marry,
yes, at the car wash. The ceremony is Tuesday night. By Bhavna
Mistry (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CARO-HOMICIDE (Los Angeles) _ Socorro Caro, the 42-year-old wife
of a prominent rheumatologist, was arrested Tuesday on suspicion of
murdering their three young sons in the family's hilltop mansion
outside Moorpark. The suspect has been hospitalized with a gunshot
wound to the head since the shootings were discovered by Dr. Xavier
Caro Nov. 22. Socorro Caro, known as Cora to her friends, was
transferred Tuesday from Los Robles Regional Medical Center in
Thousand Oaks to the jail ward at Ventura County Medical Center. By
Lisa Mascaro (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN (Cohen) _ More often than not, it's a woman who is behind
a household's choice of Internet service providers, cable,
telephone and insurance agents, according to a study to be released
Wednesday by the National Foundation for Women Business Owners.
Women who own their own businesses are even more savvy than the
average working woman when it comes to purchasing and investment
decisions, the study found. By Jason Cohen (Will move on the ``n''
California, ``a'' national and ``f'' financial news wires.)
</P>
