<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC CONSIDERS ISSUING A TRACKING STOCK FOR ITS WIRELESS UNIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc., the nation's largest local phone
carrier, is considering issuing separately traded tracking stocks
to follow the company's wireless communications unit and its
international operations, SBC said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's management has not reached a final decision on
either initiative and has not presented them to the board for
formal consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Donald E. Kiernan, SBC's chief financial officer, said in an
interview yesterday: ``The valuations for those companies, for
stand-alone wireless operators, have grown dramatically over the
last several months _ some would say even beyond what any of us
have expected. We have a duty to our shareholders to consider all
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, according to Bloomberg News, Edward E. Whitacre
Jr., SBC's chairman, said before a speech in Boston: ``I've thought
about it. It's a good way to unlock value in some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan said that SBC _ which does business through the
Ameritech, Pacific Bell and Southwestern Bell telephone companies _
seriously considered a wireless tracking stock a few months ago,
but declined to move forward because issuing a tracking stock can
make it difficult for a parent company to work closely with the
unit being tracked.
</P>
<P>
   But as it became clear over the last several weeks that AT&AMP;T
intended to issue a tracking stock for its wireless operations and
as wireless stocks in general soared in value, ``we pulled off the
shelf some of those analyses,'' Kiernan said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's management intends to announce plans for a wireless
tracking stock at a meeting with analysts on Monday, according to
executives close to that company, the largest long-distance
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan declined to say how long it might take for SBC to reach
a decision on a wireless tracking stock. In Boston, Whitacre said
he was interested to ``see what happens with AT&AMP;T,'' according to
Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   He said that any consideration of an international tracking
stock was less advanced than the internal discussions about the
wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks are a relatively recent financial invention that
can allow companies to raise the visibility, and value, of their
far-flung subsidiaries without selling parts of those units. Hughes
Electronics, for instance, trades as a tracking stock of General
Motors, which owns Hughes. Hughes reports independent financial
results, but investors who buy Hughes shares do not actually
purchase a piece of the company, as they do when purchasing normal
common shares.
</P>
<P>
   Big, old telecommunications carriers like AT&AMP;T and SBC have been
known for being financially conservative, and it is unlikely that
either company would have seriously considered issuing a tracking
stock just a few years ago. But the Sprint Corp.'s success in
issuing wireless tracking shares last year appears to have prompted
them to reconsider.
</P>
</TEXT>
