<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-DOW-CORNING-BANKRUPTC     11-30 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-CORNING-BANKRUPTCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE OKS DOW CORNING BREAST IMPLANT SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHERYL WADE and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY CITY, Mich. _ A federal judge approved a plan Tuesday to
allow Dow Corning Corp., to settle thousands of lawsuits brought by
women who claimed the firm's silicone breast implants caused them
serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The implant plan is part of a larger $4.5 billion package
approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Arthur J. Spector designed to
allow Dow Corning to emerge from bankruptcy. The firm sought legal
protection in May 1995 because it couldn't cope with the onslaught
of lawsuits brought by women with implants.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan _ which is expected to be appealed _ Dow Corning
would pay a total of $3.2 billion to 170,000 women with silicone
breast implants. Another $1.3 billion would be used to pay other
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot ahead before any money is passed,''
Spector said during a 20-minute hearing. He called his ruling ``the
end to the first chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   Spector did not elaborate on how he ruled on various issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important day, one we've been looking forward
to for the last four and a half years,'' said Gary Anderson, Dow
Corning's president and chief executive officer. But, he conceded,
``it isn't the final, final day.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Houser, the lead attorney for Dow Corning, said Spector
approved the $4.5 billion plan that the company proposed last
November.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, women would receive between $12,000 and
$300,000, depending on the severity of their illnesses. Women could
receive up to $25,000 if their implants were found to have leaked
and ruptured. They can also receive $5,000 to have their implants
removed. The payments would be made over 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   If women accept the settlement they cannot sue Dow Corning or
its parents _ The Dow Chemical Co. or Corning Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Women who decide not to accept the settlement from Dow Corning
can sue the company in federal court in Detroit. Dow Corning will
set aside $400 million to pay for any cases they might lose.
</P>
<P>
   The company got out of the implant business in 1992 after the
Food and Drug Administration banned the use of silicone breast
implants on the ground that Dow Corning and other manufacturers
could not prove they were ``safe and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of the FDA's action, hundreds of thousands of
women sued Dow Corning _ once the world's largest manufacturer of
breast implants _ and other implant makers.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning was facing nearly 19,000 lawsuits when it filed for
bankruptcy in 1995. The other implant manufacturers, including
Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing Co. and Baxter Healthcare Corp.,
have since settled implant lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning has long maintained that implants cannot be linked
to disease and, indeed, recent scientific studies have found
implants do not cause serious disease such as cancer or lupus.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs dissatisfied with Spector's ruling were weighing
whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Geoffrey White, who represents 50 Nevada women with
implants, criticized part of the settlement plan that bars lawsuits
against Dow Chemical and Corning _ Dow Corning's parent companies.
He said the plan gives Dow Chemical a `` free ride'' and said he'd
take his challenge to the U.S. Supreme Court if necessary. The
Nevada Supreme Court has ruled that Dow Chemical can be sued over
breast implant claims against Dow Corning.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers said they may appeals the $3.2 billion limit to
pay breast implant claims as well as the $400,000 limit to pay
women should they win jury trials.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is also weighing whether to appeal
Spector's ruling on the grounds that federal programs such as
Medicare _ which have paid for treatment of women with implants _
should be entitled to money.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bohan, representing the Department of Justice, said during
the hearing that the government wants the right to appeal on those
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Wade reported from Bay City, Mich. Jennifer Corbett
Dooren reported from Washington, D.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
