<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTED TO SUPPORT REVAMP OF INCOME TAX SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Governor George W. Bush plans to announce
Wednesday that he has rejected the idea of a ``flat tax'' and
instead will propose a revamped income tax system with a top rate
of 33 percent and lower marginal rates for most taxpayers, a
campaign aide sayu.
</P>
<P>
   After months of internal campaign debate, Bush will unveil the
plan in Des Moines and hopes to trumpet it Thursday during his
first GOP presidential debate in Manchester, N.H. Some of Bush's
opponents have criticized him for failing to provide details of his
tax policy until now.
</P>
<P>
   The key feature of Bush's plan is reducing the current top tax
rate of 39.6 percent to 33 percent. In addition, the middle-income
tax rate of 28 percent would drop to 25 percent. Surprisingly, the
Republican presidential contender does not address whether he wants
to reduce capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, by contrast, has proposed a flat tax of 17
percent, and Gary Bauer has suggested a 16 percent plan.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes, who also is seeking the GOP nomination, is likely
to criticize Bush's plan for not cutting taxes enough, Democrats
are expected to say it puts too much emphasis on helping the
wealthiest taxpayers. For example, only 1 percent of the taxpayers
would benefit from cutting the top tax rate, according to Robert
McIntyre, director of the labor union-backed Citizens for Tax
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said the Bush plan ``is a pretty big tax cut for rich
people.'' McIntyre's initial analysis shows that the ``top 5
percent of taxpayers would get three-quarters of the benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign is focusing on the benefit to lower- and
middle-income taxpayers by providing examples of how the plan would
affect average families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you earn $1 million, you get a big tax cut,'' another Bush
aide said. ``The governor plans to cut taxes for everybody from all
walks of life. The governor is not going to start carving people
out (of the tax cuts) just because they are successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said that when various deductions are counted,
a family of four earning $35,000 a year would get a tax cut of
$1,500, and a family earning $50,000 would save $1,900 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan sets out to make life better for average men women and
children,'' Bush says, according to the draft of Wednesday's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   To put the Bush plan in perspective, the proposal would cost
$483 billion over five years. While it is difficult to compare the
cost of tax plans without knowing all the details, that amount
falls between the estimated $1.5 trillion cost of the Forbes plan
and the $156 billion tax cut proposal unsuccessfully put forward
this year by congressional Republicans, McIntyre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan would also provide a number of increased tax
deductions. For example, Bush plans to double the child tax credit
to $1,000 and to increase the allowable annual contribution to
educational savings accounts to $5,000 from $500. Bush also
proposes expanding the use of the education accounts not just for
college but also to pay for private elementary and secondary
schooling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
