<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-PROGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDUCING HEART RISK FACTORS CAN EXTEND LIFE, NEW STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to increase the odds of living 6 to 10 years longer?
</P>
<P>
   For those who do, the prescription is simple: just don't smoke,
lower cholesterol below the current American average, and keep
blood pressure within healthy limits.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that each individual who follows this
advice will reap additional years of benefit. But a new analysis,
published Wednesday, provides the best evidence yet that, on
average, lifespans can be extended this much by paying attention to
just these three risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis also suggests that far more progress is possible in
the nation's fight against cardiovascular disease, even though
deaths from heart attacks and strokes have already plummeted nearly
60 percent from their peaks in the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Further gains would not require America to become a nation of
pure-living ascetics. The authors of the study note that the goals
are attainable _ cholesterol below 200 milligrams per deciliter,
blood pressure below 120-over-80, and abstention from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   These levels are not far from where many Americans already are,
researchers point out, and the vast majority of Americans do not
smoke. The other side of the coin, however, is that millions of
people still smoke and have high cholesterol and blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of lowering these risks are not limited to reduced
risk of heart disease. The overall risk of dying from cancer was
also about 50 percent lower for men and 17 percent lower for women
in the low-risk categories for smoking, cholesterol, and blood
pressure, according to the study, published in this week's Journal
of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found no evidence, as some earlier studies had,
that lower cholesterol is associated with higher cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the new analysis is the first to measure directly
the lifespan-lengthening effect of favorable cholesterol, blood
pressure, and smoking status. Up to now, researchers have had to
make an educated guess about the death risk among people in
low-risk categories, since no studies were large enough or long
enough to tally sufficient numbers of deaths among low-risk
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In previous studies, not enough people had low levels of all
three major risk factors ``to permit direct measurement of risk,''
explain Dr. Jeremiah Stamler and his colleagues at Northwestern
University and the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Their analysis encompassed 360,330 men and 6,229 women who
enrolled in two large studies begun between 1967 and 1975, the
Multiple Risk Factor Intervention Trial (MRFIT) and the Chicago
Heart Association Detection Project in Industry.
</P>
<P>
   The data included 16 years of follow-up among the MRFIT
participants while those in the Chicago study were followed for 22
years. Nearly all deaths and their causes were accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found that men who were young when they entered the
studies _ between 18 and 39 years old _ had 6.3 years to 9.5 years
more estimated life expectancy if they met the low-risk criteria
for smoking, blood pressure, and cholesterol, compared to all other
men of similar age.
</P>
<P>
   Among middle-aged men, from 40 to 59 years old, those who were
low-risk could expect about six years of additional life compared
to all others.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-aged women who were low-risk had 5.8 more years of life
expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   The studies did not record dietary or exercise habits, but
Stamler and his colleagues suggested that cholesterol level and
blood pressure may be not only risk-reducing factors in themselves
but also indicators of healthier lifestyles that included better
diet and more exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of not smoking and having lower cholesterol and
blood pressure extended to African Americans as well as whites, and
to those of lower socioeconomic status.
</P>
<P>
   Although genetic factors play a role in heart disease, cancer,
and other major causes of death, the researchers said successes in
reducing lifestyle-associated risk factors shows that genetics is
not a barrier to further improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge,'' the wrote, ``is to mobilize the societal will
and resources to realize these goals in all population strata to
end the coronary heart disease epidemic early in the next
century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
