<HEADLINE>
ABORTION CURBS IN 2 STATES TEMPORARILY BLOCKED BY HIGH COURT
ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wis., Neb.)   (also see SCOTUS-PLAYBOY)  
(bl) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday temporarily blocked
enforcement of abortion restrictions in Wisconsin and Illinois to
give the justices time to consider whether to decide the
constitutionality of the two states' so-called partial-birth
abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   The order was issued by Justice John Paul Stevens in his
capacity as the justice with jurisdiction over the 7th Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals, in Chicago. That court rejected constitutional
challenges to the two laws in a 5-4 decision in October. It then
refused twice, including Tuesday on a tie vote of 5-5, to issue a
stay of its own ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The laws would have gone into effect Wednesday had Stevens not
intervened. Doctors who violate the Illinois law face three years
in prison while the Wisconsin law carries a penalty of up to life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors and abortion clinics challenging the two laws,
represented in the Illinois case by the American Civil Liberties
Union and in the Wisconsin case by the Center for Reproductive Law
and Policy, in New York, have not yet filed their Supreme Court
appeals but expect to do so in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is already before the justices in a petition filed two
weeks ago by the state of Nebraska, where a similar law was struck
down in September by the 8th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals. The
justices could decide by mid-January whether to hear the Nebraska
appeal, possibly in time for a ruling by the end of the current
term in early summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has not heard an abortion case since 1992,
when by a 5-4 vote it reaffirmed the constitutional right to
abortion first established in Roe vs. Wade. While there is no
guarantee that the justices will take any of the current round of
cases, the conflicting rulings by the 7th and 8th circuits
substantially increases the likelihood.
</P>
<P>
   While Stevens offered no elaboration on his order Tuesday, the
court's own practice is to grant a stay only in cases that are good
candidates for eventual review on the merits.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty states have enacted laws to prohibit a particular method
of performing late-term abortion. Lower courts have blocked most of
them after finding, as the 8th Circuit did in the Nebraska case,
that the description of the medical procedure was broad and vague
enough possibly to outlaw another, much more common method of
abortion that is used before a fetus can live outside the womb. In
upholding the Wisconsin and Illinois laws, the 7th Circuit majority
conceded that these, too, were vague as written. But the appeals
court said the problem could be cured by U.S. District Courts in
the two states issuing ``precautionary injunctions'' that would
limit prosecutions under the laws until their meaning was clarified
by amendments, regulations, or state court rulings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
