<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-30 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SENSELESS IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there anything more ridiculous in the news today then the
protests against the World Trade Organization in Seattle? I doubt
it.
</P>
<P>
   These anti-WTO protesters _ who are a Noah's ark of flat-earth
advocates, protectionist trade unions and yuppies looking for their
1960s fix _ are protesting against the wrong target with the wrong
tools. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   What unites the anti-WTO crowd is their realization that we now
live in a world without walls. The Cold War system we just emerged
from was built around division and walls; the globalization system
that we are now in is built around integration and webs. In this
new system, jobs, cultures, environmental problems and labor
standards can much more easily flow back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   The ridiculous thing about the protesters is that they find
fault with this, and blame the WTO. The WTO is not the cause of
this world without walls, it's the effect. The more countries trade
with one another, the more they need an institution to set the
basic rules of trade, and that is all the WTO does. ``Rules are a
substitute for walls _ when you don't have walls you need more
rules,'' notes the Council on Foreign Relations expert Michael
Mandelbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Because some countries try to use their own rules to erect new
walls against trade, the WTO adjudicates such cases. For instance,
there was the famous ``Flipper vs. GATTzilla'' dispute. (The WTO
used be known as GATT.) America has rules against catching tuna in
nets that might also snare dolphins; other countries don't, and
those other countries took the United States before a GATT tribunal
and charged that our insistence on Flipper-free tuna was a trade
barrier. The anti-WTO protesters extrapolate from such narrow cases
that the WTO is going to become a Big Brother and tell us how to
live generally. Nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   What's crazy is that the protesters want the WTO to become
precisely what they accuse it of already being _ a global
government. They want it to set more rules _ their rules, which
would impose our labor and environmental standards on everyone
else. I'm for such higher standards, and over time the WTO may be a
vehicle to enforce them, but it's not the main vehicle to achieve
them. And they are not going to be achieved by putting up new trade
walls.
</P>
<P>
   Every country and company that has improved its labor, legal and
environmental standards has done so because of more global trade,
more integration, more Internet _ not less. These are the best
tools we have for improving global governance.
</P>
<P>
   Who is one of the top environmental advisers to DuPont today?
Paul Gilding, the former head of Greenpeace! How could that be? A
DuPont official told me that in the old days, if DuPont wanted to
put a chemical factory in a city, it knew it just had to persuade
the local neighbors. ``Now we have six billion neighbors,'' said
the DuPont official _ meaning that DuPont knows that in a world
without walls if it wants to put up a chemical plant in a country,
every environmentalist is watching. And if that factory makes even
a tiny spill those environmentalists will put it on the World Wide
Web and soil DuPont's name from one end of the earth to the other.
</P>
<P>
   I recently visited a Victoria's Secret garment factory in Sri
Lanka that, in terms of conditions, I would let my own daughters
work in. Why does it have such a high standard? Because
anti-sweatshop activists have started to mobilize enough consumers
to impress Victoria's Secret that if it doesn't get its shop
standards up, consumers won't buy its goods. Sri Lanka is about to
pass new copyright laws, which Sri Lankan software writers have
been seeking for years to protect their own innovations. Why the
new law now? Because Microsoft told Sri Lanka it wouldn't sell its
products in a country with such weak intellectual property laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I want to save Flipper too. It's a question of how. If the
protesters in Seattle stopped yapping, they would realize that they
have been duped by knaves like Pat Buchanan _ duped into thinking
that power lies with the WTO. It doesn't. There's never going to be
a global government to impose the rules the protesters want. But
there can be better global governance _ on the environment,
intellectual property and labor. You achieve that not by adopting
1960s tactics in a Web-based world _ not by blocking trade, choking
globalization or getting the WTO to put up more walls. That's a
fool's errand.
</P>
<P>
   You make a difference today by using globalization _ by
mobilizing the power of trade, the power of the Internet and the
power of consumers to persuade, or embarrass, global corporations
and nations to upgrade their standards. You change the world when
you get the big players to do the right things for the wrong
reasons. But that takes hard work _ coalition-building with
companies and consumers, and follow-up. It's not as much fun as a
circus in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS &LR;      11-30 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMMIANO FIGHTS TO KEEP MINIMUM WAGE MEASURE INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tom Ammiano, president of the San Francisco
Board of Supervisors and candidate for mayor, battled City Hall on
Tuesday to keep intact his legislation to boost the pay for
thousands of low-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Living Wage Task Force, putting the final touches on a set
of recommendations that will be presented to the Board of
Supervisors next month, tentatively calls for altering Ammiano's
legislation in two significant areas: money and scope.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law sponsored by Ammiano would require city
contractors and those who lease city property to pay their workers
at least $11 an hour plus benefits, or $12 an hour without
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The task force wants to lower the proposed minimum pay to $7.50
an hour plus benefits during the first year the law is in effect,
$8.25 an hour plus benefits in the second year, and $9 an hour plus
benefits in year three, said task force chair Jim Illig, an
administrator at Project Open Hand.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage in California is $5.75.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the task force hopes to exempt businesses that
operate on property owned by the Port of San Francisco, such as the
tourist-oriented restaurants in Fisherman's Wharf. It's still
undecided whether the task force will recommend that businesses at
the airport also be exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano bluntly rejected the proposal as not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't accept those recommendations,'' said Ammiano, who is
challenging Mayor Willie Brown in the Dec. 14 mayoral runoff
election.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the proposal can be used as the launching point
for debate during hearings before the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something to work with,'' he said. ``Maybe their strategy
is to go up because it's too low now.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force's tentative decision was based on the hope of
making the law more affordable to businesses that are forced to
comply and to keep them competitive with rivals who are exempt.
</P>
<P>
   A majority on the task force said the lower wages being
recommended would result in more workers ultimately being covered,
assuming that the city ends up subsidizing the increased cost to
contractors and has a finite amount of money to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The living wage debate has been swirling at City Hall for more
than a year, and has emerged as a contentious issue in the campaign
between Ammiano and Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he supports a living wage law, but suggested
Ammiano's plan goes too far. The mayor has said an $11- or
$12-an-hour wage would strain city coffers and place a hardship on
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would prefer that the city force or nudge the raises
when the opportunity arises, as it did when a recent contract was
worked out for about 2,000 workers at the airport who provide
security and clean and fuel the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said a broader approach is needed to help lift a larger
pool of low-wage workers out of poverty and to reduce the financial
strain on the city's programs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   As written, his proposal would be the most far-reaching in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 40 cities and counties have enacted a living wage law,
but they differ from jurisdiction to jurisdiction in terms of how
much workers must be paid, whether benefits must be offered and
what businesses must comply.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland requires wages of $8 an hour, with benefits, and Santa
Clara County $10, plus benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said that given the high cost of living in San
Francisco, $14 an hour would be even more appropriate than the
level he proposed.
</P>
<P>
   He called the $9-an-hour minimum the task force suggested ``a
mockery of living wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Jacobs, who heads the Living Wage Coalition, the
community-based organization pushing hardest for Ammiano's plan,
also voiced disdain over the task force's stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous. You can't live in San Francisco on
$7.50 an hour. It just won't pay the rent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned the credibility of the task force, which is
weighted with employers and has not had a strong voice for low-paid
workers and unions since their representatives resigned.
</P>
<P>
   While the task force has been tinkering with the plan, Brown
last week floated a suggestion that would expand Ammiano's plan by
tying building permits for large job-producing businesses to higher
wages and benefits for their workers. He also suggested that a
softer approach be explored, such as offering businesses tax breaks
if they pay their employees a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he would sign any living wage law the Board of
Supervisors passes, but with a caveat: It must be financially
prudent and practical to implement. Brown has not specified exactly
what that means, but in an appearance Monday with Ammiano he again
said he was certain the board would produce such a responsible
living wage law.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's plan has been embraced by organized labor, generally
scorned by business leaders, and received mixed reviews in the
nonprofit sector, whose employees staff many of the city-funded
health care and social service programs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest questions the Board of Supervisors will
tackle is whether the city will provide extra money to nonprofits
to help cover the mandated raises.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study on Ammiano's proposed law by San Francisco State
University's Urban Institute said the ordinance would cost San
Francisco businesses an estimated $210 million over two years. The
cost passed through to city taxpayers would be an estimated $74
million.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, which was appointed by the Board of Supervisors,
is still studying the proposal. The panel's draft report is due
Monday; a hearing on the recommendations has been scheduled for
Dec. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors is set to receive the task force's
suggestions Dec. 16 - two days after the mayor's election - and
from there, a new set of hearings will be held before the board
makes a final decision. If adopted, the mayor then must decide
whether to sign the legislation or to veto it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
