<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-ART-2TA     11-30 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS GAINS AT BOEING'S EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Germany, Britain, Spain, Wash.)  (ART ADV: A photo and graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ever since he helped revive Frontier Airlines in 1993,
Samuel D. Addoms, its chief executive, has considered himself a
Boeing man.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no easy task when Addoms walked into a conference room
at the carrier's headquarters here in mid-October and told a top
Boeing salesman that Frontier would be swapping its 20-plane fleet
of 737s for jets made by Airbus Industrie, the European consortium
that is Boeing's sole rival.
</P>
<P>
   After training its pilots and mechanics to fly and maintain its
new Airbus planes, it is unlikely that Frontier will buy another
Boeing jet for at least a generation because sticking with one type
of airplane significantly reduces its costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a middle ground,'' Addoms said of the competition
for Frontier's business. ``You either win or you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, a proud company that has dominated commercial aviation
since the 1950s, is losing often these days. So far this year,
Airbus has outsold Boeing by more than two to one, the largest gap
since Airbus was founded in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided orders have prompted many in the aviation industry
and on Wall Street to consider what would have been unthinkable a
decade ago: that Boeing is in danger of slipping behind Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Long the scrappy challenger, Airbus is now widely seen as more
innovative and savvier at sales than is stodgy Boeing. Many
once-loyal Boeing customers, like Frontier, now find Airbus planes
to be technologically superior and more comfortable for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were running Boeing , I would be pretty concerned,'' said
Robert J. Genise, chief executive of Boullion Aviation Services,
which leases both Boeing and Airbus jets to airlines. ``These are
decisions that are not readily reversible.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's long-term health has consequences that echo far beyond
its headquarters in Seattle. It is the nation's largest exporter,
with nearly $27 billion in overseas sales last year. Since World
War II, leaders in Washington and Europe have viewed civil
aerospace as a strategic industry that provides thousands of
high-paying jobs and helps amortize the high costs of military
research.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened Boeing would likely revive trade tensions between the
European Union and Washington, which has repeatedly accused France,
Germany and Britain of unfairly subsidizing Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its recent setbacks, Boeing still has some distinct
strengths. After swallowing its longtime rival, McDonnell Douglas,
in 1997, it is by far the world's largest aerospace company with
$56 billion in sales last year. Boeing now makes fighter jets,
launches satellites and is NASA's largest contractor. This year it
will deliver a record 620 passenger jets, more than twice as many
as Airbus does.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fatal crash of a Boeing 767 flown by Egyptair and
the Federal Aviation Administration's announcement this week that
it will inspect quality controls at Boeing's factories after
several recent lapses, the world's airlines still consider Boeing
jets to be safe and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't spend time worrying about orders,'' Philip M. Condit,
Boeing's chairman and chief executive, said in October. ``What
really matters is what comes out the factory door.''
</P>
<P>
   Because there is a gap of several years between when a plane is
ordered and when it is delivered and because many airlines are
consolidating their fleets around a few types of jets to cut costs,
Airbus' gains over Boeing today mean that Boeing's future
deliveries will shrink while Airbus' will grow. By the end of the
next decade, Airbus could be producing more jets than Boeing,
reversing a dominance dating to the mid-1950s, when Boeing
introduced the 707, the first commercially successful passenger
jet.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Boeing is no longer the daring industry leader that
nearly bankrupted itself 30 years ago building the 747 jumbo jet.
That airplane captured the imagination of millions and quickly
became an emblem of the 20th century. It is still the world's
largest civilian aircraft, occupying the last _ and most lucrative
_ niche in Boeing's product line that Airbus has yet to crack.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy that Airbus is now proposing to build the A3XX, an
airborne cruise ship that would carry 550 passengers (compared with
420 on the biggest 747) and offer sleeping cabins and workout
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing says there is not enough demand from the world's airlines
to justify the cost of building a new superjumbo jet. Its
alternative is to develop a larger version of the 747. Airbus is
pressing ahead with the A3XX even though many analysts say that
plane will end up costing 50 percent more than Airbus' estimate of
$10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can make the A3XX go,'' said Richard Aboulafia, an
aviation consultant with the Teal Group in Alexandria, Va., ``then
they will really transform themselves into the market leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's current timidity is the result of a disastrous attempt
in the mid-1990s to deal a death blow to Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to gain a lock on the narrow-body market, Boeing sold the
new version of its 737 to several large American carriers at steep
discounts. But making a profit on the deals was contingent on
Boeing's slashing production costs. Instead, the rush of new orders
clogged Boeing's production line, causing its costs to soar. The
crisis came to a head in late 1997, when the company was forced to
halt production of the 737 and 747 to sort out the mess.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze forced Boeing to delay deliveries, angering many
airlines. It also cost the company billions of dollars, forcing it
to post its first annual loss in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Boeing executives say that Airbus is cutting prices
to gain market share. The day before the Frontier deal was
announced, Condit said the company had bowed out of the competition
because it could not make a profit on the deal. But Addoms and
other Frontier executives said that Boeing was fighting to the end.
They and other airline executives said that Airbus was aggressive
but that their decision to buy the European airplanes never came
down to price.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we bought the product because we
thought it was better.'' said David Neeleman, the chief executive
of Jetblue Airways, a new carrier based at Kennedy Airport in New
York. It will fly only Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, politics appears to play a strong role. In the
face of heavy lobbying by both European and American officials, El
Al, Israel's national airline, which currently flies only Boeing
jets, is considering a Solomonic solution: splitting an order for
wide-body jets between the two manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   That Airbus is even in a position to challenge Boeing for
leadership in civil aerospace is one of the great Cinderella
stories of global commerce. Founded as a French-German joint
venture in 1970 that soon added the British and the Spanish, Airbus
was a quixotic attempt to compete with the American aerospace
industry, which had been dominated since World War II by Boeing,
McDonnell Douglas and Lockheed.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next two decades, both Lockheed and McDonnell
Douglas faded after each gambled millions on expensive jetliners
that failed to catch on. Meanwhile, Airbus, nurtured with cheap
credit and political lobbying, developed some winning designs.
</P>
<P>
   It has also proved to be a skilled marketer. For years, Airbus
failed to crack British Airways, which stubbornly retained an
all-Boeing fleet. The airline finally ordered its first A320s last
year, after Airbus rented a 737, placed it nose to nose on the
tarmac with an A320 and invited British Airways executives to
compare the two.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry executives, including Airbus' top managers,
believe that the consortium's biggest weakness is its awkward
ownership structure, which forces Airbus to make some decisions
based on the needs of individual owners rather than to maximize
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the consortium took a big step toward its
goal of consolidating under a single corporate owner when
DaimlerChrysler, which owns 37.9 percent, agreed to buy
Construcciones Aeronauticas of Spain, a 4.2 percent holder. Then in
October, DaimlerChrysler announced that it was merging its
aerospace subsidiary with Aerospatiale Matra of France, which also
owns 37.9 percent of Airbus. When the deal is completed, British
Aerospace will be the only outside Airbus shareholder, with 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its current setup, many analysts believe that Airbus is
a more efficient manufacturer than Boeing. The consortium denies
that it sells planes below cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Condit said that he can't sustain deals at these levels
and make a profit, it is music to my ears,'' said Henri Courpron,
Airbus' chief salesman in North America. ``Because I can assure you
that I can do deals like Frontier every day and still make money.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Boeing may have made a mistake in 1993, when it
decided to remodel the narrow-body 737 that was first introduced in
the 1960s, rather than invest in an entirely new plane. The new
737s fly higher, faster and farther than did the earlier versions
and their cockpits were updated with modern computer displays and
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing retained the same size fuselage, while the A320 is
seven inches wider. The difference has come to haunt executives in
Seattle because many airlines are feeling the sting from passengers
who complain that they are being jammed into narrow seats in rows
placed more closely together.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a pure marketing perspective, there is a value there,''
said Jeff S. Potter, a Frontier vice president and a former
salesman for McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovative design that is proving decisive was Airbus'
early decision to develop a family of aircraft that share the same
cockpit design so that pilots can easily shift from one model to
the next, reducing training costs. Boeing, on the other hand, has
several different families of aircraft that have different cockpit
styles.
</P>
<P>
   The family concept made it much easier for Airbus to win
additional orders from airlines to which it had managed to make one
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus was able to achieve such commonality because it pioneered
the use of electronics to control the movement of rudders and wing
flaps rather than mechanical wires and pulleys. With the help of
computers, the controls of a wide-body jet carrying 380 passengers
can be made to feel and perform the same as a single-aisle jet
carrying 120.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Boeing executives played down the advantages of
so-called fly-by-wire technology. But in the late 1980s, the
company decided to design its newest jet _ the 777 _ as a
fly-by-wire airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The 777, a twin-engine, wide-body plane carrying up to 380
passengers, is now Boeing's flagship. Airlines like its low
operating cost and passengers generally find it comfortable. Steve
Binder, an aerospace analyst at Bear, Stearns in New York, said
that in order to combat Airbus, Boeing may have to design a new jet
to replace the 737 that is more compatible with the 777.
</P>
<P>
   But others believe that Boeing's bigger challenge is to change
its insular corporate culture, learn to build its planes more
cheaply and to capitalize on its natural advantage with airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at his desk, Potter of Frontier drew a large oval on a
blank sheet of paper. ``If this is a race track,'' he explained,
describing the recent sales campaign, ``Boeing was halfway around
before Airbus even got to the starting gate. But by the end, the
two were nose to nose and Airbus won.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
