<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITOR RAISES VALUE OF WARNER-LAMBERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Home Products Corp. said Tuesday that it would work to
give Warner-Lambert Co.'s shareholders ``additional value'' under
their merger agreement to reflect possible increased revenue from
the cholesterol-reducing drug Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert had marketed Lipitor with Pfizer Inc., but it
sued on Monday to end the two companies' arrangement. The suit was
the latest in a series of maneuvers by the three companies to gain
an upper hand in a merger battle that may drag on into next year.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products and Warner-Lambert announced a
$70-billion merger deal Nov. 4, but Pfizer made an $82.4-billion
hostile bid for Warner-Lambert that afternoon. Since then,
Warner-Lambert and Pfizer have accused each other of breaching the
agreement to sell Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the merger scuffle, which is now before the Delaware
Chancery Court, American Home Products has remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the statement as code for American Home Products to
increase the value of its bid,'' Steven Gerber, a managing director
at CIBC World Markets, said of Tuesday's development.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of all three companies fell Tuesday. Warner-Lambert's
stock dropped $1.375, or 1.5 percent, to $90. Shares of American
Home Products fell 50 cents, to $52, and Pfizer dropped $1.25, or
3.3 percent, to $36.1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
