<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-EXXON-MOBIL-BOS &LR;      11-30 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON-MOBIL OK HINGES ON EXTENSIVE DIVESTITURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal antitrust regulators approved Tuesday the $87 billion
merger of Exxon and Mobil, reuniting two key units of the former
Standard Oil trust broken up by the government 88 years ago. But to
prevent a new monopoly, they required the petroleum giants shed
extensive investments.
</P>
<P>
   By a 4-0 vote, the Federal Trade Commission approved a
settlement, to become final in January, under which Exxon and Mobil
would sell or exchange more than 2,400 of their nearly 16,000 gas
stations, including every Exxon-owned or -supplied gas station in
New England, New York, and California, and all Mobil stations in
the New Jersey-Virginia corridor and in parts of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever buys the stations could continue to use the Mobil and
Exxon names, branded fuels, and services such as their credit cards
and the Mobil Speedpass payment system for at least 10 years,
allowing them to profit from the marketing might of the famed brand
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement should preserve competition and protect
consumers from inappropriate and anticompetitive price increases,''
commission chairman Robert Pitofsky said, noting that every 1
percent by which the companies could raise the price of gas would
cost consumers $240 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon chairman Lee Raymond said the deal clears the way for
creation of ``the world's premier petroleum and petrochemical
company'' and that annual operating savings will probably exceed
the $2.8 billion identified last year. Officials predicted the
companies will consummate their merger into a new Exxon Mobil Corp.
as soon as Wednesday. Its shares will trade under the ticker symbol
XOM.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts said the FTC move actually helps the
company, by allowing it to shed low-margin retailing and refining
operations while creating a richer, stronger competitor for oil
exploration, the most lucrative sector of the business.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC action, the largest retail divestiture ever required,
came nearly a year after the former Standard Oil of New York
(Mobil) and Standard Oil of New Jersey (Exxon) announced plans to
combine, and just months after it agreed to let two other former
Standard Oil units created by the 1911 breakup of John D.
Rockefeller's empire _ Amoco and Sohio _ recombine with British
Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   The companies may face some legal problems with station lessors
who want the first right at buying the stations they operate. But
the FTC wants no more than one or two companies to buy the
Northeastern markets being shed, in order to ensure a strong
competitor for the remaining Mobil stations, including 485 in
Massachusetts, where Mobil leads the market with a 24 percent share
of all gas pumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gaining confidence that litigation will not be
necessary,'' said Jim Daskal, counsel to the National Coalition of
Petroleum Retailers, which lobbied the FTC during its nearly
yearlong review of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   While the move will create a roster of Exxon-branded stations
that have no direct connection to Exxon Mobil, part of the deal
requires that Exxon stations continue to sell Exxon-produced
gasoline with the company's unique additives.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Stephen Dodge, associate director of the
Massachusetts Petroleum Council, said, ``The effect on the consumer
will be nothing. For at least 10 years, the average driver won't
see any change at all. If they didn't read about it in the paper,
they would never even know it was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general from 13 states signed off on the deal as well.
Bay State attorney general Thomas F. Reilly said, ``I am extremely
pleased with this settlement. We are confident it will preserve the
competition that should always exist in the Massachusetts
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil will also reimburse the states for $1.55 million
in legal fees and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Exxon fell slightly Tuesday, down 1/16 to 79-5/16 in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Mobil shares inched upward,
gaining 13/16 to close at 104-5/16. Investors apparently concluded
the divestitures are largely helpful. ``If you look at where they
have to sell assets, US refining and marketing is their
lowest-return business,'' said Mark Hastings, an energy analyst at
Citibank Global Asset Management in Stamford, Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil must complete its divestitures within nine months,
and if it fails to do so, the commission can appoint a trustee with
power to sell off an ever larger group of assets. It has 12 months
to sell a California refinery that produces the special blend of
gas required in that state and to divest its Exxon stations there.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil shareholders approved the merger in late May.
With a combined market capitalization of more than $275 billion,
Exxon Mobil would be one of the world's five largest companies,
with annual sales of more than $167 billion and profits of more
than $8 billion, according to FTC figures. Company officials expect
to cut 10,000 to 12,000 jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
