<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GULF-WAR-SYNDROME-NYT     11-30 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-WAR-SYNDROME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS SOME GULF WAR VETERANS WITH SIGNS OF BRAIN DAMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some veterans of the Persian Gulf war who have
complained of chronic illnesses have signs of brain damage caused
by exposure to toxic chemicals, the authors of a scientific study
partly financed by the Pentagon reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic scans of sick veterans found lower-than-normal levels
of a certain chemical, indicating damage in the parts of the brain
that control reflexes, movement, memory and emotion, the study's
authors said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 American service members sent to the Persian
Gulf in 1990 and 1991 have since reported experiencing a raft of
maladies, including fatigue, muscle pain, memory loss and sleep
disorders, which have collectively come to be known as gulf war
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers stopped short of identifying the exact cause of
the brain damage, saying that more medical research was needed. But
coupled with a survey last month sponsored by the Pentagon, the
findings showed that scientists were narrowing in on chemical
exposure _ from pesticides, low levels of nerve gas or an
experimental drug given to troops _ as the cause of the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by researchers at the University of
Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas and presented on
Tuesday at the annual convention of the Radiological Society of
North America in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig R. Quigley, declined to
discuss the findings in detail, saying they were preliminary and
had not yet been subjected to peer review in an academic journal,
which the authors said they expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many steps to go here,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   The study's principal author, James L. Fleckenstein, a professor
of radiology, said in an interview that the study was the first to
show brain damage in sick veterans.
</P>
<P>
   He and his colleagues examined 22 veterans complaining of
illnesses using magnetic resonance spectroscopy, which measures
chemical levels in the brain, and compared the results with those
from 18 healthy veterans. The experiment was repeated in a sample
of six more veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The scans found that sick veterans had 10 to 25 percent lower
levels of N-acetyl-aspartate, signaling a loss of neurons in the
brain stem and basal ganglia. Veterans with more severe symptoms
showed the lowest levels of the chemical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MET-SCROLL-PAINTING-2     11-30 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-SCROLL-PAINTING-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TRIAL AT THE MET: THE ART OF THE CONNOISSEUR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Fake'' is an unkind word to say to museum curators.
But the Meropolitan Museum has heard it many times in the past two
years, after one of its most highly touted recent acquisitions, the
Chinese scroll painting titled ``Riverbank,'' attributed to the
10th-century artist Dong Yuan, was accused of being a 20th-century
forgery.
</P>
<P>
   The word is likely to crackle in the air like static at the Met
next Saturday, when the painting _ a towering depiction of a
mountainous landscape being swept by a storm _ gets its day in
court at an international symposium titled ``Issues of Authenticity
in Chinese Painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading a stellar prosecution will be the art historian James
Cahill, who contends that ``Riverbank'' dates from the 1950s and is
the work of the Chinese artist, collector and forger extraordinaire
Zhang Daqian (1899-1983), a prolific multitasker who has been
called the Chinese Picasso. Seconding Cahill will be Sherman Lee,
former director of the Cleveland Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Among those appearing for the defense will be two curators in
the Met's Asian art department, Wen C. Fong and Maxwell K. Hearn,
presenting arguments in support of an early date and authorship.
Some of their findings are spelled out in the current Met
exhibition titled ``The Artist as Collector: Masterpieces from the
C.C. Wang Family Collection,'' where ``Riverbank'' is on display
through Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in a debate like this are not small. If ``Riverbank''
were proved beyond reasonable doubt to be what the Met believes it
to be, the museum would own one of the most important Chinese
paintings in any collection, by one of the progenitors of the
classical landscape tradition. And art history would have to expand
to accommodate it.
</P>
<P>
   But if the painting were to be confirmed as a fraud, many things
would be diminished. The Met's bank account, of course. (The
painting was bought at an undisclosed sum from the artist-collector
C.C. Wang and must have cost a bundle.) But also scholarly
reputations, and, in subtle ways, the public's faith in the
credibility of that quasi-mystical selective device known as the
connoisseur's eye.
</P>
<P>
   It is such an eye _ or group of eyes _ that brings a painting
like ``Riverbank'' to a major museum in the first place. And what
may really go on trial next Saturday isn't a painting but
connoisseurship itself, and the seal of authenticity that it
represents.
</P>
<P>
   What is connoisseurship? Basically, the assessment of the
identity and relative value of a work of art through analysis of
external evidence: in the case of Chinese painting, physical
materials (ink, paint, silk or paper), style (composition and
brushwork), documents (seals, inscriptions, records), and
comparable or related works.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the connoisseurs of Chinese art? In the West, they are
usually art historians, dealers or collectors. In China,
traditionally they have been artists.
</P>
<P>
   Through a lifelong practice of painting, the theory goes, they
develop an intimate, second-nature knowledge of the subtleties of
style and a nose for discerning the authentic from the bogus that
historical knowledge alone cannot match. Zhang Daqian was part of
this artist-connoisseur tradition. So is Wang, who bought
``Riverbank'' from Zhang in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   But authenticity means different things in different cultures.
In Western art, the original _ the unique object, the genius
creator _ is everything. And a conceptual, even legal understanding
of the distinctions between the original and a copy, and a copy and
a forgery, is clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   In Chinese painting, by contrast, tradition predominates over
individuality (though that is also prized). And the concept of
authenticity, of what constitutes the genuine article, is more
nuanced.
</P>
<P>
   As a medium, ink-and-brush painting on silk or paper is
evanescent, and relatively few early examples survive. As a result,
Chinese artists, in what amounts to a kind of centuries-long
collective archiving process, have copied and recopied revered
works, and many of these copies have come to be regarded as
masterpieces in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Copying takes various forms. The painstaking duplicate is often
executed as an academic exercise, a way of absorbing a famous
master's technique and, through it, a trace of his spirit. A copy
can also be an imitation or emulation, a loose, freehand play on an
existing model.
</P>
<P>
   Or it can be a painting of entirely new themes using the
essential elements of a master's signature style. Just as copying
has degrees of shading, the distinction between a copy and forgery
can be fuzzy, often defined (as in the West) purely by intention.
An exacting copy may be done for many reasons, self-discipline
among them.
</P>
<P>
   But if a painting is executed on artificially aged silk, or
supplied with a spurious signature or a fanciful provenance,
chances are strong that it is trying to pass itself off as
something it is not.
</P>
<P>
   The question of authenticity doesn't end there, though. Just as
any genuine painting can be a bad painting, so any forged painting
can be good, even a great one.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Riverbank,'' for example, turned out to be by Zhang Daqian,
then it would be a (italics)genuine(end italics) Zhang Daqian, with
a value of its own. ( Cahill, in fact, claims that the painting is
``the masterwork among his forgeries, and stands very high in his
oeuvre as a whole.'') The very ability to fool the practiced eye
can be a proof of aesthetic success.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such successes, which have long caused dread in the museum
world, abound in Chinese painting. (Zhang is said to have produced
30,000 works in his long life, an unknown percentage of them
fraudulent.) And they make the task of authentification through
connoisseurship difficult indeed.
</P>
<P>
   And how does the enigmatic ``Riverbank,'' which was dubbed by
its former owner, Wang, as ``the Mona Lisa of Chinese painting,''
fit into all of this? That's the question that the Met symposium
(which is open to the public free of charge with museum admission)
will attempt to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill, who has for decades crusaded as a kind of Zhang Daqian
vigilante, blowing the whistle on numerous paintings in collections
worldwide, has no doubts that the painting is a forgery and that
Zhang Daqiang is its author. He suggested as much publicly as early
as 1980, and reiterated his opinion in no uncertain terms after the
Met put the work on view.
</P>
<P>
   At the symposium, he will bring what he calls ``an indictment in
14 counts'' against the painting, based on two basic tools in the
connoisseurial arsenal. Using stylistic analysis, he finds what he
considers to be technical tics and flaws that both preclude a
10th-century date and correspond to characteristics of Zhang's
work.
</P>
<P>
   And he navigates an elaborate, whodunit-style paper trail of
falsified documents and missing references to demonstrate that the
painting probably didn't exist before the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Hearn on the Met team will offer a detailed physical analysis of
the painting to establish its antiquity. And Fong, referring to
Cahill's brief, will point out the folly of bringing Procrustean
20th-century Western stylistic criteria to bear on ``Riverbank,'' a
work that he says can be understood only in terms of a specific
period style, the period being the 10th century.
</P>
<P>
   The case itself is fraught with logistical problems and
contradictions. A carbon dating of the painting's silk cannot be
carried out (the Met says) without major damage to the painting
itself. And subjective interpretation of data simply comes with the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   For purposes of comparative analysis, the Met has hung an
acknowledged Zhang Daqian forgery of a 10th-century painting beside
``Riverbank.'' But where the museum finds telling differences
between the two paintings, Cahill finds similarities.
</P>
<P>
   Trials of this kind often end without a clear verdict, and it
looks like this one will, too (though the summary opinions of the
two scholar-referees for the occasion, Robert E. Harrist Jr. and
Jerome Silbergeld, remain a closely guarded secret). After all the
positions have been presented, ``Riverbank'' will still be a
10th-century work by Dong Yuan, or a 10th-century work but not by
Dong Yuan, or a Zhang Daqian forgery, or something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   In short, connoisseurship is an imprecise science, and one that
has acquired an iffy name in certain academic circles in recent
years. An art history concerned with political ideas rather than
iconic objects tends to view it as the preserve of a clubby,
priestly cult professing magical, almost extrasensory powers.The
very concept of authenticity as a measure of value is seen as a
tool for shoring up a market and an elitist masterpiece canon.
</P>
<P>
   But just as we rely on skilled diagnosticians in medicine, who
operate on an undefinable combination of education, experience and
instinct, so we do in art. It is, after all, impossible to write an
accurate history, political, social or otherwise, based on faulty
evidence, and connoisseurship is one way, in many cases the only
way to ensure that the correct data are in place.
</P>
<P>
   And in some ways the sheer hunger for the unique object has
never been more intense. It may be no coincidence that as digital
technology conjures a world of endlessly reproducible,
transmittable images, the museum is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds contemplating a Rembrandt or Van Gogh or a painting
attributed to Dong Yuan may not know what they're looking at,
historically speaking, but they are clearly after some primal
experience of the Real Thing.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, authenticity remains a burning issue, and a
painting like ``Riverbank,'' whatever its identity, becomes a
peculiarly troubling, tantalizing object. It really is a kind of
Mona Lisa, as Wang suggests, and whether it is smiling at our
recognition of its unique spirit or at our incredulity remains to
be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
