<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SMUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES APPEAR SPLIT IN PLAYBOY TV CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for the Clinton administration and the
Playboy channel squared off before the Supreme Court on Tuesday
over whether the U.S. government can order cable television
operators to fully block sexually explicit channels from reaching
nonsubscribers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   The high court appeared to be as split as the attorneys during
the hourlong argument.
</P>
<P>
   Some justices showed support for the government's position that
the controversial demand on cable companies prevents curious,
impressionable children from glimpsing lewd television images that
remain visible even when the scenes are scrambled for
nonsubscribers. Justice Antonin Scalia, for example, said the
graphic images could be barred as ``obscene.''
</P>
<P>
   Other justices appeared to side with Playboy Entertainment Group
Inc. The media conglomerate, which provides sexually explicit
programming, said the federal law calling for the cable restriction
violates the company's First Amendment right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision in the case,
United States vs. Playboy Entertainment Group Inc., by July.
</P>
<P>
   In other Supreme Court action Tuesday, Justice John Paul Stevens
barred Illinois and Wisconsin from enforcing laws prohibiting
late-term, ``partial-birth'' abortions, at least for now. Stevens
granted a request from abortion providers that he temporarily block
enforcement of the states' laws until the Supreme Court has a
chance to review whether the statutes are constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Playboy case addressed the constitutionality of a provision
of the 1996 Telecommunications Act that addresses cable-television
operators who provide ``sexually explicit adult programming.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which the Clinton administration is defending, requires
these operators to ``fully scramble or otherwise fully block the
video and audio portion of such (programming) so that one not a
subscriber ... does not receive it.'' Operators who refuse to
scramble the programs can air them only between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m.
when children are unlikely to view them.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. District Court for Delaware
agreed with Playboy's challenge to the law, ruling last December
that the federal government went too far in its effort to protect
children from being exposed to lewd television scenes. The law, by
requiring that images be blacked out to all nonsubscribers, targets
not only children but adults, who are free to view sexually
explicit material so long as it is not obscene, the district court
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications law allows losing parties, in this case
the federal government, to appeal a district court decision
directly to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Solicitor General James Feldman, pressing the
Clinton administration's appeal, urged the high court to reinstate
the law as a constitutionally permissible way to protect children.
He said the government has a ``compelling interest'' in protecting
impressionable young minds from glimpsing pornography and that the
justices should defer to Congress' limited restriction on the
freedom of cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman said lawmakers made a ``reasonable accommodation'' to
Playboy's First Amendment concerns by allowing the station to air
scrambled images of its shows to nonsubscribers during the late
night and early morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, while sympathetic to the government's argument, said
Congress might not have gone far enough to protect children.
</P>
<P>
   The justice said he assigned law clerks to watch tapes of the
scrambled images, known as ``signal bleed,'' and report back to him
in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even read the descriptions in public,'' Scalia
said. ``It seems to me obscenity.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, by contrast, expressed concern that
the federal government was acting as a ``super parent'' by
requiring sexually oriented cable stations to totally block their
signals.
</P>
<P>
   But Feldman responded that parents are not always available or
aware of the images being broadcast and, hence, cannot always
protect their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parental consent cannot be ensured simply because of a
parent's failure to act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy's lawyer, Robert Corn-Revere, assailed the cable
restriction as ``regulatory overkill.'' He called the law ``a
blanket, across the board'' First Amendment restriction that makes
no distinction between hard-core pornography and explicit safe-sex
public-service announcements.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Anthony M. Kennedy and Stephen G. Breyer said the
law helps working parents, who are often not at home, to protect
their children from sexually explicit images.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Corn-Revere of Washington said the cable
restriction, if upheld, might lead to other federal intrusions on
the freedom of adults to decide what they want to see on emerging
technologies, such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens appeared to bemoan the declining standards of decency
not just on cable but on broadcast television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You (hear) a lot of strong language on WGN,'' Stevens said,
referring to a popular Chicago television station that is available
on cable. ``You can hear the language ... on television any night
of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the Illinois and Wisconsin partial-birth abortion
restrictions, the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals voted 5-4 last
month to uphold the state laws as constitutional restrictions on
the freedom of women to terminate their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, by granting the stay, allowed partial-birth abortions
to continue to be performed in the two states. The stay will remain
in effect unless and until the Supreme Court either refuses to hear
an appeal of the 7th Circuit decision or votes to uphold that
ruling, said Stevens, the justice assigned to oversee that circuit,
which covers Wisconsin, Illinois and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Under the procedure, a fetus is partially delivered through the
birth canal. An incision is made in the base of the skull and its
contents are drained.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin law calls for a life sentence for anyone
performing the controversial procedure except to save the woman's
life. The Illinois law makes performing a partial-birth abortion a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck down
as unconstitutional similar partial-birth abortion restrictions in
Nebraska, Arkansas and Iowa. The dispute between the 7th and 8th
circuits increases the likelihood that the court will consider the
issue and decide whether the restrictions are constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
