<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA, RAMS LIVING LARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's football saturated edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should all get comfortable with the idea of Georgia
Frontiere walking the sidelines during the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks after most analysts threw up their hands trying to
predict what NFL teams were playoff-bound, the picture has cleared
considerably and you can now separate the contenders and the
dreamers.
</P>
<P>
   And our beloved Los Angeles Rams are living large. It would take
the flameout of the millooneynium to keep the Rams from the
playoffs and a Super Bowl berth, a tumble along the lines of the
Phillies' 1964 pratfall.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-2 Rams have games left with five non-factors at this stage
of the season, Carolina, New Orleans, New York Giants, Chicago and
Philadelphia. They can clinch the NFC West with a win Sunday, and
with no other NFC team better than 7-4, the Rams should clinch a
first round playoff bye and home field throughout the playoffs
before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   That's a massive advantage for a team has great team speed and
plays on a rug. Plus, all the other NFC contenders have at least
one notable flaw in their game. It would take a major change in the
profile of Dallas (age), Minnesota (horrible pass defense) and
Tampa Bay (a weak offense) to see them beating the Rams. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the NFC playoff hunt:
</P>
<P>
   NFC West:
</P>
<P>
   Rams clinch with a win at Carolina Sunday. Everyone else is
playing for draft position.
</P>
<P>
   NFC East:
</P>
<P>
   Washington may lead at 7-4, but the Redskins have games left at
Detroit, at Indianapolis and home with Miami. Dallas is 6-5, and if
they can past slumping New England this week, they have the Eagles,
Jets, Saints and Giants left, and three of them at home. They also
hold the tiebreaker against the Redskins. Arizona and New York
(both 5-6) are tricking their fans by saying they still are alive.
</P>
<P>
   NFC Central:
</P>
<P>
   Four playoff teams could emerge from here. Detroit, Minnesota
and Tampa (all 7-4) need only go 3-2 to finish 10-6, and 6-5 Green
Bay has games with Chicago, Carolina and Arizona left. Tampa gets
the Vikes, Lions and Pack at home, and Detroit must also visit
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   But all four teams have questions. Detroit needs a healthy
Charlie Batch, Minnesota has the NFL worst pass defense, Trent
Dilfer's injury forces Tampa to use rookie Shaun King, and the
Packers are erratic.
</P>
<P>
   Projection: St. Louis (West) and Dallas (East) get byes. Detroit
wins tiebreaker for Central. First round: Green Bay at Detroit,
Minnesota at Tampa. ...
</P>
<P>
   The AFC is clearly the better conference this season. Six teams
already have eight wins or more in hand, and the conference holds a
28-18 edge on the NFC in head-to-head play. Seven of the NFC's 18
wins can be traced to California (San Diego) and Ohio (Cleveland,
Cincinnati), too.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few NFC teams are having any rushing success, compared to
the AFC, where seven teams are averaging 114 rushing yards or more
per game. The AFC has better run defenses, too. It would be a
surprise if any of those six teams were to fall out of the
playoffs. But Miami and Seattle are still having problems running
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   AFC Central:
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (10-1) and Tennessee (9-2) meet the day after
Christmas to decide the division title. There isn't a single
winning team left on either team's schedule. The wild card team
here could have a better record than the other two division champs.
</P>
<P>
   AFC West:
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (6-5) can't lose another game, because 10-6 may not
be good enough for a wild card berth and Seattle (8-3) has games
left with the Raiders, Chargers, Broncos and Jets.
</P>
<P>
   AFC East:
</P>
<P>
   The Colts (9-2) still have road games at Miami and Buffalo, but
also a freebie at Cleveland. Buffalo's (8-4) next three games are
against the Giants, Cards and sinking Pats. Miami gets three of its
last five at home, but has both games left against the Jets, who
would love to play spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   Projection: Jacksonville (Central) and Buffalo (East) get first
round byes. Seattle wins the West. First round games send Miami at
Seattle and Indianapolis at Tennessee in perhaps the toughest first
round game ever. ...
</P>
<P>
   The rate of close games has slowed some the last two weeks,
especially last weekend, when there were a lot of heavy favorites
and eight games were decided by eight points or more.
</P>
<P>
   In 173 games this season, 85 of them have been decided by a
touchdown or less, or 49 percent. And 51 of those 85 were decided
by a field goal or less, or almost 30 percent of all games. ...
</P>
<P>
   Some stats to noodle with while waiting for the stretch run:
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is offensive, and in a bad way. Only 13 teams are
averaging two or more offensive touchdowns a game. But the flip
side is the rampant rate of touchdowns being scored by defenses.
There are 12 teams with three or more defensive scores, including
Kansas City (6), Dallas (5), San Francisco (5), and Washington, St.
Louis, Jacksonville (all 4), and only four defenses haven't scored,
Atlanta, Carolina, Cleveland and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (7-0), Jacksonville (7-0) and St. Louis (9-0) are
all unbeaten in games decided by a touchdown or more. Conversely,
Atlanta (0-6), Cincinnati (0-8), Cleveland (0-8), New York Giants
(1-4), and San Francisco (1-7) have two wins between in games
decided by seven or more points. San Diego is 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (11), Oakland (10), Minnesota (8), New England (8),
Baltimore (8) and Philadelphia (8) have played the most close games
this season (seven points or less).
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the ability to win close games is an indicator,
then you'll back the playoff fortunes of Miami (5-1 in close games)
and Tennessee (6-1), and peel off Dallas (1-3) and St. Louis (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   Live dogs for those who back their predictions with their
wallet: Chicago (9-1), Detroit (6-2), Baltimore (5-2), Indianapolis
(6-0) and Oakland (4-2). But Indy's dog days are likely over, and
the Raiders, after Sunday's crushing loss to K.C., are the team
most likely to e-mail the rest of their season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
