<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MALAYSIA-ELECT-NYT &LR;      11-30 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORING SCANDAL AND ECONOMICS, MALAYSIANS RETAIN MAHATHIR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Like other nations, Malaysia has a
national anthem. But it also has a theme song, played repeatedly in
the recent election campaign, Frank Sinatra's ``My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant, cranky, put-up-your dukes prime minister, Dr.
Mahathir Mohamad, prides himself on defying just about everybody
and in creating a rather eccentric but mostly successful
modernizing nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have achieved whatever we have achieved according to the
Sinatra principle,'' he said shortly before winning a new five-year
term in a parliamentary election on Monday. ``We have done it our
own way.''
</P>
<P>
   What Malaysians did was to reject, for the most part, the type
of change that has toppled leaders around Asia since the economic
crisis hit the region more than two years ago. They returned
Mahathir to office after 18 years in power with a huge
parliamentary majority at a time when Indonesia, South Korea and
Thailand have responded to the economic crisis with political
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir achieved his victory despite economic hardship and a
political scandal that damaged his crucial arguments of having
brought stability and well-being to this ethnically divided nation.
Analysts said part of the reason was the character of the
electorate, carefully balanced among a Malay majority and Chinese
and Indian minorities. It fears instability and has been horrified
by the upheavals that have gripped nearby Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the opposition did not offer a credible alternative
to the experienced, highly organized governing coalition, which is
anchored by Mahathir's party, Umno. A reformist movement that was
spawned by the ouster and trial of Mahathir's deputy, Anwar
Ibrahim, raised issues of democracy and openness but was rejected
by voters, winning 5 seats in the 193-seat Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But the election did shift the political ground in ways that
will be played out in the coming years. It gave a significant push
to the Islamic party, Pas, which increased its Parliament seats, to
27 from 8, and swept two state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The voting took 8 of the 15 seats in the prime minister's home
state, Kedah, where his own popular vote fell, by preliminary
estimates, to 10,000 votes from 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   The political struggle is quite likely to refocus from the
complaints of the democratic reformists to a struggle between
secular and Islamic political leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In a predawn victory statement Tuesday, Mahathir offered a hand
of cooperation to the Islamic party, saying: ``We would be very
glad to work with the opposition party outside of politics. Of
course, politically we will disagree with them. But there are other
areas where we can agree with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic party leader, Fadzil Noor, took a combative tone
Tuesday, declaring that as long as the governing coalition
``continues with its wrongdoings and does not repent, this wind of
change will blow to other states as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The weakening of Mahathir's grip on the states where Pas is
strong, the ethnic Malay heartland in the north, also potentially
weakens his control of his party. In another setback, both real and
symbolic, four Umno cabinet ministers lost their parliamentary
seats.
</P>
<P>
   It is often said that the real election in Malaysia is not the
parliamentary vote, which Umno has won in every election since the
founding of Malaysia in 1957, but the party's leadership vote. That
is due next year, and the setbacks in the fine print of the big
victory on Monday could fuel a challenge to Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed out that the three senior party members who
could potentially raise a challenge also met with setbacks and
might not be operating from positions of strength. Once again,
Mahathir may have found his own way to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest loser on Monday was the man who many thought
would by now be stepping in as prime minister, Anwar. For years, he
was Mahathir's anointed successor, until a falling out last year
that led to his dismissal and trial on charges of corruption and
sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting crisis ignited the reform movement, which for the
first time produced an opposition alliance for an election. But it
was the Islamic party, and not Anwar's democrats, who were the main
beneficiaries of that alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah, was one of the five reform candidates
to win a seat in Parliament. Anwar's sodomy trial, adjourned to
keep him out of the public eye during the campaign, can resume. But
it will have lost much of its larger political significance, in
view of the voters' rejection of his supporters and of their reform
movement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
