<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-LEAVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IMPLEMENTS IMPROVED FAMILY LEAVE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration unveiled Tuesday an experimental
program that will allow states to expand unemployment insurance
benefits to include new parents on leave, a plan hailed by
workplace advocates as a boon to poor working parents and opposed
by critics who fear the plan would deplete individual states'
jobless funds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new parental regulations proposed by the President,
along with model state legislation, each state will be able to
develop programs offering working parents time off with pay during
the first year after the birth of a baby or an adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal proposal recommends 12 weeks' paid leave,
states could offer as much as 26 weeks. Currently, unemployment
benefits average about $200 per week and are paid for a maximum of
26 weeks, the US Labor Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Halas, a senior employment lawyer at Greater Boston Legal
Services, who was instrumental in introducing two similar bills to
the Massachusetts Legislature, said the new federal regulations
were an important first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is timely, particularly for low-income families for whom
welfare once served as the poor woman's paid parental leave,'' said
Halas. ``There was a question as to whether this kind of change to
the unemployment insurance benefit system would pass muster under
federal unemployment law.''
</P>
<P>
   According to advocates, Clinton modeled his plan on the two
bills that have been introduced in Massachusetts. The bills, one in
the Senate and the other in the House, would offer workers on leave
50 percent of their weekly wage, capping compensation at about 57.5
percent of the average weekly wage in the state. Last year, that
cap would have been $402 per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving states the flexibility to experiment with paid
employment leave is one of the best things we can do to strengthen
our families and help new mothers and fathers meet their
responsibilities both at home and at work,'' Clinton said at a
press conference in the Oval Office, where he was joined by three
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children need this time to bond with their parents, and
parents need this time to nurture their children,'' US Senator
Edward M. Kennedy (D-MA) said. ``But all too often parents cannot
afford to take the unpaid leave that the current law permits. As
recent studies have shown, the loss of a paycheck during unpaid
leave prevents millions of others from taking a leave when they
need it. President Clinton's initiative today is a giant step
towards solving that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman estimated the maximum total cost
of implementing initial programs in four states, including
Massachusetts, would be $68 million a year, depending on the length
of time offered working new parents and the way the states
structure their programs.
</P>
<P>
   The four states, Massachusetts, Vermont, Maryland, and
Washington, are among the first with legislative proposals similar
to the model bills. There are, potentially, a total of 71,000
working parents who could qualify for paid leave in those states,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But while some state jobless programs are reporting surpluses
because the nation's healthy economy has helped more people find
jobs, there are 20 states whose jobless funds are far from flush
with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Those states, as well as the companies whose taxes enrich the
states' jobless funds, may be unwilling to support a program that
would permit payments for parental or family leave, some observers
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a back-door way to get employers to pay for a
program that the administration wants but can't figure out how to
pay for,'' Randy Johnson, a vice president at the US Chamber of
Commerce, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ed Potter, president of the Employment Policy
Foundation, a conservative think tank in Washington, D.C., issued a
statement warning that the administration's proposal could
``undermine the purpose and the solvency of the current
unemployment system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal would, potentially, create a $14 billion to $128
billion annual entitlement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Clinton announced that he had asked the Labor Department
to permit states to offer unemployment insurance benefits to
parents of newborn or recently adopted children who request time
off under the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993, which permits
12 weeks of unpaid leave for employees of firms with 50 or more
workers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Richard C. Lord, executive vice president of
legislative policy at Associated Industries of Massachusetts, which
represents 5,000 businesses, said such a plan would strip the state
of its competitive edge and would put too great a burdeon on
Massachusetts' $1.8 billion unemployment trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   The federal regulations released Tuesday are important because
they implement the president's executive order, providing payment
to families who need the time off but cannot afford to take unpaid
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Officials noted Tuesday that paid programs adopted as a result
of the new regulations will be regarded as experimental until a
minimum of four states have relied on the program for three years.
At the end of that three-year period, the federal government would
re-examine the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the regulations released Tuesday, state legislatures will
determine whether paid parental leave should be adopted and would
also vote on how it should be implemented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
