<SLUG> BC-CASINO-CHILD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASINO CHILD-CARE CENTERS MUST BE LICENSED, MISSOURI COMMISSION
DECIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Casino child-care centers must be licensed by the
Missouri Department of Health within 70 days under an emergency
rule put in force Tuesday by the Missouri Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Private child-care contractors at two Missouri riverboats,
including Station Casino Kansas City, currently operate under
licensing exemptions that permit churches, schools and businesses
to offer what amounts to short-term baby-sitting as a convenience
to patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Only Station Casino and the Riverport complex in Maryland
Heights, operated jointly by Harrah's Entertainment Inc. and
Players International Inc., are affected by the new rule. The rule
would also apply to any new child-care facilities that open at
gambling boats.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaming Commission also agreed Tuesday to study whether
casinos should be allowed to provide child care at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are examining whether that is good public policy,'' said
Mel Fisher, the commission's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   John V. Finamore, Station's Midwest president, said he was
disappointed in the commission's sudden crackdown on child care.
</P>
<P>
   The New Horizon Kid's Quest Inc. center at Station Casino has
operated for almost three years without incident, he said. It is
also used by customers at the casino's theaters, hotel and
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well run by a professional company with a lot of other
operations,'' Finamore said. ``Kid's Quest gives us and our guests
another option. It helps us make sure that kids are not
unattended.''
</P>
<P>
   Exempt centers remain subject to state investigations of
complaints. Margaret Franklin, chief of the state's Bureau of Child
Care Safety and Licensure, said Tuesday that no child-care
complaints had been filed against either casino with her agency.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dunkley, chief executive of Kid's Quest, which is based in
Minnesota, said Tuesday that his company's standards at 85 U.S.
facilities, including 15 other casinos, exceeded most states'
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Dunkley said, Missouri does not require
fingerprinting and criminal-background checks of child-care
workers. However, Kid's Quest workers in Kansas City undergo the
same criminal background checks that the casino conducts on its
potential employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkley also said Missouri's staff requirements were equal to or
greater than Kid's Quest. Missouri, for instance, requires one
staff member for every eight children in the post-toddler to
2-year-old range. Kid's Quest operates under a 1-to-7 ratio, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri also does not require workers to be trained in first
aid or CPR techniques, Dunkley said, while Kid's Quest workers are
required to have such training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not have any problem with that (new casino licensing
rule),'' Dunkley said. ``It's a standard that's really well below
the standards we have already set.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin said tougher criminal screening standards in Missouri
would go into effect Jan. 1. She also said first-aid topics could
be part of the 12 hours of in-service training classes that
licensed child-care workers must take each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem if someone's standards are tougher than
ours,'' she said. ``That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's Choice Learning Centers Inc., based in Dallas,
operates a second child-care facility at Station for casino
employees only. That operation is licensed and inspected by the
state, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Choice officials are seeking state approval to offer
day care for mildly ill children that would be available to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Gaming Commission:
</P>
<P>
   - Did not consider Station Casinos' proposed purchase of the
Flamingo Hilton Casino in Kansas City. Station officials had hoped
to win state agency approval in November and close the $22.5
million deal by today. Fisher said the commission's formal
investigation of the sale was not yet completed.
</P>
<P>
   - Recommended a $1,500 fine against the Southside Kansas City
Optimist Club in Grandview for allowing snack bar owner Doyle
Sullivan to also work at the club's weekly bingo games. Sullivan
has not been a member of the organization for the minimum two years
required by state law. Southside has 30 days to appeal the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   - Approved a corporate reorganization of Harrah's North Kansas
City Casino &AMP; Hotel from a corporate subsidiary of Harrah's
Entertainment Inc. to a limited liability company.
</P>
<P>
   - Allowed Station Casino Kansas City to fill its off-river
mooring basin with treated city tap water instead of water pumped
directly from the Missouri River. ``The big concern is the public
health risk of putting stinky river water within 10 feet of where
people are walking around,'' said Kevin Mullally, deputy director
of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   - Disclosed that Davis Gaming is considering selling some or all
of its interest in a proposed riverboat casino in Boonville, Mo.,
to an unidentified potential partner. The casino was tentatively
approved by the commission in 1997, but the project has stalled
over several issues and construction has been suspended.
</P>
</TEXT>
