<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CONTROLLERS NUDGE MARS ORBITER CLOSER TO LANDING SITE 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Flight controllers fine-tuned the trajectory
of NASA's Mars Polar Orbiter on Tuesday, nudging the small probe
closer to its intended landing site at the barren planet's south
pole.
</P>
<P>
   The small spacecraft is scheduled to touch down at 3:01 p.m. EST
Friday following a 5 1/2-minute, high-velocity plunge into the thin
Martian atmosphere and an 11-month journey from Earth. The probe
was designed to slow to a landing on the northern fringes of the
planet's south pole, slowed by a single parachute and the pulsing
of small braking thrusters.
</P>
<P>
   If the probe reaches the surface safely, scientists plan to use
a 6.5-foot long robot arm on the spacecraft and other instruments
to dig for evidence of frozen water in the subsoil. Scientists
believe the south pole may contain a reservoir of frozen water,
which once flowed over the now arid surface before Mars underwent a
change in climate.
</P>
<P>
   As the spacecraft sped within 780,000 miles of the Red Planet on
Tuesday, ground control teams at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
altered the spacecraft's 12,000 mph velocity by 1 mph, with a
12.6-second long maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly small change in velocity could make a big
difference as the Polar Lander reaches Mars on Friday. If it
arrives with an overly steep trajectory, the spacecraft could
descend too quickly and crash.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth such maneuver since the Polar Lander was
launched Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Though evaluations of the maneuver's accuracy will continue
until Friday, mission managers were confident that the Mars Polar
Lander is on course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current estimate of the flight path shows us right on
target,'' said NASA's Sam Thurman, the Mars Polar Lander flight
operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation and operations teams have been working around the
clock since the Thanksgiving holiday to ensure their calculations
are correct.
</P>
<P>
   A companion spacecraft, NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, was lost
Sept. 23, just as it was maneuvering into orbit around the planet
following a near 10-month transit from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The mishap was blamed on navigational errors later attributed to
a mixup between NASA and its contractor, Lockheed Martin, over the
use of metric and English unit of force for navigational maneuvers.
Though the space agency found no similar mixup with the Polar
Lander probe, it has added experts and checked and rechecked its
calculations of the spacecraft's trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   The task of landing on Mars is even more daunting.
</P>
<P>
   In order to land on the site selected by scientists in August,
the Polar Lander must hit an imaginary elliptical ``bulls eye''
about 80 miles above the Martian atmosphere. About 25 miles long
and 6.2 miles wide, the bulls eye represents the opening for an
imaginary corridor that will whisk the probe through the atmosphere
to the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's maneuver nudged the probe closer to the center of the
bulls eye. With the intense tracking and constant re-evaluations
under way, flight controllers will have an opportunity for a final
maneuver Friday, 6 1/2 hours before the landing, if they find
dispersions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize this is a very complex task we're going to
undertake,'' NASA's John McNamee, the Mars Polar Lander project
development manager, said. ``Landing on the surface of another
planet is a very difficult thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
