<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAMA-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama defense confident despite injuries
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ When Paul ``Bear'' Bryant was coaching
Alabama football, the Crimson Tide won national titles for one
reason _ defense.
</P>
<P>
   But things have changed since Bryant left town. So has good
defensive football.
</P>
<P>
   When Alabama beat Florida on Oct. 2, the Crimson Tide defense
was ranked 41st in the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, when the Tide plays the Gators in the SEC
Championship Game, the defense will be different _ and better.
Alabama has moved from 41st to 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 starters who began the season on defense, five remain,
mostly because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Tide probably had enough good athletes to survive the loss
of one, two or even three players during the season. But on Nov. 6
against LSU, Alabama lost three at once. Middle linebacker Marvin
Constant, defensive tackle Kenny Smith and defensive end Canary
Knight suffered season-ending injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Defying all odds, Alabama's defense has continued to improve,
and the coaches say they can't explain why. Reggie Myles' move from
cornerback to safety has had a lot to do with it, along with the
maturation of defensive lineman Kenny King, linebacker Saleem
Rasheed and cornerback Gerald Dixon _ all starting as freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is a game of repetition,'' defensive coordinator
Ellis Johnson said. ``Early on, they were thinking; now, they're
reacting. Those people not in the coaching business won't
understand this, but you've got to have patience with very young
players. There are no magic pills, no magic calls, no magic
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know sometimes in the past,'' Johnson said, ``when we might
be short of talent or would have injuries at certain positions, we
would try to X and O it and cover it up, but it just confused the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I teach defense with sight, reaction and contact,'' said
defensive line coach Lance Thompson, who has seen one-half of his
line disappear because of injuries. ``As we've gotten better, we've
gotten more aggressive. You're going to see us be more aggressive
against Florida than we were when we played them in October. But
now, we can afford to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In its past six games, Alabama's opponents have rushed 145 times
for 189 yards, an average of 1.3 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he respects Florida's Steve Spurrier as one of the
most innovative offensive minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good system, and he does a good job of jumping on a
weakness he sees on film,'' Johnson said. ``The speed they have
puts so much pressure on your defense. Our secondary has really
improved, and I think we can afford to be more aggressive because
of it. As they've improved, I've grown to have more trust in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with all the things they do, you may find yourself doing
too much, preparing for so many things that the kids are confused
and aren't playing fast,'' he said. ``We're not going to get too
flowery in preparing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season started, Thompson said, he was rotating 10
defensive linemen. Now he's down to six or seven. ``We just try to
keep them fresh. You couldn't ask for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
