A5485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TECH-UGA01-COX     11-30 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-UGA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As O'Leary sees it, `Better team won'
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George O'Leary was so steamed Tuesday that one would
have thought his Georgia Tech team had lost to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets coach was perturbed that a controversial
fumble call in the game against Georgia is getting more media play
than Tech's 51-48 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game wasn't stolen. ... Basically ... the better team won
_ period,'' O'Leary said. ``You win or lose a game with class, and,
obviously, a lot of people can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he has no problem with the way Georgia coach Jim
Donnan has handled the controversy. Donnan has not dwelled on the
issue publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech coach just wishes others would get over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rehashing (the fumble) is a little bit of overkill,'' O'Leary
said. ``Every game, there are calls that are made, or not made,
that have an impact. When it was all said and done, the score was
48-48, we started even in overtime _ and they lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '97, when a (questionable) interference call cost us the
Georgia game, you didn't see that replayed every day or pictures of
the play splashed across the front of the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech tight end Conrad Andrzejewski also recalls the 1997 game.
After reading a column by the Journal-Consti- tution's Mark Bradley
about the fumble call _ which was published Tuesday with a series
of photos that appeared to show Sanks was down _ he fired off an
e-mail to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought back to two years ago when Georgia won in the last
seconds of the game,'' he wrote. ``We pick off one pass that would
(have) ended the game but pass interference was called on our
(defensive back). If you watch the tape, it was the worst call I
have seen. But you don't see us (complaining) about the loss. We
lost that game just as Georgia lost this one.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary claims that the game had several critical calls, or
non-calls, that did not go the Jackets' way. He said he has a tape
with eight such incidents, including a late interception by Georgia
on which Tech's Jon Muyres was held. The Bulldogs scored after that
pickoff by Cap Burnett to take a 48-41 lead.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
