<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-CONCUSSIONS-COX     11-30 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CONCUSSIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concussions discussions hot topic for NHL
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nelson Emerson has seen the replay several times now.
</P>
<P>
   The drop pass he made in the neutral zone. The prolonged look he
made over his right shoulder to follow the trail of the pass _ big
mistake. The seeming brick wall he ran into, knocking him backward
and his head bouncing off the ice. Then the real scary part _ the
blackout, the leg twitching, the convulsing, the arms flailing.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson sees the tape. But he doesn't remember any of it
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first period,'' the Thrashers' right wing said
Tuesday. ``I remember going out to start the second period on the
power play. The next thing I remember is being in the emergency
room.''
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable that without the aid of videotape Emerson never
will be able to recall the details of a mid-ice check by Florida's
Jaroslav Spacek on Saturday that left him with a Grade 2
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the tape was provided by his wife, June, who was
home in Atlanta watching the game on television. She understandably
was panic-stricken while her husband was having his head
immobilized and was being strapped to a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   It's with some relief that Emerson is experiencing only memory
loss and nausea today and that he will be out of action two to four
weeks. At the time, it looked worse. Scott Green, the team trainer,
said it was the worst reaction to a concussion he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor timed it and said Nelson was unconscious for a
minute,'' Green said. ``It sure seemed longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was conscious, he was combative. That's when the
gloves came off his hands. He didn't really know what was going on.
That was the trauma to the brain. He was struggling to breathe, so
I was trying to hold his jaw to keep his mouth open.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's youngest organization is becoming too familiar with
concussions. It already has suffered six _ four on the Thrashers
(Emerson, Patrik Stefan, Petr Buzek and Vladimir Vujtek) and two in
the minor-league system (Jason Botterill, Sean Ritchlin).
</P>
<P>
   On the same night that Stefan _ already trying to shake his
dizzying past _ suffered one against Buffalo Nov. 19, Botterill was
KO'd in his first game after being sent to Orlando (IHL) for
conditioning, and Ritchlin suffered the same fate with Greenville
(ECHL). All have come in different circumstances and varying
degrees of severity
</P>
<P>
   ``That's scary,'' said Buzek, hit from behind into the glass in
Montreal. ``I don't know what's going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson takes partial blame for his injury. ``I made a mistake
looking back at my pass. I felt I had all the avenues covered. I
felt I knew where all of their players were. Obviously, the one
player who hit me, I was unaware where he was coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacek was given a major penalty for charging and a game
misconduct, meaning that he was thrown out for the rest of the
contest. The league has reviewed the play and will not suspend him.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, when asked about the hit, said, ``I felt he hit me very
late when I was in a vulnerable position. I felt he deserved to be
thrown out of the game because of the effects of what happened to
me. But I don't feel like the kid purposely tried to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers have more than the average, but concussions are a
league-wide concern. Since 1997-98, all training staffs have
documented all concussions _ the type of hit, whether the player
wears a mouthpiece and other information. The league's most recent
injury report, issued before Emerson's injury Saturday, showed
eight players now who have returned or are just coming back from
concussions.
</P>
<P>
   There were 92 concussions reported in 1997-98 and 105 last
season. At least six players have retired recently because of head
injuries, including Geoff Courtnall, Pat Lafontaine and Jeff
Beukeboom.
</P>
<P>
   A second referee was added in part to crack down on shots to the
head behind the play. More players are being suspended. Some
improvements are being made in helmets; for example, Stefan will be
fitted for one with additional padding. Mouthguards appear to
absorb some shock that contributes to concussions, but they aren't
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the league ordered all NHL arenas using
``seamless'' glass to be fitted with a system of boards that gives
more upon impact.
</P>
<P>
   But generally, concussions can't be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of it is the acceleration-type injuries, where a guy
is going full-bore and then gets stopped suddenly,'' Green said.
``When that happens, the brain is still traveling at the speed they
were going, and it hits the front of the head. It sloshes, like
Jell-O. There's no helmet that can stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, generously listed at 5 feet 11, 180 pounds, depends
more on speed than physical play. He understands that his rushes
through the neutral zone come with risk. ``My injury _ that's
something that happens,'' he said. ``It's an open-ice hit. It's
probably the beauty of the game that a player can step up and catch
him with his head down.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's something he doesn't want to experience again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never a good thing to see something like that,'' he said.
``And when it happens to you, it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
