<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EDITOR'S NOTE FOR WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 1
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: This editor's note will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INSIDER-MOVIE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Nov. 23,
pondered the relative professional dependability of lawyers and
journalists, as reflected in the movie ``The Insider.'' The film is
a dramatic adaptation of events four years ago, when CBS,
perceiving a threat of a devastating lawsuit, eviscerated a ``60
Minutes'' broadcast of an interview by a tobacco industry
whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   The Times article wove its thesis mainly out of the movie
version of the plot; the article signaled that device by giving the
participants double-barreled names (Hewitt-Hall, for example,
meaning the executive producer Don Hewitt of CBS, as played by
Philip Baker Hall, and Wallace-Plummer for the reporter Mike
Wallace as played by Christopher Plummer).
</P>
<P>
   At some points, though, the article spoke of ``Mr. Hewitt'' and
``Mr. Wallace,'' referring to the actual people. Those references
undercut the distinction between the actions of the two journalists
and their fictional representations. It should have been
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS staff memo, reported in The Times on Nov. 3, emphasized
the liberties taken by the movie _ noting, for example, that the
actual Mr. Wallace spoke out publicly against CBS's corporate
decision after only a day and not, as depicted on screen, after
days or weeks of persuasion by his producer, Lowell Bergman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
