<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upset causes spike in UD ticket demand
 &HT;    By Bucky Albers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ University of Dayton basketball tickets became a
hot item Tuesday on the heels of Monday night's 68-66 upset of the
13th-ranked Kentucky Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   The telephones in the UD Arena ticket office rang constantly
Tuesday morning. It was mid-afternoon before things slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Kentucky victory) had a tremendous impact,'' said
ticket manager Joe Granito, who estimated that his office had 10
times as much activity as it would on a normal day. Granito
couldn't think of anything comparable in the 10 years he's been on
the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ticket purchasers were interested in the holiday
games with Texas A&AMP;M (Dec. 21), St. Louis (Dec. 23) and Miami (Dec.
29).
</P>
<P>
   Granito said some of the callers said they think the Flyers, who
are now 4-0, might be good enough to get into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of 400 level tickets ($7 adults, $4 for those
under 16) available for all games, including tonight's game with
Maryland-Baltimore County and Saturday's game with Winthrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have the Atlantic 10 package _ eight games for $50,''
Granito said. ``We sold quite a few of those today. They're right
behind our season ticket holders. If you bought them individually,
it would cost $64. Basically, they're getting two games for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Bucky Albers writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
