<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXPORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS POLITICIANS TOUT INTERNATIONAL TRADE REPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ While protesters disrupted opening ceremonies of the
World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle on Tuesday, two Texas
politicians praised international trade and released a report
revealing the benefits to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas exports totaled $78 billion in 1998, according to a study
conducted for The Business Roundtable, a national association of
chief executives officers of leading corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas last year put $3,600 on the world market for every man,
woman and child in the state,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
``This report is important because it proves that trade works.''
</P>
<P>
   Release of the information apparently was timed to coincide with
the WTO meeting in Seattle, where discussions were to begin on new
rules governing international trade. Thousands of demonstrators
seeking to impose more worker and environmental protections blocked
the streets and forced the delay of opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they afraid of?'' Gramm asked at a press conference
in Dallas as police in Seattle were firing pepper spray at the
protesters. ``They're afraid of freedom. They're afraid of
competition. We believe Texans can out-produce any workers in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that ``enlightenment'' about free trade has made the
United States ``the greatest trading nation in the world'' and that
``we have the highest living standard of any people who ever lived
on the face of this planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Conducted by Global Trade Information Services of Columbia,
S.C., the latest trade study found that Texas exports increased by
3.5 percent from 1997 to 1998, a period when U.S. exports overall
declined by 1.1 percent and Texas trailed only California in world
exports.
</P>
<P>
   Most, if not all, of the growth came in trading with America's
partners in the North American Free Trade Agreement, which went
into effect nearly six years ago. From 1996 to 1998, Texas' trade
with Canada and Mexico increased from about $31 billion to about
$42 billion. During that same period, trade with Asia declined
slightly, trade with Europe grew slightly and trade with the Middle
East, South America and Central America remained essentially flat.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, where $33 billion worth of Texas products was sold in
1998, was by far the state's largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the report noted, Texas' exports of gas turbines
increased by 17.5 percent in 1998, up to $770 million. But, the
most striking growth was with Mexico, where gas turbine sales
jumped from $48 million to $144.5 million _ an increase of 200
percent _ in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles and parts accounted for nearly 7 percent of all exports
from Texas, the study found, and exports to Mexico grew by 64
percent in 1998, from $1.8 billion to more than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the study also found that more Texas
businesses are pursuing international markets and that is causing a
manufacturing, trucking and warehousing boom along the Texas-Mexico
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of businesses in this area has increased by 37.2
percent (from 1993 to 1996),'' the report stated. ``This is
impressive when compared to 20.5 percent for the rest of the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Employment in border counties during the same period increased
by about 31 percent, compared to nearly 12 percent for the rest of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the House majority leader,
appeared with Gramm at the Dallas press conference. He also used
the occasion to advocate free trade and criticize those disrupting
the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we close our doors to trade,'' Armey said, ``we'll be
putting the jobs of thousands of Texans on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Exporting manufacturers in Texas employ about $614,000 workers.
Of those jobs, 117,000 are directly linked to exporting, the
Roundtable report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is not easy to understand,'' said Armey, who, like
Gramm, is a former professor of economics. ``It is important for
those of us who do understand it to stand up and fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armey's 26th Congressional District exported about $3.5 billion
in farm and manufactured goods in 1998. His district was one of
five in the state profiled by the study.
</P>
<P>
   Another was the 22nd District represented by Rep. Tom DeLay,
R-Texas. In 1998, manufacturers, wholesalers and farmers there
exported $4.8 billion worth of products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
