<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-HOMELESS-6     11-30 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-HOMELESS-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS CLINTON ATTACKS GIULIANI'S POLICY OF ARRESTING HOMELESS PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (sw) 
By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Offering the most pointed attack to date on her
likely Senate opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday condemned
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's policy of arresting homeless people in New
York City for sleeping on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our political leaders must be judged on how they treat
everyone, including the least fortunate,'' Mrs. Clinton told an
audience made up of mostly black ministers. ``We must ask
ourselves: do we solve problems or simply push them away,
politicize them and criminalize them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be absolutely clear,'' she continued. ``Breaking up
families that are homeless is wrong. Criminalizing the homeless
with mass arrests for those whose only offense is that they have no
home is wrong. Locking people up for a day will not take a single
homeless person off the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton did not mention the Republican mayor by name during
her remarks at the New York Theological Seminary in Manhattan. But
she clearly sought to portray Giuliani as favoring policies that
were less than humane to homeless and poor New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also clearly intended to sound like the candidate
she promised to be just last week, when she declared, under
pressure from fellow Democrats, that she fully intended to run for
the Senate although she declined even then to get drawn into a
debate over the mayor's homeless policy.
</P>
<P>
   Her advisers suggested that Tuesday's appearance, marked by her
strong condemnation and her deliberate attack on one of the mayor's
latest programs, signaled a decision to move into an active
campaign mode by staking out positions highlighting her differences
with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, her aides said, Mrs. Clinton had determined through
polling and surveys by news organizations that Giuliani's position
on arresting homeless people for sleeping on the streets was widely
unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, traveling from fund-raiser to fund-raiser in Texas on
Tuesday, was quick to defend his strategy. Noting that the city had
a complex set of responses to the issue of homelessness and that
just a small percentage of the homeless have been arrested,
Giuliani said that take ``some of the few situations in which
someone's arrested and to try to make that into the whole program,
could portray a misunderstanding of how the program works.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made her remarks at an hour-long meeting where she
was warmly received and interrupted several times by applause. The
audience included many of the most prominent black ministers in New
York City, including two friends of the president and Mrs. Clinton:
the Rev. Gardner C. Taylor, the pastor emeritus of the Concord
Baptist Church in Brooklyn, and the Rev. James Forbes, the pastor
of Riverside Church in Manhattan. Mrs. Clinton was also seated at a
table in the front of the room with former Mayor David Dinkins and
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton covered a number of topics, the issue of
homelessness was the cornerstone of her speech at Tuesday's
breakfast. Noting that 250,000 households in New York are on an
eight-year-long waiting list for federally subsidized housing, she
called for more federal funds for low-income housing and pledged
that, if elected, she would work to secure more money for housing
and for programs that treat mentally ill people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am elected senator, I will fight hard to triple new
housing vouchers and target them to areas with the highest need,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Joseph Llota complained later in the day that Mrs.
Clinton wanted to ``turn back the clock'' on homeless policy.
``Unfortunately, Hillary just doesn't get it,'' Llota said. ``New
York City spends more money on the homeless than any other
community in America. Our strategy is to get as many people as
possible off the streets to get the services that we pay for.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After her appearance at the morning breakfast on Fifth Avenue in
Manhattan, Mrs. Clinton flew to Buffalo, where she spent several
hours greeting customers in a pizza restaurant on a busy commercial
strip.
</P>
<P>
   There she took pictures with patrons and signed autographs
before doing interview with several television and radio stations
in western New York. Then, in the evening, she flew to the town of
Great Neck on Long Island to attend a fund-raising reception for
Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2050EST &QL; 
