<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TRADE-TALKS-SCENE-NYT     11-30 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-TALKS-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATIONS IMPEDE PROGRESS AT TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TRADE-TALKS) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER and JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Four members of President Clinton's Cabinet and
hundreds of other American officials came to Seattle this week to
push America's agenda on free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they spent Tuesday trying to negotiate their own free
passage.
</P>
<P>
   As demonstrators and tear gas mingled on the streets below, U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky was unable to leave her
hotel to start the four-day-long, 135-nation talks, which were
supposed to begin in an aging downtown theater. The Secret Service
would not let her into the streets. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and the secretary-general of the United Nations, Kofi
Annan, did not fare any better.
</P>
<P>
   And by midafternoon the ``millennium round'' of trade
negotiations that was supposed to start here this week was reduced
to a series of frantic telephone calls between hotels, as
Europeans, Asians, Africans and Americans who cannot see eye-to-eye
on trade could not even meet face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the midlevel American officials involved in the
negotiations ended up in the lobby of the Westin Hotel here sipping
lattes and waiting for security officials to signal that it was
clear for them to venture outdoors. But even then, there was no
assurance that they could get to various meeting sites, as hotels
were wringed by protesters.
</P>
<P>
   It was an embarrassing beginning to a set of negotiations that
the administration had once been reluctant to hold. Then, in a move
many American officials clearly regretted Tuesday, the White House
reversed position and Clinton volunteered to host the session here,
in hopes that launching the negotiations on home turf would give
Washington more sway over the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the focus has been on the streets instead of on the
talks. And it wasn't only downtown Seattle that was suffering from
gridlock. So were the negotiations. Europe and the United States
dug in their heels on one of the most contentious issues, an end to
Europe's huge subsidies for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there was no real progress on one of the big
questions that the protesters were shouting about: getting the
World Trade Organization to regulate working conditions in
factories around the world. India has so far blocked any real
discussion of the issue, and American officials were scrambling,
cell phones permanently attached to their ears, to drum up some
allies in their struggle to get a ``working group'' within the WTO
that, for the first time in the history of trade talks, would make
labor conditions an explicit subject of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, all sides were trying to use the protests for
political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The French were delighted to see protesters echoe their longtime
complaint that free trade in agriculture hurts local farmers and
forces them to market foods of suspicious origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening outside is having an effect on the
negotiations,'' the European Union trade commissioner, Pascal Lamy,
said Tuesday. The American desire to eliminate government subsidies
in Europe that make it extraordinarily difficult for American
farmers to export their goods ``is even less possible'' given the
tenor of the protests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The American delegation, milling in the lobby and conference
rooms of the Westin Hotel here, insisted that the protests
underscored the importance of moving labor rights to the top of the
WTO's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear expression of concern by ordinary workers has to be
taken into consideration,'' said Sue Esserman, one of Ms.
Barshefsky's top deputies, who recently traveled to India in an
attempt to persuade its leaders that a discussion of labor rights
would ultimately be in their national interests. ``And that's
exactly what we have done,'' she said. Ms. Barshefsky herself
wasn't talking; her aides said she was glued to her telephone,
conferring with her foreign counterparts across town.
</P>
<P>
   American officials went to some lengths to argue Tuesday that
their work had not really been disrupted. The real give and take
goes on in back rooms and over the phone anyway, they noted, as
countries try to protect their most powerful constituencies and
search for trade-offs. ``We are using all the time available,'' Ms.
Esserman said, though she acknowledged that ``the lines are
jammed'' because hotel switchboards were overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Barshefsky was working the phones, the ministerial
meeting of the WTO began without her and without the Europeans.
Mike Moore, the former boxer and prime minister of New Zealand who
is now director general of the WTO, announced Tuesday afternoon
that ``this has not stopped our work. We are already meeting and
discussing our negotiations.'' But without two of the world's
biggest economic powerhouses in attendance, it was a bit like
beginning an opera with the soprano and the tenor stuck in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the thousands of trade officials here saw the
activity in the streets as the cacophony of democracy, a few
suspected that there was a deeper conspiracy at work. One
ambassador of a developing nation, who insisted on anonymity, said
he was certain that the Clinton administration had orchestrated the
protests in hopes of shortening the time for real negotiation.
That, in turn, would put pressure on smaller nations to give in, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
