<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TRADE-TALKS-ART-NYT &LR;      11-30 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-TALKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATORS THROW TRADE TALKS AND SEATTLE INTO TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to be filed by 9:30 p.m.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 43 and 44 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK and STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A new round of global trade talks was thrown into
turmoil Tuesday as thousands of demonstrators poured into downtown
Seattle and forced the postponement of opening ceremonies for an
event that President Clinton, who is scheduled to arrive on the
scene early Wednesday, had hoped would showcase American leadership
on free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day the protesters surrounded the convention hall,
pinned trade dignitaries in their hotels and stopped traffic on
several intersections. By late afternoon, there was a barrage of
tear gas canisters fired as Mayor Paul Schell declared a state of
emergency in the downtown area, asked for the National Guard and
ordered a curfew that would last until sunrise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The police used tear gas, pepper spray and rubber bullets at
some intersections to break up the demonstrators. A small group of
men, dressed in black clothing and masks and ignoring cries of
``Shame on you!'' from other protesters, smashed windows and
spray-painted graffiti at downtown stores like Nordstrom, Niketown,
Starbucks and the Gap. Both were jarring sights in a city that
prides itself on its laid-back image.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters gathered here in opposition to the scheduled
meeting of the World Trade Organization, a global body intended to
resolve trade disputes and promote free trade. They carried banners
and chanted slogans that spoke to an eclectic array of grievances,
most of them centered around the belief that the trade organization
is a handmaiden of corporate interests whose rulings undermine
health, labor and environmental protections around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other scheduled
speakers for opening ceremonies Tuesday morning were unable to get
through the crowd, which in many cases blocked intersections by
linking hands or lying down on the street.
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of protesters already gathered downtown and about
20,000 additional marchers in a union-backed rally headed that way,
the trade body's director-general, Mike Moore, the former prime
minister of New Zealand, announced early Tuesday afternoon that the
opening ceremonies would be put off. But he vowed that the trade
talks would go on. In fact, he held meetings Tuesday with a few
trade ministers who managed to leave their hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiating groups are in full swing,'' Moore said. ``This
conference will be a success.'' Outside, protesters chanted:
``Whose world? Our world! Whose streets? Our streets!''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction of the trade delegates here seemed to run the gamut,
from bewilderment to bemusement to, in some cases, anger. As
demonstrators shouted ``Go home! Go home!'' a German delegate,
Arnold Schwez, made his way back inside the Sheraton Hotel after he
could not get through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people don't understand the benefits of free trade to
the developing nations,'' Schwez said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday night, as Christmas lights and displays came on in
parts of downtown streets, demonstrators continued to hold their
position on the streets. A few fires, most set in trash cans,
burned in the street.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-WTO-PROTESTS-1201-COX     11-30 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-PROTESTS-1201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMONSTRATORS THROWING WORLD TRADE SUMMIT INTO CHAOS
 &HT;    With CLINTON-WTO-1201.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The global trading system slammed against a
broad-based backlash in blue jeans here Tuesday, as tens of
thousands of demonstrators shut down the core of this booming
Pacific port and threw a long-planned world trade conference into
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Helmeted police backed by armored vehicles fired rubber bullets
and exploding cannisters of pepper gas throughout the day to break
up demonstrations that turned violent on the opening day of a
four-day World Trade Organization meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The city declared a civil emergency as night fell, imposing
Seattle's first curfew since Vietnam-war era protests nearly three
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 p.m. (PT), state officials were forced to call
out the national guard to bring order to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters, some hurling stones, firebombs and firecrackers,
smashed windows in a dozen upscale department stores and shops.
Others blocked entry into the main WTO venue, forcing organizers to
delay for nearly six hours opening ceremonies for the largest
gathering of trade negotiators in history.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before President Clinton was due to arrive here, police
circled two dozen city buses to cordon off his hotel, as a tense
stand-off ensued several blocks away between a thin phalanx of riot
police and more than 20,000 protesters.
</P>
<P>
   As additional police poured into the downtown area, the city
declared an emergency curfew from 7 p.m. (PT) until sunrise,
setting the stage for a nighttime showdown with diehard protesters.
Police reported 19 arrests as of nightfall, and a series of
explosions rocked the downtown area as police cast a giant cloud of
noxious gas over the core of downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes past 5 p.m. (PT), officials at the hotel Clinton
was to stay in made
</P>
<P>
   an unusual announcement _ in English, followed by Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a lock-down situation. For your safety we would ask
that those of you who are guests in this hotel please go to your
rooms at this time,'' hotel officials announced. The hotel was the
seat of the U.S. trade delegation, led by U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to arrive early Wednesday, where he plans
to address trade ministers from about 135 countries assembled here
to launch a new round of WTO negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a range of tensions resulting from the growth in
international trade. As the U.S. economy has become increasingly
linked to a global marketplace, scores of groups have rallied to
contend that the world trading system is placing profits ahead of
worker safety, the environment and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Seattle, where the WTO is meeting to launch an ambitious
round of negotiations aimed at setting the rules of global commerce
for the coming decade and beyond, environmental groups, organized
labor and others are using the event to draw a line in the sand
over world trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are helping us change the face of the global economy,''
John Sweeney, president of the giant AFL-CIO told a crowd and
estimated crowd of 35,000 at a labor rally at Memorial Stadium.
``Your presence here is proof that public opinion is fueling a
growing protest that has begun to speak to power.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, whose confederation of labor unions represents some 14
million organized workers, vowed to work to block any future trade
agreements that lack protections for workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stop them,'' said Sweeney, whose constituents have
come under virulent wage and job pressures from low-cost imports
produced in countries where pay is a fraction of U.S. levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here in Seattle is the beginning, the
beginning, of a fight we must carry to every level of government in
every country in the world,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO is an international tribunal that sets and enforces the
rules of the road in the global marketplace. If trade is the ship
powering one-sixth of the $30 trillion global economy, the WTO is
the system of buoys and navigational aides that guide it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the world's most powerful advocate of a strong WTO,
claims it has lent stability and predictability to a global trading
system that is creating hundreds of billions of dollars in new
wealth each year.
</P>
<P>
   That wealth, he contends, is helping to broaden the global
middle class, alleviate poverty and knit together a community of
nations tethered by commerce, not riven by contention.
</P>
<P>
   Its critics, though, say the WTO's enforcement powers give it
broad authority to supersede national laws, raising issues of
sovereignty and state control over the economic destiny of its
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anybody here vote to join the WTO? Anybody here paying
dues to the WTO,'' James Hoffa, president of the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, asked the crowd at Tuesday's union rally.
``Then why don't we get the hell out of the WTO?''
</P>
<P>
   Rousing the crowd shortly before it held a peaceful, two-hour
march through Seattle, Hoffa drew enthusiastic cheers from
organized labor groups and others assembled on a sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ones that make the work, we are the ones that make
the profits,'' Hoffa thundered, ``and we are the ones that are
going to have a place at the table of the WTO, or we're going to
shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of high rhetoric. Air Line Pilots Association
president Duane Woerth even paraphrased Patrick Henry at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know not what course others may take,'' said Woerth, ``But
the Air Line Pilots Association isn't going to the WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   Woerth said the WTO negotiators want to bring the civil aviation
industry _ worth, he said, $1 trillion a year worldwide _ under its
regulatory umbrella. That, said Woerth, would threaten unions like
the one he represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over the world are getting hurt by the WTO and
their tactics,'' said Jay Boyle, 44, a telephone installer for US
West in nearby Vancouver, Wash., and a member of the Communications
Workers of America labor union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think workers in the United States understand labor
anger,'' Boyle said. ``Social unrest is something we haven't seen
since the 60s, and maybe it's time to get back to something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
