<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OBIT-BIGGESTBASEBALLF     11-30 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BIGGESTBASEBALLFAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alison DeGenero, who saw 52 straight World Series, dies
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Julius Whigham II
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Whenever Alison DeGenero attended the
World Series, he usually didn't have to worry about getting a
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Vero Beach, Fla., resident knew someone would take
care of him.
</P>
<P>
   For 52 consecutive years, he attended at least one game of the
annual Fall Classic, a feat documented by the Baseball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the man known to many as ``DeGe'' died of natural
causes, a Vero Beach newspaper reported Tuesday. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   He had been living at a Vero Beach nursing home since late
October, after being injured in a fall.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DeGenero, whose house featured a baseball diamond-shaped
driveway, began his string of attending the World Series games with
the 1946 contest between the Cardinals and Red Sox. But the string
ended earlier this year when his fall caused him to be briefly
hospitalized and made him miss the New York Yankees' sweep of the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   He was perhaps best-known in baseball circles for his World
Series string _ his tickets are prominently displayed at the
Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y. _ but he also became one
of baseball's biggest ambassadors, attending games in Cuba, China,
the former Soviet Union, Australia and Italy, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worry about finding a place to stay because I know
that I'll befriend somebody,'' Mr. DeGenero said in a 1994 Palm
Beach Post interview. ``Baseball is so beautiful. They take care of
their people better than the churches do. That's how sacred the
game is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DeGenero maintained his love of baseball despite losing his
eyesight to a degenerative eye disease in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   He attended each game with a tape recorder, recording memorable
moments such as the San Francisco earthquake at the 1989 World
Series. He also attended the Little League World Series in
Williamsport, Pa., every year from 1990 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is like a religion. It influences the good things,''
he once said.
</P>
<P>
   Born to Italian immigrants, Mr. DeGenero spent much of his
childhood in Ohio. He became a manufacturer of eyeglasses cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his daughter, Patricia Mong; five
grandchildren; two sisters; a brother; and five
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held at 1 p.m. Friday in Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, his family is requesting donations be madein
his memory to the Recreation Department of Vero Beach/Indian River
County. Proceeds will benefit the county's five Little League
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Whigham II writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: juliuswhigham(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2103EST &QL; 
