<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DELHOMME-CINEMATOGRAP     11-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELHOMME-CINEMATOGRAPHER-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RISK-TAKING PERFECTIONIST BEHIND THE CAMERA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Laura Winters' most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
director Francis Veber and French comedies.  
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Being a cinematographer is, in many ways, like being a
psychoanalyst,'' said Benoit Delhomme recently at his studio here
on the outskirts of the city. ``We let the director of a film talk,
and then, from just a few key words, we guess what's in his head
and come up with the images that he seeks.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``Unlike a psychoanalyst, however, we don't have to
cure the director. On the contrary, if he's a bit mad, it's even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme, who is one of France's leading cinematographers and
one of the few whose work is sought outside his homeland, has
fashioned the lighting, camerawork and imagery of some of the most
distinctive directors working today. Among them are the
French-Vietnamese director Tran Anh Hung (in ``The Scent of Green
Papaya'' and ``Cyclo''), the French filmmaker Cedric Klapisch (``Un
Air de Famille'' and ``When the Cat's Away''), David Mamet (``The
Winslow Boy)'' and most recently the British director Mike Figgis
in ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' and ``Miss Julie,'' which opens
in New York on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme, 38, has become known for his innovativeness and
versatility. While each of the 13 movies he has filmed has a
distinctly different look and style, there are some recurring
elements: rich colors, close-ups and a handheld camera technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing about Benoit,'' said Klapisch, ``is that he
seems equally at home on a studio film or a small film shot on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for his calm on the set, Delhomme is secretly a
perfectionist and a worrier. A slight man with a gentle manner, he
stands outside scanning the streets when a visitor is late. In his
atelier, his striking primitivist paintings (which he has never
exhibited) vie for space with objects that have inspired him for
various films.
</P>
<P>
   There are photographs he took in Vietnam before shooting
``Cyclo,'' a lump of salt from the Tunisian desert location of
``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' and books of paintings that
inspired his explorations of light for ``Miss Julie,'' Figgis'
adaptation of the 1888 August Strindberg play about a young,
disturbed aristocrat and her father's manservant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Julie'' seems to be a departure from ``The Loss of Sexual
Innocence,'' the first collaboration between Figgis and Delhomme.
While ``Sexual Innocence'' is a sprawling contemporary story filmed
in several different countries, ``Miss Julie'' is a period drama
filmed on one set and featuring only three principal actors:
Saffron Burrows as Miss Julie, Peter Mullan as the servant, Jean,
and Maria Doyle Kennedy as Jean's fiancee, Christine.
</P>
<P>
   Both films, however, were filmed in Super-16mm, which involves a
lighter camera than the standard 35mm, and both were shot with two
mostly handheld cameras manned by Delhomme and by Figgis himself.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis (who perhaps is best known for ``Leaving Las Vegas'')
developed this method to allow greater mobility. He is a director
who plunges into all aspects of filmmaking: composing the score (as
he did in ``Miss Julie'' and ``Leaving Las Vegas'') or working a
camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was searching for a cinematographer who would not get upset
if I wanted to operate a camera as well,'' he said by telephone
from Los Angeles. ``With Benoit, I found a kindred spirit. On the
two films, he lit and did all the main operating, and whenever I
had the opportunity I went in and got shots on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Miss Julie,'' the actors move freely around the kitchen
where much of the action is set while the camera circles them,
swooping in for sudden close-ups and then zooming away
vertiginously. Although the actors are in period dress, the effect
is both modern and intimate.
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme relished what he calls ``the crossfire of cameras,''
adding, ``Mike didn't want `Miss Julie' to be the usual heavy
costume drama. It was as if the actors were wild beasts let out of
their cages, and we had to scramble to capture their every
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ``wild beasts'' found this liberating as well. ``We were
doing what felt right for the characters,'' said Ms. Burrows, whose
Miss Julie has a feral intensity. ``I never felt so alive at
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Delhomme wanted to create a lighting setup that would not only
permit filming from all angles but also create the luminous glow of
a Swedish midsummer night. Inspired by the paintings of the
Norwegian artist Edvard Munch and of the Danish painter Vilhelm
Hammershoi, he eventually settled on a big, soft overhead light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always do research, but I don't recreate paintings on
screen,'' he said. ``For me, the worst thing you can say about a
film is that it is `painterly.' Paintings are static. Films have to
breathe, to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before Delhomme was interested in either painting or
cinematography, he was an amateur photographer. He grew up in
Cherbourg, in northwest France, and as an adolescent spent hours in
the darkroom. His family has an artistic bent: his grandfather,
Georges Delhomme, was a painter and designer of perfume bottles for
Lancome.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit's brother, Jean-Philippe Delhomme, is an artist who
illustrated, among other things, a talked-about 1993 advertising
campaign for Barneys, featuring whimsically drawn figures
accompanied by ironic headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Young Benoit became interested in film, but from the standpoint
of creating images rather than directing. He attended the
prestigious Ecole Louis Lumiere in Paris, graduating in 1982, and
served as an assistant cameraman and short-film cinematographer
before meeting Tran Anh Hung in 1991. Tran asked him to collaborate
on his first and then his second feature, ``The Scent of Green
Payaya'' (1993) and ``Cyclo'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   ``Papaya,'' which was filmed inside a Paris studio, is a
tranquil, loving evocation of a bygone era in Vietnam. ``Cyclo,''
which was shot verite-style on the streets of Saigon, is virtuosic,
fractured and violent.
</P>
<P>
   These two films, which won many awards, showed off Delhomme's
range internationally and gave him the entree to work with
English-speaking directors like Mamet. Here, again, Delhomme
rendered a play (``The Winslow Boy'') cinematically vivid by basing
the look of the film on John Singer Sargent's portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he shot Benoit Jacquot's ``Sade'' in France, starring
Daniel Auteuil as the infamous Marquis, and is now considering
several Hollywood projects, albeit warily. ``The rules can be so
important for a Hollywood film that one risks losing the lightness
of a European film,'' he said. ``I'd like to do a big film, though,
if it was personal for the director.''
</P>
<P>
   For Delhomme, this personal touch is critical; he makes it clear
that his own sensibility is in service to a director's vision. When
asked what he himself seeks in an image, he grows animated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to feel the grain of the actor's skin, direct and
pure,'' he replies. ``I hate those films where there is this
diffuse light over everything, like a golden sauce. There are
cinematographers who are like great cooks, but with every film they
do, they give you the same thing to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``Whereas for me the important thing is to take
risks. I want to give you the elements raw, or at least change the
sauce every time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
