<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ECON-900(2TAKES)     11-30 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ECON-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO CALL FOR SWEEPING TAX CUTS IN SPEECH ON WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for print and electronic media.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush will lay out the centerpiece of
his economic agenda on Wednesday, calling for sweeping cuts in
income tax rates, a tax break for many married couples and an
increase in the child credit, his aides said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, valued by the Bush campaign at $483 billion over
five years starting in 2002, seemed certain to ignite debate among
his rivals for the Republican presidential nomination, and drew
fire on Tuesday from Vice President Al Gore, who called it fiscally
irresponsible even before its details were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-cutting package, which would be financed out of
anticipated budget surpluses, would be larger than the tax cut
passed by the Republican-led Congress last summer and vetoed by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seeks to shore up Bush's standing as a traditional
economic conservative even as it addresses his theme of helping the
working poor. But like Republicans in Congress, Bush faces a
complicated task in selling a big tax reduction. With the economy
strong and many people feeling prosperous, polls show that the
electorate is more interested in using the nation's newfound fiscal
health to address other issues, like education and the solvency of
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal _ to be unveiled in a speech in Des Moines on
Wednesday _ would reduce taxes across the income spectrum gradually
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy would see the top income tax rate reduced from 39.6
percent to 33 percent. The 28 percent and 31 percent rates paid by
many middle-class taxpayers would be consolidated and reduced to 25
percent. Lower income families would benefit from the creation of a
new 10 percent tax bracket that would apply to much of the income
currently taxed at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would also double the child credit to $1,000 and allow
more affluent families to claim the credit than under current law.
It would benefit many married couples by reviving a deduction based
on the lower-earning spouse's income. And it would phase out the
inheritance tax on large estates over eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan does not contain any reduction in taxes on capital
gains.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the plan sticks closely to Republican orthodoxy,
concentrating its benefits on the upper end of the income scale,
the people who pay the most taxes, while also appealing to
middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   One of its unstated messages is that Bush _ more than his
father, who as president broke a vow not to raise taxes and who
once derided the supply-side tax-cutting philosophy as ``voodoo
economics'' _ can be counted on by his party's conservative base to
do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is simply an effort to show that he's a serious candidate
who has ticked off all the little boxes of things you're supposed
to do when you run for president,'' said Bruce Bartlett, a former
Treasury Department official in the Reagan and Bush
administrations. ``The important thing is that it touches all the
various bases, that it's small enough not to be considered fiscally
irresponsible but substantial enough that it means something to the
people who he feels need to be given something in the tax area.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's proposal is also his first major effort to put a
detailed policy behind his theme of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   His advisers said the combination of the new 10 percent rate and
the increase in the child credit was intended to help working poor
families. Under the current tax code, those families lose a
substantial portion of tax breaks available to them through the
earned income tax credit _ and therefore face much bigger tax bills
_ as their income approaches middle-class levels.
</P>
<P>
   By the Bush campaign's calculations, the changes would remove 6
million families from the federal income tax rolls, or 20 percent
of all families with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a plan that will reduce the upper rate,'' Bush told
reporters in Chicago on Tuesday. ``It's a plan also that recognizes
that our current system is not fair. If you're a single mother with
children, and you live on the outskirts of poverty, and you work
hard, as you move toward the middle class, you pay an enormous
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said the tax cuts would go overwhelmingly to
the wealthy, and would do less for low-income people than Bush
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree that there's much for low income,'' said Iris J.
Lav, deputy director of the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities,
a liberal-leaning research organization in Washington. ``Even the
things that look like low income are really middle income, and as I
understand the rate structure, you're really talking about a
massive tax cut for high-income people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is putting out his economic plan as he prepares for his
first debate with his rivals for the Republican nomination on
Thursday night in New Hampshire, and is clearly eager to show that
he has a detailed agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also risking criticism from some of his Republican
opponents as being too timid on tax cuts. From the Democratic side,
Bush is already under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Even before knowing the Bush plan's details, Gore criticized its
approach on Tuesday, saying that like the tax bill passed by
Republicans in Congress this year it would endanger the nation's
fiscal health. Campaigning in New Hampshire, Gore said Bush had
endorsed ``a truly reckless tax scheme that would immediately put
our country back into deficits.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan was developed by a team of economists headed by
Lawrence B. Lindsey, a former Federal Reserve governor and policy
aide to President George Bush. The team also included Michael
Boskin, who was chief economist in the Bush White House, and John
F. Cogan, who was a budget official in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   The size of Bush's plan was determined in part by projections of
the size of the budget surplus. Both parties in Washington have
agreed that the portion of the projected surplus generated by
excess Social Security revenue _ about $2 trillion over the next
decade _ should be off limits for tax cuts or new spending. But the
rest of the surplus _ the portion generated by general tax revenue
_ is up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's economic team estimated that the non-Social Security
surplus during the first five years of their tax cut would be $586
billion. That estimate is higher than current surplus estimates by
the Congressional Budget Office and the White House, although their
estimates are likely to be increased in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said there was still considerable uncertainty about
how big the surpluses will be, in part because the current
projections are based on assumptions that spending increases will
remain far more limited than they have been in each of the past few
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
