<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PETE-ROSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NEW TIMES SQUARE, ROSE SINGS HIS SAME OLD SONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT21) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two police officers noticed Pete Rose and waved to
him when he emerged from a hotel in midtown Manhattan. Rose turned
left and began walking toward a sports cafe for a news conference,
and another man stopped and shook his hand. Another man, who had
been consumed with lighting a cigarette, dropped the match, nudged
his friend and shouted, ``Look, it's Pete Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rose was mostly oblivious to the attention he received
Tuesday on Seventh Avenue, because he was too busy talking about
getting the chance to be reinstated to baseball. Rose was talking
quickly and walking quickly, and probably would have lectured all
the pedestrians at West 46th Street and Seventh about why he
deserves to be in baseball and in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Commissioner Bud Selig has repeatedly said that he
has seen no new evidence that would lead him to overturn the
lifetime ban that Rose agreed to in 1989 because of his gambling on
professional sports, the sides will meet to discuss Rose's status
in January. Rose sent a letter to Selig eight days ago seeking
reinstatement. Selig responded by giving the letter to Robert
Dupuy, baseball's executive vice president for administration, who
will meet with Roger Makley, Rose's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it'll lead to anything,'' Rose said. ``But it
can't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, who has been described by associates as being rigid in
his feelings about not reinstating Rose, was cautious in describing
the meeting as more of a courtesy than an initial step toward
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rose's attorney has written me a letter,'' Selig told The
Associated Press. ``I read it very thoughtfully, very carefully,
and turned it over to Dupuy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose would not specify what evidence Makley will present to
Dupuy, but he claimed that he had spent $1.5 million in assembling
his case 10 years ago and that it will include handwriting and
fingerprint experts and witnesses who will talk about gambling.
John Dowd, the lawyer who was hired by baseball to investigate
Rose's gambling, said in his report that he obtained betting slips
that handwriting and fingerprint analysis verified had been used by
Rose. There are eight people in the Dowd report who said they had
some knowledge of Rose betting on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying for 10 years that I didn't bet on baseball,''
Rose said. ``Why am I going to change my mind now?''
</P>
<P>
   When Rose was asked if he would amend his statements from the
Dowd report to concede that he had bet on baseball, he said,
``Forget about that.'' He added that he would not accept an
agreement in which he is allowed to go into the Hall of Fame and is
still banned from baseball because he's a ``baseball person'' and
would like to return to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, the career hits leader, said he should be reinstated if
his lawyer proves he did not bet on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a judge, wouldn't you reinstate me if I could
prove that?'' Rose said. ``Or are you going to be one of those
people who still believe I did it?''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement that Rose reached with A. Bartlett Giamatti, the
commissioner at the time, was not deemed an admission or a denial
of the allegation that Rose bet on baseball. But the agreement also
said the commissioner had a ``factual basis'' to impose the
lifetime penalty and that Rose could not challenge it in court.
Still, when Rose was asked what he would do if the meeting between
Makley and Dupuy does not somehow lead toward reinstatement, he
said: ``You always have legal options. But I'm not looking for a
fight. I'm a lover, not a fighter. Give my people a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said that he has uttered ``I'm sorry'' in hundreds of
interviews, but that ``not everybody is going to hear you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry for the mistakes I've made,'' Rose said. ``I'm sorry
for betting on football through a bookmaker. I was wrong. Although
I'm as sorry as I can be, I didn't hurt anybody but my family. I
disagree with people who say I tarnished the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose asked: ``How did I tarnish the game of baseball? Did I
tarnish the game as much as calling off the World Series? The
strike? The lockout?
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, I tarnished myself. I'm sorry I did that. Do you
think I wished this to happen? If it didn't, I'd probably have
several million dollars in the bank and still be managing the
Cincinnati Reds.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
