A5521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEXAS-WTO-PROTEST-COX     11-30 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WTO-PROTEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protesters in Texas decry WTO
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The international trade agreement protests in
Seattle echoed in Austin streets Tuesday as consumer, labor and
environmental groups rallied at the Capitol to call for abolition
of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at the peaceful rally here, which drew about 400
people, denounced what they said was the WTO's power to force
nations to accept genetically altered food, products made with
slave or very low-wage labor, and lower environmental standards,
all in the name of ensuring free trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a turning point in American politics,'' said
Robert Jensen, a journalism professor at the University of Texas
and moderator of the rally. The protesters, he said, were ``saying
no to the guys in the suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, Renu Namjose of Texas Consumers for Safe Foods,
criticized WTO rulings that have required countries to allow
imports of scientifically altered food. The WTO, for example, ruled
that European Union nations must allow the sale of hormone-treated
beef after the United States protested a ban on such imports.
</P>
<P>
   Namjose said a nation should retain the right to ban such
altered foods. ``Remember, gene pollution cannot be cleaned up or
brought back on recall.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Harrington, state director of the AFL-CIO, said American
corporations have exploited Mexican workers under the North
American Free Trade Agreement by moving manufacturing south of the
border and paying low wages.
</P>
<P>
   While the Austin demonstrations were peaceful, meetings of the
135-nation World Trade Organization were delayed Tuesday by
protests during which police fired pepper spray at demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   The central issue in Seattle is who gets to make the rules,
Harrington said, charging that ordinary workers and others
concerned with the environment and human rights are not consulted
in writing the trade rules and settling disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But as groups as diverse as the Teamsters, the Sierra Club and
the Gray Panthers protested in Austin on Tuesday, a business group
touted the benefits of free trade with a new study showing how much
Texas and Travis County depend on exports for jobs and sales.
</P>
<P>
   The study was commissioned by the Texas International Trade
Alliance. The alliance is a part of the goTRADE initiative launched
by The Business Roundtable, an association of chief executive
officers of major corporations committed to free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Travis County about 300 manufacturers _ most of them
employing 20 or fewer workers _ exported $2.54 billion in goods and
products in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Countries in the Asian Pacific Rim and South Asia are the top
export markets for Travis County manufacturers; 85 percent of the
manufacturers sold products to Asia; 84 percent to Europe; 82
percent to Canada; and 70 percent to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _ Products exported from Travis County include semiconductors,
heart valves, golf clubs, computers, orthopedic implants, concert
lighting, Italian food products, oil field equipment,
telecommunications gear and interactive multimedia video
conferencing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Statewide, exporting manufacturers in Texas employ about
614,000 workers, and 117,000 of those were directly related to
overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   The trade alliance issued a statement from U.S. Rep. Lloyd
Doggett, D-Austin, who said that ``international trade equals jobs
for the working men and women in Central Texas, particularly in the
high-tech industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, Doggett said, ``clearly demonstrates that in order
for the technology sector in Central Texas to be successful we must
be able to export our products to other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
