<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAFF OF FTC OPPOSES BP AMOCO-ARCO MERGER
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the Federal Trade Commission has concluded that the
proposed $29 billion merger between BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield
violates antitrust law and has recommended that the commission
block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was based on concerns that the merger could
result in significantly higher gasoline prices in California and
the West Coast. Those states are supplied crude oil from the North
Slope of Alaska, where exploration and production are dominated by
BP Amoco and ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED BY THE ENTREPRENEURIAL SPIRIT
</P>
<P>
   Umang Gupta, the chairman and chief executive of Keynote
Systems, which measures Web site performance for e-commerce
companies, did not start out wanting to be an entrepreneur. But
Gupta eventually caught the entrepreneurial bug, joined some
start-ups and started his own company. In 1997, he made an
investment in Keynote. A few months later the board asked him to
take over as chief executive. Gupta's stake in the company is now
worth more than $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL AS BOND PRICES CLIMB
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined after selling erased gains in financial stocks
spurred by an increase in bond prices. The Dow Jones industrial
average dropped 70.11 points, to 10,877.81. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index decreased 18.76 points, to 1,389.07. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 85.21 points, to 3,336.16.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE INDEX RISES
</P>
<P>
   The consumer confidence index climbed to 135.8 in November from
130.5 in October just as retailers geared up for the holiday
shopping season, the Conference Board said.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE AND WTO PROTESTERS CLASH
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the World Trade Organization was thrown into
turmoil as thousands of protesters poured into downtown Seattle,
forcing the postponement of opening ceremonies. Police used tear
gas, pepper spray and rubber bullets to break up the demonstrators.
The National Guard was called in.
</P>
<P>
   It took Mike Moore nearly a year to become director-general of
the World Trade Organization. It could take a just a few days for
him to be judged a success or a failure.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER WARNER BID SEEN AS POSSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products said that it would work to give
Warner-Lambert shareholders ``additional value'' under their merger
agreement to reflect possible increased revenue from the
cholesterol-reducing drug Lipitor. The move was interpreted by some
analysts as a signal from American Home that it might raise its $70
billion offer.
</P>
<P>
   SBC CONSIDERS TWO TRACKING STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications is considering issuing separately traded
tracking stocks to follow the company's wireless communications
unit and its international operations.
</P>
<P>
   $7.5 MILLION PAID FOR WEB ADDRESS
</P>
<P>
   Ecompanies, an Internet ``incubator'' in Los Angeles, is paying
$7.5 million to a Houston entrepreneur for the rights to the domain
name business.com. It is thought to be the highest price ever paid
for an Internet address.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT TALKS BEGIN
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Microsoft, the federal government and 19 states met
for about two hours with a federal judge appointed to seek a
settlement in the antitrust case against the company. No one
involved in the talks would comment on their progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
