<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTIAN AND U.S. OFFICIALS COOPERATE ON CRASH INVESTIGATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON and MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first public comments on the crash of
EgyptAir Flight 990, the director of the FBI, Louis J. Freeh, said
Tuesday that the Egyptian authorities were cooperating with the
inquiry into the cause of the crash and would investigate a list of
leads at the request of American law-enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, speaking with reporters at the FBI headquarters, said
that the authorities in Cairo were assisting American investigators
even though Egyptian officials have dismissed the principal
American theory that a reserve pilot might have deliberately
brought down the airliner.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, aviation safety experts and Egyptian
investigators have completed a transcript of the cockpit voice
recorder in Arabic, but have not completed an English translation,
an official at the National Transportation Safety Board said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian and American linguists must agree on the translation,
and aircraft experts must identify whatever nonspeech sounds they
can. Then they must synchronize the words and sounds on the tape
with events recorded on the other ``black box,'' the flight data
recorder, the official said. The date for finishing that work has
gradually been moved back, though the board now hopes to finish by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   American investigators have not ruled out any possibility for
the Oct. 31 crash but have primarily centered their effort on Gamil
al-Batouti, an EgyptAir reserve pilot. They theorize that it was
Batouti who pitched the Boeing 767 into a steep dive toward the
Atlantic Ocean. The aircraft crashed in the sea about 60 miles
south of Nantucket, killing all 217 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said that the Egyptian authorities had complied with every
American request for assistance, supplying personnel and aircraft
maintenance records that have been turned over to the FBI and the
National Transportation Safety Board, which is in charge of the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're receiving cooperation at this time,'' Freeh said.
``We've not had any request turned down.'' Freeh added that the FBI
had reached no conclusions about the cause of the crash.
``Everything is on the table,'' he said. ``Everything is being
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, other law enforcement officials said that the
requests to the Egyptians, including requests for more information
about the backgrounds of Batouti and other crew members, implied
that investigators believe Batouti might have been responsible.
Egyptian officials have said that an undetected mechanical failure
might have been responsible for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said he had been consulting closely with aviation safety
officials, and he talked Tuesday with James E. Hall, chairman of
the aviation safety board. Freeh said he discussed the continuing
recovery of wreckage from the ocean bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A large civilian ship chartered by the Navy, the Smit Pioneer,
is expected to arrive from Lisbon at the safety board's operations
headquarters in Quonset, R.I., by Monday. It will spend several
days being prepared to move to the crash site. The ship is heavy
enough to operate in rough early winter seas.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crash, the Navy has been using a small
remote-controlled submarine to map the debris field, as weather
allows.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh and Hall have discussed whether to transfer responsibility
for the inquiry to the FBI _ an action that would indicate that
authorities suspect a criminal act in the crash. But Tuesday, Freeh
said such a step would have little practical impact on the pace or
direction of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A safety board official said that at some point after the
Egyptian and American team completes the translation of the cockpit
voice recorder, Hall may ``characterize'' its contents, but his
agency will not make public the transcript itself if, as many
aviation safety investigators hope, the investigation is turned
over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the safety board have raised the possibility that
the Egyptian government, which delegated the investigation to the
United States a few hours after the crash, might seek to rescind
that assignment if American officials conclude that the crash
should be investigated by the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2113EST &QL; 
