<SLUG> BC-WINE-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S AND WINE DEALER END AUCTION ARRANGEMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Britain)   By HOWARD G. GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After five years of auctioning fine and rare wines
together, Sherry-Lehmann and Sotheby's have parted company.
</P>
<P>
   The split was announced Monday, nine days after a two-day sale
that brought in $14.4 million, setting a world record for wine
auctions by eclipsing a 1997 Christie's sale in London that
realized $11.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Sherry-Lehmann, a Madison Avenue store
with a national clientele, and Sotheby's, the international auction
house, said they ``have mutually agreed to pursue different
courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Aaron, the chairman of Sherry-Lehmann, and Serena
Sutcliffe, the director of Sotheby's international wine department,
said in the statement that since both organizations began sharing
auctions in 1994 they ``always thought of this as a three- to
five-year commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   They added, ``We believe that this is the right time for each of
us to pursue our different directions'' in this ``expanding
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sutcliffe, reached in London, declined to go into detail
about the differences, but said Sotheby's would soon announce the
name of a new partner and that it expected to hold auctions in New
York next year.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said, ``We could not agree upon a contract,'' adding only,
``Basically, a contract is about one thing: economics.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Sherry-Lehmann, which has retail sales ``in excess of
$30 million a year,'' was contemplating holding its own auctions by
the middle of 2000. ``We have a very good auction team here
already,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said that in 24 auctions since 1994, the team had
grossed $64.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, independent auction houses like Sotheby's,
Christie's and Phillips International can conduct wine auctions
only if they have as a collaborator a wine merchant who has held a
license for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   If Sherry-Lehmann goes it alone, it will join Manhattan
merchants like Morrell &AMP; Co. and Acker Merrall &AMP; Condit, which have
sponsored auctions for years without the assistance of professional
auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry-Lehmann With Sotheby's, as the partnership had been
called, has gone head to head against Zachys-Christie's, which
joins a $20-million-a-year merchant in Scarsdale, N.Y., with the
auction firm.
</P>
<P>
   In 32 auctions since 1995, Zachys-Christie's, which also holds
auctions in Los Angeles, has grossed $72.5 million. In Manhattan,
it sells wine at Christie's new headquarters at Rockefeller Plaza
and at Christie's East.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the London-based Phillips International Auctioneers,
whose partner in Manhattan-based auctions is the Park Avenue Liquor
Shop, was bought by Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
