<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CURB ON BEEF SALES TO END
</P>
<P>
   A two-year-old ban on sales of beef on the bone is to end Dec.
17 after assurances from medical officials that there is no longer
any risk that certain cuts may be contaminated with the infective
agent that causes mad-cow disease, which attacks the brain. The
action was unrelated to the continuing French blockade of all
British beef imports in defiance of the European Commission's
decision to lift its worldwide ban last Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ASSEMBLY APPROVED BY LORDS
</P>
<P>
   A bill to transfer home rule to the new Northern Ireland
Assembly passed the House of Lords and is expected to clear Commons
on Wednesday. The process was speeded up to enable the
Protestant-Catholic coalition for Ulster to start work Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY: POPE TO VISIT PORTUGAL
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II plans to visit Fatima on May 13, 2000, his third
pilgrimage to the site in Portugal where the Virgin Mary is said to
have appeared to three young shepherds on May 13, 1917. On May 13,
1981, the pope was shot by a Turkish gunman, Mehmet Ali Agca, and
he believes that Mary saved his life. The pope is expected to
beatify two of the children. The third, Sister Lucia Dos Santos,
92, lives in a convent in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: MORE HOLOCAUST PAYMENTS
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss fund for Holocaust survivors approved payments of
$1.27 million to 1,600 Jewish and Gypsy applicants and political
opponents of the Nazis. The fund has distributed more than $160
million.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: PEACEKEEPERS ARRIVE
</P>
<P>
   One hundred thirty Kenyan soldiers, the start of a 6,000-member
United Nations peacekeeping force, arrived in Freetown. A July
peace accord granted the rebels several high-ranking positions in a
coalition government, but Amnesty International said ``deliberate
and arbitrary killings, rape and abductions of civilians have
increased despite the peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   EAST AFRICA: COMMON MARKET REBORN
</P>
<P>
   Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania signed a treaty to resurrect their
common market, but the agreement does not resolve the issue of
removal of trade barriers. The three have said they will admit
Rwanda to the union.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   HAITI: U.N. POLICE TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council voted to keep a police training force in
Haiti until mid-March, when Haiti is to hold an election and the
United Nations plans to send a broader development mission. The
council voted 14-0, with Russia abstaining. China, which opposed an
extension because of Haiti's ties with Taiwan, voted yes.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: 2 JOURNALISTS KILLED
</P>
<P>
   Two journalists were shot to death in a northeastern area that
has experienced heavy fighting between Marxist guerrillas and
right-wing paramilitary groups. The journalists were covering a
local election that had to be called off after a mayor was
assassinated. No group has claimed responsibility for the three
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: CORRUPTION TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   One hundred special courts will be established to try people
charged with corruption and loan defaults, said Pakistan's leader,
Gen. Pervez Musharraf. A list of 5,000 names has been given to
immigration officials to keep suspects from leaving the country.
The general seized power Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: CURB ON OIL SALES
</P>
<P>
   Still divided on how to treat Iraq, the United Nations Security
Council is likely to extend for only one week the program under
which Iraq exports oil to pay for food, medicine and other items.
The Iraqis rejected the measure in advance. An earlier two-week
extension led to a cutoff of exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
