<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-TAXES-HNS &LR;      11-30 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO OUTLINE $483 BILLION TAX-CUTTING PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: 3 a.m. EST embargo for all media) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush hopes that the $483 billion
tax-cutting plan he unveils Wednesday will keep the nation
prosperous and avoid the kind of economic downturn that contributed
to his father's 1992 re-election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, according to an aide who briefed Texas newspaper
reporters, includes a combination of expanded tax deductions and
lowered marginal tax rates that are intended to favorably affect
low-income and wealthy individuals, as well as two-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tax-cut plan is not just about productivity, it's about
people,'' the Republican presidential front-runner said in a
statement released by his campaign. ``It will make life better for
average men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor will deliver a speech outlining his tax-cut
plan Wednesday in Des Moines, Iowa, one day before his first debate
with his rivals for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But promising tax cuts is not as popular as it once was, as
congressional Republicans discovered when they devoted much of the
summer unsuccessfully trying to sell voters on a $792 billion
tax-cut package.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
congressional Republicans in July that they should hold off on tax
cuts because the cuts might be needed later to jump-start a sagging
economy.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton vetoed the $792 billion Republican-backed
tax cut in September, Bush said he would have signed the plan
because it would have been good for individuals and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush admitted in a recent interview he worries that the economy
might suffer a cyclical downturn after he takes office as
president, creating the appearance of a second Bush Bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be one of the great ironies, wouldn't it? I'm not an
alarmist. You shouldn't read into the words any sense of panic or
concern, but it's important,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons I've advocated cutting the marginal
rates of taxes, as an insurance policy against an economic
downturn. I certainly hope the economy doesn't turn down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan would reduce federal revenues by $483 billion over
the next five years, the aide said, and is based on a
``conservative'' estimated revenue growth rate of 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The key elements of the plan include reducing the federal
marginal tax rates by reducing the number of tax brackets from five
to four and cutting the range of rates from the current 15 percent
to 39.6 percent to a new range of 10 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also would double tax credits from $500 to $1,000 per
child; create a 10 percent deduction for two-income families to
lessen the marriage penalty; eliminate estate taxes; make the
research and development tax credit permanent; allow non-itemizing
taxpayers to deduct charitable contributions; and eliminate the
Social Security earnings limit for seniors between the ages of 65
and 69.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan also would expand the Education Savings Account
program beyond the current tax-free savings for college. The amount
that could go into the account would be raised from $500 to $5,000
a year per child, and the money could be spent tax-free on tuition
and books for private and parochial schools from kindergarten
through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton made the economy, which took a slide in the early
1990s, a driving element of the successful campaign he waged to
deny President Bush a second term in 1992. The campaign's internal
slogan was: ``It's the Economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he worries that the nation's current boom economy
might not be sustainable over the next several years without the
kind of boost that a tax cut would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the growth has been balance-sheet growth, stock
markets. We've been able to refinance our homes, interest rates
dropping. But there's beginning to be some pressure on interest
rates,'' said Bush, adding that there also is inflationary pressure
because of tightening labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to insure against a downturn is to put more money into
the pockets of consumers. And one way (to do that) is to cut
marginal rates,'' Bush said. ``Remember any plan I propose today
won't be in effect until a couple of years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   The unsuccessful congressional plan had some of the same
elements as Bush's proposal, including reduction in marginal rates,
the elimination of estate taxes and reduction in taxes for some
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan does not include a cut in the capital gains tax
rate, which is favored by businesses but easily portrayed by
Democrats as a benefit for the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won the public relations battle by portraying the GOP
tax plan as fiscally irresponsible, one that would increase the
national debt and cause cuts in needed federal programs. The
president had proposed a tax cut of about $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed that voters were more interested in reducing the
national debt and saving Social Security and Medicare than getting
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In an Associated Press poll released Tuesday, only eight percent
of those surveyed said taxes would be the most important issue in
deciding whom to vote for in the 2000 election. The poll of 1,023
adults found that among voters' priorities taxes ranked behind
education, Social Security, Medicare, the economy, the nation's
moral values, and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent poll by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP;
the Press found that only staunch conservatives believed that taxes
should be a high priority for the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have been thinking of those conservatives, who play a
pivotal role in the GOP primaries, particularly in states such as
New Hampshire, where Bush is in a tight race with Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   While taking questions from New Hampshire voters last week, Bush
said he wanted to make certain his proposed cut in tax rates would
benefit low-income individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marginal rate, if you are near poverty and you're headed
to the middle class, say you are a single mom with children ... as
you head into the 15 percent bracket and the earned income tax
credit drops off, you pay a high marginal rate on taxes,'' Bush
said. ``And that's not right. That's unfair in the tax code. That
needs to be adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, the aide briefing Texas reporters said, a
family of four earning $35,000 a year would pay no income taxes
because of the adjustments to rates and the increased child tax
credits. A family of four earning $50,000 a year would save $1,900
a year on taxes, while a family of four earning $75,000 a year
would save $2,500 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan also would have a benefit for the nation's
wealthiest people.
</P>
<P>
   Income of $130,250 to $283,250 is taxed at a rate of 36 percent
and income above that level is taxed at a rate of 39.6 percent.
Under Bush's plan, income of $130,250 and above would be taxed at
the lower rate of 33 percent. That means an individual earning
$500,000 a year could save more than $18,800 in federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The overall size of Bush's tax proposal has been limited by the
spending plans made by Congress and the Clinton administration,
which use much of the budget surplus for the next several years. It
also will be limited by Bush's promise that all payroll taxes for
Social Security will be ``lock-boxed,'' meaning his administration
will not borrow from the Social Security trust fund to finance
deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has promised there will be no cuts in Social Security
benefits for the elderly, but he is promoting individual retirement
savings accounts for younger people as a supplement to the Social
Security system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
