u f BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-B     11-30 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY GROWS OVER `LOST' HANCOCK CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Working-class people with modest burial policies and
Stephen L. Brown, the multimillionaire chairman and chief executive
of John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., have something in
common: Both have been ``lost'' in the big company's databases.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a growing controversy about the Boston insurer's failure to
locate scores of missing customers, nearly a million policyholders
gave an expected nod Tuesday to Hancock's plan to go public. The
approval puts Hancock on track to conduct an anticipated initial
public offering on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in a personal note to the lost-customers flap, said
Tuesday after the tally that he, too, had turned up missing. But he
blamed himself, not the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a John Hancock customer, I myself am guilty of losing track
of a life insurance policy and of allowing John Hancock to lose
track of me,'' Brown told a policyholder meeting in Boston. ``It
wasn't until demutualization packets were mailed out that I
remembered an old policy whose address I had never updated.''
</P>
<P>
   About 94 percent of 1 million policyholders who cast votes were
in favor of Hancock's plan to become one of the insurance world's
largest publicly held companies, a process known as
demutualization. Policyholders, who are technically the owners of a
mutual, will receive stock in the new company, cash, or beefier
policies in exchange for their ownership rights.
</P>
<P>
   Barely one in three of the 2.8 million policyholders who were
eligible to vote cast ballots. Most of the 400,000 policyholders
that Hancock has lost track of _ nearly 15 percent of its eligible
customer base _ were entitled to vote on the plan. About 300
policyholders turned out Tuesday to ask Hancock executives about
the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Most insurers lose track of 3 to 5 percent of their customers,
according to consumer advocate and Boston lawyer Jason Adkins.
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. of New York, which is also
demutualizing, lost track of 600,000 of its 11.1 million total
policyholders. Hancock originally could not find a whopping 25
percent of 2.8 million policyholders, or 800,000 customers, who
were eligible to vote on the company's conversion. The insurer has
a total 3.3 million policyholders. After $4 million and 18 months
of searching, Hancock is still looking for 400,000 customers,
typically older people with burial policies worth less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has blamed its missing-persons problem on people who
move without leaving forwarding addresses. Many policies were sold
by door-to-door agents decades ago, before easily traceable Social
Security numbers were used on documents. Critics have countered
that Hancock has a fiduciary responsibility to keep track of its
customers, for whom life insurance can be their most valuable
investment. Annual mailings to policyholders who had moved would
have been returned, which should have prompted the insurer to
launch a search years ago, Adkins said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have also slammed Hancock. Secretary of State
William Galvin said Tuesday that he was disturbed by the company's
inability to find missing clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about pursuing missing people,'' said
Galvin, who as the state's top securities overseer has some
regulatory authority over Hancock. ``I'm less than clear as to what
the company is saying it is going to do about this, and I'm looking
for a written commitment from them'' that missing customers will
receive compensation should they show up later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-MARS-1STLDWRITET     11-30 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CONTROLLERS NUDGE MARS ORBITER CLOSER TO LANDING SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to fix lede to ``Lander'') 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Flight controllers fine-tuned the trajectory
of NASA's Mars Polar Lander on Tuesday, nudging the small probe
closer to its intended landing site at the barren planet's south
pole.
</P>
<P>
   The small spacecraft is scheduled to touch down at 3:01 p.m. EST
Friday following a 5 1/2-minute, high-velocity plunge into the thin
Martian atmosphere and an 11-month journey from Earth. The probe
was designed to slow to a landing on the northern fringes of the
planet's south pole, slowed by a single parachute and the pulsing
of small braking thrusters.
</P>
<P>
   If the probe reaches the surface safely, scientists plan to use
a 6.5-foot long robot arm on the spacecraft and other instruments
to dig for evidence of frozen water in the subsoil. Scientists
believe the south pole may contain a reservoir of frozen water,
which once flowed over the now arid surface before Mars underwent a
change in climate.
</P>
<P>
   As the spacecraft sped within 780,000 miles of the Red Planet on
Tuesday, ground control teams at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
altered the spacecraft's 12,000 mph velocity by 1 mph, with a
12.6-second long maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly small change in velocity could make a big
difference as the Polar Lander reaches Mars on Friday. If it
arrives with an overly steep trajectory, the spacecraft could
descend too quickly and crash.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth such maneuver since the Polar Lander was
launched Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Though evaluations of the maneuver's accuracy will continue
until Friday, mission managers were confident that the Mars Polar
Lander is on course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current estimate of the flight path shows us right on
target,'' said NASA's Sam Thurman, the Mars Polar Lander flight
operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation and operations teams have been working around the
clock since the Thanksgiving holiday to ensure their calculations
are correct.
</P>
<P>
   A companion spacecraft, NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, was lost
Sept. 23, just as it was maneuvering into orbit around the planet
following a near 10-month transit from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The mishap was blamed on navigational errors later attributed to
a mixup between NASA and its contractor, Lockheed Martin, over the
use of metric and English unit of force for navigational maneuvers.
Though the space agency found no similar mixup with the Polar
Lander probe, it has added experts and checked and rechecked its
calculations of the spacecraft's trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   The task of landing on Mars is even more daunting.
</P>
<P>
   In order to land on the site selected by scientists in August,
the Polar Lander must hit an imaginary elliptical ``bulls eye''
about 80 miles above the Martian atmosphere. About 25 miles long
and 6.2 miles wide, the bulls eye represents the opening for an
imaginary corridor that will whisk the probe through the atmosphere
to the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's maneuver nudged the probe closer to the center of the
bulls eye. With the intense tracking and constant re-evaluations
under way, flight controllers will have an opportunity for a final
maneuver Friday, 6 1/2 hours before the landing, if they find
dispersions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize this is a very complex task we're going to
undertake,'' NASA's John McNamee, the Mars Polar Lander project
development manager, said. ``Landing on the surface of another
planet is a very difficult thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-MARS-1STLDWRITET     11-30 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CONTROLLERS NUDGE MARS LANDER CLOSER TO LANDING SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to fix lede to ``Lander'') 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Flight controllers fine-tuned the trajectory
of NASA's Mars Polar Lander on Tuesday, nudging the small probe
closer to its intended landing site at the barren planet's south
pole.
</P>
<P>
   The small spacecraft is scheduled to touch down at 3:01 p.m. EST
Friday following a 5 1/2-minute, high-velocity plunge into the thin
Martian atmosphere and an 11-month journey from Earth. The probe
was designed to slow to a landing on the northern fringes of the
planet's south pole, slowed by a single parachute and the pulsing
of small braking thrusters.
</P>
<P>
   If the probe reaches the surface safely, scientists plan to use
a 6.5-foot long robot arm on the spacecraft and other instruments
to dig for evidence of frozen water in the subsoil. Scientists
believe the south pole may contain a reservoir of frozen water,
which once flowed over the now arid surface before Mars underwent a
change in climate.
</P>
<P>
   As the spacecraft sped within 780,000 miles of the Red Planet on
Tuesday, ground control teams at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
altered the spacecraft's 12,000 mph velocity by 1 mph, with a
12.6-second long maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly small change in velocity could make a big
difference as the Polar Lander reaches Mars on Friday. If it
arrives with an overly steep trajectory, the spacecraft could
descend too quickly and crash.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth such maneuver since the Polar Lander was
launched Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Though evaluations of the maneuver's accuracy will continue
until Friday, mission managers were confident that the Mars Polar
Lander is on course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current estimate of the flight path shows us right on
target,'' said NASA's Sam Thurman, the Mars Polar Lander flight
operations manager.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation and operations teams have been working around the
clock since the Thanksgiving holiday to ensure their calculations
are correct.
</P>
<P>
   A companion spacecraft, NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, was lost
Sept. 23, just as it was maneuvering into orbit around the planet
following a near 10-month transit from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The mishap was blamed on navigational errors later attributed to
a mixup between NASA and its contractor, Lockheed Martin, over the
use of metric and English unit of force for navigational maneuvers.
Though the space agency found no similar mixup with the Polar
Lander probe, it has added experts and checked and rechecked its
calculations of the spacecraft's trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   The task of landing on Mars is even more daunting.
</P>
<P>
   In order to land on the site selected by scientists in August,
the Polar Lander must hit an imaginary elliptical ``bulls eye''
about 80 miles above the Martian atmosphere. About 25 miles long
and 6.2 miles wide, the bulls eye represents the opening for an
imaginary corridor that will whisk the probe through the atmosphere
to the Martian surface.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's maneuver nudged the probe closer to the center of the
bulls eye. With the intense tracking and constant re-evaluations
under way, flight controllers will have an opportunity for a final
maneuver Friday, 6 1/2 hours before the landing, if they find
dispersions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize this is a very complex task we're going to
undertake,'' NASA's John McNamee, the Mars Polar Lander project
development manager, said. ``Landing on the surface of another
planet is a very difficult thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
