<SLUG> BC-WTO-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS, SEATTLE POLICE CLASH; TRADE TALKS DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a day split by peaceful protests and angry
activism, police in full riot gear Tuesday fired tear gas into the
crowds of demonstrators who filled downtown Seattle, and shut down
the latest round of world trade talks, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   As 20,000 or more union workers from around the country prepared
for a massive afternoon march on the city, thousands of other
protests locked arms to form human chains, sat down in the streets,
and surged against police barricades to keep World Trade
Organization delegates from reaching their meetings. The WTO
conference is intended to be a starting point for a new round of
negotiations on ways to liberalize trade; WTO members this week are
trying to set an agenda for further discussions.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the singing and sloganeering, ugliness erupted
repeatedly throughout the day, and by late afternoon several street
corners were in chaos. To force the protesters to disperse, a 7
p.m. curfew was imposed in the downtown area, a state of emergency
was declared, and the National Guard was called out.
</P>
<P>
   Face to face with police determined to hold the line, protesters
set a dumpster on fire at one intersection, spraypainted a squad
car at another, and hurled insults and objects at officers at both
locations. Standing beside an armor personnel carrier, and backup
vehicles, police in gas masks and holding plastic shields responded
again and again with tear gas, pepper spray and what were believed
to be rubber bullets. They did not move toward the crowds, and,
instead, appeared almost relaxed as white clouds of gas rose from
the ground and spread throughout through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth it,'' said Isaac Rojas, a 29-year-old lawyer and
environmental activist from Costa Rica, said between fits of
coughing caused by an early volley of gas. ``We did what we wanted,
we got a chance to confront the delegates directly. We got our
message heard, although this is just the beginning of our work.''
</P>
<P>
   With the heart of the city paralyzed from dawn past dusk, at
least two dozen people were arrested and a half dozen injured,
police said. Her eyes red, her body limp, one woman hit by pepper
spray had to be carried to safety as people shouted, ``Stay calm,
no stampeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some WTO delegates criticized the city's handling of what
everyone expected to be the largest protest effort in recent
history, one bringing together people from different nations and
with different concerns but all of them opposing the Geneva-based
trade group as a secretive, undemocratic organization that favors
trade over everything from human rights to animal rights to labor
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But WTO Director-General Michael Moore stressed that overall
ceremonies were cancelled, a working lunch was held as scheduled,
negotiations were ``in full swing'' and other meetings were
continuing uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not stopped our work,'' he said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, however, did agree with many of the peaceful protesters,
who were in the clear majority and who expressed disgust at the
lawlessness that broke out at what had been billed as a non-violent
protest.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, a small band of teenagers and young adults,
dressed in black, their faces covered with bandannas, went on a
rampage, smashing store windows with crowbars, overturning trash
cans, and vandalizing cars for nearly an hour. Authorities used a
bulldozer to prevent large barrels from being rolled down one
street. The trouble-makers tended not to be affiliated with any of
the human rights, environmental, labor, or members of other
organizations who were taking part in demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day ministerial conference, where President Clinton is
scheduled to speak Wednesday, runs through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful the hoodlums would tarnish the other gatherers' message,
some protesters stepped in to try to stop the trouble themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain point where actions like this should be
taken, but this is rash,'' said Greg Dean, 29, a Seattle carpenter,
as he watched somone spray-paint graffiti on the wheels of a police
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people feel tied down, sometimes they have to break out
and vandalism and violence happens. I'd rather have seen this stay
peaceful today.''
</P>
<P>
   But with an hour to go until curfew, the crowds refused to back
down as poice issued five-minute warnings and more canisters of gas
and spray were tossed their way. As they had throughout the day,
demonstrators struggled to keep their faces covered with sweatshirt
hoods and scarves.
</P>
<P>
   An eerie quiet settled in on some street corners, with only
occasional chants of ``the world is watching,'' but people made no
move to leave. In response, police reinforcements carrying batons
and other anti-riot equipment arrived by the score and, four and
five deep, faced off for more confrontation. Loud booms and the
sound of sirens filled the air. One man, his bloody head bandaged,
said he believed he had been hit by a rubber bullet after hearing
the crack and seeing a flash. The ground was littered with tiny
black rubber projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the protest marches of all sizes that passed
through downtown starting at 7 a.m. and lasting well into the
afternoon, sometimes causing bottlenecks at intersections and often
paralyzing traffic, came and went without incident.
</P>
<P>
   Every organization, every cause, appeared to be represented,
many of them having no obvious ties to the events centered around
the WTO and its right to settle trade disputes among its 135 member
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Banners flew for the Freedom Socialist Party, the Communist
Party, and Veterans for Peace. A group calling itself ``Radical
Women'' was represented, as was the Free Mumia Movement, the
coalition that supports the release of a Philadelphia man convicted
of killing a police officer years ago. Other groups supported a
free Taiwan and free trade with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But it was international trade and its impact on US workers that
was intended as the theme of the day until violence broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Teamsters International president James Hoffa Jr. and
trade unionists on Harley motorcycles, tens of thousands of union
members _ machinists, school teachers, dock workers, steel workers,
and electrical workers, among others _ rallied at Seattle's Sports
Stadium, then filed into downtown in an hourslong procession that
extended for block after block. Planned with city officials and
police, with hundreds of union-appointed marshalls in orange caps
keeping order, the march was a sharp contrast to the activities
that greeted the men and women as they headed toward the convention
center, where many of the WTO meetings are supposed to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal was to draw attention to the loss of American jobs to
overseas workers who earn far less money and sometimes work in
conditions below US standards. One of the few floats featured in
the procession was built in recent days by unionized General
Electric workers from Lynn, Mass., who paid their own way to
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could give you propaganda and say, `Yeah, this is it,
this is the turning point for us,' '' said Edward Fire, president
of the International Union of Electrical Workers and chairman of
the coordinated bargaining committee for the 14 unions that
represent GE plants. ``The whole question of better deals for
workers has come into the forefront in the last couple years. This
is just another step in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the peaceful protesters and union members alike worried
late Tuesday that the world would remember only the anger here,
much of it directed at police rather than the WTO. As one young man
scaled a streetlight to replace a banner welcoming the WTO with one
condemning the trade group, a sometimes forest-firefighter named
Jeremy Plotkin from British Columbia wished aloud that everyone had
attended a three-hour class in non-violence training, as he had.
Within hours, police would be ordered to clear out Seattle's
downtown, although no one was sure how to accomplish that without
incurring more violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO goes against all my core beliefs, and I think we're
sending a strong message that we're fed up,'' said Plotkin, 24, who
is active in environmental causes. ``But right now I'm worried
about what message these other people are sending. Maybe 1 percent
of the people out here are doing damage, but it's damaging all of
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
