<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JORDAN-CAREER-ART-2TA     11-30 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-CAREER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNON JORDAN IS JOINING LAZARD FRERES, THE INVESTMENT BANK IN NEW
YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Ill., Germany) (Exclusive) 
(ART ADV: A photo, NYT52, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vernon E. Jordan Jr., a close friend of President Clinton and a
leading political power broker in Washington, is giving up his
senior executive position with the law firm Akin, Gump, Strauss,
Hauer &AMP; Feld to become a partner in Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., the
private investment bank, in New York in January.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, one of the most powerful black men in the country, said
in a telephone interview that his focus will shift from legislation
to global corporate strategy when he moves from Washington to Wall
Street. ``I won't be talking about how do you work some particular
law,'' he said. ``I'm going to be an investment banker giving
strategic advice.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the timing of his move as ``more propitious'' than
when he had been approached to move to Wall Street in the past. It
comes at the tail end of Clinton's presidency and in the wake of
the tumultuous impeachment hearings in which the 64-year-old Jordan
had to testify about the role he played in finding a corporate job
in New York for Monica Lewinsky, the former White House intern at
the center of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan and his partners at Akin, Gump stressed that he
will maintain an advisory role with the firm and its legal clients,
his presence in political and social circles in Washington is
likely to diminish when he begins commuting from his home there to
Lazard's offices in Rockefeller Center. ``I'll do what I've been
doing for years,'' Jordan said. ``I'll ride the shuttle or, when
the weather's bad, I'll take the train.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lazard, a firm that is in the midst of a sweeping
reorganization, Jordan will be expected to use his contacts with
corporate chief executives to help rebuild the firm's stature as a
leading adviser on corporate mergers and acquisitions. In June,
after a series of high-level defections from Lazard's New York
office, the firm's chairman, Michel David-Weill, announced that, by
the end of the year, the firm would integrate its operations in New
York, Paris and London into a single, global unit.
</P>
<P>
   In looking for a partner with a platinum Rolodex, Lazard could
hardly have done better than landing Jordan, said Stephen Hess, a
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution. ``He's a hell of a
rainmaker,'' Hess said of Jordan. ``I can only assume that he's
going to make more money and have more fun, not that he hasn't been
making a lot of money and having a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess said Jordan long ago stopped practicing law and became a
trusted adviser to politicians and corporate leaders. He fell into
``an old tradition in Washington of people who can carry messages
because they have built respect for their word,'' Hess said. ``They
build trust in what they do by getting the message straight and
being good negotiators. In the sort of interactions he has, it
probably doesn't make much difference whether he's a partner in a
law firm or an investment banker.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been a fixture in the Washington establishment since
he joined Akin, Gump in 1982. In many ways, he modeled his legal
career on the firm's patriarch and senior partner, Robert S.
Strauss. Strauss, a titan in the Democratic Party, also served as a
confidant to Republicans, including former Senate Majority Leader
Bob Dole and former President George Bush, in whose administration
he served as ambassador to the Soviet Union and the Russian
Republic. When Strauss left for Moscow, he looked to Jordan to
carry on the firm's tradition as a legal and political powerhouse
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Like Strauss, who rejoined the firm after his sojourn in Moscow,
Jordan eschewed lobbying, preferring to quietly counsel a stable of
corporations on how to craft their legislative strategies rather
than going to Capitol Hill to plead their causes. That work was
left to more junior lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan became embroiled in the Lewinsky scandal, Strauss
and other figures in the Washington establishment defended Jordan.
In a televised interview on the CBS News program ``60 Minutes,''
Strauss said, ``Vernon isn't a man who does things that he knows to
be either conceivably illegal or improper. He doesn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was also the bridge between Bill and Hillary Clinton and
the Washington establishment, a bridge that has grown more fragile
over time. In 1991, he took them to the Jockey Club, once a
favorite haunt of Nancy Reagan, to have dinner with Thomas S.
Foley, then speaker of the House (and later ambassador to Japan)
and the late Pamela Harriman, a formidable Democratic party
fund-raiser who became ambassador to France.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who you need to be having dinner with if you want to
run for president,'' Jordan told the Clintons. That same year, he
took Clinton to the Bilderberg conference in Germany, an exclusive
annual retreat for international businessmen and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did not name money as a motivating factor for his
decision to join Lazard. People who know him estimate that he earns
considerably more than $1 million a year at Akin, Gump. But that is
far less than a partner at an investment bank like Lazard can earn.
People close to Lazard say that Jordan negotiated a handsome,
guaranteed income in meetings with David-Weill.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has stirred up some controversy by holding seats on the
boards of a large number of public corporations, a practice he said
he would not necessarily change after he joins Lazard. He sits on
10 corporate boards, including those of the American Express Co.,
the Revlon Group, the Xerox Corp. and Dow Jones &AMP; Co. He is also a
member of the international advisory council of automaker
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bankers once were fixtures in corporate boardrooms,
but that has changed. Now most chief executives are concerned that
having an active investment banker as a director could create the
appearance of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the possibility of a conflict, but I've dealt with
conflicts before,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also intends to remain politically active. He has
helped rally support for Jon S. Corzine's Senate campaign in New
Jersey and called Corzine, the former chairman of the investment
bank Goldman Sachs Group, a rival of Lazard, a ``very good
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the idea of becoming an investment banker was
broached by William Loomis, Lazard's chief executive in New York,
who approached him. He said he did not consider joining any other
firm on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   He is the latest of a group of people with ties to the Clinton
administration to make the leap into the financial world. Rahm
Emanuel, a Clinton adviser, joined Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co., a New
York-based boutique investment bank in Chicago earlier this year.
Erskine Bowles, a former chief of staff in the Clinton White House,
returned to investment banking last year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Loomis said that Jordan would be the 10th partner Lazard has
added since June. He said Jordan would be a senior partner ``by
virtue of how he is.'' But Jordan will not have a management role
at the firm and will not immediately be in line to run the firm or
its New York operation, people inside the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vernon Jordan epitomizes the people we are looking for,''
David-Weill said. ``We want people who are strong individuals.
That's the way this firm functions.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm has been trying to add influential people since losing
some of its best-connected senior partners, including Felix G.
Rohatyn, who is now U.S. Ambassador to France, and Kenneth Wilson,
who joined Goldman Sachs as a partner. Steven Rattner, who stepped
down as chief executive of Lazard in New York earlier this year,
plans to leave the firm in 2000, people inside the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's ranking among advisers in mergers and acquisitions
worldwide fell to 13th last year from fourth in 1997, according to
Thomson Financial Securities Data. This year, with a wave of
mergers in Europe, Lazard has rebounded to rank ninth among
advisers in announced deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
