<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GERMANY-KOHL-2NDLD-WR     11-30 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GERMAN CHANCELLOR ADMITS TO USE OF SECRET PARTY FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT dollar sum accepted by former treasurer
to $670,000, or 1 million marks.) 
 (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The former German chancellor, Helmut Kohl,
who has been facing widening accusations of having run illegal
political slush funds, admitted Tuesday that he had used cash from
secret bank accounts to help local branches of his party, the
Christian Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's admission aggravated a nationwide uproar that began three
weeks ago, after disclosures that the party's former treasurer
secretly accepted 1 million marks, about $670,000 at the time, from
an arms merchant in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, prosecutors have turned up evidence that Kohl's
party maintained numerous secret bank accounts that may have been
used to accept illegal political contributions from business
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl engineered the reunification of Germany and reigned as
chancellor for 16 years before losing an election last year. Until
Tuesday, he had dismissed all the allegations as ``a lot of noise
about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of his own former colleagues have gone public with
their own allegations in the last few days. Heiner Geissler, who
was general secretary of the Christian Democratic Union from 1977
until 1989, said on Monday that he had repeatedly argued with Kohl
about the secret accounts and that the former chancellor knew
everything about them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Christian Democratic leaders acknowledged that there
may indeed have been improper financial dealings and that these may
have persisted until as recently as a year ago. There have been no
allegations so far that individual political leaders enriched
themselves. The main question is whether the party has been selling
influence.
</P>
<P>
   In an uncharacteristically contrite written statement, Kohl
admitted that he had used secret accounts to provide financial
support for local party branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have, as chairman of the party, deemed as necessary the
confidential treatment of certain issues, such as special payments
to party branches and associations,'' Kohl said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl said it was reasonable to describe the secret accounts as
having been ``managed separately'' from those of the party's normal
federal treasury. He said he regretted that he may have allowed a
``lack of transparency'' in party finances and perhaps even a
violation of the party's own rules. ``That is not what I wanted,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are investigating what appears to be a network of
accounts. The parliament plans to establish a special investigative
committee on Thursday. And the Christian Democratic Union has
itself hired the accounting firm of Ernst &AMP; Young to examine its
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that not all the party rules were adhered to,''
said Wolfgang Schauble, Kohl's successor as chairman of the
Christian Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``No one enriched themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation could lead to criminal charges against some
Christian Democratic officials. Under German law, political parties
are required to disclose publicly all contributions and their
sources. Prosecutors are also investigating whether people who
either accepted or channeled covert contributions evaded taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging allegation _ but also the most difficult to
prove _ is that Kohl and other party leaders sold favors for large
sums of money.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the spreading revelations threaten to tarnish
Kohl's reputation as the statesman who reunified Germany and was
Europe's most formidable political leader throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   They will also deal a major political blow to the Christian
Democrats, who were just beginning to recover from their
devastating electoral defeat last year to the Social Democratic
Party of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first allegations surfaced in early November as a result of
a long-running investigation into tax evasion by Walther Leisler
Kiep, who served as the Christian Democrats' treasurer for many
years, until 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Tax investigators charged that Kiep had failed to pay taxes
after receiving 1 million marks from an arms trader, Karlheinz
Schreiber. At the time, Schreiber was trying to get government
approval for the sale of tanks to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber, whom the German authorities are trying to extradite
from Canada, reportedly handed Kiep a suitcase filled with cash.
Kiep admitted receiving the money but insisted that he had merely
put it in a special party-controlled bank account.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with the Frankfurter Allgemeine newspaper,
Kiep said he knew Schreiber ``wanted to do something good for the
party'' but had no idea that 1 million marks would be handed over.
</P>
<P>
   The German government approved the sale of the tanks, and the
investigation focuses on whether there was a quid pro quo. Party
officials say, though, that the sale was logical because Germany
was not sending troops to the Persian Gulf during the military
campaign against Iraq, and the sale of tanks was a way to provide
support.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have now uncovered a number of other unofficial bank
accounts that also appear to have been means for receiving a wide
variety of political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Schauble, the Christian Democrats' current chairman, said
Tuesday that there appear to have been a number of other unofficial
accounts during the 1990s. The last was shut down at the end of
1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such accounts are not in themselves illegal, nor are large
political contributions. The legal issue is whether the
contributions were properly reported and whether the money was used
to buy influence.
</P>
<P>
   Geissler, the party's longtime general secretary, has alleged
that Kohl used the accounts to buy the political loyalty of local
and regional party officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Geissler, an acerbic and cerebral politician who is almost a
mirror opposite of the backslapping Kohl, has been a sworn enemy of
the former chancellor for years now.
</P>
<P>
   For Germany's governing Social Democrats and for Schroeder, the
swirl of new charges are a welcome relief from their own recent
troubles. The Social Democrats have been battered in a series of
regional elections from the Rhineland to Berlin to Hesse, the state
that contains Frankfurt and Germany's main financial center.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Struck, a Social Democratic Party leader in parliament,
said allegations will be pursued wherever they may lead. ``The
investigating committee will have to determine whether there was
influence exerted on the decisions of the federal government,'' he
said Tuesday. ``One can't simply believe what Kohl says.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
