<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-BANKS-ART-NYT &LR;      11-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BANKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFITABLE CANADIAN BANKS MAKE PLANS FOR CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada's biggest banks are reporting record total
profits, while laying out plans to cut jobs and branches to further
increase their rates of return. In a country where banks dominate
the corporate landscape and are already a focus of consumer
discontent, advocacy groups are saying that fatter profits probably
mean people will pay more for less service.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide branch networks have been the backbone of Canada's
financial sector for decades. But with the growth of electronic
banking and a range of new money-management services, having a
branch on the main street corners of most cities and towns is
outdated and costly, said Jamie Keating, a banking analyst at
Merrill Lynch Canada Inc. in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has one-third more bank branches in relation to its
population than does the United States. The banks are now closing
hundreds of traditional branches and trimming as many as 15,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, four of Canada's largest banks proposed merging into
two much bigger ones. Mergers were needed, the banks told
governments and their customers, to help them compete with the
global giants. But the mergers would also have made it relatively
easy to close up to a fifth of Canada's 13,000 branches.
</P>
<P>
   When Canadian Finance Minister Paul Martin blocked the mergers,
the bankers devised alternative plans. If the cost-cutting measures
seem severe, it is largely because revenue growth is beginning to
slow, said Kevin Choquette, a banking analyst at Scotia Capital
Markets in Toronto. And faced with slower growth and more foreign
competitors at home, expansion outside Canada is a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Never have Canada's big banks been in better shape for ambitious
undertakings. Toronto Dominion, Canada's fifth-largest bank, is now
the country's most profitable bank and growing in size. Toronto
Dominion has been allowed to buy Canada Trust, which will move it
up to third place, measured by assets.. But 5,000 jobs will be lost
as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Bank of Canada, the nation's second-largest bank, provides
the best example of how Canadian banks are adjusting their
priorities. Its profit of 1.7 billion Canadian dollars, or $1.1
billion, for fiscal 1999 yielded a 15.3 percent return on equity,
which is good but not considered good enough by its management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to take over $400 million of costs out of our base
over the next year,'' said chairman John Cleghorn. A prime
objective is a 17 to 20 percent return on equity. The bank plans to
cut up to 4,000 jobs over the next year and 2,000 more a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Montreal, the fourth-largest bank, reported a record
profit of 1.4 billion Canadian dollars, or $952 million, for fiscal
1999, but it is planning to cut 1,500 jobs and 10 percent of its
1,040 branches. Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, the biggest,
has not yet released 1999 results but plans to cut annual operating
costs by 500 million Canadian dollars. That could mean at least
2,000 fewer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Nova Scotia, which Tuesday reported an 11.5 percent
gain in fiscal 1999 earnings, to 1.55 billion Canadian dollars, or
about $1 billion, has not announced any layoffs but has said it
will cut costs by 100 million dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
   Returns on equity among Canadian banks, while high, are roughly
two percentage points lower than the 17 to 19 percent achieved by
many banks in the United States. Raising returns to retain favor
among investors, the bankers admit, will mean they will no longer
try to provide all services to all customers.
</P>
<P>
   Trimming costs and services is one route to higher returns, but
consumers and small-business groups also fear that banking fees,
which are lower than in the United States, will go up. ``The banks
are making more money by withdrawing full service rather than
serving their customers well,'' said Duff Conacher, chairman of a
Toronto-based coalition of labor and consumer groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
