<SLUG> BC-TRUE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE NORTH WILL ACQUIRE STEIN ROGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An agency company that was early to explore
cyberspace is expanding again in the fast-growing realm of digital
communications, acquiring a New York shop specializing in online
and offline advertising for dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   True North Communications in Chicago, the world's No. 7 agency
company with estimated billings of $12 billion, is buying Stein
Rogan &AMP; Partners in New York, which has estimated capitalized
billings of $75 million from clients like Apartment.com,
Blackboard.com, Cars.com, Flycast, Mail.com and FasTV.com.
</P>
<P>
   Stein Rogan, with 70 employees, will operate as an autonomous
unit of True North, which also owns traditional agencies like FCB
Worldwide, Bozell and Temerlin McClain. The top managers of Stein
Rogan, which also has a small office in Chicago, will continue
leading the agency. They include Tom Stein, president, and Mark
Rogan, executive vice president and creative director.
</P>
<P>
   The deal for Stein Rogan, which started in 1986 as Stein
Kilpatrick &AMP; Rogan, is indicative of the intensification of efforts
by Madison Avenue to meet the challenges posed as the Internet
remakes advertising, marketing and the media, particularly in
competing against upstart startups.
</P>
<P>
   Giants like True North, the Omnicom Group, the Interpublic Group
of Companies and the WPP Group are responding with strategies that
range from acquisitions to investments in independent new-media
shops to opening digital units within their traditional agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omnicom probably has the largest list of dot-com clients,''
said Michael J. Russell, an analyst who follows the advertising
industry for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in New York, ``but Bozell
has Datek and FCB has Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Omnicom and True North lead among the biggest agency companies
in estimated revenue to be derived from dot-coms in 2000, by
Russell's estimates, at about 3 percent of the total, compared with
about 1 percent for the others.
</P>
<P>
   The mad dash to capitalize on the dot-coms is not limited to
agencies. For instance, NBC, part of General Electric, is combining
several of its online operations with the portal Web site Snap.com
and Xoom.com, an electronic commerce company. The combined company,
named NBCi, began trading Tuesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   The True North cyberholdings include R/GA Interactive and 50
percent of Modem Media.Poppe Tyson, the digital agency that began
as two interactive units of FCB and Bozell before being combined
and eventually sold in an initial public offering. And DoubleClick,
the giant Web ad network, started in 1995 as the Internet sales
group of Poppe Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the explosion of e-commerce companies seeking to brand
themselves online and offline, it's obvious not every one is going
to win,'' said David Bell, chairman and chief executive at True
North. ``Tom and Mark are experts in placing their chips on those
that are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell discussed the acquisition in an interview Tuesday; the
formal announcement is to be made Wednesday. Terms of the deal are
not being disclosed, though recently agency acquisitions are being
made for prices equal to about one year's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Stein Rogan's 1998 revenue was $12 million and its revenue for
the first six months of 1999 was $11 million, according to
estimates by IQ Interactive News, a weekly supplement to the trade
publications Adweek, Brandweek and Mediaweek. The 1999 figure
placed the agency 24th among the top 50 interactive agencies ranked
by the supplement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to move on to bigger and better things,'' said
Stein, 43, ``and True North is going to help us get there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd started out as a general advertising agency but took
those capabilities and focused ourselves in 1995 as `the
information agency, using interactive media as a marketing venue,''
he added. ``We saw an opportunity that today involves building
brands in the Internet space in entertainment, education, finance,
e-business of all sorts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's going to be a tremendous continuing intensity of
activity in that space,'' Stein predicted. ``There will be not just
a lot of dot-com advertising on the Super Bowl, but all through the
first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exaggerating a little bit to say one or two business
models come across our desks every day,'' he added, ``and every one
we see is ramping up for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, 44, echoed his colleague's optimism, but noted that the
growing popularity of the Internet brings more dot-com campaigns,
which makes it increasingly difficult ``to break through the
clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So what you do for dot-com brands has to be done a lot
smarter,'' he added, ``and in Internet time.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he cited the work Stein Rogan has produced for
Cars.com, an automotive Web site operated by Classified Ventures, a
consortium of large newspaper companies. The campaign sought to
balance the needs of car shoppers with the needs of car dealers,
who are the site's primary revenue source.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to build a value proposition for Cars.com with
consumers,'' Stein said, ``but at the same time not alienate
dealers, who pay the freight.'' So rather than proceed with a
campaign carrying the theme ``Drive home a better deal,'' the
Cars.com ads carry this theme: ``Car shopping the way it should be.
Simple.''
</P>
<P>
   And the offline ads for Cars.com, on television and in
newspapers, ``have the look and feel of the Web site,'' Rogan said,
by including ``a lot of screen shots'' and even ``duplicating the
browser frame'' computer users see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creatives fight that,'' he added, ``saying, `People know
they're going on the Web.' But there's nothing wrong with a product
demonstration.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-30 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEADERSHIP, NOT RIDICULE, IS THE KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Nets coach Don Casey stood in an empty
Continental Arena on Tuesday afternoon after a pregame
shoot-around. He spoke about wide-ranging, far-reaching subjects _
everything from Robert De Niro and James Dean, to playing hurt
versus playing it safe, to Keyshawn Johnson and Stephon Marbury, to
the difference between venting in frustration and providing
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Casey, whose Nets had won only two games
this season while losing 12, received a rare piece of good news
when the team doctor cleared Kerry Kittles to play. The lithe guard
had virtually missed the whole season thus far with a surgically
repaired knee that left him uncomfortable. But last night he was in
the starting lineup against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles was cleared to play early in the season but felt
weakness in the knee and decided to sit out until it become
stronger. So he sat and watched as his team sunk deeper. He played
only once _ a game in mid-November in which he scored 3 points in
seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cage, the Nets' 16-year National Basketball Association
veteran, admitted that he wondered what was going on with his young
teammate, but kept silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play with pain every day: sore back, sore knee, sore
ankle,'' the 37-year-old Cage said. ``That's just the nature of the
game. I went from injured reserve to the starting lineup the other
day. But that's me; I'm from the old school. We're in a different
age now.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey is an old-school coach with new-school sensibilities.
Admiring a player's fierce desire to play, but respecting a
player's instinct to preserve his body. Coveting the warrior but
respecting prudence.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a selfish viewpoint, I'd rather have seen him out here
two or three weeks ago,'' Casey said of Kittles. ``But you have to
be aware of a player's mind-set and his threshold. But that
argument of old school versus new school is there and you can't get
away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant coach with the Boston Celtics, Casey remembered
how Larry Bird could not sit in a chair during timeouts because his
back was so bad. He recalled Michael Jordan scoring 63 points with
a hairline fracture in his foot. But Tuesday, Casey was more
perplexed by Keith Van Horn's early departure from the
shoot-around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed,'' a frustrated Casey said. ``I
heard he just bolted out.''
</P>
<P>
   But frustration has splattered all over the New York sports
scene lately with a force that has caught many of us by surprise.
New York teams had a great run for much of 1999: the Jets in the
American Football Conference title game, the Knicks in the NBA
finals, the Mets in October, the Yankees winning the World Series.
We forgot how miserable losing can be. Now it's coming back.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jets' slim playoff hopes disintegrated Sunday,
Keyshawn Johnson, the team's star receiver, blasted unnamed members
of his team for accepting losing. The Nets' Stephon Marbury has
ridiculed his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has refused to yield an inch to his fellow receiver,
Wayne Chrebet, feeling, perhaps with good reason, that Chrebet from
the beginning of his career was eagerly accorded stature and
respect that has only grudgingly been given to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury has been equally hard on Van Horn, who was hailed as the
next Larry Bird before he even took a shot. Van Horn lost a
security blanket when Jayson Williams was sidelined with a broken
leg. The hard-nosed Marbury is not inclined to lend a sympathetic
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the player's respective coach _ Parcells with the
Jets and Casey with the Nets _ has walked a thin line between
keeping his star's fires burning and getting him to be less
searing. Johnson is a key symbol of the Jets' renaissance; if the
Nets ever have a renaissance, Marbury will be its author.
</P>
<P>
   Casey is shepherding Marbury through the pastures of a difficult
season, a season the coach may not survive. Casey is showing
Marbury that criticism, like the game of basketball, has more than
one dimension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird would pass a guy who was leaving practice early,''
Casey recalled. ``He'd say, `You must be shooting 50 percent.' You
don't want to extinguish passion, just rechannel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury has an entire season before him. The Nets have talent;
Marbury has to bring it out. ``He realizes now that he has to use
his talents more to make teammates better, and not by asking, `Why
aren't you making that shot?''' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Wilson offered a perspective on leadership at the
beginning of the century that Marbury and Johnson might consider at
the end. ``One cool judgment is worth a thousand hasty counsels,''
Wilson said. ``The thing to do is supply light and not heat.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
