<HEADER>
A5629 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i BC-MEXICO-SCENE-TEX     11-30 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNT FOR GRAVES DISRUPTS QUIET DESERT COUNTRYSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: One ``c'' in Rebeca in byline is cq.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By REBECA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico _ Brenda Balandran clutched her infant son
and stared at the masked men in black with rifles dangling at their
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard to believe,'' she said. ``Imagine all this going
on in such a peaceful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Balandran, who lives in Juarez, was one of many stunned by
reports that Mexican and U.S. authorities were searching for a mass
grave on a ranch south of the city. Based on an informant's tip,
officials suspect several ranches near Juarez may be the burial
site of scores of bodies, possibly victims of drug-related
violence.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continued on Tuesday, the tranquility of
the Chihuahuan Desert landscape was broken by swarms of Mexican
federal agents patrolling the area around the ranch where heavy
equipment was being used to search for bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, a steady stream of trucks and buses passed
on the two-lane highway in front of the ranch, known as Club
Cazadores de Juarez. Children in school buses waved and smiled,
while whole families pulled their cars to the roadside and watched
for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Balandran, 21, was making her weekly visit to see family in the
country when she came upon the scene. She said she expects things
like this in the city, but not in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Juarez, you can't go out at night any more and drugs are
everywhere,'' she said. ``We just stay inside after dark, but here
we're out in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the search for bodies did not shock everyone, however.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Magallanes stood on a pile of rocks and watched the frenzy
from the auto parts yard where he works across the street from the
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that surprised,'' said Magallanes, 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the drug capital of the border. The stuff comes
straight from Colombia through here and then to the United
States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Magallanes lives and works only feet from the ranch's
iron gates that were heavily guarded on Tuesday, he said he is not
afraid and does not own a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many poor people in the campo,'' he said. ``Many of
them work on these ranches and I don't fear them.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of their agriculture products store just yards from the
ranch entrance, Cruz Martinez Gamboa and Jesus Cruz Pinon shielded
their eyes from the bright sun as black government helicopters
swooped down over the desert. For them, the massive investigation
was a stark contrast to the usually peaceful life in the rolling
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live right here and I've never seen anything suspicious,''
Martinez Gamboa said. ``Life here is pretty simple and we don't get
a lot of action.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez Gamboa said that although she has lived in the area for
nearly a year, after moving from the Mexican state of Durango, she
has never met the family who lived and worked on the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep to myself, don't go out much, and I don't have
electricity for a television set,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the setting sun cast flares of soft color across the sky,
Magallanes continued watching from his perch as news media camped
out in front of the ranch gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the media being here is good,'' he said. ``The world
has to know what goes on out here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
