<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC--UCLA-LADN     11-30 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HURT UCLA IN '99 COULD BOLSTER IT IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What was a curse now becomes a blessing for UCLA's
reeling, beaten football team.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 season, framed by injuries and the handicapped-parking
scandal, was a three-month test of resolve. But the Bruins didn't
have enough upperclassmen to face the challenge alone. Instead,
they trotted out freshmen and sophomores and asked them to play
like veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The results were predictable: inconsistency, doubt,
disappointment and the program's worst record (4-7) in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But when those same players report for spring practice in April,
and for training camp in August, they'll be a year wiser and, the
coaches hope, a year better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be young and inexperienced, and I'm looking forward
to that,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said a few days after the loss to
USC.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the depth chart will ooze sophomores and juniors _
players with enough experience to hold leads, win close games and
win on the road, something the '99 Bruins didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   The depth chart will ooze players who should, in theory, know
their assignments so well they don't think, they simply react. Time
and again, the '99 Bruins wasted precious seconds analyzing, not
attacking.
</P>
<P>
   The depth chart will ooze players who should, in theory, be
strengthened by the failures of '99. It can't get much worse than
the 48-point loss at Oregon State, the shutout against Cal, or the
loss to USC that ended the Bruins' eight-game city series winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Will a veteran lineup translate into a Pac-10 title or top-10
ranking? It's too early to tell _ nine months too early. The answer
should come Sept. 2, when Alabama visits the Rose Bowl. If not,
then certainly two weeks later, when Michigan arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Given reasonable talent and myriad returnees, the natural
progression from 4-7 is probably 7-4, maybe 8-3. But nine wins
seems a bit much for the Bruins next season, considering their
schedule and unanswered personnel questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Will the injured/suspended players be ready?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins played most of '99 without two of their top players:
receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (broken wrist) and cornerback Jason Bell
(post-surgical pain in his heel). In addition, receiver Freddie
Mitchell was a step slow (preseason cartilage damage in his knee),
and cornerback Marques Anderson was suspended from school for the
fall quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bruins to thrive next year, Mitchell and Poli-Dixon must
make big plays, Bell and Anderson must prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   _A quarter (back) for your thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   Cory Paus and Ryan McCann, both sophomores-to-be, will compete
for the starting quarterback job in spring practice. Chances are,
Toledo won't name a starter until August, forcing both to work hard
through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The season could hinge on the outcome. If McCann's the winner,
is he destined to repeat Paus' mistakes? After all, McCann started
one game and threw just 63 passes, which means he'll be more a
freshman than a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll be a little beyond that,'' Toledo said. ``He's
been in the program two years, and he's seen some game action.''
</P>
<P>
   _Line them up and turn them loose?
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line is loaded with prep All-Americans who
probably will form a superb college line one day. But which day?
The Bruins had so many breakdowns in '99 it's hard to imagine them
without glitches next season.
</P>
<P>
   The difference could be dependency. In '99, with a rookie
quarterback and injuries to Poli-Dixon, Mitchell, Danny Farmer and
DeShaun Foster, the Bruins didn't have enough playmakers to
compensate for the young line.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, if Foster, Mitchell and Poli-Dixon are healthy, there
won't be as much pressure on the line to make every block and
execute every assignment. It'll be older and have more margin for
error.
</P>
<P>
   _Will the secondary become primary?
</P>
<P>
   With second-team all-conference end Kenyon Coleman and gifted
linebacker Robert Thomas, the Bruins have the makings of a solid
front seven. But without improvement from the porous secondary, the
linemen and linebackers won't have much chance to show their stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Anderson and Bell will help tremendously, and
don't be surprised if Anderson moves to safety to accommodate
talented freshman cornerback Ricky Manning Jr. That leaves Lovell
Houston, Jason Stephens and Audie Attar to fill the remaining
safety spot. If someone emerges, the secondary should be solid.
</P>
<P>
   So that's it. Four concerns for spring practice, and one
question for next season:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be better in the fall,'' Toledo said, ``but whether
we're ready to take a giant step, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
