<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ABUSE-RECORDS-KAN &LR;      11-30 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-RECORDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI BILL WOULD OPEN CHILD-ABUSE RECORDS TO REPORTERS,
CAREGIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE and WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A bill to be introduced Wednesday in the
Missouri General Assembly would, for the first time, provide
limited public access to state child-abuse records and would allow
lawsuits against the Division of Family Services when workers are
found negligent in cases where children have died or been seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Wiggins, a Kansas City Democrat, plans to submit the
bill in Jefferson City on Wednesday, the opening filing day for the
2000 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was drafted in response to the October deaths of Larry
and Gary Bass. The 8-year-old Kansas City brothers died from
starvation and infected burns, even though teachers for years had
reported the children's plight to the state's child-abuse hot line.
Just two months before the boys died, a relative also called the
hot line.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Division of Family Services workers were
suspended 20 days for failing to properly do their jobs after the
final hot-line call. The boys' mother, Mary Bass, 31, faces charges
of second-degree murder and child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with the torture and murder of two innocent
8-year-old boys,'' Wiggins said. ``We are trying to stop that from
happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   He said more deaths might be prevented if child-abuse workers
know that news media have access to investigation records. Wiggins
plans to ask Gov. Mel Carnahan today to release the Bass records to
the media immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Division of Family Services staff members, he said, ``are
working at public expense, and taxpayers are paying their salaries.
I don't see why they should be so afraid of letting the press and
public know what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders expect child abuse to be a key topic at the
2000 session. And Wiggins' bill may not be the only one addressing
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan on Thursday is expected to announce 30 policy and
legislative recommendations from Missouri's Child Fatality Task
Force, which the governor appointed last year. The task force
deliberated three months before drafting its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stangler, the director of the Missouri Department of Social
Services, deferred comment on Wiggins' bill until he saw Carnahan's
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri law now makes it a misdemeanor to release child-abuse
investigation reports to unauthorized people. The law is designed
to protect families and children named in reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of Family Services has cited the law in refusing to
release the Bass records. Critics complain that the law allows the
division to hide internal problems.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 states have relaxed child-abuse confidentiality laws in
recent years, though not as far as Wiggins proposes. Most of those
states allow records to be opened after abused children have died
and have no surviving siblings. In Missouri, the Jackson County
prosecutor's office supports opening child-abuse records after
children's deaths. Stangler previously said he favors such a
change, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins' bill would do more. It would give the media access to
files after the Division of Family Services has found that abuse
occurred and entered the record into a central registry. There is
no threshold on the seriousness of the abuse and no waiting until
children die. The media would have to know a child's name to
request his or her file.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Wiggins' bill also would expand access to schools,
day-care centers, foster parents and others who supervise or have
custody of children. Caregivers and teachers then would know what
has happened to children and would be better able to watch for
subsequent signs of abuse, Wiggins said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one advocate for children disagrees with releasing the
full report to schools or day-care centers. It would be more
helpful if the Division of Family Services shared key information
with those people and enlisted their support in monitoring
children, said Linda Spears, child protection director for the
Child Welfare League of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just having the (record) information does not help you do
anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two states, Florida and Washington, allow caseworkers
to be sued if children die and the workers are found negligent,
Spears said. In most states, including Missouri and Kansas, workers
are protected against such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins' bill would allow lawsuits when a child's situation had
been reported at least twice to the state, the child then dies or
is seriously injured, and ``negligent supervision'' of Division of
Family Services workers is found to have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leader Delbert Scott of Lowry City criticized
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are never going to stop crazy people from doing awful
things,'' Scott said, adding the state should ``look to the person
responsible for causing the deaths and be unmerciful'' in holding
them accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Making Division of Family Services workers legally liable for
deaths or injuries would make it difficult to fill those jobs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't work in a situation like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins plans to start seeking co-sponsors for his bill today
and expects to find broad support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing bad that can come out of this, only good,''
said Democratic Rep. Henry Rizzo of Kansas City, who will sponsor
Wiggins' bill in the House. ``I don't think anybody with a
reasonable mind will object to the light being shone on this.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat who has sponsored
key child-care bills in recent years, endorses greater access to
Division of Family Services records. Those records are shrouded far
too often now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are going to be a lot of hard questions asked
during the legislative session about the case in Kansas City,'' he
said. ``It will be one of the priorities as far as I am
concerned....The key is at what point in time the case is
substantiated and how much of that information should be
released.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaw said he was unsure whether efforts to loosen legal
protection when children die or suffer serious injury would be
approved. He noted that a bill that raised the state's legal
liability limits this year won approval despite the controversy it
created.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tem Ed Quick, a Liberty Democrat, said
allowing the state to be sued in cases where a child dies or
suffers serious injury ``might happen'' but the issue would trigger
extensive debate.
</P>
<P>
   Quick said that opening Division of Family Services
investigative records was ``a very touchy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be so careful with those records that you
don't put out something publicly that shouldn't be put out,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
