<HEADLINE>
RESTORATION OF KANSAS CAPITOL IN EARLY STAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ These days at the Capitol, it is common to spot
workers dangling from ropes from the dome, standing on scaffolding
in the Senate chamber or crouched in the building's elevator
shafts.
</P>
<P>
   They are all part of the early stages of what is expected to be
an extensive restoration program for the 96-year-old French
Renaissance building, the seat of Kansas government.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the craftsmen in recent weeks has been a cadre of
architects, preservationists and system specialists. They have been
examining every detail of the building, work that eventually will
lead to creation of a historic- structure report.
</P>
<P>
   That document, to be completed in March, will provide guidelines
for restoring the limestone Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers led by Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park
Republican who is chairman of the Capitol Restoration Commission,
are beginning to explore sources of money to support the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's going to cost, but it's going to be
big,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is to use part of the $70 million the state is
holding in its the unclaimed property account, money that Kansans
have lost track of. Interest earned on the money also could be used
to finance a bond issue.
</P>
<P>
   A $45 million bond issue could be supported by draining off $4
million a year from the account over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Groth, the Capitol architect, said it was difficult to come
up with accurate cost estimates, particularly when no one knew for
sure just what would be found once major renovations began.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's dollars, and not knowing exactly what we will be
doing: $80 million,'' Groth estimated. ``It could be less; it could
be more.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar Capitol projects are in various stages of completion
across the country and with widely varying costs. For example:
Texas, $180 million; Iowa, $59.5 million; Idaho, $40 million to $50
million; and Ohio, $112 million.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Tim Shallenburger, the former House speaker who
was an early supporter of revamping the neglected Capitol, told
lawmakers that it was time to get on with the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to fix the roof is when it leaks, not when there's
money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
