<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEAVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAID LEAVE FOR NEW PARENTS TOPS ISSUES IN CLINTON SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton announced new rules Tuesday to
allow states to offer paid leave to new parents and marked the
anniversary of a landmark gun-control measure by urging Congress to
do more.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tackled several domestic issues before flying to Seattle
for the contentious World Trade Organization session.
</P>
<P>
   The president first flew to San Francisco where he helped
Democrats raise campaign contributions and later to Los Angeles
where he helped raise money for the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence and the Southwest Voter Registration Education Project.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Washington, the president said he had signed an
executive order that would allow states to use unemployment
insurance to provide paid leave to new parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this act, the United States joins the rest of the world's
advanced economies, all of whom already have some form of paid
leave for parents,'' Clinton said, surrounded by parents and
children in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the program would be voluntary for states.
</P>
<P>
   ``State flexibility and the voluntary nature of this effort are
key to its success,'' Clinton said. ``In our strong economy, we
hope states will take advantage of this new option, and we believe
those that do will balance this new benefit with the imperative of
maintaining a fiscally sound unemployment insurance program.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during his first year in office, sponsored legislation
providing up to one-year unpaid leave for employees with ailing
family members or new children. The president said an estimated 20
million people have taken up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave to be with
newborns or sick relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the current law meets just a fraction of the need. And the
number one reason families give for not taking advantage of Family
and Medical Leave is that they simply can't afford to take time off
without a paycheck,'' Clinton said. ``The actions we take today
will go a long way toward alleviating that burden if the states
take up the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Clinton also marked the sixth anniversary of the
passage of the Brady Law, the measure named for former press
secretary James Brady who was injured during the 1981 assassination
attempt on Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also released new figures showing 160,000
people were barred from purchasing handguns under the instant
background check system that took affect a year ago. There were 8.7
million background checks in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on Congress to make passage of more gun-control
legislation the first priority when it returns in January.
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress failed to pass ``common sense measures'' such
as extending background checks to gun shows, banning juvenile
offenders from possessing guns when they turn 21, mandating child
safety locks be sold with every handgun and banning the importance
of high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced Treasury Secretary Larry Summers will
launch ``Online LEAD,'' a new crime fighting technology to help
trace weapons. The program will provide every Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms field office with instant access to 1 million
gun traces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
