<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MAYOR-HUSBAND-KAN &LR;      11-30 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-HUSBAND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSBAND OF KANSAS CITY'S MAYOR REGAINING STRENGTH AND SPIRIT AFTER
LATEST ROUND OF CHEMOTHERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A week ago Tuesday at the Chamber of
Commerce's annual dinner, Frank Barnes did what some people say he
does best: worked a room.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in what he calls his dark ``IBM'' suit and red power
tie, the husband of Kansas City's mayor pumped hands, made small
talk and laughed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty gregarious guy,'' Barnes said later. ``That guy
was back.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a comeback it was from just a few months ago when
Barnes, 74, was undergoing yet another round of chemotherapy for
the cancer that has ravaged him off and on since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   During his chemotherapy treatments this summer, he dropped 20
pounds, although he never lost his hair. At times, a constantly
fatigued Barnes was too weak to answer the door.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, a long time ago for a cancer survivor such as
Barnes, who strives to live one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Barnes was feeling good as he escorted his wife to
the Hyatt Regency ballroom and mingled with the likes of Missouri
Gov. Mel Carnahan and U.S. Sen. Kit Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can work a room,'' Barnes quipped, ``almost as good as she
can.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kay Barnes took office in April, she knew she would be
dealing with deteriorating bridges, budget woes and scads of
mayoral appointments.
</P>
<P>
   But then, on top of those demands, came news of the reoccurrence
of her husband's cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Barnes defeated George Blackwood to become the
city's first woman mayor, Frank Barnes received an ominous report
about suspicious bumps in his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   In early May came another jolt. A bone scan revealed three
cancerous ``hot spots'' in his hip and both arms. Radiation
treatment followed, as did rigorous weeks of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something positive. In August, scans showed shrinkage
in the tumors in his lungs and last month doctors said no new
lesions were forming in his liver and kidneys. His bones were
healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all very good news,'' Frank Barnes said recently, in
his first interview on his health. ``The doctor was ecstatic. I'm
feeling a lot like my old self.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I'm not out of the woods yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Barnes insists that her husband's roller-coaster medical
ride has had little effect on her work as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say this (illness) has not in my opinion
interfered with that,'' she said about her mayoral duties. ``Yes,
it is stressful. But Frank is the healthiest person I've ever known
emotionally. And so he is very straightforward and realistic about
what he's dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the same token, he lives day by day and is, by nature,
optimistic. So that mitigates the stress a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   She typically works full time during the workweek and at least
part of the day on Saturdays and Sundays. Barnes, 61, says she's
missed only two days since taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the mayor found that she had even more time for City
Hall work because her husband couldn't carry on an active social
life.
</P>
<P>
   By her count, in the fewer than 200 days she's been in office,
Barnes has met with more than 200 groups, nearly 300 individuals,
spoken at or participated in at least 200 events, and had 60-plus
meetings with the media.
</P>
<P>
   But she's made some concessions, such as sometimes leaving
evening banquets early so that she can be at home. Or skipping
out-of-town conferences, such as the June meeting of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Close associates agree that her husband's cancer has not had a
major effect on her mayoral performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you have a family illness, it has an
impact,'' said Mike Burke, a Kansas City lawyer and informal
adviser to the mayor. ``Is it of great concern? Obviously. Has it
had a visible impact on the way she conducts business at City Hall?
Not that I can detect.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said Barnes ``keeps herself on a pretty even keel and
doesn't show a lot of her emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   For Frank Barnes, life with cancer has meant an endless
succession of visits to doctors in Arizona, Missouri and
Massachusetts and a lingering sense of uncertainty. He's received
conflicting diagnoses. The best guess now is that he has melanoma,
an aggressive skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   His battle with the disease began shortly before he married the
former Kay Waldo. In 1988, Frank Barnes had a small lesion removed
from his stomach that turned out to be a rare form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Frank Barnes noticed a bump on the back of
his head, just under the hairline. A piece of his scalp was
removed. The diagnosis: A slow-growing sarcoma, a malignant tumor.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Barnes had a cancerous growth on his hip
removed. In June 1998, he noticed a new bump at the base of his
neck. The bump was removed, but not before doctors found that the
cancer had spread to lymph nodes in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   More surgeries followed, then radiation treatment, and more
surgery for new stomach lesions.
</P>
<P>
   Then came several months of relative calm as his wife battled
her way through the mayoral primary and ultimately, on March 30, an
easy win over Blackwood.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before March 30, Frank Barnes got the news about the
suspicious growths on his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Barnes said she realized a few years ago that she had to
choose between living her life in fear, or ``staying in the present
and literally taking it one day at a time, and living in that
day.'' She chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe,'' the mayor said of living with the
ever present knowledge of her husband's illness. ``But my
experience is that once you make that decision that you're going to
take it only a day at a time, it changes a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Being mayor allows Barnes to focus her energies in an outward
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's good for me, because otherwise I might be obsessing
in a way that would not be helpful to either Frank or me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't go with Frank Barnes to the doctor. He prefers to go
alone.
</P>
<P>
   He's comfortable dealing with doctors and arcane medical
terminology because of his background as an Abbott Labs
pharmaceutical executive. He retired in 1993 and continues to work
occasionally as a business consultant, linking upstart biotech
companies with partners to give the companies firmer financial
footing.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Barnes' energy is now returning. He's started to exercise
again. He's begun to make the social rounds with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   That's important to her. She ranks him as one of her closest
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made an investment in her campaign, and I haven't realized
any return on that investment at all,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   That, he added, is about to change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
