<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-CAVIL-HNS &LR;      11-30 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-CAVIL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ Kwame Cavil is an All-Big 12 football player, without
question the best receiver in the conference.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is so talented that teams have tried every type of coverage
imaginable to try to slow him, but few, if any, have worked.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil is also an All-Big Talker, without question the best in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing Cavil's gift of gab, opponents have also given their
best effort in trying to slow the junior's verbal assault with a
barrage of trash talk early in games.
</P>
<P>
   But they have found out that is like trying to outswim a fish.
By the fourth quarter, Cavil has usually worn 'em down.
</P>
<P>
   After a daylong tete-a-tete with Cavil, Oklahoma State defenders
were reduced to the weakest of all comebacks in linguistic warfare:
``Man, you talk too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, opponents do not get too upset at Cavil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing is you don't push anybody's button to where
they hate you,'' Cavil said. ``They know it's part of the game.
When you play basketball or any other sport off the field, you're
going to trash-talk. That's the competitive nature, the competitive
joy you get out of playing this game. But after the game,
everybody's cool. It's not like it's a hatred thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Cavil and Texas fans are concerned, it's a love
affair. Cavil, who broke the Texas single-season receptions mark
weeks ago, is poised to become the first Longhorn to haul in 100
catches in a season. The Waco native has a Big 12-record 95
receptions for 1,098 yards, which is also a school mark.
</P>
<P>
   With nine catches in Saturday's Big 12 Championship Game against
Nebraska (he averages almost eight per game), Cavil would set a
Texas career receptions record, surpassing Michael Adams' mark of
177 set from 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into the year wanting to set records,'' Cavil said.
``Those were goals of mine. One hundred receptions was a goal of
mine at the beginning of the season. I knew that if I had that type
of year, the team would do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Cavil may talk a lot, but he is just having fun playing the game
he loves, and opponents know it. Nebraska cornerback Ralph Brown,
who will face Cavil on Saturday, got a taste of what Cavil is like
when the Longhorns played the Cornhuskers on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Brown, who has been named to several All-America
squads this season, came in prepared for the confrontation with the
Longhorns' on-the-field spokesman. During the week of the game,
Brown's All-America cohort in the Cornhuskers' self-billed
``Secondary to None,'' rover Mike Brown, said everyone on the
defense would be prepared to answer Cavil with words of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the student of trash talk, Cavil said he had noticed in
Nebraska game film that Ralph Brown wore a mouthpiece. Not so
against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out there and didn't have one, so I knew he was going
to talk,'' Cavil said. ``I said, `You're not wearing a mouthpiece.
Is that any indication you're going to be talking to me the whole
game?' He said, `What do you think?'''
</P>
<P>
   As per his norm, Cavil got the last laugh, and word, against the
No. 3-rated pass defense in the country. He finished with eight
receptions for 84 yards and a touchdown in Texas' 24-20 win, the
third-ranked Cornhuskers' lone loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, Cavil accounted for all 58 yards in a
touchdown drive that gave the Longhorns their first lead of the
game. It took three plays.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil lined up wide right and gained 18 yards on a deep in
pattern, beating cornerback Keyuo Craver. Following the play, Cavil
put a finger to his mouth, giving the ``shhh'' signal to the
sophomore from Harleton.
</P>
<P>
   Cavil lined up on the right side again, went in motion and beat
Craver once more on a corner route for a 27-yard gain to the
13-yard line. Cavil then delivered a stoic ``you can't hold me''
stare to a jabbering Craver.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Cavil lined up on the left side of the formation against
Ralph Brown and Nebraska's man-to-man coverage. He darted straight
ahead, fought off a chuck at the 10 and sliced in front of Brown to
grab a strike from Major Applewhite for the touchdown. This time,
however, Cavil didn't say anything after the play. He didn't have
to. He did his talking before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I'm going to the end zone on this play, and I'm
going right past you.' I told him the play and everything,'' Cavil
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis may not want Cavil
sharing play information with defenders, but sometimes the
confident 6-2, 205-pounder can't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one thing I admire about him _ his confidence,'' said
UT receiver Ryan Nunez, who with 53 receptions for 569 yards this
season has combined with Cavil to form the school's all-time top
pass-catching duo in receptions and second-best tandem in yards.
``He knows no one can stop him, and by the end of the game, they
know it too.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' quarterbacks have confidence in Cavil as well.
</P>
<P>
   When Applewhite needs a completion, his first thought is to find
Cavil, because open or not, he'll likely make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman quarterback Chris Simms, who got his first start last
week against Texas A&AMP;M because Applewhite was ill, knew where to go
with the ball. Simms had eight completions in the first half
against the Aggies _ seven to Cavil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man,'' Simms said. ``He's great. You can't miss him.
You throw it high, throw it low, throw it too far, he's going to
catch it. I knew if I got it to him and got him into the game he
would make plays for me, too, and that's what I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Cavil was looking for from himself entering the
season. He said he was ``champin' at the bit'' to take a leadership
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to put it on (my) shoulders, blame me for it,''
Cavil said. ``It's not having to be second fiddle to anybody, a
chance to control your own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Cavil has indeed been second fiddle to none.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
