<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS &LR;      11-30 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Hardly a football game at any level of competition goes by without
at least a little trash-talking between opposing players.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kwame Cavil, an outstanding receiver from his first day at
Texas, is a junior academically. But it's alleged he could have
long ago earned a Ph.D. in talking smack.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska senior rover Mike Brown is among those who know
firsthand. Having played in the Cornhuskers' secondary for four
years, during which the Longhorns have beaten his team three
straight times, Brown has received more than an earful from Cavil
in the last two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to talk a lot,'' Brown said. ``It keeps you involved
in the game. It's a heated competition out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun just to ride up against receivers like him
because you know he's a great player. He's going to test your
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Cavil didn't have a big game statistically last year when
Texas rolled into Memorial Stadium in Lincoln, Major Applewhite
passed for 269 yards and two touchdowns en route to a 20-16 victory
that snapped Nebraska's 47-game home winning streak, then the
fifth-longest in NCAA history.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Cavil was on the receiving end of eight Applewhite
passes for 84 yards, including a third-quarter touchdown, as the
Longhorns beat the Cornhuskers 24-20 in Austin on Oct. 23. It
remains Nebraska's only loss of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Cavil will renew acquaintances Saturday at San
Antonio's Alamodome when the Cornhuskers, the Big 12's North
Division champions, and Longhorns, champions of the South, decide
the decade's final Big 12 football titlist.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet the farm that Brown comes away with singed earlobes,
regardless of the game's outcome. But the All-America candidate and
captain of Nebraska's last line of defense, who had a career-best
19 tackles during the Longhorns' win in 1998, apparently doesn't
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just stuff that goes on between football players all the
time,'' Brown said of his chats with Cavil. ``He's just one of
those guys who says, `You can't stop me,' things like that, normal
things anyone would say on the football field.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the edited version of Cavil's game-day
verbal grab bag.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Cornhuskers' long home winning streak had been
scissored last year, trash-talking gave way to sportsmanship that
had Cavil a little surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny, because they kind of congratulated us, shook our
hands and said, `Good game,''' Cavil remembers. ``But they had that
wink in their eye like, `We're going to come back at you next
year.' But it was just a special victory for us when we went down
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could play Nebraska every game, anyone would love to do
that, just because of being an athlete and the competitive nature
of the sport. They're a great team, and (Brown is) a great player.
You know they're going to come ready to play this Saturday, and you
just have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska posted a 33-30 overtime victory over archrival Colorado
in Boulder last Friday to finish the regular season 10-1 and ranked
No. 3 in the national polls. And though the Cornhuskers allowed the
Buffaloes to get back in the game with 24 fourth-quarter points,
Nebraska coach Frank Solich says this has been a season in which
Brown and the secondary have performed up to some very tall
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, sophomore free safety Dion Booker and cornerbacks Ralph
Brown, a senior (and no relation to Mike Brown) and Keyuo Craver, a
sophomore, were considered the strongest part of the team going
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great secondary for us throughout,'' Solich said.
``You can imagine in terms of experience and the quality of athlete
that we have here that there was a lot expected of them right out
of the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they delivered immediately. They have played great
football. Certainly, a lapse in the last half, basically the last
quarter, of the Colorado game can be attributed to a lot of
different things. Overall, they have been just tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The secondary cannot be singly blamed for the rally that brought
the Buffaloes from a 27-3 deficit to a 27-27 deadlock that
necessitated overtime. The Nebraska offense gained only 78 yards in
the second half and dogged itself with fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado senior quarterback Mike Moschetti threw for three
touchdowns in the fourth quarter. That, Mike Brown said, burned the
pride of the Cornhuskers and will be a source of motivation
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, every game we want to go out and show our abilities,''
he said. ``We struggled (against Colorado), and we've struggled in
some other games. That's going to happen because we play so much
man-to-man. Sometimes you're going to get beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But definitely, they (the Longhorns) are awesome. They're a
challenge because they throw the ball very well. They've got two
capable quarterbacks, especially Major Applewhite. His poise and
leadership _ you can't deny what he can do for a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a great leader. You've got the (team) confidence
(bred from three straight wins over Nebraska) and that great
leadership. It just builds up, and it's a hard wall to break
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
