<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FDA-GENES-FOOD-ART-NY     11-30 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-GENES-FOOD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS SHOW OFFICIALS DISAGREED ON ALTERED FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Food and Drug Administration officials have
disagreed with the agency's conclusion that genetically engineered
foods can be regulated in the same way as conventional food
varieties, according to internal agency memorandums read Tuesday at
a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the memorandums, which were written in the early 1990s,
accuses the agency of siding with industry and giving short shrift
to consumers. An advocate of labels on genetically modified food,
Steven M. Druker, obtained the documents in a lawsuit and read them
at a hearing about the safety and labeling of such foods.
</P>
<P>
   The agency says there is no difference between foods modified by
genetics engineeering and foods modified by traditional breeding
practices. But it organized a series of three hearings to listen to
the public and a range of panelists on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Druker made public a 1992 memorandum from Dr. Linda Kahl, a
compliance officer, to Dr. James Maryanski, the agency's
Biotechnology Coordinator, that shows the range of views that
existed within the agency itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of genetic engieneering and traditional breeding
are different, and according to the technical experts in the
agency, they lead to different risks,'' Dr. Kahl wrote. ``There is
no data that addresses the relative magnitude of risk _ for all we
know, the risks may be lower for genetically engineered foods than
for foods produced by traditional breeding. But the acknowledgment
that the risks are different is lost in the attempt to hold to the
doctrine that the product and not the process is regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate memorandum, Dr. Louis Pribyl, an FDA
microbiologist, commenting on the draft of the Federal Register
notice on bioengineered foods, reiterated Dr. Kahl's point and
added that an agency document ``read very pro-industry, especially
in the area of unintended effects.'' It is ``industry's pet idea,''
he said that ``there are no unintended effects that will raise the
FDA's level of concern.'' But time and again, he said, ``there is
no data to back up their contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Pribyl also said the document ``contains very little input from
consumers and only a few answers for their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryanski said in an interview that the concerns of agency
scientists were old news and that the comments the scientists made
were in response to an agency request for them. ``Those views were
taken into account,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The internal documents came to light because of a lawsuit filed
against the agency by the Alliance for Bio-Integrity, founded by
Druker, a lawyer who is the organization's executive director.
Druker is conducting a one-man campaign to force the agency to
institute mandatory, rigorous safety testing of all genetically
engineered food and require labeling. Safety testing and labeling
are now voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Druker, a panelist at the hearing Tuesday, was joined by Carol
Tucker Foreman, director of the Food Policy Institute of Consumer
Federation of America, and Dr. Rebecca Goldberg, a senior scientist
with the Envronmental Defense Fund, in calling for labeling and
testing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Goldberg said ``the agency has not squarely placed the
burden of proof on industry to demonstrate the safety of new food,
which had historically been required in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising public sentiment for more information about
bioengineered foods, which prompted the public hearings, Maryanski
said there was no reason to change the rules covering them. He
maintained that as long as developers of these foods ``follow the
agency's guidelines and do the testing that is recommended,''
though not required, genetically engineered foods were ``as safe as
any food on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this past year, Americans _ if they thought about
genetically engineered food at all, and most did not _ seemed
willing to leave these judgments to the agency. But all around the
globe, particularly in the European Union, consumers and activists
have opposed genetically modified food with such force that
American farmers have found those crops banned from some countries.
</P>
<P>
   Now many British supermarkets require labeling of genetically
modified products. The furious activity has finally had an effect
in this country and many of the questions that were not asked in
1992 are being asked now.
</P>
<P>
   The original decisions on how to regulate genetically altered
foods were made by the Bush White House. Vice President Dan Quayle
announced details of a government policy for steamlining regulation
of food produced through genetic engineering, saying that because
the United States ``was the world leader in biotechnology,'' the
government wanted ``to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Foreman said in her remarks that the process of regulating
bio-engingeered food ``began under a cloud of political influence
peddling and managerial bean counting and the FDA has done nothing
to dispel that cloud.'' She said that both labeling and a mandatory
pre-approval process are essential. Several food trade associations
have told the agency the same thing. The Food Marketing Institute
and the Grocer Manufacturers of America said they ``believe a
mandatory consultation process would help ensure continued consumer
confidence in the FDA regulatory policy'' and that the agency
should set up criteria for labeling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BINGHAM-DEATH-NYT &LR;      11-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINGHAM-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTLING ENDING FOR YOUNG WRITER OF PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Ky.) 
(jt) 
 By TINA KELLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As his first novel was being typeset, Robert Bingham,
33, was found dead in the bathroom of his TriBeCa home in lower
Manhattan on Sunday. A law enforcement official said that the
authorities believed that Bingham, the last male writer in the
storied and contentious Kentucky newspaper family, had overdosed on
heroin.
</P>
<P>
   It was a startling ending to a writing career with auspicious
beginnings. At 26, Bingham saw his first story published in The New
Yorker. His first book, a collection of short stories, was well
received, he married in May, and his novel, ``Lightning on the
Sun,'' was being compared to those of F. Scott Fitzgerald. He was
known for his reportorial portrayal of disaffected, burned out,
rich young men.
</P>
<P>
   A Kirkus review of his first book, ``Pure Slaughter Value''
(Doubleday, 1997), said Bingham's work ``at its best, stands out
for its precisely rendered and convincingly bleak view of life.''
</P>
<P>
   His death is the most recent in a string of family tragedies.
His father, Robert Worth Bingham III, the assistant publisher of
The Courier-Journal and The Louisville Times, was killed in a car
accident in 1966 when he was 34. Two years earlier, the novelist's
uncle, Jonathan Bingham, was electrocuted at a barn on the family's
Kentucky estate while trying to string lights for a Cub Scout
reunion party.
</P>
<P>
   Alex S. Jones, who, with Susan E. Tifft, chronicled the Bingham
family in ``The Patriarch: The Rise and Fall of the Bingham
Dynasty'' (Summit Books, 1991), remembered the younger Bingham's
efforts to find his place in a famous family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob was very young when his father died,'' Jones said, ``and
he seemed to be trying his whole life to live up to his father's
reputation, both for being a journalist and sort of a
swashbuckling, hell-raising, reckless adventurer, which his father
also had a fair portion of. Rob did a lot of things that made
people who knew him confused.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Bingham's told Jones how, while he was working in
Cambodia, Bingham would ride his motorcycle alone, late at night,
over roads that were thought to be controlled by the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't understand why he would take such a chance,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gerald Howard, Bingham's editor at Doubleday
Broadway, ``He'd seen something of the world on his journalistic
ticket, the way novelists in training used to.''
</P>
<P>
   This was unusual for writers Bingham's age, most of whom simply
come out of Masters of Fine Arts programs, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham's agent, Jennifer Rudolph Walsh, vice president of the
Virginia Barber Literary Agency, said she and Howard had been
looking forward to working with him on future books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both thought we were at the beginning of something so
palpable and tremendous,'' Ms. Walsh said. ``And how did we know we
were at the end as well?''
</P>
<P>
   Bingham backed several artistic ventures, including Open City, a
literary magazine that he helped found.
</P>
<P>
   ``His community of people that he helped and cared about was
just really, really large,'' said Daniel Pinchbeck, editor, with
Thomas Beller, of Open City.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham gave money to a friend who is an artist to help her
finish her film, and he was generous with other friends who were
starting Web sites, said Pinchbeck, who last saw Bingham on
Thanksgiving night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed very sharp, very happy, very upbeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An empty glassine envelope that had held heroin was found at his
side in the bathroom where his body was discovered, the law
enforcement official said. The medical examiner's office said the
determination of the cause of the death was pending histology and
toxicology tests, which will not be completed for up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
