<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HOLIDAY-FIGHT-HNS &LR;      11-30 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MERRY LITTLE LEGAL TANGLE: TEXAS HOMEOWNERS GROUP OBJECTS TO
ELABORATE CHRISTMAS DECORATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PECAN GROVE, Texas _ Children who see Steve Richardson's
elaborate Christmas display do more than ooh and aah.
</P>
<P>
   They stop. They get out of their cars, look at themselves on a
big-screen television and walk around, touching the animated toys
and dolls.
</P>
<P>
   It delights Richardson, but it does not delight the homeowners
association in this upscale northeast Fort Bend County subdivision
in suburban Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was working on the lavish display Tuesday with the
warning that it probably will lead to court action from the Pecan
Grove Plantation Property Owners' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Though the display has won several awards from the association
in years past, the group contends that it has become a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   Each year Richardson spends thousands of dollars and several
days putting up the elaborate prize-winning Christmas display at
his two-story home.
</P>
<P>
   ``His house would make Clark Griswold envious,'' said Steve
Broussard, his neighbor and attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold is played by Chevy Chase in the 1989 movie ``Christmas
Vacation,'' and he covers his house in a blanket of blinking
lights.
</P>
<P>
   At the Richardson house, all the shrubs are covered in a mesh
lighting, and more lights hang from the second-floor eaves. Lights
also ring the yard.
</P>
<P>
   But the lights are just a start.
</P>
<P>
   Because the house is on the corner, he has plenty of yard space
to create a miniature Christmas theme park, including an artificial
skating rink complete with animated skaters.
</P>
<P>
   On one portion of his lawn he has a television camera pointed at
the street. The signal is fed into a giant television, allowing
people on the street and sidewalk to see themselves on the big
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said it is the TV screen and other features, such as
toy figures, dolls and a bubble machine, that cause people to stop
for a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the homeowners association sent Richardson a letter
saying his holiday decorations are so excessive they have become a
nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   The association said that unless he limits his display so that
sightseers are not encouraged to stop and walk about his property,
it will seek a temporary restraining order forcing him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that letter, Richardson said, he decided not to put
up his display this year.
</P>
<P>
   He changed his mind Saturday, though.
</P>
<P>
   First, two little girls stopped to ask whether he was going to
put out his decorations, and he said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `That's not fair. It's not Christmas without the
lights,''' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, he said, he was checking with neighbors to ask
if it would bother them if he put up the display again. He said he
knocked at one woman's door and asked her, and she began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked me inside, and she had about six Christmas trees
inside her house,'' Richardson said. ``She told me that she had
cancer and was undergoing treatments and she said, `I need your
lights to boost my spirits.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we decided, let's go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, ``If my house is a nuisance, then so is every
other house in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Broussard agrees that there are many houses in the subdivision
with elaborate displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the kids just love it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is the children's reactions that motivate Richardson,
who has a 21-year-old daughter and an 18-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to the parents, they say they just love it,'' he
said. ``But, if you will watch the children, that is the big payoff
_ the squeals, the giggles. It is just awesome watching those
little kids. That is why I do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who owns several video stores, said the homeowners
association encourages residents to decorate their homes and that a
contest is held each year.
</P>
<P>
   He has lived in the subdivision seven years, four of those at
his present address, and won several awards for the decorations,
including first place awards in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Coveler, attorney for the homeowners association, said no
one is trying to keep Richardson from decorating his home for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the very interactive things in his yard that
cause people to stop their cars, park and get out. This creates a
traffic hazard and other problems,'' Coveler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no other homes in the neighborhood that have
decorations that encourage people to stop and come onto the
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are singling me out,'' he said. ``There are other homes
out here that are interactive. People stop, get out and take
pictures. They have the same traffic problem that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   (This is not his first disagreement with the homeowners
association. The group is taking him to court Friday, seeking a
temporary restraining order because he stores a golf cart in his
back yard.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Richardson, all but two residents on the two
streets near his home have signed a petition saying his display is
not an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Coveler said many residents have complained to the Sheriff's
Department about the traffic snarl around the Richardson house.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sheriff's Department spokeswoman Amanda Ashley said she
could find no records of such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the complaints were made to us through the
association,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Coveler said the association had not taken any legal action
against Richardson because he was not finished installing his
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Richardson was still putting on finishing
touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you who should be complaining about me,'' he said. ``It
should be HL&AMP;P, because their stock will drop if I am not allowed
to do Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
