<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC WILL TAKE MORE TIME TO IMPOSE NEW SHELTER RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City officials said Tuesday that new rules to make
work and other welfare requirements a condition of shelter for
homeless families would not go into effect Wednesday, despite an
earlier announcement by the city's homeless agency.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were still working out procedures for
ejecting parents and seeking foster care for some homeless
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are protocols being finalized, and that is very much
under discussion now,'' said Nicholas Scoppetta, the commissioner
of the Administration for Children's Services, on Tuesday. ``We're
very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Coles, a senior adviser to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
declined to specify a new starting date. Though the Department of
Homeless Services told shelter operators in October that the new
program would begin Wednesday, Coles denied that any postponement
was involved. The Giuliani administration has said that the rules
will be in place by late December, and Coles said the actual
starting date would be sooner _ ``within the next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Assistant Corporation Counsel Leonard Koerner said that he
had been about to fax a letter setting a new date of Dec. 13 to
Steven Banks, a Legal Aid Society lawyer for the homeless, and to
attach plans for putting the rules into effect. ``But that letter
was withheld'' until Wednesday or Thursday for revisions, he said.
In any case, Koerner added, the rules will not be enforced until
after Banks is officially notified.
</P>
<P>
   The Dec. 1 date became doubtful after many shelter operators
declined to attend a Nov. 29 meeting scheduled to explain the
rules. New training sessions have been scheduled for Dec. 6, 8 and
11, said Fred Shack, president of the Tier II Coalition, which
represents the nonprofit agencies that run all homeless family
shelters under city contract.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say that requiring work in exchange for shelter
will help move homeless people into gainful employment and
independence, and keep them from using shelters to escape personal
responsibility if they fail to follow public assistance rules.
</P>
<P>
   But coalition members are on record opposing the regulations and
are being canvassed now to see if they are prepared to refuse to
enforce them, Shack said. Shelter operators are alarmed by the
experiences of families ejected from shelters in Suffolk County
under the same regulations, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that people would want families living in
cars, living in basements, moving children every day or two,'' he
said. ``That's just not in the best interest of our families. It
doesn't motivate people to work.''
</P>
<P>
   A coalition survey of shelters has determined that about 10
percent of the 5,000 families in them have public assistance cases
that are closed or are under welfare sanctions that would make them
subject to expulsion. ``That's 500 families,'' Shack said. ``It's
very frightening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
