<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT COULD RETURN WEDNESDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Lakers got an unexpected boost Tuesday from the
their medical team. Kobe Bryant was cleared to play and is likely
to be activated in time for tonight's home game against the Golden
State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who broke a bone in his right hand Oct. 13, had hoped to
return a week ago. Then he was told he might be out until Dec. 8.
He split the difference, as team orthopedist Dr. Stephen Lombardo
and hand specialist Dr. Robert Zemel gave him the clean bill of
health Tuesday morning in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tests showed Bryant completely healed, though he has been fitted
with a protective pad that he'll wear in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him on the phone this afternoon, he's excited
about playing,'' coach Phil Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on when is up to Jackson. But the coach doesn't
plan to wait long and said Bryant could start as soon as Friday
night, when the Lakers play host to the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor came to him and said, `It looks like you're OK, the
results were good.' Kobe said, `Does that mean I can play?' He
said, `Yes.' (Bryant) said, `I'm playing tomorrow night. . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will have to make a roster move _ rookie John
Celestand could go back to the injured list _ and Jackson has to
mull whether Bryant should practice a couple days before being
activated, but noted, ``It's almost impossible to keep him off the
roster and not let him play (Wednesday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Bryant has been wearing the protective pad for
several days, and ``I think he can shoot with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who along with Glen Rice has been carrying the
team in Bryant's absence, said he was ``glad to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're going to have all our weapons at full strength,'' he
said. ``Kobe misses games, I held the fort down for those games,
now we should be on our way. We should be a dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal said reintegrating Bryant into the triangle offense
won't pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not going to be a test, because there's rules (to the
offense),'' he said. ``First guy to the post gets to take the post,
everybody else has to take the backside. Those are the rules. We
ain't going to be fighting over that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
