u a BC-HOSPITAL-DEATHS-NYT &LR;      11-30 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WHAT TO DO ABOUT MEDICAL ERRORS COULD BECOME CAMPAIGN
ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been known for some time that medical errors are a major
cause of death and suffering in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Institute of Medicine, the medical arm of the National
Academy of Sciences, has called for a new federal office to protect
patients and said Congress should require all health care providers
to report mistakes that cause serious injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   The main question is how the proposed system might work. While
many health-related organizations and consumer groups welcomed the
proposal, others expressed concern about additional government
involvement in personal health care. Still others, including
President Clinton, were concerned about patient confidentiality.
Health maintenance organizations say they wonder how frank
discussion of errors can occur as long as health care providers
fear malpractice suits. And some state governments pointed out that
they already had systems designed to do just the kind of thing the
academy was suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, though, the medical error is likely to be an
issue in the presidential campaign. Both Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley have talked about using advanced
technology to improve the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued on Monday, the academy said there was a clear
need to impose ``rigorous changes'' throughout the fragmented
health care system to reduce the estimated 44,000 to 98,000 deaths
from medical errors each year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of medical errors do not result from individual
recklessness, but from basic flaws in the way the health care
system is organized,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member committee that wrote the report said that in
alerting the public to the problem it had been inspired by several
well-publicized cases.
</P>
<P>
   One was that of Betsy Lehman, a 39-year-old health columnist for
The Boston Globe who died in 1994 after an overdose of chemotherapy
for breast cancer at the Dana Farber Cancer Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Another case was that of Willie King, who had part of the wrong
leg amputated at University Community Hospital in Tampa, Fla., in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1995, the chief neurosurgeon at Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center in New York operated on the wrong side of a patient's
brain.
</P>
<P>
   But the public is less aware of the thousands of other medical
errors that occur each year in hospitals, clinics and doctor's
offices, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
   Adverse medical events occurred in 3.7 percent of patients in a
large study in New York state, and in 2.9 percent of patients in a
study in Colorado and Utah. And deaths among those who experienced
adverse events in the studies ranged from 8.8 percent in Colorado
and Utah to 13.6 percent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said that deaths resulted from hospitals' stocking
full-strength drugs despite the fact that they posed a great danger
unless they were diluted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The know-how exists to prevent many of these mistakes,'' the
report said. But it also said that ``unsafe care is one of the
prices we pay for not having organized systems of care with clear
lines of accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong support for the findings came from the National Patient
Safety Foundation, a group started by the American Medical
Association but which is now independent.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA supported the proposal, a surprise turn of events for a
group that has long criticized newspaper articles that called
attention to incompetent doctors and medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't my grandmother's AMA. A lot of the AMA is different
than in the 1970s,'' said Dr. Nancy Dickey, a former president of
the association. ``We're talking daily about health insurance for
every individual and openly about impaired doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy said a crucial strategy in reducing errors was
shifting the focus ``from blaming individuals for past errors to a
focus on preventing future errors by designing safety in the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that ``we've got to work through how we can use
technology, and how we can maybe even slow some of the actions, to
make sure that mistakes like this aren't made.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also concerned about protecting patient privacy, said
Chris Jennings, &UR;  &LR; deputy assistant to the president for health
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, which represents HMOs, said: ``The National Academy of
Sciences should be commended for shining light on an important
problem. Health plans will rise to this challenge and will work
with doctors, hospitals and public officials to address these
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``If we want to move in this direction to secure
improvements, as the public wants, there have to be some changes in
liability and malpractice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ignagni said the recommendations by the academy's expert
panel were consistent with the goals and strengths of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   In defining error as the failure to complete a planned action as
intended or the use of a wrong plan to achieve an aim, the academy
said errors could happen at any stage of care, from diagnosis to
treatment to preventive care. Not all errors result in harm, the
committee said.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce errors, the academy called for creation of a center in
the Department of Health and Human Services to develop tools and
systems to address persistent problems.
</P>
<P>
   The new federal center would also set national safety goals,
track progress in meeting them and be an objective source of the
latest information on patient safety. Units in the center could
focus on particular types of errors, like those related to drugs
and those in particular settings, like intensive care units.
</P>
<P>
   Information would come from a mandatory reporting system similar
to one in New York, where the state specifies which adverse
outcomes hospitals must report and which they may exclude. Health
officials have visited various hospitals statewide to help identify
the cause of certain bad occurrences and help them to establish
strategies to avoid them in the future, said Kristine Smith, a
spokeswoman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of states have mandatory reporting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report cited New York's program as a model, a
committee member, Dr. Mark Chassin, a former New York state health
commissioner who works at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York,
disagreed. Chassin said the program ``is the weakest link'' in the
proposal. Specific programs like one to measure outcomes from heart
bypass operations would be more valuable, he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The report said, ``It may be part of human nature to err, but it
is also part of human nature to create solutions, find better
alternatives and meet the challenges ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
