<SLUG> BC-WTO-ANNAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN URGES U.S. TO REJECT ISOLATIONISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Chanting demonstrators who took over city streets
Tuesday are people who ``feel vulnerable'' and ``feel lost'' in a
fast-changing world where economic issues are global but politics
remain local, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a message here for all of us,'' Annan told the
Seattle Rotary Club, some of whose members had to brave tear gas to
reach the Washington Athletic Club to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reach out and explain the link between the local,
the national and the international,'' said Annan, a diplomat from
Ghana who has witnessed his share of turmoil heading such sensitive
U.N. operations as refugee assistance.
</P>
<P>
   As Annan began his speech, the sound of exploding tear gas
canisters could be heard outside on 6th Avenue, along with the
voices of the protestors.
</P>
<P>
   Annan was urbane, funny and gracious toward a city that Tuesday
gave international visitors such a raucous and sometimes violent
welcome. Annan thanked those who ``braved it'' to hear him _ a
gathering that grew to over 300 _ and added: ``This is a great
city, a high-technology city, and a city with a history of dealings
with the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. leader said that isolationism, in both foreign and
economic affairs, was the policy of the United States for many
years. ``We need to hear that you reject isolationism,'' he said.
``Isolationism has run its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some suggest that the United States, as the one superpower,
need not cooperate with others or do so on its own terms,'' Annan
added. ``Most of the world's problems are so complex, however, that
they cannot be solved by any power, no matter how peaceful, acting
on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Congress' recent grudging agreement to pay
much of the United States' overdue U.N. dues ``is a turning point
in efforts to restore the U.S. to its rightful leadership role'' in
the world body. He criticized some of the conditions imposed on
U.N. agency funding.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Tuesday signed a waiver that would allow
$15 million in U.S. funds to go toward international family
planning organizations that promote abortion rights. The budget
compromise tied paying off about $1 billion in U.N. dues to banning
U.S. funds for those international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Annan exchanged compliments with Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash. ``I
am glad we are paying our dues,'' said Murray, who was supposed to
introduce Annan to the group but was held up by the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your vote,'' Annan replied with a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle businessman Skip Kotkins asked Annan why the WTO has
become such a lightning rod for protest. He apologized for not
wearing a tie, explaining that well-dressed pedestrians had been
singled out for abuse by more militant demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look more relaxed and at ease,'' Annan replied with a
broad smile. The Secretary-General jokingly chided another
questioner, Seattle attorney William H. Gates, Sr., for not being a
member of Rotary.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has brought an intellectual aggressiveness to his U.N.
office, which suffered from weak leadership in the two decades
before his election. It was reflected in his statements Tuesday
night. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   __ Cuba: Annan said that the U.S. policy to isolate Cuba
economically has failed and should be abandoned. ``Sometimes these
sanctions entrench leaders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Debt forgiveness: Answering a question from former Washington
Gov. Mike Lowry, Annan agreed that wealthy nations need to relieve
poor Third World countries of their debt load. He said, too, that
investment and development assistance must continue if conditions
of poverty are to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dictators: Annan strongly endorsed putting those responsible
for ethnic cleansing in Bosnia and Rwanda on trial before
international tribunals. ``I hope international courts send out the
message that those who commit these crimes will be prosecuted,'' he
said. ``With what has happened to (former Gen. Augusto) Pinochet in
British and Spanish courts, leaders are beginning to think twice
(about) what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Chile's former dictator has been held in Britain pending a
decision on whether he will be extradited to Spain to be tried for
the deaths of Spanish citizens during his regime.
</P>
<P>
   With Annan gracefully fielding complex questions, it was
possible to see the sophisticated face that Seattle hoped to show
the world in hosting the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Murray made the point afterward. ``It is right that Seattle is
hosting the World Trade Organization and reaching for the future by
talking to people rather than shouting them down,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
