<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID FRIENDLY GREETING, A CANDIDATE'S GRILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE, N.H. _ This is a state that takes its responsibility for
holding the nation's first presidential primary very seriously.
Voters expect to meet candidates, shake their hands and ask them a
barbed question or two. Plenty of folks here would probably take a
candidate home for a good health care debate over coffee if they
could.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, then, it was that sense of duty that inspired Aine
Whittum to subject former Sen. Bill Bradley to an aggressive
grilling Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who is running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, was greeting voters along the snow-covered main drag of
this western New Hampshire town when he decided to pop into Ms.
Whittum's place of employment: the Vitality Shop, a purveyor of
herbal and homeopathic medicines, organic foods and sundry other
New Age products.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had just begun bantering with the store's owner when Ms.
Whittum, 24, sweetly piped up: ``Can I ask a question?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Bradley, sounding affably unprepared for the
interrogation he was about to get.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whittum pulled out one of the Bradley campaign's policy
papers and, holding it aloft like a summons, said, ``I was
wondering about your economic policy. I don't feel you are being
very clear.'' She continued: ``Part of your agenda is to keep the
economy growing and growing. But the earth is only one size and
everything can't keep growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly sensing the danger of having to face down a hostile
questioner while surrounded by half a dozen reporters, Bradley
quickly tried to address her concerns. In the new global economy,
he said, American economic growth would be fed by software and
service companies, nonpolluting industries that don't use a lot of
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Whittum said she wasn't talking just about natural
resources, but about unchecked population growth, global economic
instability and a range of other potential catastrophes. It was
time, she suggested, for a return to the barter system.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had patiently launched into an analysis of the failures
of the barter system in Russia when his aides began nudging him
toward the door. He bid adieu.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whittum, despite having monopolized the candidate for more
time than many reporters get in a week, was not satisfied. Who
would she vote for? ``I'm thinking of writing myself in,'' she
answered.
</P>
<P>
   If Bradley has that hungry look about him, it's probably because
he is. Hungry, that is.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to keep weight off during the campaign _ a nearly
impossible task given the pressures to load up on fatty fast foods
_ Bradley usually dines on salads and fruits. But it just doesn't
seem to be quite enough for his 6-foot-5 frame.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Bradley can often be spied grabbing food at odd
moments while he campaigns. For instance, on Monday night after a
televised town hall meeting in Manchester, he ducked into a room
where reporters had been watching the event. But Bradley was not
looking to offer last-minute dollops of spin to stray journalists.
No, he was in search of pizza. He triumphantly emerged from the
room munching a cold slice, unperturbed by the congealing glob of
cheese that was hanging off it like a lead sinker.
</P>
<P>
   It is also probably his growling stomach more than his desire to
win votes that drives Bradley to steal stray french fries and onion
rings from the plates of diners when he visits restaurants on
campaign events.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley may have recently shifted eating tactics. Monday's
dinner: steak.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Bradley and clothes?
</P>
<P>
   He is known for wearing the same suit for weeks at a time,
repairing torn ties with Scotch tape and resoling shoes scores of
times to avoid buying new ones. But Bradley is not just unchic: he
has made a political art form of being unartfully dressed.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter once jokingly asked him where he had bought his
tie, Bradley proudly volunteered that he had forgotten to pack one
and had to steal the tie from an aide. And when, at his wife's
urging, he bought shoes for the first time in _ he claims _ 25
years, he made a campaign event out of it, leading a pack of camera
crews into a shoe store in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   So it should not have been surprising, perhaps, that Washington
was aflutter with rumors about Bradley's attire this week. Was that
an earth-tone suit he was wearing during a speech at Tufts
University? And since when does the dowdy Bradley wear French-blue
shirts? Was this an attempt to mimic the clothing strategies of his
Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   Well, in fact the suit was not earth-toned, but stolid,
conservative banker's gray. (It just looked kind of earthy from a
distance.) And about that deep blue shirt, well, Bradley had an
answer for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seems that, once again, he had forgotten to pack enough shirts
during a recent visit to Iowa. So he had a trusty aide buy him some
new ones. He asked for blue, but he didn't specify trendy French
blue. But that was what he got and that was all he had to wear in
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was some trend here, Bradley, as he often does
when confronted with a question he considers silly, sighed and ever
so slightly rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not trend,'' he said. ``This is a moment that
illustrates the deeper character of the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
