<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      11-30 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIPS OUSTED AS UMPIRES VOTE TO FORM NEW UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With an overwhelming 62 percent majority, insurgent
major league umpires effectively tossed Richie Phillips out of his
job Tuesday, ending his 21-year reign as the chief labor negotiator
and lawyer for the umpires' union. Only a successful appeal of the
election, overseen by the National Labor Relation Board, could save
Phillips' job.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires voted 57-35 to decertify the Major League Umpires
Association and replace it with the Major League Umpires
Independent Organizing Committee as their collective-bargaining
representative. Phillips has represented the umpires for as long as
they have had a union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a statement by all major league umpires that it's
time for change,'' John Hirschbeck, one of the dissident leaders,
said. ``We want a union that's run by umpires and advised by
attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he would have said to Phillips if he had been at
the NLRB's New York office for the ballot counting, Hirschbeck
said: ``It's time for us to move on. Thank you for what you've done
for us in our careers. Now it's time for major league umpires to
move in a new direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Crawford, the union president and a staunch supporter
of Phillips, indicated the fight was not over. ``I have a few
options left and I'm going to explore those options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, a veteran National League umpire, acknowledged that an
appeal of the outcome was one of the options. ``I would say it's
probably likely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford declined to say what the grounds for an appeal might
be. But Joel Smith, a Baltimore labor lawyer working with the
Hirschbeck group, said: ``I know of no solid grounds for appeal.
This has been an effort by umpires for umpires and the vote is
quite emphatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck and Joe Brinkman, another leader of the organizing
committee, had expected to receive at least 48 votes and as many as
57 votes.
</P>
<P>
   In figuring on 48, they had counted on votes from at least seven
or eight of the 22 umpires who lost their jobs last summer as a
result of Phillips' failed resignation strategy. More than eight of
the 22 may have added their votes to the dissident group in the
secret ballot, people on their side of the issue said.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires, who obviously remain deeply split as they approach
negotiations for a new labor agreement with Major League Baseball,
began their fight after more than 50 umpires signed letters of
resignation last July, although some quickly rescinded. After
Phillips submitted the letters to the National and American League
offices, the league presidents hired 25 new umpires and accepted 22
resignations. Their action is the subject of an arbitration hearing
that is scheduled to begin Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Shapiro, a Baltimore lawyer and player agent, who has been
advising the dissident umpires organizing committee, said the
existing union would continue to handle the arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Major League Umpires Association is charged with
that arbitration and we won't interfere,'' he said. ``But we'll do
everything we can from a legal standpoint to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said getting the 22 umpires back to work would be
among the new group's top priorities when it begins negotiating a
new labor agreement with baseball officials. The current contract
expires Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The 22 terminated umpires were permitted to vote, as were the
new umpires the leagues hired. All 93 eligible voters mailed in
ballots, but one was voided because the umpire signed his name on
it. Names of voters are not permitted in elections conducted by the
NLRB.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Stephen Appell, an NLRB lawyer, began counting the
ballots in the board's offices at Federal Plaza in Manhattan, it
was clear that the dissidents would win. The existing union led
only once in the 14-minute count, by 3-2. The organizing committee
received 10 of the next 12 votes, and the rout was on. When Appell
read out the 47th vote for the committee at 5:24 p.m., Phillips was
_ barring a successful appeal _ baseball labor history.
</P>
<P>
   The union has seven days in which to file an appeal.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
