<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, UCLA MORE LIKE ICU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when UCLA was gaining momentum and its
wounded were starting to walk . . .
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jerome Moiso accidentally headbutts forward Sean
Farnham, giving Farnham a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Barnes accidentally headbutts forward Jason Kapono,
giving Kapono a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso gets the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ray Young tumbles to the floor and strains his neck.
</P>
<P>
   All in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, No. 12 UCLA's lineup is in flux entering tonight's
matchup with winless Morgan State at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Don't worry about who starts, you should all be
ready to play,' '' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``Between the
injuries and our conditioning level, it'll be a while before we
find a routine to the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnham, who started against Iona, did not practice Tuesday but
was cleared to play tonight. He's listed as probable.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono, the superb freshman, practiced Tuesday and is expected
to make his third start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso, who's averaging 17 points and 10 rebounds, is
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who made 5 of 6 3-point shots and scored a career-high 17
points against Iona, is questionable. He also has a strained
ligament in his right (shooting) thumb that requires a protective
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably go another two weeks with tape on my hand, then
let it go free,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of concussions: The Bruins treated Kapono and Farnham
better than they did forward Todd Ramasar when he was injured two
seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a concussion, and the guys told him his name was Frank,
and he believed them,'' Lavin said, laughing. ``Since then, his
nickname's been Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   The big man's minutes: Center Dan Gadzuric played seven minutes
against Fairfield and 15 against Iona on his tender,
tendinitis-plagued knees, and his time might climb tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is 20 minutes, at the most 23, but it could be as low
as 15,'' Lavin said. ``I rely on him (to gauge discomfort), but
it's more on a feel of what I think he's capable of. I try to take
the conservative stance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably a wise strategy considering the January
gauntlet. When the Bruins face Arizona and North Carolina in a
five-day span _ and Stanford two weeks later _ Lavin wants Gadzuric
available for 25-30 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain matchups I'd like to keep him in as much as
possible,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Point of emphasis: After tonight, the Bruins play two games in
2{ weeks because of exams. (Gonzaga on Dec. 11, DePaul on the
18th.) That gives Lavin plenty of practice time to correct
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is not where we need it to be,'' he said. ``Some
of it's tied to (poor) conditioning (resulting from injuries). When
you're tired, you come out of your stance and you reach more. We
have to play better help defense, better position defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
