<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS BEGAN INSTANTLY IN FATAL NEWARK PLANE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Troubles on the small single-engine plane that crashed into a
Newark, N.J., neighborhood last Friday morning started almost
immediately after takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Only a minute and 25 seconds into the flight, the pilot, Itzhak
Jacoby, radioed air traffic controllers in Westbury, N.Y. ``I have
a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the next minute and 35 seconds, Jacoby sent the
same short message, the last time about three minutes before his
white and red Beechcraft Bonanza glanced off the top of a factory
building a mile from downtown Newark about 10:55 a.m. It fell from
there and hurtled along Kent Street, breaking apart as it went.
</P>
<P>
   The crash killed Jacoby, 56, an experienced pilot; his wife,
Gail, 50; and their daughter, Atira, 13. It injured 25 people, 2
seriously, on a 200-yard stretch of the street, and damaged 17
apartment buildings and nine parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary transcript of three minutes of conversation
between Jacoby and the air traffic controller, released Tuesday by
the National Transportation Safety Board, offered few clues to the
small plane's problems. Only once did Jacoby provide a hint of the
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a gyro problem,'' he said, at 10:50 a.m. ``Maybe some
water got in it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Muzio, who is directing the safety board's investigation
of the crash, declined Tuesday to offer any analysis or
interpretation of the three minutes of conversation, or Jacoby's
four references to ``a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the plane's three gyroscopes _ small devices that
operate crucial cockpit instruments _ are being examined at the
safety board's laboratory in Washington. Two of the gyroscopes were
found on Kent Street on Saturday, and the third was found Sunday
imbedded in a wall of a KFC fast-food restaurant at the end of the
street. Most of the pieces of the wrecked plane came to a stop in
the restaurant's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Muzio said Tuesday that his inquiry had turned up no signs of
engine failure or defects in the plane's frame.
</P>
<P>
   A malfunctioning gyroscope could lead to the failure of other
instruments that show the direction the plane is flying and whether
it is ascending, descending or turning, said an aviation expert,
Drew Steketee, a senior vice president of the Aircraft Owners and
Pilots Association in Frederick, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Steketee said other backup instruments in the cockpit provide
that flight information, but not as quickly or in as detailed a
form as the primary instruments served by the gyroscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Steketee cautioned that he had no information about Jacoby's
flight or of the problems he reported. But he said that a pilot
unable to see the ground or the horizon and flying solely by
cockpit instruments, as Jacoby was because of overcast skies, could
quickly lose control of his craft if the gyroscopes had
malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript suggests that Jacoby was preoccupied with the
plane's difficulties. Three times in the first two minutes of his
communications with the Westbury tower, Jacoby was told to change
his plane's direction from north to west. The Jacoby family, who
lived in Bethesda, Md., were flying from Linden Airport, eight
miles south of Newark, to Dulles International Airport outside
Washington after spending Thanksgiving in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby did not respond to the instructions to fly westerly or to
a request that he not climb above 2,000 feet. Twenty-six seconds
before his last transmission, Jacoby asked for permission to climb
higher. Steketee said the request suggested that Jacoby wanted more
time to overcome his plane's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Five seconds after Jacoby asked to fly above 2,000 feet, the
controller asked him the direction of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   His answer suggests he was not certain. ``My heading looks like
zero-three-zero,'' he answered. That meant he was headed slightly
east of north.
</P>
<P>
   The controller told him four seconds later, at 10:52 a.m., to
turn west and stay at 2,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Ten seconds later, Jacoby repeated his earlier message a fourth
time. ``I have a problem,'' he said. It was his last transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The crash displaced 50 families in 17 two- and three-family
apartment houses on Kent Street. The force of the crash blew out
windows and knocked plaster off apartment walls and ceilings. Mayor
Sharpe James said Tuesday that about 30 of the families now want to
leave Kent Street, either because they were traumatized by the
crash or because they hope to find better housing elsewhere in
Newark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
