<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-NAVY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY TO TRAIN OFF PUERTO RICO WITH LIVE-FIRE ISSUE UNSETTLED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An aircraft carrier and amphibious battle group
will begin training this week even though the White House has yet
to decide if the ships will be able to use a Puerto Rican island
for the final live bombing practice.
</P>
<P>
   The training schedule for the carrier Eisenhower has been held
hostage for months in a dispute between the governor of Puerto Rico
and the Pentagon over the use of a firing range on the island of
Vieques. Last month a presidential panel recommended that the range
reopen for live firing exercises, but Secretary of Defense William
Cohen has delayed making a recommendation to President Clinton
until a compromise can be reached with Pedro Rosello, the governor
of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The range was closed in April after a Puerto Rican guard was
accidentally killed in a bombing accident there. Protesters have
occupied parts of the 900-acre range that has been used for more
than 30 years for exercises the Navy considers essential for combat
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators have vowed to stay on the range to prevent any
further exercises regardless of what Clinton decides.
Administration officials say the prospect of forcibly removing the
protesters has been a concern in resolving the issue.
</P>
<P>
   By going ahead with the original training schedule but staying
away from the waters near Puerto Rico, the aircraft carrier will
begin its final preparations for deployment to the Mediterranean
Sea and the Arabian Gulf next February with routine carrier
qualification tests.
</P>
<P>
   The exercises will continue two more weeks. The Navy still
expects the carrier and battle group to train with live-fire at
Vieques during that time, a spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PAPER-LABOR-NYT &LR;      11-30 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PAPER-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ANNULS ARBITRATOR'S PAY RAISE FOR DAILY NEWS DRIVERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Raising the specter that The Daily News could go out
of business if forced to pay more than $18 million in back wages, a
U.S. District Court judge Tuesday overturned a pay increase granted
by an arbitrator to the union representing the newspaper's drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas P. Griesa announced his decision in open court
Tuesday, but he said that the parties' lawyers would receive the
written opinion under seal, because it contained confidential
financial information about the newspaper, which is owned by
Mortimer B. Zuckerman and Fred Drasner.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief explanation of his decision, Griesa said, ``I have
found that the arbitrator manifestly disregarded the evidence about
the financial condition of The Daily News.'' The central question,
he said, was, ``Is a wage increase going to be of such magnitude
that it jeopardizes the business and jeopardizes jobs entirely?''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks indicated that he felt that The News would be in
such jeopardy. ``The financial issue is so serious that further
arbitration proceedings are necessary to deal with an issue which
could really be whether these union members have jobs or don't have
jobs,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a setback for the Newspaper and Mail
Deliverers' Union of New York, which decided nearly three years ago
that its members could get a better deal than the raise of about 3
percent that eight other craft unions at The News got for their
members. The drivers' union and The News submitted their
negotiations to binding arbitration, a proceeding that began in
April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For The Daily News, which over the last two years has been
forced to grapple with a series of costly problems _ most notably,
its balky $62 million presses _ the judge's ruling was a
vindication. The newspaper's executives and its lawyers have been
arguing since March, when the original arbitration award was made,
that the arbitrator had failed to take into account crucial facts
about the newspaper's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon Zuckerman said, ``I think this decision was
essential to the continuation of The Daily News as a thriving,
growing newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked outside the courtroom if the union would appeal the
judge's ruling, J. Kenneth O'Connor, one of the lawyers
representing the drivers, gave a thumbs-up sign. His law partner,
J. Warren Mangan, said that the ruling was ``a surprise'' and that
he would need to discuss the situation with his clients before
there could be any decision on an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, it seemed that the truck drivers' strategy had
succeeded, when the arbitrator, J.J. Pierson, awarded the 420 or so
regular drivers an immediate increase in base salary, to $911.79 a
week, up from the current base of $773.57.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers' initial victory had also been a victory for members
of the eight other unions, based on so-called ``me too'' clauses in
their contracts, which stipulated that whatever the drivers got,
the members of other craft unions would also get.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision means that the drivers face the prospect of a
potentially time-consuming appeal and, if they lose, another
arbitration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
