<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IMMIG-DETAIN-ART-600&AMP;     11-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-DETAIN-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED DETAINEE PLANS MOSQUE REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After spending three years in detention on the basis
of secret evidence, Nasser K. Ahmed said Tuesday that he planned to
use his freedom to revive an Islamic religious movement that
federal investigators say was a haven for terrorists who carried
out a bomb attack on the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed was released from the Metropolitan Correctional Center in
lower Manhattan on Monday night after Attorney General Janet Reno
decided against intervening to keep him in custody. The decision
went against the wishes of FBI officials who had linked Ahmed, and
the Brooklyn mosque he was affiliated with, to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI broke the Abu Bakr Mosque just as it broke David
Koresh's church,'' he said, referring to the mosque he administered
before he was jailed in April 1996. ``They brought in new leaders
and tried to take over while I was in jail. They turned the
community against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials had argued that Ahmed's release would only raise
his stature among Islamic radicals, a stature they say had grew
during his years of detention. Those arguing against his release
predicted that he would plunge anew into the organizational work
that under his direction caused the Abu Bakr Mosque to become, in
the eyes of the government, a center for Islamic radicals. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service, using classified evidence,
is seeking to deport Ahmed to Egypt, his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, 39, who speaks in soft, measured tones, says he intends
to look for work again as an electrical engineer and to be a good
father to the three children he saw only during their periodic
prison visits over the past three years. But he is also a man on a
mission, determined to rebuild the world shattered by his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Abu Bakr Mosque was unique because it was independent _ it
was beyond the control of the Egyptian government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mosque was once used as the pulpit for Sheik Omar Abdel
Rahman, who was convicted in 1995 of plotting to blow up New York
City landmarks. Ahmed praises Abdel Rahman as ``a great and
fearless scholar whose sermons made me realize that we were all
sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed had been a legal assistant to Abdel Rahman, but he has
denied being involved in terrorism. Colleagues describe him as a
central figure in the Abu Bakr Mosque's operation when Abdel Rahman
was delivering sermons there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasser was in the mosque every day,'' said Ahmed Sattar, 40, a
board member at Abu Bakr. ``Whenever the mosque needed him, he was
there. He was the backbone of Abu Bakr Mosque. If you wanted to do
anything, you went first through him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they wanted to destroy the mosque, they had to remove
Nasser first,'' Satter added. ``He was more devoted e to the mosque
than to anything else in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed said the mosque had been a haven. ``It was the only place
Egyptians could go to find out about what was happening back
home,'' he said. ``There people could find food, a job or
assistance when no one else in the city would help. We never closed
the doors. It was open 24 hours a day so people would always have a
place to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Ahmed, the Abu Bakr Mosque withered. Its politically
active congregation, which supported the Islamic insurgency in
Egypt and raised money for Muslims who fought as volunteers in the
war in Bosnia, has dispersed. It now draws a couple of dozen
dispirited Muslims and is led by a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Reno's decision not to act to keep Ahmed in jail means
he is free for now, his troubles may not be over. He is free on
personal bond pending a final ruling by the Board of Immigration
Appeals on whether he should be granted asylum. Ahmed has said that
if he were returned to Egypt, he would be tortured by the
government. &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ahmed said that the scars of jail lie heaviest on his family.
His children, he said, were shunned by school friends who told them
their father ``was a bad man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My youngest son, Omar, began to worry me,'' said Ahmed's wife,
Salwa Elbayadi. ``We live on a first-floor apartment and the
children in the street would yell up for him to come out and play.
He would make believe he was talking to his father and then tell
them that his father had told him he could not go outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then Ahmed began sleepwalking,'' she said. ``I found him
one night by the door and had to get a lock for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed's eyes narrowed and his voice dipped to a terse whisper.
''I went to the prison psychologist to ask what we should do,'' he
said. ``I had a friend whose father was jailed in Egypt and it left
terrible memories. I am concerned, concerned about what they have
done to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
