</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-ART-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN MUSEUM CANCELS CONTROVERSIAL ART SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the furor created by the ``Sensation'' exhibition at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, the National Gallery of Australia in
Canberra has canceled the show, which was to have opened there in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's director, Brian Kennedy, said the decision stemmed
from ethical questions about how the exhibition was financed in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cause for concern for us was the documentation and
discussion that occurred and the extent to which this show was
enmeshed in funding,'' he said. He cited an article in The New York
Times that revealed that Charles Saatchi, who owns the collection,
and Christie's, the auction house, provided financing for the show
and have a commercial interest in the works of its British artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a public institution can't take it,'' Kennedy said. ``We
cannot ignore what's happened in Brooklyn; we're not disconnected
from the art world. We're not separate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kennedy acknowledged that he had received
several hundred letters from people criticizing the museum for
agreeing to take the show. ``Sensation'' includes such disturbing
images as a dead shark floating in a tank of formaldehyde and a
bust of a man made from his own frozen blood.
</P>
<P>
   Even before ``Sensation: Young British Artists From the Saatchi
Collection'' opened in Brooklyn in October, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
called the show, which also features a painting of the Virgin Mary
with a clump of elephant dung at her breast and pornographic
cutouts in the background, ``sick stuff.'' He cut off the city's
annual contribution of $7 million to the museum, but was forced to
restore it after losing a battle in court.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that when he agreed to show ``Sensation,'' he had
no idea that Saatchi had contributed money toward the exhibition's
Brooklyn visit, nor had he any knowledge that dealers who represent
some of the artists in the show had made contributions as well. He
also said he had not known that Christie's, the auction house, was
a sponsor and had sold other works from Saatchi's vast contemporary
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that ``Sensation'' was to go to Australia
completely financed by the government, Kennedy said ``it comes too
close to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny L. Blyth, director of the Saatchi Gallery in London, said,
``We gather Brian Kennedy felt that it was hard to follow on after
the problems in Brooklyn _ that the integrity of the art would be
compromised and overshadowed.''
</P>
<P>
   All the art in the show belongs to Saatchi, the British
advertising magnate. When the show opened in London at the Royal
Academy of Art two years ago, critics charged that it helped raise
the value of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   In London and later at the Hamburger Bahnhof in Berlin, Saatchi
paid only insurance costs. But in Brooklyn, he gave $160,000 to
help mount the show. The information turned up in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Arnold L. Lehman, director of the Brooklyn Museum,
and his assistants solicited donations of at least $10,000 from
dealers who represent many of the artists in the show. The museum
also received a $50,000 contribution from Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Arnold Lehman that may be OK,'' said Kennedy, who added
that he had not talked to the Brooklyn Museum's director about his
decision to cancel the show. ``I didn't want to embroil him in my
decision,'' he said. ``He has his museum to run and I have mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman said in a telephone interview: ``I don't know anything
about their decision. I know they were very excited about having
the show, and I'm sure they are disappointed not to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Australia is a public museum. People
associated with it said that a public outcry there could well lead
to criticism from its government-appointed 11-member council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gallery had looked forward to engaging the Australian
public about issues in contemporary art and will now seek other
avenues in which to do so,'' Kennedy said. He said he was still
deciding what would replace ``Sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that ``Sensation'' will not be seen by other
audiences. Ms. Blyth said it was scheduled to open in March at the
Municipal Museum of Art in Toyota, northwest of Nagoya, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
