<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUTGERS-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 EX-STUDENTS SUE RUTGERS OVER STRIPPING DURING BASKETBALL
PRACTICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ Earl Johnson, the former Rutgers point guard, recalled
Tuesday that he initially thought a free-throw game that his coach,
Kevin Bannon, ordered the team to play two years ago _ in which
players were forced to remove an article of clothing after missing
a shot _ would be fun.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, the 1996-97 Big East rookie of the year, said he
never thought Bannon would go all the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it got to the point where he wanted us to strip buck
naked, that wasn't funny,'' said Johnson, adding that he had to run
wind sprints naked through the school's gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Johnson filed a civil lawsuit against Rutgers; Bannon;
an assistant coach, Tod Kowalczyk; Robert E. Mulcahy III, the
current athletic director, and Fred Gruninger, who was the athletic
director at the time of the incident, saying the free-throw contest
violated state and federal civil rights statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Johnson in the lawsuit, filed in state Superior Court in
New Brunswick, were Josh Sankes, who played center for Rutgers, and
a student-manager of the basketball team, Juan Carlos Pla. Another
participant in the contest, Robert O'Connor, is still a team
manager and did not join the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The students are seeking unspecified monetary damages and
injunctive relief to force the school to implement a training
program to prevent the reoccurrence of similar misconduct in its
sports programs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Sankes have admitted that other players walked off
the court and refused to participate in the drill, but said they
reluctantly went along with the game because they feared they might
lose their athletic scholarships, or in Pla's case, tuition
credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stood there and didn't want to do it,'' Pla said during
a news conference at the Newark law offices of Ginarte, O'Dwyer,
Winograd &AMP; Laracuente, the firm representing the students. ``I
remember the coach was at a table with a cigar in his mouth
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleges that the contest, which it called an
``abusive coaching method,'' was rigged in such a way to humiliate
players recruited by Bannon's predecessor, Robert Wenzel.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Sankes have since transferred to other schools.
Sankes enrolled at Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass., in 1998, and
Johnson is attending Iona College in New Rochelle, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday afternoon, David B. Scott,
counsel for Rutgers, said the university had not been served with a
complaint, nor had it ``even seen an advance copy of a complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, based on our athletic department's investigation,
when this matter first surfaced last summer and based on statements
in the press from the three complainants' attorney, the university
believes that any such lawsuit would be without legal merit, and
the university will defend it vigorously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bannon told university officials that the free-throw drill was
conducted to ``provide some levity and fun'' for the team during a
difficult period. He denied that the drill was mandatory, as
alleged in the complaint, and said everyone, including himself and
the plaintiffs, were laughing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, no one was forced to remove his clothes or to
run,'' Bannon told The Record of Hackensack in August, when the New
Jersey newspaper first reported the contest.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
