<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CRADLE-WILL-ROCK-FILM     11-30 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRADLE-WILL-ROCK-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LABOR PAINS OF A LEFTIST MUSICAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore.  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the thousands who cheered it in the late 1930s, Marc
Blitzstein's musical play ``The Cradle Will Rock'' blazed like a
comet of hope in the dark Depression skies. The millennium was far
away, but Armageddon was now.
</P>
<P>
   Germany was rearming, Mussolini had seized Ethiopia, and the
Spanish Civil War seemed like a dress rehearsal for a final
confrontation between Left and Right. The American economy was
again on the slide, and labor strife across the country was taken
as the beginnings of class warfare.
</P>
<P>
   A series of razor-sharp satirical songs, ``The Cradle Will
Rock'' presented these conflicts as a battle between the good of
unionized labor and the corruption of everyone else. It opened on
June 16, 1937, under circumstances so dramatic that Orson Welles,
who had directed the production, later wrote a screenplay about the
show's creation. But it was never filmed; and as times changed,
``The Cradle'' disappeared into the recesses of cultural outer
space.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Robbins, who has taken on politically charged subjects in
his previous films ``Dead Man Walking'' and ``Bob Roberts,'' brings
Blitzstein's show back to life in his new movie, ``Cradle Will
Rock,'' opening on Friday in New York City. Not simply a cinematic
rendering of Blitzstein's play, or the story of its premiere, the
film is a panoramic view of New York in the Depression years,
filled with such historical characters as Nelson Rockefeller, Diego
Rivera, Frida Kahlo, William Randolph Hearst, Margherita Sarfatti
(Mussolini's former mistress who wrote pro-Fascist stories for
Hearst) and the young Orson Welles, a fireball of theatrical
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing fact and fiction and blending the directorial styles of
Welles and Preston Sturges, Robbins surrounds the story of the
show's birth with a web of plot lines about artists and patrons and
timeless questions of opportunism, compromise and integrity _ and
just putting on a show.
</P>
<P>
   Though his music is rarely performed today, Marc Blitzstein
revolutionized American musical theater, and not just politically.
Critics and composers have recognized that he created a new idiom,
distinct from the Broadway musical and European opera.
</P>
<P>
   His style sprang from popular music yet kept a sharp edge of
satire and psychological insight. In ``The Cradle,'' he leans
heavily on the manner of Kurt Weill (who referred to it, somewhat
bitterly, as ``my latest show''), but later he developed a lyrical,
jazzy melodic style of his own. His influence has permeated the
genre for the last 60 years, especially in the works of Leonard
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Blitzstein, played by Hank Azaria, composes ``The
Cradle'' as a man possessed. ``I read that he worked in a state of
white-hot inspiration,'' Robbins says, ``and that gave me the image
of Blitzstein's character.'' Indeed, driven by the political ideas
of his wife, Eva Goldbeck, who died of anorexia in May 1936, and of
Bertolt Brecht, Blitzstein wrote the words and music for ``The
Cradle'' in just five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A political soul-mate to the homosexual Blitzstein, Goldbeck had
introduced the composer to Brecht's writings, and to Brecht. Before
her death, the composer had played Brecht his song ``Nickel Under
the Foot'' _ which tells of a woman forced by poverty into
prostitution. According to Blitzstein's biographer, Eric Gordon,
Brecht said, ``Why don't you write a piece about all kinds of
prostitution _ the press, the church, courts, the arts, the whole
system?'' Despondent after his wife's death, Blitzstein recalled
Brecht's advice and feverishly set to work.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ``I'm Checking Home Now,'' sung by the Moll, a
hungry prostitute, ``The Cradle'' goes on to skewer the hypocrisy
of the Establishment of Steeltown U.S.A., which dances to the tune
called by Mister, owner of the steel mill, and his overstuffed
family. The preacher advocates peace or war depending on the price
of steel, a journalist defends his antiunion distortions as
``freedom of the press,'' a painter and violinist describe their
dependence on Mrs. Mister's patronage as ``art for art's sake,'' a
doctor falsifies medical records to help the police, and a college
president fires pacifists who will not endorse ROTC. The two
younger Misters fill their empty lives with marshmallow pop tunes.
</P>
<P>
   The only incorruptible character is Larry Foreman, a
middle-class union supporter who rejects Mister's attempt at
bribery and predicts the downfall of the social order and the
coming triumph of unionism with the fiery anthem ``The Cradle Will
Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles and John Houseman, who had already directed and
produced three shows for the Federal Theater Project, including an
all-black ``Macbeth'' in Harlem, brought Blitzstein's musical to
Hallie Flanagan, the project's head. She decided to present ``The
Cradle'' even though she was under attack in Congress for promoting
left-wing ideas. Citing Blitzstein's show as proof that the Federal
Theater Project was fomenting revolution, Congress cut its funds by
30 percent. In the film, as in the actual hearings, congressmen
brand Euripides and Christopher Marlowe as Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the public dress rehearsal (with full orchestra
and an elaborate set), the Works Progress Administration, the
financing umbrella for the Theater Project, canceled ``The Cradle''
for lack of funds and padlocked the theater. Houseman quickly found
an empty theater, the Venice, 20 blocks away. Word got out that the
premiere would be moved, and the cast and an audience packed with
union members _ Virgil Thomson wrote that the leftwing audience was
``the most formidable army of ticket buyers in the world'' _ walked
uptown. One obstacle remained. Actors Equity and the Musicians
Union would not let their members perform at the Venice.
</P>
<P>
   Houseman and Welles explained the problem to the audience, and
Blitzstein came out on a bare stage to narrate and sing his work at
the piano. But as he began the Moll's song, Olive Stanton rose from
the audience to play her role, soon followed by the rest of the
cast, who were all seated in the theater and were risking their
jobs with the Federal Theater by taking part. Art seemed to spring
miraculously from life, and the evening ended with jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was less interested in the show,'' Robbins says, ``than in
the impact it had on people's lives, and the way it helped them
understand the world around them.'' He centers his film on two of
the actors in the show, the actual Olive Stanton, played by Emily
Watson, and the fictional Aldo Silvano (John Turturro), an
Italian-American anti-Fascist. Stanton, a homeless woman who had
never been on stage before, found a job as a stagehand with the
Federal Theater Project, then took possession of the role of the
Moll as if it were her birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins says he invented fictions to connect facts: ``Where
there was an A and a C, I created a B.'' During rehearsals for
``The Cradle,'' the film's Silvano, a struggling young actor,
breaks with his parents because of their support of Mussolini. At
the actual premiere, an audience member tore down the Italian
Fascist flag hanging in the Venice Theater. Robbins gives that
defining act to Silvano, who adds his own political passion to
Larry Foreman's electrifying pro-union tirade.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Performing in ``The Cradle'' despite the economic disaster sure
to follow, Stanton and Silvano fuse their theatrical and political
vocations.
</P>
<P>
   A piano on a bare stage and a cast emerging from the audience
have become essential to performances of ``The Cradle,'' even
though Blitzstein had never imagined it that way. (For the film,
David Robbins, the director's brother, has rescored the music for a
klezmerish quintet.) Both Welles and Houseman later claimed that
they had instructed the cast to create the illusion of a
spontaneous performance.
</P>
<P>
   The movie script originally had Welles eloquently instructing
the cast on how to make their entrances; but when he learned that
members of the cast had recalled acting on their own, Robbins
rewrote the scene as a spontaneous show of political courage.
</P>
<P>
   As counterpoint to these stories of integrity, there are two
subplots about treachery and self-betrayal: the story of the
destruction of Diego Rivera's Rockefeller Center murals (which
actually took place in 1934) and an account of the decline and fall
of a fictional ventriloquist employed by the Theater Project.
</P>
<P>
   The young Nelson Rockefeller (John Cusack) commissioned Rivera
(Ruben Blades) to paint a mural for the centerpiece of his family's
contribution to the Manhattan skyline, after Picasso and Matisse
had turned him down. When Rivera refused to remove the face of
Lenin from the mural, ``Man at the Crossroads,'' Rockefeller
canceled the commission, paid Rivera handsomely and had the murals
jack-hammered off the walls.
</P>
<P>
   The film shows Rockefeller announcing that from then on he would
promote only nonpolitical art _ abstractions and nudes. It's a sly
joke at the expense of the Museum of Modern Art, which was built
with Rockefeller money and which still promotes an apolitical view
of modernism as a series of aesthetic innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his credentials as a political filmmaker, Robbins has
tried to balance political and nonpolitical characters in the film.
``Welles didn't buy into the absolutism of politics,'' Robbins
says. ``He embraced celebrity and bacchanalia, arriving at the
theater in an ambulance after partying all night in Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   The ventriloquist, played by Bill Murray, also seems to be
non-political at first. But when he sides with the enemies of the
Theater Project, his dummy turns on him, denounces his hypocrisy
and dies. Robbins crosscuts the post-performance celebration for
``The Cradle'' with the dummy's funeral march.
</P>
<P>
   This slice of magic realism springs from fact. One of the
Theater Projects' most successful productions was ``Pinocchio.''
When Congress shut down the program in 1939, the cast placed the
puppet in a coffin and marched up Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzstein's musical play received accolades from critics
spanning the political spectrum _ from The Daily Worker to Walter
Winchell. The entire score was recorded _ the first original cast
album of a Broadway musical (available now on a Pearl CD).
</P>
<P>
   Welles and Houseman went on to produce ``The Cradle'' on their
own, touring steel towns and then returning to New York in January
1938 for a 13-week run. Productions popped up across the country,
including one at Harvard, produced, directed and performed at the
piano by the 20-year-old Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the avid support of Bernstein and Aaron Copland,
Blitzstein became a neglected figure in the history of American
music, remembered mainly as the translator of Brecht's ``Three
Penny Opera.'' His 1949 opera ``Regina,'' based on Lillian
Hellman's ``Little Foxes,'' was praised after its premiere as ``the
most exciting music theater since `Rosenkavalier.''' But it has yet
to claim a place in the repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzstein, who was murdered in 1964 at age 58 by three sailors
he had met in a bar in Martinique, left three theater pieces
incomplete, including an opera about Sacco and Vanzetti he was
writing for the Metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzstein's work was always politically charged and far to the
left, though the caricatures in ``The Cradle'' will not alarm
anyone familiar with ``The Simpsons.'' In both the ``The Cradle''
and Blitzstein's next musical play, ``No for an Answer,'' he
integrated dialogue and singing as no American had done before: the
music continues the dramatic action so effectively that the
audience barely notices the transitions from speech to song.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzstein's shows may have languished and his hard line proved
unpersuasive, but without ``The Cradle Will Rock'' there would have
been no ``On the Town,'' ``Trouble in Tahiti,'' ``Wonderful Town,''
``Candide'' or ``West Side Story.'' Indeed, two songs from ``West
Side Story'' _ ``Officer Krupke'' and ``A Boy Like That'' _ are
pure Blitzstein; ``America'' is Blitzstein plus Copland; and
Bernstein even lifted the melody of ``Maria'' from ``Regina.''
</P>
<P>
   You can hear Blitzstein in Jud Fry's song, ``Lonely Room,'' from
``Oklahoma!'' And Blitzstein's mordant, sleazy melodies are the
models for ``Cabaret'' and ``Sweeney Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   Free of the necessity (or even possibility) of producing hit
tunes, and once again drawn to themes of social unrest, today's
generation of music theater composers will find Blitzstein's work
more relevant than ever _ even in the ``miracle'' economy of the
late '90s. And so, Robbins hopes, will the movie audience. ``They
are still censoring art today,'' he says. ``And there are still
individuals who exercise their freedom of expression, and pay the
price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
