<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5803 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WTO-POLICY-SPI &LR;      11-30 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-POLICY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO FINALLY UNDER WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At mid-morning Tuesday, Shyh-bao Lai of Taiwan stood
at the downtown Seattle Sheraton Hotel, blocked at Pine Street by a
chain of protesters. ``This is democracy? Shutting us out?'' he
exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, protesters shut out almost everyone from the site of
official meetings of the World Trade Organanization, including
people inclined to agree with them. ``We've come with quite a
progressive agenda,'' said Belgian delegate Gaetane Nihoul of the
Green Party, who stood frustrated on a Seattle street.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters who had vowed to shut down the WTO conference
succeeded in that aim, at least for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Talks finally began by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates opened the serious work by dividing Tuesday afternoon
into five groups: agriculture, market opening, implementation and
rules, transparency (opening up the WTO's process), and new issues
_ such as labor, environment and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also evident that the demonstrators succeeded in
getting themselves heard within the Convention Center's walls.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said the
protesters spoke for values that the Clinton Administration wants
the WTO to embrace, including open procedures, labor rights and
protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the message to take from the protests, not the
violence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   European Union Trade Commissioner Pascal Lamy said he understood
the protest. ``They have some belief that trade liberalization
works against what they care about,'' he said. ``They have to be
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine Albright, U.S. Secretary of State, said, ``We have
learned from history that attempts to stifle trade through
protectionism and closed markets usually backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   WTO Director-General Mike Moore said critics were wrong to label
the WTO undemocratic, because most of the delegates were sent by
democratic governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have over 100 ministers who want to engage on behalf of
their people,'' he said. ``It should be the right of our ministers
to sit around a table as equals and try and settle their
differences and try to build a more just system.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests clearly did not prevent the main work of the
meetings from being done. Albright met with Japan's foreign
minister, Yohei Kono, and discussed agriculture and anti-dumping
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Each side continued to set out its positions. EU negotiator Lamy
said Europe agrees that labor and the environment should be
considered in trade agreements. The United States agrees. But the
low-wage countries don't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing countries can only compete with lower wages,'' said
a Costa Rican delegate.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants an end to all export subsidies for farm
products. So does the Cairns Group of food exporting countries,
which includes Canada and Australia. Japan is willing to end export
subsidies, but wants to keep its protected market for rice, which
sells at six times the world price.
</P>
<P>
   That is a matter, a spokesman said, of ``food security,''
because Japan grows only 38 percent of the grains it eats.
</P>
<P>
   Lamy of the EU said ending all farm subsidies is an idea that
``just won't float.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, home of most of the dot-com companies, wants
to extend an agreement for zero tariffs on videos, texts and other
products that cross borders electronically. One supporter is the
WTO's newest member, Estonia. Its foreign minister, Toomas Ilves,
said his country has more Internet users than half the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's big priority with the United States is to reopen the
agreement on anti-dumping, because it says the United States is
using the law in an abusive way. South Korea, India and others
agree. But according to a Japanese source, Albright told Kono that
a substantial tightening of anti-dumping rules ``would invite a
huge political backlash in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the European Union are willing to cut tariffs to zero
on almost all products from the poorest countries. Barshefsky said
the United States will go along on most commodities _ but not
textiles.
</P>
<P>
   For Geoffrey Mkandawire, chief trade officer for Malawi, the No.
1 priority is market access for textiles.
</P>
<P>
   Patteson Oti, minister of foreign affairs of the Solomon
Islands, worries about negotiating with the big powers. ``It's like
boxing,'' he said. ``You can level the ring. But if you put Mike
Tyson in as an opponent, you know what the outcome will be. What we
need is equal fitness.''
</P>
<P>
   How it all would work out was far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said she expects agreement on some issues by
Wednesday. The toughest issue is agriculture, but she said she
expects some sort of a declaration on that by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, the Seattle Democrat and longtime champion
of trade with Africa, said the final deal probably won't be reached
``until the middle of the night Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the protests, McDermott said, ``They are not going to stop
the World Trade Organization. They may slow it down for a little
while, but it's going to go on. They're not going to stop
globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Mwansa Musonda, a Zambian who works for the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa, said he understood where the
protesters were coming from, but only to a point. ``There are a lot
of half-truths,'' he said. ``I see the same type of thing back
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Finnish delegate Peter Boldt of the Central Organization of
Finnish Trade Unions said the protest was a good thing. ``I used to
do it in the 60s, in the streets,'' he said. ``Of course this is a
little bit irritating, but eventually these protests will lead to
more of a social agenda in the WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests did succeed in changing some delegates view of
Americans. Said Muhammad Sulaiman of Pakistan, looking over at
colored banners and a large stuffed head, ``We thought at least in
the U.S., everybody was for free trade. Obviously not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
