<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRUMP-SUPERMODEL-ART-     11-30 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-SUPERMODEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUPERMODEL AT THE WHITE HOUSE? THINK SERENE AND TRADITIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo (NYT50) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One hates to muck about in sensationalism before a
fellow is even in office _ in this case, before a fellow has even
declared for office _ but there is an obligation to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   So let us discuss with the Slovenian model Melania Knauss the
notorious interview that she and boyfriend Donald Trump, who is
``exploring'' a run for the presidency, recently did with Howard
Stern. The phone interview during which Ms. Knauss was reportedly
naked and in which Trump bragged about their sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that became everything so fast,'' says Ms. Knauss
(pronounced Kuh-NAUS), in an Eastern European accent that can
render scrambled eggs caviar. ``It was like a comedy show. People
who hear it direct from the radio show, it was completely different
from the next day in the newspaper how they quoted. It was fun. ''
</P>
<P>
   Did Ms. Knauss do the interview naked?
</P>
<P>
   ``He did ask me what I'm wearing and I said, `Not much' and it
was quoted that I am nude. Then he was asking Donald, `Does she
have cellalite?''' Struggling with the pronunciation of cellulite.
`` `Shallalite?' He says, `Howard, she doesn't even know what the
cellalite is,' because I don't deal with the cellalite. I know what
it means, but they quote it like I don't know what the word means,
like I don't understand English.''
</P>
<P>
   But her boyfriend talked about their sex life on the air.
</P>
<P>
   A shrug, a conspiratorial woman-to-woman grin. ``It's the man
thing, that's how the man talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Trump a lucky billionaire or what? He's got a woman who does
not simply stand by her man, but over him. (Five feet 10{ inches,
but over 6 feet in her spiky Manolo Blahniks.) A 26-year-old model,
she has done Vogue covers in Europe. She also speaks four
languages.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Knauss, who maintains her own one-bedroom apartment, does
not wish to talk about something, like income or previous
relationships or George W. Bush, she will not talk, declining
charmingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comfortable to talk about that.'' Pause, playful grin,
flash of the approachable, friendly style that Trump's political
consultant, Roger Stone, said is making Ms. Knauss an asset on the
exploratory trail. ``Thank you for asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Other questions, she has no problem with.
</P>
<P>
   What does she like about this old guy with the funny hair?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very successful businessman, he's very charming. He's
very smart, the energy between us is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News poll in early November reported that
70 percent of Americans had an unfavorable opinion of Trump _ a
record, of sorts. He was less popular than Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the beginning. Maybe it will be 70 plus in
February.''
</P>
<P>
   Piaget gold-and-diamond ladies' watches, by the way, start at
$17,000. Ms. Knauss started in Slovenia, which declared its
independence from Yugoslavia in 1991 in a largely bloodless 10-day
war. If you are picturing a financially difficult life for Ms.
Knauss, however, you are wrong. Ms. Knauss' family was prosperous;
her father managed a chain of car and motorcycle dealerships, her
mother was a fashion designer. The family skied in Austria and
Slovenia; in summer they went to the shore. Ms. Knauss, who has an
older sister, started modeling at five. She graduated from the
Academy of Design and Architecture in Ljubljana at 19, bounced
between Paris and Milan, modeling.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, she came to New York, where work included
catalogs for Bergdorf Goodman and Lord &AMP; Taylor, a Concord Watch
campaign. At a party a little over a year ago, Ms. Knauss met
Trump. The attraction, she says, was immediate, although when he
asked for her number she declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a girl who will just give away the number to
anybody,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later she called him. They have dated since. Trump's
public ways, which might seem to some women to suggest the
objectification of women _ ``Where's my supermodel?'' Trump yelled
from the stage at a ``town hall'' meeting at the University of
Pennsylvania _ do not trouble her.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she admit to being bothered by the not uncommon
suggestions of gold diggery that sometimes accompany young women
who date wealthy older men; by a New York Post cartoon, after the
Howard Stern interview, which pictured Ms. Knauss in bed with
Trump, with a thought bubble in the form of a dollar sign over her
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press could be sometimes very mean,'' Ms. Knauss says.
``They love to make a joke, that's how they're selling the
newspapers. But I think you can't be with the person if it's not
love, if they don't satisfy you. You can't hug a beautiful
apartment, you can't hug an airplane, you can't talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   What would Ms. Knauss' role be should she and Trump ever end up
in The White House?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very traditional. Like Betty Ford or Jackie
Kennedy. I would support him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
