<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSECO-MARKETPLACE-N     11-30 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSECO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS SHARE PRICE SAGGING, CONSECO REFOCUSES ON ITS BALANCE SHEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c .1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conseco Inc., an insurance holding company with a sagging stock
price, announced a reversal of strategy Tuesday, promising to
improve its balance sheet while slowing its rate of growth. It
slashed its common stock dividend and agreed to raise $478 million
by selling convertible preferred stock on extraordinarily generous
terms to a private investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy brought immediate rewards for Conseco, whose
stock price rose $1.6875 to $20.25. Moody's Investors Service said
that when the investment by the investment firm, the Thomas H. Lee
Co., is completed next month, it would raise the company's rating
from the junk bond level to investment grade. Other bond rating
services already give the bonds an investment grade.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements came a day after Conseco stock traded as low
as $18.50, a three-year low and a 68 percent decline from its peak
of $58.125, reached in the spring of 1998. In the three and
one-half years leading up to that high, the stock price had risen
more than 500 percent as Conseco grew rapidly through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The dividend cut, from 15 cents a quarter to five cents, came
only four months after the payout was raised from 14 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price decline has been intensely frustrating to
Stephen H. Hilbert, Conseco's chairman, chief executive and
president, who noted Tuesday that the company has never missed a
quarterly earnings target. ``Conseco has not had an earnings
problem,'' he said in a conference call with analysts. ``It's had a
multiple problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Conseco's stock price has been hurt by suspicions that it
overpaid to acquire Green Tree Financial last year for $7.6 billion
in stock. That company, since renamed Conseco Finance, specializes
in mobile home loans. Part of Tuesday's announcement was a plan to
slow the growth in that business, a decision that Hilbert said
would enable the company to make loans that were more profitable
and less risky, although he said there was no problem with its
loans now.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco said that it now expects operating earnings of $2.80 a
share in 2000, rather than the $3 it had previously forecast, but
Hilbert added that those earnings would rise to $3.50 in 2001 and
grow by more than 20 percent in 2002. Conseco's closing stock price
Tuesday was just seven times the revised 2000 earnings target, a
figure that is far below that of most companies.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 earnings forecast was already below the $3.17 expected
by Wall Street for 1999, but that decline was due to a change to
more conservative accounting policies at Conseco Finance. A Conseco
spokesman said earnings for this year would have been about $2.16 a
share had the accounting change been made before the year began.
</P>
<P>
   As Conseco's stock price has fallen, a major issue has been cash
flow _ specifically whether enough cash would be coming in to the
parent company to meet its obligations, including those to
creditors. Hilbert told analysts that the company had projected it
would have just enough cash next year, but that the changes
announced Tuesday _ including a $135 million annual savings in
dividend payments _ would mean that it had twice as much cash as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert said Conseco's merits had ``been overlooked because of
the bears on the street spreading one ridiculous rumor after
another that cash was an issue here.'' He added that ``Cash flow
has not been a problem, but it has certainly been enhanced.'' He
forecast that Conseco's bond rating would be raised further as the
company's financial flexibility increased.
</P>
<P>
   The investment by Thomas H. Lee Co., a firm known for investing
in troubled financial companies, will give it $500 million in
preferred stock, convertible into common at $19.25 a share. Lee
will pay $500 million, but immediately get back about $11 million
in fees from Conseco for arranging the deal. Another $11 million in
fees will go to other bankers and lawyers, a Lee spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco said the preferred was priced to convert at a 4 percent
premium to Monday's closing stock price, but the terms appear to
actually be more generous to Lee. Not only does Lee effectively pay
less than full price because of the fees, but it will get more and
more shares as time goes by. The preferred carries a 4 percent
yield, but only a fraction of that will be in cash, with the rest
to be in additional preferred shares.
</P>
<P>
   If the preferred issue were to be converted in three years, the
earliest that Conseco can force conversion, it would be convertible
to about 28.4 million shares. That would mean an effective
conversion price, based on an original investment of $489 million,
of $16.84 a share.
</P>
<P>
   That contrasts with the average price of $40.80 a share that
Conseco paid to buy back 15.7 million shares of stock, for $641.3
million, in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As Conseco's share price has fallen, criticism has risen on Wall
Street of the company's unusual stock plan. Under the plan, Conseco
guaranteed loans made to officers and directors for the purchase of
company stock. The company also paid the interest on the loans. The
most unusual provision was that if the company were sold, the
executives and directors would not lose money. If the executives
paid more for the stock, including interest on the loans, than they
garnered in a sale, the company would pick up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But last month the company changed that provision, so that top
officers and directors now could lose money if the company were
sold at a low price. The guarantee against losses would still apply
to lower-level officers, said Jim Rosensteele, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Hilbert retains another unusual provision that would kick in if
the company were sold. He has options to buy 7.2 million shares at
prices ranging from $30.81 to $50.69. Those options are now out of
the money, but if the company were to be acquired at any price, the
exercise prices would be reduced to zero, according to a filing by
Hilbert with the Securities and Exchange Commission, to compensate
him ``for loss of the potential future speculative value of the
unexercised options.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Hilbert took what amounted to a pay cut,
however. He agreed that his annual bonus _ which was $13.5 million
a year in 1998 _ would be paid in stock valued at $50 a share. With
the stock now trading for about 40 percent of that price, the
change amounts to a 60 percent reduction in his bonus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
