u a BC-NY-MINORITIES-POLICE-     11-30 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MINORITIES-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE CITES RACIAL INEQUALITY IN NYC POLICE SEARCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Blacks and Hispanics are much more likely than whites
to be stopped and searched by New York City police officers, even
when the numbers are adjusted to reflect higher crime rates in some
neighborhoods where members of minority groups live, according to a
report released Tuesday by the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said the findings confirmed
blacks' and Hispanics' perceptions that they are disproportionately
targeted by police, who have made such questioning on the street a
pivotal tactic in reducing crime.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials faulted the report's methodology Tuesday,
calling it ``terribly flawed,'' although the analysis was prepared
with the help of researchers at Columbia University's Center for
Violence Research and Prevention and was reviewed by an independent
expert at the University of Illinois at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said his study clearly demonstrated racial inequity in
police searches, but he said he was not accusing the Police
Department of racial profiling. ``Racial profiling is all about
intent,'' he said. ``We were careful in this report not to
speculate about any motivations or intent that may underlie the
disparities in this report.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have defended the use of street searches as
part of an effort to catch criminals as they prepare to commit or
flee crimes. The program has often been cited as one of the ways
the city has been able to reduce the number of illegal guns on the
street. The courts have allowed officers to make the searches as
long as they have a reasonable suspicion, like a bulging waistband
that may betray the presence of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   But Spitzer said that although he endorses them as a
crime-fighting strategy, overuse of the street searches in some
areas had created resentment and mistrust of police among blacks
and Hispanics. Included in the 178-page report, alongside table
after table of statistics, were several anecdotes of blacks and
Hispanics who said they had been humiliated when police stopped and
searched them for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have good, tough policing and a lower crime rate
without infringing on people's basic constitutional rights,''
Spitzer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Police Commissioner Howard Safir characterized Spitzer's
release of the report as an attempt to attract the attention of the
news media, not foster substantive reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he shared with us his information before he shared it with
the press,'' Safir said, ``we could have pointed out to him that
the basis for stop-and-frisks is not the race of the individual as
determined by the police officer but the race of the individual as
determined by the description from the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, the first comprehensive analysis of the search
program by an outside agency, reviewed records from 175,000
incidents in which citizens were stopped by the police during the
15-month period that ended in March. The review was precipitated by
the police shooting of Amadou Diallo, a West African immigrant who
was killed in a barrage of 41 bullets by four officers assigned to
the Street Crime Unit, which conducts 10 percent of all street
searches in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo killing, in which the officers stand charged with
second-degree murder, set off months of demonstrations in which the
police were accused of trampling the civil rights of blacks and
Hispanics in their zeal to curb crime. Many critics said they were
particularly upset by what they described as the indiscriminate and
routine searches of people in predominantly minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The most basic finding of Spitzer's eight-month study was that
blacks were six times more likely to be stopped than whites.
Hispanics were four times more likely to be stopped, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, for example, made up 25 percent of the city population
but 50 percent of the people stopped. Whites, by comparison, made
up 43 percent of the population but were stopped only 13 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have long contended that the disparity is based
on the fact that most people are stopped in poor, high-crime
neighborhoods, many of which have a majority black and Hispanic
residents. But the attorney general's analysis found that, even
when the statistics were adjusted to take account of the higher
crime rate in some neighborhoods where large numbers of blacks and
Hispanics live, the number stopped still far exceeded the number of
whites stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide, the study found that, after adjusting for crime,
Hispanics were 39 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
Blacks were 23 percent more likely to be stopped, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   To arrive at those percentages, and adjust for differing crime
rates among racial groups, the analysts compared how often members
of a particular race were stopped to how often they were arrested.
The analysis found that blacks and Hispanics were stopped at a rate
that was much higher than the rate at which they were arrested. The
rate at which whites were stopped was only slightly higher than the
rate at which they were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there were 1.5 stops of blacks for every black
arrested, but 1.2 stops of whites for every arrest. Analysts
calculated that blacks had a 23 percent greater chance of being
stopped than whites. The disparity was even greater for stops when
the police were seeking suspects in violent crimes, the study
found.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said Spitzer's report was flawed because the
analysis used arrest data from 1997 but stop-and-search figures
from 1998 and 1999. ``The underlying numbers that he uses are in
question,'' said Maureen Casey, deputy commissioner for policy and
planning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
