<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE MAY RETURN FOR DATE WITH DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kings coach Andy Murray is conferring with the
team's schedule as much as team doctors in making a decision on the
return of injured left winger Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who scored 10 goals in the Kings' first 15 games,
appeared in a team scrimmage Tuesday for the first time since
learning he suffered a broken left foot 10 games ago. Murray has to
decide whether to play Robitaille on Friday in Anaheim against the
rival Ducks, or let him rest until a game against the expansion
Atlanta Thrashers five days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extra time obviously couldn't hurt the foot and it might
do him a lot of good,'' Murray said. ``When we get him back, we
need him back all the way. If that means keeping him out a couple
of days, I'm OK with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray is not ignoring the importance of the upcoming game
in Anaheim, where the Kings have not played well in the past. But
after playing the Thrashers, the Kings go back on the road for a
four-game trip to Detroit, Montreal, New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today will tell a lot about Luc,'' he said. ``We'll see how he
responds to the day after a tough workout. I'm sure he'll want to
go right away. But if we feel he's ready, he'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad news: Goalie Stephane Fiset, sidelined the past 3{ weeks
with a deep bruise in his right hand, experienced no improvement
Tuesday after five days of wearing a cast designed to immobilize
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is not stopping shots, but gripping the
stick to clear the puck. Fiset, injured in warmups just before the
Oct. 6 loss to Philadelphia, was hoping Tuesday's practice would be
more encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very upset after practice,'' Murray said. ``At first
this looked like a 10-day kind of injury. Now it looks like six
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings goalie situation looked pretty bleak last week when
Jamie Storr was sidelined with a strained right groin. But Storr
returned after missing just one game and beat San Jose last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He will be in goal Friday against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Winger Dan Bylsma and defenseman Jaroslav Modry
will play tonight in Salt Lake for minor-league Long Beach but will
return to the Kings on Friday. If Robitaille can't go, Bylsma will
dress for the game. Modry will not. . . . Murray almost was late
for Tuesday's practice because of travel problems getting back from
his home in Minnesota. He spent the holidays with his family, but
his return flight was re-routed through Ontario. It was a $140 cab
fare to the Kings' Iceoplex training facility in the Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-30-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991130.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-30 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TOURCHAMPIONSHIP-     11-30 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURCHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Tour Championship will be returning to Houston sooner than
expected.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The PGA Tour has reached a preliminary agreement with
representatives of Champions Golf Club to return the domestic
season-ending tournament for the top 30 money-winners to Houston in
2001, two years earlier than originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Because negotiations with several other sites around the country
yielded no satisfactory alternatives, the tour decided to return to
a proven commodity as the Tour Championship will be staged at
Champions for the fourth time in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have verbally agreed to have the Tour Championship return
to Champions in 2001,'' Earl Elliott, longtime board member of the
Houston Golf Association and one of the point men in the Tour
Championship's relationship with Champions, said Tuesday. ``There
still are some contract matters that need to be finalized, but it's
official in the sense that we have a verbal agreement between the
tour and Champions Golf Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Champions was under contract to host the Tour Championship in
2003. But the tournament will be played elsewhere that year since
it is returning to Houston in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the lure for bringing the elite tournament back to
Champions was the way the tournament was handled this year under
difficult circumstances. The HGA and officials at Champions werecited by the PGA Tour for their professionalism in the wake of
Payne Stewart's death in an airplane mishap Oct. 25, just three
days before the Tour Championship was to begin. The local parties
were responsible for setting up the Thursday morning tribute to
Stewart that included a bagpiper and was broadcast live nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout tournament week, the event went off as smoothly as
could be hoped for in the face of the tragedy, including a
suspension of play on Friday so that players could travel to
Orlando for the memorial service for Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, players at each of the past three Tour
Championships at Champions have raved about the golf course, which
is a more straightforward test of golf than many of the courses
they play during the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the original plan, Champions was to be included in a rotation
of four courses for the Tour Championship. The 2000 tournament will
be at East Lake Country Club in Atlanta. The Olympic Club in San
Francisco and Pinehurst No. 2 in Pinehurst, N.C., were expected to
be part of the regular rotation as well. But another Bay Area
course is under consideration, and it appears the tour will try to
formulate a rotation of six courses throughout the country for use
in the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan, according to sources, is to have two suitable
courses on the West Coast, two in the Midwest and two in the
Southeast, so that the tournament can start a six-year rotation
among those courses.
</P>
<P>
   Under this tentative plan, the Tour Championship would be back
at Champions in 2006 and 2012. Filling the other slots in the
rotation remains a work in progress for the tour.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will not change is the involvement of the HGA in
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HGA will continue its strong association with the Tour
Championship,'' Elliott said. ``Originally, we were to have the
tournament here in 2003. But since we've moved up the date to 2001,
it's not likely we will have it again for another five years. But
we will be part of the rotation that is being formed.''
</P>
<P>
   With Houston likely to have the Tour Championship only once from
2002 through 2011, it could open the door for a Senior PGA Tour
event or an LPGA Tour event to get established during the fall
months. Finding a presenting sponsor and a non-profit organization
to run such a tournament are two hurdles that would have to be
cleared before any such event could become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 event will mark the fourth time the Tour Championship
has been at Champions. In October, Tiger Woods was victorious in
the tragedy-marred tournament. In 1997, David Duval was victorious,
and in 1990, Jodie Mudd earned the title in what was then the
Nabisco Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Tour Championship had a $5 million purse, with Woods
winning $900,000. The tournament also is expected to generate more
than $1 million for charity, although the amount has yet to be
finalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
